<SLUG> BC-COL-CHARTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: CHARTER HEARING ADDS INSULT TO REVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roughly three hours into Tuesday night's Charter
revision hearing, Joe Blinstrub approached the microphone to sum up
how most of the audience clearly felt about the distinguished panel
of civic leaders on stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like everyone to join me in laughing at the commission,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ha, ha, ha!'' the crowd obliged.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the purpose of Tuesday's hearing, in the auditorium
of Murry Bergtraum High School in lower Manhattan, was to solicit
ideas from concerned citizens on changing the City Charter. Should
New York hold nonpartisan elections? Should its City Council
members serve full time? Is campaign finance reform necessary?
</P>
<P>
   But no one was biting. The crowd in the auditorium had not
assembled to weigh in on the Charter but to trash the Charter
Revision Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your participation on this commission justly earns you our
disrespect,'' said Michael Farrin, who identified himself as a
community activist.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lederman, by his own account SoHo's most frequently
arrested street artist, said: ``I would like to offer my
condolences to this distinguished panel. You do a great deal of
damage to your own reputations by participating in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Meyers, director of the New York Civil Rights Coalition,
said, ``You can only do one thing honorable and that is resign: Do
not delay!'' The mayor ``expects you to roll over,'' he said.
``Well, bowwow.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission's ordeal began at 6:30 p.m. and it was not until
after 10 p.m. that its many well-wishers had used up their allotted
three minutes at the microphone. About 50 people spoke, and with
the exception of one councilman, Andrew Eristoff, and a few
speakers who could only be described as cranks, it was essentially
one continuous assault on the panel's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's 12 appointees had shown up
for the hearing and they sat through it all impassively, never
posing a single question, never challenging a single statement and,
at least as far as this columnist could discern, never taking a
single note.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it makes sense that the commission did not hear much
about actual Charter revision, since, after all, this Charter
Revision Commission was never actually about revising the Charter.
</P>
<P>
   Even the mayor himself made no secret of its members'
resemblance to those little plastic peanuts that you pack glass in.
When he appointed them back in May, he all but openly said that
they were just there to come up with something _ anything, really _
to fill up space on the November ballot and prevent a referendum on
building a new Yankee Stadium. As everyone who cares about such
matters by now knows, this is the first Charter Revision Commission
in city history whose real subject is baseball.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, the commission has not done much to
obscure the absurdity of its situation or encourage a more
respectful attitude by the public. Just this Monday, after holding
its first public hearing, on Staten Island, its chairman, Peter
Powers, a former deputy mayor, issued a statement suddenly altering
its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   No, the commission would not, as it had earlier promised,
consider such sweeping changes as eliminating the public advocate's
office and the Independent Budget Office. There just wasn't enough
time, Powers explained, before the fall deadline for issuing
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the time-pressed commission would consider a series of
even more far-reaching measures, like introducing nonpartisan
elections and eliminating outside employment for City Council
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned much,'' Powers asserted somewhat implausibly,
``and have a better sense of what can be attained during this
initial round of reform.''
</P>
<P>
   During a break in Tuesday's hearing occasioned by a
stenographer's trip to the bathroom, Paul Crotty, the commission's
vice chairman, talked to reporters out in the hall. He brushed
aside concerns that two months was not enough time to come up with
well-considered proposals and, indirectly at least, compared the
commission's work to that of the Founding Fathers. The U.S.
Constitution, too, he said, was the work of a single summer.
</P>
<P>
   Crotty also played down the long line of speakers back in the
auditorium who were still waiting for a turn to insult him. ``There
is an awful lot of this,'' he said, ``that is anti-Giuliani
diatribe.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he had to admit that he was not having fun yet. ``I
don't,'' he acknowledged, ``particularly enjoy the abuse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
