<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SECRETSERVICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SECRET SERVICE AND THE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, July 9:
</P>
<P>
   In a firm, correct decision, a federal appeals court in
Washington has rejected the Clinton administration's creative
concoction of a new ``protective function privilege'' to prevent
Secret Service officials from testifying before a grand jury in the
Monica Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is pondering whether to pursue an appeal. The
nation and the presidency would be better served if the White House
took its unanimous legal defeat by a three-judge panel as a message
to switch from the obstructionist mode that has needlessly
prolonged Kenneth Starr's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The administration had argued for a broad privilege allowing
agents to avoid testimony in criminal inquiries unless they
recognized a president's actions as criminal at the time they
witnessed or heard about them. In dismissing the privilege claim,
the appeals court recognized the public interest in protecting the
president.
</P>
<P>
   But, echoing the conclusion reached by the lower court, the
appellate judges found the concern that a president would be
inclined to deny his agents adequate proximity to be unlikely in
light of the president's ``profound personal interest in being well
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the court noted that the privilege being asserted
would have the greatest effect when the president was at the White
House or in private meetings, not in public situations when the
greatest threat to his safety arises.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship of trust between the president and his closest
guards is important, and prosecutors should not interfere with it
absent a pressing law enforcement need. But the idea of a broad
Secret Service privilege cuts against the rule of law. So does the
continued lack of cooperation by the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
