<HEADLINE>
BROADCAST INDUSTRY DRAWS FIRE OVER DIGITAL TV
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only three months before the scheduled rollout of
digital television, members of the Senate Commerce Committee
lambasted the broadcast industry, cable companies and television
manufacturers Wednesday for failing to cooperate on crucial
technical and political issues that threaten a smooth transition to
high-definition TV.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chairman, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., erupted in
anger and frustration at a hearing called to measure progress in
moving American industries and consumers to digital TV.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who opposed the agreement that started digital
television, reminded broadcasters that the government had given
them what he estimated were billions of dollars' worth of new
broadcast frequencies for high-definition television; in return,
the industry had promised a smooth transition that would enable
them to return their analog channels to the government for resale
by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   That deadline now seems unlikely, broadcasters told senators
Wednesday, because some key technical standards remain unresolved
and because cable operators have refused to guarantee that they
will carry digital broadcasts by local stations.
</P>
<P>
   Th second issue will be taken up on Thursday by the Federal
Communications Commission, which is expected to start the public
comment process that will help it write so-called must-carry rules
requiring cable operators to carry local stations.
</P>
<P>
   Other senators expressed dismay at the price of the new digital
sets, which are expected to go on sale in November. Despite price
tags of between $7,000 and $10,000, they will not be able to pick
up digital cable broadcasts because the cable industry still has
not developed a standard for carrying digital signals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
