<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRANCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE REACHES GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ France finally figured out how to score
goals, although the source of its new-found offense was as big a
surprise as the fact that one had been found.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring just once in its previous two games, the French
registered the biggest triumph in its soccer history, claiming a
spot opposite Brazil in the World Cup final when defender Lilian
Thuram scored twice in a 2-1 victory over Croatia. It will be
France's first appearance in a World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lilian saved us,'' said France coach Aime Jacquet. ``It's an
excellent reward for all the work he's put in.... I don't think we
had a wonderful game, but we really played our hearts out. That's
what made the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Thuram's defensive prowess and ability to run the wing has been
well-documented, but his nose for the net has been, say, clogged.
He had not scored in 38 previous appearances for Les Bleus.
</P>
<P>
   France's first-half dominance had led to few chances and Croatia
had jumped ahead seconds into the second half on Davor Suker's
fifth World Cup goal. There has rarely been a safer lead, given
France's finishing touch of late. Then Thuram took over.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute after Suker's goal, the Guadaloupe-born right
back stripped Zvonimir Boban of the ball just outside Croatia's
box. He played a give-and-go with Youri Djorkaeff, beating
goalkeeper Drazen Ladic from 16 yards.
</P>
<P>
   His second, in the 69th minute, was more brilliant than the
first. He played the ball from the right wing into Thierry Henry,
whose return pass lacked precision and pace.
</P>
<P>
   That left Croatian defender Robert Jarni with possession, except
he never got to it. As the ball arrived, Thuram stuck his foot
between Jarni's legs and nudged it away. He strided toward the ball
about 22 yards from the net, still out on the right and ripped it
with his left foot past a diving Ladic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost concentration,'' admitted Miroslav Blazevic, Croatia's
coach. ``We weren't careful enough; we weren't attentive enough. We
felt at the time that France was failing, that it lacked strength.
But as so often happens in football, when you score and your
opponent scores immediately afterward, it gives them the strength
to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The triumph, which wasn't secure until goalkeeper Fabien Barthez
parried a deflected Goran Vlaovic shot over his crossbar in the
closing seconds, sparked celebration throughout France. President
Jacques Chirac called it ``truly the most wonderful day in French
sports history.''
</P>
<P>
   It came with a heavy price. Laurent Blanc, sweeper
extraordinaire and scorer of the ``golden goal'' that beat Paraguay
in the second round, was red-carded. He was dismissed in the 74th
minute following an altercation in the Croatian box as Zinedine
Zidane prepared to send in a free kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a catastrophe for the team, but it is for me,'' Blanc
said. ``I'm the only one who's punished and that's good. The whole
team would have been punished if we had lost the match because of
me being sent off. It would have been awful. I would have felt
guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanc's departure enabled the Croats, the Cup's Cinderella team,
to attack, something they hadn't done aside from Suker's strike,
which required a perfect Aljosa Asanovic chip and blown offsides
trap by France. But the French defense _ led by Thuram, Marcel
Desailly and Franck Lebouef filling in for Blanc _ limited them to
the just two solid chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``France's victory was deserved,'' Blazevic conceded, ``but I
can't help but feel we could have been there ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And so now the French, losers in three previous World Cup
semifinals, get a shot at mighty Brazil, the reigning champion
seeking a fifth crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the masters of world football... the greatest team in
this World Cup,'' Jacquet praised. ``They are able to dominate
opponents almost at will. But France is at home and that's a
wonderful opportunity. It's a challenge I think we can rise to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
