<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION DOCTOR SURPRISED WITH DELIVERY OF 37-WEEK-OLD BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINA LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Police are investigating a Phoenix abortion clinic
where a doctor delivered a full-term baby he had intended to abort.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise birth occurred after an examination by clinic
personnel showed the baby was only in its 23rd week, police said,
and the doctor prepared to abort the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he ended up delivering a 37-week-old baby.
</P>
<P>
   Police and Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley said Wednesday
they had not yet determined whether any crime had been committed in
connection with the incident June 30 at the A-Z Women's Center on
East McDowell Road in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we're going to look at this,'' Romley said. ``We
will also do research on the law and reserve judgment until the
investigation is complete.``
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police Sgt. Mike Torres said detectives are still
investigating, but, ``at this point, it doesn't appear anybody will
be charged with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the A-Z Women's Center were not returned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's mother is a 17-year-old woman who came to the clinic
June 29 after a home pregnancy test turned up positive, police
said. Police did not reveal her identity.
</P>
<P>
   An ultrasound examination performed at the clinic showed her to
be 23.6 weeks along in her pregnancy; the clinic will abort fetuses
up to 24 weeks, police said.
</P>
<P>
   During the abortion procedure the next day, police said, Dr.
John Biskind realized the fetus was full-term, and delivered a
6-pound, 2-ounce girl. The newborn was taken across the street to
Good Samaritan Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The child, who suffered a skull fracture and two deep
lacerations, will be adopted by a Texas couple, Torres said. She
shows no signs of brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind, who has been licensed in Arizona since 1981, has been
investigated in the past. In 1996, he was censured by the state
Board of Medical Examiners for ``gross neglect/conduct harmful to
patients or the public,'' according to board records.
</P>
<P>
   Another quality-of-care complaint is pending with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the medical community expressed shock Tuesday after
learning of the birth at the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missing a 37-week gestation and confusing it with a 23-week
pregnancy is unacceptable,'' said Dr. Brian Finkel of the Metro
Phoenix Women's Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of abortion nightmare that anti-abortionists
. . . would like to banter about the press and paint all of us with
this big, broad brush.``
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Carolyn Gerster, chairwoman for AZ Right to Life, said,
``Sounds like a grave error was made in estimation of the size.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an ultrasound, there shouldn't be that kind of
discrepancy.``
</P>
<P>
   Gerster said the average weight for a child at 24 weeks is about
2pounds. At 36 weeks, a baby is usually 6{ pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Howard, CEO of Planned Parenthood, said he had never heard
of a case such as this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likelihood that something like this could happen is
incredibly small,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Howard said this incident may be unusual simply because
most women seeking abortions do so soon after discovering they are
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well over 90 percent (of abortions) take place in the first
trimester,'' he said. ``The vast majority wouldn't even be
approaching this point.''
</P>
<P>
   And although Howard said ultrasound techniques are becoming
``increasingly precise,'' the results depend on circumstances. For
example, if a fetus is lying in a certain position, it could skew
the results, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with all health care, it's an imprecise science,'' Howard
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
