<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-HALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL TO FIGHT LAYOFF  
 SWIMMER TESTS POSITIVE FOR DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Olympic medalist Gary Hall Jr. said Wednesday that he
plans to fight a suspension for a positive drug test that, if
upheld, will cloud his future as a world-class athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Hall was placed on a suspension that was termed ``provisional''
by swimming's international governing body, FINA, which took the
action against him after it reported that he tested positive May 15
for a recreational drug.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in Phoenix, site of the random test, said the substance
is marijuana, which after the 1996 Olympics was placed on a banned
list that includes performance-enhancing drugs such as steroids.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is provisional, according to FINA, until it has
acquired results of an alternate sample and has heard from Hall at
an official hearing. He could be suspended for as long as three
months. Hall also plans to undergo another test next week at the
International Olympic Committee laboratory in Montreal. Phoenix
attorney Edwin Hendricks will represent him, according to his
father, Valley eye surgeon Gary Hall. Hendricks was not available
for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that once I am afforded the opportunity to
present my position, I will be able to prove I did not violate any
FINA rule, and the provisional suspension will be removed,'' Hall
said in a prepared statement from Hawaii. ``The test was allegedly
positive for marijuana, a non-performance-enhancing substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I have requested that another test be performed, to
which I am entitled under FINA rules, it has not yet been
completed. Nor have I been given my right under FINA rules to
appear before a FINA panel.''
</P>
<P>
   The positive test occurred on the first day of the US
West/Nortel Swimfest at Phoenix Swim Club. According to Hall's
statement, he was not competing in a FINA-sanctioned event but in a
non-sanctioned match race. His prize for winning the sprint was
this week's expense-paid trip to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of his impending battle, Hall, 23, won't be
with the U.S. team for the Goodwill Games in New York later this
month because the process is expected to last through at least July
28, when swimming is scheduled to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, because of the time required for this due
process to occur, I regret I will not be allowed to compete at the
Goodwill Games,'' said Hall, who won two gold medals for relay legs
and two individual silvers.
</P>
<P>
   He had been training for a Goodwill Games rematch with Russian
Alexander Popov, who narrowly beat him the 50 and 100 freestyle
events at the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, Hall's name still was on the Goodwill Games
roster. A spokesman in Colorado Springs said U.S. Swimming has been
notified of Hall's provisional suspension. But U.S. Swimming will
wait on further action because of uncertainty surrounding his case
and others.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Four Chinese women have had provisional suspensions
temporarily lifted because of a legal wrangle over testing for
agents designed to mask performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is still way up in the air,'' the spokesman said.
``Otherwise, it's not appropriate for us to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   If a three-month suspension is handed down, Hall will be banned
from major international competition through 1999, a key year
before the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia, in July and August.
</P>
<P>
   It would depend on how FINA times the suspension. If it starts
May 15, date of the test, and ends Aug. 15, Hall likely will be
ineligible for the national championships Aug. 11-15, in Clovis,
Calif. U.S. teams for the 1999 Pan American, Pan-Pacific and
Shortcourse World Championships will be selected at that meet.
</P>
<P>
   Hall will be eligible for World Cup competition, a somewhat
anonymous pro circuit. Without the limelight of big meets that
point to the 2000 Olympics, there is concern about Hall's
motivation to continue training.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches marvel at his talent but complain about his work ethic.
Hall, whose endorsements include Speedo and Gibson guitars, is
known for going his own way. He has a reputation for thumbing his
nose at the sport's various bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   If a three-month suspension sticks, will he continue?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know,'' said his father, a three-time Olympic
swimmer. ``He has to get over this hurdle. I'm very concerned about
him right now. He's not a drug user. He's a good kid.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the 1998 rankings, Hall had a legitimate chance to
beat Popov in at least the 50. For the year, Hall has the world's
second-fastest time, 22.40 seconds, behind fellow American Bill
Pilczuk, who beat Popov at the World Championships in January.
Popov is fourth at 24.43. Popov, however, has the year's best time
in the 100 at 48.74. Hall is fifth at 49.60.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really looking forward to the Goodwill Games,'' his
father said. ``He is devastated by this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
