<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA ABROAD 
TURNING HEADS 
A HAMPTONS HELLO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oklahoma Abroad &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mary Rodgers, the daughter of Richard Rodgers, took
three English women she calls ``war babies'' to a preview of Trevor
Nunn's new production of her father's ``Oklahoma!'' at the Royal
National Theater in London. The three _ Lady Astor, Gillian
Warrender and Zoe Hyde-Thomson _ spent World War II in New York and
were classmates of hers at the Brearley School on the Upper East
Side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still call them kids even though we're all 67 years old,''
Miss Rodgers said. ``The kids in school were envious of them. We
loved their accents, and they were smarter. When they went home,
they were accused of losing their British accents, of being
Americanized, but they didn't sound that way to us at all.''
</P>
<P>
   And the show? Miss Rodgers gave it a thumbs up. ``I wasn't
bored,'' she said, ``but it's three and a half hours. I think
they'll tighten it up in the first act, especially.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning Heads &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now is the time for midsummer silliness, or at least
attention-getting stunts. Yesterday Campari, the Italian aperitif
that is about the same color as weak Sangria, hired a room at Remi,
a restaurant on West 55th Street in Manhattan. Campari's spokesmen
said that the company had hired an artist to paint two ``seminude''
women the color of the drink.
</P>
<P>
   The two women, Zhenya Pizarro and Lana Piryan, were wearing red
bathing suits when artist Joanne Gair, who once painted a pinstripe
suit onto Demi Moore's body for a photograph in Vanity Fair
magazine, went to work, using lipstick (a shade called ``heat
wave'').
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pizarro said the trick was to apply a primer coat of lotion.
``If you don't,'' she said, ``the paint seeps into your pores. I
didn't the first time, and it was, like, a week later and it was
still coming out of my ears.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the bridal bouquet tossed in Bryant Park.
</P>
<P>
   The event was organized by Bride's magazine and Romance
Classics, a cable network not carried on the New York systems owned
by Time Warner, whose HBO unit has its offices on 42d Street across
from Bryant Park. They expected a crowd of would-be brides to jump
when James Dolan, the chief executive of Cablevision, threw the
bouquet, because the catcher would win a $25,000 prize.
</P>
<P>
   It was caught by a man, Anthony Scavone.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the prizes was a vacuum cleaner,'' said Scavone, an
actor who went by the park after his physical trainer canceled an
appointment. ``I really needed a vacuum cleaner because I have
cats. I didn't even realize what the grand prize was.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he now consider popping the question? ``I've always been a
little commitment-phobic,'' he said, ``but this is an incentive. I
always thought if I ever was financially secure, I'd consider doing
that. Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   A Hamptons Hello &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A postscript: Sean (Puffy) Combs, the party giver and
rap music impresario, has learned the way they do things in East
Hampton, N.Y., where he bought a house last year. There was a
last-minute flurry when a neighbor asked the police whether he had
a permit for his Fourth of July party.
</P>
<P>
   He did not, so his managers called in a lawyer, Michael
Griffith. He said the call about the permit had come from Debra
Lobel, a former East Hampton Town Attorney. Griffith went to her
house. ``I say, `Look, why don't you start a dialogue, meet your
neighbor?''' Griffith recalled. (Ms. Lobel did not return a call
for comment.)
</P>
<P>
   Soon Combs was at Ms. Lobel's door. ``On the way over I said,
`What time did you plan to knock off?''' Griffith said. ``He said,
`About 9.' I said, `Tell her it was going to go till early in the
morning, but as an accommodation to her, we'll cut off at 11,'
because I know the town law says you have to cut off at 11.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Combs sent Ms. Lobel a plate of food and a bottle of
champagne. And yes, the party ended on time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
