<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PICKING AGAINST THE UNKNOWN'  
 OBSCURE DRAFT CAN SUPPLEMENT ROSTERS WITH UNSCOUTED PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quarterback Dave Brown's mother received a disturbing phone call
the night before the 1992 NFL supplemental draft.
</P>
<P>
   A league official had called to inform Brown that the NFL had
cancelled the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom flipped out,'' said Brown, in his first year with the
Cardinals. ``She said, `What do you mean, you're not going to have
one?' ''
</P>
<P>
   When Brown heard the news, he called his agent, Leigh Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leigh said it was unconstitutional to cancel it,'' Brown said.
``I would have been hung out to dry. I already had an agent, so I
couldn't go back to school (at Duke). We would have sued the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooler heads prevailed and the NFL held the supplemental draft
for Brown, who was taken in the first round by the New York Giants.
The incident shows how different the supplemental draft is from the
NFL's regular draft, which is a big event held over two days and
broadcast by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Today's supplemental draft, however, is an obscure event. Only a
few teams will participate and most of the 10 players available
won't be picked.
</P>
<P>
   Brown isn't the only Cardinals player who entered the league
through the supplemental draft. Pro Bowl wide receiver Rob Moore
was a first-round pick by the New York Jets in the 1990
supplemental draft. Both entered the draft because they graduated
after the regular draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals also chose quarterback Timm Rosenbach in the first
round of the 1989 supplemental draft, but he was out of the league
by 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful player ever taken in the supplemental draft
was University of Miami quarterback Bernie Kosar, a 1985
first-round selection by Cleveland who led the Browns to two AFC
title games.
</P>
<P>
   But few in the NFL like supplemental drafts, including Giants
General Manager Ernie Accorsi, who was running the Browns when they
picked Kosar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pick on (the regular) draft day, you know exactly who
you are picking that player over,'' Accorsi said. ``In a
supplemental draft, you are picking against the unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals General Manager Larry Wilson, who picked
Rosenbach, said he wishes supplemental drafts didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are only (there) to appease players,'' he said. ``All
these decisions should be made the time the draft occurs. In 99
percent of the cases, the reasons aren't good why players are
available. You've never scouted them other than on films. It's an
unfair situation for clubs to get into.''
</P>
<P>
   The top player in this year's supplemental draft, Oklahoma State
defensive tackle Jamal Williams, entered the draft because he was
academically ineligible. Navy offensive tackle Mike Wahle, the
second best player in today's draft, was dismissed from school
after failing an NCAA-administered drug test.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the available players are junior college guys _ all
kinds of garbage are in it,'' said Bob Ferguson, Cardinals vice
president of player personnel. ``Half of them were kicked off their
teams. Sure, you get the Dave Browns and Rob Moores every once in a
while, but they are the exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, for the team, the preparation isn't there. It's kind of
disjointed. The coaches are on vacation.'' &QL; 
__ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Brown decided to enter the supplemental draft after going
through Duke's spring practice in 1992. Most of the team's best
players had departed, and he needed only one class to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after the NFL (regular) draft, teams started calling
me,'' he said. ``They are not supposed to do it, but they do it. I
heard that such and such didn't get a quarterback and needed a
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown knew he would be a No. 1 pick the next year. Going into
his senior season, he was rated the third-best quarterback prospect
behind Drew Bledsoe and Rick Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing he would bypass his senior season, Brown worked
out for 20 teams. He thought he would be picked by Cleveland, which
was looking for a replacement for Kosar, or Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leigh (Steinberg) told the Browns I would be tough to sign, so
they passed on me, and the Giants took me right behind them,''
Brown said. ``Leigh didn't have any quarterbacks in New York and
wanted to get me there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a native of Westfield, N.J., wound up joining his
home-town team, the Giants, but was inconsistent as a starter for
nearly four seasons. He was released in the spring and signed as a
free agent to compete for the backup job behind Jake Plummer. &QL; 
__ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Moore liked the idea of having his ``own draft.'' So midway
through the spring of 1990, he decided he wanted to apply for the
supplemental draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already had been projected as going 10 to 15 in the regular
draft,'' Moore said. ``If I figured I would have been a
second-rounder or later, I never would have applied for the
supplemental draft. The benefit of the supplemental draft is you
don't get put in the mix with everybody else. It gave me an
opportunity to sit back and watch how the regular draft unfolded.''
</P>
<P>
   He graduated in May, making him eligible for the supplemental
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always promised my mom I'd graduate before I left school,''
Moore said. ``I knew if I had to prepare for the (regular draft),
I'd never have graduated.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who grew up in Hempstead, N.Y., not far from the Jets'
practice facility, was picked by his neighborhood team. He was a
starter from the outset but got into a contract dispute with the
club after making the Pro Bowl in 1994 and was traded to the
Cardinals on draft day the next spring. &QL; 
__ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals still were reeling from the career-ending hip
injury to quarterback Neil Lomax in 1989 when they drafted
Rosenbach, who was eligible because he graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbach won the starting job his second year and threw for
3,098 yards in 1990. He was expected to be the team's longtime
starter but suffered a serious knee injury in a non-contact drill
the next summer and was lost for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had done some research on him,'' Wilson said of Rosenbach.
``At the time, we thought he might be a first-round pick in the
regular draft. It was a fluke thing what happened to him in
practice. You never can predict those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to him later contradicted what we knew about him
as a player and a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbach, slowed by injuries again in 1992, suddenly retired
that summer, saying he had lost his desire to play pro football.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to make a comeback with the New Orleans Saints in March
1995 but suffered a back injury fishing and never played.
</P>
<P>
   He is running a commercial boat in Cabo San Lucas, Mexico. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
