<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROWN-NEWHOUSE-420&AMP;AD     07-09 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-NEWHOUSE-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BROWN'S DEPARTURE, NEW YORKER FACES CRUCIAL DECISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 (With BROWN-RESIGN, BROWN-HOLLYWOOD.) 
(nk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   ith STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the departure of his high-profile editor, Tina
Brown, S.I. Newhouse Jr. will have to make crucial decisions about
the editorial and advertising future of the loss-plagued New Yorker
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown was credited with making the magazine timely, relevant
and far flashier than it had been under former editors. It is now
up to Newhouse, whose family owns The New Yorker, to decide whether
to seek an editor who will continue that strategy or veer toward a
less timely approach. Also at issue is whether to trim the
magazine's high editorial budget and rethink its strategy of making
expensive efforts to build circulation.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the magazine faces great difficulty because of
increased competition for advertising addressed at affluent
readers. Some of that competition comes from other Conde Nast
publications, like Conde Nast Traveler and Vanity Fair, as well as
niche publications owned by competitors in fields such as travel,
life style, gourmet foods and home decor.
</P>
<P>
   Some even believe that the magazine should return to its past as
a less topical, literary magazine and thus differentiate itself
from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most attention Wednesday, in the advertising industry at
least, focused on the need to make a strong statement of direction
with a new editor, especially now when advertising is being sold
for the all-important fourth quarter, by far the most lucrative
period of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishers are relatively easy to replace in this business,''
said Roberta Garfinkle, senior vice president and print media
director at McCann-Erickson New York, part of the McCann-Erickson
World Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies. ``The much
bigger issue is who will replace Tina,'' she added. ``It's a very
hard spot to fill,'' because of the prominence of The New Yorker
and the publicity recently given its financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Tassaro, senior vice president and director for print
services at the Media Edge, the media services arm of Young &AMP;
Rubicam Inc. in New York, said Ms. Brown's resignation ``is
definitely a blow to The New Yorker'' primarily because ``Tina as a
personality became synonymous with The New Yorker'' as a result of
``the enormous buzz'' that she created for the weekly magazine in
media and advertising circles.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ms. Tassaro added, ``The New Yorker is like a phoenix
that will rise from the ashes'' because ``it's a venerable title
with such an incredibly loyal readership.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But at a magazine that does not have a natural advertising niche
_ it is not a fashion or beauty book _ an editor with an identity
can be a lure for skittish buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker's new publisher, David Carey, was appointed only
a month ago. Under both former publishers _ Steven T. Florio and
then his brother Thomas A. Florio _ the magazine raised its
circulation beyond what was seen as the ``natural'' level, the
level a magazine reaches without costly promotion. Under both
Florios, circulation grew, though new subscribers were often
courted with inexpensive subscription rates. At the same time, the
magazine lost advertising pages because many advertisers could no
longer afford the expensive ad prices. Though The New Yorker's
losses have declined over the last several years, it still lost $11
million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Conde Nast is folding the magazine into the operations of
its other publications to save money on back-office functions. The
plan is to lower advertising prices once the merger is made.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, well-established writers who are part of The New
Yorker's lure may not remain. Most have one-year contracts, Ms.
Brown said yesterday, adding that when she left Vanity Fair to join
The New Yorker she did not take many writers with her. But even
those who do not join her at the new monthly she plans to start
could well leave The New Yorker if they are unhappy with Newhouse's
editorial choice.
</P>
<P>
   With all the possible changes ahead, Steve Greenberger, senior
vice president and print media director at Grey Advertising, said
he believed that ``The New Yorker needs a push to establish where
it is in the advertising marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tina Brown had reached a point where she had done what she
came there for,'' he said, ``and now it's time for the magazine to
stand on its own two feet. The good news is that it could, with the
right marketing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
