<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TKACHUK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK CONFIDENT OF PACT EXTENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Most people think his future in Phoenix won't last as
long as the beanie baby craze.
</P>
<P>
   So why does Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk get all warm and fuzzy
inside when he talks about his stalled contract negotiations with
General Manager Bobby Smith?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm optimistic things will get worked out,'' Tkachuk,
the team's leading scorer each of the past three seasons, said
Wednesday from his home in Cape Cod, Mass. ``I'm not worried or
frustrated about it at all. I still believe it will get done in
time. My prediction is I'm going to sign with the Phoenix Coyotes
and be there for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk already has rejected two offers from the team, including
one worth $33 million _ an average of $6.5 million a year. Last
week, Smith pulled it from the table and announced that
negotiations were off indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk and his agent, meanwhile, reportedly want a package
worth $40 million, an average of $8 million a year. If they don't
get it, sources said Tkachuk is prepared to sit for however long it
takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it wouldn't be smart for the player or for the
team, I know that,'' Tkachuk said. ``It doesn't make any sense, so
let's get a deal done. There's still plenty of time left.''
</P>
<P>
   The raging debate in the Valley is why does Tkachuk deserve $8
million a year when he has two years left on his current contract
(worth $2.8 million next season, $3 million the next), and he never
has led his team out of the first round of the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   The only athletes in the Valley expected to get that kind of
money are Diamondbacks Jay Bell and Matt Williams. Bell will make
$8.1 million for each of the last two years of his five-year, $35
million deal. And Williams will make more than $9 million in the
last two seasons of his five-year extension, which begins next
season. The only Suns player who ever has made that much money is
11-year veteran Kevin Johnson, who was paid $8.4 million for last
season after leading his team to the playoffs nine seasons in a
row. No Cardinal, let alone any NFL player, is even in that
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk said it's simple economics. Salaries are skyrocketing
around the NHL. Top players such as Eric Lindros, Paul Kariya and
Joe Sakic have raised the bar. Jaromir Jagr and Teemu Selanne, he
points out, signed lucrative extensions before their original deals
expired. All have at least made it to the second round of the
playoffs, and Jagr and Sakic have their names on the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on where you put yourself in that category,''
Tkachuk said. ``Players are getting paid more than ever, (and)
teams are taking care of their better players. Ten months ago, we
gave them our offer, and basically, it hasn't changed at all
despite the fact the market was going up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first-round-of-the-playoffs thing, I can understand that
being a fan. But some of these other guys haven't won a Stanley Cup
yet, either, or made it to the second or third round themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk followed up back-to-back 50-goal seasons by scoring 40
last season despite missing 13 games and playing with a fractured
rib in about a dozen others. He said he realizes his public image
may be tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people are only hearing one side of the coin,'' he said.
``I know I'm getting portrayed as a bad guy, but I know I'm not.
People don't know what's going on in the marketplace. They don't
understand what's gone on behind the scenes. The only people who
really know are Bobby Smith, myself, (Coyotes owner) Richard Burke
and my agent (Bob Murray).''
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of the disagreement, apart from the dollar
amount, is the alleged promise that Smith and Burke made to Tkachuk
in September. Tkachuk and Murray contend they were promised an
extension would get signed, sealed and delivered. Smith and Burke
said the only promise they made was that they would ``try.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me to come back and play (after sitting out the
preseason) and they'll get me an extension because it'll look
better after I played at least three years of my contract,''
Tkachuk said. ``They looked me right in the eyes and shook my hand
and promised. I was there. I know what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still willing to negotiate, but by (Smith) saying the
talks are off and the offer's off the table, he's telling me he
doesn't want Keith Tkachuk in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk wouldn't say whether he is prepared to budge from his
original demands. He wouldn't confirm whether he would hold out, as
many expect. He did say that he doesn't want the situation to lead
to a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play in Phoenix. I want to lead that team,'' he
said. ``No way would I ask for a trade. But it's all in Bobby
Smith's hands now. He's going to do what he thinks is best for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only July, and we've still got time to talk. If we can't
reach a deal, then we'll cross that bridge when we come to it. But
my insides tell me we'll get a deal done. I'm convinced of that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
