</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-SCHEDULE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SCHED ULED TO PLAY 10 ROAD GAMES IN DECEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They're playing in a new division inside a new
three-division conference format, but once again the Coyotes will
be road warriors during December.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes will play four of 14 games in December at America
West Arena, according to the 1998-99 schedule released Wednesday by
the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Coyotes played five of 15 games in December at
home and escaped major damage with a 5-5-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we would have liked to see more home games in December,
but we can't complain,'' Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith said.
``Actually, we worked hard to have our schedule changed from the
initial way it looked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had us playing 17 of our first 22 at home, which would have
meant coming down the stretch with most of our games on the road.
Giving this schedule a cursory look, I'm pleased with it. We start
the year with a good mix of home and away games, and it's more
balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Coyotes had to play five of their final eight
games on the road while struggling to earn a playoff spot. They
came away with a 5-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, they end the season with eight of their last 13 at
home, as well as five of their last 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, our last 27 games are just about evenly split,''
Smith said. ``It's a lot better than it looked initially. We
avoided a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes opened last season with seven of their first 10
games on home ice. The upcoming season sees an equal split in the
first 10 games. They open the season against the Ottawa Senators at
home on Oct. 11, then host Colorado and Boston before departing on
a five-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes also will host New Jersey on Thanksgiving night,
Dallas on New Year's night and Anaheim on Valentine's Day. They
twice have home dates when the Arizona Cardinals also are at home _
the season opener (Ottawa) and Dec. 20 (New York Islanders).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about playing on Thanksgiving night,'' Coyotes
President Shawn Hunter said. ``It's the third year we've played
that night, and we want it to become a tradition. . . . The same
goes with New Year's night.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new conference alignments necessitated by expansion
(Nashville this year) and future expansion (Atlanta in 1999-2000;
Columbus and Minnesota in 2000-2001), the Eastern and Western
conferences feature three divisions each.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, having been members of the Western Conference's
Central Division in the past, move into the Pacific Division this
season along with Dallas, Anaheim, Los Angeles and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary, Colorado, Edmonton and Vancouver make up the Northwest
Division, with Chicago, Detroit, Nashville and St. Louis comprising
the Central.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule calls for each Western Conference team to play six
times against divisional foes, four times against the teams in
other divisions within their conference, and once each against
teams in the Eastern Conference. But each team will play a minimum
of 12 ``wild card'' games, which were decided on the basis of
promoting geographic and traditional rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   In the Coyotes' case, it means they will play each Eastern
Conference team twice (home and away), with the exception of
Carolina and Toronto. The Coyotes will visit but not host the Maple
Leafs, and they will host but not visit the Hurricanes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
