<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WAITING FOR BROWN DRAKES AT DUSK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a stand of trees a 3-year-old elk grazed, the velvet on his
antlers still plush and unrubbed. His paunch sagged with the weight
of constant feeding, and on his back sat a cowbird, heedless. In
the evening light the seedheads of the grasses across the river,
where the elk stood, seemed unduly ponderous, dense and purple. The
river was the Gibbon, where it bends far away from the highway in a
section of Yellowstone called Elk Park.
</P>
<P>
   I had come to fish with two good friends. The fishing, highly
speculative, would wait until a mayfly called the Brown Drake
appeared, if it appeared at all. Where we sat, the Gibbon flowed
from west to east, its surface as bright as the fading sun. Every
now and then, a lily pad on the far bank would turn on its side and
knife downward through the water in a motion very like the arc a
trout makes when it rises and falls through the surface, feeding. I
held a hand up to the sun and saw caddis flies drifting across the
backlit meadow and the dark timber to the west. The elk lay down in
the tall grass.
</P>
<P>
   In Yellowstone you get used to the happenstance of seeing
wildlife. One year the thermal meadows near the Firehole are full
of bison. The next year at the same time, the flies have already
driven them to higher ground. The highway through Yellowstone, to
which most visitors cling, comes to seem like a path through a set
of loose probabilities _ weather, season, time of day, etc. _ that
determine whether you will come across a moose or a coyote. To the
movements of wild animals, we naturally impute a narrow determinism
_ they are driven by hunger, irritation, danger, courtship. But to
what do the elk impute our love of asphalt?
</P>
<P>
   When darkness began to settle, it looked at first as though the
Brown Drakes would not appear. A few caddis began laying eggs on
the water, slowly stitching their way upstream. Brown Drakes are
very big mayflies. They adhere to the corridor of the river as
tightly as tourists adhere to pavement. They simply appear when the
light is low and the air and water temperature are right.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly there they were, fluttering up and down in twos and
threes and then in dozens, knotting and unknotting as they mated.
We waited for the flies to settle onto the water and cause the big
brown trout to feed. The mayflies rose and fell, always a little
nearer to the river's surface. We looked on tensely, trying at once
to watch the insects and all of the visible river, as though it
were an unmoving plane of light. Then they vanished _ who knew
where or why? _ and the Gibbon began to flow again. We walked to
the highway, where a cow elk wearing a radio collar grazed in the
abrupt glow of flashbulbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
