<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW CORNING REACHES DEAL TO SETTLE IMPLANT BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning and lawyers for women claiming injury from silicone
breast implants have agreed to a $3.2 billion settlement to the
nearly 10-year-long battle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would allow women seeking damages from the
implants to receive money as early as next year and enable Dow
Corning, a joint venture between the Dow Chemical and Corning, to
emerge from Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   TINA BROWN LEAVING THE NEW YORKER
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown has resigned as editor of The New Yorker to start a
company with Miramax Films that will publish a monthly magazine,
publish books and produce films and television programming. The
announcement came after months of rumors of growing tension between
Ms. Brown and Conde Nast Publications, which owns the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   SEC IN TALKS OVER PRICE-FIXING
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is negotiating
settlements with several stock traders and as many as two dozen
brokerage firms after an investigation into possible price-fixing
on the Nasdaq stock market, executives at several Wall Street firms
said.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P 500 SET HIGHS
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index soared 27.28 points, to a record
1,935.39. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also jumped to a
new record, 1,166.38, as all major market gauges increased.
Investors expect the broad market to fare well in coming weeks
because of the favorable interest rates and a less negative
earnings picture.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year bond rose to 5.62 percent, from 5.60
percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   DREYFUS PORTFOLIO MANAGER ON LEAVE
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus placed the former portfolio manager of two of its mutual
funds on ``paid administrative leave.'' Federal and state
securities regulators are investigating the manager's personal
trading activities.
</P>
<P>
   HASHIMOTO PROMISES TAX CUTS
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto promised long-term tax
cuts, but he gave no details on how much the cuts would be.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO REDUCES SPENDING AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Mexico said that it would cut an additional $730 million from
federal spending in 1998. The new reductions bring Mexico's
cutbacks so far this year to $3.7 billion, closely matching its
lost oil revenue. And Finance Minister Angel Gurria said Mexico
expects a deficit this year, of about 1.25 percent of economic
output. The Mexican government depends on oil revenue for about a
third of its annual income.
</P>
<P>
   NO BIG CHANGES SEEN FOR GM
</P>
<P>
   As negotiators continued to work toward resolving a strike at
two General Motors parts plants in Flint, Mich., more signs emerged
that any deal might not produce big improvements in the automaker's
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST INDUSTRY DRAWS FIRE
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Senate Commerce Committee lambasted the broadcast
industry, cable companies and television manufacturers for failing
to cooperate on crucial technical and political issues that
threaten a smooth transition to high-definition TV.
</P>
<P>
   GLITCHES VEX HONG KONG AIRPORT
</P>
<P>
   Three days after its much-trumpeted opening, Hong Kong's $20
billion airport continues to lurch from crisis to crisis. Just as
the airport seems to be reducing the chaos in the passenger
terminal, computer glitches have all but paralyzed air-cargo
operations.
</P>
<P>
   $195 MILLION ANTI-DRUG CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   The White House's drug policy agency will introduce its first
paid national advertising to fight drug use among adolescents. The
campaign, the largest government-financed social marketing effort,
will have an initial budget of $195 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
