<HEADLINE>
FRED GOLDEN, 83, WHO PROMOTED BROADWAY SHOWS FOR 60 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fred Golden, a dean among theatrical advertising men
and winner of a special Tony Award in 1988, died July 3 at his home
in Manhattan. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Golden started his career in 1931 as a messenger for the Blaine
Thompson Company, a theater advertising agency that spawned most of
the firms in that business today. To the end he remained close to
the theater, sitting on industry committees, attending functions
and dispensing counsel as one of Broadway's elder statesmen.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of his 60-year career he handled the publicity for
more than 1,000 Broadway productions, including classics like ``The
Glass Menagerie,'' ``Kiss Me Kate,'' `` Roberts,'' ``Hello,
Dolly!,'' ``Funny Girl,'' ``A Raisin in the Sun,'' ``Gypsy'' and
``A Streetcar Named Desire.'' He was Frank Sinatra's advertising
representative for many years. Adweek magazine proclaimed him
``Broadway's Star Adman.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Golden was raised in West New York, N.J., the son of
Romanian immigrants who had arrived in steerage. He helped his
father deliver seltzer from a horse cart on weekdays, and if he
behaved, his mother took him on the ferry to Manhattan on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then she splurged and bought standing-room tickets at
the Metropolitan Opera _ $1 for both of them. Thus began his life
in and around the performing arts. When he was a teen-ager, he
worked as an usher at the Met and could not get over the fact that
he was hearing Mozart and getting paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   He went to work for the Blaine Thompson agency and rose to
become an owner and partner in the firm. After it was sold he moved
to the Ash-LeDonne agency in 1978 for six years, then joined
Diener/Hauser/Bates to create the Golden Group in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 68, after laboring for the talented and
vainglorious alike behind the scenes, he had his name on a
company's logo. He formally retired 10 years later.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tony Awards ceremonies in 1988 he was honored by the
League of American Theaters and Producers for ``Lifetime Service to
the Theater.'' Many of those present did not know him, but Broadway
insiders seemed in rare unanimity when voting him that rare special
award.
</P>
<P>
   Golden is survived by his wife, Hope Mansfield Golden; a sister,
Ruth Lev Peck of Fort Lee, N.J., and a stepson, Dr. Scott Smoller
of Plantation, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
