<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND HALF NO VACATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(SLANG) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dave Mlicki took his family to Universal Studios
over the All-Star break, while Eric Young enjoyed a relaxing
fishing outing in Mississippi. But don't expect the Los Angeles
Dodgers to spend a lot of time sharing vacation photos before they
return to action today.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers begin a four-game series against hot San Diego this
afternoon. The National League West-leading Padres are 12{ games
ahead of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   It won't get much easier for the Dodgers after the Padres
depart, since their next opponent is rival San Francisco, which
will be in town for a three-game series starting Monday. The NL
wild-card-leading Giants are 8{ games ahead of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the season is just in the infant stage. But
these two series could well set the tone for the Dodgers, who are
hoping to catch both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some work to do,'' said Young. ``Is it impossible? No.
These (two) series are important. There is no ifs, ands or buts
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman said, ``These are big games
playing the first-place club and the second-place club. I'm excited
about starting the second half and seeing where we go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Young back?: After doing some running exercises during
Wednesday's voluntary workout, a decision on whether Young will
return to the lineup will be made before today's game. He leads all
National Leaguers with 32 stolen bases, despite being limited to 71
games due to a strained right quadriceps muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to come back. It's important as far as being a
competitor, and I want us to get off to a good (second half)
start,'' said Young, who missed the last five games prior to the
All-Star break. ``But if I come back too soon, it can also hurt me
in the long run, whereas I can go in the (disabled list) for just
another week and be ready for the last two and a half months.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Fifth man: Hoffman said he would have an answer today on who
would be the Dodgers' new fifth starter and scheduled to pitch
Sunday against the Padres. There is speculation the Dodgers are
still interested in Seattle ace Randy Johnson (7-8, 5.07) and might
include reliever Antonio Osuna, infielder Wilton Guerrero and
outfielder Roger Cedeno in a deal. Another left-hander on the
trading block is Montreal's Carlos Perez (6-9, 3.69).
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said general manager Tommy Lasorda was working on the
situation. Lasorda was not available for comment Wednesday, since
he was in Washington, D.C., as part of a group supporting a
constitutional amendment that would allow Congress to protect the
U.S. flag from desecration. If the Dodgers do not make a deal,
possible starters include left-handed reliever Mark Guthrie or
left-handed minor-leaguers Gary Rath and Wil Brunson.
</P>
<P>
   __ Etc: Members of the Dodgers' 25-man roster who attended
Wednesday's workout included Young, Mlicki, Eric Karros, Darren
Dreifort, Scott Radinsky, Juan Castro, Adrian Beltre, Wilton
Guerrero and Tom Prince.... The Dodgers are leaning toward sending
Beltre back to minors this week to get him more at-bats. The third
baseman, who would prefer to stay, is batting .194 with a home run
and four RBI in 31 at-bats since being promoted from Double-A San
Antonio on June 24.... Right-hander Ramon Martinez began shoulder
exercises Wednesday. Martinez, who had season-ending shoulder
surgery June 30, said he will begin lifting weights in August. He
also said he will stay with the team and not depart to his native
Dominican Republic during the remainder of the season....
Right-hander Darren Hall pitched two innings for Class-A San
Bernardino at Rancho Cucamonga on Tuesday and said he is ready to
return. The reliever, who has been on the DL since April 8 with a
rotator cuff injury, is not expected to do any more rehab work. The
Dodgers are expected to either recall him or send him to minors
soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
