<HEADER>
A6762 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-MIDSEASON-     07-09 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-MIDSEASON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS FOCUS ON 2ND HALF, NOT EARLY-SEASON FAILURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Halfway through painting the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel,
Michelangelo didn't climb off the scaffolding and say, ``Oh, my
aching back! That's it! I'm outta here!''
</P>
<P>
   The people who carved Mount Rushmore didn't forget to include
Teddy Roosevelt's teeth or leave Abe Lincoln's face as smooth as a
baby's behind.
</P>
<P>
   When Mother Nature was creating the parfait-layered colors of
the Grand Canyon, she didn't say, ``Enough of this eroding
already!'' and send the Colorado River's course off toward Las
Vegas so she could spend some time at the tables.
</P>
<P>
   Get the idea? You just can't know how something is going to turn
out when you're in the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case of the Diamondbacks as they embark on the
second half of their inaugural season. It doesn't take a seamhead
to figure out they're a long way from even getting a sniff of the
playoffs. It's all there for the world to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a work in progress,'' Manager Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been things here and there that have been
disappointing, which is to be expected in a situation like this.
But we prefer to dwell on some of the good things that are
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   To see the direction in which the Diamondbacks might be headed,
one must first review where they have been.
</P>
<P>
   The team lost its first five games, 12 out of its first 14 and
31 of its first 39. Since that time, it has played a much more
competitive brand of ball, going 22-27 for a 30-58 mark at the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of the improvement,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest improvement has been on offense. The team's batting
average was near .230 for a large part of the first half and now is
at .249. Arizona is in the top five in home runs with 93.
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, the pitching has been lukewarm at best.
The staff has been particularly vulnerable to the long ball, having
given up 109 home runs, which is the most in the National League,
and second in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries also have been a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Andy Benes, who signed a three-year, $18 million
contract to become the team's No. 1 starter, needs to step it up a
few notches. He is 6-9 with a 4.73 ERA in 19 starts (129 innings).
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has not gotten much bang for its buck in right-hander
Willie Blair, who signed a three-year, $11.5 million free-agent
deal in December. At 3-12, he has the highest number of losses in
the National League. Perhaps Blair has not received enough
offensive support at times, but he also has to start pitching much
better.
</P>
<P>
   Blair still is enough of a commodity that he could provide help
for a contending team down the stretch. A trade by the July 31
deadline is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Brian Anderson, the team's top pick in the expansion
draft, does not have overpowering stuff, but the combination of
good control (he's among the NL leaders in fewest walks per nine
innings) and an aggressive nature has put him at 6-7. But he and
Blair have given up 21 home runs, Benes 19.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Jeff Suppan, the No. 2 pick in the expansion draft,
struggled, was sent to Triple-A Tucson, then recalled and sent back
to Tucson during the break for a second round of seasoning. At 1-7,
he has been a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Joel Adamson began the season as the fifth starter,
but suffered a rotator-cuff injury. Left-hander Omar Daal moved
into the rotation from the bullpen and became perhaps the most
consistent starter before going on the disabled list because of a
badly strained hamstring. He's projected to return next week.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen has undergone the most significant change.
Right-hander Felix Rodriguez began as the closer, then struggled
and now is on the DL (hip flexor). Veteran Gregg Olson took over
that role and has been an anchor with 11 saves. He also is a solid
presence in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are Barry Manuel, Scott Brow, Ricky Pickett and Russ
Springer and in their place are Amaury Telemaco, Alan Embree, Aaron
Small and Willie Banks. Showalter said he thinks right-hander
Telemaco, who can start or relieve, and left-hander Embree have
been significant upgrades. Right-hander Clint Sodowsky remains as a
setup man, but he has been hot and cold.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter is going with a three-headed catcher _ Jorge Fabregas,
Kelly Stinnett and Damian Miller. Fabregas began the season as a
starter, suffered an ankle injury and went on the DL and still
hasn't regained his footing. Stinnett has been very solid, and
Showalter is exploring the possibility of using Miller's
athleticism to go beyond the mask at other spots.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for Chicago right-hander Kerry Wood, Diamondbacks
first baseman Travis Lee would be a lock for NL Rookie of the Year.
If he can come close to matching his first-half numbers of .284, 17
homers and 47 RBIs, he might win it, anyway. What has been
overlooked is Lee's defense _ he already is close to being Gold
Glove-caliber. Watching him on a daily basis, there can be no
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter has tried two Andys (Stankiewicz and Fox) and a Tony
(Batista) at second, but the future may be with a Danny (Klassen),
who was called up from Tucson just before the break. After starting
his career as a shortstop, Klassen has been at second for only
about a month, but has made a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the signing of Blair, the critics' biggest target has
been shortstop Jay Bell, particularly since he signed a five-year,
$34 million free-agent deal. Critics have focused on what they say
is a lack of range defensively and an average bat.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Bell has fit the critics' pattern, looking his age
(32) or even older on defense with 11 errors. But he also has
played well at times. He has hit only .240 with 11 homers and 37
RBIs and leads the team in strikeouts with 80. He admits he needs
to pick up the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams, who came here in the
well-publicized trade with Cleveland to be near his children and
signed a five-year, $45 million extension that begins next year,
has been hit by nagging injuries _ wrist/hand, back and most
recently, foot. If Williams, hitting .271 with 14 homers and 41
RBIs, can stay healthy and get into one of his hot streaks, he can
carry the team a long way.
</P>
<P>
   The most pleasant surprise in the outfield has been center
fielder Devon White, acquired in a trade with Florida on
expansion-draft day. He was the team's first All-Star
representative after hitting .292 with 13 homers, 49 RBIs and 11
stolen bases and has tracked down virtually everything hit his way.
</P>
<P>
   The second-most pleasant surprise has been David Dellucci, who
was in Tucson for the first month of the season and then came on to
hit .290 with five homers, 31 RBIs, and some above-average glove
work.
</P>
<P>
   The other two outfielders _ Karim Garcia and Brent Brede, have
not panned out. Garcia, in particular, has been one of the biggest
disappointments. He was sent down to Tucson for about a month and
has hit better since his return, but not enough to suit his bosses.
He has a strong throwing arm, but has been shaky on a large
percentage of fly balls hit to him in right field.
</P>
<P>
   The team has turned down some trade offers and is considering
others. General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. and other front-office
personnel worked the rooms at the All-Star Game. The names of Blair
(Cardinals) and White (Giants) have surfaced in the past month or
so, but the Diamondbacks aren't likely to bite unless they can get
a few prospects.
</P>
<P>
   When the season ends, Arizona likely will go after more free
agents, such as Yankees outfielder Bernie Williams and perhaps
Padres right-hander Kevin Brown. There undoubtedly would be a lot
of support in a pursuit of Mariners left-hander Randy Johnson, who
lives in the Valley, but his age (35 in September) and his physical
status would seem to make him a large, 6-foot-7 risk. The question
then would be, would Johnson in that scenario still be better than
a younger pitcher with more potential?
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Diamondbacks' potential lies in its farm system,
with pitchers such as John Patterson, Vladimir Nunez, Nick
Bierbrodt, Brad Penny and Ben Ford, catchers Rod Barajas and Mark
Osborne, infielders Junior Spivey and Ron Hartman and outfielders
Mike Stoner, Rob Ryan, Jason Conti and Garry Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the biggest temptations that we fight, trying to
bring those guys along too soon,'' Showalter said. ``They all have
good upsides, but we have to try to be as patient as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The work is not complete by any means. Far from it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
