<HEADLINE>
AS CZAR, I'D BAN DH, SPIT TOBACCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If baseball is truly our national pastime, we should
select a commissioner the way we do the president.
</P>
<P>
   Let the American people decide. Give every man and woman _ and
child _ the opportunity to vote for candidates nominated by the
teams at a convention.
</P>
<P>
   Mistah Chairman, Mistah Chairman, the Atlanta Braves from the
great state of Georgia, the Empire State of the South, home of
Herschel Walker, Jimmy Carter and the `Gawja Peach,' the great Ty
Cobb . . . Atlanta, host to the world at the 1996 Summer Oh-lymic
Games, is pleased as punch to cast its vote for a man who needs no
introduction, a man who stands as tall as a Georgia pine. . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Get on with it!'' the Baltimore delegation cries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistah Chairman, the land of the free, and the home of the
Braves, proudly and unequivocally, casts its vote for the Rhett
Butler of his times, the ``next'' commissioner of major league
baseball . . . Ted Turner!!!''
</P>
<P>
   (insert horn-blowing here)
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't happen that way, of course. Baseball takes a Vatican
approach. The appointment is made in private, by the owners, behind
closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, the man we thought might become Interim Commissioner
for Life, officially will be named today.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us will sigh and think baseball could have done better.
Count me among those who believe the game hasn't had a ``real''
commissioner since they buried Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis. They
had to. He was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Landis was the game's original czar. A fearless leader. Selig, a
decent, kindly man, is not. He is an owner himself, which makes him
one of them. A company man.
</P>
<P>
   It's a thankless job, baseball commissioner. There are three
things in this world everyone knows how to do. Manage a newspaper.
Raise other people's children, and run big-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, I might not serve. But if forced to, and given
complete autonomy, here's my agenda: &QL; 
Eliminate the designated hitter. Batting is a God-given right.
Pitchers like to hit, and in their hearts some even think they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want me to take one, or let 'er rip?'' Andy Benes asked the
other day in Houston before he went to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go for it,'' Buck Showalter said, returning Benes' smile.
``Hit it where the grass don't grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliminate artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   Fine any active major league player who charges money for his
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   No radical realignment.
</P>
<P>
   Do away with home-run porches. If a left-hander can't hit one
330 feet he doesn't deserve a major league home run.
</P>
<P>
   Place a $4 price limit on ballpark suds.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminate any promotions _ notably Bat Night _ that arm fans
with potentially lethal weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Find some reason to suspend George Steinbrenner, again.
</P>
<P>
   Ban spit tobacco. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tell television that weekend Fall Classic games must be played
in the afternoon. Kids shouldn't have to stay up past midnight to
watch the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Change the name of BOB. Suggestions are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Shorten the games. Any pitcher who throws to first more than
three times while attempting to hold a runner on base will be shot.
</P>
<P>
   Halt expansion until the pitching catches up to the hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Commission a study to determine the viability of a revolutionary
rules change that would allow right-handed hitters to run to third
base and then to second, first, and home.
</P>
<P>
   As the game is played now, the left-handed batter has a big
advantage, since he is a yard closer to first base. His swing
starts him in the right direction. The right-handed hitter ends up
facing third. Is this fair?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there might be some confusion if the bases are loaded
and a right-handed hitter is at bat. But this could be worked out,
if baseball put its mind to it. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
