<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL SHOWS GLOBAL REACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major League Baseball delivered an excellent touch during the
pregame ceremonies at Tuesday's All-Star Game in Denver when it
displayed all the national flags of players in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Right there, only four flags away from the stars and stripes,
flapped one of the last reminders of communism, the Cuban flag.
Among the other flags waving in the mile-high winds were those from
Australia, the Dominican Republic, Japan, Panama, Puerto Rico,
Germany, Venezuela, Jamaica and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   No section of the globe outside the United States has had more
of an impact on the game than Latin American countries. To
demonstrate just how far the Latin player has made inroads into the
game, take a moment to remember the seventh inning of the All-Star
Game.
</P>
<P>
   The National League's infield had  &UR; Andres Galarraga (Venezuela)
at first,
 &UR; Fernando Vina (first generation American of Cuban heritage) at
second,  &UR; Edgar
 &UR; Renteria (Colombia) at shortstop and  &UR; Vinny Castilla (Mexico) at
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the number of Latins who were here, and it makes you
so proud to be one of them,'' said Chicago Cubs outfielder  &UR; Sammy
Sosa (Dominican), who did not play because of a sore shoulder. ``It
shows the world of our love for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 55 players who participated in the game, 17 were Latin.
Among the first-year All-Stars of Latin decent were  &UR; Rolando
Arrojo, who became the first Cuban defector to make an All-Star
team, Vina,  &UR; Omar Vizquel (Venezuela),  &UR; Bartolo Colon and  &UR; Ugueth
Urbina (Dominicans) and Renteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are more and more Latins making it to the major
leagues,'' Baltimore's &UR; Roberto Alomar said. ``We're showing we can
play at the highest level.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 39 Most Valuable Players, Alomar became the sixth
Latin-born player to win the award and third in the past nine
years. He joins  &UR; Juan Marichal (1965, Dominican), &UR; Tony Perez (1967,
Cuba),  &UR; Dave Concepcion (1982, Venezuela),  &UR; Julio Franco (1990,
Domincan) and
 &UR; Sandy Alomar (Puerto Rico), last year's MVP. &QL; 
Bronx bombs away &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees are having such an incredible season that
already there is talk of possibly winning an insane-sounding 120
games.
</P>
<P>
   With exactly 81 games remaining, the Yankees would finish 101-61
by going 40-41 the rest of the way. And they appear way too good to
play .500 ball the rest of the season, especially with 43 of their
remaining games to be played at Yankee Stadium, which has become
the in place to be in New York this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees also should see the return of  &UR; Bernie Williams and
 &UR; Chili Davis before the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've played like a great team, no doubt about that,'' Mets
Manager &UR; 
 &UR; Bobby Valentine said. &QL; 
Shades of bloopers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Minnesota's  &UR; Bob Tewksbury retired St. Louis' hulking
first baseman,
 &UR; Mark McGwire, with a pair of slow-pitch-softball-looking pitches
last week, Cincinnati pitching coach &UR; Don Gullett got to thinking
about a game against the Pirates that featured Reds reliever &UR; Pedro
Borbon, who loved throwing a similar pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing a game in Pittsburgh in 1970 and  &UR; Roberto
Clemente was up in a crucial situation,'' Gullett said. ``Manager
 &UR; Sparky Anderson sent pitching coach  &UR; Larry Shepard to the mound to
give Borbon the message, `Don't throw that blooper pitch to
Clemente. I don't want to see the ball land in one of the three
rivers.' '' &QL; 
Clipped redbirds &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals wound up with the worst interleague
record, something that did not sit well with Manager  &UR; Tony La
Russa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time they have major league meetings, I'm going to
avoid the eyes of any National Leaguer I see,'' said La Russa,
whose Cardinals finished 4-9 against the AL. ``I'm embarrassed that
I'm letting the league down, and I'm embarrassed that these
American League clubs think this is what we are. It's adding insult
to injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the Cardinals look worse is that their losses were
against the AL Central, which features only one club (Cleveland)
with a winning record. The rest of the division is a combined 46
games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis, expected to strongly compete for the NL Central
title, is floundering under .500, and some of their players are
even ready to admit the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stink,'' said Cardinals outfielder  &UR; Brian Jordan, who leads
the NL in batting and is eligible for free agency after the season.
``No mystery about it. This puts you into a bad attitude. There'll
be some trades made here soon.'' &QL; 
Remember the bird &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Detroit is going bonkers over rookie right-hander  &UR; Matt
Anderson, selected first overall in last year's June draft. Already
talk around Motown is creating comparisons to another hard-throwing
right-hander who burst on the scene in 1976 _  &UR; Mark ``The Bird''
Fidrych.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, asked if he knew of Fidrych, replied, ``No. He was
here in 1976? That was the year I was born.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has made quite an impression since being called up less
than two weeks ago. His fastball has already been clocked at 100
mph. The Tigers' closer of the future made several fans out of
Cincinnati hitters last week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dmitri Young swung and missed at three straight pitches from
Anderson, clocked at 99, 99 and 100 mph, then told teammate  &UR; Barry
Larkin, ``I wasn't even close to that last one.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin said, ``I got news for you. You weren't close on any of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 21, then threw another 100 mph fastball to the next
batter,  &UR; Willie
 &UR; Greene, a good fastball hitter who managed to foul the pitch back
to the screen before turning to Detroit catcher  &UR; Joe Oliver and
saying, ``I'm in trouble.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
