<SLUG> BC-BBM-DBACKS-MINORS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETHBRIDGE'S CUST BUSTS OUT WITH 12-FOR-24 SPREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Jack Cust, the Diamondbacks' No. 1 pick in the 1997 amateur
draft, accepted congratulations from fans after word spread that
the grand slam he had just hit for Lethbridge happened on his 19th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great story, except that it wasn't true. Not the grand
slam, but the part about his birthday. It seems that Cust turned 19
on Jan. 7, not July 1. Somehow the numbers got transposed, probably
because in Canada the day comes before the month. So 1/7 was
interpreted as July 1 in Lethbridge, Alberta. Get it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they got mixed up,'' he said. ``It was kind of
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so funny, however, is how Cust is treating Pioneer League
pitchers. A week ago, he was hitting .207 with no home runs, no
RBIs and 12 strikeouts in 29 at-bats. But after a 12-for-24 blitz,
he is up to .340 with a homer, nine RBIs and only five more
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Equally as impressive, he has walked 21 times, more than twice
as many times as the next player on the Black Diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to get my swing back,'' he said. ``I just feel
real good the way I'm hitting the ball. I was thinking too much at
the plate. Anyone who plays baseball knows you shouldn't think too
much. You've got a fraction of a second to recognize the pitch and
hit the pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Cust, drafted for his power hitting out of a New Jersey high
school, is playing left field, where his future in the organization
lies. Earlier in the year, he played first base for a couple of
weeks at Class A South Bend after
 &UR; Wyley Steelmon got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't go so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel comfortable in South Bend,'' he said. ``I was
pressing a little bit. Here, I'm not worrying about the home runs.
I figure they'll come.''
</P>
<P>
   Cust hit well his first week there, ``but I tried to do too much
after that,'' he said. ``I hit a couple of singles and doubles, and
then I wanted to drive the ball even more. I tried to pull
everything. That's not really my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a year out of high school, Cust is learning to be patient
about his progress. He just wishes his friends would understand
that he won't be joining the Diamondbacks any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask me, `Is it going to be next year? Is it going to be
next year?' '' he said. ``Nobody really understands baseball until
they're part of the game. It's not like basketball, where you see
somebody in college and then they're playing against  &UR; (Michael)
Jordan on Sunday afternoon.'' &QL; 
Sidewinders stuff &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the All-Star break, Tucson had won only twice in
its past nine games. Pitcher  &UR; Vladimir Nunez won both games.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the team's leaders at the break: batting average _  &UR; Mike
Stoner (.375); hits _  &UR; Edwin Diaz (82); homers _  &UR; Rob Ryan (12);
RBIs _ Ryan (46); stolen bases _  &UR; Hanley Frias (13); wins _  &UR; Bob
Wolcott (6); strikeouts _ Wolcott (64); saves _  &UR; Ben Ford (9).
Ryan, an outfielder, replaced  &UR; Danny
 &UR; Klassen in the Triple-A All-Star Game in Norfolk on Wednesday
night. &QL; 
Brief stints &QL; 
High Desert, which has taken over first place in the California
League in the second half, had won four straight through Tuesday,
including a 21-10 victory over Lancaster. The Mavericks had 23
hits.
</P>
<P>
   High Desert right-hander  &UR; Brad Penny leads the California League
with 123 strikeouts and needs 20 more to break the league record
set last year by Nunez.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Adam Neubart, a 43rd-round pick from Rutgers in the
June draft, replaced Kevin Sweeney on the Mavs roster. Sweeney went
on the disabled list because of a pulled back muscle. Catcher Rod
Barajas is on the DL (shoulder). Josh McAfee came up from
Lethbridge and Brad Allison was sent down from Tucson. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
