<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6775 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCREENWRITER-FOUND-2t     07-09 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCREENWRITER-FOUND-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREENWRITER'S BODY PULLED FROM AQUEDUCT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHERRY JOE CROSBY, JESSE HIESTAND AND BHAVNA MISTRY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Calif. _ The yearlong mystery of missing screenwriter
Gary Devore came to a tragic end Wednesday when his body was found
in his Ford Explorer submerged in 12 to 15 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   An amateur sleuth calling himself ``Dr. Find It'' who had been
relentlessly tracking the disappearance led authorities to Devore's
vehicle, which apparently ran off the Antelope Valley Freeway when
the writer fell asleep and plunged into the California Aqueduct
south of Palmdale, 62 miles northeast of downtown Los Angeles.
Devore's skeletal remains were found in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Devore was on his way home to Carpinteria in Santa Barbara
County northwest of Los Angeles from a visit with actress Marsha
Mason in Santa Fe, N.M., to work on a script when he disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   For Devore's wife, the discovery only triggered more questions
and new concerns.
</P>
<P>
   She said she could make no sense of how San Diego resident
Douglas Crawford could solve a mystery that had baffled authorities
for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know how the hell he knew. And I want to know who he
is and I want to know why, if he was interested in that
information, he didn't come forward far, far sooner,'' said Wendy
Oates-Devore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know why no one else, when there was a $100,000
reward, could find this man.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that there were no preliminary indications of
foul play and that dental records will be used to verify Devore's
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford led authorities to the Explorer via e-mail after
conducting his own long-shot search.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by news stories last month on the anniversary of
Devore's disappearance, Crawford recalled the case of an Orange
County woman who disappeared en route to Montana: Three years
later, her car was found in the muddy water of the California
Aqueduct _ but only after another crash occurred at the same spot.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford examined Devore's route, concluded that he had fallen
asleep and crashed sometime after his last 1:15 a.m. call to his
wife. He figured there was only one place for a vehicle to
disappear: the California Aqueduct, where it crosses the Antelope
Valley Freeway near Avenue S.
</P>
<P>
   Tracing Devore's likely route from Barstow home to Carpinteria,
Crawford drove south on the Antelope Valley Freeway and stopped
where it crosses the aqueduct.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail Crawford subsequently sent to Devore's publicist
Michael Sands, he wrote: ``I climbed down the embankment to the
aqueduct access road. I first saw the large piece of white metal
laying slightly up the embankment. This appeared to be a hood
re-enforcement for a white Ford, possibly an Explorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford then found a broken, plastic light cover, imprinted
with a serial number. He took the part to a Ford dealership, to
confirm it came from an Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   When Sands got Crawford's e-mail, he contacted the Santa Barbara
County Sheriff's Department. They discounted the significance of
finding Explorer parts beside the aqueduct while Crawford persisted
in asking for a search.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, CHP officials visited the aqueduct Tuesday with
Crawford, checking the area where he had found the car parts. On
Wednesday, officials returned to the aqueduct with the Los Angeles
County Sheriff's Department Emergency Services team of six scuba
divers.
</P>
<P>
   The sport-utility vehicle was found with all four wheels on the
ground directly beneath the overpass. The license plate matched
that of Devore's missing vehicle, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised we saw anything,'' diver Larry McCabe said. ``I
didn't know if we were on a wild goose chase. ... I didn't know how
good the information was. I was just hoping we would find
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer was filled with water and covered in mud and algae,
its undercarriage dripping strands of aquatic plants, as it was
slowly pulled from the water. All its windows were smashed, and
major body damage was evident on the driver's side and front end.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that ``partial human remains'' were found in the
driver's seat, with the seat belt fastened. The body was clad in
cowboy boots, western style jeans, a western shirt and a
distinctive large belt buckle.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's officials defended their work during the past year,
saying they had little evidence and widely varying theories about
Devore's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area has been driven over and flown over by helicopter
and fixed-wing numerous times,'' said Sgt. Michael Burridge of the
Santa Barbara Sheriff's Department, which has been handling the
missing person case filed for the Carpinteria resident. ``I have
been over this bridge numerous times.''
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to Crawford, Burridge added: ``I'm just glad he was
able to read it and give us the ability to put some resolution to
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Devore disappeared in the early hours of June 28, 1997, while
driving back to Carpinteria from Santa Fe, where he had been
working on a script at Mason's home.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   He called his wife about 1:15 a.m. to say he had passed Barstow
and would be home in a few hours. He never showed up.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his disappearance, Devore had been upbeat because
he had ``broken the back of the script,'' a remake of the 1949
movie ``The Big Steal,'' Sands said Wednesday. Devore would have
made his directorial debut with the RKO film.
</P>
<P>
   When Devore failed to return home, his wife offered a $10,000
reward but later withdrew it for fear that bounty hunters would
kill the screenwriter to collect the money. Later, a $100,000
reward was offered in his disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Devore's screen credits include ``Back Roads,'' which co-starred
Sally Field and Tommy Lee Jones, ``The Dogs of War'' with
Christopher Walken and ``Running Scared'' with Gregory Hines and
Billy Crystal.
</P>
<P>
   For Oates-Devore, there are still unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the autopsy has been performed and I know that someone
did not put a bullet in him or anything else, then I will be glad
for him that there was no pain for him other than his car,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know this was an accident. I want it proven to me.
At this point, I at least deserve that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
