u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEE-STADIUM-1S     07-09 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEE-STADIUM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS GATE RISES, STEINBRENNER SOFTENS ON BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 15th graf to make it read Yankees rank ninth among major
league teams in attendance, not simply among American League
teams.)  (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the Yankees winning games at a historic pace and
drawing fans to Yankee Stadium at a record rate, George
Steinbrenner said Wednesday that gains in attendance could lead to
discussions about keeping the team in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone from Tampa, Fla., Steinbrenner said that
if the Yankees draw 3 million fans this season and could be
guaranteed similar attendance in the future, he would be willing to
talk about staying in Yankee Stadium after the team's lease expires
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are on pace to draw a franchise-best 2.83 million
fans this season; the franchise record was 2.63 million in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   It was a startling concession from Steinbrenner, the Yankees'
principal owner, who has complained for almost a decade that he
cannot make money because of traffic and safety concerns in the
Bronx and a dearth of luxury boxes at 75-year-old Yankee Stadium.
With the support of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, he has openly
campaigned for a new stadium on the West Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the 3 million and then we'll talk about the Bronx after the
season,'' Steinbrenner said. ``That isn't getting me where I want
to be, but maybe it would be worth talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   While Steinbrenner was not specific about what Bronx officials
could do to guarantee 3 million fans, he issued a challenge to
Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer to find a way to make it
worth his while to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Fernando Ferrer want to guarantee we'll get 3 million?''
he said. ``Tell them to put their money where their mouth is. If he
can guarantee we'll get 3 million, then I'll sit down and talk
about the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``That number still doesn't get me where I need to be, but he
threw that figure out, so I'm calling his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   While Steinbrenner offered, for the first time, a starting point
for discussions about keeping the team in the Bronx, any talks
would surely include additional parking, easing the traffic
congestion around the stadium and finding a way to increase the
number of luxury boxes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Yankees, who begin the second half of the season Thursday
night in St. Petersburg with a stunning 61-20 record, have
attracted 1,362,987 fans in 39 home dates, an average of 34,948 per
game.
</P>
<P>
   They would have to average 38,977 fans in their final 42 home
dates to exceed 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer, whose office issued a news release this week which
focused on the pursuit of the 3 million mark, was excited about the
new expression of interest in remaining in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Yankees have never reached the 3 million mark,
which has long been considered a sort of magic number in
discussions of attendance, the Mets did it in 1987 and 1988 after
winning a World Series championship in 1986. The Toronto Blue Jays
drew 4 million in 1991, 1992 and 1993, and the Colorado Rockies set
the major league record of 4.48 million in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly willing to accept that challenge,'' said Ferrer.
``The money is there. Let's build the Metro North station so more
fans can come to the games. Let's promote the players. Let's build
up the Bronx instead of trying to suppress attendance.''
</P>
<P>
   While issuing his challenge, Steinbrenner also scoffed at the
Yankees' 9 percent increase in attendance over last year at this
time, pointing out that they are still ninth among major league
teams in attendance. He continued to claim that fans hesitate to
attend night games at the Stadium because of the ``perception''
that it is unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear all this talk about record numbers,'' Steinbrenner
said. ``I think we'll do 2.6. It's going to have to be very good
just to get us to 2.6, whereas Cleveland and Baltimore will be
about 4 million. The perception, right or wrong, is that people
don't want to come to the Bronx at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer, pointing out that the Stadium is one of the safest
places in New York when the Yankees are playing because of the
heightened police presence there, said, ``The only crime at Yankee
Stadium would be taking them to Manhattan and spending over a
billion dollars to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendance data can be used to bolster both sides of the debate.
Those in favor of keeping the Yankees in the Bronx argue that this
season's increase proves that a winning team can thrive in the
Bronx. Provide a dominating club, they argue, and fans will pour
through the turnstiles. If the current facility is improved, and a
new Metro North terminal in the Bronx gives better access,
supporters say, then the figures will increase more.
</P>
<P>
   But those in favor of relocating the Yankees, like Steinbrenner
and Giuliani, can argue that attendance would be even higher if the
games were being played in Manhattan, and that this season is an
aberration because the Yankees have played exceptionally well. Give
the fans a new stadium along the lines of Baltimore's Camden Yards
or Cleveland's Jacobs Field, preferably with a retractable roof, in
a location friendlier to mass transit and they will pour through
the turnstiles. In that case, supporters of a Manhattan stadium
say, the team would not have to win 75 percent of its games to
attract fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Location, location, location,'' Steinbrenner said. ``We'd sell
out every night if we played in Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner provided statistics that Yankee officials had
compiled documenting the average attendance of five teams with
recently built stadiums, for the 10 years before they moved and the
years since. The teams had all experienced a tremendous spurt in
attendance entering this season, he said, from 41 percent for the
Chicago White Sox to 43 percent for the Texas Rangers, 62 percent
for the Baltimore Orioles, 75 for the Toronto Blue Jays 135 percent
for the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to compete with Cleveland for an American League
Championship and I was competing with Baltimore for the division,''
said Steinbrenner. ``How do I compete when they draw 15,000 to
20,000 more fans a game?''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that the Yankees have the wealthiest cable television
contract in history for a sports franchise at more than $500
million, Steinbrenner said, ``I also have a payroll that is
considerable.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see if the fans remain enamored by the
Yankees' pursuit of greatness during the regular season. While the
Yankees are on pace to set a major league record with 122
victories, how appealing will it be to witness No. 79 on a sunny
afternoon in August if beaches and barbecues beckon?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they would come,'' Steinbrenner said. ``They've wanted
winners in this city a long time. Look at how the Knicks and the
Rangers draw. They're sold out every game. Location, location,
location.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer blasted the notion of a potential fall in interest this
summer, saying: ``I don't see any early indication of that. Fourth
of July weekend, when everybody is doing something else, Yankee
attendance was great. That argument goes out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner could use the heftier attendance figures to argue
that this is as impressive as it will get, and that the numbers
actually provide a reason for the Yankees to move. He could say
that 3 million fans is commendable, but that it occurred in a
once-in-a-lifetime season and is still less than a handful of other
teams have drawn. Or, Steinbrenner could see 3 million and then,
surprisingly, see the Bronx in his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do 3 million,'' Steinbrenner said several times. ``Say,
`George, we're going to do this for you.' I'm doing my part. Let's
see them do their part. Don't come in with 2.6. It's got to be 3
million.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6783 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     07-09 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASORDA MUST FIND WAY TO WIN TO STAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Whether you like Tom Lasorda or hate him, know
this. If anyone can make something of this Dodgers season, he is
the man.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the hellfire and brimstone that so endeared him to fans
and players for most of his 20 years as manager. This team is far
too smug for that approach. Lasorda, back now as interim general
manager, is gone if he doesn't turn around this dreadful season and
he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter how many Fox people he schmoozes. It might not
even matter how many games the Dodgers (43-44) win the rest of the
way. Many think the firing of manager Bill Russell and executive
vice president Fred Claire was the first step _ and not the last _
in a radical overhaul of the club.
</P>
<P>
   But Lasorda is a fighter and he desperately wants to keep his
job. Long before he was passed over for the spot when Al Campanis
was fired in 1987, he dreamed of building his own team. He has
never been an interim anything.
</P>
<P>
   He can't go to Rupert Murdoch in November and say, ``Hey, look
at the way I cut San Diego's 13{-game lead in the West to four.''
That isn't going to work the way it did with Peter O'Malley. That
sends him back to kissing babies, and someone like Pat Gillick
pulling the strings.
</P>
<P>
   For Lasorda, the future is now, beginning tonight with the
second-half opener against the Padres. The deal to acquire closer
Jeff Shaw from Cincinnati cost the Dodgers two players who could
have helped down the line. Shaw, however, can close out games Scott
Radinsky and Antonio Osuna couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   If Shaw remains the league's top save man the way he was with
the Reds, the Dodgers will pick up some games. Shaw also will build
a confidence in the starting rotation and the team in general.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda now needs to go out and get a fifth starter. The team
needs a winning streak and they aren't going to do that with a hole
in their rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda talks a lot about 1983, when the team gained 10 games on
Atlanta in 11 days. What he doesn't say is that feat was the
Halley's Comet of comebacks. The Dodgers also used so much energy
getting back in the race, they fizzled in the final two weeks. And
that team was much younger than this.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Dodgers are so banged up, an $18.5 million player might
have trouble finding a training table.
</P>
<P>
   They are hoping to get back shortstop Jose Vizcaino, their
steadiest defensive player and valuable No.2 hitter. His absence,
because of a badly sprained right ankle, put added pressure on
leadoff man Eric Young, who should have gone on the DL 10 days ago
when he strained his right quad for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   Divisions are won at the top of the order. The Dodgers learned
that last year with four hitters who had 30 or more home runs but a
second-place finish in the West. Young is to be applauded for his
grit, a rare virtue on past Dodgers teams, but leading the league
in stolen bases is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield, who replaced Eric Karros 10 days ago in the
cleanup spot, needs protection. Raul Mondesi, moved to the third
spot during the same shuffling, had a great road trip before the
break. He probably is the best all-around center fielder in the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half last year, Mondesi batted .326 with 13 homers
and 39 RBI. But he also batted .251 overall with runners in scoring
position. That can't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, wounded by the demotion from fourth to fifth in the
order, won't have the same opportunities on offense, but the knee
injury that cost him 22 games at the beginning of the season is
much improved.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla, the left-handed bat acquired in the May 15 Mike
Piazza trade, had a miserable first half. Even if he recovers
completely from the intestinal infection that zapped much of his
strength, Bonilla is not the same player who drove in 97 runs last
year for the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla is coming off surgery to his left wrist and left
Achilles' tendon. Both injuries require at least a year to recover
fully. He also is 35 and is due $15 million over the next 2{ years.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely the team will change his position unless it moves
Karros. Bonilla is too slow to play the outfield. The Dodgers liked
youngster Adrian Beltre during his brief trial at third, but they
want him playing every day, which means Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have a favorable schedule in the second half with 14
of their first 18 at home. Between Aug. 7 and Sept. 6, they play 21
of 28 games at Dodger Stadium. They close the season with six
straight and nine of 12 at home.
</P>
<P>
   But will it matter? Will a veteran team respond to this
challenge when most have multiyear contracts? The Baltimore
Orioles, predicted by many to win the American League East are
38-50, 26{ games behind the New York Yankees. Their roster is
filled with potential free agents, anxious for new contracts but
not anxious enough show they are worth more money.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda has all that to deal with in the final three months of
the season. The big trade for Mike Piazza failed to produce the
leadership they have been missing for years.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he has to allow new manager Glenn Hoffman to establish
a new identity, but it's difficult because Lasorda has waited so
long for this position.
</P>
<P>
   How long will he keep it? It still is worth coming to the
ballpark to find out.
</P>
<P>
   DODGERS REPORT CARD
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   It all starts with Eric Young, who leads the NL in stolen bases,
but he's been out of the lineup too much. Gary Sheffield has been
superb but needs support from Bobby Bonilla and Raul Mondesi. With
a hot streak, Eric Karros could get 100 RBI, but he has to realize
that barring an injury to Sheffield he will never be the cleanup
hitter here again. C-
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   The addition of catcher Charles Johnson and shortstop Jose
Vizcaino plus the switch of Mondesi to center are improvements. But
Bonilla needs to have a consistent second half at third or teams
will expose him. B
</P>
<P>
   STARTING PITCHING
</P>
<P>
   No one has stepped up to take Ramon Martinez's place. Ismael
Valdes had two brilliant starts lately but has not shown ace
tendencies. Neither has Chan Ho Park. Darren Dreifort has the tools
but is short on experience. C
</P>
<P>
   BULLPEN
</P>
<P>
   Bringing in Jeff Shaw not only means saves, it means putting
Scott Radinsky and Antonio Osuna back where they pitch best, in
setup roles. That also means less quality time for guys like Greg
McMichael, who has allowed eight of his last 10 inherited base
runners to score. C
</P>
<P>
   BENCH
</P>
<P>
   Except for Matt Luke, this group has not shown up. Jim
Eisenreich acknowledges he has been a flop the past two years. Juan
Castro is solid backup infielder with emphasis on backup. Too many
guys just happy to be here. F
</P>
<P>
   MANAGER
</P>
<P>
   Depends who you are calling the manager. Is it Lasorda, who
walks through the clubhouse trying to pump guys up, or is it Glenn
Hoffman, who has gotten good marks for game management? Lasorda
doesn't connect with these players, Hoffman needs to have a
presence in the clubhouse. INC.
</P>
<P>
   OVERALL
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy for the veterans to mail in the rest of the
season. Everyone has a multiyear contract except Johnson. Veterans
blamed the moves for the first-half mediocrity. No one looked in
the mirror. Shaw will add confidence because the team knows he will
close out victories. C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
