<HEADLINE>
SHOOTERS FAIL TO SPARK FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Well, so much for a winning streak. For the
third time around, the Sparks failed to figure out the Sacramento
Monarchs, who escaped this time with a 76-71 victory in front of a
Los Angeles franchise-low 4,851 at the Forum on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tangela Smith came off the bench to lead the Monarchs with
career-high 20 points on 7 of 11 from the field, and LaTasha Byears
added 18.
</P>
<P>
   Poor shooting haunted the Sparks, who hit for 36 percent, while
the Monarchs made a 52 percent connection.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks were looking to string together some wins during this
four-game home stand after defeating the Eastern Conference leading
Charlotte Sting on Tuesday. But so much for that. The streak ended
at one. The Sparks are in the cellar at 3-8. The Monarchs moved two
spots forward to third in the conference with a 4-8 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the Sparks had their chances, but they were denied.
</P>
<P>
   Franthea Price (10 points) made only one of three free throws,
but it gave the Monarchs a 70-69 advantage with 1:25 to go. Then
Lisa Leslie hit a 12-foot baseline shot with 1:04. Byears' layup
returned the lead to Sacramento with 46 seconds on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks' Pamela McGee was then charged with an offensive foul
to put the ball back to her former team. McGee then picked up her
fifth foul, sending Byears to the charity stripe for two points
with 25 seconds to play as the Monarchs took a three-point lead and
the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
