<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-09 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCHISE WITHERING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Antonio Osuna asks to be traded, Eric Karros
breathes a sigh of relief when he sees his jersey hanging in his
locker and Gary Sheffield has to be talked into playing in the
All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition dies ponderously. The once-youthful, glowing face of
the organization formerly known as the Dodgers is growing gray and
gaunt in front of our eyes. Those who can bear to look will see in
the first half of the Dodgers' season all the classic stages of a
grave illness as outlined by physician Elisabeth Kubler-Ross some
30 years back.
</P>
<P>
   Denial, anger, bargaining and depression. The Dodgers have been
there, done and felt that. And if they eventually pull the trigger
on the long-discussed deal that would send Ismael Valdes and/or
Wilton Guerrero or some other combination of youth and promise to
Seattle for veteran left-hander Randy Johnson, you'll know they've
reached the fifth and final stage, acceptance of the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   What is dying is an era when players culled from the farm teams
matured into stars, or at least everyday players whose constancy
and consistency anchored the mother club. The Dodgers squad that
will host San Diego today in the first game of the rest of the
season will have 10 faces that didn't grace the opening-day roster.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 percent turnover in a matter of a few months, while
wildly out of character for a franchise heretofore considered as
sleepy as Rip Van Winkle, is consistent with baseball's depraved
new world where everything changes but the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers under previous owner Peter O'Malley kept brushing
off signs the times kept flashing, never more obdurately than when
they had the opportunity to secure the services of catcher Mike
Piazza well into the next millennium. They balked, signing him for
two years instead. Their denial of baseball's evolving economics
cracked open the door that led to Piazza's departure this spring as
well as the window of opportunity for him to become baseball's
first $100-million man.
</P>
<P>
   With new ballparks _ and new teams _ springing up across the
country like concrete mushrooms, more teams have revenues to burn.
Big-name, free-agent ballplayers have been the beneficiaries,
commanding salaries in upwards of $70 million from a few cash-rich
teams while the rest of the league struggles to adapt (or in some
cases, survive).
</P>
<P>
   The result is something only a moving company could love;
players changing addresses more often than people in the
witness-protection program. A USA Today survey found that 60
percent of the players on opening-day rosters were not with the
organization that they first played for. Paul Konerko's abrupt
departure to Cincinnati last week notwithstanding, the Dodgers
remain ahead of the curve, with 11 players on their current 25-man
roster who have bled only Dodger Blue (in addition, there are two
others, Todd Hollandsworth and Ramon Martinez, on the disabled
list).
</P>
<P>
   Time was when Konerko, the reigning minor-league player of the
year, would have been untouchable. A franchise doesn't produce five
consecutive Rookies of the Year, after all, by throwing its top
prospects to the tradewinds. But for all the success of their
first-year players, the Dodgers have been abject failures in the
standings, producing nary a single win in the postseason this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, the Dodgers under O'Malley were stuck on
potential for an awfully long while. The same won't be said of the
team under the Fox Group, which has moved swiftly to dispense of
the new in favor of the tried-and-true.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers fail to make up the 13{ games that separate them
from the division-leading San Diego Padres or aren't able to
surpass the five teams currently ahead of them in the wild-card
race, it won't be for a lack of experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox braintrust was angered by Piazza's preoccupation with
making baseball history to the possible exclusion of enhancing
Dodgers lore. So Piazza _ along with Todd Zeile _ was shipped to
Florida for catcher Charles Johnson, infielder Bobby Bonilla and
outfielders Sheffield and Jim Eisenreich. The quartet is nine
months removed from a successful World Series run, which shouldn't
be long enough to have forgotten what it takes in the clubhouse and
on the field to be a champion.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Fred Claire was infuriated by Hideo Nomo's
petulance _ his inability to find the plate no doubt fueled the
flames. So the pitcher was dropped from the roster and traded to
the Mets for pitcher Greg McMichael and Dave Mlicki.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that the Dodgers added more experience without
getting appreciably older; their opening-day roster averaged 28.8
years (it stands today at 28.5).
</P>
<P>
   The decisions to fire Claire and manager Bill Russell and give
interim manager Glenn Hoffman a broom to clean house if he saw fit
smacked of desperation. It was as though president Bob Graziano
made a Faustian pact (in this case, Tommy Lasorda), trading
steadfastness for the promise of a quick turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   There's no good time to pull the plug on tradition, but now
seems a particularly curious time to do it. With the Padres barely
discernible on the horizon and the organization in a state of flux,
a case could have been made to let the boys play out the summer, if
only so Graziano and Lasorda could discern who are the men among
them. What better way to read talent than by taking it off the
shelf?
</P>
<P>
   A lineup with Konerko, Guerrero, Adrian Beltre, Juan Castro and
Dennis Reyes in it would have afforded Lasorda the chance to
eyeball the future. And had Russell been allowed to play out the
hand he was dealt, his strengths and weaknesses also would have
come into sharper focus.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Dodgers have invested an awful lot in a season
that itself may be on life support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
