<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER SCORES HAVE PREDOMINATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those rascals at the U.S. Golf Association are sure having a fun
summer. They've already staged two of their big national
championships to identify the planet's best golfer by either
gender, age group, ability to impersonate a walking, shot-making
billboard or just play golf for fun.
</P>
<P>
   And what jokesters they are.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after showing the best male players in the world what
it's like to be thankful for reaching a par-4 in 3 and getting off
the green with a 2-putt, they showed the world's best women players
that golf can still be a game of pluses.
</P>
<P>
   Like plus-32 over par for last-place finisher Kim Bauer to
plus-6, which is where youngsters Se Ri Pak and Jenny Chuasiriporn
found themselves at the end of regulation on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pak finally emerged the winner after 20 more holes on Monday in
what was the most exciting women's open in memory. And who knows,
maybe the USGA will wind up being responsible for creating golf's
next great rivalry. Both Pak and Chuasiriporn are 20 and plan to be
around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, with zero fanfare, is living up the the kind of
expectations some set for Tiger Woods, who downplays any talk of a
rivalry with the other young guns of the PGA Tour. She's a rookie
and has already won back-to-back majors on the LPGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   So far the best shot of the year has to be Pak's pitch while
standing knee deep in a water hazard on the 18th playoff hole. And
she's already got a Woods-style endorsement deal with Samsung, the
giant Korean electronics company.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn plans to finish her senior year at Duke University,
though her personality is well-suited for and needed on the ladies
professional tour.
</P>
<P>
   __ The next stop: Up next on the USGA's summer road show is the
U.S. Senior Open at Riviera Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, tournament officials promised to grow Open-style rough
at Riviera. Look for grass deep enough to swallow small animals and
golf bags.
</P>
<P>
   The Senior Open, July 20-26, will have its usual famous field,
which still includes Jack Nicklaus. He will skip next month's PGA
Championship but plans to play in this week's Senior players
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus has a bad left hip, which hurts his game. But it is
still good enough for a sixth place finish at this year's Masters
and 43rd place at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Senior Open features two junior golf clinics hosted
by former champion Dave Stockton and tour pros Jim Dent and Al
Geiberger. The clinics will be from 8 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. July 20
and 21 at Riviera's driving range. The clinics will be limited to
200 participants each day from the L.A. County Sheriff's Youth
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   __ Golf and the law: A survey by Menlo Park-based The
Affiliates, a staffing service specializing in filling legal
positions, found that 20 percent of the attorneys responding listed
golf as their favorite sport, nearly double the amount who liked to
spend time with the wife, kids and pets.
</P>
<P>
   Reading was favored by 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   __ Wearing out Nike: Camarillo's Chris Zambri is making steady
progress up the Nike Tour money list. This year he's played in 14
events, winning $83,259, good for second place.
</P>
<P>
   The top finisher receives exempt status on the regular tour next
year and the numbers two through 15 earn their tour cards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
