<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6790 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-MCCLOUD-LADN     07-09 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-MCCLOUD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLY-ANGLING TECHNIQUE PROVES VALUABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCLOUD, Calif. _ In hockey, high-sticking is a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   On the Upper McCloud River, it's a goal... and one of the surest
ways to put fish on a fly when flows are furious and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   The fly-angling technique involves raising the rod high off the
water to keep the floating line from being grabbed by the current
and giving the bug pattern an unnatural presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't high-stick, you get a `belly' (slack) in your
line, the water catches it and you get drag, which makes your
insect imitation look like a jet skier,'' said fly-angling guide
Terry Edelmann of nearby Cottonwood. ``And fish aren't going to hit
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A sixth-generation Shasta County resident whose family has been
fishing the McCloud in neighboring Siskiyou County for five
generations, Edelmann appreciates more than most the challenges of
high water, volcanic outcrops and strange undercurrents that
characterize the river this year.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by his son's trusty sheepdog, Tops (Spot in
reverse), Edelmann would show me the finer points of high-sticking
on a fairly remote and trail-less section of the river. He promised
aqua-colored waters, forests of pine and fir, lots of bushwhacking
and lava rocks ranging in size from five-gallon buckets to
Volkswagens that would make wading nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Though just 31, his goatee and tattered waders _ layered with
patches that might reveal the age of the ancient garment like a
tree's rings _ evoke the image of a much more grizzled resident
angler.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, Edelmann is an appropriate representative of a
community impassioned by the outdoors, whose never-forget attitude
about the catastrophic Cantara chemical spill on the Upper
Sacramento River in July 1991 led to major upgrades to its
decimated fishery. Whose ire is raised by proposals to enlarge
Shasta Dam and Shasta Lake. Whose independent nature and
dissatisfaction with faraway government management of its wild and
precious environs once spawned secessionist notions of forming the
State of Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   But enough with the rhetoric, already. This was fishing. And
Edelmann was, indeed, the man.
</P>
<P>
   A recent cold snap had postponed hatches of salmonflies,
stoneflies, caddis flies, mayflies and other insects that would
normally be airborne by this time of year. My guide would therefore
rely on a bevy of patterns meant to mimic the nymphal, or
waterborne stages of the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   An imitation would be tied to a 9-foot leader that was tapered
down to size 5X and attached to a weight-forward floating fly line,
a 4- to 6-weight rod of 9 feet in length and a matching reel. To
keep the nymph pattern near the bottom where it belongs, micro-size
split shot are added or deleted 6 to 12 inches above it, according
to the river's power. A yarn indicator is tied on to better flag a
bite.
</P>
<P>
   Burgeoning runoff from an El Nino winter was pushing high water
down the McCloud. Slack in the floating line would create drag _ a
fatal flaw. Hence the high-sticking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep your cast short, and lift that rod over your shoulder,''
Edelmann said with a kindly tone. ``It gives you more line
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Large pockets of water created by the bigger lava rocks make for
tricky casting. The idea is to aim for the top of the pocket, close
to the rock, so that the nymph appears to the trout as if it
floated into the hole, naturally, from upstream. ``If you are going
to parachute a nymph in, you don't want to do it right in the
middle of the pocket so that the fish sees it fall from the sky,''
Edelmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Just when I got off the perfect cast, THWAP, at the head of the
pocket, I would inevitably forget to high-stick and the
presentation would be ruined by the whitewater catching the
floating line and pulling the bug out of the hole. What a drag...
literally.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again I tried to copy Edelmann's style, and again and
again my line came up empty. Apparently he had scared all the trout
off during an exploratory trip two days earlier that produced
several beefy specimens to 17 inches.
</P>
<P>
   He was surprised to see rainbows that size, since the biggest
usually come in the 10-inch range. Along with stocked rainbow,
brown and brook trout, the waters are home to the native McCloud
River redband trout, which are ``wild and colored like no other
fish you've seen unless you've seen them in a book somewhere,''
Edelmann said. The browns run to 18 inches during the fall spawn.
</P>
<P>
   I was satisfied to catch a single 10-inch brookie on a dry fly.
A much fatter rainbow rose to another dry pattern, but, overly
excited by the prospect of landing the day's first ``big one,'' I
set the hook well before the fish got to the surface. The knowledge
that my guide wasn't catching much either eased my feelings of
inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the weather; it snowed the day before and this was
mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   High-sticking is awkward and tiring, to be sure, but that's
often what defines truly rewarding adventures, especially here in
Jefferson Territory _ billed as America's greatest concentration of
wilderness areas and wild and scenic rivers.
</P>
<P>
   With that understanding, we knew when we ran into the first
cigarette butt before the firstdecent trout, it was time to call it
a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 0200EDT &QL; 
