<HEADLINE>
NEXT THREE WEEKS CRUCIAL FOR MARINER MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners begin the second half of the season at
the Kingdome Thursday familiar with erasing a large deficit and
turning a lost season into something magical.
</P>
<P>
   They keep thinking about 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it once and can do it again,'' insisted center fielder
Ken Griffey Jr. ``We know it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for '95, when the M's trailed the then-California Angels
by 13 games on Aug. 24 and suddenly embarked on a heart-stopping
stretch drive that resulted in a one-game playoff victory over the
Angels, you would think another 13-game bind would be too much to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   This time, time might be the Mariners' best friend.
</P>
<P>
   The defending American League West champions have 74
regular-season games remaining to get their collective act together
and climb from last place in the division to at least become
involved in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The journey starts Thursday when left-hander Jeff Fassero
opposes former M's right-hander Omar Olivares in the opener of a
four-game series against the division-leading Angels. Anaheim has
lost five straight after zipping through June with a 21-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: What the M's do the next three weeks will
affect not only this season, but next season and beyond. Nineteen
of their next 24 games are at the Kingdome, and that stretch will
take them past the July 31 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' franchise is at a crossroads. Who goes? Who stays?
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella, who has been remarkably calm considering
how poorly his team has pitched and played defense this season,
knows the second half will be a repeat of the first unless changes
are made.
</P>
<P>
   There already have been indications management has decided to
improve the defense, hoping it helps the pitching. During the
All-Star break, left fielder Glenallen Hill, a defensively
liability, was placed on waivers and claimed by the Chicago Cubs.
Before the break, Piniella decided the team would be better off if
error-prone third baseman Russ Davis plays another position,
specifically left field.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest question concerns left-handed starter Randy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Mariners be better off trading him, say, to the Los
Angeles Dodgers for second baseman Wilton Guerrero and right-handed
reliever Antonio Osuna? Or does it make more sense to stand pat and
hope that Johnson returns to his former dominant self before
bolting out the free-agent door at the end of the season?
</P>
<P>
   And what if the same M's owner who blocked a previous trade with
the Dodgers throws a roadblock into another proposed deal for
Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Johnson is a major issue,'' said Harold Reynolds, an
ESPN baseball analyst and former Mariner second baseman. ``It's
almost like they are putting a dagger in his heart and twisting it.
I don't see how they can keep him, risk losing him to free agency
and getting almost nothing (two draft picks) in return. I think
they have to trade him.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward, M's vice president of baseball operations, says
filling the team's most obvious needs won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a position of strength right now,'' he said. ``I
have a job to do and work within the (financial) guidelines my
president lays down. Lou wants things done yesterday, because
that's his nature. But it doesn't move that quickly. And if other
teams feel you are out of the race, they are ready to take
advantage of you, and we do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Balancing now with next year, when the team moves into its new
stadium, is a difficult challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to fill one hole and create another one,''
Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Mariners sit at the bottom of the division entering
the second half, Hall of Famer Joe Morgan believes the team has the
capability of getting involved in a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season got off to such a horrible start because the
bullpen did not do as well as everyone anticipated, including
myself,'' he said. ``I also was on the bandwagon, and I think that
really hurt. It hurts more than people realize to blow leads late
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get into the race, they obviously need better relief
pitching in the second half. Those guys are under tremendous
pressure and must regain their confidence. If that happens, they
are capable of running off a hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think they are too far out. The Mariners are
capable of getting hot and winning 19 of 22 ballgames. Let's face
it, everyone in the division can beat everyone else and it's just a
matter of (the M's) getting a hot streak. Everyone in the division
except the Mariners has been hot during the season.''
</P>
<P>
   But to get hot, or even warm, the Mariners must catch the ball
better, pitch better and improve their situational hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened so far reminds me of Boston in 1996,''
left-handed pitcher Jamie Moyer said. ``In the first half, we
couldn't hit, couldn't field and couldn't pitch. But after the
break, it was almost like a different team.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one gave up, but everyone was more relaxed, went out and
played and started winning. This team can do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer said it starts with the starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to step it up a notch, if that's possible, and start
feeding off each other. Once you start winning, everyone's
confidence improves and who knows what can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It happened once. Can it happen again?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
