<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR MARINERS TO BE THINKING 1999 AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To begin the baseball season's second half, the
Mariners propose at the moment to start a left fielder who has
never chased a game ball in the outfield and a 34-year-old third
baseman who has hardly played in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   With these two representing 25 percent of an everyday lineup,
the club proposes to rally from 13 games down to contend for a
championship?
</P>
<P>
   I would prefer the chances of all the camels in the Sahara being
herded through the eye of a needle. I'll even spot you a dozen
water buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   While it's unlikely that Russ Davis and Rico Rossy will long
hold their new positions, the fact that this will happen for even a
few games is just the latest bit of preposterousness that the
Mariners, with a straight face, are foisting upon the public.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how generously one analyzes the decisions that have
created this little franchise crossroads _ ``the deal looked good
at the time, and it got us to the postseason'' _ it remains
astonishing that the Mariners are down to such impotent answers for
such serious shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   The unofficial word is that more deals are forthcoming. That
certainly should inspire the peasantry to storm the Bastille.
</P>
<P>
   In the last offseason, well before last place could be seen,
felt and smelled, the Mariners acquired some players. Among the new
faces were Glenallen Hill, Pat Listach, Jeff Huson, Rick Wilkins
and Tony Fossas. None were ever labeled all-stars, but were
adjudged reasonable role players who could fill obvious holes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Hill's unceremonious boot off the roster _ the
Mariners couldn't get so much as a mascot for him, so he was waived
_ all are gone. With the exception of first baseman David Segui,
the one player upon whom they paid high-market value, the Mariners
in the offseason went only to the blue-light special table and got
exactly what they paid for. Pitcher Billy Swift has been the lone
keeper from the retread pile, and at 37 with a long history of
injuries, he is more day-to-day than most of the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, these players were acquired before serious pressure
was on and the Mariners were exposed as threadbare, before the
current crop of Class AAA minor leaguers, already picked over from
seasons of rent-a-vet trades, were certified as bereft of
breakthrough talent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the lack of possibilities now.
</P>
<P>
   With even less willingness from ownership to extend the player
budget, now that it is writing checks for the new ballpark's cost
overruns, the Mariners have no choice but to deal from weakness.
Even the increased revenue anticipated from the new park already
has been earmarked for owners, not player payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Time to write off 1998 and look to 1999 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   With the bullpen showing few signs of recovery, the lost glove
of Davis and the lost interest of Randy Johnson, the sore knees of
Jay Buhner, the lame stick of Dan Wilson, the control problems of
Ken Cloude and Joey Cora, this year has been butchered beyond
redemption. With three teams to surpass in the American League
West, the miracle of 1995, which required overcoming only one team,
will not be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   That means it's time to quit loving these guys and start trading
the few that have value. Given Johnson's continuing malaise _ 12
strikeouts and eight earned runs in one game? _ it's obvious that
the Big Unit has pitched his way off the team. If the Mariners are
no longer stuck on rescuing '98, the idea of acquiring two or three
top-drawer prospects becomes plausible.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a decent market for Edgar Martinez, that brutal call
must be made. A handful of other Mariners could be packaged with
one or both to acquire a substantial down payment on the future.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is the Mariners will come away with the same thing they
received in their most recent trades of All-Star talent. From the
trades of shortstop Omar Vizquel and first baseman Tino Martinez,
the Mariners are left with Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Please, please, please: Do not accept stock market advice from
this team. Even if they suggest Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   But the risk of doing nothing is greater. That's because the two
Mariner All-Stars, Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez, have deals
that expire after the 2000 season. That means a good team and high
revenues must be in place by the end of 1999 to be able to recruit
and pay what figures to be two of the biggest contracts in sports
history.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mariners, after the tepidness of last winter, must be
bold. They must risk the PR backlash of heroes lost, they must take
chances with elite veteran free agents (think Roberto Alomar would
work OK at second base next to Rodriguez and in front of Griffey on
a new grass field?). They must show the guts at this trading
deadline in three weeks and in the off-season to make a futile 1998
turn into a one-year reloading instead of a multi-year rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   There is no good choice. The time for good choices came when
they had a decent left fielder in Roberto Kelly, a good closer in
Mike Jackson and a respectable third baseman in Dave Hollins.
</P>
<P>
   The choices were made, and ended up being Hill, Fossas and
Rossy, who might be just as effective helping me round up the
camels.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
