<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-THORNTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' TOP DRAFT PICK FACES BIG TRANSITION TO FULLTIME PITCHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Matt Thornton thought he knew what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   So the little-known left-handed closer decided not to sit in
front of a television while baseball conducted its annual amateur
draft last month. Instead, Thornton packed up his clubs and a few
friends for a golf outing.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton took along his mother's cell phone _ just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was ready when the draft came around. I was
thinking second or third round. ... This is a dream,'' said
Thornton, a 6-foot-6 power reliever whom the Mariners took 22nd
overall in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The M's signed the bright-eyed prospect to a $925,000 contract
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton says he was still in a jolted state, when the Mariners
introduced him to Seattle media Wednesday. After all, the Mariners'
No. 1 pick attended Grand Valley State University _ a Division II
school in Grand Rapids, Mich. _ and on a basketball scholarship,
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton has pitched since he was 7 years old, but last season
was his first as a reliever. When the 21-year-old reports to the
Class A Everett AquaSox this week, he will totally commit to
baseball for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are confident that Thornton will make up for his
lack of experience with enthusiasm and undoubted power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I calmed down for a week,'' Thornton said of his
selection. ``I got into my first accident and got my first ticket
the next day (after being drafted). It's interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   More intriguing is Thornton's ability, according to Roger
Jongewaard, the M's vice president of scouting and player
development. Thornton earned just three saves in 15 games last
season. However, he throws a fastball that ranges between 91 and 94
mph, and also possesses a hard slider and changeup.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is his lack of innings against professional-caliber
players. The upside is Thornton's youth and the relative low
mileage on his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about fast-tracking him as a closer,'' said
Jongewaard, who points to Thornton's size and mobility as two of
his biggest assets. ``But we'll give him more innings _ like the
last three innings so he can work on his pitches. We think he could
move rapidly. ... He could be very good (early) or long-range.
Fast-tracking on some guys doesn't work at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be at least a week before Thornton pitches for Everett.
He will go through workouts and simulated action until then.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners were not discouraged by Thornton's small-school
tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not dependent on Baseball America or the media for
finding our guys,'' Jongewaard said. ``We like his athleticism.
With him being a basketball player, he's got good balance and
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton has never had professional training. Basketball always
impeded his work in baseball, which Thornton played only in the
spring and summer. Had Thornton been drafted in the later rounds,
he says he would have returned to Grand Valley State for his senior
season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Thornton finds himself thrust into the Mariner organization
and ready to tackle the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll be effective in whatever I do,'' Thornton said.
``I'm not going to quit working hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
