 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY No 2462 - JULY 9, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. ``ROARING ORGAN'' : REVIVAL OF AN ITALIAN MOTORCYCLE LEGEND
MV Agusta, the Italian motorcycle-maker that dominated racing
circuits in the '60s and '70s as few manufacturers have ever done,
went into a deep sleep some 20 years ago. Now it is back, with an
astonishingly high-performance motorcycle. The first 200
hand-finished bikes will be provided to well-known personalities
this year, before the series machines go on the market next year at
a price of nearly $20,000. (King Juan Carlos of Spain is already on
the list. ) From Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. English translation
available.
_______________________________________________________________2.
EASTER ISLAND YIELDS ITS SECRETS GRUDGINGLY Archeologists are at
last making progress in recovering the history of Easter Island and
its 900 stone statues. The scientists are also gaining a better
understanding of the motivations, practices and economic
foundations of the statue builders. But the place is in danger of
losing its alluring air of mystery. By John Noble Wilford. New York
Times Science Times. 2,500 words + art.
_______________________________________________________________3.
EBOLA'S LETHAL SECRETS Few viruses are as deadly as Ebola. Its
victims bleed to death within days of infection. Researchers are
just starting to learn how the virus kills, reports Josie
Glausiusz. From Discover magazine. 700 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
DOUBTS ABOUT BREAST CANCER PREVENTION DRUGS A recent U.S. study
found that the anti-estrogen drug tamoxifen reduced the risk of
breast cancer in women at high risk for the disease by 45%. Now two
studies in The Lancet find that, overall, taking tamoxifen was no
better than a placebo in preventing breast cancer. By Michael
McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
GEO-PSYCHICS MUST ALSO BE ACCOMMODATED Geo-economics has obviously
become the dominant force driving international relations. But
there is a rising force of tension which can be called
geo-psychics. By Flora Lewis. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
WHAT'S GOOD FOR YOUR BACK Back pain rarely occurs out of the blue.
Bending and lifting in the wrong way and not keeping in shape all
add up. Here are some good, general guidelines on how to protect
your back. By Ken McAlpine. Spirit. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   7. WHAT'S DOING IN ASPEN Behind the buzz of celebrities and high
prices, Aspen, Colorado is a magical town where the beauty of the
Elk Mountains combines with a stimulating cultural life. James
Brooke reports on what to see, what to do, where to eat and where
to stay. New York Times Way To Go! 1,800 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
BIRDS OF A FEATHER Songbirds are small and tough to track when they
head south for the winter. Now biologists are learning to trace
birds by studying the chemicals in their feathers. By Shanti Menon.
From Discover magazine. 700 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
SHOES THAT WALKED THE EARTH 8,000 YEARS AGO One of the longest
chapters in the history of fashion has emerged from an unlikely
hiding place. From an ancient rubbish dump in a cave overlooking
the Missouri River in the United States, archeologists have
retrieved a series of discarded shoes that range in age from 8,000
to 800 years ago. By Nicholas Wade. New York Times Science Times.
700 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
SPECIAL REPORT ON WOMEN'S HEALTH She asks the doctors the important
questions. She makes most of the over-the-counter pharmaceutical
purchases. She monitors the health and well-being of the entire
family. In most households, the woman is the healthcare gatekeeper.
We are offering 9 special stories (plus art) from The New York
Times to help your readers understand the medical innovations and
trends that affect women's lives - and the lives of those around
them. Please contact us for more details.
_______________________________________________________________ 11.
TAPPING THE MIDDLE-AGED MOOD Personal-care products like Retin A
are aimed specifically at a maturing population, but age is not a
big issue when it comes to marketing fashion to baby boomers.
Fashion firms target the baby-boom generation by portraying their
products as fitting a certain lifestyle or state of mind. By Karyn
Monget. Women's Wear Daily. 1,100 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 12.
HELPING KIDS COPE WITH MOVING DAY Children often don't understand
why they have to move house (whether it's across town or across
country.) As they may have little control over the situation,
moving can be a traumatic experience for them. Liza N. Burby
explains the steps that can help pave the way. Child magazine.
1,400 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
