<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN12-COX-1     07-09 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN12-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Eight great books
 &HT;    (Corrects improvised to impoverished in 11th graf.)
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Letter from a student:
</P>
<P>
   ``What books do you suggest for a high school senior that reads
and writes a lot and dreams of being a teacher or writer, maybe
even a journalist?
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, what books really impacted you when you were
almost 18 and trying to find your place in the world?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure books are the place to look for what you seek. My
experience has been that books tend to raise more questions about
life than they answer.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Here's a crate of eight that I've pulled from the
bookshelf. Think of them as points on the compass:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' (1960) by Harper Lee, the story of a
little girl growing up in the South during the Depression. Harper
Lee's father was the inspiration for the character Atticus Finch,
and Atticus Finch is an inspiration for everyone who reads this
book.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Thanksgiving Visitor'' (1967) and ``A Christmas Memory''
(1956) by Truman Capote, a pair of novellas available in a single
volume. Beautifully written, these stories serve as companion
pieces to ``To Kill a Mockingbird.'' Truman Capote and Harper Lee
grew up together, and he is also a character in her book. Indeed,
there's literary hearsay that Capote may have helped Lee with the
writing of ``Mockingbird,'' her only published novel.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Sun Also Rises'' (1928) by Ernest Hemingway, one of his
first and arguably his best novel, the story of expatriates at play
in postwar Europe. The book is prefaced with Gertrude Stein's
quote, ``You are all a lost generation.'' Even more poignant are
the novel's concluding lines: ``Oh, Jake,'' Brett said, ``we could
have had such a damned good time together.'' ... ``Yes,'' I said.
``Isn't it pretty to think so.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Moveable Feast'' (1964) by Hemingway, published
posthumously, recounts a nonfiction version from the same era as
``The Sun Also Rises.'' Here's Hemingway's quote that introduces
this memoir: ``If you are lucky enough to have lived in Paris as a
young man, then wherever you go for the rest of your life, it stays
with you, for Paris is a moveable feast.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Great Gatsby'' (1925) by F. Scott Fitzgerald, the
defining novel of the Jazz Age that has a place on most everyone's
list of great American literature. ``There was music from my
neighbor's house through the summer nights,'' recounts Nick
Carraway in telling the tragic story of Jay Gatsby. ``In his blue
gardens men and girls came and went like moths among the
whisperings and the champagne and the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Grapes of Wrath'' (1939) by John Steinbeck, who
chronicles the plight of impoverished American farmers, Okies
searching vainly for a workers' paradise in California. ``They had
hoped to find a home, and they found only hatred. Okies _ the
owners hated them because the owners knew they were soft and the
Okies were strong, that they were fed and the Okies hungry.'' Songs
have been written about this novel, such is the lyrical quality of
its prose.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``All the King's Men'' (1946) by Robert Penn Warren, perhaps
THE novel of American politics, with the fictional Willie Stark in
the role of legendary Huey P. Long. ``It might have all been
different,'' Stark says as he lay dying from an assassin's bullet.
The lament of man's history on Earth has never been summed up so
simply.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Gay Place'' (1961) by Billy Lee Brammer _ the title is
from a poem by Scott Fitzgerald, ``I know a gay place nobody
knows,'' and has nothing to do with gender preference _ is
considered probably the best novel ever to come out of Texas.
Brammer does for Lyndon B. Johnson what Robert Penn Warren does for
Huey P. Long. The period is the late 1950s and the location is
Austin, though the reader is never told. Like Harper Lee, Brammer
never published again.
</P>
<P>
   Runners-up: ``The Last Picture Show,'' Larry McMurtry; ``The
Sound and the Fury,'' William Faulkner; ``From Here to Eternity,''
James Jones; any of the Travis McGee books by John D. MacDonald;
and all of the essays of E.B. White.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the books that mean the most to me. The fun is
in finding your own.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for writing. Thanks for reading.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
</P>
<P>
   AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 0956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7003 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV12-C     07-09 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: RISKS AND REWARDS IN A SUBPRIME UNIVERSE
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, July 12.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Among people who make their living lending money,
the subprime market has become a hot meal ticket. And these folks
aren't talking about second-tier steak houses, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subprime home equity loans are commonly marketed as
bill-consolidation loans, particularly as a means to pay off credit
card debt,'' a recent Federal Reserve Board study notes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you've seen these loans being aggressively pitched on TV
to homeowners with lower incomes, with limited borrowing power or
with soiled credit ratings. By the end of 1997, the Fed study
pegged the overall size of this loan pool at $90 billion, and
growing at a sizzling 15 percent annual clip.
</P>
<P>
   For some borrowers, such loans are a good deal. Interest rates
can be as low as 10 percent, and average 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While that's more than double what one can expect to pay for a
top-of-the-line first mortgage, it's usually less than the carrying
charges on credit cards or on other forms of revolving consumer
debt. What's more, interest on mortgage debt is deductible on
itemized federal tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   The bank that issues our credit card will thank us for being
such prompt payers by bumping up the family credit limit. But
industry insiders know the bank would be still happier were we to
keep a large open tab on our plastic money.
</P>
<P>
   Card issuers must look askance at the success shown by such
sports figures as Dan Marino, Dan Dierdorf and Jim Palmer in
pitching home equity loans. According to researchers, since
mid-1996 about 4.2 million U.S. households have pulled the plug on
$26 billion of credit card debt by converting it into mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The card issuers who really get hammered are the monoline
companies (that offer only one type of credit) and retail store
operations,'' said Bruce Brittain, president of Brittain
Associates, an Atlanta-based research firm. ``If a consumer pays
off their card balance with an equity loan and the issuer isn't
(also) in that business, those balances simply have to go
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brittain has tracked what he sees as a worrisome trend among
some subprime borrowers to once again max out their cards after
paying them off with an equity loan.
</P>
<P>
   So what would happen if the good times should stop to roll?
</P>
<P>
   ``If these consumers then find themselves having to decide on
which loan to make a monthly installment, we predict it will be the
equity loan because the borrower's home is the collateral,''
Brittain says.
</P>
<P>
   Such an economic climate could trigger a run of credit card
delinquencies. Lenders try to factor such losses into the cost of
doing business by passing along the charges to their good
customers. Those that can't can go broke.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the prime interest of subprime borrowers, who may
fall prey to such schemes as ``equity stripping'' (inflated loans
based on falsely padded income) or abrupt demands for payment on
``balloon loans?'' These ploys could cause them to lose their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators and congressional probers also fear that
subprime borrowers can fail to sense the risk they run from
personal or general economic reversals. On Capitol Hill, hearings
are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 0958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
