<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7017 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-COOKING10-COX     07-09 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-COOKING10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cooking makes a comeback
 &HT;    (Fixes author of 'Pies and Tarts' in 16th graf.)
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last February, while most young professionals were stalking top
restaurants for Valentine's Day reservations, Monica Hoover was
learning how to launch the real arrow to her partner's heart: with
homemade cookies and ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   No fussy restaurant desserts for this 34-year-old Atlanta
comptroller. No crowds and no expense, either. Instead she joined a
group of culinary enthusiasts for a Valentine's Day primer at the
Cook's Warehouse, a cookware store that has become a popular venue
for cooking classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was kind of a neat alternative to going out to
dinner and spending $200,'' said Hoover. ``Even though there was a
Valentine's theme, it was simple, stress-free cooking that you and
your date could make together.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when slaving over a hot stove was absolutely no
one's idea of a successful evening's entertainment, much less a hot
date. After all, wasn't the idea to get out of the house, away from
the chores?
</P>
<P>
   But for a generation of people who frequently dine out as a
matter of stomach-rumbling necessity, cooking _ honest, satisfying
home cooking _ is making a comeback. For special dates. For weekend
projects. For fun.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kroger Cooking School in Alpharetta, Ga., more than 3,000
students took a class in 1997, up 7% from the previous year.
Chef-instructor Kathy Blanda says popular classes, such as one that
teaches basic kitchen skills, are ``jam-packed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fascinated by it,'' says trend guru Faith Popcorn,
chairman of BrainReserve, a marketing consultant to the Fortune
500. ``Cooking at home is a skill, not a drudgery. When you
generate a home-cooked meal you get so much recognition for it
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly since so many others can't. ``Literally we have a
generation of people who don't know how to boil an egg,'' says
Popcorn. Maybe we passed on that home ec class in high school.
Maybe we paid no attention when mom put the Thanksgiving turkey in
the oven, or _ for the post-baby boom generation _ mom was too busy
at work to even think about any turkey other than Swanson's.
</P>
<P>
   But, boy, are we making up for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how we got interested in Martha Stewart,'' continues
Popcorn, ``and all these cooking shows. It's homemaking
voyeurism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fashionable element at work here,'' agrees Art
Siemering, whose Trend/Wire newsletter tracks food trends for
professionals. ``Cooking has experienced a real liberation and
gravitated from a chore or daily task that we have to do to an
occasional pleasure. Now we can cook whenever we want and never
when we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   For busy professionals, that usually means once the work week is
over. Hoover knows ``a lot of folks who stop by Harry's in a
Hurry'' (a popular gourmet carryout) on the way home from work
during the week. But on the weekend they break out the chef's
knives and cutting boards _ not to mention the videos, the CD-ROMs,
and a whole new generation of cookbooks that Jennifer Griffin,
senior cookbook editor at MacMillan, terms a full-fledged ``back to
basics movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Trendwatchers and editors agree the home cooking revival is
fueled mostly by young adults who grew up with more Hamburger
Helper than homemade meatloaf. And they want to make up for lost
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel they're missing something,'' says Siemering. ``It
might be something real like memories of visiting their
grandmothers. Or maybe it's something imagined from watching Nick
at Nite. But they're asking themselves, `How can I get a little
better at this or that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Hunnicutt of Decatur, Ga., 35, is teaching herself how to
cook one pie at a time. Her mother, who worked full-time when she
was growing up, made ``really good Thanksgiving dinners, but that's
about it. I don't remember her ever teaching me how to cook. Maybe
it's me. Maybe I wasn't interested back then.''
</P>
<P>
   She is now. Hunnicutt has been working her way through Martha
Stewart's ``Pies and Tarts,'' which she describes as a ``pretty
like basic book for people who shy away from pies because they're
afraid of a rolling pin.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple American recipes and basic technique are the two themes
echoed through many of today's hottest cookbook titles, and the
Titanic success of the updated ``Joy of Cooking'' was only the tip
of the iceberg. Atlantan Shirley Corriher's ``CookWise,'' a food
scientist's explanation of superior results _ the fluffiest
biscuits, the most gorgeously bronzed roast chicken _ has been the
surprise sleeper of the season, even inching up the charts at
Amazon.com, whose ``literary foodie kind of crowd'' usually favors
glossy coffeetable books, according to spokesperson Beth Garson.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Willan's latest volume, ``Cook it Right,'' uses
in-your-face photos with each basic recipe to illustrate both
desirable and undesirable results. Those people who can't boil an
egg can find out exactly what they did wrong to get that green ring
around the yolk.
</P>
<P>
   More are in the pipeline. MacMillan's big hit for the fall
season, ``How to Cook Everything'' by Mark Bittman and edited by
Jennifer Griffin, will use color photography and simple,
contemporary recipes to show people how to cut and cook everything
from chicken to squid.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know how to clean a squid?'' asks Griffin. ``The
first time I tried I didn't know it had that piece of cartilege
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooking instructor James Peterson, author of the just released
``Vegetables: The Most Authoritative Guide to Buying, Preparing,
and Cooking, with More Than 300 Recipes,'' is currently writing and
photographing a yet-unnamed book that zeroes in on technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about how to fillet a fish and how to carve a roast
and how to peel this or that. My goal,'' says Peterson, ``is to get
people to think they don't need a recipe at all. If they understand
the essence of it, they'll be able to taper it to their own
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also the goal of Pam Anderson, executive editor of Cook's
Illustrated, whose just released cookbook ``The Perfect Recipe''
dishes up the kind of idealized mac and cheese, chicken pot pies
and brownies that June Cleaver would hock her pearls for.
</P>
<P>
   But for her next work she'd like to move completely beyond
traditional recipes, to do away with measurements, and to really
teach people the instincts of a good cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have lost their confidence and ability to look, smell
and taste the food they're cooking. You have to poke and probe. You
have to take some initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, just maybe, you'll make your grandma proud.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
