<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7018 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRIDER-COOKSMAG10-COX     07-09 2224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIDER-COOKSMAG10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine editor tackles perfect recipes
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Pam Anderson has cleaned and cooked 100 pounds of
greens, roasted 20 prime ribs, and baked 50-plus cobblers.
</P>
<P>
   She has roasted more than 40 turkeys, developing a brining
method that turns out a cooked bird with breast meat as moist as
its legs.
</P>
<P>
   All in in search of the perfect recipe.
</P>
<P>
   This Pam Anderson is not the Baywatch babe, but the executive
editor of Cook's Illustrated, a serious no-advertising bimonthly
cooking magazine. The author of ``The Perfect Recipe: Getting It
Right Every Time'' cookbook (Chapters, $27), Anderson was in Austin
at Central Market recently to show how to cook the perfect roast
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things she did was clarify her definition of
perfection. ``These are my perfect recipes. These are not the only
way to do a recipe ... I try not to emphasize that this is the last
word, the ultimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, she sees her perfected recipes more as publishing her
notes for other cooks to try in their culinary experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Her recipes may depart from the norm. In roast chicken, the
breast meat tends to overcook before the legs and thighs, she
explains. So her roast chicken goes backless. With a pair of
poultry shears, she demonstrates how she cuts out the back bone,
leaving a butterflied bird that cooks in 30 minutes _ in the oven
or on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   It is a roast chicken so good and so easy to carve that Kathleen
Caoyonan, a student in the class and a novice cook, promptly put
the recipe on her July Fourth menu.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect, however, does not always mean complicated, Anderson
says. It can be easy and fast. ``I'm a busy person, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Before developing her collection of ``perfect'' recipes,
Anderson says, she used to try different recipes from cookbooks and
magazines, usually with varying results. She decided to make a
study of dishes she prepared frequently and fine tune the recipes
to turn out delicious results every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a chicken pot pie that I'd actually have time to put
on the table on weeknights, and macaroni and cheese that both my
kids and I would eat. I wanted foolproof coleslaw and potato salads
that would go with all sorts of dishes, and a cobbler recipe that I
could vary with seasonal fruit and top in several different ways.
For special occasions, I wanted dishes that would deliver the
absolute best,'' she explains to the class as well as in her book's
foreword.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing black slacks, a blue sweater and sandals, Anderson leans
on the counter with a cup of coffee in her hand and talks to her
students as if she were chatting over a table with a neighbor, her
warm manner contrasting with the more erudite tone of Cook's
articles. She tells how she grew up in the Florida Panhandle,
privileged to know wonderful S outhern foods like prime, aged
steaks and home-churned banana ice cream. ``These are the taste
memories I work from,'' she says as she discusses her quest for the
best recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she nails her improved recipe in four tries, like her
technique for making fabulous chicken stock. But other times it
takes dozens of tries to achieve the perfection she seeks. The best
roast turkey, for instance, was one of the most involved testings.
She recalls waking up in the mornings thinking, ``Oh, God. I've got
to make another turkey ... But you can't stop. You have to keep
going until you get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Perseverance paid off, and her brining technique has been widely
received. She even uses it on chickens when she has a couple of
extra hours because it distributes the salt more evenly throughout
the bird.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve an optimum recipe, she first looks at 30-35
variations to understand the full range of possibilities. On her
computer, she sets up a spread sheet comparing ingredients and
methods of the recipes. Using this information as a guide, she
devises a composite recipe. Then she and an assistant start
tinkering, working with one variable at time.
</P>
<P>
   Initially she cooks in small batches, testing in her New Hope,
Pa., home kitchen, using typical consumer appliances. When she hits
roadblocks, she calls on research centers, chefs, food science
experts, and cookbook authors for enlightenment. Then she tests
some more.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, her husband and teen-age daughters, who, like most 13- and
15-year-olds would be happy eating pizza every night, sometimes get
tired of eating turkey, or whatever she is testing, meal after
meal. But generally they are good sports, she says.
</P>
<P>
   And they do not consume all the test food. Some of it simply
falls victim to research. ``I feel bad sometimes about throwing
away food,'' she says. `` But it's hard to take someone a turkey
that does not taste very good and has four bites out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once she has a recipe perfected, it is sent to the magazine's
test kitchen in Boston, where other testers compare it in blind
tastings to other classics, the same procedure now used for all
recipes in the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for the perfect recipe is an involved, thoughtful
process _ one, she believes must be approached with the innocence
of a child, the questioning of youth, the drive of young adulthood
and the wisdom of age.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of recipes that worked 50 years ago are not as successful
today because ingredients are different. Meat, for instance, is
leaner and less forgiving in cooking, and chicken is not as
flavorful as birds of the past. Thus, in testing recipes, she says
you have to question everything, including old practices.
</P>
<P>
   Interested in food since her Southern childhood, Anderson
started out majoring in home economics in college, but hated the
child care and sewing classes that went along with the program. She
switched to history, with an English minor. After she married and
moved to Chicago, she returned to food with a vengeance, devouring
the books of Julia Child and James Beard and spending half her
family's graduate student budget on food and entertaining. She
segued into catering for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Then on to the East Coast when her husband, an Episcopal
minister, continued graduate studies in N ew Haven, Conn. There she
went to the former Cook's magazine, and asked for a job as a recipe
tester. By the time the magazine folded in 1990, she was food
editor. She went to work for Restaurant Business Magazine, a job
she credits with teaching her how to write.
</P>
<P>
   When Christopher Kimball decided to start up Cook's again, he
asked her to write a story for the first trial issue. Through the
modern technology of telecommuting, she became food editor when the
magazine premiered in 1993. And for three or four years, she did
all of the recipe testing in her kitchen in Pennsylvania, faxing,
e-mailing and modeming the results to Kimball, the editor and
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Not unlike a restaurant review, the results primarily were based
on her tastes and those of her assistant. But Anderson does not
claim to be a super-taster. ``I think I have an average palate and
reflect what most Americans think tastes good,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Now most of the magazine's testing is done in the magazine's
central kitchen in Boston and, as executive editor, she primarily
works with the food writers and issue planning. But, unlike some
cookbook authors, she does her own recipe testing when she is
working on an article for the magazine or her next cookbook. (That
book's working title is ``Cooking by Heart.'' It will teach people
how to be less recipe dependent for weeknight meals.)
</P>
<P>
   Because Anderson cooks dinner for her family most nights, she
knows of what she writes. And despite her test-kitchen experience,
she economizes efforts in the kitchen like many home cooks,
re-using a pan or spatula when it does not cross-contaminate foods.
(''I hate ending up with lots of dishes at the end.'')
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, she connected with her full class of 30 students. Two
cases of her new book, ordered for the occasion, sold out. And one
student even purchased Anderson's used copy. Another went next door
to a book store and found a copy in stock, bringing it back after
class for Anderson to autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate compliments to the perfect recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Pam Anderson's versatile recipe for chicken, which can
be roasted, grilled or broiled. The Perfect Recipe: Roast
Butterflied Chicken with Tarragon-Mustard Pan Sauce 2 teaspoons
minced fresh tarragon leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 medium garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 whole chicken (3 pounds), butterflied
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup homemade chicken broth or low-sodium canned broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Place the chicken breast side down, with the tail end facing
you. With kitchen shears, cut along one side of the tail down the
entire length of the backbone. With the chicken still breast side
down, turn the bird so its neck faces you. Cut along the other side
of the backbone and remove it from the chicken. Reserve back for
another use, such as making broth.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the chicken breast side up. Open the chicken and lay it on
a work surface. Use the palm of your hand to flatten the breast so
that the whole chicken lies flat. Use your fist or the flat side of
a mallet to pound the chicken to a more even thickness. Make a
1/2-inch slit on either side of each breast about 1 inch from the
tip. Tuck the corresponding leg into each opening.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 500 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Mix tarragon, garlic, 1/2 teaspoon salt and 1/4 teaspoon pepper
into a paste in a small bowl. Loosen breast and leg/thigh skin and
rub herb-garlic paste over exposed areas. Tuck legs into slits in
breast skin, then transfer chicken to a large roasting pan or jelly
roll pan, skin side up. Rub skin with oil and very lightly season
with salt and pepper. Let chicken stand at room temperature while
oven heats.
</P>
<P>
   Roast until chicken skin is nicely brown and juices run clear,
about 30 minutes. Transfer to a serving platter or cutting board,
cover with foil and let rest while making sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon off all fat from roasting pan. Heat one or two burners
(depending on roasting pan size) to medium-high. Pour broth into
pan, scraping up any drippings that have stuck to bottom of pan.
Pour liquid into a small saucepan and reduce by half, about 4
minutes. Whisk in mustard, then swirl in butter.
</P>
<P>
   Halve chicken down breast bone and snip skin between breast and
legs/thighs. Serve immediately with sauce passed separately. Serves
4.
</P>
<P>
   Never roast a butterflied chicken without throwing a couple of
vegetables in the pan _ red or sweet potatoes, carrots or parsnips,
onions or shallots and turnips or rutabagas _ cut into 2-inch
chunks. Since the vegetables will be cooked but not browned when
the chicken is done, remove the bird from the pan and return the
vegetables to the oven while the chicken rests. Don't use more
vegetables than will fit in a single layer in the pan. You can
deglaze the pan with stock, water or wine after removing the
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Cook over direct heat for 12 minutes breast side up, then about
15 minutes breast side down. Place an old jelly roll pan on top of
the bird with a couple of bricks in it to weight it down, making it
cook faster and more evenly. Perfect tips from a pro:
</P>
<P>
   Everyone ought to have a spoonula, a rubber spatula slightly
curved like a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   For the best burger, poke small holes in the surface with your
fingertips and use 100 percent ground chuck.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not have a food processor (which she likes for cutting
shortening into flour) or a pastry blender, grate cold or frozen
butter into the flour using a box grater. This works well for
biscuits or pastry. Stock your kitchen with a pair of heavy-duty
kitchen shears or poultry shears. (She's had good luck with Henckel
and Cutco shears.)
</P>
<P>
   A combination of butter and shortening makes the best crust for
cobbler or pie _ butter for flavor and shortening for flakiness.
</P>
<P>
   In testing cobblers, Anderson was surprised at how well frozen
fruit did in recipes. Because cobblers are one of her easy, standby
desserts, she now keeps bags of frozen blueberries in her freezer
all the time for unexpected company.
</P>
<P>
   A little butter makes a difference in recipes, she says,
stirring a tablespoon into a sauce for chicken. ``It's not going to
kill you. Well, I don't think it's going to kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   For the smoothest, lightest mashed potatoes, add the milk before
the butter.
</P>
<P>
   In making single, unfilled pastry crusts , instead of pie
weights placed on foil to keep the crust from puffing, she grabs a
handful of screws and nails from her garage.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I cannot live without is my Poldar Thermo-Timer, a
digital read thermometer with a two-foot long metal wire and a
probe at the other end. The wire is so thin that the oven door can
remain closed with the thermometer staying outside the oven, making
it possible for cooks to check a roast's temperature without
pulling the meat in and out of the oven. (William-Sonoma stocks
this item.)
</P>
<P>
   For moist, full-flavored cornbread, stir boiling water into part
of the cornmeal before adding the remaining ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Crider is the food editor for the Austin
American-Statemsan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
