<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7020 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-ROSS10-COX     07-09 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ROSS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lillian Ross remembers the magazine and the man behind it
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes it seems that all that's left of the classic age of
The New Yorker is the typeface and Lillian Ross. She went to work
at the magazine in 1945 and quickly became a legend for her
profiles, notably one on Ernest Hemingway, as well as for Picture,
her book-length story on the making of John Huston's ``The Red
Badge of Courage.'' Ross helped invent a painstaking, incrementally
observational journalism for which others have received most of the
credit.
</P>
<P>
   She has recently published ``Here But Not Here'' (Random House,
$25), a memoir of her 40-year love affair with New Yorker editor
William Shawn that has aroused much negative comment, largely
because of Ross' decision to publish while Shawn's widow is still
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn has usually been characterized as a preternaturally shy,
vaguely creepy little man, if, admittedly, a genius, who moved the
magazine away from the light sophistication of founder Harold Ross
to a more serious, reportorial base.
</P>
<P>
   But Ross gives us a Shawn who adores French cooking, movies and
jazz, a passionate man with immense yearnings for a writing career,
who felt imprisoned by his responsibilities _ to the magazine, its
writers and to his separate but, apparently, equal families.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, voluble, continually interesting, Lillian Ross is not a
woman used to bad reviews, and she took the opportunity of a recent
phone conversation to expound on her career, her relationship to
Shawn and the responses her latest book has evoked.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was writing ``Here But Not Here'' a way to keep Mr. Shawn
close?
</P>
<P>
   A: I know exactly why I wrote the book _ for three reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Number one, I wrote it for him. He wanted to be regarded as the
man that he was, not this creepy little fellow they insist on
making him.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason was for my son Erik. Because we don't have
much of a family, I wanted Erik to know his own true heritage. Bill
Shawn was like a father with him, and Erik absorbed all of the good
that was in Bill Shawn without any of the handicaps. He wasn't
raised to feel guilty about anything, which Bill was.
</P>
<P>
   Thirdly, I wrote it for myself, to tell the truth, about a love
story that I think is rather unusual, if not unique.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've always, to the best of my memory, been very
well-treated by reviewers. Has the criticism been difficult for you
to deal with?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've been puzzled by it. It's an unusual experience for me.
It seems as though they're not reading the book. They're using it
as a point to take off and express something they've been harboring
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Everything I've written in a way has been controversial,
starting with the profile of Hemingway. I loved him and loved the
way he was. It was such fun to be around him, and we always had a
great time together.
</P>
<P>
   But the profile was taken as devastating. I discovered that
writing is a Rorschach test; people are ready with opinions and
prejudices, and words like ``devastating,'' because of the images
they had in their own heads about what Hemingway should have been.
A writer is supposed to sit in a leather chair with a pipe in his
mouth and contemplate God knows what. My picture of Hemingway was
exactly as he was _ a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't prepared for bad reviews . . . To hear the way these
clods talk about it in what passes for a review, but is really an
opportunity to divest themselves of bitterness or envy or
frustration in their own lives, and their own ignorance . . . They
just come out with it and pretend it's a review.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Shawn have a specific editing method, or did it vary
according to the writer and the subject?
</P>
<P>
   A: It started long before there was a manuscript handed him.
First of all, he was able to tune in to the writer, or the artist.
He often would be able to feel what the writer was trying to do
before he did it, and could give them guidance.
</P>
<P>
   There were others with whom he struggled, and whom he did a good
deal of writing for. He made it part of what they were doing. And
there were still others he felt personally sorry for, and he
struggled with them. One or two became burdens to him, and he
agonized over that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Other than vulgarity, what could be counted on to make alarm
bells go off in his head?
</P>
<P>
   A: Vulgarity is a very broad word when it comes to Bill Shawn.
Obscenities didn't bother Bill. He used them himself, the way all
people do in private.
</P>
<P>
   What always bothered him was unnecessary cruelty; that he found
unacceptable. He had many arguments with one writer in particular,
who was absolutely brilliant, but she could go out of her way to be
cruel, and that bothered him. He tried to get her to be kinder.
</P>
<P>
   He did his best to persuade, but if the writer was implacable _
and she was one of the few who was _ then he would let the word or
the cruelty stand, but he would be depressed about it for three
weeks. But there weren't many who were implacable. They would
listen. And he always tried to encourage writers to write better,
to be writers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If Shawn had been able to leave The New Yorker earlier, say
1960 or 1965, would he have been able to begin his own writing
career, or do you feel that his yearnings for a writing career were
just a case of the-grass-is-greener?
</P>
<P>
   A: Perhaps, but it's hard to tell. It's just a guess, and what
does it mean? I don't like psychoanalytic writing, I don't like
giving my opinions, unlike the critics. I like to give very telling
facts, and leave it to the reader to understand, based on his own
capacity to understand. Some understand, and others don't.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Of all the writers and artists you've observed and become
friendly with over the years, from Charlie Chaplin to Huston to
Hemingway, are there any specific traits you've noticed that they
have in common?
</P>
<P>
   A: These people were different. Th(ere) was the time I met
Chaplin, who had just married Oona (O'Neill, his last wife), and I
was struck by the difference between people who were geniuses,
artists. I don't know if it can be defined. There's a freedom
there, something that pushes them to express what they have.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging out with Chaplin, I saw again how fortunate a genius is
to hook up with the right partner, whether it's a wife or someone
else. Oona gave him a real life, a life that he could enjoy outside
of his work. And that's very rare. That's why you find so many
writers and artists who make one mistake after another in marriages
and relationships. That's one aspect of a genius that's rare, the
ones who are able to enjoy _ I don't like to say little things,
because they're not little. Things like having babies, watching
them grow, being able to participate in that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In your work, you have a way of seeming resolutely un-awed by
the legends you're writing about. Is that the way you approach
them, or just the way you feel about them by the time you come to
write about them?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's the other way around. I had gotten to know John Huston
several years before he invited me out to watch him make ``The Red
Badge of Courage.'' I found him very, very appealing instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Oh?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not like that. I was always very careful about any kind of
personal relationship in that way. You have to remember the
relationship with Bill Shawn started very early; I came to work for
him in '45, and it was only a matter of three or four years before
he started to indicate his feelings. Those were the years I was
starting to do the work I became well known for.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't get personal with them. I found Huston appealing as a
man, but I had my emotional feelings bound up with somebody else.
Some people can have more than one person in their life, but I'm
not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   I think one of the reasons I've always been able to form the
basis for a good working relationship when I'm doing a story is
it's always been a two-way thing. The people liked me and I liked
them. If they hadn't liked me, I wouldn't have been able to work
with them. I love to write about what I love.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
