<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pair of books captures past in different ways
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cover picture is of a hundred or so rotary phones, which
nicely captures the essence of ``Going Going Gone'' (Chronicle,
$19.95) a very amusing volume about vanishing Americana.
</P>
<P>
   Among the things cast into obsolescence are: penmanship, men's
garters, the Red Menace, hotel keys, sanitary napkin belts, the
draft, Civil Defense, slide rules, white gloves, chop suey, men's
clubs, psychoanalysis, the nuclear family, wedding night virgins
and two-newspaper towns.
</P>
<P>
   Call me contrary, but it seems to me that, in most cases, it's
no big loss.
</P>
<P>
   Other things tagged as gone with the wind strike me as debatable
_ nuns, organized labor, paper dolls and even typewriters all seem
to me likely to stick around in some form, if not with the density
they had when the century was younger.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a thought-provoking book about the evolutionary _ and
transitory _ nature of civilization's products.
</P>
<P>
   Another, rather more serious but equally entertaining book is
``Paul Robeson: Artist and Citizen'' (Rutgers University Press,
$25), a collection of essays and beautiful photographs published on
the centenary of the great singer and political activist.
</P>
<P>
   The essays, by writers ranging from Martin Duberman to David
Levering Lewis undertake specific aspects of Robeson's work, from
his singing to his acting to his infatuation with the Soviet
experiment. Charles Musser contributes a very interesting take on
Robeson's work with black filmmaker Oscar Micheaux, and his
starring in O'Neill's ``The Emperor Jones'' on stage and film.
</P>
<P>
   For those who know Robeson only from his stunning performance in
the 1937 film of ``Show Boat,'' this collection is a good entry
point to learn more about one of the most gifted, tormented men of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW WRINKLE . . . Random House is extending its Modern Library
franchise into paperbacks for the first time. The first releases in
the new format include Sam Tanenhaus' ``Whittaker Chambers,''
``Nothing But You: Love Stories from The New Yorker,'' and a
paperback original from Filipino author F. Sionil Jose .
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Wilde's ``The Picture of Dorian Gray,'' the first book
ever issued by the Modern Library back in 1917, will also be issued
in paperback, as will Volume 1 of the Moncrieff/Kilmartin
translation of ``Swann's Way,'' and a single book including two
volumes Teddy Roosevelt wrote before he became president: ``Hunting
Trips of a Ranchman'' and ``The Wilderness Hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . . ``I do not know of a single relationship of
my life in which I wasn't eating or being eaten.'' _ Athol Fugard
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-08-98 1142E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
