A7022 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOODS-DISAPPEARING10-     07-09 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODS-DISAPPEARING10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Are decadent foods disappearing?
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a Valentine's Day without chocolate. Or a birthday party
without ice cream. Or even a wedding without champagne, smoked
salmon or cream cheese to spread on it?
</P>
<P>
   It could happen. Chances are, however, the foods will be around
_ but at a precious price.
</P>
<P>
   Decadent foods may be on the wane for a variety of reasons, but
mostly, it's simply supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   Take the butterfat situation _ for only the second time in
history, the price of Grade AA butter recently hit $1.95 a pound on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. A predicted shortage had consumers
scrambling for premium ice cream, cheese and butter.
</P>
<P>
   Demand is up for butterfat, said Bob Butler, an Okeechobee,
Fla., dairy farmer. ``Generally, people have decided they prefer
taste again'' after years of low-fat eating, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the cows are on a nine-month production schedule. You can
expect higher prices till the cows catch up, Butler said, but we're
in no danger of running out.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the fish is more in question _ demand for seafood is
growing steadily, said David Nitchman, spokesman for the National
Fisheries Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Overfishing has been the result. Some argue that up to 30
percent of species are being overfished _ swordfish, once an
expensive fish but now common, is only one of those species.
Sturgeon, which produce caviar, are threatened, as are certain
types of salmon. But many fish have faced cyclical declines for
several reasons, including popularity.
</P>
<P>
   If left alone, they do recover, said Tom Thomas, of Florida's
Bureau of Seafood and Aquaculture. ``Florida has a management plan
for swordfish, and we do have swordfish _ we want consumers to know
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There will be enough fish around for everyone, he said, but
maybe not as much and not right away.
</P>
<P>
   Wine experts have already said if you don't have your Dom
Perignon for the year 2000 New Year's celebration, you aren't
getting any. Production for premium champagnes, again, is only so
great _ and we're talking about a whole world celebrating with a
toast.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast for Godiva, and other chocolate, is pretty sweet,
however, even though prices may increase to keep up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Smith, spokeswoman for the Chocolate Manufacturers of
America, said, ``Researchers are just now beginning to learn how to
better grow the beans, and increase production.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly not in any danger of running out of chocolate
any time, but I can't predict the prices,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Art Simmering, trend watcher and editor of Trend/Watch, a
newsletter for the food industry, said luxury foods will always be
with us, but their availability is simply ``supply and demand.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, he said, chocolate, caviar and butter _ and
other luxury foods _ may again find their way back to their high
positions in the food pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's a good thing,'' he said. ``Maybe some of us could
stand to cut back on our consumption of things like butter, and ice
cream, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
