A7023 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEE-BEETLE10-COX     07-09 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEE-BEETLE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honey eating beetle is everyone's beeswax
 &HT;    By Jim Reeder
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ A tiny beetle that somehow made its way from
South Africa to attack honeybee hives in South Florida threatens
the state's $11 million honey business as well as other crops that
depend on bees to pollinate their flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The beetles eat the honey, defecate in the honeycomb and destroy
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's sour, rotten honey running out of the hives,'' said
Laurence Cutts of the state Department of Agriculture and Consumer
Services. ``It's sickening.''
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture officials can't figure out how the beetle moved from
South Africa to a Port St. Lucie area grove where it was discovered
last fall but only identified in early June.
</P>
<P>
   The beetle has spread to Indian River, Lake, Polk, Brevard and
Martin counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew exactly what they were, their potential for damage
or what to do about it,'' said Cutts. ``They totally destroy the
combs, honey, the bees _ they wipe out everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The small hive beetle is a native of South Africa and until
recently had been found nowhere in the western hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Beetles live in bee hives as larva and as adults, though the
pupa live in soil, Cutts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody brings South African dirt to Florida and it would be
easier to smuggle in an elephant than to bring in a bee hive,''
Cutts said. ``We have no earthly idea how they got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony York, a Fort Pierce beekeeper, noticed the beetles last
fall but didn't think it was a real problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider anything a threat until something happens to
the hive,'' York said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the beetles have destroyed 32 of his hives.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Russ of Haines City discovered the beetle in hives he was
keeping near Port St. Lucie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought it in and said it was killing his hives,'' Cutts
said. ``I didn't believe it and thought the beetles were just
scavenging in a sick hive.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 38 of Russ' 40 hives have been destroyed and another is on
the critical list.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture and state officials are
studying the pest in hopes of finding a way to control it.
</P>
<P>
   They're studying pesticides, traps , bacteria, fungus and other
methods to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   The beetles aren't considered a problem in South Africa where
they co-habit with the tougher ``killer bees'' on that continent,
Cutts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not a serious concern except among the weakest
hives,'' Cutts said. ``The killer bees there defend their hives
vigorously and are able to keep the beetle at bay more than our
docile European bees.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
