<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7024 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-CONWAY10-COX     07-09 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CONWAY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author Raye Virginia Allen rediscovers art of Gordon Conway
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Most of us first heard about Gordon Conway when she
became the subject of a book.
</P>
<P>
   She was a Texas debutante with a man's name who broke into the
male-dominated New York advertising and magazine world in 1914. At
age 20, she helped inaugurate the fashion image of the Jazz Age's
New Woman with her stylized drawings for Vogue, Vanity Fair and
Harper's Bazaar magazines. Her working years took her from New York
to Paris and London. She created billboards and costumes for stage
and film, became a set designer, and managed the first costume
department at a British film studio. All the while, she created
posters and illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Her high-pressure, stressful life resulted in a heart attack at
age 39 that forced her to retire. And she faded from view. Just
like that.
</P>
<P>
   Why? It was mainly her health. But styles in art were changing.
The public came to prefer a softer edge. The less-expensive
photographic image had begun to replace drawing. Plus, she was away
from urban centers and thus easily forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Always a loner, Conway did not network in professional
associations and had no acolytes or interns to keep her name alive
once she left the scene. At least, that's the way the author of
``Gordon Conway: Fashioning a New Woman'' explains how she came to
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Conway, who died in 1956, remained forgotten until another
well-connected Texan, Raye Virginia Allen, researched her story and
put it into a book. Since its publication last fall by the
University of Texas Press, ``Gordon Conway: Fashioning a New
Woman'' has prompted _ and continues to prompt _ numerous exhibits
around the country on the talented artist and her work.
</P>
<P>
   And within the past year, most of Conway's original artwork has
been collected by the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center at
UT.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the renewed interest in Conway is the seductive
nature of her colorful, sophisticated drawings. Another is the
passion author Allen feels for her subject, spending more than a
decade working on this book. Living part of the year in Washington,
D.C., and the rest at her comfortable hilltop home in Temple, Allen
proselytizes for Conway from both places. Scheduled events have
included one this past April at the National Museum of Women in the
Arts as well as upcoming fall events in Austin, Kerrville,
Galveston, Dallas, Corpus Christi, Fort Worth, Nacogdoches, New
York, and London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I traveled for 14 years in search of the woman's artwork and
life story,'' Allen said. ``Now _ in 1998-'99 _ I'm telling the
tale of the hard-working glamorous New Woman in the very places
that unearthed details of her era between the World Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her artwork is so gay and cheerful and happy, so full of
celebration,'' Allen said, ``even when her personal life was on a
downward spiral. At first everything came together for her and it
all seemed so effortless. She had this Texas savvy about how to get
things done.'' But then, Allen said, the stress of her meteoric
career cut short her life.
</P>
<P>
   The interest in Conway for Allen began not in Texas but in
Washington, where Allen's husband was part of the Carter
administration, and she was a cultural historian serving on the
board of the American Folklife Center. A friend from Paris, Texas,
introduced her to a cousin of Conway who owned the collection of
the late artist's work, diaries and letters. After seeing the
pictures and learning of the archives, Allen scrapped other plans
and agreed to write her American Studies dissertation at UT on
Conway. ``I knew I should do it and could do it, and I wanted to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her UT adviser, the Pulitzer-Prize winning historian William
Goetzmann, agreed. ``He told me, `Raye, if you have the use of this
private collection and archives, do not miss a day. Join up.' So I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a rare chance to do primary research on an important
shaper of popular taste. Born in Cleburne, reared in Dallas, and
educated in Washington and Switzerland, Conway grew up wealthy. Her
forte became the creation of images that fed the dreams of
middle-class people everywhere yearning for glamour and excitement.
``If the stern women's movements of the early 20th century aimed to
drag males into the world of equality,'' UT professor Goetzmann
wrote in the introduction to Allen's book, ``Conway's females
enticed them into it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether on paper, on stage, or in person, Gordon carefully
developed her style like a commodity for the consumer market _ a
product that a large segment of the public liked and came to
expect,'' Allen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One Conde Nast editor at the time said, ``The American woman
feels that she can be a better wife, a better worker, if she can
only believe that glamour is to be her lot.''
</P>
<P>
   As the book tells it, the backstory was that Conway fought
stress by reordering the world around her. Art and design became
the leitmotif of her life.
</P>
<P>
   What came to interest Allen as much as Conway's art was her
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started out, it was to write about the artwork
and how it reflected the culture _ also, how she helped shape it.
That eventually became Part II of the book. Once I got into the
diaries and interviews and discovered her stress level and burnout,
I realized this was a very modern story,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my editor at UT Press, Frankie Westbrook, that modern
women would identify with this story, and she agreed I should write
it.... I would like to think I have resurrected Gordon Conway.
She's a woman who deserves it _ a model for women today
struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen did 75 interviews researching the book. She talked to
family, friends and associates of Conway, as well as to authorities
on that time period. Of Conway's declining days, Allen says that
she ``remained optimistic, even though she had cancer and heart
trouble. She stayed hopeful by sheer will. She never complained.
She didn't want her mother to know she had cancer.'' In the last 14
years of her life, Conway had various malignancies from breast
cancer to uterine cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Allen writes that on the afternoon before Conway died, at the
family estate in Virginia in 1956, she went downstairs for a game
of backgammon with her mother. ``Halfway into the game, she sighed
and asked to be excused.''
</P>
<P>
   UT Press plans a special book signing this fall to provide an
opportunity to meet the author.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Morris is the book editor for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
