<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7025 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROGE-PROFILE10-COX     07-09 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROGE-PROFILE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Profile of Seattle rocker Pete Droge
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN Like most great heart-on-their-sleeve garage-rockers,
Pete Droge looks as if he should be working in a convenience store
or a sandwich shop somewhere. His T-shirts and shaggy, lazy hair
recall the looks of everyone from Soul Asylum and Matthew Sweet to
a young Tom Petty, and his melodic, guitar-heavy, three-chord rock
songs are as simple yet wonderful as theirs.
</P>
<P>
   While Soul Asylum was making cameos in ``Clerks'' and Petty was
dancing around with Kim Basinger, though, Droge was working on his
1994 debut, ``Necktie Second,'' which featured the rock radio hit
``If You Don't Love Me (I'll Kill Myself).'' Four years later, the
question is whether there's any place left for Droge or other
plainly clothed rockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be,'' the 29-year-old singer said recently,
calling from his home in Seattle. ``Guys like me, though, have to
go the more traditional routes.''
</P>
<P>
   For Droge, ``traditional'' means touring a lot, which he does.
His show at La Zona Rosa on Friday will be his third stop in Austin
this year.
</P>
<P>
   It also means he has to make great records instead of strong
singles. Which he has done. His 1996 LP ``Find a Door'' was one of
the highlights of that year, a rootsy, toe-tapping,
sing-along-worthy disc from start to finish. His new one, ``Spacey
and Shakin,'' is almost as enjoyable, featuring a touch of
psychedelia and an overload of guitar effects layered onto Droge's
catchy, melodic numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a reaction to being on tour,'' Droge said of the
louder, fuller sound on ``Spacey and Shakin,'' augmented by his
longtime backing band, the Sinners. ``It's a natural thing. Iif you
perform a lot, you're going to want to turn it up and let the band
loose. That's just what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Spacey and Shakin'' _ produced, like Droge's other albums, by
Brendan O'Brien (Pearl Jam, Rage Against the Machine) _ was also
the result of some down time that occurred when Droge's former
record label, American Recordings, folded. Because of the record
company's foundering business, the ``Find a Door'' album went
mostly unnoticed. You probably won't hear Droge complaining,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it was frustrating at first, going on tour and not
seeing my record in any of the record stores,'' he said. ``But
looking back, it gave me some much-needed down time. I had the
chance to really think these songs and this album through and take
a breather, and that may have been more healthy for my longevity
than making a hit out of that record.''
</P>
<P>
   And anyway, there really is only one way to make a hit in
Droge's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have sort of a romantic notion about what rock 'n' roll used
to be,'' he said. ``I still believe in the hard-work ethic and that
genuine connection you make with audiences at a concert. Everything
else is unimportant.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Riemenschneider is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1021EDT &QL; 
