<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADELINE-POEM10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The shrewdest one was Madeline
 &HT;    By Dale Fuchs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: A Long Island lass heralds Friday's big screen
debut of the plucky French heroine every girl knew.
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   In a new house in Boca without any vines,
</P>
<P>
   I recall my youth as I sip red wine.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, I read bedtime stories all the time;
</P>
<P>
   my favorite one was Madeline.
</P>
<P>
   She was so different from you and me;
</P>
<P>
   she lived in a house in Gay Paree
</P>
<P>
   with 11 little girls in two straight lines,
</P>
<P>
   and wherever they went, people spoke in rhymes.
</P>
<P>
   (What that house was, I could never tell _
</P>
<P>
   An orphanage? A prep school? A convent? Oh, well.)
</P>
<P>
   Madeline was famous for raising hell,
</P>
<P>
   and oh, could she frighten that Miss Clavel.
</P>
<P>
   The action always took place somewhere pretty,
</P>
<P>
   some touristy spot in that classy French city.
</P>
<P>
   I, meanwhile, lived an ocean away,
</P>
<P>
   in a boring 'burb off the Long Island Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   While Madeline would dress oh-so-proper
</P>
<P>
   I looked nothing like a Chanel shopper.
</P>
<P>
   No matched hats and coats or Catholic school shoes:
</P>
<P>
   I wore pink Danskins and rubber snow boots.
</P>
<P>
   While she got to stroll past the Eiffel Tower,
</P>
<P>
   I sat home with the Flintstones for hours.
</P>
<P>
   And when Miss Clavel took the girls to the Seine,
</P>
<P>
   My mom shlepped me to Loehmann's again.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, I rode the bus to Cantiague School
</P>
<P>
   where standing in two straight lines wasn't cool.
</P>
<P>
   No reason for mom to dial DANton-ten-six,
</P>
<P>
   'cause nothing (shucks) was wrong with my appendix.
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, Madeline hasn't grown.
</P>
<P>
   She has no job or home of her own.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be deceived by her innocent looks.
</P>
<P>
   She's making a mint with dolls, videos and books.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day, readers cried, ``Boo Hoo!
</P>
<P>
   We want a movie tie-in, too!''
</P>
<P>
   So now like the mermaid and Mr. Magoo,
</P>
<P>
   Madeline is coming to a theater near you.
</P>
<P>
   (But I'll skip the movie _ in sunshine or rain.
</P>
<P>
   I'm saving my money for a Paris-bound plane.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
