<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SCHOOL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School program scheduled out of space flight
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A popular education program has been scratched from
the October space shuttle flight of Sen. John Glenn because the
astronauts are booked solid with a vast array of science
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   One school in Japan and five in the United States _ including
John Glenn High School in New Concord _ were each scheduled to
connect via amateur radio with the shuttle Discovery for 10-minute
conversations between students and astronauts. Although the
air-time is relatively short, NASA schedulers decided last week
that the process of setting up and then stowing the radio equipment
makes the classroom program too time-consuming for a mission that
already has more than 80 experiments aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time-liners have come to the conclusion that it doesn't
all fit,'' said Doug Ward, head of public information at Johnson
Space Center in Houston. ``That's not one we like to give up, but
it also has a lower priority than the science.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shuttle Amateur Radio Experiment (SAREX) began in 1983
aboard the ninth shuttle mission, and spent its first few years as
a secondary project that astronauts did only in their leisure time.
Although it now is a scheduled shuttle program like any other, it's
not uncommon for a SAREX project to be scratched when a shuttle
schedule gets too full.
</P>
<P>
   Now NASA's education division is looking for a replacement
project that will fit the schedule of the nine-day flight that also
has great education potential because of its high public profile
with Glenn aboard. In addition to being the oldest person in space
(he'll be 77 by launch day), Glenn is returning to space for the
first time since being the first American to orbit the earth in
1962.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Robertson, who heads the education and information
services division of the Johnson Center, said she's been given a
short window in the astronauts' schedule to fill with an education
project and she said Glenn will be at the center of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 30 minutes open for some kind of education event,''
she said. ``And right now, we don't know what that's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Word that the SAREX program had gotten the ax apparently hadn't
reached Glenn, who on Tuesday touted it as one of the
``intangible'' benefits of the space program. During debate on the
Senate floor over an amendment to kill the International Space
Station, Glenn's defense of the station included mention of the
radio talks he'd be giving to students while aboard the Discovery
in October.
</P>
<P>
   A staff member for Glenn said the senator wouldn't comment on
the loss of SAREX from his mission because he doesn't want to
overstep his role as a regular member of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   Since being named to shuttle crew in January, Glenn has taken
pains to point out how ``research rich'' the flight would be, and
two weeks ago his flight commander, Air Force Lt. Col. Curt Brown,
said in Houston that the flight was so rich in experiments that
NASA schedulers were considering cutting some projects.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a multitude of experiments, the crew also will
use the heavy mechanical arm in the shuttle's cargo bay to deploy
and then retrieve a sun-measuring device called the Spartan. Glenn
himself will be the subject of two experiments in which scientists
are searching for links between the human body's reaction to
extended periods of weightlessness and old age, which cause similar
debilitating effects.
</P>
<P>
   For more on this subject, check out our on-line partner at
www.ActiveDayton.co
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
