A7029 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN10-COX     07-09 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    She wanted a picture of her smiling son's face
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The woman on the other end of the phone line identified herself
as Betty Capps, not that this meant anything to me. I have a hard
enough time putting
</P>
<P>
   names with faces, much less voices on the telephone. I just
assumed that Mrs. Capps was a loyal reader with a problem.
</P>
<P>
   That much was true, though it was a problem I had never been
presented with before, or since. Nor do I expect it to happen
again.
</P>
<P>
   Her complaint began in an ordinary enough fashion. She was upset
about her son's picture in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   I must admit that I got an instant mental picture. I didn't know
who her son was, but I imagined it was somebody who had been shown
on the front page
</P>
<P>
   of the newspaper, legs splayed, hands up against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   I put on my stern editor's voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Capps, this newspaper has a duty to print the news of the
community, as uncomfortable. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Capps heard me, if she was even listening, I will never
know. She just kept right on with her compliant.
</P>
<P>
   I just had to do something about her son's picture. She was
nice, but firm beyond any thought that she might change her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Capps, what do you want me to do?'' I was getting a bit
exasperated, but I already had a good idea I was going to lose this
argument.
</P>
<P>
   She paused for a moment and then said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to get him to smile.''
</P>
<P>
   A brief picture of a criminal up against the wall smiling at the
camera flashed through my mind before I realized something was
wrong here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is your son, Mrs. Capps?''
</P>
<P>
   It was Jack Stallard, the sports editor at the Lufkin Daily News
and who now works for our sister paper, the Longview News-Journal.
Mrs. Capps had a
</P>
<P>
   Lufkin paper mailed to her mostly to read her son's column. The
column was accompanied by a thumbnail picture of a serious
Stallard. I had questioned
</P>
<P>
   the picture at the time, but Jack mumbled something about how
women loved the serious look.
</P>
<P>
   Not the one woman who counted. She had apparently been pestering
him for a while to change the picture but he had conveniently
forgotten. When that
</P>
<P>
   failed she went to the top. Lord knows where she would have gone
had I not responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack has such a pretty smile,'' she said, though ``pretty''
was never an adjective I used when describing Stallard. ``The world
needs to see my son smile.''
</P>
<P>
   I agreed and thanked Mrs. Capps for the call. I walked to my
office door and ordered Jack inside. Now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will,'' I said, ``get a new picture taken this moment. In
that picture you will give your best smile. When you go home this
weekend, you will show
</P>
<P>
   it to your mama and see if that smile is good enough. If it is
not, you will retake that picture until you get it right.
Understand?''
</P>
<P>
   He understood.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later I got another call from Mrs. Capps thanking
me for the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love that smile,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack's mom died last week. I had only met her in person a few
times, but I knew her well, through three of her sons.
</P>
<P>
   It sometimes happens that good people produce bad children, but
bad people almost never rear good kids.
</P>
<P>
   At least three of her children, the ones I know, are first rate.
One was a career Marine who is the only male I've ever let keep my
children overnight
</P>
<P>
   (he actually drilled them). One is a Lufkin police officer; the
other is Jack, who is one of the best people I've ever known.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure Mrs. Capps would have understood why Jack's smile was
gone last week, but I don't think it is something she would accept
for very long.
</P>
<P>
   The world needs to see your smile, Jack. Don't take it from me,
those are your mother's words.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
