<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-SMOKING10-COX     07-09 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-SMOKING10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE DIARY OF A (PSYCHOTIC) NON-SMOKER
 &HT;    BY EMILY J. MINOR
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note:
</P>
<P>
   Emily quit smoking three months ago Monday. But folks, it hasn't
always been pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks prior to April 6
</P>
<P>
   Wherever I was _ baseball game, car, kitchen talking on the
phone, computer at home _ tried to imagine myself not smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, April 5
</P>
<P>
   Filled out my quit smoking pledge card.
</P>
<P>
   Got my little nicotine patches all ready for in the morning
</P>
<P>
   Bought sugarless gum, and put it in a bowl on the kitchen
counter
</P>
<P>
   Bought vegetables and cut them up
</P>
<P>
   Smoked like a fiend all day
</P>
<P>
   Smoked last cigarette around 7 p.m. (when pack ran out.)
</P>
<P>
   Went to bed at 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't fall asleep because I was so scared about tomorrow
</P>
<P>
   Monday, April 6
</P>
<P>
   Ate chips and dip all morning
</P>
<P>
   Swam in pool every time I felt like smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Had girlfriend over with her kids and we swam and stenciled
little buckets (that we later put plants in)
</P>
<P>
   Called girlfriend on vacation to wish her Happy 40th BD. (Quit
on April 6 so I'd always remember the quit date. Her birthday.)
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, April 7
</P>
<P>
   Felt like a crazy woman all day. Talked on the phone. Wanted a
cigarette so bad my insides were actually itching.
</P>
<P>
   April 17
</P>
<P>
   Went out drinking with the girls to celebrate Riz' 40th
birthday. Didn't smoke!
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, April 18
</P>
<P>
   Hung over from last night's shenanigans. Didn't wear patch
today. Didn't smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, April 19
</P>
<P>
   Still hung over. Didn't smoke. Didn't wear patch.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, April 25
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina for my niece's wedding. Marty smoked a
cigarette and I wanted one so much my mouth was actually watering.
I WISH I SMOKED!!
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, April 26
</P>
<P>
   Woke up glad that I didn't smoke yesterday
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News,'' said Young, a
past chairman of the American Chemical Society Division of Chemical
Health and Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Young, a former chemistry professor at Florida State University,
said that E. coli bacteria are quickly killed in a pool with proper
levels of chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Hancock, an epidemiologist at Washington State University,
said E. coli might survive for some time in properly chlorinated
water if the bacteria were encased in feces. If feces became lodged
in a pool's filter system, it could slowly dissolve and be released
unnoticed into the water, lengthening the time of hazard, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts and health officials stress that the White Water E. coli
outbreak is only the second known case of a pool spreading the
disease. The first also occurred in Georgia in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Without state laws, Georgia counties and cities are free to set
differing standards on pool care. Fulton County, for instance,
allows public pools to dip to 0.5 parts per million on a chlorine
test before posting a failing grade.
</P>
<P>
   Hall County does not routinely inspect the water park at Lake
Lanier Islands. The seven pools at Stone Mountain are inspected
about once a month during the summer, according to DeKalb County
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Among Southeastern states, Florida, South Carolina and North
Carolina have statewide pool laws. Florida is considered toughest
at cracking down on its 30,000 public pools, taking action against
4,000 of them last year.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 water parks operate in the U.S. and Canada, and
inspection routines vary so much that it's difficult to compare
them to White Water's track record.
</P>
<P>
   In San Dimas, Calif., the county inspects the pools at Raging
Waters twice a month during the warmer months. That's twice as
often as the Marietta pools are checked. About once a month, one of
the 13 attractions falls below the county's chlorine minimum of 1.0
parts per million, which local officials consider a good record.
</P>
<P>
   Like Georgia, there's no state law on public pool sanitation in
Missouri, where the owners of White Water have another water park
in Branson. That city has adopted a low-chlorine standard of 0.4
parts per million.
</P>
<P>
   But at even lower levels of chlorine a pool may pass inspection
depending upon other factors, said Health Department director
Linnea Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Only one pool has failed at the Missouri water park since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But if one of the pools at the Soak City water park in Sandusky,
Ohio falls below 1.0, it fails, said Sandusky sanitarian Bob
Butler. Butler inspects the pools twice a year and said a Soak City
pool fails about once every two years.
</P>
<P>
   Chlorine testing is not an exact science, and mistakes are easy
to make, said Wally James, president of Con-Serve Associates, an
Iowa-based water park consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Inspections are conducted by dipping a small container into the
pool, and then mixing the water with a chemical that turns varying
shades of pink, depending on the chlorine level.
</P>
<P>
   The dyed water is then held up to a color chart and matched to a
color that indicates the chlorine level.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hold the kit up to the sun, or do the test in poor
light, you could be off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James said investigators looking into the E. coli infections may
want to check beyond the pool. ``E. coli dies within six seconds in
water with 2.0 (parts per million) chlorine,'' he said. James
speculated that the outbreak might stem from a child having an
``accident'' in one of the bathrooms, on a pool deck, or some other
place where chlorine is not used.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials have discounted that possibility, said Joyce
Goldberg, spokeswoman for the state Department of Human Resources.
``We believe it was probably a bunch of kids in a corner of a pool
in close proximity to the one who had the accident,'' Goldberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
