<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYROLL09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mr. Payroll debuts at Ohio Speedway/Starvin' Marvin
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A new money machine making its Dayton debut uses
military technology to let people cash checks anytime they like.
</P>
<P>
   The Mr. Payroll Check Cashing Machine has been installed at the
Speedway/Starvin' Marvin station at 2232 Needmore Rd., just west of
Interstate 75. Nestled between car care products and soft drinks,
the machine cashes any type of check any time of day without photo
identification.
</P>
<P>
   On first use, the machine asks for the user's address and other
information to help establish the person's identity. The machine
also uses technology called facial biometrics to electronically
measure and record an image of the user's face.
</P>
<P>
   On subsequent visits, customers enter their Social Security
numbers while the machine photographs the faces and matches them
with images on file. If number and photo match up, the check is
cashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The security feature on this is outstanding,'' said R. Day
Harter, Speedway district manager. ``People can steal your PIN
number from your ATM card, but they can't steal your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the first machine became operational in June 1997, 45 more
have been installed in 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Payroll is the brainchild of Michael Stinson, who founded
Mr. Payroll Corp. in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we thought there was potential for an evolutionary
development along the way,'' Stinson said. By October 1996, the
company had an agreement to develop the machine. The following
summer, the first machine was unveiled for public use.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Payroll charges 1.5 percent of the amount cashed for
payroll/government checks; 2.5 percent for personal and two-party
checks; and 3.5 percent for tax, insurance and other checks.
Stinson said the cost to use Mr. Payroll compares favorably with
other outlets for getting quick cash, such as automatic teller
machines and stand-alone check-cashing outlets, whose fees can go
as high as 20 percent in some markets.
</P>
<P>
   Stinson said the company will monitor how well Mr. Payroll is
received in Dayton before deciding whether to add machines in the
Miami Valley and in Speedways across the country. Harter said the
response so far has been positive, with lines forming in the store
the first weekend in July.
</P>
<P>
   Stinson said he hopes to install Mr. Payroll in grocery stores,
major discount stores and a variety of bank branches. Already Mr.
Payroll is in 11 Wells Fargo bank branches for use by non-bank
customers, he said
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
