<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE QUESTIONS KING JURORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge questioned each juror in the fraud
trial of Don King on Wednesday to gauge the impact that one
panelist had on the others by relating a news report of the
sentence King could face if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The all-day interviewing in U.S. District Court Judge Lawrence
McKenna's chambers in Manhattan, postponed the third day of
deliberations and delayed McKenna's expected ruling on a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of defrauding a Lloyd's of London insurance
syndicate in 1991, King could be sentenced to up to 45 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The jury forewoman sent McKenna two notes on Tuesday, one saying
she was convinced that a verdict could not be reached because of a
holdout juror and another that ``the one juror,'' possibly the
holdout, had related the newspaper report about the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In the second note, the forewoman also said she wanted to
discuss matters privately with McKenna, who said he would let her
``tell me what she wanted to tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what she is going to say,'' McKenna said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1035EDT &QL; 
