</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FRIDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Friday, July 10, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ Coverage for the new fall TV season in
California: first up _ A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' of Ernest Hemingway,
Comedy Central, Fox Family Channel and USA. (LHarris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Eds: CNN and Turner group appears this day
before the press. ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HBO-OZ _ HBO's ``OZ,'' the preposterous prison drama returns on
Saturday. (Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   CRIDER-COOKSMAGAZINE _ AUSTIN _ Pam Anderson has cleaned and
cooked 100 pounds of greens, roasted 20 prime ribs, and baked
50-plus cobblers. This Pam Anderson is not the Baywatch babe, but
the executive editor of Cook's Illustrated, a serious
no-advertising bimonthly cooking magazine. The author of ``The
Perfect Recipe: Getting It Right Every Time'' cookbook (Chapters,
$27), Anderson was in Austin at Central Market recently to show how
to cook the perfect roast chicken. (Crider, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-COOKING _ For a generation of people who frequently dine
out as a matter of stomach-rumbling necessity, cooking _ honest,
satisfying home cooking _ is making a comeback. For special dates.
For weekend projects. For fun. (Kessler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-DISAPPEARING _ Imagine a Valentine's Day without chocolate.
Or a birthday party without ice cream. Or even a wedding without
champagne, smoked salmon or cream cheese to spread on it? It could
happen. Chances are, however, the foods will be around _ but at a
precious price. Decadent foods may be on the wane for a variety of
reasons, but mostly, it's simply supply and demand. (Norris, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ The cover picture is of a hundred or so rotary
phones, which nicely captures the essence of ``Going Going Gone''
(Chronicle, $19.95) a very amusing volume about vanishing
Americana. Another, rather more serious but equally entertaining
book is ``Paul Robeson: Artist and Citizen'' (Rutgers University
Press, $25), a collection of essays and beautiful photographs
published on the centenary of the great singer and political
activist. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ROSS _ Sometimes it seems that all that's left of the
classic age of The New Yorker is the typeface and Lillian Ross. She
has recently published ``Here But Not Here'' (Random House, $25), a
memoir of her 40-year love affair with New Yorker editor William
Shawn that has aroused much negative comment, largely because of
Ross' decision to publish while Shawn's widow is still alive.
(Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-CONWAY _ Gordon Conway, who died in 1956, remained
forgotten until another well-connected Texan, Raye Virginia Allen,
researched her story and put it into a book. Since its publication
last fall by the University of Texas Press, ``Gordon Conway:
Fashioning a New Woman'' has prompted _ and continues to prompt _
numerous exhibits around the country on the talented artist and her
work. (Morris, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   BACKSTREETBOYS _ The last time we talked to the Backstreet Boys,
they were just starting to be noticed. They've succeeded. The Boys
today are one of the hottest bands around. (Harrison, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BACKSTREET-SIDE _ Sidebar to the Backstreet Boys main bar. A
look at the proliferation of ``boy'' groups. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   9JAM _ Ruminations on whether Pearl Jam still matters, after
seeing them Sunday in Dallas. (Chris, Austin American-Statesman)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DROGE-PROFILE _ AUSTIN Like most great heart-on-their-sleeve
garage-rockers, Pete Droge looks as if he should be working in a
convenience store or a sandwich shop somewhere. His T-shirts and
shaggy, lazy hair recall the looks of everyone from Soul Asylum and
Matthew Sweet to a young Tom Petty, and his melodic, guitar-heavy,
three-chord rock songs are as simple yet wonderful as theirs.
(Riemenschneider, Austin American-Stateman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL BLACK ARTS FESTIVAL
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-JITNEY _ ATLANTA _ Noted playwright August Wilson dusts off
one of his first plays, ``Jitney.'' Why? What's next? (Hulbert,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-HOMAGE _ ATLANTA _ A look at Homage, four short films
screening at Atlanta's High Museum. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-JAM _ ATLANTA _ What happens at the famous midnight jam
sessions that take place at the Renaissance Hotel. Scene piece
covers the who, what, where, when, why and gives a flavor of these
sessions. (Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-SHANGE _ ATLANTA _ Catching up with Ntozake Shange, who
comes to the NBAF to read poetry. (Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA MOVIES (Move with an ETA of 8 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-JEALOUSY _ Review of ``Mr. Jealousy'' with Eric Stoltz.
(Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SMOKE _ Review of ``Smoke Signals.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-HIGHART _ Review of ``High Art,'' with Ally Sheedy.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SOLDIERS _ Review of ``Small Soldiers.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MADELINE _ Review of ``Madeline,'' based on children's
books, with Frances McDormand. (Vejnoska, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-LETHAL4 _ Review of ``Lethal Weapon 4.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN MOVIES (Move with an ETA of 8 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   9CINEMA _ The Austin Film Festival and how they cope with the
mountain of screenplays they receive for their Heart of Film
screenplay contest. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   PALM BEACH MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   MADELINE-POEM _ In a new house in Boca without any vines,
</P>
<P>
   I recall my youth as I sip red wine.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, I read bedtime stories all the time;
</P>
<P>
   my favorite one was Madeline. (Fuchs, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-SCHOOL _ WASHINGTON _ A popular education program has been
scratched from the October space shuttle flight of Sen. John Glenn
because the astronauts are booked solid with a vast array of
science experiments. (Montgomery, Cox Washington Bureau) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   REVIVAL-JAKES _ Bishop T.D. Jakes is in town this week, telling
women how to refocus their lives. The nationally known and
respected cleric from Texas will be holding a three-day event at
the Georgia Dome and is expected to draw thousands of the faithful
each night. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitutioin) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   NEEDLES _ The pain of a shot could become a thing of the past as
Georgia researchers develop ways to inject medicine through the
skin without the use of traditional needles. From the development
of ``microneedles,'' several times smaller than the diameter of a
human hair, to a laser punch, the techniques would make it easier
for patients to get the drugs they need, reduce the chance of
infection and remove the need for medical workers to administer the
medications. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-LIGHTNING _ A summer thunderstorm rumbling across Central
Texas can produce hundreds of lightning strikes in a short time. We
talk to weather experts about the impact/dangers of these strikes.
(Holloway, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BEE-BEETLE _ FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ A tiny beetle that somehow made
its way from South Africa to attack honeybee hives in South Florida
threatens the state's $11 million honey business as well as other
crops that depend on bees to pollinate their flowers. (Reeder, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WWATER-CHLORINE _ ATLANTA -- At least one pool at White Water
park failed chlorine tests during 16 of about 75 county inspections
performed since the park opened in 1983, according to public health
officials and inspection records obtained by The Atlanta Journal
Constitution. The inspection record prompted mixed reactions from
public health officials and experts. (Schneider, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
