<SLUG> BC-FLAG-BURNING-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH SIDES SPEAK AT ANTI-DESECRATION BILL HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to correct Rick Monday team affiliation to Cubs.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wednesday was Flag Day at the US Senate as Tommy
Lasorda of the Los Angeles Dodgers and other Americans told the
Judiciary Committee of their love for the red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  During a hearing on a proposed constitutional amendment that
would allow Congress to protect the flag from desecration, others
testified that what the flag represented was more important.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed its version of the flag desecration amendment
last year, and the Senate Judiciary Committee approved it by a 10-7
vote June 24. A date has not been set for the full Senate to vote
on the issue, but a close vote is likely.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda and most of the other panelists said they support the
amendment. The Dodgers' general manager told of a time he witnessed
protesters set fire to a flag at a Dodgers game against the Chicago
Cubs in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all watched dumbstruck as the man pulled out a match and
tried to light the American flag to burn it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda said Cubs outfielder Rick Monday committed ``one of the
most heroic acts ever to take place on the field during a Major
League Baseball game'' when the player grabbed the burning flag
from the protester and ran toward the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``And without any prompting that I can remember, the whole crowd
stood and began to fill the stadium with an impromptu rendition of
`God Bless America,' '' Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   Another celebrity, actor and singer John Schneider, who played
Bo Duke in the former television show ``Dukes of Hazzard,'' also
encouraged the Senate to pass the amendment. Schneider has recorded
a song called ``I Love Old Glory,'' which was written by Senator
Orrin G. Hatch of Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who sponsored the proposed amendment, said, ``While it
might be nice if a statute were all that was needed to permit
Congress to prohibit flag desecration, a constitutional amendment
is necesary because the Supreme Court has given us no choice in the
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1989 and in 1990 that flag burning is
considered free speech and protected by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Russell D. Feingold, Democrat of Wisconsin, said ``it
may be the most politically unpopular position I could take,'' but
he opposes the proposed amendment. Although he is offended by acts
of flag desecration, Feingold said, people should have the right to
commit them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand in opposition to this amendment because it will limit
Americans' First Amendment right to freedom of speech _ the most
fundamental of rights guaranteed our citizens by our Constitution
and the most fundamental of rights necessary to maintain our
constitutional democracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin V. Stenhammar, a disabled veteran from Asheville, N.C.,
also urged the Senate to vote against the amendment. ``Flags, no
matter how honored, do not have rights. People do. Please protect
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To be enacted, the proposed amendment must pass the Senate with
a two-thirds vote and then be ratified by 38 states. In 1995, a
similar amendment failed by three votes in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
