<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LYME-DISEASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYME DISEASE TICK AN ADDED GOLF COURSE HAZARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By TOPSY SIDEROWF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you play golf, you're at risk for getting Lyme disease. In
fact, the worse you play, the greater your chances. Deer ticks,
prime agents in the spread of Lyme and other tick-borne diseases,
lurk in the damp, tall grass of the rough and leafy underbrush of
the surrounding woods.
</P>
<P>
   Don't go nonchalantly looking for balls that stray off the
fairway. That's especially true if you play in metropolitan New
York, one of the endemic areas for the disease in the country. New
York state leads the nation with more than 40,000 cases reported
between 1982 and 1997. Connecticut, where Lyme disease was first
identified in 1975, is next, followed by New Jersey and
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   From early reports, this is going to be a bumper year. ``On a
scale of 0 to 10, the tick index is 10 now and it's likely to
remain 10 for the next several weeks,'' said Rich Falco, an
entomologist at Fordham.
</P>
<P>
   Nymphal ticks, active through August, are the culprits. Often
undetected because they're so small _ like a sesame seed _ nymphs
account for 95 percent of Lyme disease cases. Apple-seed-sized
adult ticks, which come out in the fall, are less of a threat,
since they are more likely to be seen and felt.
</P>
<P>
   A bull's-eye rash is the classic symptom of Lyme disease. If you
have this, it means the tick that bit you is infected with Borrelia
burgdorferi, the bacteria that causes the disease. See a physician
immediately. Early Lyme disease responds to antibiotics like
doxycycline and amoxicillin.
</P>
<P>
   But diagnosis is sometimes elusive because the tell-tale rash
appears in only 80 percent of cases. There's also a high
false-negative response in laboratory tests early in the disease.
If you feel as though you have a summer flu _ fever, chills,
headache, muscle and joint pains _ but no runny nose, and have
spent time outdoors in a Lyme disease-endemic area _ like the
Northeast, the upper Midwest and northern California _chances are
good it's Lyme disease. Untreated, it can lead to chronic arthritis
and heart and nervous system abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   This same deer tick is responsible for two other emerging
tick-borne diseases, ehrlichiosis and babesiosis. Both are more
severe initially than Lyme, but respond well to therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few simple precautions can reduce your exposure to tick
bites by 99 percent,'' said David Weld, executive director of the
American Lyme Disease Foundation in Somers, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Spray exposed skin and pant legs with a repellent containing
DEET (diethyl-meta-toluamide). Since ticks are found on the ground,
you need only spray from the knees down. Reapply if you have become
wet. Follow directions on the label.
</P>
<P>
   After your round, do a tick check. Inspect your scalp, armpits,
groin, beltline, back, nape of the neck and behind the knees. If
you find a tick, remove it with a tweezer, grasping the tick by the
head close to the skin. Apply antiseptic at the site. If you remove
the tick within 24 hours after attachment, you are much less likely
to be infected.
</P>
<P>
   Wash your golf clothes and dry them in a dryer after each
wearing. The heat will kill any roaming ticks.
</P>
<P>
   Wear lightly colored clothing so you can more easily see ticks.
</P>
<P>
   Your course superintendent can also take the following steps to
reduce tick populations:
</P>
<P>
   Spray the perimeter with an insecticide between late May and
early June. This targets and eliminates most nymphs.
</P>
<P>
   Build nests for hawks and owls. These birds feed on small
rodents, which are essential in perpetuating the life cycle of a
deer tick.
</P>
<P>
   Clean up wood and leaf piles, which attract rodents.
</P>
<P>
   Lay a 3- to 4-foot-wide path of mulch between your course and
the woods. This creates a barrier ticks won't cross.
</P>
<P>
   Also, SmithKline Beecham's Lymerix vaccine has been recommended
for approval by an advisory panel to the FDA and should be approved
and available for those ages 15 to 70 by the end of August. Three
inoculations over a period of 12 months have been shown to induce
immunity for 8 out of 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   Further information can be obtained by calling the American Lyme
Disease Foundation at (800) 876-LYME or (914) 277-6970
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
