<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW HAVE SPOKEN EASILY IN DISCUSSION ON RACE, CLINTON NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wrapping up his yearlong race initiative, President
Clinton conceded Wednesday that he has had trouble getting people
to talk bluntly and honestly about their racial feelings and that
America's increasing diversity has made the subject more complex
and harder to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that ``unique and still unresolved issues between
black and white Americans'' exist, but he has sought to emphasize
how the country is becoming more ``multi-racial, multi-ethnic,
multi-religious ... and therefore it will be more important both to
understand the differences and identify the common values that hold
us together.''
</P>
<P>
   In a taping of a dialogue on race that will be broadcast on PBS,
Clinton said, ``I think the more people work and learn and worship,
if they have faith, and serve together, the more likely you are to
strike the right balance between celebrating our differences
instead of being afraid of them and still identifying common
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Clinton in the hourlong discussion was a panel of eight
journalists and scholars, moderated by Jim Lehrer of ``The NewsHour
with Jim Lehrer.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the other panelists darted from such topics as
affirmative action, the poor, mixed marriages, and the language of
race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rodriguez, editor of the Pacific News Service and
essayist for ``The NewsHour,'' told Clinton: ``The racial
relationships now in America are so complex and so rich that it
seems to me that we don't have a language even to keep up with that
complexity.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez spoke of a young woman who was asked about her racial
identity and called herself a ``Blaxican,'' because her father is
African-American and her mother is Mexican. ``The fact is we have
been falling in love with each other for over 200 years in this
country, from Pocahontas to Thomas Jefferson's children,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed to agree, later suggesting: ``We need a
vocabulary that embraces America's future. We need a vocabulary
that embraces America's present and past on this race issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The session was the last of three conversations on race led by
Clinton as part of the President's Initiative on Race. The
initiative began in June 1997 with the appointment of a
seven-member advisory board to help spark a national conversation
on race.
</P>
<P>
   During Wednesday's taping, Chicago Tribune columnist Clarence
Page pointedly told Clinton that a problem with the racial dialogue
was the advisory board's ``tiptoeing around the really tough issues
of race'' and its reluctance to grapple with affirmative action.
Clinton did not directly respond.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Lehrer asked Clinton whether he had trouble
getting people to open up and talk about race. The usually verbose
Clinton simply responded: ``Yeah, we don't talk a lot about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer then asked the panel, ``How do you get people to talk
about race?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just walk into a room. I think people are always talking about
race,'' said Sherman Alexie, a filmmaker and author of nine books.
``They use coded language. Well, nobody says that's a black person,
let's talk about being black. It ends up coming up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie, who is a Native American, gave an example: ``What they
will do is come up to me and tell me they're Cherokee. But that's
usually what it amounts to.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton laughed because earlier in the discussion, he said he
didn't know much about the American Indians while growing up in
Arkansas. But he had mentioned that his grandmother was one-quarter
Cherokee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
