<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLEGE-WORKFARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING STUDY, MAYOR SAYS WORKFARE DOESN'T HURT STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Brandishing a new study by the city comptroller's
office, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani said Wednesday that despite fears
to the contrary, his workfare policy requiring welfare recipients
to work for their benefits is good for students at City University
of New York who are receiving public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It improves their grade point average,'' Giuliani said at a
news conference. ``It improves their chance of remaining in school
because they drop out less often, and it improves their chance to
graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found that CUNY students on workfare assignments
during the 1996-1997 school year had slightly higher grades and
slightly lower drop-out rates than the average for other students
who were not on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The study covered only students remaining in college after
workfare provisions were enacted, not the 5,000 or so welfare
recipients who dropped out soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican mayor also attacked Comptroller Alan G. Hevesi, a
Democrat, saying that he had withheld the study for ideological
reasons because it supported the mayor's position.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, Hevesi called his own news conference to deny
the charge, and to say that he agreed with the mayor that CUNY
students on welfare should work.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that 287 students who had workfare jobs for at
least half of the fall semester had a 2.59 grade point average,
while the 160,000 CUNY students not on welfare had a 2.53 average.
Those workfare students earned an average of 10 credits that
semester and 83 percent enrolled for the spring semester, while the
comparison group earned an average of 9 credits and had a 79
percent spring enrollment rate. The study did not look at how
students' grades and credit loads changed from one semester to the
next.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY officials declined to comment on the report, except to say
that the period studied was brief and the sample of students small.
</P>
<P>
   Workfare has been a running battle between CUNY and the Giuliani
administration since the policy was instituted in 1995. At that
time, about 27,000 CUNY students were on public assistance, more
than any other college or university in New York state. By
mid-1996, that number had dropped by 17 percent, and CUNY officials
said that although students dropped out for many reasons, the new
workfare requirement was a serious obstacle for many students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
