<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-PLANT-315&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY SEEKS TO CLOSE NUCLEAR PLANT IT CAN'T SELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Officials of GPU Service Inc., a utility based in
Parsippany, N.J., said Wednesday that efforts over the last year to
sell its Oyster Creek nuclear plant had been unsuccessful and that
it would now begin steps to decommission the plant and close it by
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The plant could have continued to operate until 2009, when its
operating license will expire.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear from the company and the state's
Board of Public Utilities what impact if any the closing would have
on electrical rates for the company's two million customers in 13
counties in the central and southern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the announcement came as the utility industry is undergoing
sweeping deregulation, which has so far increased the available
sources of electricity, thereby lowering its costs. At the same
time, GPU has begun to divest itself of its generating plants and
to convert itself into only a buyer and distributor of electricity.
Because of these factors, regulatory officials and executives at
the utility said, the move to close the nuclear plant has raised
tough new questions for both the company and the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a serious and extensive effort to sell the plant,''
Fred D. Hafer, the president and chief executive officer of GPU,
said in a statement. ``However, in the end we were unable to
finalize a deal with the one potential buyer who expressed an
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Hafer said that the company would seek state approval for the
closing of the plant by 2000, but would reconsider the plan if
regulators took a different view of the plant's economics and the
state's energy needs.
</P>
<P>
   GPU spokesman Jeff Dennard said that the company had not
abandoned its efforts to sell its other nuclear plant, Three Mile
Island in Londonderry, Pa., and that the outlook for the sale of
that plant still looked good.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The 620-megawatt plant at Oyster Creek is the second-oldest
nuclear generating plant in the country. It opened in late 1969
just two weeks after the nation's oldest plant, Nine Mile Point
Unit 1, near Oswego, N.Y. Oyster Creek is on Barnegat Bay, 10 miles
south of Toms River, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, as deregulation of electricity sales has
gotten under way, plants like Oyster Creek have ceased to be
competitive. The current cost of electricity in this new market,
Dennard said, was about 2.5 cents a kilowatt hour. The Oyster Creek
plant, with its fixed capital costs of about 3.8 cents a kilowatt
hour combined with an operating cost of 3.1 cents a kilowatt hour,
is not able to compete in that market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Chilton, director of the energy division of the state's
Board of Public Utilities, said that the possibility of closing the
plant early had been suggested by the company more than a year ago.
State officials knew, he said, that ``Oyster Creek would be a tough
sell'' because of its high operating costs, and so the inability to
find a buyer was not a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   What is a surprise, he and others said, are the questions now
facing the state in the new era of deregulation, including whether
the company even needs the state's permission to close the plant.
Chilton said it is an ``open question'' whether the company must
come to the state to take ``competitive steps.''
</P>
<P>
   The closing of the plant has long been advocated by
environmentalists in the state, as well as by consumer advocates,
who insisted that its high operating costs saddled residents with
some of the region's highest utility rates. Local government in the
Lacey Township area receive more than $10 million in taxes annually
from the plant, which accounts for 64 percent of the local budget.
But last year state lawmakers passed legislation guaranteeing the
tax revenues should the plant close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
