<HEADLINE>
A PROGRAM WEDS 2 WHO LED THE PHILHARMONIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Deprived of its centerpiece, the musical arm of
Lincoln Center Festival '98 must find another. I doubt it will be
the New York Philharmonic. Tuesday's Bernstein-Mahler concert was
to have been corollary to the opening of ``The Peony Pavilion,''
the 16th-century opera that Chinese officials have declined to send
abroad. Leonard Bernstein remembered was always a subtheme of this
year's festival; but judging from this makeshift evening, it will
serve as poor substitute for a main event.
</P>
<P>
   Wedding ``The Age of Anxiety'' to the Mahler First Symphony
makes some superficial sense. Both composers were music directors
of the Philharmonic. Bernstein helped revive Mahler's reputation,
and certainly the heart-on-sleeve theatricality of his music owes
something to the older man's confessional style.
</P>
<P>
   Yet festival events are made to take us out of the everyday, and
programming the most ubiquitous of the Mahler symphonies speaks of
a management more interested in selling tickets in the face of a
Bernstein piece not a lot of listeners knew. Quite naturally, the
evening's Central European conductor, Kurt Masur, showed more
sympathy for Mahler than for Bernstein. Curiously, the Philharmonic
musicians played the Mahler a lot better than they did music by
their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Age of Anxiety,'' inspired by W.H. Auden and finished in
1949, is actually Bernstein's Second Symphony. Its two parts, each
in three sections, resemble a film score for which only a scenario
and a partial script exist. The piece follows one evening's
peregrinations by a lonely foursome, beginning at a Third Avenue
bar. There are a cab ride and a final nightcap, and during it all
thwarted attempts at bonding, philosophizing and a lot of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein's music, with an elaborate piano part played here by
Lukas Foss, acts as a kind of emotional underpinning. Its long
melodic lines and ambiguous harmonies have a fine theatrical touch,
knowing just when to underline a particular surge of emotive juices
or how to fall back in quiet despair. Much of the music is drab,
I'm afraid, like a good production of an uninspired play.
</P>
<P>
   As accompaniment to a visual or dramatic art form, ``The Age of
Anxiety'' could become a soundtrack only subliminally noticed and
do its work admirably (and there is, of course, the Jerome Robbins
ballet). On its own, the piece tends to sag, depending on a a
touchingly grandiose finale and some rollicking jazz piano in the
solo parts to rescue its credibility. I cannot speak for Masur's
like or dislike of the piece. I can only say that string ensemble
was uncharacteristically vague for such a superb orchestra, that
brass choirs were blowsy, that individual accidents were many, that
over large stretches the players sounded bored to death.
</P>
<P>
   The Mahler was not tidy, but it was at least engaged. One thing
that truly binds these two pieces is their use of the vernacular,
and Masur and his players made the inner movements happily bend and
swerve to the pop-tune influences of the day. We know Foss mainly
as a composer and conductor of wildly uneven accomplishment, but it
is a shame we don't hear him play the piano more. It may be what he
does best. The scale was perhaps too small for Bernstein's music,
but the difficulties were handled with elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center will always have trouble dealing with the
festival ideal of pilgrimage, retreat and concentration. Tuesday's
house, not a sellout, behaved badly at the start and then calmed
down; it seemed to love the Mahler at the end. For the Philharmonic
it was business as usual, bowing to the Bernstein theme but
generally going its own way. This is not what the ancient Greeks
had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   To find the true spirit of an urban festival, one had to go
outside Avery Fisher Hall and onto the plaza it faces, where Loren
Schoenberg's band played Fats Waller and hundreds of couples
jitterbugged happily.
</P>
<P>
   More Bernstein soon: The Philharmonic plays an American program
at Fisher Hall on July 14 and 15. There are ``The Unknown
Bernstein,'' gathered by Michael Barrett (July 20), and ``Literally
Bernstein,'' with the Eos Orchestra (July 23), both at Alice Tully
Hall. Note, too, next week's programs with the Hamburg Ballet at
the New York State Theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
