<SLUG> BC-VILLAGE-THEATER-RFVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VILLAGE': WHERE PAST AND FUTURE INTERSECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cataclysmic events in faraway places may change
fortunes in an obscure Israeli settlement, but to the Jewish
pioneers of Joshua Sobol's ``Village,'' it is the earthy exigencies
of everyday life that matter most. Like the price of manure.
</P>
<P>
   A witness account of the Holocaust reaches the community in the
person of a Russian refugee who arrives shortly after the war and
relates the story of her family's liquidation. (``Where's she
from?'' a villager inquires. ``From there,'' another replies.) The
woman's news brings the village to a standstill, but the
transfixing moment is fleeting. Her testimony is completed and
digested by the village in a few dry-eyed minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sobol, an Israeli writer who has dealt with issues of Jewish
survival in plays like ``Ghetto,'' is not so much concerned with
another contribution to the literature of the Holocaust in this
curious play, presented by the Gesher Theater of Israel as one of
the initial offerings of Lincoln Center Festival '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``Village,'' as demonstrated in a scene of luxurious length in
which a Jew and and an Arab spar over the quality of the manure the
Arab provides for the Jew's orange groves, is preoccupied by the
prosaic minidramas that set the rhythms of insular, small-town
existence.
</P>
<P>
   How taken you are with Sobol's surreal reconstruction of the
village of his own youth in the Sharon Valley in the 1940s will
depend on whether a town full of talking turkeys, aria-bellowing
emigres and love-starved socialists is your idea of a
spirit-lifting flight of fancy. For long stretches of the
three-hour production at Alice Tully Hall _ performed in Hebrew,
and a smattering of Russian, with simultaneous English translation
_ it's hard to escape a feeling that you're being taken places
against your will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memory, true memory, as opposed to false, mythologized memory,
is always personal, always individual,'' the playwright wrote in
1989, in a defense of ``Ghetto,'' a play about a Jewish theater
troupe in Nazi-occupied Lithuania presented that year at Circle in
the Square. The problem with ``Village,'' however, is that despite
the generic locality implied by the title, Sobol's memories,
embedded in an array of mirage-like interludes, rarely transcend
the deeply personal.
</P>
<P>
   His characters _ the village's wayward wife, the stern pedant,
the doctrinaire Marxist _ never seem to emerge from the dream
state. They remain flimsy and cartoonish, fixed perhaps as
individuals in Sobol's mind, but remote and insubstantial to most
of the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the years leading to Israel's independence in 1948,
``Village'' has apparently been a popular and critical hit in
Israel. The Gesher, a seven-year-old theater company founded by
Russian Israelis and headed by a Russian-born director, Yevgeny
Arye, has rapidly established itself as one of Israel's most
innovative theater troupes. It just may be that a company of
recently arrived exiles, in a land of refugees deep in reflection
about its first 50 years of nationhood, struck a responsive nerve
with a play that manages to be nostalgic without being gratuitously
sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   The play is ``Our Town'' reimagined by Marc Chagall; the village
it conjures is a mystical bend in the road of Palestine's past and
Israel's future. It begins, a la Thornton Wilder, in the town
cemetery, with the villagers upright in their graves. In place of
``Our Town's'' stage manager, however, is Yossi, played by Israel
(Sasha) Demidov, the simpleton who presides over the cemetery as
gravedigger and the story as narrator.
</P>
<P>
   Yossi is the pure-hearted soul of the young nation, so free of
the taint of the bad blood and violence that lie ahead that at the
outset, he doesn't even understand what death is. His education
progresses from the slaughter of his barnyard friend, the turkey
(played by Klim Kamenko), to the slaughter of his soldier brother
Ami (Mark Ivanir). Along the way, Yossi observes with only meager
comprehension as the villagers couple and cheat and drink and
struggle to eke out fruitful lives, and in the end, he is left
alone in a more complex world, puzzling over the question of how
much progress he and his village have made.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Lisiyansky's all-purpose set suggests a pastoral world
in a biblical land: it's love among the bulrushes. A narrow
turntable moves with the scene changes, but only once is it
employed by Arye to optimal effect, in a scene in which Ami is
slowly revealed to be kissing his girlfriend, Dassi (Efrat
Ben-Zur), behind a screen onto which a Charlie Chaplin movie is
being projected.
</P>
<P>
   The gawky Demidov does what he can with the only mildly engaging
Yossi; the character is never more than a childlike tour guide. The
others in the energetic cast of 20 try to embody the idea of the
life force of a community, but vague ideas are all anyone seems to
have.
</P>
<P>
   VILLAGE
</P>
<P>
   By Joshua Sobol; directed by Yevgeny Arye; sets by Alexander
Lisiyansky; music by Avi Benjamin (Nedzvetsky), costumes by Anna
Khruscheva; lighting by Bueno (Bambi) Avi-lona; dramaturge, Miriam
Yahi-Wax; assistant director, Maria Nemirovskaya; puppets, Ester
Peker; backdrop painter, Mark Goldenblank; film editor, Herz Frank;
stage manager, Tatyana Suchanova; company manager, Victor Sokolov.
Gesher Theater. Presented by Lincoln Center Festival '98. Alice
Tully Hall.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Israel (Sasha) Demidov (Yossi), Leonid Kanevsky (Chaim),
Klim Kamenko (Indik, a turkey), Mark Ivanir (Ami), Efrat Ben-Zur
(Dassi), Boris Achanov (Itzhak) and Vladimir Halemsky (Sayid).
</P>
</TEXT>
