<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, July 9, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CADET-TRIAL (New Braunfels, Texas) _ Attorney Dan Cogdell,
defending former Air Force Academy cadet David Graham, says he has
his work cut out for him finding an unbiased jury when ``every
newspaper has convicted my client on page one.'' Graham is accused
of killing a 16-year-old girl in 1995 at the request of his
then-fiancee. By ROGER CROTEAU.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MARIJUANA (Oakland, Calif.) _ Unanimously and without
discussion, the Oakland City Council has established the state's
most permissive medical marijuana guidelines. Henceforth, medical
marijuana users in Oakland may hold a stash of 1 1/2 pounds _
equivalent to 30 outdoor flowering plants or 48 indoor plants _
without fear of arrest. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   PARTNERS-AIRPORT (San Francisco) _ The clock is ticking for
United Airlines to decide whether to comply with San Francisco's
pioneering domestic partners law or to fight the ordinance in court
under its own name. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HEAT (San Antonio) _ In the movie ``Armageddon,'' pieces
of a Texas-size asteroid obliterate entire cities, leaving
blackened, charred remains. In Texas these days, it feels a lot
like the movie. A scorching heat wave is breaking records set more
than a century ago, sending people scurrying for shade or air
conditioning. But, as with the movie, there appears to be nowhere
to hide. By CECILIA BALLI.
</P>
<P>
   MEGAN'S-LAW (San Francisco) _ Megan's Law, the controversial
measure requiring police to make information about sex offenders
public, remains popular despite reports of vigilantism,
noncompliance and most recently, a parolee suicide blamed by some
on police who went door-to-door to notify neighbors of his
presence. By EMELYN CRUZ LAT.
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-MOLEST (San Antonio) _ Officials from the Archdiocese of
San Antonio still don't know where the Rev. Jose Luis Sandoval is,
and they aren't spending much time looking either. Sandoval, 58,
the former pastor of St. Alphonsus Catholic Church, disappeared
after being accused of sexually assaulting a former altar boy. By
SUZANNE HOHOLIK.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IRISH-PEACEMAKER (Portadown, Northern Ireland) _ Three thousand
miles from New York, Dorothy Bukantz is in the Dump, a grassy field
that separates Catholic and Protestant neighborhoods in Portadown.
The 46-year-old American is one of 80 members of the International
Observer Delegation _ a group of volunteers from around the globe
acting as a sort of social watchdog over the conflict. By LARA
JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-VISION (San Francisco) _ In what may be the biggest
corporate fraud case in Silicon Valley history, the former top
executives of Media Vision Technology Inc. were accused by federal
regulators of fraudulent financial reporting and insider trading.
By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BARNES-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ How to get a piece of the Golden
Gate Bridge, getting prepared with the ``Credit Card Condom'' and
where to turn for help on getting along with an ex-spouse. By STEVE
BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING-GRIPES (Piedmont, Calif.) _ At least three times a week
I slip on my Reeboks and trot down to the jogging trail that
circles Oakland's Lake Merritt. Most runners greet me with a
friendly nod or a wheezing ``Hi,'' but there are a few I meet who
turn the miles into misery. There are ways during exercise to
exorcise these haunts. By HOSEA MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-MUSEUM (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ It's just a bat, but I
can't stop looking at it. The bat is on display at the National
Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum. On the barrel is the signature of
Babe Ruth. Henry Aaron. Willie Mays. Ted Williams. Frank Robinson.
The enrollment of major-league baseball's 500 Home Run Club is 15.
Each and every member of the club has signed his name on this bat.
By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   MARATHON-VETERAN (San Francisco) _ With 163 marathons behind
him, Tony Stratta, 68, has found a reason to stop. Sunday's San
Francisco Marathon, which he's run 18 times in its 20-year history,
will be his last. His body hasn't failed him. It's his patience
with the scheduling process that has deteriorated. By JEFFRI
CHADIHA.
</P>
</TEXT>
