<SLUG> BC-LIABILITY-BILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCT LIABILITY BILL HEADS FOR KEY VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Legislation sought by Republicans for 20 years
that would protect companies from costly product liability lawsuits
may have its best chance yet to become law, as it heads toward a
key vote in the Senate Thursday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the bill carries the support of Republicans, the White
House and most of the business community, a controversial amendment
by California Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein to exclude the gun
industry could drag down the entire bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill includes special protections for California's
biotechnology and medical device industries, and rejection of the
legislation would amount to a serious blow in their four-year
crusade for lawsuit relief. Without some form of legal protection,
the industries argue, more and more suppliers will be unwilling to
provide materials for many life-saving products.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton vetoed a product liability bill two years ago,
saying it undermined consumers' rights to sue manufacturers of
defective products, but he has agreed to a compromise measure that
meets his concerns. Republicans will attempt to overcome a
Democrat-led filibuster on the measure Thursday, and the vote is
too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Strongly backed by business lobbies, Republicans argue that
companies are beset by frivolous lawsuits that jack up product
prices and stifle innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, backed with equal vigor by trial lawyers, contend
that limiting manufacturer liability will expose consumers to
dangerous products.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader denounced the bill as ``a
disgraceful effort to subvert our civil justice system, allowing
corporations to escape financial responsibility for the harm and
damage they cause innocent citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Although large businesses complain that the new version is too
watered down, the measure retains strong backing from the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, which called it ``a solid platform on which to
build future reforms'' and a ``historic opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would:
</P>
<P>
   -- Require plaintiffs to show ``clear and convincing evidence''
that a manufacturer acted with ``a conscious, flagrant indifference
to the rights or safety of others.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Cap punitive damages against small businesses at $250,000 or
twice compensatory damages, whichever is smaller (small businesses
are defined as $5 million or less in revenue and 25 or fewer
full-time employees).
</P>
<P>
   -- Reduce damages if consumers misused or altered products or
were intoxicated at the time of injury.
</P>
<P>
   -- Shield suppliers of ``biomaterials'' used in medical devices
if the supplier did not make or sell the allegedly defective
medical device. (The provision does not limit lawsuits against the
devicemakers themselves.)
</P>
<P>
   The biomaterials provision enjoys strong bipartisan support and
was added to gain votes for the broader liability reform package.
Championed by Reps. Anna Eshoo of Palo Alto and Zoe Lofgren of San
Jose, both Democrats, the biomaterials provision is ready for a
House vote as a stand-alone bill.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 40 percent of the medical device industry is located in
California. Devicemakers say they are running out of raw materials
for such life-saving products as brain shunts and heart pacemakers
because their suppliers _ makers of silicones, plastics and other
materials _ refuse to sell to them for fear of being dragged into
lawsuits against the devices. Medical devices are inherently
riskier, and thus far more likely to be hit by lawsuits, than other
products containing plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Most suppliers are huge businesses, like Du Pont, with ``deep
pockets'' to pay big damage claims, while devicemakers are often
much smaller companies with far fewer financial resources.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, medical devices offer such a tiny market for plastics
and similar materials _ a $10,000 pacemaker may contain only a few
pennies worth of silicone _ that many suppliers have cut off sales
to devicemakers because the profits do not begin to offset the cost
of defending a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But devicemakers worry that their provision will be dragged down
by the current fight over product liability legislation, which has
not even begun to move in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Nau, director of government affairs for ALZA, a drug
delivery device manufacturer in Palo Alto, said devicemakers are
relying now on dwindling biomaterial stockpiles. A bigger problem,
Nau said, is that manufacturers have quit developing new materials
for the medical device industry because of the potential legal
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Innovative plastics, new polymers, the kinds of things that
have been developed regularly and with rapidity for the past 40, 50
years, are not being developed anymore because people do not want
to sell to us,'' Nau said.
</P>
<P>
   The new measure excludes tobacco companies and silicone breast
implant manufacturers _ both subject to extraordinarily broad and
costly litigation _ from any liability protection.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein wants to exclude gun manufacturers as well. But the
bill's backers say her addition is unnecessary and could shatter
the fragile compromise with the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very delicately tied together,'' said U.S. Chamber of
Commerce lobbyist Neil Trautwein. ``Amendments like Feinstein's
could start a flood'' of other amendments and ``add another decade
to the long-standing fight for product liability reform.''
</P>
<P>
   But Feinstein spokesman Howard Gantman said the bill's sponsors
were ``very willing to include exclusions for the tobacco industry.
The senator's point is that guns are right up there with tobacco in
terms of killing people.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein remains undecided on the overall bill. Lobbyists
contend that Feinstein and other Democrats they were counting on to
break the filibuster are now threatening to bolt if they are denied
their amendments.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
