<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENKINS-JENKINS-SFCHR     07-09 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-JENKINS-SFCHRON-WORLDCUP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SMOKE CLEARS, FRENCH LOVE THEIR BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE JENKINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ I'm not sure what they were singing on the
Champs-Elysees on Wednesday night, but it has replaced ``Got a
light?'' as the French national theme.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the joyous lyrics, I heard  &LR; Les Bleus.  &LR; Not the St.
Louis blues, or the lowdown blues, but the nickname for the
blue-clad French soccer team. In defiance of reason, they are
single-handedly dismantling the barriers of Gallic indifference.
</P>
<P>
   It was astounding, how it all came down. Throughout the day,
there were few signs of the World Cup around Paris. Not in my
neighborhood, the thriving Montparnasse, not even on the
Champs-Elysees, the world's most beautiful and famous boulevard.
Then it became official that France had beaten Croatia 2-1 to earn
a spot in Sunday's final against Brazil _ and an unbelievable party
broke out.
</P>
<P>
   So many important things are happening here, from the pure glory
of sport _ France never has won the World Cup _ to the character of
a nation. The monthlong tournament has brought joy to a people
mired in gloom, tolerance in the realm of sensitive racial issues.
It isn't likely that a soccer tournament can cure all of that; not
in the long run. But the French feel delightfully different about
themselves these days, particularly the nation's youth, who poured
out of subways by the thousands Wednesday night to join the
merriment.
</P>
<P>
   My evening started at a little cafe called Le Deauville on the
Champs-Elysees, and the scene was quintessentially French. A little
man played romantic tunes on the accordion. Couples kissed
unabashedly. Many people had their backs to the television set as
the game began, indulging themselves in vintage French delights:
smoking, brooding, intellectualizing.
</P>
<P>
   It was a crisp, perfect night, a bit like Carmel in autumn. I
kept looking for the crazed fanatics and painted faces; there were
many at the stadium, but none here. Nobody dressed for the occasion
or went out of his way in any respect. They just dropped into the
bars, perhaps hoping they wouldn't be noticed, at any old time.
Imagine it: The French invented the World Cup, and they've spent
nearly 70 years trying to win it. Here they're playing a semifinal
game in their home country, and cafe-goers arrive fashionably late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but that is the national pastime,'' cracked one man
between dramatic pulls on his cigarette. ``Not to be embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   The French cannot be the Dutch, spending a couple of hours
painting themselves, then staring glumly in the mirror after a
crushing loss. They choose not to win by sheer will; they sit back,
watch quietly, have a smoke, and let the victory come to them.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular player on the screen was Fabien Barthez, the
bald-headed French goalkeeper. This guy could pass for a bass
player in a Greenwich Village jazz club _ or a bouncer on Sunset
Boulevard. He has flair and takes risks, endearing him to the
populace. The French have doubted his ability on occasion _ hell,
they doubt everything, come to think of it _ but he had a great
night, often sprinting madly to catch corner kicks on the fly. The
first half ended scoreless, but there were many French
opportunities, lending a world of promise.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to move around the boulevard a little. It was still
business as usual out there, pedestrian and auto traffic moving
busily along. I passed by a restaurant/bar, saw the TV set
flickering and pulled on the door _ only to have a menacing-looking
figure wave me off.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly there was a goal for France, and bedlam. A man sneaked
in, and I tried to slide in behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are you?'' asked the proprietor.
</P>
<P>
   ``American journalist,'' I answered, immediately figuring it was
the wrong answer. A better one would have been, ``I'm a big Jerry
Lewis fan.'' Or, ``That Charlie Sheen (plastered all over town in
billboard advertisements for his latest travesty), hell of an
actor.''
</P>
<P>
   But the journalist angle seemed to work. ``Are you a loner?'' he
asked in his heavy French accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep. Actively hated people my entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Come in.''
</P>
<P>
   I never did figure out the cloak-and-dagger stuff, but I spent
the rest of the night in there, witnessing the inexorable growth of
French emotion. I was glad to see the great Davor Suker have one
last moment for Croatia (he scored his country's only goal), but
suddenly his plight paled against larger issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lilian Thuram, who is black, scored both of the goals for
France. Marcel Desailly, born in Ghana, is a titan of defense.
Zinedine Zidane, the master midfield creator, is the son of
Algerian immigrants, and three other French players have roots in
former French colonies in Africa. This information would be
irrelevant in America's sporting taverns, but racial hatred burns
white-hot throughout Europe these days. It is the source of many
crimes by German and British hooligans. It has stirred major crises
among the Dutch soccer team over the past two years. And it is a
problem in France, where noisy politician Jean-Marie Le Pen, leader
of the National Front, built his campaign around vilifying
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible for a racist to enjoy this wonderful French
team. Judging from Wednesday night, they all had gone into hiding.
When I left the Cafe Mysterie and all its high intrigue, I walked
onto the Champs-Elysees and one of the most memorable scenes of
modern-day France.
</P>
<P>
   You would have thought the country had been liberated from
oppressive foreign rule. The street was filled with friendly mobs
and horn-honking motorists. I can't speak for the after-hours, but
there wasn't even the hint of trouble. Descending into the Metro
station, I sat there watching new trains arrive, each loaded with
singing, shouting French people under 25.
</P>
<P>
   I finally boarded the train bound for Montparnasse, and there
was an old man sitting there in a black beret. The scene had not
moved him. ``Football,'' he scoffed, waving dismissively at the
departing throng.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to tell him that, for once, he is in the minority. What
a wonderful time to be French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
