<SLUG> BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON-OAKLANDA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR A'S MAY HAVE TO MOVE TO FIND FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.W. NEVIUS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   People think the A's don't get it. They think the team of green
and gold is moping around the Coliseum, trapped in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   After all, there is the looming presence of Mt. Davis, the
football renovation for the Raiders that made it clear just who was
the really important tenant in Oakland. Then there are the
Godzillas of baseball, the mega-teams of the game with their huge,
intimidating payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there are the cross-Bay Giants, stealing the local
baseball thunder with their run toward the playoffs for the second
straight season.
</P>
<P>
   Poor A's. They never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Well, don't underestimate them. The Athletics are not only
perfectly happy to be themselves, they are more than a little bit
smug about their chances. They know that they have a nice little
product, undervalued and with a huge upside, and if people around
here don't appreciate it, someone else _ maybe somewhere else _
will.
</P>
<P>
   In the next six months, expect to see a serious evaluation of
the option of a move to a new ballpark in the San Jose/Santa Clara
area. The Giants swear the A's can't move the team to the South
Bay, but if someone down in Silicon Valley wants to step up, the
A's are convinced they can win that battle, either in the courts or
in baseball's inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   And if a move to the South doesn't pan out, the A's are willing,
and able, to wait this out. Things may improve here, or they may
get a nice offer to move to where the fans would be delighted to
watch them. The way the A's see it, they are in the catbird seat,
and they can just sit where they are until something good happens.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it isn't as if they are leaking money. Attendance may
be lousy, but with the lowest payroll in the American League _ $20
million, compared with Baltimore's baseball-high $68 million _ they
don't need to hear the turnstiles whir to break even.
</P>
<P>
   And the other side of the equation is pretty impressive. Even
with the lowest payroll, the A's own the seventh-best record in the
American League. Remember, that's with a bunch of kids out of the
farm system, a couple of well-weathered veterans, and mini-splurges
into the free-agent market from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the team, and the franchise, are doing their
part. This isn't easy. As long as the A's are militantly committed
to the sensible idea of running a franchise without losing buckets
of money, the margin for error is very thin. One expensive
free-agent screwup _ hello, Ruben Sierra _ and the whole franchise
goes into a tailspin for a spell.
</P>
<P>
   The law of averages does not favor a team like the A's, but they
have a track record of beating the odds. Smart, penny-wise, and
young, this is the template for an up and coming baseball franchise
in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   None of which is to say that the A's aren't a little peeved.
This is a team that won four in a row heading into the All-Star
break, swept two games over the Giants at 3Com Park at the end of
June and were greeted with resounding shrugs in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   You don't think that sticks in their craw? It is hard enough
battling into the prevailing wind every day, but when you finally
make some headway, you would like to get the credit from the home
folks.
</P>
<P>
   And don't get them started on the big-wallet crowd, like the St.
Louis Cardinals, who simply went out and blew the concept of the
draft right out of the water with a $7 million contract to
draft-buster J.D. Drew. The only satisfaction the A's get in that
is that the Cardinals, with a payroll of $52.5 million, have won
one less game so far than Team Frugal.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics have turned into a bit of a favorite pet with
baseball's national deep thinkers. Thoughtful essays have been
penned about how the Pittsburghs and the Oaklands of the world are
the real soul of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot to like. For all the attention paid to their
payroll, the A's would rather that you look at their impressive
collection of kids, beginning with All-Star Ben Grieve.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can they play, they are an appealing group, the kind of
young guys a group of fans would like to latch onto and ride for a
while. If you are really trying to build something, it might be
better to plug the youngsters in right now and let them play,
rather than sit on the bench and watch the free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it, if this were an expansion team, starting up somewhere
like Phoenix, they'd be writing poems to this gritty bunch. They're
cuter than Beanie Babies, and they've probably got a better shelf
life.
</P>
<P>
   And if the fans in Oakland don't catch on, somebody else will.
Maybe in Santa Clara, or maybe in Portland or Las Vegas, but it is
going to happen. The A's are sure of it.
</P>
<P>
   So save your tears for the A's. You'll need them if they leave.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
