<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARATHON-VETERAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENERABLE RUNNER, 68, SAYS UPCOMING MARATHON WILL BE HIS LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tony Stratta doesn't even make an attempt at
selling the notion that the motivation behind his 50 years of
marathon running is a complicated story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that I was never very good at it,'' he said.
``So I just kept on doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to expect more than such a simple explanation
for his desires, but after a few moments with Stratta, a
68-year-old retired hotel manager who talks with the energy of a
stand-up comedian, it all makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   He's never been a star runner. He's just a guy who learned long
ago that he liked running, and no matter how he placed at the end,
he always would find a reason to start.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with 163 marathons behind him, Stratta has found a reason
to stop. Sunday's San Francisco Marathon, which he's run 18 times
in its 20-year history, will be his last. This isn't something
sentimental, either. The bottom line for Stratta is that his body
hasn't failed him. It's his patience with the scheduling process
that has deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   It takes so long now to enter a marathon and then actually run
in it, he said. ``They want you to know what you're doing on New
Year's Day in the year 2000. The process gets held up. I still
haven't gotten my medal from last year's (San Francisco)
marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Retracing Stratta's running routes is about as hard as
deciphering the driving force behind his long-distance love. You
jump back to his days at Daniel Webster grammar school in Potrero
Hill, when he had to find some way to arrive at school on time. An
admitted late riser, he regularly raced the 3 miles from his home
to school.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Stratta garnered no fame while running
cross-country and track at Lowell High. There isn't a varsity
letter lying among the varied collection of trophies and medals in
his living room. But when he was 18 years old, he ran in his first
marathon in Petaluma. The year was 1948 and Stratta didn't think
about stopping until this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, you couldn't get people to do marathons,'' he said.
``People made fun of it. To be good as a runner, you had to win the
quarter-mile. Then the half-mile became big. Then the mile and the
2-mile. But that happened over a few years. It was like anybody who
had to run 26 miles to get some attention wasn't special.''
</P>
<P>
   Stratta has never tired of trying tougher races. His marathon
experience includes 42 50-mile events. His best time in the San
Francisco Marathon is 3:42, which he accomplished at 43. There are
less than a handful of top 10 finishes in his lifetime, but as
Stratta says, those types of achievements never drove him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Stratta is content in knowing that he can still run his
4 miles each morning and maintain his affiliation with the San
Francisco Dolphin South End Runners. He's had his fill of marathons
and doesn't expect to leave any regrets behind him at the
conclusion of Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to run this race in 7:16, get my medal, and walk
away happy,'' Stratta said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
