<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACWORLD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Apple's Grand Design   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 New York  
 
Apple Computer, which popularized the phrase, ``The computer for
the rest of us,'' says its future growth and survival hinge on the
consumer market it all but shunned the past few years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interim Apple CEO Steve Jobs _ looking fresh despite a red-eye
flight from the West Coast _ told a gathering of 2,500 yesterday at
the Macworld Expo trade show that Apple's new iMac home computer
will fuel sales during the next six months, contributing to a
recent resurgence at the Cupertino company. He also announced that
Apple will record a third-straight quarter in the black next
Wednesday, but he declined to say how much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple (recently) had failed in the consumer market, but the
iMac will change that,'' said Jobs, who was greeted with a
thunderous, 30-second standing ovation from the partisan crowd.
``It is a kick-ass consumer product.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 22 million installed Macs in the world, 10 million are
home computers, but Jobs said Apple hadn't made compelling products
for that market _ until the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs announced that some 177 consumer applications _ from
companies including America Online, Adobe Systems, Quicken,
Symantec Corp. and Mattel _ have been designed for the iMac in the
two months since it was announced.
</P>
<P>
   He then trotted out Richard Wolpert, president of Disney Online,
who said the Magic Kingdom has developed a Macintosh version of
Blast, its online service for kids. (Rumors of an Apple-Disney
partnership were rife this week, but many erroneously thought
Disney would announce that it was installing thousands of iMacs in
its hotels around the world.)
</P>
<P>
   The iMac, which was announced in May and doesn't ship until
August 15, already has created a buzz among Mac fanatics. Industry
observers estimate that 400,000 units will ship by the end of
September, making it one of the most popular Macintosh models ever.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs said the iMac will closely weave in Web browsing and will
come with a 56K modem, faster than the 33.6K modem initially
expected.
</P>
<P>
   A laptop counterpart to the iMac is due in the first half of
1999, according to Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs and other Apple executives said the company's consumer bent
is the final piece of a five-step plan that Jobs jokingly compared
to Abraham Maslow's theory on the hierarchy of needs.
</P>
<P>
   Under Apple's ``hierarchy of skepticism,'' the company first
needed to convince computer shoppers, investors, analysts and the
press that it would shake out of its ``death spiral,'' Jobs said.
It did so, he said, by putting in place a new management team and
board of directors and striking a development deal with Microsoft
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Apple had to stabilize business by whittling down its
unwieldy product lines, from 15 to two (consumer and professional).
The company also focused on strongholds in the education and
desktop-publishing markets. ``We needed to protect the business
before we could grow,'' Clent &UR;  &LR; Richardson, Apple's senior director
of worldwide developer relations, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Apple forged business relations with hardware-and
software-makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, developers were hopping mad at Apple,'' Jobs said.
``Our deal with Microsoft drew boos (from Mac fans last year), but
it brought other developers aboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple also may have created goodwill among developers by footing
part of the bill on some companies' trade show booths. One
developer said he wouldn't have attended if not for Apple defraying
the costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple first had to show the discipline to get its internal
house in order. Its consumer strategy is dead-on for future
growth,'' said Louis Mazzucchelli Jr., vice president of Gerard
Klauer Mattison &AMP; Co. in New York. ``If they had tried this a year
ago, it wouldn't have worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation for Apple's comeback isn't complete, however,
unless the company succeeds in increasing year-over-year sales and
improving its market share, its critics argue. In its most recent
quarter, Apple registered $1.4 billion in sales, compared with $1.6
billion the previous year. Meanwhile, its market share hasn't
budged from 4.1 percent a year ago, according to Dataquest Inc., a
San Jose-based market researcher.
</P>
<P>
   That's where iMac, and its potential for a boost in sales, comes
in, Apple executives say.
</P>
<P>
   So far, potential customers like what they see.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a great consumer product that combines software,
modem, memory and a big screen,'' said Pamela Steffen, who traveled
from Boston to get her first glimpse of the roundish, aqua
marine-colored computer. ``The younger crowd will especially love
it since it looks like a beach ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Cingone, standing nearby in front of an iMac display at
the Apple booth, said she is buying the $1,299 machine for her
college-bound daughter. ``It's a winner. I've been waiting for a PC
like this Apple for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
