<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Ex-Media Vision Execs Charged In Fraud Case   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In the largest securities fraud and insider trading case in Silicon
Valley history, the Securities and Exchange Commission filed
charges yesterday against four former senior executives of Media
Vision Technology Inc.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The suit, filed in San Francisco federal court, alleges that
former Chief Executive Officer Paul Jain and former Chief Financial
Officer Steven Allan ``directed subordinates to falsify documents
in order to artificially inflate revenue and understate expenses in
an extensive scheme to defraud investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Controller Robert Williams and former manufacturing
director Wayne Nakamura were also charged in the suit with
participating in the scheme that in 1993 overstated profits of the
Fremont-based multimedia products company by $119 million.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC charges that by trading on inside information, Jain
reaped profits of $1.5 million, Allan $825,000 and Nakamura
$21,250. In its civil action, the SEC seeks a return of this money
and penalties of as much as $7 million. The federal regulatory
agency also seeks an order barring Jain and Allan from serving as
officers or directors of any public company.
</P>
<P>
   Jain, who was fired from Media Vision four years ago, could not
be reached for comment. But his lawyer, Paul Dawes of Latham &AMP;
Watkins, said, ``He certainly plans to deny the claims.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the SEC charges, an assistant U.S. attorney said
yesterday that a grand jury investigation of Jain continues.
</P>
<P>
   So far three former Media Vision executives have pleaded guilty
to criminal charges filed by the U.S. attorney's office in Oakland.
They are:
</P>
<P>
   _Former Controller Robert Williams, who has pleaded guilty to
one count of providing false information to the FBI but has yet to
be sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   _Former Chief Operating Officer Russell Faust who has pleaded
guilty to a federal mail fraud charge and agreed to pay $556,000 in
fines to cover insider-trading profits.
</P>
<P>
   _Former sales director Michael Humphress, who has pleaded guilty
to similar fraud charges and was fined $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   After financial irregularities at Media Vision were first
reported by The Chronicle, the company's stock skidded from a high
of $46.50 in January 1994 to below $5 a share four months later.
The company's market value fell from a high of $630 million to zero
by the time it filed for bankruptcy protection, according to David
Bayless, the SEC administrator in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The company was reorganized and emerged from bankruptcy in 1994.
It changed its name to Aureal Semiconductor Inc. in 1996 and under
new management began selling a new line of personal computer audio
chips in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
