<HEADLINE>
GETTING A PIECE OF THE GOLDEN GATE BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Websites are CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CREATIVE REUSE: A California manufacturer has a bridge to sell
you _ part of one, at least. And it's none other than the famed
Golden Gate span in San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, when the bridge was being repaired, a man
named Vince Bindi bought tons of sections of the handrail that ran
along the bridge's pedestrian walkway. His company cuts
14-foot-long, 800-pound segments into smaller pieces, refinishes
them and creates paperweights, plaques, key and candle holders, and
clocks, ranging in price from $20 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   There also are a pair of tables, including a 2-foot-square,
glass-topped, 100-pound table that costs $1,200. The company will
consider custom-making furniture to your specifications.
</P>
<P>
   For information or to order, call 888-625-3558 or visit the Web
site at: http://www.goldensteel.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY FINANCIAL PLANNING: In the mail we find the ``Credit Card
Condom.'' Like the latex sheaths from which they get their name,
the CCCs (actually, non-tear envelopes) are meant to be slipped on
in advance to keep yourself from getting into trouble later.
</P>
<P>
   Financial trouble, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The envelope lists advice about ``safer spending'' and
prevention of debt. The extra time it takes to remove the card may
make you think twice about the advisability of charging yet again.
The envelopes can be used in tandem with stickers, meant for the
front of cards, that bear dire warning such as, ``Overuse can be
hazardous to your wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Both come from the National Center for Financial Education in
San Diego. The envelopes cost $5 for 10; stickers, $1 for 10. To
order, for more information or for free tips on smart credit-card
use and reduction of charge debt, call 619-232-8811 or visit the
Web site, http://www.ncfe.org.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GET CIVIL: July is national Get Along With Your Ex month. The
very necessity of such a thing will give radio zealot Dr. Laura
fits of moral fury, but let's face it: some folks get divorced.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, begun on the Internet, has a Web site full of
tips, referrals and discussion groups for post-split people on how
to try to maintain cordial relations with those with whom you
produced offspring.
</P>
<P>
   The premise: Parents who don't fight with or disparage each
other raise healthier children. Central to getting along is a
pledge: ``Although I am no longer in a committed relationship with
my child(ren)'s other parent, I will make every effort to maintain
a working relationship for the sake of our child(ren). I promise
always to take the high road, regardless of how my ex behaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeating the pledge is said to help maintain perspective when
the ex starts doing the very things that made you want out in the
first place. The Web address is
http://www.freeyellow.com/members4/getalong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
