<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Jitters Drive Net Stocks Off Highs   By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
After a month of spectacular gains, Internet stocks took a beating
yesterday but are expected to rebound today.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jittery investors drove down the share prices of Amazon.com,
Yahoo, and other Internet companies, fearing that the high-flyers
might have peaked.
</P>
<P>
   However, after the markets closed yesterday, the No. 1 Internet
search engine Yahoo announced better-than-expected earnings, giving
investors hope for a quick turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect we'll see a strong upswing tomorrow,'' said Andrea
Williams, analyst at Volpe Brown Whelan &AMP; Co. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's dip tops a dramatic run-up among Internet stocks in
the past month. Since June 3, shares of Internet bookseller
Amazon.com have climbed from $42.25 to as high as $143.75, while
Yahoo shares have skyrocketed from $102 to a record price of
$207.50.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two days, however, investors got skittish _ a
typical reaction to all-time high prices, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would describe it as a bit of a mania,'' said Richard Welty,
president of Welty Capital Management in Lafayette. ``There has
been such a run-up that you have to have a correction.''
</P>
<P>
   During yesterday's ``correction,'' Amazon.com shares plunged $15
_ from $122.13 to $107.13 _ and Yahoo shares fell $4.81 _ from $191
to $186.19. Trading also dragged down the share prices of other
Internet firms, such as Lycos, Inktomi, DoubleClick and Excite.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet slide did not affect the rest of the market, which
comfortably cruised to its second-highest closing price ever: up
89.93 points to 9,174.97 for the Dow Jones Industrial Average. The
Dow was up strongly because investors switched out of Internet
stocks and into the big blue chips that make up the average.
</P>
<P>
   And the day's turmoil continued even after the market closed,
when Yahoo announced that its second quarter earnings significantly
beat Wall Street's expectations. Excluding an acquisition charge,
Yahoo earned 15 cents per share, while analysts had expected 9
cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo also announced a two-for-one stock split and that investor
Softbank Holdings boosted its stake in the company by $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   The combined good news caused Yahoo shares to soar 8 percent in
after-hours trading to $202. Amazon, Netscape and Lycos shares all
also rose in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the gains are justified _ because Internet stocks are
simply recovering to their normal prices.
</P>
<P>
   But others say it is crazy for companies with little or no
revenues to be trading for prices higher than corporate mainstays.
</P>
<P>
   ``In times like this, it doesn't pay to be rational,'' he said
David Simons, managing director of Digital Video Investments in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jim Balderston said investors are wrongly placing their
bets on the sexy well-known companies _ such as Yahoo and Excite _
rather than the boring little-known ones such as Cisco Systems that
are already generating significant profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long haul, the people that are going to make a lot of
money on the Internet are the guys that build the infrastructure,''
said Balderston, an analyst at Zona Research in Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit of the gold-rush fever where people are
heading off the Internet investment trail,'' he said. ``The problem
is that most of them are going to come back broke and humiliated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
