<SLUG> BC-RUNNING-GRIPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOLO JOGGERS, EXORCISE TIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOSEA MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ Ever since my high school days I've enjoyed
running (long before it became a fashionable pastime), and at least
three times a week I slip on my Reeboks and trot down to the
jogging trail that circles Oakland's Lake Merritt.
</P>
<P>
   Most runners greet me with a friendly nod or a wheezing ``Hi,''
but there are a few I meet who turn the miles into misery. There
are ways during exercise to exorcise these haunts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chatterbox: This guy is more interested in exercising his
jaws than his legs. In less than a mile you learn about his
business deals, political preference, religious affiliation, trips
to Hong Kong and the terrific deal he got on his BMW.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing your pace won't lose this bore; he'll risk heart
failure to keep up and tell you about the killing he made on the
stock market. Try answering him in gibberish that he'll mistake for
insider information. When he ducks into a phone booth to call his
broker, run like hell.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ms. Cutie-pie: She paid $500 for her pink-and-blue jogging
outfit. She doesn't want to ruin it with sweat. She wants you to
run with her to shoo off lechers lurking in bushes. Her
conversation is limited to, ``Can't you slow down a bit?'' and
``Haven't we run far enough?'' She asks these questions every 50
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Swallow air and expel it in a lusty belch. She'll sprint away
and shout over her shoulder, ``How gross!''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Authority: This is a variation of the chatterbox. He's
read everything from Jim Fixx to Jane Fonda, which he believes
makes him an expert on fitness. Chances are he began running two
months ago. He peppers his conversation with terms such as
``runners high'' and ``hitting the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   He wears T-shirts ``awarded'' after weekend runs, but doesn't
mention the 20 bucks or more that he paid for each one. He doesn't
hesitate to tell you that your shoes, shorts, breathing, etc., are
all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Unfriendliness won't get rid of this prancing pedant. You'll
have to resort to blatant dishonesty. When he criticizes your
stride, say something like: ``Gee, it felt so comfortable when I
finished fourth in the '92 Olympic marathon; I would have won the
bronze medal if that damned Hungarian hadn't cut in on me in the
last mile.''
</P>
<P>
   You won't see him again.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Masochist: You have to feel sorry for this guy. He hates
running. He'd rather be sitting at home sipping a brew and watching
``Baywatch,'' but his doctor has told him that he's got to exercise
to melt off the extra 50 pounds. You don't have to worry about him
talking; the poor fellow can barely breathe between groans and
gasps.
</P>
<P>
   Do this sorrowful soul a favor. Advise him to take up golf.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pro: This is the worst of all. As you're struggling
through your second mile, her (yeah, guys, it's usually a woman)
lean body will suddenly and effortlessly glide past. If she glances
back at all _ and she usually doesn't _ it is only to give you a
disdainful look for momentarily blocking her path. You know without
her saying a word that she is a true runner, and for an instant you
have been in the presence of royalty.
</P>
<P>
   This time it's your turn to slink.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Hosea Martin is a vice president with the San Francsico Bay
Area United Way.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
