<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINOLINK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 LatinoLink Founder's Vision for Web Site Pays Off   By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
When Lavonne Luquis founded her Web company in 1995 to provide
online news, chat and entertainment for Latinos, she knew nothing
about technology.
<TEXT>
<P>
   She didn't know how to finance a startup. She'd never sold an
advertisement, let alone a Web ad. And she'd never heard of an IPO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know diddly-squat,'' said Luquis. ``But I didn't know
I didn't know diddly-squat.''
</P>
<P>
   But this week, San Francisco-based LatinoLink made headlines
when it was one of 21 Internet companies Zapata Inc. invested in or
bought outright.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata, a Houston fish processor, is trying to turn itself into
a major Internet gateway competing with the likes of Yahoo, Excite
and America Online. It will split off its Internet businesses into
a separate company called Zap Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the acquisition were not disclosed. But Luquis, who
personally financed much of her three-person company's growth,
hopes that Zapata will provide capital to advertise and upgrade
computers. LatinoLink will also get increased visibility on Zap's
home page.
</P>
<P>
   From humble beginnings _ when she was grateful if the site
attracted three hits a day _ LatinoLink has become the leading Web
site for Hispanics, pulling in some 10,000 hits on an average
weekday. The company broke even for the first time in the most
recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Luquis, 38, spent six years as a newspaper reporter and editor,
first at the San Juan Star in Puerto Rico and later as city editor
at The Olympian in Olympia, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   When she first began Web surfing in 1994, she looked for sites
for Latinos or about Puerto Rico, where she'd grown up _ and was
sorely disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of that was born the thought that there had to be a market
for something like LatinoLink,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And so began the 12-hour days. In early 1995, Luquis hooked up
with Max Ramirez, a photographer she'd met at a journalists'
convention, and LatinoLink was born. For the first month, she put
in a full day at the paper and then came home to work on the
startup.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started the company, people said, `You're so
brave.' I didn't feel brave at all,'' Luquis said.
</P>
<P>
   During the next year, as she tried to keeping the business
afloat, keep the technology current, make deals with content
providers and attract people to the site, Luquis learned just how
brave she'd been.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In the early days, most of the company's capital came from
Luquis' savings, a business loan and some $50,000 in credit card
debt.
</P>
<P>
   While Ramirez was keeping the computers running, Luquis went out
and tried to sell ads. The site's first advertiser was brokerage
house Charles Schwab. Current advertisers include AT&AMP;T, IBM and
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Luquis quit her newspaper job in March 1995 and Latino Link
debuted the following month. It has news and features, job
listings, e-mail, chats and lots of feedback from users. Current
postings include: a news story about how immigrants pay more in
taxes than they receive in benefits, a column about novelist Isabel
Allende and an essay by a user on finding a recipe for flour
tortillas on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Web Magazine described LatinoLink as ``the premiere
place for Latinos online.'' A little over a week ago, Hispanic
magazine named Luquis a recipient of one of its 1998 Hispanic
Achievement Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had the vision to see there was an opportunity and a
market,'' said E. David Ellington, chief executive of NetNoir, an
online service aimed at African Americans. ``She does her homework,
and it's really quite amazing. She's very thorough and very
effective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1237EDT &QL; 
