These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business section
plans to move for Thursday, July 9, on the New York Times wire. For
questions, please call Marcus Chan at 415-777-8443.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; NETSTOCKS _ &LR;  After a month of spectacular gains, Internet stocks
took a beating yesterday but are expected to rebound today.
</P>
<P>
   Jittery investors drove down the share prices of Amazon.com,
Yahoo, and other Internet companies, fearing that the high-flyers
might have peaked.
</P>
<P>
   However, after the markets closed yesterday, the No. 1 Internet
search engine Yahoo announced better-than-expected earnings, giving
investors hope for a quick turnaround. By Julia Angwin
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MACWORLD  &LR; _ Apple Computer, which popularized the phrase, ``The
computer for the rest of us,'' says its future growth and survival
hinge on the consumer market it all but shunned the past few years.
By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUN _ &LR;  Could Sun Microsystems become the next big victim of the
Microsoft-Intel blitzkrieg? By David Einstein
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDIAVISION  &LR; _ In the largest securities fraud and insider
trading case in Silicon Valley history, the Securities and Exchange
Commission filed charges yesterday against four former senior
executives of Media Vision Technology Inc. By Peter Sinton
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PEOPLE IN TECHNOLOGY &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; HALLA &LR;  _ Not too many chip companies like to take on the mighty
Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   While Microsoft's vocal rivals expressed glee at its federal
antitrust woes, its Wintel counterpart operated in a much quieter
climate when it faced its own antitrust suit.
</P>
<P>
   But big, bear-like Brian Halla, entering his third year at the
helm of National Semiconductor in Santa Clara, doesn't back away
from a fight. Ask him about the Federal Trade Commission lawsuit
against Intel, and he'll tell you it doesn't go far enough. By Dan
Fost
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATINOLINK &LR;  _ When Lavonne Luquis founded her Web company in
1995 to provide online news, chat and entertainment for Latinos,
she knew nothing about technology.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't know how to finance a startup. She'd never sold an
advertisement, let alone a Web ad. And she'd never heard of an IPO.
By Jamie Beckett
</P>
