<HEADLINE>
IN THE WAKE OF TINA BROWN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Upon learning that  &UR; Tina Brown &LR;  had announced her departure as
editor of the New Yorker, Personals called a Bay Area contributor
to the magazine, a former staff writer, to ask who he thought would
replace her. ``A very brave person,'' he said, noting that despite
Brown's much-publicized efforts, the magazine has continued to lose
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Newhouse could comfortably do it,'' he said of Conde Nast
owner  &UR; Si &LR;   &UR; Newhouse &LR; , ``he would probably fold the magazine. But
nobody wants to be the person who killed the New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer said the magazine had been profitable until late in
the editorial reign of  &UR; William Shawn &LR; . Brown's efforts to make it
more topical and to break stories that made news failed to result
in a financial turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown would say she tried everything, &LR;  and it didn't work,''
he said. ``Maybe the new editor will spend less money, &LR;  and turn it
back into a small literary magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUPAUL RE-BENDS HIS GENDER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a shocking turnabout, &UR; RuPaul &LR; , the 6-foot-7 man who, dressed
as a woman, is M.A.C. cosmetics' celebrity spokesperson, is
appearing in ads dressed as a man.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper ads that appeared last week for Rockport shoes showed
him bald and with a goatee. A series of Saks Fifth Avenue
billboards _ the first was in Las Vegas _ show him as both man and
woman, two halves of a couple.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative  &UR; Charlene Barshefsky &LR; , who went to
China with  &UR; President Clinton &LR; 's entourage, was reported by the
Washington Post to have bought 40 Beanie Babies there for her young
daughter. The dolls are made for export to America, and sale is
forbidden in China. Barshefsky denied to the Post that she had
bought 40, but she didn't deny that she had bought any.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chicago Sun-Times says that  &UR; Larry King &LR; , the talk-show
host who boasts that he never reads his guests' books, has signed a
contract with Warner Books to write a book about President &LR; 
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Leroy Neiman &LR;  painted a portrait of  &UR; Joe DiMaggio &LR;  recently,
after which both he and the Yankee Clipper signed a print. ``First
time I ever co-signed a print with another person,'' Neiman told
the New York Times. ``I think it's, I'm not going to say degrading,
but unnecessary for another person to sign it besides the artist.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tommy Lasorda  &LR; was in Washington this week to testify before
the Senate Judiciary Committee in favor of a constitutional
amendment to ban flag desecration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOUSEKEEPING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Film director  &UR; Spike Lee &LR;  is moving from Brooklyn to an
Italianate Manhattan townhouse that used to belong to artist
 &UR; Jasper Johns &LR; , and before that to stripper  &UR; Gypsy Rose Lee &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Recalling a report in January that the Cuban government had
OKd a visit from  &UR; Martha Stewart &LR;  to that country,  &UR; Tina Martin &LR; ,
just back, says she found evidence that Stewart had visited
Castroland: At the Hotel Sevilla in Havana, the towels were folded
into swans.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a crafty investigator of international intrigue, says
she wrote a postcard from Havana to a friend praising origami- &LR; like
fans folded out of the toilet paper at a hotel in Mexico. The day
after she handed the postcards to a Hotel Sevilla desk clerk to be
mailed, the toilet paper in her room was folded into fans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUYING ONE'S NAME BACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Personals is leahg &LR; sfgate.com, but Personals got there first.
Entrepreneurs hoping to get rich quick have been, in the past year,
registering Web sites under celebrity names, then selling those
sites back to their logical owners.  &UR; Michael J. Fox &LR; 's name is
worth $10,000, reports the New York Times;  &UR; Bill Gates &LR; ' name is
worth is $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among the traders is  &UR; Vern Barke &LR; , who says he's willing to
swap. ``I would give up vannawhite.com for a shot on `Wheel of
Fortune,''' he said. `I would give up woodyallen.com for a cameo
appearance in Woody's next movie.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Lisa, the important thing is for your mother to repress what
happened, push it deep down inside her so she'll never annoy us
again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ TV anti-hero Homer Simpson sharing his wisdom with his
daughter, cited in a Library of Congress exhibit on Sigmund Freud
to open in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
