A7206 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALL-STARS-SFCHRON     07-09 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STARS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY HENRY SCHULMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
AL Tops Off All-Star High  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ It would have been such perfect symmetry.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after Bobby Bonds of the Giants homers in the
44th All-Star Game and wins the Most Valuable Player award, son
Barry Bonds of the Giants hits a mammoth three-run homer to bring
the National League back from behind and is named MVP of the 69th
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds the younger did his part Tuesday night, smashing a
451-foot home run in the fifth inning off Cleveland pitcher Bartolo
Colon to turn a 5-3 NL deficit into a 6-5 lead. But Bonds and his
mates were done in by Montreal Expos closer Ugueth Urbina and his
fielders, who immediately coughed up three runs in a very ugly
inning to erase the good Bonds had done.
</P>
<P>
   The American League added seven more runs, including three off
Giants closer Robb Nen in the ninth, and won 13-8 in the
highest-scoring All-Star Game ever, their second straight victory
and ninth in the past 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down 5-3, and that made it 6-5, and you think you have
momentum, then they jump right back at you,'' NL right fielder Tony
Gwynn said. ``That's the way it is in this ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the homerfest that a sellout crowd of 51,267 and NBC
might have wanted. Remarkably, 26 of the 31 hits in the game were
singles. But it was the offensive show that everyone expected from
Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Alomar, who snatched the MVP trophy, and Alex Rodriguez
also homered, Cal Ripken doubled, and Devon White tripled for the
only extra-base hits in the longest nine-inning All-Star Game ever
(3 hours, 38 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch the scoring in Denver, you're always seeing big
numbers: 13 to whatever, 13 to 6,'' Alomar said. ``This was a
different kind of All-Star Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar, White and Ivan Rodriguez each had three hits for the
American League. Mark McGwire went hitless with a walk in four
trips to the plate for the National League, although he nearly left
the yard with a sixth-inning drive to the warning track in center.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds had one only hit, but it was easily the most electrifying
of the night.
</P>
<P>
   His smash off Colon in the fifth inning traveled 451 feet and
nearly reached the upper deck in straightaway right field. Hanging
from the deck was a string of banners bearing the logos of all 30
major-league teams. Incredibly, Bonds' ball hit the Giants' banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was cool he hit the San Francisco sign,'' said
McGwire, who with White scored ahead of Bonds. ``It was very
impressive because he battled. He just missed a hit down the line
in left (that was foul), and he fouled off some pitches. He's
facing one of the young studs in the American League, he got a good
pitch to hit and he drove it a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds said he was just trying not to make a fool of himself
after whiffing at two fastballs in the 96-mph range to start the
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock. He threw so hard,'' Bonds said. ``I was just
trying to stay calm and not strike out. I was just nervous hitting
behind Mark. They walked him and put all the pressure on me.
Hitting behind Mark McGwire is not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer was Bonds' first in 20 All-Star at-bats. In 1973,
Bobby Bonds homered and doubled in a 7-1 NL victory at Kansas City.
The Bondses became the second father-son combo to hit All-Star
homers. The Griffeys did it first.
</P>
<P>
   But the one-run lead Bonds presented the NL was gone in moments
after Urbina took the mound to start the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar led off with a single off Craig Biggio's glove into
center, followed by an infield hit by Ken Griffey Jr. The runners
pulled off a double steal to get into scoring position before
Urbina struck out Juan Gonzalez. But with Jim Thome at the plate,
catcher Javy Lopez of Atlanta committed a passed ball. Alomar
scored to tie the game and Griffey moved to third.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey then scored on a wild pitch to put the AL ahead for good
7-6, and Ivan Rodriguez capped the rally with an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar added a homer in the seventh, brother Sandy hit an RBI
single in the eighth, and the AL finished the rout with three runs
off Nen in the ninth. Only one was earned.
</P>
<P>
   So ended a bad night for some great pitchers. The AL scored four
runs in the fourth off Tom Glavine, two on Ripken's double, after
the NL had taken a 2-0 lead off Roger Clemens on a Tony Gwynn
single in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The NL scored twice in an eighth-inning rally to close the
deficit to 10-8, but the rally died when Paul O'Neill of the
Yankees threw out Fernando Vina at home trying to score on a
single. Andres Galarraga then hit an inning-ending double play. &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
