<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL HITS A HOME RUN (AND MORE) IN COOPERSTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ It's just a bat, but I can't stop looking at
it. I can't stop racing from one name _ and one stream of
consciousness _ to the next. I can't stop wishing I could reach
into the glass case, pull out the bat and hold it in my hands.
Please? For just a few moments?
</P>
<P>
   The bat is a Lou Gehrig-model Louisville Slugger, and it is on
display at the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum. On the
barrel is the signature of Babe Ruth. Henry Aaron. Willie Mays. Ted
Williams. Frank Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The enrollment of major-league baseball's 500 Home Run Club is
15. Each and every member of the club has signed his name on this
bat.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth died in 1948, the year after Jackie Robinson become the
first African American to play in the major leagues. Robinson
opened doors _ if not minds _ for 20-year-old Henry Louis Aaron to
break into the majors with the Milwaukee Braves in 1954. Five days
short of his 20th anniversary in the majors, Aaron hit his 715th
career home run to end Ruth's reign as the home run king. Hate mail
and death threats turned it into a joyless coup for Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer took Ruth at age 53 _ before the two most recent
additions to the 500 club, Eddie Murray and Mike Schmidt, were
born. Nine other members (Aaron, Mays, Robinson, Harmon Killebrew,
Reggie Jackson, Mickey Mantle, Willie McCovey, Eddie Mathews and
Ernie Banks) started their major-league careers after Ruth's death.
While Ruth was alive, Mel Ott, Jimmie Foxx and Williams were the
only other players to hit any of their 500-plus homers.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there is this bat, on the second floor of the Hall of
Fame, that connects them all. Living and dead. Black and white.
Stocky and sleek. Sluggers who swing from the heels, sluggers who
transform hitting into science. Seven right-handers, five lefties,
two switch-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Do people from this part of the country truly realize what a
treasure is in their midst?
</P>
<P>
   I grew up 2,000 miles away, trusting that one day the chance
would come to visit baseball's shrine. Now that the Hall of Fame is
barely a 90-minute drive from home, I occasionally have to remind
myself of the wonders that never cease in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   The first catcher's mask, worn at Harvard in 1876. The
fingerless fielder's gloves of the 1880s. The 1899 contract that
Hall of Famer Christy Mathewson signed for $90 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Mathewson accumulated the first 20 of his 373
career victories. Mathewson, one of the five original inductees in
the Hall of Fame, served in a chemical warfare unit in France
during World War I. Accidentally exposed to poison gas that
weakened his lungs, he contracted tuberculosis. Mathewson enlisted
the healing powers of Saranac Lake in the Adirondack Mountains, but
he died on the first day of the 1925 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Did somebody mention the 1925 World Series? Check out the bat
the Pittsburgh Pirates' Kiki Cuyler used to hit a Series-winning
double off Walter Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Johnson, one of the artifacts in the Hall of Fame is
a ball signed for him by Teddy Roosevelt. One floor above is a row
of presidential box seats from Griffith Stadium. Nine different
presidents sat there before the wrecking ball came down on the
stadium after the 1961 season.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Stadium, of course, is where Mantle hit his 565-foot
homer in 1953. The ball and bat from that homer are on display.
</P>
<P>
   So is the bat Roger Maris used to hit his 61st homer in 1961.
And the bat _ now bronzed _ that Bill Mazeroski used to finish off
the Yankees in the 1960 World Series. And a bat Williams used when
he hit .406 in 1941. And the bat that Roberto Clemente used to get
his 3,000th _ and final hit _ months before he died in a plane
crash while attempting to carry food and medical supplies to
earthquake-striken Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   The connections from past to present are as endless as your
passion for the game. Shoeless Joe Jackson's shoes from the 1919
season. Ty Cobb's spikes and sliding pants. Ozzie Smith's glove.
The cowboy hat Dizzy Dean wore in the broadcast booth, where he did
his best to break every grammar rule known to English teachers.
</P>
<P>
   On one floor is a copy of a hate letter that Jackie Robinson
received when he was breaking into the majors: ``Robinson we are
going to kill you if you attempt to enter a ballgame at Crosley
Field.''
</P>
<P>
   To wipe out that ugly image, walk over to the St. Louis Browns
jersey worn by Satchel Paige in 1952. That was the year Paige went
12-10. He was 46 at the time, having spent his best years toiling
in the Negro Leagues. Paige, who didn't make his major-league debut
until he was 42, once came up with the following list of tips of
how to keep young:
</P>
<P>
   1. Avoid fried meats, which angry up the blood.
</P>
<P>
   2. If your stomach disputes you, lie down and pacify it with
cool thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   3. Keep juices flowing by jangling around gently as you move.
</P>
<P>
   4. Go very light on the vices, such as carrying on in society.
The social ramble ain't restful.
</P>
<P>
   5. Avoid running at all times.
</P>
<P>
   6. Don't look back. Something might be gaining on you.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire is gaining fast on the members of the 500 Home Run
Club. Upon hitting his 400th homer earlier this season, McGwire
donated the batting gloves he wore to the Hall of Fame. More than a
decade earlier, the Hall of Fame collected the bat that McGwire
used to hit his 49th homer as a rookie. McGwire passed on the
chance to hit No. 50 on the final day of the 1987 season because he
wanted to be at the hospital for the birth of his son.
</P>
<P>
   It's just a bat, and it rests in a glass case on the second
floor of the Hall of Fame. I can't wait until the day that Mark
McGwire's name is on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
