<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-ARMY-BOS &LR;      07-09 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-ARMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORANGEMEN SEE BETRAYAL IN BRITISH ARMY ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ Stephen McKinney peered across the
quarter-mile expanse that separates his camp from that of the
British army and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disgraceful,'' said McKinney, 33, one of the hundreds of
Protestant Orangemen who are maintaining a vigil in the pasture
next to Drumcree Church as a standoff between the Orange Order and
the security forces drags on. ``Here we are, loyal Ulstermen, and
they've our own army preventing us from asserting our civil rights.
They're up there with the same lot that killed them and us all
these years. Absolutely disgraceful.''
</P>
<P>
   The British army's prominent role in the standoff triggers
conflicting emotions on both sides of the barriers. For Protestants
like McKinney, it deepens their sense of frustration, insecurity,
and isolation. While they profess their British identity, the
Orangemen are defying British law by demanding to march in a
neighborhood where they are not wanted and where a
government-appointed commission has said they cannot go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around you, all these men who fought in the Second World
War, and they're being prevented from walking the Queen's highway
by the army they served in. It's a real slap in the face,'' said
McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   For hard-line Catholic republicans who have supported the Irish
Republican Army, there is the awkward acknowledgement that the
British army has been transformed suddenly from being their enemy
to their protector.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fair play to Tony Blair and fair play to the Brits,'' said
Anthony Murray - words that he, as a committed Irish republican,
never thought he would.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order, a 200-year-old Protestant brotherhood, holds
some 2,000 marches every summer to commemorate the defeat of an
invading Catholic king in 1690. Most of the parades pass without
controversy, but those which go through Catholic neighborhoods,
especially the one here, are a major source of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, police held the line for five days before they
allowed the Orangemen to march down the Garvaghy Road through a
Catholic neighborhood. This time, the British government appears
determined not to give in to threats or force by using its army to
take a more prominent role in the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Army engineers have erected barbed wire, metal barriers that
prevent face-to-face confrontation at roads, and a long, deep moat
that has stranded the Orangemen about a half mile from their goal,
the top of the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   Murray stood at the bar in Tir na nOg, the local Gaelic Athletic
Association club, where extreme nationalists who once justified the
killings of British soldiers and police officers acknowledged, with
some discomfort, that they are now depending on the security forces
to uphold their rights.
</P>
<P>
   Like many republicans, Murray finds himself in the odd position
of wanting the soldiers to go home, but not just yet. Murray
worries, however, that his neighborhood could become a sealed-off
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Most Catholic nationalists here don't believe the police are
capable of keeping the peace without the army. They cite the
collapse two years ago, and they say that the natural sympathy of
the 93 percent Protestant Royal Ulster Constabulary lies with the
Orangemen.
</P>
<P>
   The situation carries a strong sense of deja vu. British
soldiers were dispatched here in 1969 to quell the disorder that
grew from the Catholic civil rights marches and the violent
attempts by loyalists and Protestant authorities to suppress it.
When the soldiers arrived, Catholics brought them tea and biscuits,
considering them to be their protectors.
</P>
<P>
   But the IRA, which had been dormant, exploited the unrest and
the heavy-handed treatment of Catholics to rejuvenate itself. It
then began to target soldiers as members of an occupation force.
The army hit back hard, alienating most nationalists, and fed a
vicious cycle leading to almost 30 years of violence that killed
more than 3,400 and injured 10 times as many.
</P>
<P>
   Today, none of the 3,000-odd Catholics who live in the housing
projects around the Garvaghy Road are bringing the soldiers tea and
biscuits. But there is a grudging realization that if the Orangemen
are to be forced to obey the rule of law, British soldiers will
have to hold the line. For nationalists, the determination of the
army and the police to maintain order is a critical test of the new
political arrangements here.
</P>
<P>
   Extremists on both fringes are monitoring the situation to find
weaknesses in the enemy camp and to make sure, at least on the
Catholic side, that no one gets too friendly with the British.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA cannot be pleased by the sight of young Catholic boys
talking to the troops, most of whom come from Scottish regiments -
an irony because most Orangemen trace their roots to Scotland.
Youngsters here largely ignore the police, but they are fascinated
by the soldiers, with their uniforms and their machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   Someone presumably sympathetic to the IRA put up a notice
admonishing children not to fraternize with the security forces.
``Children and adults are advised not to have any dealings with
them,'' it read.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen's camp is anything but tense. A few dozen tents
are pitched in the pasture, and Orangemen, some of them with their
families, sit in lawn chairs, chatting and barbecuing. They seem
more like early arrivals for an outdoor concert than hard-liners
vowing to stay in the field until they are allowed to march the
same route they have been marching since 1807.
</P>
<P>
   One Orangeman underscored his resolve by putting up a Christmas
tree. Fast-food trailers came in to feed those without their own
barbecues, and an enterprising loyalist put up a souvenir stand,
selling loyalist paramilitary flags, cassette tapes that pay
tribute to dead gunmen, and baby bibs that proclaim, ``Born to
March the Garvaghy Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Orangemen complained that most of the international news media,
and all of the more than 100 international observers, stayed on the
nationalist side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media and the international observers are biased toward
the nationalists,'' said Bryan McDowell, 32, who wore his Orange
sash and buttons demanding his right to march.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why none of the international observers had gone to the
loyalist side to hear their grievances, Warren Allmand, the leader
of a Canadian delegation, said he feared observers might be beaten
up if they went over. Besides, he said, they had been invited by
the Garvaghy Road residents' group.
</P>
<P>
   Allmand said, nonetheless, that the observers can maintain their
objectivity: ``We call them as we see them.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Stephen McKinney sees it, all of the forces of society _
the nationalists, the government, the news media, international
opinion, and now even the British army _ are aligned against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't exactly instill confidence in you,'' McKinney said,
watching as his 7-year-old son played nearby, ``but we'll stay here
as long as it takes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
