<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7257 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-RECOVERED-DEFENDAN     07-09 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-RECOVERED-DEFENDANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOVERY LEADS SLAYING SUSPECT TO THE COURTOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By most accounts, Gena Spero left the sane world 15 years ago.
Arrested after her best friend was found strangled in a bathtub in
1983, she has lived in state institutions ever since, her behavior
under close medical watch, her eyes hollowed from an array of
anti-psychotic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Spero was never convicted of the murder. She never even faced
trial, appearing too psychotic in annual competency reviews for
doctors to recommend her case move forward, refusing to take
medication that would aid her coherence.
</P>
<P>
   But now, at age 35, Spero is scheduled for trial. Last month,
after more than a decade of treatment, a psychiatrist suddenly
declared her competent to face a first-degree murder charge in the
killing of Gina Sindoni, a 21-year-old Hampshire College student.
</P>
<P>
   Like a growing number of mental patients, specialists say, Spero
could be edging back toward the world of sanity with the help of
comprehensive treatment. Though her doctor says there is ``no magic
pill,'' she is clearly a beneficiary of medical research, which has
brought a better understanding of psychiatric disease.
</P>
<P>
   But with that understanding may come a price: If convicted,
Spero faces life in prison. Her psychiatric treatment could
diminish. And her mental fitness _ which her attorney says is
fleeting, anyway _ could disappear as quickly as it came.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the movie `Awakenings'?'' said Dr. Paul Appelbaum,
referring to the 1990 blockbuster about a doctor who raises
encephalitis patients out of their comas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite that dramatic,'' continued Appelbaum, the chair
of the department of psychiatry at the University of Massachusetts
Medical Center. ``But you've now got people who've been psychotic
for decades, who get these new medications and suddenly aren't
psychotic anymore, and are asking, `What happened to the last 20
years of my life?'''
</P>
<P>
   There are no statistics on how many mental patients who avoided
criminal trials due to their lack of fitness are now facing
long-dormant charges, specialists say, but the number of patients
being brought into competency is clearly rising.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the number of suspects incompetent to stand
trial is recorded together with the number of convicts found guilty
by reason of insanity _ for a total of about 700 a year, according
to a spokesman for the Department of Mental Health.
</P>
<P>
   But with the development over the last 10 years of new
medication known as ``atypical anti-psychotic'' drugs _ which work
in neurotransmitter systems that were ignored until the 1980s _
psychotic suspects are expected to regain competency more quickly
than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of different factors that influence how and
why a person might take a long time to be restored to competency,''
said Steven Schwartz, a mental-health lawyer at the Center for
Public Representation in Northampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drugs have become much better. More people are getting
restored quicker,'' he said. ``And after a serious crime, it can
take years for the pain of that experience to get addressed in some
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Spero's drug regimen is confidential. Even her precise diagnosis
is a mystery. Dr. David Greenleaf, the Medfield State Hospital
psychiatrist who assessed Spero for the court, described her
condition as ``puzzling.'' But he confirmed that it is most likely
a form of schizophrenia, and that her recent recovery is best
explained as a combination of the passage of time and
``comprehensive treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Spero was arrested eight days after the death of Sindoni, a
Beverly native whom she met in a women-only boarding house in
Boston. Each woman had a long history of psychiatric treatment, and
their shared troubles had brought them together _ occasionally in a
romantic relationship, according to reports at the time.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 10, 1983, Sindoni was found dead in the soapy water of a
bathtub inside the Haverhill apartment of Michael Costas, a
boyfriend of Spero's. Joe Spero, a Haverhill police officer,
immediately brought his daughter to see attorney Steven Colella,
who described his young client as ``obviously psychotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 15 years she repeatedly was found incompetent to
stand trial. Although she was treated successfully with
psychotropic drugs in the months after her arrest, Colella advised
Spero not to take her medicine when it came time for assessment, so
that she would appear before a judge and jury as psychotic as she
was at the time of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   And so the case dragged. After three years at MCI-Framingham,
Spero was transferred to a maximum-security unit at Medfield State
Hospital, where she remains. Once a year she was evaluated for
mental fitness; in 1992, she was even declared competent to stand
trial, briefly. But the psychiatrist changed his opinion at a court
appearance, and minutes later Spero collapsed with a seizure,
according to Essex County Assistant District Attorney Kevin
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, however, Spero has shown an ``attitudinal
shift,'' said Greenleaf, who has evaluated her for the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Colella said she is still being medicated, and whether to take
the medicine before her next hearing on July 22 is now ``her
decision.'' Greenleaf said her lucidity is the product of
comprehensive treatment and therapy, not drugs alone. Either way,
Spero has adjusted her perspective on facing the charges against
her, Greenleaf said.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas once she was unable to speak or sit up during a court
hearing _ and was ``destabilized by the thought of a trial'' _
Spero can now discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was profoundly different is that she can now sit with
this painful stuff,'' Greenleaf said. ``She seems to want to move
forward. She has slowly gotten better. Time has passed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
