<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_BOOST FROM ESTROGEN MAY BE BRAIN TEASER   
 _UP OR DOWN DURING EARLY LABOR? UP TO YOU   
 _PROMISE SEEN IN DRUG TO TREAT HEPATITIS B   

</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Boost from estrogen may be brain teaser
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does taking extra estrogen protect older women against
Alzheimer's disease or even normal age-related mental decline?
Research in recent years has suggested that it can, but results
from a new study of 532 older women suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists from the University of California at San Francisco
tested the theory by measuring estrogen levels in the blood of
women over age 65, and administering mental tests at the outset and
then five years later. (Most of the previous studies had asked
women about their use of postmenopausal estrogen supplements,
rather than measuring the hormone directly.)
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the scientists report in the July issue of the
Journal of the American Geriatrics Society, the women generally did
more poorly on the second mental test. But there was no relation
between a woman's estrogen levels and her performance over time. In
fact, women in the highest quartile of estrogen measurements did
slightly worse on one test than those women in the lowest quartile.
</P>
<P>
   These results, pending those of larger studies, should caution
women who may want to take estrogen to benefit the brain, writes
Dr. Elizabeth Barrett-Connor, of the University of California at
San Diego, in an accompanying editorial. ``Enthusiasm for the
neuroprotective effect of estrogen appears to have outrun the
actual data,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Up or down during early labor? Up to you
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some women say they feel better walking around during the first
stage of labor, but many caregivers tell mothers-to-be it's better
if they lie down. Now, a study in which women were randomly
assigned to either walk or stay in bed concludes that it really
doesn't make any difference, at least in uncomplicated pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   In a report in the current issue of the New England Journal of
Medicine, researchers from the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center in Dallas say they assigned 1,067 women in
spontaneous labor to be confined to a labor bed or to move around
as they pleased. The women had to be having regular uterine
contractions and the fetus had to be in the normal head-down
position.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, headed by Dr. Steven L. Bloom, found no
differences in the two groups with respect to the length of labor;
the need for forceps, episiotomy, or caesarean section, or any
other pregnancy outcomes. Therefore, ``it seems reasonable to let
women elect either alternative,'' the authors wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Promise seen in drug to treat hepatitis B
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An antiviral drug, lamivudine, can be given safely to patients
with chronic hepatitis B and can reverse the inflammatory damage
caused by the widespread disease, says a report. The drug could be
more effective and less toxic than the current treatment,
interferon alpha.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 million people worldwide are chronically infected
with hepatitis B, which can cause cirrhosis, liver cancer, and
death. The report in the current issue of the New England Journal
of Medicine said that researchers at several Chinese Hospitals and
at the drug company Glaxo Wellcome studied results for 358 Chinese
patients. The patients had been treated for nearly a year with
lamivudine, which blocks DNA replication of the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Liver biopsies revealed that 67 percent of the patients saw
improvement of liver damage, and there were few adverse effects.
Interferon alpha treatment has shown less success, the researchers
said, and can cause severe side effects. Further long-term tests
should be undertaken, they said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Marijuana byproduct to fore in stroke study
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cannabidiol, a natural component of the marijuana plant, shows
promise as a potential treatment for stroke, say researchers who
tested it in rat brains. The tests showed that the substance, which
has no mind-altering properties, was highly effective in blocking
the brain-damaging effects of glutamate, a chemical messenger
released in huge quantitites during a stroke. And cannabidiol
appears to have few side effects in humans, even at high doses, the
researchers from the National Institutes of Health said in a report
in the current Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
