<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7267 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-BACKLASH-$ADV12-     07-09 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-BACKLASH-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRAN'S HARDLINERS TRY TO TURN BACK THE REFORMERS
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    With JOURNAL-IRAN-$ADV12.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, July 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Iran's hardliners are fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   A fact brought home recently when conservative clerics -- those
men with the long brown robes, turban-like headwear and cellular
telephones -- hustled around the parliament that they control to
efficiently orchestrate the ouster of moderate President Mohammed
Khatami's top cabinet minister.
</P>
<P>
   To ordinary Iranians, it was ominous but not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   A year into the term of the popular but not-so-powerful
president, the political climate in this country of 60 million
people swings daily between Khatami's quest for reform and
conservative backlashes against him.
</P>
<P>
   While Khatami stocks his government with moderates, the
religious conservatives run the parliament, courts and the
military.
</P>
<P>
   While reformers are now free to take their case to the streets,
their demonstrations are sometimes broken up by semi-official mobs.
</P>
<P>
   The political and cultural clash is laid out in the pages and
offices of the lively Iranian press.
</P>
<P>
   At Shalamche magazine's storefront office, the walls are covered
in burlap, one corner is ringed with sandbags and artillery shells
are used as trinkets.
</P>
<P>
   The young, idealistic, editors do not talk to foreign
journalists, but their magazine defends Islamic values under
attack. Originally dedicated to the memory of the 1980s Iran-Iraq
war, its latest target is across town: The Jameah daily.
</P>
<P>
   Jameah is a snappy broad-sheet that started in the bloom of more
than 300 publications founded since Khatami's election. It pokes
fun at political leaders and prints long interviews with
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   Its office is also staffed with young idealists, but it is in a
California-styled villa. A tongue-in-cheek staff petition posted on
the wall asks editors why the swimming pool is empty.
</P>
<P>
   But Jameah has bigger problems than an empty pool. The Iranian
courts have ordered it to close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving from traditionalism to modernism,'' urges the
paper's editor, Mashallah Shamsolvazeen. ``Don't let this newborn
baby, the (Khatami) election, die now.''
</P>
<P>
   Khatami supporters sometimes call themselves ``The May 23
Front,'' referring to the election last year when Khatami stunned
the world by winning 70 percent of the Iranian vote.
</P>
<P>
   Youth and women _ two groups especially hard-pressed under
Iran's strict Islamic rule _ were strong supporters. In his
cautious talk about a ``civil society,'' Khatami offered hope of
more personal freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   The poor were attracted to his pledges to improve the Iranian
economy, largely controlled by quasi-government conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   His win inspires open, but still dangerous, questioning of
whether religious rulers should have the final say in government.
</P>
<P>
   The press is flourishing. Women are asking for more rights to
divorce and for child custody. Unmarried couples feel freer to hold
hands in public.
</P>
<P>
   But, Khatami's mandate recently suffered losses on three fronts:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Last month, the parliament, run by Khatami's conservative
election opponent, impeached Interior Minister Abdullah Nouri.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri was a key Khatami confidante whose office gave him a say
in how future elections will be organized and the power to appoint
the mayor's of Iran's cities.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The judiciary, run by religious authorities, has placed Tehran
Mayor Gholamhossein Karbaschi on trial for corruption. Seen as a
reformer and an effective administrator of the city of 10 million
people, he helped run Khatami's election.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The judiciary, also, ordered the closing of the Jameah
newspaper after complaints were filed against it by a large,
quasi-government business group and the prisons department. The
paper is still running, as it appeals the order.
</P>
<P>
   The attack against Nouri illustrated the hardliners' approach.
</P>
<P>
   They accused him of allowing too many public demonstrations and
replacing too many old administrators. They said crime and disorder
were rising and that he was encouraging supporters of Karbaschi to
challenge the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has preferred one man (Karbaschi) over a nation,'' said
parliament member Taher Taheri(cq). ``He has given permission to
too many to speak out and comment, causing great stress in the
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Khatami supporters say the hardliners know the president is too
popular to attack directly. So they attack his advisers, hoping to
tarnish the president and the idea of reform in this
still-conservative society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever anyone talks about freedom, soon (the hardliners)
connect the word 'freedom' to immorality,'' said student activist
Serajeddin Mirdamad (cq).
</P>
<P>
   Even in south Tehran, a working-class area where people adhere
to strict Muslim customs, they worry about their beloved president.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are putting pressure on him . . . If he weren't limited,
he could do so many good things,'' said Abbas Zavaraian, 35, who
works in his father's ice cream store.
</P>
<P>
   He explains Khatami's popularity simply: ``A good man will be
loved.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives are trying to preserve their power in a
society where the sources of power have always been hard to define
and are now getting even cloudier.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Leader, Ayatollah Ali Khameni, is the ultimate
director of the police, military, courts and many business groups.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed Khatami, who had served in the government in the
past, to run for president at a time most thought he had no chance
of winning.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Khameni was visibly weak at a public appearance and
Tehran is flush with whispers that he has a terminal disease.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami's own influence is limited both by the narrow powers of
his office and Iran's history of harshness with reformers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, clerics in the parliament impeached President Abolhasan
Bani Sadr after he tried to centralize power and reform the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami enters while Iran's fortunes are mixed. It has largely
recovered from it's eight-year war against Iraq. It is modern and
productive despite a U.S. trade embargo against this country it
says sponsors terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   But, slumping oil prices are gouging deficits into the
government's budget and increasing unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   About half of all Iranians were born after the 1979 Islamic
Revolution that ousted the dictatorial Shah of Iran, and they are
restless for material and social freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami is wary of giving his opposition any ammunition in their
claims that reform leads to chaos. He consistently urges followers
to stick to only legal, non-violent avenues for activism.
</P>
<P>
   Many have urged him to respond more forcefully, which he finally
did when the parliament fired his interior minister.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day as the impeachment, Khatami appointed Nouri to a
newly created position with broader authority -- a move reportedly
viewed as a direct challenge to the conservative offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
