<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFF GORDON IS NASCAR'S GOLDEN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OMAR KELLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He adorns milk ads with the likes of actress Claudia Schiffer
and tennis ace Pete Sampras. He's graced cereal boxes and
toothpaste ads along with appearing on the ``Tonight'' show and the
``Late Show with David Letterman.'' He was selected as one of the
world's 50 most beautiful people by People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, the millionaire with his own jet and a wife who was
a former Miss Winston, has struck gold in only six full seasons on
the NASCAR circuit. And he's really on getting started.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life's great. Racing has given me the opportunity to do
some really fun and exciting things,'' said the 26-year-old Gordon,
whose chiseled features and piercing eyes give him the look of a
Hollywood star. ``Being in a Super Bowl commercial was exciting.
The milk mustache (ad) was cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being one of People magazine's most beautiful people was fun
too, but I really wanna know who voted on that one. My sport is
great because it's so commercial. If you couldn't tell just look at
our cars. Racing provides me a lot of exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, Gordon sits in front of his bowl of Kellogg's
mini-wheat cereal, one of his many endorsements, and wonders if his
life could get any better. Winning a third Winston Cup in four
years might help.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon sits atop the standings, leading Jeremy Mayfield by 40
points, but even if he were to slip and not win the title, he'll
remain the circuit's best and brightest star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Gordon is certainly a star in our sport and appears to
have a bright future for many years to come,'' said NASCAR
president Bill France. ``Just as Richard Petty and Dale Earnhardt
opened the doors for the new generation, Jeff Gordon is doing the
same as NASCAR heads into the 21st century. He has become a great
ambassador for NASCAR.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into this weekend's Jiffy Lube 300 at the New Hampshire
International Speedway in Loudon, Gordon won four times this
season, collecting $1,678,665.
</P>
<P>
   Considering his success rate at NHIS, on the NASCAR circuit for
the last four years, it's a strong possibly Gordon's Chevrolet
Monte Carlo will be rolling into the winner's circle this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only been going there for three or four years, and I've
won twice so far. It's safe to say my track record is pretty good
there,'' said Gordon. ``It's always kind of been a hit-or-miss
situation at New Hampshire. Either our team wins or runs really
good on the track, or we do the total opposite, like crash or run
really bad. There has been no in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like his career. He's become the biggest star in United
States motorsports in what seems like the blink of an eye. Gordon
was 24 when he won his first NASCAR Winston Cup title, the youngest
ever. Bill Rexford had won the title at 23 in 1950, before
Winston's sponsorship. And Gordon can only improve with experience.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon credits his crew chief, Ray Evernham, with much of his
success, Evernham's swift decisions and cunning strategies have
steered Gordon to the winner's circle 10 times in one season on two
occasions since their hookup in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes us a great combination is our communication back
and forth,'' said Gordon, who will announce later this year that he
and his wife, along with Evernham, will form their own Busch Grand
National series team. ``The difference between us and the field is
that the more precise my observations are about the car, the more
precise Ray's adjustments can get. Small changes makes a big
difference in the speed.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday's race, Gordon is again being lined up for success by
his Hendrick Motorsports team. They'll put him behind the wheel of
a fairly new vehicle, one that has been particularly stong on the
long straight aways, which Gordon said he'll need.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (NHIS) track has long straightaways with very tight, flat
corners,'' he said. ``It takes a very different driving style to
really go fast. We've got some momentum right now. Things have been
handling well.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's likely that they'll continue, along with NASCAR's
steadily increasing popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have a hand in NASCAR's success. I simply try to put
on as good of a race as I possible can, but I do it for the fans,''
Gordon said. ``If it weren't for my fans supporting me, spending
money, going to my races, Jeff Gordon wouldn't be anybody. Those
people are special. They keep me hungry and working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon merely wants to return what the fans demand _ a winning
tradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7278 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-SOCIALITE-BOS     07-09 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-SOCIALITE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE OF MISSING SOCIALITE SULLIES NEW YORK CITY'S NEW IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For nearly 40 years, Irene Silverman has lived a
block from Central Park in a limestone mansion she converted into a
boarding house for the very rich. She's been attended to by cooks,
housekeepers, a personal assistant, a driver and several other
helpers, none of whom saw her vanish Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman, who is 82 and barely 5 feet tall, still has not
turned up, and police now fear she has fallen victim to one of the
bizarre, deadly deeds that once screamed regularly from Gotham
tabloids before crime began to plummet a few years ago under Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The missing woman is a retired Radio City Music Hall ballet
dancer. She is the kind of moneyed, East Side socialite who once
took a limo to art class at Columbia University. She has been known
to tote champagne in her purse and favored used-up bottles of
expensive gin to water the roof garden atop her five-story home.
</P>
<P>
   She is still classified as missing, but police are questioning a
pair of grifters who, fortuitously, were already in custody here: a
mother and son who have committed felonies from coast to coast, and
who were picked up Sunday on federal charges that they passed a bad
$14,000 check to purchase a green Lincoln Continental in Utah
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two people in custody and we are following a number of
leads, but we do not know where Mrs. Silverman is at the moment,''
police commissioner Howard Safir said Wednesday at a briefing where
he also announced that crime in New York had fallen another 8
percent. ``We don't know whether any harm has befallen her.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have combed sections of the park, hundreds of dumpsters
and any dark place around the gilded Fifth Avenue salons, for her
body. The search for Silverman also has spread to other states,
said Safir. He said a dismembered arm and leg discovered in a Bronx
recycling bin belonged to an unidentified Hispanic woman.
</P>
<P>
   Safir declined to say whether 63-year-old Sante Kimes, known to
prosecutors as ``The Dragon Lady,'' and her well-dressed
23-year-old son Kenneth Kimes were cooperating with investigators.
New York newspapers reported Wednesday that the two had Silverman's
passport and checkbook when they were arrested Sunday evening, and
that they are also wanted for questioning in connection with the
murder of a man who was found in a garbage bin four months ago in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by their records, the Kimes have dedicated much of their
their lives to felonious crime. Authorities said Sante Kimes has
been arrested about a dozen times on charges ranging from grand
theft to credit-card forgery to involuntary servitude. She was
caught stealing a $6,500 mink coat from a Washington hotel in 1985.
In 1986, she was charged with forcing illegal immigrants from
Mexico to work in virtual slavery at her home in Southern
California. Kenneth Kimes was charged last year in Miami with armed
robbery and resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Silverman came in contact with Kenneth Kimes
three weeks ago, when he rented a $6,000-a-month apartment in her
five-story building under the name Manny Gueren. Janice Herbert, a
close friend of Silverman's who had been scheduled to get together
with her Wednesday, said: ``The staff was always like little birds
watching over her all the time. This man who weaseled his way into
that house, he must have been casing her and her patterns.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses were arrested Sunday night by federal agents and New
York police on the unrelated charges, around the same time that one
of Silverman's housekeepers reported her missing. The next day,
police discovered blood stains in front of Silverman's E. 65th
Street house and issued a sketch of Kimes as a suspect. A detective
involved in Kimes's arrest made the connection between Kimes and
the Manny Gueren alias.
</P>
<P>
   Now, friends of Silverman are hoping that she is still alive. In
interviews Wednesday, they described her as a quintessential New
York socialite who grew up poor in New Orleans, spent 10 years as a
ballet dancer in New York, then married a rich, quiet real estate
developer who showed her the world and left her with millions when
he died about 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a grande dame, she was very elegant, and she loved the
dance,'' said John Gruen, a long-time dance writer. Silverman, who
danced under her maiden name Irene Zambelli, was related to the
great 19th century dancer Carlotta Zambelli, and she studied under
famous Russian ballet instructor Michel Fokine. Pretty and petite,
she danced from 1933 to 1943 with the now-defunct Corps de Ballet
at Radio City Music Hall, which at the time was the only ballet
company in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody can live to tell this tale it's Irene,'' said
Herbert, who also danced with the Corps de Ballet in the '50s.
``Ten years at the Music Hall prepare you for life. The stage is
cement, and you're dancing on point, seven days a week, four shows
a day, and that can do a job on your body.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverman gave up her career when she married Samuel Silverman
and began to live as a Manhattan gadfly. She sponsored artists,
attended classes, and eventually started the Colby Foundation,
which is dedicated to advancing the cause of ``all forms of needle
arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruen, the dance writer, said he met Silverman through his wife,
Jane Wilson, who was conducting a drawing class in the 1950s at
Columbia. ``Jane came home to say that here were all these
18-year-old and 19-year-old kids and there was this woman who was a
certain age _ she must have been pushing 50 _ taking courses in
drawing. And she was really quite talented. She was very bright and
asked intelligent questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is more, she was a very wealthy woman,'' said Gruen.
``Jane soon realized that Mrs. Silverman arrived in a limo to
Columbia. The courses lasted three hours, and she kept her limo
waiting there three hours on several occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruen said Silverman loved champagne so much she once took out a
bottle that she was carrying in her purse. ``Not to say she was a
drunk, because she definitely was not. But the champagne just
flowed. She said she needed it because she was in pain'' for her
back.
</P>
<P>
   When Silverman's husband died, she decided to convert their home
into a boarding house, renting out apartments to artists and
professionals. The house, said Herbert, was like ``an incredibly
magnificent museum,'' with expensive paintings filling the walls.
</P>
<P>
   From the street, it is impossible to tell what Silverman has
done to the place. Wednesday, it stood out on the upscale street,
but only because of the camera crews who hovered around the front
door.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very careful about that,'' said Herbert. ``You never
knew from the outside what was going on inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
