<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASPIRE TO PERSPIRE? I DON'T THINK SO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   I am old enough to remember when ladies didn't sweat. They may
have perspired, they may even have glowed. But they didn't sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are no more ladies, and women are sweating all over
the place. Yes, we've earned the right to sweat. It's one of the
less-acknowledged triumphs of the feminist movement. For some of us
who came of age pre-Title Nine, this new sweat equity takes some
getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   I am trying to learn to love it. To love my own sweat, that is.
Do I have to learn how to love everybody else's too? That would be
asking a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Before we go on, perhaps I should pause to say that if this
subject offends you, please move to the next column which, whatever
it's about, won't be about sweat. Don't say you weren't warned.
</P>
<P>
   On one of the hottest evenings in recent memory, a friend and I
were talking in my kitchen, which, like the rest of the house, is
cleverly designed to be drafty in winter and airless in summer. I
was attempting to cook dinner, I suppose you might even say
``slaving over a hot stove'' (I certainly would), and complaining
that I hate sweat, that it was driving me crazy, that I'd taken two
showers that day and was working up to a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn to accept your sweat,'' Chris said. ``Don't
fight it. Give in to it. Relax. Learn to love it.''
</P>
<P>
   I know sweat is healthy, that you're supposed to break a sweat
when you exercise, that if you don't sweat you'll boil over and
die. So sweat is swell. But do I have to love it?
</P>
<P>
   Chris grew up in Florida. Chris is male. Both these facts have
formed his view of sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Men love to sweat. Ask any man. ``I love to sweat!'' he'll say.
It's one of those guy things.
</P>
<P>
   But now it's a girl thing, too. Women love to sweat. Because
it's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We taxed our muscles, and ended up very sweaty. Which is why
we loved it,'' say the editors of Women's Sports &AMP; Fitness
magazine, reviewing a 30-minute workout in the summer number.
</P>
<P>
   And because sweating is so healthy, it's fashionable. Which is
great, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The division between fashion and fitness is officially blurred
into oblivion,'' the July issue of Vogue declares in a sportswear
layout featuring athletic-looking young models, some of them
actually sweating, unless they've been sprayed with Evian, a
possibility; it is Vogue after all.
</P>
<P>
   A workout-induced sweat is what a tan used to be: a status
symbol. Once, not so long ago, a tan was a mark of the leisured
class, of the sort of people who could afford to summer and winter
at resorts and watering places. Workers were pale. Now workers are
pale and sweaty. Because work is the new status symbol. So is
working out. And getting a tan is unthinkable. It can kill you.
Worse, it can age you before your time.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat, on the other hand, is good for you, assuming you
re-hydrate yourself by drinking gallons of bottled water and
electrolyte-replacing fluids specifically designed for those who
sweat. Sweat sells. It sells makeup. Waterproof mascara to help you
avoid the dread ``racoon-eyes'' look. Tinted moisturizers instead
of foundation, which tends to run when it meets sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat sells clothing. ``Your skin sweats, gets clammy, dries up
and dies,'' reads an ad for a new line of Nike training wear
described as, ``a highly-evolved way to facilitate the evaporation
of sweat by hauling it away from the skin.'' This ad features a
photograph of track star Marion Jones, caught in the middle of a
long-jump, her amazing form aglow. Sweat looks great, on her. But
on me? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
