<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAL-BEACHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA BEACHES ARE BARELY SURVIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOLANA BEACH, Calif. _ From his perch at Fletcher Cove, Carl
Stahmer has almost everything expected of a California lifeguard:
blond ponytail, even tan, an endless vista of blue ocean. All
that's missing is sand.
</P>
<P>
   Even at low tide, the beach is more gravel than grain.
Sunbathers and surfers between waves scramble for a patch of sand
that won't poke. Riprap, as the boulders brought down for
protection are known, lines the base of the fragile bluffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been screaming about the sand for years,'' said Stahmer,
a 10-year veteran who, between stints on the beach, is working
toward his doctorate degree in romantic literature. ``This last
winter was like a spike in the coffin.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as beachgoer MaryEtta Eaton put it, ``It's a disaster. This
isn't a beach, it's a strip.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher Cove, like many of southern California's
tourist-attracting beaches, is a lot less attractive than usual
this summer. Waves powered by last winter's El Nino storms pummeled
the coastline month after month, stripping away sand and slashing
the size of some beaches, lowering them by 10 feet or more in
spots. In nearby Cardiff, for instance, beachfront restaurants are
now oceanfront restaurants, with the water almost lapping at their
outdoor patios.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem of natural, episodic erosion is the
damming of large inland rivers, now unable to carry sand back to
the sea. Flood prevention also stops sand from returning to the
beaches, and oceanologists estimate that the dams have cut the
amount of sand traveling from river to sea in southern California
by half.
</P>
<P>
   With some beaches so bare they give new meaning to the term nude
beach, coastal cities are struggling to find ways to restore their
shorelines. Many of their economies depend on it. Southern
California beaches bring in billions of tourism dollars each year.
Solana Beach, a half-hour north of San Diego, has 14,000 residents;
its 1.25-mile stretch of beach attracts 1.2 million people a year,
60 percent of them out-of-towners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beaches are the hallmark of San Diego County,'' said Steve
Sachs, a coastal-erosion specialist with the San Diego Association
of Governments, a voluntary association of 18 cities. ``The quality
of life here is really dependent on the beaches. ... So we want to
get our beaches back.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the missing sand will return naturally; in fact, some
beaches are already coming back. Some, like popular Venice Beach,
are as wide and sandy as ever. But others, which never recovered
from the even more violent El Nino of 1981-82, need help. Sachs
estimated that San Diego County needs 30 million cubic yards of
extra sand for its 60 miles of beach, or enough to fill San Diego's
Qualcomm football stadium 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego had hoped the solution was in its own bay. To make
room for a nuclear aircraft carrier, the Navy late last year began
dredging the harbor, bringing up more than enough sand to replenish
the county's beaches. But the first sand pumped onto an Oceanside
beach was found to contain military munitions _ including some live
rounds. The rest of the sand was dumped out at sea instead.
</P>
<P>
   Now San Diego County must look to other sources, such as
sandbars. So far, Sachs said, it has raised about $14.5 million in
state and federal funds for the project. That's just to put the
sand down. Maintaining the beaches would cost $5 million a year,
not much when compared with another staple of California life. It's
about a third the cost of a freeway interchange, Sachs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother Nature will go a long way toward bringing the beaches
back, but we need some intervention on our own part if we're going
to keep them,'' said Blayne Hartman, vice president of a Solana
Beach soil-testing firm called TEG. ``Otherwise, the next El Nino
could wipe us out, maybe for good.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Solana Beach is involved in a pilot project to
truck sand in from Yuma, Ariz.. Two waste transport firms, whose
trucks were returning empty from Arizona, have kicked in $50,000;
the city put up $32,750, and another $5,000 came from an anonymous
donor.
</P>
<P>
   That will haul enough sand to raise Fletcher Cove, the tourist
beach, by 6 feet. But Tide Park, the smaller beach used by locals,
was going to be left to erode. Then Hartman pledged $10,000 and
helped raise another $30,000. Now Tide Park will get its own sand,
a project that City Councilman Joe Kellejian said should get under
way before month's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our entire beach during El Nino, and this ... adds
material from an outside source,'' Kellejian said. ``The analysis
that's been done on the sand so far was `as good as you can get.'
The grain size is excellent, the color's good. It'll be just like
it was before.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. A higher beach is not necessarily a wider beach.
During low tide at Fletcher Cove, the water reaches almost to the
lifeguard station. At high tide, during a full moon, Tide Park
disappears altogether. But both beaches are in better shape than
Cardiff State Beach, which has been reduced to rubble in the last
10 years and was depending on the bay dredging for new sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will ask us, `Why did you bring the cobbles in?''' said
Denny Stoufer, chief lifeguard for the San Diego Coast District,
referring to the stones that litter some area beaches. ``At South
Carlsbad, there was dry sand anywhere from 20 to 40 yards wide when
I was a rookie lifeguard. Now there's no dry sand, and in winter
there's no sand. ... Unless we do something, I can see a time when
there are no beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   To ensure the beaches' continuation, some specialists say,
artificial intervention is essential. Some are eroding too fast,
and the sand is moving too far off shore for natural replenishment.
Others, built by developers, were never natural and demand constant
care. Still, some environmentalists prefer to leave the coastline
to erode as it will _ an argument that upsets homeowners who live
atop the bluffs that must now be protected by seawalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that if you're going to have a highly developed
coastline, which we do, it's a little late to say we're not going
to intervene,'' said Reinhard Flick, a research associate at the
Scripps Institution of Oceanography and staff oceanographer for the
California Department of Boats and Waterways. ``Most of the
intervention in the last 60 or 80 years has increased the beaches
more than it's cost us coastline. This thing about man's
interference is a kind of bogeyman.''
</P>
<P>
   Intervention, of course, costs money. In May, US Representative
Ron Packard, a Republican whose district includes parts of San
Diego County, pushed through legislation that will make as much as
$7 million available for beach-rebuilding efforts. The bill will
also free the Navy to use whatever funds aren't spent on the harbor
dredging to dredge clean sand from natural offshore deposits,
meaning more sand for San Diego-area beaches.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Tide Park is so rocky that Andrea Sessions insists that
her son and daughter wear ``aqua socks,'' or rubber shoes. On a
recent sun-soaked day, Sessions sat surrounded by pebbles. She knew
enough to carry a lawn chair for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just keep sitting farther and farther back because the
beach keeps getting smaller and smaller,'' Sessions said. ``We've
got to get the sand back on the beach because that's a big reason
you go to the beach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
