<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7290 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-09 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR'S DECEIT ON PROP 226 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Beginning next week, JACOBY-COLUMN will move on Mondays and
Thursdays.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The defeat last month of Proposition 226, California's
``paycheck protection'' intiative, was a blow to conservatives and
Republicans, especially those Republicans who pay dues to labor
unions and resent seeing their mandatory fees used to promote
Democratic candidates. Proposition 226 would have required unions
to get a member's permission in writing before spending any part of
his dues on political activities. That, said the advocates of
paycheck protection, would finally stop unions from riding
roughshod over many members' wishes and beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   But organized labor fought hard to defeat Proposition 226,
pouring at least $20 million into a campaign of astonishing deceit.
The unions claimed, for example, that the measure would stifle the
voice of California workers. They warned that it would threaten
``Medicare, Social Security, public education, health and safety
regulations, and environmental protections.'' They even howled,
ludicrously, that paycheck protection ``could mean the difference
between life and death'' for sheriffs and police officers.
</P>
<P>
   It is always painful to lose to mendacious opponents, but the
supporters of Proposition 226 can take comfort in this: Even if
they had won, nothing would have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, I wrote that Proposition 226 would ultimately prove
futile. If California unions were barred from spending workers'
money on political activities without permission, I predicted, they
would simply call those activities nonpolitical and continue
spending as they pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's proof.
</P>
<P>
   I have from Mike Antonucci, the relentless teachers union
watchdog who runs the Education Intelligence Agency, the 1998-99
budget of the California Teachers Association. Or rather, the two
budgets _ the union prepared one spending plan marked ``226 wins,''
and a second marked ``226 loses.'' (Antonucci's communiques, must
reading for anyone interested in the skinny on teachers unions
nationwide, are dispatched from EducIntel(at)aol.com).
</P>
<P>
   Few unions blasted Proposition 226 as harshly as the powerful
CTA, which described paycheck protection as ``the biggest threat to
teachers and public education by far.'' Lois Tinson, the union's
president, prophesied that Proposition 226 would stifle the voice
of teachers in the public arena. Making unions get members'
permission before spending their dues on politics would prove a
bureaucratic nightmare, she said, and would ``open the door to
government intrusion into teachers' lives.'' It was a dagger
``aimed right at the heart of the work CTA does for children and
teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the union believed not a word of its own rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   The amount the CTA budgeted for the new fiscal year if Prop 226
failed _ that is, if its political operations would continue as
usual _ was $97,394,400. The amount it planned to spend if Prop 226
passed was ... $97,394,400. A difference of nothing. Zero dollars
and zero cents. One of the most partisan unions in California
intended to spend exactly the same amount of its members'
compulsory dues whether the paycheck protection measure won or
lost.
</P>
<P>
   The two budgets differed in only one respect. The ``226 fails''
version allotted $7.1 million to its so-called Initiative Fund and
its political action committee. The ``226 passes'' budget shifted
that $7.1 million into a mysterious new line item, the Public
Policy Center. The center's purpose would be to ``engage in the
development of public policies'' _ read: politics _ and to
undertake ``organizational outreach to other interested groups with
common goals and objectives to obtain visibility and coordinated
advocacy.'' Translation: Instead of giving money directly to
Democratic candidates and left-wing campaigns, the CTA planned to
funnel its members' money to other liberal groups and let
(itals)them(unitals) make the political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In short, a paycheck protection law ``would have resulted in no
net reduction in CTA income,'' says Antonucci, ``no increased say
for CTA members, and probably no effect on CTA political
influence.'' Had Prop 226 passed, evading it would have been as
simple as announcing that the money the union had formerly spent on
politics it was now spending on mere ``outreach.'' And for mere
outreach, it wouldn't have had to ask anyone's permission.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the new law wouldn't have changed a thing. Union
leaders in California, as in other states where paycheck protection
has been enacted, would not have shut down their political
operations and gone quietly into that good night. With a little
tapdancing here, a bit of ragtime there, they would have continued
pumping money into the coffers of their left-wing allies _ with or
without the approval of the workers from whom the money was
confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Real(unitals) paycheck protection is not about politics
and permission slips. It's about ending compulsory unionism in the
first place. Employees who wish to join unions should always be
free to do so, but no one should have to tithe to a union _ or any
other organization _ as a condition of keeping his job. Extortion
is a crime when an individual does it. It should be just as illegal
at the hands of a union.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Jacoby is a Globe columnist. His e-mail address is
jacoby(at)globe.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
