<HEADER>
A7292 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARLIE-ONTHE-MTA-BOS     07-09 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLIE-ONTHE-MTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF `CHARLIE' ON THE MTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL A. GRECH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Jacqueline Steiner heard of the death last week of
Walter A. O'Brien Jr., a long-forgotten Boston mayoral contender in
1949, her thoughts moved, once again, to a song about a man riding
the subway without enough money to get off.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's campaign, which finished last in a field of five, had
one enduring feature. It was O'Brien's objection to a change in T
fares that required an extra nickel to leave the subway, which
inspired Boston's legendary ditty, ``Charlie on the MTA.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am continually amazed that people _ it doesn't matter where
they're from _ still know the song, which we wrote all those long
years ago,'' said Steiner, now 79, who co-wrote the song with Bess
Lomax Hawes for O'Brien's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, a union supporter and well-known liberal politician,
ran a campaign that championed the working man hurt when commuters
were forced to pay five cents more if they used surface
transportation after getting off the Metropolitan Transit
Authority, now the MBTA.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to afford radio or television advertising, O'Brien asked
the group to compose campaign songs, which were played by sound
trucks that were driven through Boston neighborhoods. ``Charlie on
the MTA'' was adapted from the melody of ``the Wreck of Old '97,''
about a train crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wrote seven songs for Wally in that election, and `Charlie
on the MTA' was one of them,'' said Sam Berman, 75, who was part of
a group that sang the song during the campaign. ``In those days,
political campaigns culminated at a delicatessen in Dorchester, and
different campaigns used to try and drown each other out with their
sound trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie, of course, was the luckless subway rider who paid his
only dime to board the MTA but, because he lacked another nickel,
could never get off again. Steiner says the best-known lyrics were
written by Hawes:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charlie's wife goes down to the Scollay Square Station
</P>
<P>
   Every day at quarter past two
</P>
<P>
   And through the open window she hands Charlie a sandwich
</P>
<P>
   As the train comes rumblin' through.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People all the time ask me why Charlie's wife gives him a
sandwich and not the five cents he needs to get off the train,''
Steiner said, laughing. ``There is a paradox there, naturally. That
is part of the marvelous humor of the verse _ you are left with an
open question.''
</P>
<P>
   During the election, Steiner met with a group of politically
involved folk singers at Hawes' house in Cambridge to sing
traditional American folk music and, for fun, to adapt folk songs
to topical events of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, who was one of the folk singers, says the idea for the
song started as a joke between him and his younger brother, Arnold,
now 73. The song was popularized nationally by the Kingston Trio in
the 1950s, but O'Brien's first name was changed to George to avoid
its being associated with the Progressive Party, of which O'Brien
was a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Progressive Party at the time was very liberal and Walter
was regarded as a red,'' explained Steiner. ``The '50s were a very,
very bad time for any view that was not orthodox, and Walter began
getting hate mail until the decision was made to change his name at
the end of the song.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien was the only liberal candidate in one of Boston's most
famous mayoral elections, which James Michael Curley lost to John
Hynes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1949 election was one of the three biggest in Boston and
all of the media attention was trained on Curley and Hynes,'' said
historian Charles Bahne. ``O'Brien was a union man and no one
really paid attention to him. In the 1950s he was denounced as a
communist by Massachusetts' version of House UnAmerican Committee.
They hauled him in and he refused to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   A World War II veteran, O'Brien lost the 1948 race for the 10th
Congressional District and then the 1949 mayoral race. In 1957,
O'Brien returned to Maine, his native state, became a high school
librarian and ran a used book store with his wife, Laura Manchester
O'Brien, whom he married in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he died at age 83 at his home in Cundy's Harbor,
Maine, O'Brien was a footnote in Boston's colorful political
history. Charlie, however, took up a whole chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wrote the song because we believed in Walter O'Brien,''
said Steiner. ``He was a warm-hearted, generous man, a man of
principles and courage, who fought for his beliefs all of his
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
