<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7293 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERB-GARDEN-BOS &LR;      07-09 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERB-GARDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTHA PAUL'S HERBAL THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; POMFRET, Conn. _ On four acres in this rural Connecticut town,
Martha Paul, 43, has carved out a recipe for a magical kingdom. Her
ingredients are a 1780 house with a renovated kitchen, a shop set
up in a former rickety shed, and a backyard filled with herb and
flower beds.
</P>
<P>
   She never has to fight traffic. She's home for her daughter,
Saga, at the end of the school day. She's surrounded by the things
she loves. And she's doing what she most likes to do _ sharing her
knowledge of herbs in cooking, home decorating, and aromatherapy.
It's a recipe for happiness, one that feeds Paul's vision of a
nurturing lifestyle and a successful career.
</P>
<P>
   `I've created a pleasant place here for people to take classes
and look at our gardens,'' says Paul, who calls her business
Martha's Herbary. ``It's a comforting place where people can learn
a little about enhancing their lives. A lot of people come here
feeling empty because they've not set aside time for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here as an inspiration, I hope,'' says Paul, a tall,
energetic, and handsome woman with dark red hair. ``I make
everything seem easy, whether it's showing people how to cook with
phyllo dough, make a wreath, or serve a Tuscan dinner or afternoon
tea.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul and her husband, Richard, bought their 18th-century home
four years ago. In search of a large home on a main road, they
chose the big white house on the corner of Route 169 because this
rural road was named one of the top 10 scenic US highways by Scenic
America in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also across the street from the Vanilla Bean Cafe, a
very popular restaurant,'' says Paul. ``And there's three private
schools in town and some really great B&AMP;B's. These all draw a lot
of visitors to the area, and we are positioned to attract drive-by
traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pauls moved up from Hampton, a sleepy little town ``with
great hidden houses, stone walls, and lots of small cottage
industries. But our house there was off the beaten track and my
business had outgrown the space.''
</P>
<P>
   So her husband quit his job at Charrette in New Haven, and the
couple set about opening a new Martha's Herbary here. They had
their work cut out for them. Trees obscured the house, and the yard
had long been allowed to go wild. But within six weeks the new
kitchen with its large center island was completed, a new shop was
set up out back in the former carriage shed, and 15 raised herb
beds were in place _ all by Richard's hand. He also added a
fanciful bird house fence by the driveway and cleaned up a sunken
garden that became a medicinal herb garden bordered by two existing
fish ponds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little scary when Richard joined the business because
the herbary became our sole source of income,'' says Paul,
strolling through her backyard and pointing out the hops, pink
honeysuckle, and morning glories covering tall trellises. ``But
everything's gone very well. He just took a job at CVS several
weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Stooping to pick up a potted herb, Paul sang the praises of its
texture, color, leaves, and scent. ``My interest in herbs has
always been there _ since I was a little girl,'' continues Paul,
lovingly ruffling the leaves of a lovage plant and sharing the
celery scent with a visitor. She recalled following her
grandparents around their restaurant on Long Island, where she
cultivated her passion for herbs and cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want this to sound strange, but I think I have an
interest from past lives. It's inside of me. I just get so excited
when I talk about herbs, plant them, and smell them. My stomach
flutters. Herbs are great because you can cook with them, they look
beautiful, and they smell wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul didn't set out to be the herb lady of Pomfret. She worked
as a food and beverage manager at hotels after graduating from the
University of Maine, where she majored in environmental science.
When she and her husband moved to the New Haven area in 1984, she
befriended a woman who ran a landscaping business and retail shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I up and left the hotel business and went to work with her,''
says Paul. ``I had no retail experience but I knew I was a good
people person, knew about gardening, and could offer her my
knowledge of herbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to the garden shop was a small antique store run by two
women; it was these three people who taught Paul that she could do
anything if she had the passion.
</P>
<P>
   And, after her daughter was born in 1988, she had a visceral
passion to stay home. She had been trying to have a child for years
and did not want to leave her baby in the care of anyone but
herself. So she began teaching a class in herbal breadmaking out of
her kitchen. These classes became so popular that she added others
_ the difference between cooking with fresh and dried herbs, how to
preserve fresh herbs for the winter, and wreath making. She also
opened a small shop in her dining room, where she sold teas and
potpourri.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just grew and grew,'' says Paul, who is a member of the
Herb Society of America. ``I started the business with about $200
and filled my first classes with friends who didn't pay just so I
could make the classes full. But I didn't have to do that for very
long. Today my mailing list has grown to 4,000 people and that's
without buying anyone else's list.''
</P>
<P>
   She now teaches about 120 classes per year but would like to cut
back and devote more time to writing her second book _ this time on
lavender. Her first book, self-published, is called ``Seasonal
Herbal Favorites.'' She'd also like to do a cable television show.
</P>
<P>
   Paul enjoys her Saturday evening Tuscan feasts, when couples
join in preparing an authenitc Tuscan meal that might include
seafood bruschetta, polenta with rosemary blood orange and fennel
salad, and roast chicken with fennel seed. Noncooks kick back and
enjoy a glass of wine, and then follow the food into the dining
room for a formal dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Paul has also instituted for-women-only weekend packages that
include two nights at a local B&AMP;B and classes in medicinal facial
steams and foot rubs. Among her course offerings are soapmaking,
lavender, kitchen herb and spice swags, and herbal cordials.
</P>
<P>
   This spring she began an eight-month herb garden apprenticeship
program. One Sunday a month from April through November,
participants are brought through the entire herb growing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We start by planning and designing a garden and then get into
such things as cosmetics, edible flowers, and brewing garden tea.
It's a good life here,'' says Paul. ``I love my house, my business,
and being at home for my daughter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
