<HEADER>
A7294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-VISION-HNS &LR;      07-09 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-VISION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC ACCUSES FORMER SILICON VALLEY EXECUTIVES OF FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In what may be the biggest corporate fraud case
in Silicon Valley, federal regulators are accusing the former top
executives of Media Vision Technology Inc. of fraudulent financial
reporting and insider trading.
</P>
<P>
   Fremont-based Media Vision, a former multimedia maker of CD-ROMS
and sound boards, was one of the hottest stocks on Wall Street a
few years ago. But reports of fraud led to government
investigations, the resignation of several executives and
bankruptcy for the company.
</P>
<P>
   In a civil complaint filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in
San Francisco, the Securities and Exchange Commission sued former
Media Vision President and Chief Executive Paul C. Jain of
Berkeley, former vice president Steven J. Allan of Los Gatos,
former controller Robert S. Williams of Los Altos and former
director of manufacturing Wayne Nakamura of Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly the largest and most elaborate financial fraud
case in the history of Silicon Valley,'' said David Bayless, the
SEC's district administrator in San Francisco. ``We know of no
other cases where top corporate officers were involved in planning
out the fraud, carrying out the fraud and covering up the fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate word on whether related criminal charges
would be filed by the U.S. attorney's office, which also is
investigating the former executives.
</P>
<P>
   Allan's attorney, Darryl Rains of Morrison &AMP; Foerster in San
Francisco, said: ``Obviously, I'm sorry this is happening. The
action against Steve is unnecessary, and he is not responsible for
the problems at Media Vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the other former Media Vision executives either
declined to comment on the charges or could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC complaint, Jain and Allan ordered their
subordinates to falsify documents and inflate sales figures ``in a
scheme to defraud investors'' in the third and fourth fiscal
quarters of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The executives falsely reported that 1993 fiscal year revenue
had tripled to $241 million and profits increased six-fold to $19.9
million, according to the complaint. In reality, the company lost
$99 million in 1993 and $75 million in the first quarter of 1994,
the SEC alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The executives allegedly recorded millions of dollars in product
orders that were never shipped to customers, according to the SEC
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal securities laws designed to protect investors,
companies whose shares are publicly traded must turn in accurate
financial statements and other corporate documents to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC charged that Jain, Allan and Nakamura had sold Media
Vision stock while they were privy to ``inside information'' on the
company's financial fate, also a violation of federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC complaint alleges that Jain pocketed $1.49 million from
insider trading, Allan made $825,000, and Nakamura obtained
$21,250.
</P>
<P>
   All four executives also are accused of hiding the fraud from
Media Vision's auditors, Ernst &AMP; Young, by lying and ``cooking the
books'' _ creating a second set of accounting entries.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is seeking the return of all illegal profits, civil
penalties and an order barring Jain and Allan from serving as
corporate officers or directors of any publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Media Vision's lightning-fast rise and fall made headlines four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company's high-flying stock traded at 46 1/2 in January
1994, and the company boasted a market capitalization of $630
million.
</P>
<P>
   After the alleged fraud was discovered in the ensuing months,
the company's stock plummeted to 4~, and Media Vision went
bankrupt. The SEC estimates that investors lost more than $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   After filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in 1994, Media
Vision reorganized under new management and emerged two years later
under a new name, Aureal Semiconductor.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, other former Media Vision executives have
settled their civil and criminal cases with the SEC and the U.S.
attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   In June of 1997, Senior Vice President Michael Humphress paid a
$200,000 fine to settle fraud charges that he inflated company
revenues by shipping unordered products. And in January, Chief
Operating Officer Russell Faust paid $359,000 in penalties and
agreed to return $197,000 in profits from insider trading on Media
Vision stock, according to the SEC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
