<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7303 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-09 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNRAVELING LOVE'S TANGLED SKEIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I learned how to handle conflict from my dad. It was easy. You
wrote the offender out of your life. For years at a time my
brother, my sister, and I weren't speaking to one another, but my
dad held the family record for Most Consecutive Years of Silence.
He didn't speak to his brother for 30 years. They made up in the
last few years of his life.
</P>
<P>
   My dad taught me his technique for handling conflict. I was 15
and heartbroken when my first boyfriend, who lived out of town,
wrote to criticize me for not choosing a nicer girl to fix up with
his friend. This guy wasn't ditching me. He was just complaining,
but I was hurt and my dad wanted to share with me what made him
feel better in such situations.
</P>
<P>
   He sat me down with a pen and paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write, `You are absolutely right,''' he said. ``Now go mail
it.''
</P>
<P>
   I stood at the mailbox, knowing I was saying goodbye to one of
the cutest boys I'd ever met, but the message I was sending was
crystal clear: You want to criticize me? OK, I'll admit I was
wrong. I never want to have anything to do with you again. I felt
as if I was dying as I dropped the letter in the slot. It was hard
to imagine how much more pain I'd be feeling if my dad hadn't
showed me how to protect myself so well.
</P>
<P>
   These were his rules of self-defense, whether your adversary was
an enemy or someone you loved. You hauled out your biggest guns and
fired away. You ridiculed your assailant and if she ever raised her
voice, you walked out the door. Being in the wrong was intolerable.
Loving the person who put you there was impossible. If, after all
your defensive maneuvering, you were forced to acknowledge even the
smallest act of thoughtlessness, or stupidity, or wrongdoing, you
severed the connection.
</P>
<P>
   I can't count how many friendships I abandoned as a young woman,
or how many doors I slammed behind me in the early years of my
marriage. Like my dad, I felt I had to be perfect in order to be
lovable, and if I wasn't perfect, anyone who loved me was supposed
to pretend I was or suffer the consequences. I felt such shame when
my faults were pointed out that I imagined my critics felt toward
me as I did myself, unforgiving and full of contempt. I didn't want
to reproduce my parents' marriage _ they lived apart for 18 years _
but I was on that path.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly and painfully, this column, along with years of therapy,
taught me the art of conflict resolution. I'd adopted the policy of
sharing my rough drafts with whomever I wrote about and in doing
so, I could no longer simply blame the other guy. In discussing
disagreements, I got to hear the other side of the story _ what
she'd really meant, how I'd misunderstood his intent, that this was
a specific criticism not a total condemnation, how what he really
wanted was for me to see how my behavior was affecting him.
</P>
<P>
   At times I felt as if I was taking shrapnel from all sides, but
as I forced myself to remain in contact, I noticed something
utterly amazing. When I allowed family and friends to criticize me
without retribution, issues got resolved without any lingering bad
feelings. It worked so well that I too learned to say what was
bothering me before my annoyance grew out of all proportion.
</P>
<P>
   My latest collection of columns owes a lot to the folks I
practiced on, especially my brother Ken and my sister Susan. That's
why I dedicated the book to them, to thank them for their
``willingness again and again to unravel with me the tangled skein
of our love.'' They never asked to be part of my new
forthrightness, especially in print.
</P>
<P>
   My brother confesses that he dreaded the phone calls from me
that began, ``Ken, I have to tell you about something that's
bothering me,'' after what seemed to him like every family
get-together. The only thing that kept him from following my dad's
seductive example was his realization that he could no longer
follow it and sustain a relationship. He'd learned the hard way
that the resulting loneliness and lack of intimacy were far more
troubling than any possible blows to his ego.
</P>
<P>
   The other day I took another big step. After saying something
thoughtless to Susan, I summoned up my courage, called her back and
apologized before she had a chance to brood about what I'd said.
This might not be unusual in another family, but Susan marveled at
it, reminding me again how much we've been shaped by the same
forces.
</P>
<P>
   This is why it's worth the struggle to work things out with your
siblings. Sometimes they're the only ones who recognize love in
action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
