<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-09 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION: TOO MUCH, TOO SOON _ TOO BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old song about some things that naturally go together _ love
and marriage, horse and carriage _ may be a little outdated, but
apply the principle to children and the competitive spirit and
you've got a basic concept of child development: You can't have one
without the other.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes, however, is one afternoon of hearing siblings
bicker with each other _ (itals)``I am too faster than
you!''(unitals) _ or driving car pool with 7-year-olds badmouthing
the soccer referee for parents to wish they could turn down the
competitive instinct.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a bad idea. Researchers say too much competition at too
young an age can get in the way of healthy development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much too soon can work against the child who is very good
as well as the one who isn't because it inhibits possibilities for
each, cutting off potential growth,'' says child psychologist
Richard Weinberg, director of the Institute of Child Development at
the University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 7 or 8, the child who sees himself as a winner may
stubbornly refuse to try new skills or activities in which he
doesn't excel. The child who thinks she's a loser may say to
herself, ``Why bother,'' and stop trying, says Weinberg. She may
even see herself as a bad person who doesn't deserve to ``win.''
</P>
<P>
   This starts younger than we realize, although not in a toxic
way. What fuels a 14-month-old to applaud herself or a toddler to
beam when he gets to the end of the driveway on his Big Wheel
faster than his playmate is a need to control herself and her
environment. ``It's not pleasure at winning, it's pleasure at one's
competence,'' says Vonnie Colvin, an associate professor at the
University of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is a preschooler's comparative stage _ ``I'm
taller/faster/smarter'' _ about winning or losing, says University
of Wisconsin developmental psychologist Leona Schauble. ``It's
about noticing differences,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   This changes at about first grade when a child internalizes our
culture's win-lose mentality and sees that a child who is best at
something is rewarded by a teacher's smile or a parent's attention.
Now ``I'm taller'' translates to ``I'm better.''
</P>
<P>
   It's at this stage that problems can begin. Five- to 7-year-olds
are still moving back and forth between parallel play, where they
play side by side without paying attention to each other, and
interactive play, where they play together. ``If your child is
mostly still engaged in parallel play and he's put in a competitive
situation that emphasizes winning, it feels uncomfortable to him,''
says Colvin, a kinesiologist.
</P>
<P>
   That means he's not having fun, which means he's not paying as
much attention as another child or putting forth as much effort.
What's more, if he's in a competitive situation like a team sport,
he won't be valued as much.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, says Colvin, ``You can be setting a kid up to
fail at 6 or 7.'' He's turned off because he doesn't have the
skills and he isn't going to develop the skills because he's on the
bench or he's labeled a slow learner. Confidence and self-esteem
can plummet and so can a child's learning curve: Research shows
that the prime age for building skills of all kinds is 3 to 9. If
the window is missed, it can be harder (but not impossible) to
recoup.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who argue that this is a harsh lesson but one
children need to learn. Life is not fair. We live in a competitive
world. Weinberg's answer is that for young children, there's time
enough for that a few years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inappropriate competition results in premature closure,'' he
says. ``It doesn't allow a child to try things on and see how they
fit. If the music teacher tells you in third grade that your voice
isn't good enough for the chorus, you might never sing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for parents, pitfalls abound, often including a
child himself. ``Some kids by temperament are highly competitive.
You can see it as early as 5,'' says Schauble.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier you intervene, the better. The trick is not to
discourage achievement but at the same time to also:
</P>
<P>
   _Value, model, and reward teamwork and cooperation;
</P>
<P>
   _Help him make realistic self-evaluations so he doesn't set
himself up to be disappointed;
</P>
<P>
   _Emphasize process, not product, effort not ability. The idea is
to have fun, to like the learning itself rather than being focused
on the A or the score.
</P>
<P>
   Schauble says parents who stress ability over effort
inadvertently defeat a child. ``If you talk about how Tom is so
smart and Jane is so athletic, the message is that you're smart or
you're not, you're a winner or you're not, and there's not much you
can do about it,'' she says. Stressing effort over ability enables
a child to handle variability in others and in himself, to be
flexible to try new things and to handle losing.
</P>
<P>
   With preschoolers, losing shouldn't be a concept they deal with
at all, says Schauble. For instance, when you play Candy Land with
a 4-year-old, let him win; with a 6-year-old, you can let the game
play its course. The younger child enjoys the interaction with you
and the fun of the action of the game, says Weinberg, but doesn't
yet understand strategies or rules or even what a game is all
about. By 6, he does. If you're faking losing, he'll know it and be
insulted, to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of too much competition is usually most obvious, of
course, in organized sports.
</P>
<P>
   Schauble urges parents who enroll a child in any athletic
program to make sure not only that the level of competition is
appropriate (for children under 7, look for programs that stress
skills and drills, not winning), but also that it meshes with your
values. Both she and Weinberg advocate pulling a child under 10
from a team where a coach shows a pattern of putting inappropriate
emphasis on winning, belittling children, modeling poor
sportsmanship, or not playing children equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't act on your values, children assume you agree
with the coach,'' Schauble says. ``You don't want kids to be so
fragile they can't handle disappointment, but you don't want them
throwing down the bat and cursing the ump, either.''
</P>
<P>
   There is perhaps no better example of how all this gets put into
action than the Massachusetts Youth Soccer Association. Hoping to
counter inappropriate attention on winning, MYSA changed its
tournament policy last year for children under 10.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy didn't eliminate scorekeeping as was widely
reported inaccurately in the media, including in this newspaper,
but it did eliminate the elimination process. Head coach Dean
Conway says under the new regulations, losing teams play as many
games as winning teams. At the end of a weekend's play, there is no
single, overall tournament winner.
</P>
<P>
   The change became necessary, he says, because too much emphasis
on winning hurts kids. ``You'd have a coach always playing a child
in the same position instead of giving him a chance to try
something new, and you'd have kids practicing one or two skills
rather than many. Some kids would get played all the time, others
hardly at all.'' Perhaps most detrimental, he says, is when kids
``play for the coach instead of for themselves. They don't exercise
their own creativity, just do what he tells them. That isn't fun
for kids under 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway says the question coaches ask him most frequently is how
to get 6- and 7-year-olds not to bunch up around the ball. ``I tell
them, here's the way little kids think: `Wherever the ball is,
that's where I want to be.' They can't help it. You have to accept
this about them and work with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway understands that kids and competition go together all
right, but his answer has nothing to do with sports strategy and
everything to do with child development.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUGGESTIONS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _With children under 7, point out that winning is often a matter
of luck. If they think winning always depends on skill, they may
connect their loss to incompetence. Avoid talking about The Winner
or The Loser. Say instead, ``You're the one who won this time and I
lost. Next time it may be different.''
</P>
<P>
   _One way a young child works out handling losing is to play
games with an imaginary friend who loses and whom he consoles.
</P>
<P>
   _When children are in the stage where everything is about
winning, sprinkle your conversation with comments like: ``What's
important to me isn't that you get the highest grade but that you
understand the material/that you do better than before.''
</P>
<P>
   _Help a child who doesn't see herself as a winner note her
progress: ``You couldn't do that six months ago. Now you can!''
</P>
<P>
   _Don't push your child under 10 ahead of her age level in
organized sports even if ability warrants it. The level of
competition will be more than she can cope with developmentally.
</P>
<P>
   _Activities oriented to performance rather than winning _
gymnastics, dance, karate _ are better for children under 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Almost every two hours, a teen in the United
States kills him or herself, according to the Brown University
Child and Adolescent Behavior Letter. There are 90,000 documented
suicide attempts among teens each year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
