<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DUQUETTE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUQUETTE'S DEALS STOCK SOX WITH PLAYOFF-CALIBER TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As the man who has taken withering criticism for Red Sox
failures in the previous two seasons, it would be understandable if
general manager Dan Duquette pointed to the unexpected success of
his '98 team as personal vindication.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps because the season is only at its midpoint and this
is a team for whom late-summer collapses are legendary, Duquette
isn't playing that card.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway, even though the native of Dalton has fashioned
a ballclub that has received remarkable contributions from players
developed within the Red Sox system, like shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra and second baseman Lou Merloni, players that other
clubs had little interest in keeping, like outfielders Troy O'Leary
and Darren Lewis, and players, like pitcher Bret Saberhagen, who
have defied the medical odds and made triumphant comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've delivered exactly what we said we were going to
deliver,'' Duquette said in a recent interview from his private
booth above Fenway Park, the one in which he has hung pictures of
two of his personal favorites, Ted Williams and Bruce Springsteen,
and where he was watching the Red Sox play with his two young sons,
Daniel and Dana.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always some bumps in the road,'' he said, ``but our
program was always in place. This is an organizational
accomplishment. We know that it takes a complete ballclub, a
complete team effort. And we also know you need top quality
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's also an organizational effort. It's the
accomplishment of a lot of people. A lot of blood, sweat, toil, and
tears went into building this ballclub, and we're hopeful of
keeping it together in the next couple of years. We have a
foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, 40, is in his fifth season as Red Sox general manager,
hired by CEO John Harrington on Jan. 27, 1994. Only three players
remain from his first Red Sox team _ first baseman Mo Vaughn, third
baseman John Valentin and Tim Naehring, who has been unable to play
since a year ago last June because of reconstructive surgery on his
right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox won the American League East Division title in
Duquette's second year, 1995, when they were eliminated in three
straight games by the Cleveland Indians, who went on to win the
American League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   After a third-place finish in 1996 under manager Kevin Kennedy,
who was fired after the season and a fourth-place finish under Jimy
Williams, the Red Sox enter the second half of the season with an
excellent chance of returning to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Their record of 52-33 at the All-Star break is second in the
American League only to the East Division-leading New York Yankees,
who with a record of 61-20 are on a pace to win more games than any
team in baseball history. If the playoffs were to begin tomorrow,
the Red Sox would qualify as a wild-card entry.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty years after winning their last World Series, Duquette was
optimistic when asked about the team's chances of winning another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' he said. ``We've got a good group of core
players, we have some outstanding pitchers and we believe we can
play with the other top teams in the league. We've shown we can
play with the top teams in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an excellent record against the top teams in both
leagues, so time will tell. But we've got ourselves in position to
contend for a title. We believe we can compete with the Yankees in
a short series. Saberhagen beat them, (Pedro) Martinez beat them,
(Tim) Wakefield beat them, and (Tom) Gordon pitched effectively
against them.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at this time, Duquette was criticized for his failure
to keep future Hall of Famer Roger Clemens, who signed as a free
agent with the Toronto Blue Jays, compounded by his inability to
find a suitable replacement for Clemens as ace of the pitching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   He also was ridiculed for maintaining a revolving door of fringe
talent, players like Rudy Pemberton and Shane Mack, Rick Trlicek
and Toby Borland, while seemingly overselling, and overpaying for,
major question marks like Robinson Checo, a pitcher from the
Dominican Republic whose only previous success had come in Japan,
and Steve Avery, whose years of brilliance with the Atlanta Braves
had long since faded, even though he was only 26 when Duquette
signed him.
</P>
<P>
   Last offseason, however, Duquette engineered a trade for
Martinez, voted the best pitcher in the National League last
season, with the Montreal Expos, who were courted by many other
teams but preferred Duquette's offer of pitching prospect Carl
Pavano, a product of the Red Sox minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a good farm system to be able to make trades
like that,'' said Duquette, who was acquiring Martinez for the
second time, having traded for the Dominican-born pitcher when
Duquette was GM of the Expos and Martinez was pitching for the
Dodgers. ``In Montreal, we developed Delino DeShields and traded
him for Martinez. In Boston, we developed Carl Pavano.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't develop a Carl Pavano, you're not in position to
trade for Pedro Martinez. And Martinez is a true ace. He's shown
great leadership and results.''
</P>
<P>
   The farm system also has produced Garciaparra, on whom 11 other
teams passed in the 1994 draft before Boston took him with the 12th
pick of the first round. Garciaparra was the American League's
Rookie of the Year last season, signed a long-term deal that could
keep him with the Red Sox for seven years, and despite missing 16
games with a separated right shoulder, his production is even
better than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
