<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7319 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-DUQUETTE-2     07-09 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DUQUETTE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... a year ago.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Last year he went by all our great players _ Williams, Yaz,
Jim Rice _ in his rookie year,'' Duquette said. ``He had the best
(rookie) year of any ballplayer this team has ever had, and he's
improved on it this year. He's a real special player.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're starting to see some hope in the farm system. This
dynamic kid Garciaparra. Scott Hatteberg, Lou Merloni came through
the farm system. Soon, you'll see a group of players. It takes
about five to seven years. We're coming along pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette doesn't dispute that some of the fringe players he
acquired last season did not help the ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are going to work out, some aren't,'' he said. ``If they
don't work out, move on to the next piece of the puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of center fielders Lewis, who cost a pittance
($500,000) by today's free agent standards, and Damon Buford, who
came with Jim Leyritz in a trade from Texas for pitcher Aaron Sele,
has had a profound impact on the team's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran utilityman Mike Benjamin, re-signed last winter to his
second season with the Red Sox after beginning last year with
Pawtucket, has been an invaluable contributor, filling in at
shortstop when Garciaparra was injured, playing second when
newcomer Mark Lemke sustained a career-threatening cvoncussion,
even replacing Mo Vaughn when the first baseman strained his right
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duquette acknowledges that it's a struggle to put all the
pieces together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to get the proper balance between
pitching, defense, hitting, and team chemistry,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   An industrywide shortage of pitching has caused Duquette to sign
pitchers considered to be major medical risks, including Butch
Henry, who missed nearly two years after elbow reconstruction
surgery and is out this year after tearing the anterior cruciate
ligament in his left knee, and Saberhagen, who missed almost two
full seasons after radical surgery on his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, offered only $250,000 to re-sign with his former
team, the Colorado Rockies, accepted a make-good deal a year ago
with the Red Sox that paid him just over $1 million, and came back
this season for roughly the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   With 10 wins, Saberhagen has a chance to be the league's
comeback player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be resourceful, because good pitching is so
difficult to come by,'' said Duquette, who last March also signed a
22-year-old Korean pitcher, Jin Ho Cho, who made an impressive
debut with the Red Sox last Saturday and will make his second start
Sunday in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the advancement in medicine and technology has been so
significant the last couple of years, we've seen a number of
veteran pitchers come back and pitch effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Duquette received a three-year contract extension
that takes him through the 2000 season. Also receiving an extension
through the '99 season was manager Williams, who hadn't managed
since being fired by Toronto during the 1989 season and upon his
hiring by the Red Sox was widely viewed as an inferior candidate to
some of the big names Duquette had interviewed, like Jim Leyland,
manager of the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy Williams has used his entire roster this year,'' Duquette
said. ``He's gotten them involved. He's created a sense of team by
employing players in situations in which they can succeed. He has
an excellent work ethic, and he's very effectively managed the
pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real determined, professional atmosphere around the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's success will not shield Duquette from further
criticism. He remains unusually secretive for a baseball general
manager, and openly admits his suspicion of the media, whose needs,
he says, are opposed to the goals of the team. Some of his fellow
general managers have also expressed frustration at his limited
access; unlike most of them, Duquette rarely travels with the major
league team.
</P>
<P>
   And still looming is the possible departure of star slugger
Vaughn, with whom Duquette has had a frequently contentious
relationship. Vaughn, whose agents rejected the club's latest
contract offer in Denver Tuesday, could leave as a free agent after
the season, in a painful duplication of Clemens's exit in December
1996. Clemens blames Duquette for his leaving and has predicted
that he will drive Vaughn away, too.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Duquette does not convey the sense that he considers
it a matter of highest priority that Vaughn be re-signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made efforts in the past to sign him,'' Duquette said.
``During the season we're going to put our focus on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's having a solid season. He's done a nice job. He's played
very well defensively and he can hit, and hit with power.''
</P>
<P>
   Complimentary words, to be sure, but ones that fall short of
describing Vaughn the way many inside and out of the organization
do, as the team's franchise player and one the Red Sox can ill
afford to lose. Even Martinez has publicly stated that Vaughn is
the most important member of the team.
</P>
<P>
   But Duquette retained the confidence of Harrington after Clemens
left, and he probably will weather whatever fallout should come if
Vaughn leaves, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody once asked me when I got in baseball, `Are you
evaluated on your job?''' Duquette said. ``I said, `Yeah, every
day. You just pick up the newspaper and look at the box score.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an evaluation every day. But do enough things right
and you create a winning culture, and a winning team in your
city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
