<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-PEACEMAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN VOLUNTEERS TRY TO ENSURE PEACE IN RESTIVE NORTHERN
IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ Dorothy Bukantz is spending much
of her time in the Dump. No barbed wire surrounds the Dump, a
simple grassy field that separates Catholic and Protestant
neighborhoods in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   No troops patrol the Dump's perimeters, like they do at other
blockades and checkpoints around the city. So it's up to Bukantz,
equipped only with her yellow ``Official Observer'' vest, to guard
against violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a real outbreak here, this vest is it,'' Bukantz
said Wednesday as she stood a half-mile from where protesters
hurled threats and snide remarks at one another across barricades
set up at the Drumcree church.
</P>
<P>
   ``And my real job here is to witness, not to prevent. But I am a
little worried,'' said the 46-year-old woman who splits her time
between her home in the New York borough of Queens and her
volunteer job at the Peace Pagoda in Grafton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   With a name like Bukantz, she joked, one can easily assume she
is not Irish. But she also is neither Protestant nor Catholic. She
simply believes in basic human rights, she said. And that is why
she is spending her yearly vacation here.
</P>
<P>
   Bukantz is one of 80 people in Northern Ireland this week as
part of the International Observer Delegation, a group of
volunteers from around the globe acting as a sort of social
watchdog over the Northern Ireland conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five percent of the delegation is from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Flynn, who worked at the New York City Legislative
Office in Albany until four months ago, is here. She and the other
observers all came to make sure that all sides _ Protestants and
Catholics, those loyal to the British crown and those favoring
union with the Republic of Ireland _ are treated equitably by
political leaders and police forces as the standoff at Drumcree
church in Portadown and riots in Belfast and other Northern Ireland
cities continued.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent peace efforts brokered by the British and Irish
governments in Northern Ireland, the tensions persist. The promise
created by a recent vote in favor of peace faded in recent days
because of Protestant-led marches.
</P>
<P>
   The observer delegation is keeping a strict eye on the Royal
Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police force. More than 90
percent of the force is Protestant, and delegation officials
believe the police in the past turned a blind eye to attacks on
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   For example, said co-organizer Scott Dougherty, no one has yet
been arrested in 10 recent arsons at Catholic churches in Northern
Ireland. But an attack on an Orange hall _ a meeting place for the
Protestant and loyalist Orange Order _ yielded an arrest within two
hours, Dougherty said.
</P>
<P>
   While the observer group aims to ensure equal treatment for all
citizens, it admittedly sympathizes with the nationalist cause,
Dougherty said. For example, while observers patrol Catholic
neighborhoods and buffer zones, they do not cross the RUC
barricades very often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't feel safe over there. I'd feel threatened,'' said
Dougherty, who runs Peace Watch Ireland out of his Boston office.
``Some of our observers were told by loyalists that they'd have
their throats cut and bodies thrown in the River Bann.''
</P>
<P>
   Loyalists say the observers create more tension than they quell.
``It has been clear that they're on the nationalist side,'' said
Gareth Watson, the chief marshal of the Drumcree parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They obviously don't take into consideration the needs of a
widow with two or three children whose husband has been murdered in
cold blood by the IRA (Irish Republican Army). They don't consider
the needs of the business owner who has had his shop blown up.''
</P>
<P>
   But the delegation is aware of horror stories caused by the
loyalist faction as well. And though the group has no power to
enforce policy, they have no problem standing up to the RUC.
</P>
<P>
   The police force is supposed to make sure that Catholic homes
surrounding the Dump are protected from gasoline-bomb throwers and
hecklers outside their gate. But walkways in front of those homes
go largely unnoticed by the officials responsible for safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``This entryway is wide open,'' said Flynn, pointing to a home
behind agate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone could get in here. Why isn't it being guarded? That's
the question,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
