<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7363 &Cx1f; tth-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI &LR;      07-09 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, July 10, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PASSION (Undated) The thing you need to know right up front
about the film version of Balzac's novella, ``A Passion in the
Desert,'' is the ``passion'' of the title is not between man and
woman, or man and man, or woman and woman. It's between a man and a
leopard.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SOLDIERS (Undated) There's nothing in ``Small Soldiers''
that Joe Dante hasn't done before, most notably in ``Gremlins,''
but Dante's so good at what he does that this is unexpectedly the
summer's most delightfully inventive mainstream movie.
</P>
<P>
   By Jeff Shannon. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MADELINE (Undated) ``Madeline'' falls short of its
admirable ambition. It's a perfectly harmless, occasionally
delightful diversion for young children, at least partially
maintaining the simple appeal of Ludwig Bemelman's books to offer a
note of courage and adventure for kids who are just discovering the
