<SLUG> BC-FILM-PASSION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A PASSION IN THE DESERT' IS A CONSTANT TREAT FOR THE EYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thing you need to know right up front about the film version
of Balzac's novella, ``A Passion in the Desert,'' is the
``passion'' of the title is not between man and woman, or man and
man, or woman and woman. It's between a man and a leopard.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, this relationship is ultimately not all that
passionate, and the movie is not much more than a vignette. But
it's completely absorbing, its wild animal footage is thrilling and
its exotic desert locations are a constant treat for the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The film is set in 1789 Egypt. The man is Augustin Robert (Ben
Daniels), a young officer of Napoleon's invading army whose company
has wandered further than intended into the Libyan Desert in
pursuit of the opposing Mamalukes, and is frantically trying to
return to the Nile.
</P>
<P>
   After a Mamaluke ambush, he and an elderly artist (Michel
Piccoli) _ who has tagged along to document the wonders of Egyptian
antiquity for the Emperor _ get further cut off from the main body
of the company, and are soon wandering helplessly in circles.
</P>
<P>
   When the artist goes bonkers, the near-dead Augustin leaves him
and wanders into the ruins of an ancient city enclosed within a
desolate rock formation (filmed in Jordan's famed Roman ruin,
Petra) that, he soon discovers, is ruled by a stunning she-leopard.
</P>
<P>
   This leopard can be quite lethal (Augustin sees her grab one of
his Mamaluke pursuers and gobble him right up), but she seems to
take a benign interest in him, slowly approaches, shows him a
hidden source of water and even shares her kill with him.
</P>
<P>
   Augustin calls her ``Simoom,'' the Bedouin name for the wind,
and pretty soon man and cat are frolicking playfully in the sand,
and grooming each other like the closest of cat-family members.
Augustin becomes so fond of her, in fact, that a male leopard
appears, he gets insanely jealous.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of the movie is that it has nowhere to go with this
star-crossed love affair, and when Augustin starts painting himself
yellow and putting charcoal spots on his body to make himself more
attractive, the romance loses its appeal for us.
</P>
<P>
   But the leopard star is such a breathtaking sight that the film
works as a visual ode to the magnificence of nature; and the
lengthy sequence of man and cat bonding together is the most poetic
thing the movies have produced in this department since Kevin
Costner was dancing with wolves.
</P>
<P>
   First-time director/writer Lavinia Currier also makes the most
of her desert locations, which include Jordan's Wadi Rum _ the
setting of ``Lawrence of Arabia.'' This movie is no ``Lawrence,''
and not even an ``English Patient,'' but it is another haunting and
enjoyable outdoor epic in which the desert is a most prominent
character.
</P>
<P>
   Passion in the Desert. Directed, produced and written by Lavinia
Currier. Cast: Ben Daniels, Michel Piccoli, Paul Meston. Fine Line.
93 minutes. Rated PG-13 for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1428EDT &QL; 
