</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SOLDIERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SMALL SOLDIERS' IS CLEVER AND WITTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFF SHANNON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing in ``Small Soldiers'' that Joe Dante hasn't done
before, most notably in ``Gremlins,'' but Dante's so good at what
he does that this is unexpectedly the summer's most delightfully
inventive mainstream movie.
</P>
<P>
   Dante's up to his old tricks with the latest technology, and his
creative sensibility _ he's a mischievous renegade with a
movie-buff's enthusiasm _ thrives in a project tailor-made for his
talents.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be a Dante movie without a small Rockwellian town
where suburban peace gives way to fantastical mayhem. In this case
it's idyllic Winslow Corners, Ohio, where young Alan (Gregory
Smith) runs his dad's ``Inner Child'' toy story to restore parental
trust after a spate of troublesome behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But Alan's got two problems: He's attracted to his cute neighbor
Christy (Kirsten Dunst) who has a stuck-up jock boyfriend, and he's
just accepted a shipment of 12-inch action figures that are about
to turn his life _ and the toy store _ into a battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, the Gorgonite and Commando Elite action figures
arent't just any toys. The latest cutting-edge product from the
Globotech Corp., they've been designed with X-1000 microprocessors
procured from top-secret U.S. Defense munitions technology, and
these toys don't just play _ they learn as they doggedly apply
their programming.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Chip Hazard (voice of Tommy Lee Jones), the Commando
Elite are determined to annihilate the ``Gorgonite scum,'' a band
of misfit, pacifist aliens led by Archer (Frank Langella), who
studies Earth by speeding through Alan's multimedia encyclopedia
(after which he dubs Alan ``the keeper of Encarta'').
</P>
<P>
   That's just a taste of the movie's clever wit, and for every
throwaway pun or satirical movie reference (as when Hazard surveys
a fiery battle and proclaims ``I love the smell of polyurethane in
the morning''), there's a half-dozen rib-tickling groaners to
accompany the escalating warfare. Before long, the Commandos have
built an arsenal from household hardware, forcing Alan and
Christy's parents (among them the late Phil Hartman) and the toy
designers (Jay Mohr, David Cross) to defend themselves in a
neighborhood siege. (Hartman's fans are advised to stay through the
end credits.)
</P>
<P>
   With voices supplied by the original cast of ``The Dirty
Dozen,'' the jingoistic Commandos look like steroid mutants and
grunt military jargon with enough gusto to make G.I. Joe retire in
shame, while the Gorgonites (voiced by the members of ``Spinal
Tap'') could easily populate one of Tim Burton's nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Courtesy of Stan Winston's animatronics and computer-generated
antics from ILM, they're all given distinct personalities and time
in the spotlight, including the single-eyed ``Ocula'' and a critter
that resembles a cross between Robin Williams and the Tazmanian
Devil. Not since ``Toy Story'' (to which this movie owes great
debt) has there been this much giddy inspiration in one movie, and
although the plot gradually resorts to ``implausible'' extremes
(hey, even fantasy has rules), there's never a dull moment as chaos
erupts.
</P>
<P>
   Dante (who always finds a role for his favorite character actor,
Dick Miller) handles it all with consummate flair, and the script
includes such inspired military strategy as the use of Spice Girls
music as a Waco-like method of psychological warfare. Composer
Jerry Goldsmith even gets to riff on his own ``Patton'' theme, and
as always Dante adds some creepy underpinnings to the notion of
reckless greed and cynical marketing ... not to mention a platoon
of freaky Barbie-like dolls turned into the buxom brides of
Frankenstein.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one problem: Since the Gorgonites and Commandos are
ready-made for real-life toy stores, how will parents explain their
low-tech inability to perform like the real thing?
</P>
<P>
   Small Soldiers. Directed by Joe Dante. Screenplay by Gavin
Scott, Adam Rifkin, Ted Elliott, Terry Rossio. Cast: Gregory Smith,
Kirsten Dunst, Jay Mohr, Phil Hartman, Kevin Dunn, David Cross,
Denis Leary. Universal/DreamWorks. 109 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
some bizarre violence involving toys.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1428EDT &QL; 
