<HEADER>
A7375 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MADELINE-SPI &LR;      07-09 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MADELINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MADELINE' IS PRETTY TAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFF SHANNON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The opening credits of ``Madeline'' are accompanied by vivid
recreations of illustrations from the world-famous children's books
created by Ludwig Bemelmans, upon which the movie is based.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful Parisian scenes include moving figures of Madeline
and her schoolmates, bobbing along like paper cutouts created in an
animation workshop for children. Along with music by veteran French
composer Michel Legrand, these charming backgrounds set a promising
tone, suggesting the filmmakers have found a perfect way to
translate Bemelmans' books to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the French title ``Fin'' announces the conclusion of
this youthful Parisian adventure, it's pretty obvious that
``Madeline'' falls short of its admirable ambition. It's a
perfectly harmless, occasionally delightful diversion for young
children, at least partially maintaining the simple appeal of
Bemelmans' books to offer a note of courage and adventure for kids
who are just discovering the world around them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, slavish devotion to Bemelmans' ``Madeline''
books _ four out of six have been combined into a marginal plot _
is what turns the film into a rather tame and inconsequential slice
of family entertainment. Its charms are more subtle and infused
with an offbeat European sensibility, but because Bemelmans' books
were deliberately constructed as instructional vignettes, the film
can't entirely break free of its own episodic structure. Highlights
remain isolated in a familiar and lightweight storyline.
</P>
<P>
   When it works, it works quite well. Her role is rather starchy
and dull, but Frances McDormand is wonderfully understated as Miss
Clavel, the nun who runs the Parisian girl's school where Madeline
(precocious newcomer Hatty Jones) lives with 11 other girls. As in
Bemelmans' books, Miss Clavel has keen instincts for knowing when
``something is not right,'' as when she bolts upright in bed and
races to find Madeline suffering a bout of acute appendicitis. (Not
long after, all the girls want appendectomy scars like Madeline's.)
</P>
<P>
   The school is going to be sold as a diplomat's estate following
the death of school patron Lady Convington (Stephan Audran in a
too-brief cameo), whose bereaved husband (Nigel Hawthorne) is too
grief-stricken to consider any other option. While incorporating
incidents from the books ``Madeline and the Bad Hat'' and
``Madeline's Rescue'' (the latter involving a valiant dog), the
minimal plot follows Madeline as she foils the school's potential
buyers with the help of Pepito (Kristian De La Osa), the
mischievous son of a neighboring Spanish ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   The movie then rushes toward a forced climax involving Pepito's
kidnapping in a Gypsy caravan, but none of these individual
episodes is woven together with satisfying continuity. Instead,
``Madeline'' consists of several smaller stories that will give
children plenty to identify with.
</P>
<P>
   Director Daisy von Scherler Mayer (who scored an indie hit with
``Party Girl'') may not have found a dynamic vehicle for Bemelmans'
creation, but she's certainly got a knack for capturing
nine-year-old girls in all their charmingly clever glory.
</P>
<P>
   With her cherubic cheeks and pixie nose, Hatty Jones leads them
all with infectious enthusiasm, and careful casting allows plenty
of amusing activity on the fringes of many scenes. Still, with so
many cute kids involved, you get the distinct impression that some
of the best performances occurred when nobody was looking.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline. Directed by Daisy von Scherler Mayer. Screenplay by
Mark Levin, Jennifer Flackett. Cast: Frances McDormand, Nigel
Hawthorne, Hatty Jones, Ben Daniels, Kristian De La Osa, Stiphane
Audran. TriStar. 86 minutes. Rated PG for some very mild cartoonish
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1429EDT &QL; 
