<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LETHAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LETHAL WEAPON 4' GTETS BY ON FAMILIAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riggs and Murtaugh may be back, but that doesn't necessarily
mean they're still bad.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Martin Riggs (Mel Gibson) and Roger Murtaugh (Danny
Glover) are beginning to feel a little, well, soft and silly, in
the fourth go-round of the popular ``Lethal Weapon'' series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon 4'' ekes by on their familiar, rusty banter and
creaky camaraderie and its only real source of friction comes from
its younger co-stars, Chris Rock and Chinese action sensation Jet
Li, who makes his American film debut.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since ``Lethal Weapon'' debuted in 1987, the films have
enjoyed a huge following. The unconventional cops played by Gibson
and Glover struck a chord and audiences flocked to each consecutive
sequel. The filmmakers added Joe Pesci (as the annoying sidekick,
Leo Getz) in ``Lethal Weapon 2'' and Rene Russo came onboard as
detective Lorna Cole, Riggs' love interest, in the part three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon 4'' strings a slender bit of narrative between
car chases, reverberating explosions and violent,
``Bladerunner''-like fight scenes. This time around, Lorna is
pregnant, as is Murtaugh's daughter, who refuses to disclose the
identity of the dad.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs has to come to terms with his guilt over his wife's murder
and decide whether or not to marry Lorna. Leo Getz tags along in
the guise of a private investigator and comedian Rock joins the
team as junior detective Lee Butters, who has a suspiciously
intense interest in Roger and his family.
</P>
<P>
   But is jam-packing the screen with more faces necessarily
better? In this case, not always. To be fair, the movie is loud,
furiously paced and one roller coaster ride after another and the
stunts (many performed by Gibson) are certainly impressive.
</P>
<P>
   But the easy repartee that was affecting and charming in the
first installment, and the intimacy that ensued and grounded the
loose-wired Riggs and actually gave us access to these two cops'
lives, has been replaced with mean-spirited, mindless violence.
Even the pregnant Lorna gets kicked around and actress Rene Russo
virtually screams her way through a thankless role in order to be
heard over the perpetual noise.
</P>
<P>
   Director Richard Donner and writer Channing Gibson have crafted
a serviceable story about immigrant smuggling and counterfeiting
that ultimately steers the heroes to a confrontation with Wah Sing
Ku (Jet Li), a member of a discipline called the Asian Triad with
an agenda a mile long and a martial arts ability to match. But
while Jet Li is a blast to watch in motion, his villain is so
one-dimensional and singularly evil we can't relate to his dilemma
for an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Too, the story wanders all over the place and the running time
is tiresomely long, with characters introduced and killed off
relentlessly. If another chapter is in the works, hopefully the
filmmakers will recall the main thing that garnered a following in
the first place was the chemistry between Riggs and Murtaugh.
</P>
<P>
   The first ``Lethal Weapon'' interestingly gave us a focused look
at family and relationships that was exceptional for the genre. We
were given some psychological insight into Riggs and Murtaugh's
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the trend in action films demands more special
effects and less story. Here it's just one wiseguy crack after
another, so it's not all that surprising that, in ``Lethal Weapon
4,'' the most sympathetic and complicated character turns out to be
Pesci's grating Leo Getz.
</P>
<P>
   Lethal Weapon 4. Directed by Richard Donner. Written by Channing
Gibson. Cast: Mel Gibson, Danny Glover, Joe Pesci, Rene Russo,
Chris Rock, Jet Li. Warner Bros. 128 minutes. Rated R for language,
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
