<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLACIER-PARK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NATURAL SPLENDOR, MONTANA'S GLACIER IS CLEARLY THE TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By JEFF LARSEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you do the math, Glacier National Park played host to 1.7
visitors per acre last year. And few of those visitors to the
million-acre park in northwestern Montana likely came away
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1910, Glacier is an American treasure. The
$10-per-vehicle entry charge, good for seven days, has to be one of
the best entertainment tickets in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The natural splendor is extraordinary. From Lake McDonald in
West Glacier across the 52-mile-long Going-to-the-Sun Highway to
St. Mary Lake at East Glacier, the park offers some of the most
interesting geology and geography in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, an International Peace Park was created when Glacier
was linked to Canada's Waterton Lakes National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy hikers and campers might try some of the backroads that
slice through less-traveled areas. North Fork Road, for example,
leads to several remote lakes and campgrounds on the west side. Be
warned, however, that the roads can be quite difficult, even worse
than some Cascade range logging roads.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers and campers throughout the park are warned not to feed
bears and other wildlife. A fed bear, goes the saying, is a dead
bear. Bear warnings are posted at all the almost 1,000 campsites,
and rangers will fine violators unless they follow posted
guidelines for food storage.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicle size restrictions limit the number of motor homes,
fifth-wheel and conventional trailers in the park. This helps
reduce the congestion, making Glacier more camper-friendly than
some other parks. It's a smart policy, especially considering the
number of visitors each year.
</P>
<P>
   Late June, July and August are the busiest times at the park.
You can miss most of the crowds early to mid-June and post-Labor
Day, but be warned: A foot of snow fell in August 1992 in the
northeast portion of the park.
</P>
<P>
   From Seattle, take Interstate 90 across Washington and Idaho to
just west of Missoula, Mont., then north on Highway 93 to
Kalispell. Or you can jump on Highway 2 from I-90 at Spokane and
follow it right to the park gate.
</P>
<P>
   You can find out more about Glacier National Park
</P>
<P>
   at http://www.nps.gov/glac/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7384 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FOOL-SPI &LR;      07-09 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FOOL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORDS CAN'T DESCRIBE WHAT GOES ON IN `HENRY FOOL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gone is the smug, dissatisfied Hal Hartley. Sure, that
rat-a-tat, Mamet-esque elliptical dialogue is still there, but
``Henry Fool'' marks a turning point in the director's career and
technical prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Though this Faustian parable contains some surprisingly immature
gags _ they reek of Monty Python mentality and could make a
sensitive stomach queasy _ it maintains a remarkable,
multi-dimensioned depth of vision, even if it does ramble on a bit
too long.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Fool (stage actor Thomas Jay Ryan) is a stranger who
barges into the life of Simon Grim (James Urbaniak), a dour, quiet
garbage man who lives in Brooklyn and supports his depressed mother
and histrionic, nymphomaniac sister, Fay (Parker Posey). Henry
takes over the basement apartment in the Grim house, armed only
with his ``lifelong achievement'' _ his memoirs and a six-pack of
Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
   In due course, he will urge Simon to write down his thoughts and
to bare his soul on paper _ an act that will alter the course of
both men's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Henry will also seduce both Mom and Fay and prove to be the
catalyst that unifies the seedy, diverse neighborhood. Most of all,
he will help transform Simon from his somnambulistic trance into
the Allan Ginsberg of his day; Simon's poetic reminiscence will
become reviled and embraced as pornography and brilliance after
Henry posts it on the Internet. His epic will make a mute girl sing
and a right-wing politician scream with indignity.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the plot of ``Henry Fool'' is difficult. There is so
much happening in Hartley's abrasive, beautiful, even transcendent
movie that words can't begin to touch everything going on. Hartley
won the best screenplay prize at the recent Cannes Film Festival
and his demanding, taxing script is frustratingly exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, ``Henry Fool'' is an emperor's new clothes movie in
that it's about everything and nothing. It's about art, community,
loyalty, family, pornography, loneliness, abuse, celebrity and
responsibility _ and the story is so tenuous and fragile that it
could evaporate in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   ``An honest man is always in trouble,'' says Henry, and we never
know if he is a prophet, a demon or, as his name depicts, simply a
fool. We only know that his saga is a complex tale that is indeed
troubled, but also poetically honest and full of the ecstasies and
disappointments of modern urban existence.
</P>
<P>
   Every frame of the film is lovingly shot, textured and full of
significant _ if initially incidental _ symbolism. Several scenes
evoke the austere color of an Edward Hopper or George Bellows
painting, and that is an important note. Hartley frames his
desperate subjects with a raw, gritty vulnerability, sets them in
their squalid environments and creates a film full of haunting
tableaux. It's a case of life imitating _ literally _ art.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Fool. Directed and written by Hal Hartley. Cast: Thomas
Jay Ryan, James Urbaniak, Parker Posey, Kevin Corrigan. Sony
Pictures Classics. 137 minutes. Rated R for sexual content,
violence, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
