<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT DOGS TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECILIA BALLI  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In the movie ``Armageddon,'' pieces of a
Texas-size asteroid obliterate entire cities, leaving blackened,
charred remains.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas these days, it feels a lot like the movie. A scorching
heat wave is breaking records set more than a century ago, sending
people scurrying for shade or air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   But, as with the movie, there appears to be nowhere to hide. And
the hottest part of the summer is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, 70 daily temperature records were topped in 17 Texas
cities, the National Weather Service reported.
</P>
<P>
   Six of those records were broken in San Antonio. Other cities
breaking heat records in June included Abilene, Amarillo, Austin,
Brownsville, College Station, Corpus Christi, El Paso, Houston and
Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past couple of months we have been running consistently
above normal,'' weather service meteorologist Jeff Orrock said.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio on Monday, the temperature soared to 102,
breaking a 1996 record of 101. Although weather forecasters don't
expect temperatures here to break record highs in the next few
days, they do promise readings considerably higher than 30-year
averages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say there's a big change in the forecast, but
there's not,'' forecaster Daryl Williams said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters say the ``record minimum highs'' _ a technical term
used to measure each day's lowest temperature _ also are hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``So not only do we suffer in the daytime; the nighttimes aren't
cool enough either,'' Williams said. ``The bad news is the air
conditioner is going to run all night, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
