(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
LETHAL-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ When Mel Gibson and Danny Glover were
cast as the suicidal cop Riggs and his family man partner Murtaugh,
they were a couple of actors with star potential. What they've done
with the ``Lethal Weapon'' series, now in its fourth and final
installment, is build a chemistry that has been the basis for their
successful run that began in 1987. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
KILLING-FILM (Los Angeles) _ The premise of Mark Weidman's first
full-length feature is that people will kill to make a movie, and
that's exactly what happens in ``Killer Flick.'' Four wild-eyed
guys with dreams of Hollywood set off across the desert on a
killing/filming spree. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
WEAPON-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Lethal Weapon 4'' has everything
you'd want _ great action set pieces, vile villains, fresh comic
improvisation from Chris Rock, plus the palpable chemistry between
Mel Gibson and Danny Glover, still vibrant after four outings. 3
Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
SMALL-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Gremlins'' director Joe Dante is
responsible for this lifeless dud, a boring recycling of that
film's story about a group of angry critters who wreak havoc until
a resourceful kid saves the day. 0 Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
STOMP-THEATER (Los Angeles) _ Unless you've spent the last four
years standing in line to buy World Cup tickets, you know that
``STOMP!'' isn't a show about British soccer hooligans. But it does
suggest the creative things Brits are capable of when they find a
good pair of boots. By Reed Johnson. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ Bay Area-based Asian pop vocal group Kai
has hit one out of the park in the first inning. Kai's self-titled
debut disc recently reached No. 12 on Billboard's Heatseekers chart
for new and developing artists, and ``Something Inside Me,'' the
group's first single, is chalking up extensive airplay. By Fred
Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ With `Hello Nasty' ``We're losing the
kids.'' The Beastie Boys' manager wasn't taking no for an answer.
Dump that sample-silly conceptual approach, he might've said, or
the Beasties will end up on the same slag heap as Dinosaur Jr. By
Fred Shuster. 
. 
RUSCHA-ART (Los Angeles) _ L.A. artist Ed Ruscha is famous for his
experiments with light. An exhibition of two dozen paintings and
works on paper tracing the theme of light in Ruscha's work is on
view at the Getty. By Reed Johnson. 
. 
. 
