<HEADLINE>
TROUPE `STOMP!'-ING BACK TO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Unless you've spent the last four years standing
in line to buy World Cup tickets, you know that ``STOMP!'' isn't a
show about British soccer hooligans. But it does suggest the
creative things Brits are capable of when they find a good pair of
boots.
</P>
<P>
   The wham-bam-bang fest (with a U.S. cast) returns to Los Angeles
Tuesday for a three-week engagement at Royce Hall on the UCLA
campus. Performances are 8 p.m. Tuesdays through Fridays, 2 and 8
p.m. Saturdays and 2 and 7 p.m. Sundays. Tickets are $39 and $25,
$16 for UCLA students with valid ID. For tickets and information,
call (310) 825-2101.
</P>
<P>
   WAITING FOR SAM: The characters in Samuel Beckett's plays often
behave like prisoners in a penal colony of their own making.
Metaphorically speaking, they're trapped in the exitless prison of
existence. Which may be why the San Quentin Drama Workshop was able
to form a long, productive relationship with the late Nobel
Prize-winning playwright, and why its productions of Beckett's
works _ some of which Beckett staged himself _ have toured
internationally, stopping at places such as London's Young Vic and
Dublin's Abbey Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The workshop will present Beckett's ``Krapp's Last Tape'' at
8:30 tonight and Sunday at the St. Ambrose Arts Center, 1261 N.
Fairfax Ave. in West Hollywood. The production, with Beckett's own
staging, continues through Aug. 28 in repertory with ``Beckett's
Women,'' which consists of three short plays, ``Come and Go,'' ``Eh
Joe'' and ``Footfalls.'' For information and tickets, call (323)
660-8587.
</P>
<P>
   AIRING THINGS OUT: Seat cushion? Check. Mexican takeout? Check.
Sweat shirt for when the sun sets? Check.
</P>
<P>
   OK, you're ready for another season at the Will Geer Theatricum
Botanicum, the Topanga outdoor amphitheater where Shakespeare's
verses ripple through the canyons every summer. This year's lineup:
``Romeo and Juliet'' through Sept. 20; Peter Shaffer's ``Lettice &AMP;
Lovage'' through Sept. 19; Arthur Miller's ``The Crucible,'' Aug.
2-Sept. 20; and Shakespeare's ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' Sept.
4-25. For schedules, times and tickets, call (310) 455-3723.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE MOON: Four young urbanites search for ideal love in ``Even
the Moon Languishes,'' a new musical opening tonight at Aaah!
Capella, 5907 Lankershim Blvd., North Hollywood, playing at 8 p.m.
Fridays and Saturdays through Aug. 8. The book and lyrics are by
Tony Foster, who has managed to crank out 30 plays while also
earning a bachelor's degree in theater arts from California State
University, Long Beach. His one-act play ``It's a Saturday Night
...'' was produced at Actors Theatre of Louisville. The music is by
Damon Newman, a guitarist, bassist and piano player and member of
Pasadena's Knightsbridge Theatre Company. Tickets are $8. For
information and reservations, call (818) 509-6738.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
