<HEADER>
A7403 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-BEAT-LADN     07-09 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-BEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWCOMERS KAI RIDING HIGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bay Area-based Asian pop vocal group Kai has hit
one out of the park in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Kai's self-titled debut disc recently reached No. 12 on
Billboard's Heatseekers chart for new and developing artists.
Meanwhile, ``Something Inside Me,'' the group's first single, is
chalking up extensive airplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't have any expectations, but we felt good about
what we had done,'' said Kai singer AC Lorenzo. ``We worked on the
record for 18 months, and we're proud of everything on it. It was
scary when it was first released.''
</P>
<P>
   The r&AMP;b-tinged Filipino-American quintet grew up on a cappella
harmony singing, performing at festivals, community fairs and
corporate events. The group's name is an abbreviated form of the
Tagalog word kaibigan, which denotes the common bond among all
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on stage with nothing but your voice, you can't
hide,'' said Kai's Errol Viray. ``A cappella is our foundation.
It's the reason we take such full advantage of harmony, which makes
us truly come together as one.''
</P>
<P>
   Until intensive recording sessions began for ``Kai'' (Geffen),
members of the group continued to hone their chops with three shows
per weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzo, 22, says Kai's taste in music is as diverse as its
hometown's population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area is a melting pot of culture,'' he said. ``At our
high school, there was somebody from every single country. So, we
all like different types of music. Luckily, the line between genres
is blurring. I've heard Shania Twain on an r&AMP;b-pop station. It's a
good thing for people to be exposed to various kinds of music.''
</P>
<P>
   DEE DEE'S DEMONS: In the acclaimed 1996 book, ``Please Kill Me:
The Uncensored Oral History of Punk,'' Ramones bassist and
co-founder Dee Dee Ramone is portrayed as both a poignant figure
and a prime mover in New York's underground music scene.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Dee Dee tells his side of the story in ``Poison Heart:
Surviving the Ramones'' (FireFly; $16.95) co-written with Veronica
Kofman. The British paperback, available at a reduced price from
amazon.com, begins as Dee Dee sits in the Chelsea Hotel, sweating
it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken a lot of drugs in this hotel, and now I'm going to
get off drugs in this hotel,'' he writes. ``I am two weeks into
withdrawal, and all the demons from my past are tormenting me.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ramones fans, the now-sober Dee Dee's perspective on 15
years touring with the band is a must-read. He pulls no punches as
he admits to intense conflicts within the group and his own mental
and substance-abuse problems.
</P>
<P>
   ONE JUMP AT A TIME: If the jump-blues number used in the new TV
commercial for the Gap reminds you of ex-Stray Cat Brian Setzer,
you're right. Santa Monica resident Setzer's ``Jump Jive an' Wail''
is the song, and it can be found on his new album, ``The Dirty
Boogie'' (Interscope).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7406 &Cx1f; tdy-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      07-09 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNUFF OUT THE JFK SNUFF FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) A company in Orland, Ill., plans to sell copies of
Abraham Zapruder's home movie of the assassination of President
John Fitzgerald Kennedy. The expected price is $19.98 for a VHS
tape and $24.98 for a digital video disc.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy one, you are a pig.
</P>
<P>
   Everything that has anything to do with Kennedy has become a
``collectible.'' At an auction in 1996, a cigar box Milton Berle
gave to the president brought $574,500.
</P>
<P>
   Even a mass-produced copy of the Zapruder film will increase in
value. So, it's understandable that hobbyists would have an
interest it.
</P>
<P>
   If, as a memorabilia buff, you buy one, you are a pig.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, of course, the value of the film can't be
underestimated. Taken Nov. 22, 1963, as Kennedy's motorcade cruised
into Dealey Plaza in Dallas, it's the most significant 26 seconds
of documentary film in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Those who spend their lives studying the events of the past
might understandably consider a copy of the Zapruder film an
invaluable educational resource.
</P>
<P>
   If, as a history buff, you buy one, you are a pig.
</P>
<P>
   Not many years ago, this single snippet of 8mm footage was added
to the National Film Registry. Congress created the registry in
1988 to celebrate American cinema and preserve our film heritage.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the Zapruder film has taken a place next to
``Casablanca,'' ``American Graffiti,'' ``The Adventures of Robin
Hood'' (Errol Flynn version), ``Cabaret,'' ``Stagecoach'' and ``The
Day the Earth Stood Still''.
</P>
<P>
   Connoisseurs of the cinema may justifiably consider Zapruder a
necessary addition to their video libraries.
</P>
<P>
   If, as a film buff, you buy one, you are a pig.
</P>
<P>
   Those who investigated the death of President Kennedy believed
the home movie to be the most important piece of evidence in the
case. It's been analyzed and re-analyzed for all the years since
the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Amateurs and experts have used it to prove or disprove ``the
single-bullet theory,'' ``the multiple-gunmen theory,'' and notions
of secret governmental plots and official cover-ups. To those still
hoping to shed light on the case, a copy of the film could be seen
as a necessary piece of the puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   If, as a conspiracy buff, you buy one, you are a pig.
</P>
<P>
   There is no exception to this rule.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 1 the Zapruder film becomes public property, designated
as such by the Kennedy Assassination Records Review Board. Justice
Department lawyers are negotiating with the late dressmaker's
family over how much they'll receive for it. The parties are
millions of dollars apart, according to the family's high-powered
Washington attorney, Robert Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Zapruders have been very reasonable, very generous in
their dealings with the government,'' Bennett said. ``They have no
desire to exploit the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, no matter how you try to disguise it, the Zapruder
film is nothing more than a few hundred pictures of a man getting
his head blown off.
</P>
<P>
   He was a real person.
</P>
<P>
   He had real children.
</P>
<P>
   Those children are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else matters.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it isn't as if you haven't seen the film. Most likely
you've seen it again and again, frame by gruesome frame. It's been
on television hundreds of times.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if the person getting killed was someone you knew,
imagine if it was your dad.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a done deal. There's one thing we can do to put the
sick JFK profiteers out of business. That is:
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, inaction is action. Don't buy. Continue not
buying. Tell your friends and famly not to buy. Plot and whisper
and scheme until all of us, acting as one, fire a fatal economic
shot to the heart.
</P>
<P>
   For you conspiracy buffs, I call this the ``single-bullet
theory.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1444EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0153 </DOCNO>
