<P>
   &UR; ORGANS WITHOUT DONORS &LR;  _ It's a transplant surgeon's dream: an
endless supply of organs and tissues neatly matched to their
recipients. This may happen if a radical new technology works. A
cow egg stripped of its nucleus would be fused with a human cell to
create a nonviable cloned embryo, from which embryonic stem cells
would be taken. These can then develop into a wide range of
tissues. By Philip Cohen. 900 words. (slugged:
BC-ORGANS-WITHOUT-DONORS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIDEPRESSANTS, NO BETTER THAN PLACEBO &LR;  _ Antidepressants may
be little better than placebos. The benefits of taking the drugs
could be almost entirely due to the psychological boost derived
from taking a pill rather than their effects on brain chemistry,
say two researchers in the United States. By Michael Day. 500
words. (slugged: BC-TENNIS-CLICHES-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRAVE NEW WORLDS &LR;  _ Astronomers may have had their first
glimpse of Earthlike planets beyond the solar system, showing that
an unexpectedly powerful technique for planet-hunting can work.
Until now, astronomers thought they lacked the techniques to detect
small extrasolar planets, but an international research team has
proved them wrong. By Charles Seife. 400 words. (slugged:
BC-PLANET-HUNTING-TECHNIQUES-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DECAFFEINATED MICROCHIPS &LR;  _ The technique used to make
decaffeinated coffee beans could be used to clean up the microchip
manufacturing industry. Researchers are using supercritical carbon
dioxide _ used to extract caffeine from coffee beans _ instead of
corrosive chemicals to etch circuits on silicon chips. By Mark
Ward. 300 words. (slugged:
BC-DECAFFEINATED-MICROCHIPS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you have any editorial questions or comments, please call
 &UR; ALEXANDRA SALAZAR, &LR;  associate editor at The New York Times
Syndicate, at (212) 499-3339.
 &UR; Many thanks. &LR; 
