<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7430 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOFULIST-AZR &LR;      07-09 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOFU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST SAY SOY: PRODUCT LINE IS VAST, VARIED 
</HEADLINE>
 LIST-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (WITH TOFU)  
 By STEPHANIE L. PEARSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - These food items are good sources of soy protein and
genistein, a compound that is genetically similar to the human
hormone estrogen: &QL; 
 &QL; 
Edamame
</P>
<P>
   Plain ol' soybeans. Most commonly found in Japanese restaurants,
lightly blanched or steamed and sprinkled with salt. Make them at
home in the microwave or steamed _ an excellent snack or precursor
to a main meal. These are high in protein and fiber and contain no
cholesterol. Find these fresh or frozen at Asian grocery stores and
specialty stores, such as Whole Foods.  &UR; Note: Don't eat the whole
pod. Crack it open and eat the beans. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fake meat
</P>
<P>
   Even the most ``tofuphobic'' among us can stomach a veggie
burger or two. Soy-base ``hamburgers,'' ``hot dogs,'' ``ground
beef,'' ``sausage'' and the like are probably the easiest way to
start incorporating soy into our diets. Don't assume that all
vegetarian ``meat'' is soy-based. Read the ingredients. Most are
made from soy protein, tofu and other ingredients and can be
frozen, canned or dried. There are dozens available, and their
nutritional values vary considerably, so read the labels carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Look for soy sausage, soy bacon, hamburgers and hot dogs and soy
ground beef. Beware that these products have less fat than their
animal counterparts and so may need to be cooked with non-stick
sprays and for a shorter time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Miso
</P>
<P>
   Miso soup is a rich, salty broth of fermented soybeans. Although
available powdered, miso is best sold as a paste. Add water for
soup or use as a seasoning (in a salad dressing, for instance).
Different kinds of miso have different flavors, so keep trying
until you find your favorite. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Non-dairy soy frozen dessert
</P>
<P>
   A lifesaver for the lactose-intoler ant. Made from soy milk or
soy yogurt, soy-base frozen desserts have just about all the yum of
ice cream with the benefits of soy, no cholesterol and usually less
fat. Find brands, such as Tofutti, in natural food and specialty
stores such as A.J.'s. These taste more like ice milk than ice
cream. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy cheese
</P>
<P>
   Made from soy milk, soy cheese approximates both hard and soft
cheeses. Be sure to use full-fat versions for cooking or baking,
because low-fat versions don't melt well. In baking, use a lower
oven temperature than you would with normal cheese. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy flour
</P>
<P>
   Made from roasted soybeans ground into a fine powder, soy flour
comes in three incarnations: natural or full-fat; defatted, which
has the oils removed during processing; and lecithinated, which has
had lecithin added. The defatted flour gives even more of soy's
protein kick to recipes because the protein is concentrated.
Because soy flour is gluten-free, yeast-raised breads made with soy
flour are more dense in texture. Replace a fourth to a third of the
flour with soy flour in recipes for muffins, cakes, cookies,
pancakes and quick breads. Don't try to use it alone. Also, note
that it must be refrigerated. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy grits
</P>
<P>
   Soy grits are similar to soy flour except that the soybeans have
been toasted and cracked into coarse pieces, rather than fine
powder. Soy grits can be used as a substitute for flour in some
recipes. High in protein, soy grits can be added to rice and other
grains and cooked together. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy protein concentrate
</P>
<P>
   Soy protein concentrate comes from defatted soy flakes. It
contains about 70 percent protein, while retaining most of the
bean's dietary fiber. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Isolated soy protein
</P>
<P>
   When protein is removed from defatted flakes, the result is soy
protein isolates, the most highly refined soy protein. Containing
92 percent protein, soy protein isolates possess the greatest
amount of protein of all soy products. They are a highly digestible
source of amino acids (building blocks of protein necessary for
human growth and maintenance). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Textured soy protein
</P>
<P>
   Textured soy protein, or TSP, usually refers to products made
from textured soy flour, although the term also can be applied to
textured soy protein concentrates and spun soy fiber.
</P>
<P>
   When hydrated, it has a chewy texture. It is widely used as a
meat extender. One of the more popular brands is made by Archer
Daniels Midland Co., which owns the right to the product named
Textured Vegetable Protein, or TVP.
</P>
<P>
   Textured soy flour contains about 70 percent protein and retains
most of the bean's dietary fiber. Often referred to simply as
textured soy protein, textured soy flour is sold dried in granular
and chunk style. It can be found in natural food stores and through
mail-order catalogs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Soy sauce is a dark brown liquid made from soybeans that have
undergone a fermenting process. Soy sauces have a salty taste but
are lower in sodium than traditional table salt. Specific types of
soy sauce are shoyu, tamari and teriyaki. Shoyu is a blend of
soybeans and wheat. Tamari is made only from soybeans and is a
byproduct of making miso. Teriyaki sauce can be thicker than other
types of soy sauce and includes such ingredients as sugar, vinegar
and spices. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Soy yogurt is made from soy milk. Its creamy texture makes it an
easy substitute for sour cream or cream cheese. Soy yogurt can be
found in a variety of flavors in natural foods stores. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whole soy beans
</P>
<P>
   As soybeans mature in the pod, they ripen into a hard, dry bean.
They're a bit more firm than most other beans but can substitute
for most beans in recipes. They're an excellent source of protein
and fiber. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy beverages
</P>
<P>
   This is the liquid extracted from soybeans, which is usually
fortified with calcium and makes a great, nutty-flavor substitute
for cow's milk. It's also good for camping or keeping on hand,
because it's generally sold in aseptic containers that can keep in
your pantry for months. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy nut butter
</P>
<P>
   Made from roasted, whole soy nuts, which are then crushed and
blended with soy oil and other ingredients, soy nut butter has a
slightly nutty taste, significantly less fat than peanut butter and
provides many other nutritional benefits as well. Soy nut butter
can be found in a few supermarkets or through mail-order
companies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy nuts
</P>
<P>
   Roasted soy nuts are whole soybeans that have been soaked in
water and then baked until browned. Soy nuts can be found in a
variety of flavors, including chocolate-covered. High in protein
and isoflavones, soy nuts are similar in texture and flavor to
peanuts. You can find roasted soy nuts in natural food stores and
through mail-order catalogs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Soy sprouts
</P>
<P>
   Although not as popular as mung bean or alfalfa sprouts, soy
sprouts (also called soybean sprouts), are an excellent source of
nutrition, packed with protein and vitamin C. They can be sprouted
in the same manner as other beans and seeds. Soy sprouts must be
cooked quickly at low heat so they don't get mushy. They can be
used raw in salads or soups, or in stir-fried, sauteed or baked
dishes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tempeh
</P>
<P>
   This traditional Indonesian food is a chunky, tender soybean
cake. Wholesoybeans, sometimes mixed with another grain such as
rice or millet, are fermented into a rich cake of soybeans with a
smoky or nutty flavor. Tempeh can be marinated and grilled and
added to soups, casseroles or chili. Found in Asian food stores. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tofu products
</P>
<P>
   Tofu, also known as soybean curd, is a soft cheeselike food made
by curdling fresh hot soy milk with a coagulant. Tofu is a bland
product that easily absorbs the flavors of other ingredients with
which it is cooked. Tofu is rich in high-quality protein and B
vitamins and low in sodium. Firm tofu is dense and solid and can be
cubed and served in soups, stir-fried or grilled. Firm tofu is
higher in protein, fat and calcium than other forms of tofu. Soft
tofu is good for recipes that call for blended tofu. Silken tofu is
a creamy product and can be used as a replacement for sour cream in
many dip recipes. Several types of tofu can be found in
supermarkets and natural health food stores. Tofu is also available
as a powder. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1451EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7431 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOFU-AZR &LR;      07-09 1588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOFU-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH BENEFITS SPROUT FROM MIGHTY BEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (WITH TOFU LIST)  
 BY STEFANIE L. PEARSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Ponce de Leon needed a better map.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Fountain of Youth. He should have been looking for
the (begin ital) field (endital) _ that is a field filled with
soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to praise a bean, but this is one mighty bean.
</P>
<P>
   Research shows that not only can it lower fat and cholesterol in
diets by pinch-hitting for numerous items heavy in animal fats, but
soy can play a preventive role in the fight against several
cancers, including breast, colon and prostate. Soy also has been
found to help soften the unpleasant symptoms of menopause.
</P>
<P>
   The key, says Patricia Greenberg, author of ``The Whole Soy
Cookbook,'' is a tiny compound in soy called genistein.
</P>
<P>
   Genistein is an isoflavone, a compound that is genetically
similar to the human hormone estrogen. It's known as a
phytoestrogen, which means that it is a plant compound similar to
estrogen.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, a nutritionist who is a graduate of the Scottsdale
Culinary Institute, says soy is the closest thing to a ``perfect
food'' that nature offers.
</P>
<P>
   Soy foods differ somewhat in their concentration of isoflavones,
but all of the traditional soy foods _ tofu, soy milk, tempeh and
miso _ are rich sources of isoflavones, providing about 30 to 40
milligrams per serving.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 300 plants that are sources of
phytoestrogens, including such mundane veggies as carrots, corn,
apples, barley and oats. Soy has received the most attention
because it has a much more intense concentration of the chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers long have noted that many Asian countries, which
tend to consume diets high in soy foods, have lower rates of
breast, prostate and colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Those countries' diets also tend to be lower in fat and
cholesterol and higher in fiber than Western diets. Low-fat,
high-fiber diets are linked to lower rates of cancer and heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Tofu goddess Greenberg just smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Adding just 25 grams of soy protein to your daily diet taps into
genistein's protective powers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   People who consume that soy protein will be more likely to lower
their intake of other proteins that tend to be higher in fat and
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg's book includes dozens of recipes using soy foods and
offers sample daily menus that provide at least 25 grams of soy
protein.
</P>
<P>
   Many people know soy is great for them, but don't know how to
introduce it into their diets.
</P>
<P>
   Are they stuck eating blob after blob of tasteless tofu?
</P>
<P>
   Nope.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of ways to get that soy protein into your diet,
from raw soybean pods lightly steamed to highly processed soy
protein turned into hot dogs and hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   Soy meat substitutes tend to absorb the flavor of whatever
they're cooked in. By contrast, meat itself puts out distinctive
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Most palates can't necessarily tell the difference between
flavors of spices and flavors of meat. Greenberg once made a
vegetarian gumbo for a group of people who don't eat shellfish.
</P>
<P>
   They insisted they tasted the fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were tasting the saffron in the stock,'' she explained.
``They were tasting the flavor they were used to in the stock,
which they associated with fish.''
</P>
<P>
   This means chefs can simply marinate, season, sauce or spice
their way to a flavorful dish.
</P>
<P>
   The key is remembering that your soy product will play second
fiddle to your sauce.
</P>
<P>
   More processed products _ tofu hot dogs, for instance, or
pre-spiced soy cheese _ have less of a need to be spiced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PASTA WITH CREAM SAUCE AND MUSHROOMS &QL; 
(From the Indiana Soybean Board)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 382 calories, 18 g fat, 44 g
carbohydrates, 444 mg sodium, 42 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3 cups soy milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh vegetables, cut into small pieces (such as
broccoli, mushrooms, cauliflower, zucchini)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pasta, cooked
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan, heat the olive oil over low heat. Add the
onion and garlic, and saute until tender. Add the oregano, thyme
and rosemary, and saute a few minutes more. Add the wine and bring
to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Add the soy milk, margarine, salt, pepper and bay leaf. Return
the mixture to a boil, stirring occasionally until the margarine
melts. Add the flour a tablespoon at a time, whisking after each
addition to avoid lumps. Stir until the mixture thickens, about 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place the vegetables in a steamer or metal sieve over boiling
water and steam until just tender. To serve, toss the vegetables
with the freshly cooked pasta. Remove the bay leaf from the sauce,
then pour the sauce over the pasta and vegetables, and toss to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SPINACH SALAD WITH WARM SOY BACON DRESSING &QL; 
(From ``The Whole Soy Cookbook``)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 139 calories, 3 g fat, 10 g
carbohydrates, 403 mg sodium, 20 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Salad:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces soy bacon strips
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soybean oil
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce package of cleaned spinach leaves (about 6 cups loosely
packed)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, sliced thinly
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Dressing:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soy milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cornstarch dissolved in 2 tablespoons of water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Fry the soy bacon in soybean oil 1 minute on each side until
crisp, and set aside. Dice when cool.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the spinach leaves, mushrooms and red onion onto 6 large
plates and chill or place in a cool area of the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a small sauce pan on medium high heat, and saute
the onion until translucent, about 5 minutes. Add vinegar, soy milk
and sugar, bring to a boil, and reduce heat to low.
</P>
<P>
   Add cornstarch, stirring as mixture thickens slightly. Add the
diced bacon. Let cool slightly and season with salt and pepper.
Pour the warm dressing over salad greens.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
APPLESAUCE CAKE &QL; 
(From ``The Soyfoods Cookbook``)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 240 calories, 8 g fat, 42 g
carbohydrates, 291 mg sodium, 27 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 3/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups unbleached flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup soy flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cups applesauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soft tofu
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raisins, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a large bowl, combine the sugar,
unbleached flour, soy flour, baking soda, salt, cinnamon, cloves,
allspice, nutmeg and baking powder; mix thoroughly. Add the
applesauce and vegetable oil; mix well, then beat about 300
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mash the tofu until creamy; add to the batter.
Beat the batter about 300 strokes. Fold the raisins into the
batter. Pour the batter into a 9- by 13-inch non-stick baking pan.
Bake for 40 to 45 minutes. Cool before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 18 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ARROZ CON TEMPEH &QL; 
(From ``The Whole Soy Cookbook'')
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 663 calories, 18 g fat, 0 mg
cholesterol, 93 g carbohydrates, 39 mg sodium, 24 percent calories
from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds tempeh, cut into strips
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 small green bell pepper, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 small red bell pepper, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 cups vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon saffron
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups long-grain rice
</P>
<P>
   10-ounce package frozen peas
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large saucepan over high heat and saute the
tempeh, onion and bell peppers until the tempeh is slightly
browned, about 8 minutes. Add the garlic and cook for 1 more
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Add the stock, saffron and cayenne, mixing well. Bring the
mixture to a boil and stir in the rice. Reduce heat to low, cover,
and cook for 20 minutes. Stir in the peas and cook 5 minutes more,
until the peas are thoroughly heated. Add salt and pepper to taste.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE SOY BROWNIES &QL; 
(From ``The Whole Soy Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 113 calories, 2 g fat, 0 mg
cholesterol, 22 g carbohydrates, 110 mg sodium, 16 percent calories
from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 1/2 cups unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces plain soy yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup non-fat soy milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees and grease an 8- by 8-inch square
pan, or line it with parchment paper. In a large bowl combine
flour, baking soda, sugar and cocoa, and set aside. In a food
processor or blender, mix the yogurt, soy milk, oil and vanilla
until smooth. Pour the yogurt mixture into the dry ingredients,
stirring until well combined. Pour the batter into the greased pan
and bake for 25 minutes, or until the brownies spring back when
lightly touched.
</P>
<P>
   Cool brownies to room temperature before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
