<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETRO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC SETS MOOD FOR TRIP THROUGH TIME 
</HEADLINE>
 MUSIC-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (WITH RETRO)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - There's more to living retro than just buying
clothes, Daddy-O. Like, for instance, what you're going to pop on
the hi-fi as you prance around your rumpus room in pedal pushers or
a poodle skirt and crinoline.
</P>
<P>
   That's right: Living retro means listening retro. So, goodbye
Pearl Jam. Hello, Pearl Bailey. Here's some backward-looking discs
that any vintage vixen would enjoy. And while these titles probably
would be best-enjoyed on vinyl, we'll cheat a little bit since it's
the digital age:  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Swing set &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Capitol Recordings'': Louis Prima, Keely Smith and Sam
Butera: It's a whopping eight-disc set, but it's also everything
that Vegas' hottest combo recorded for the Capitol label during
their heyday in the '50s. Downside: ``That Old Black Magic'' is
gonna burn a hole in your budget since this thing's price tag runs
well into triple-digit figures.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Glenn Miller: The Popular Recordings'': Sixty songs,
including ``Moonlight Serenade,`` ``Pennsylvania 6-5000'' and
``Perfidia.'' At his best, Miller was hotter than a Julie London
album cover. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Exotica_ &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The ``ExotiLLLLLLLLLof Martin Denny'': It's two discs of
Hawaiian-flavored tunes from the tiki master himself, Mr. Denny. If
the Jungle Ride is your favorite Disneyland attraction, this will
keep you amused for hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Space-Age Bachelor Pad Music,'' Esquivel: The ``Thriller''
of exotica albums, the release of this disc in 1994 marked a
small-scale revival for the wildly dissonant ramblings of the
Mexican composer and arranger. I bet Connie Francis never imagined
``Who's Sorry Now'' sounding like this.
</P>
<P>
   Easy listening &QL; 
 &QL; 
_ ``Once Upon a Time/Blue Smoke,'' Johnny Desmond: Everybody knows
about Sinatra, Bennett and Damone. But Desmond, who died in 1985,
is perhaps the one that got away. The one-time Glenn Miller singer
had a silky, masculine style, and this brilliant reissue combines
two of his classic albums onto one unforgettable disc. ``Once Upon
a Time'' features tunes he originally recorded with Miller; ``Blue
Smoke'' is a somber after-hours collection. One listen and you'll
find out why fans dubbed him the ``Creamer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It's Magic,'' ``Secret Love,'' ``Que Sera Sera,'' ``Move
Over Darling,'' Doris Day: It may sound like overkill, but the guys
at Bear Family Records have reissued (begin ital) everything
(endital) the divine Miss Day put on wax between 1947 and 1968 in
these four box sets. There's obviously some filler here, but there
are also plenty of examples of why so many people consider Day one
of the finest singers of the 20th century. On the other hand, fluff
like ``Que Sera Sera'' also will remind you why so many other
people completely dismiss her talents as a singer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
