<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7438 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRETRO09-AZR &LR;      07-09 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRETRO09-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING IN YESTER-DAZE CAN BE WHOLE LOT OF FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (ART ADV. Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients)  
 By JAYE BEELER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - From her sleek, chin-length bob to the hem of her
gabardine 1940s pantsuit, Brandi Kvetko is a vision of vintage.
</P>
<P>
   She is a collector and fan of all things vintage _ items at
least 25 years old. Luckily for Kvetko, her husband, Chris
Swanberg, is a devoted player in this ``Ozzie and Harriet''
re-enactment.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the couple turned their passion into a career when
they opened Go-Kat-Go, a vintage department store now in Glendale,
Ariz. The resale store has an amazing assortment of furniture,
appliances, clothes and even beauty products from the 1940s through
the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with this stuff,'' Kvetko says. ``Even when I was
little, we had vintage stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents, Bo and Barb Kvetko, own Bo's Funky Stuff down the
road. They carry zany furniture and collectibles from 1890 to 1970,
such as an amoeba-shaped, pop-up bar coffee table, mechanical
oversized camel and 1960s dryer that chimes out &UR; ``How Dry I Am'' at
the end of the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The subculture of vintage aficionados is distinct as an Eames
lounge chair. You (beginital) do (endital) know what that is _
right?
</P>
<P>
   These people spend most of their waking hours living in
yester-decade. They crave clothing, furniture, restaurants, lounges
and even neon signs manufactured at least two decades ago. And the
hunt for nostalgia fulfills that longing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing interesting in the '90s,'' says Amy Bowling,
26, who caught the vintage fever five years ago when she began
wearing vintage clothes exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage clothing always has been popular with teenagers, who
could scarcely afford anything else. But when swing music cruised
into nightclubs, the dance scene rocked into vintage shops.
</P>
<P>
   The lounge core movement arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of happened,'' says Bowling, who works part time at an
antiques mall and runs a booth and display case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started wearing the vintage clothes. Then I bought a piece
of furniture. I started taking dance lessons and seeing rockabilly
bands.
</P>
<P>
   oon I was hanging out with people who had hot rods.''
</P>
<P>
   She's decorating her apartment with 1960s Danish Modern
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Kvetko and Swanberg, who took the plunge into vintage years ago,
furnished their 1947 bungalow with stuff from the '40s, '50s and
'60s.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical-print wallpaper is the backdrop for a 1940s rattan
couch and rattan bar.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen is a sea of turquoise, from the '60s Whirlpool
washer and dryer to the '60s General Electric stove to the salvaged
and restored kitchen counter tops. The color scheme extends to the
appliances, such as the blender, ice crusher and hand mixer, as
well as the canister set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy, but it's us,'' Kvetko laughs.
</P>
<P>
   For hard-core vintage fanatics, the Phoenix area's street scene
is limited. They lean toward restaurants and lounges that never
lost their style, such as the New Yorker coffee shop and the Copper
Queen Cocktail Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   For Bowling, the Copper Queen in Phoenix is classic vintage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's untouched,'' Bowling says. ``It's not trying to be a
lounge. It (begin ital) is (endital) a lounge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been overtaken by people. This older couple does a
lounge act that is so hysterical. They are hilarious.''
</P>
<P>
   More Phoenix area nightclubs are catering to the retro
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The pompadours and Billy Betties (women who love retro and
rockabilly) rule on Tuesdays at the Rhythm Room and Thursdays at
the Melody Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months ago, the Rhythm Room ushered in its Roots Tuesday,
which spotlights rockabilly, swing, surf and lounge bands.
Rockabilly mixes old rock and roll with the twang of country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a specialized music, but it has a serious following,''
says Bob Corritore, who runs the Phoenix blues nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Pingleton and Brian Marsland rarely bother with the
Phoenix retro scene. They want authenticity. They often dine at the
s Kon Tiki, a Polynesian seafood restaurant, in Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the few remaining Polynesian restaurants in the
country,'' says Marsland, a 28-year-old Tempe, Ariz., artist.
``We're always going on road trips to specific places we've heard
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Pingleton and Marsland are taken with all things tiki, those
small sculptured Polynesian figures.
</P>
<P>
   At Pingleton's apartment, beads hang from the door of her tiki
room. Hundreds of tikis stare from bookshelves, windowsills, the
rattan bar, black-velvet pictures and desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the tiki room, you feel good,'' says Pingleton, a
30-year-old dietitian. ``You're smiling. You're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Pingleton and Marsland are dating the vintage way. At the
end of the evening, they go to their separate apartments. There was
no shacking up in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   The couple shares fond memories of vintage goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandparents' house was a fun place to be,'' Marsland says.
``It was a clean, minimalist decor. I have a lot of positive
associations with this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Their apartments are in the same apartment complex and are
painted in shocking pink and turquoise, a color scheme reminiscent
of a 1930s Miami Beach hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Their vintage furniture is perfect in this get-up. Pingleton's
long, curvy sofa shares space with a pair of hoop chairs and
amoeba-shaped coffee table. Marsland's chrome dining room set is
glossy and sleek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always looking,'' Marsland says. ``We're always
upgrading.''
</P>
<P>
   They can't explain their longing for old things, but they know
it exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that you saw as a little kid,'' Marsland says.
``Maybe you caught a flash at your grandparents' house. But it was
up on a shelf, and you couldn't touch it. Now you can finally
touch.''  &QL; 
Jaye Beeler can be reached at jaye.beeler(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
