<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILKINS ENJOYS WORKING VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Francis G. Power Gym boasts old-fashioned
bleachers, a wooden scorer's table, no air conditioning _ and the
best basketball in New England right now. It may be thus for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of Celtics and other NBA players and wannabes converge
on Boston College during the week to get their picks and rolls in
during what appears to be a long, hot, management-free summer. The
NBA has locked out its players, meaning Walter McCarty, Dominique
Wilkins, Dana Barros, and others must get their hoop kicks in the
Beantown Basketball League, now in its third year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the league was a pleasant diversion and supplement
for the NBA players. Under normal circumstances, the Celtics would
be getting ready for rookie camp this week and a summer league
appearance with a few veterans and a lot of hopefuls. The players
would be visiting Brandeis daily to get in their work.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it is quite different. Brandeis might as well be in
Paraguay. And the Beantown Basketball League is the only game in
town. There are refs, coaches, a public address announcer and, most
of all, a game. A lot of games. The league started June 18 and runs
through the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   For the 38-year-old Wilkins, the league is just what he wants
and needs as he prepares for yet another season and, hopefully, a
spot on an NBA team. He said his weight is down to 220 after a
season in Italy and he is chilling out in Dover, an adopted New
Englander. Wednesday night, he was manning the middle against
McCarty, both pros depending on the collegians and ex-collegians to
make the plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This keeps me in shape,'' said Wilkins, who looks terrific. He
has been using a personal trainer for the last three years and says
it has made a big difference. ``It's hot in here, it helps keeps
the pounds off, and it gives me a chance to play with the younger
guys,'' he said. ``I can work on a few things. It's perfect for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have been playing in Chicago this week and off to Monte
Carlo, Rome, and Athens after that. USA Basketball had called his
agent and inquired if Wilkins would want to try out for the United
States team for the World Championships. Wilkins was flattered but
could not see himself doing so while his former, and possibly
future, teammates were being locked out and the original 12-man NBA
team decided not to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with a lot of those guys over the years, and I
couldn't do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins was considered because he had no NBA affiliation last
season. He played in Italy after spending the year before with the
Tim Duncan-less, David Robinson-less San Antonio Spurs. He still
wears his Spurs warmup shirt. His Italian team in Bologna did well,
but lost in the playoffs in the fifth and final game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have won the series easily,'' he said, ``but I
chipped a bone in my (right) elbow during the playoffs. Other than
that, I feel as good now as I ever did. I'll tell you this: I know
some teams could have used some scoring in the playoffs. You think
Utah couldn't have got something more out of the small forward
position? But I knew Chicago would win. They know what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italian experience was markedly different from his previous
European foray, with Panathinaikos. That disastrous season ended up
with lots of litigation amid charges of breach of contract on both
sides. Wilkins also had some tough personal misfortune that season
as well and had to make some unscheduled trips back to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   There was none of that in Bologna. He and David Rivers were an
excellent 1-2 scoring punch and there was also Carlton Myers.
``They call him the Michael Jordan of Europe,'' Wilkins said,
rolling his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just wasn't the same pressure in Italy that there was in
Greece,'' he went on. ``People were nicer. You could relax and just
play. I still don't think the Europeans really understand the game
yet. They look at the scoring as if that's all there is. They don't
look at rebounds, assists, things like that. When they do that,
they'll understand the game more. And the competition is getting
better each year.''
</P>
<P>
   It has come to that. One of the greatest scorers of our time _
someone whose identity and legacy are forever entwined in point
production _ is worried that the fans in Europe aren't versed to
the finer things. It was hot in the gym Wednesday night, but not
that hot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
