<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS09-TAKE     07-09 1826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS09-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q. I understand that the Federal Reserve sets interest rates,
which in turn affects unemployment. By what authority does ``the
Fed'' exist? Who makes its policies?
</P>
<P>
   A. More than unemployment is involved. The Federal Reserve
encourages the nation's economic growth and controls inflation by
influencing interest rates, as you say, and thus the availability
of money and loans. It also performs many financial services for
the federal government and provides numerous services in its role
as central bank of the United States, to commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is an independent government agency. Its policies are
directed by two main committees, the Board of Governors and the
Federal Open Market Committee. The board has seven members,
appointed to 14-year terms by the President, subject to the consent
of the U.S. Senate. The committee, which makes the main decisions
on Fed monetary policies, consists of the Fed governors; the
president of the New York City Federal Reserve Bank; and the
presidents of four other Federal Reserve Banks (there are 12
nationwide).
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is formic acid? I recently read that an interstate
highway ramp was closed for five hours recently when that type acid
spilled from a truck. I've never heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   A. Here's the dictionary definition: ``a colorless, irritating,
fuming, water-soluble liquid . . . CH 2 O 2 (or HCOOH) . . . used
in dyeing and tanning and in medicine.'' Our definition:
``something that stings and irritates like you wouldn't believe.''
</P>
<P>
   If you know where the word ``formic'' comes from, you'll
understand why firefighters donned masks, gloves and heavy garb,
and closed the ramp for five hours, when the stuff spilled from
that truck at Old National Highway and I-75 in Clayton County.
Think of how a teeny, tiny ant can sting you if it chooses. Ants
belong to the family Formicidae. If the formic acid produced by an
ant can, in almost microscopic amounts, create a painful experience
in humans, what could the synthetic version in concentrated amounts
do?
</P>
<P>
   Q. The governor of Georgia and Sony Music are involved in a
program to give parents of newborn babies in Georgia a CD or tape
of various classical music selections. It is believed that an
infant hearing such music will have a positive intellectual
response. How can people who aren't parents of newborns in Georgia
obtain the CDs or tapes?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Build Your Baby's Brain Through the Power of Music!'' can
be ordered by calling Sony Music Special Products, 1-800-356-1052.
The cost is $9.98 for a CD, $5.98 for a cassette tape, plus sales
tax and $3.95 for shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Old and new gospel hymns speak of Beulah land. The word
Beulah is not in the Bible and I can't find a reference anywhere to
Beulah land. Can you explain what it means?
</P>
<P>
   A: Before we answer, let's start the song going in everyone's
mind by repeating the refrain from C. Austin Miles' ``Dwelling in
Beulah Land'' (and don't forget to clap your hands):
</P>
<P>
   I'm living on the mountain, underneath a cloudless sky,/
</P>
<P>
   I'm drinking at the fountain that shall never run dry;/
</P>
<P>
   O yes! I'm feasting on the manna from a bountiful supply,/
</P>
<P>
   For I'm dwelling in Beulah Land.
</P>
<P>
   Beulah's origin is in the Bible (the book of the Prophet Isaiah
62:4), where it refers to ``your land Beulah,'' meaning the new
Jerusalem _ a place, neither heaven nor Earth, that enjoys God's
loving benevolence.
</P>
<P>
   A more immediate source for contemporary usage may be ``The
Pilgrim's Progress,'' by John Bunyan, the religious allegory first
published in 1678. In it, Christian, the hero, arrives at last in
the land or country of Beulah on the border of the Celestial City
(heaven). Bunyan describes this land as a garden of perfect harmony
between nature and man, who, finally understanding God's plan,
rests from the arduous journey before confronting the final
challenge: crossing the river of death to eternal salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please explain the concept of the dew point. What is it? How
is it related to relative humidity, temperature and dew?
</P>
<P>
   A: The dew point is the temperature at which moisture in the air
begins to condense. The dew point is either lower than the air
temperature, or the same as the air temperature when the relative
humidity is 100 percent. The difference between air and dew point
temperatures, popularly called the ``spread,'' is especially useful
to people in aviation, because it helps anticipate fog. However, it
has little bearing on precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   Dew forms when a thin film of air, in contact with the surface,
is cooled to below the dew point _ the point at which it cannot
hold all its water vapor. If the air temperature and dew point are
below freezing, frost may form on the surface, or ice crystals may
form in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the term ``crackers'' in referring to
poor white Southerners?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are various explanations of how ``cracker'' acquired
the meaning of ``a low-down Southern white man,'' in the words of
H.L. Mencken, who added that such people ``were especially numerous
in Georgia.'' According to the Dictionary of Word and Phrase
Origins, the one that seems soundest traces to the verb ``crack,''
as in the expression ``he's not what he's cracked up to be,''
meaning that the person doesn't live up to his own boastful opinion
of himself. The Dictionary of American Regional English defines the
word, in this sense, as ``a backwoodsman, rustic, countrified
person,'' and also traces it to cracker or corn-cracker, the
probable original form of the word, meaning a ``braggart.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible origin is from the cracking of a whip, since
North Florida and South Georgia at one time were the site of large
ranches, but this wouldn't have any negative connotation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Back in the spring, I read that film director James Cameron
would release a longer version of ``Titanic.'' When will this come
out?
</P>
<P>
   A: Don't start popping corn quite yet. While Cameron has said he
``eventually'' will put together a special edition of the movie,
which could include as much as 20 minutes of scenes edited from the
first version, he has yet to start working on it. In an interview
in June, he said it would be released ``anywhere from one to five
years from now,'' although he added that he would like to start
putting it together ``while it is still fresh in our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you compare the relative burn of calories by walking and
running?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are lots of variables involved, such as the person's
weight, the length of stride, grade of terrain, degree of vigor
expended while walking or running, even heat and humidity, so these
numbers, provided by the American Council on Exercise and the book
``The New Fit or Fat,'' are only guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   An ``average'' person (for statistical reckoning, let's assume
it's a 160-pound man) waliing will burn 8.7 calories a minute, or
261 calories for half an hour. That same man jogging will burn
about 12.4 calories a minute, or 372 calories during 30 minutes. If
that same man picks up the pace and runs, his caloric burn will be
15.1 calories a minute, or 453 calories for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers would be skewed a bit if a person measures the
caloric burn by distance _ a mile, for example _ instead of the
amount of time. ACE says our average man will walk a mile in about
15 minutes; burning 8.7 calories a minute, his total burn will be
130.5 calories. That same person will run a mile in about 7 1/2
minutes, ACE says; at 15.1 calories a minute burned while running,
that totals 113.25.
</P>
<P>
   Jogging, by the way, is just ``slow running,'' said ACE's Rachel
Narsh. She said the average jogger would burn 372 calories in 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article said air carriers have been given permission to
resume charter flights between the United States and Cuba. Does
that mean the embargo for tourists has been lifted?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Nothing has changed in connection with the sanctions
against general tourist travel to Cuba, said Hamilton Dix of the
Treasury Department. Long-standing U.S. regulations applying to the
spending of U.S. currency on travel to Cuba are intended to limit
the flow of hard currency into that country. Only those U.S.
citizens who meet certain restrictions _ such as U.S. government
travelers on official business, including representatives of
international organizations of which the United States is a member;
journalists; and family visitors traveling once a year due to
extreme humanitarian need _ are permitted to fly on the direct
charters. And the eligibility of those people will be verified by
the Treasury Department at least 48 to 72 hours in advance of
travel.
</P>
<P>
   The restricted direct flights to Cuba, which were begun in 1977,
were suspended in 1996 by President Clinton as part of a series of
measures to punish the Cuban government for shooting down two
planes over international waters. Three U.S. citizens were killed.
</P>
<P>
   American tourists determined to visit Cuba, by the way, can fly
there via another country, such as Mexico, the Bahamas or Canada.
But Beth Weaver of the Treasury Department says if Americans go to
Cuba without a specific license, and spend money there, ``which
they certainly would do,'' they would be breaking the law. They
could be investigated when they come back into the United States,
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Thomas Harris wrote ``Silence of the Lambs'' 10 years ago.
The subsequent movie garnered several Oscars. Fans have eagerly
awaited his sequel, but a decade has passed and we're still
waiting. What has happened to Harris?
</P>
<P>
   A: Harris is said to have been working on the sequel for more
than five years, but no one _ not Anne Sibbald, his literary agent;
not his publisher; not even his family _ has yet to see a word.
``It will arrive when it arrives,'' Sibbald told a British
newspaper last December.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, creator of psychiatrist and psychopath Dr. Hannibal
Lecter, is not exactly prolific. His first book, ``Black Sunday,''
a non-Lecter thriller, was published in 1973. ``Red Dragon,'' the
tense thriller that introduced Lecter, became an instant bestseller
when published in 1981. Fans had to wait another seven years before
Lecter reappeared in ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' which was made
into the hugely popular 1991 film of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   At last report, the divorced Harris, who has a daughter, was
living in seclusion with Pace Barnes, a former publishing house
editor, and they were dividing their time between Miami and Long
Island's Sag Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
