<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON EXHIBITS PRUDENCE IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ President Clinton and his officials are speaking softly
and keeping America's big stick in the closet in Kosovo, the latest
flash point of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis by U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke, who earned
his spurs as a tough-talking mediator in Bosnia three years ago, is
all on persuasive diplomacy in attempting to bring together Serb
ruler Slobodan Milosevic and the independence-minded Albanian
population of the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said this week there is no sense in threatening to
rain bombs on the Serbs because ``further violence by anyone won't
solve anything.'' What he meant was that such a threat would be a
bluff and Milosevic would know it. The 15-nation European Union has
called for bombing and, at one time, seemed to have Washington's
support. But no more.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's policymakers have realized that military action over
Kosovo would open up many dangerous possibilities, including a
renewal of war elsewhere in the former Yugoslavia, and would not be
worthwhile, least of all for the ethnic Albanians there. Without
the United States in their corner, the EU countries will do
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the six-nation contact group (the United States,
Britain, France, Italy, Germany and Russia) that handles relations
with the countries of the former Yugoslavia urged immediate
negotiations between the Serbian regime and the Kosovo Albanians,
although Milosevic is unlikely to comply quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The situation differs greatly from the uproar over Iraq's
refusal to cooperate with U.N. weapons inspectors early this year.
Then Clinton was doing the blustering, and most of America's allies
told him to cool it, as he eventually did. The Iraqi episode
appears to have taught the U.S. administration that waving Theodore
Roosevelt's famous ``big stick'' isn't invariably the solution to
complex foreign policy issues even when unsavory bullies like
Saddam Hussein and Milosevic are the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   General approval existed for intervening in Bosnia because it
was a sovereign state and its survival was threatened not only by
rebels but outsiders from Serbia and Croatia. Furthermore, after
four years of war, all sides were exhausted by the fighting and
looking for a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is different. It is a province of Serbia, and military
intervention, even to protect the Albanians, would from any
perspective be an undeniable violation of international law.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo's Albanians indisputably nurse serious political and
cultural grievances. However, Americans might ponder how they would
react if a group of militant Mexican Americans demanded
independence for the American Southwest or sought its reabsorption
by their ethnic brethren south of the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government, with massive popular support, would
certainly resist such a step and reject outside efforts favoring
it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, some might argue that the legal case for the Southwest's
autonomy or outright secession is stronger than that of the Kosovo
Albanians. Most of the U.S. Southwest was acquired in the Mexican
War only 150 years ago. Kosovo has been part of Serbia for seven
centuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
