<P>
   FRENCH-ART-REVIEW (Washington) _ Art exhibitions that resemble
art history seminars often do so at their peril. Full of wordy text
panels, such shows can swamp the viewer with extraneous information
or make interesting points that one would rather encounter in book
form, sitting down. But every pitfall has escapees carefully
skirting its brink. Curators are becoming increasingly skilled at
mixing and matching artworks and ancillary material to conjure up
the times, places and personalities that produced those artworks.
There are growing numbers of shows in which words and pictures
share the wall to mutually illuminating effect, so that looking and
reading become one, or close to it. A rewarding example is ``Manet,
Monet and the Gare St.-Lazare,'' a small beautiful show that moved
to the National Gallery of Art here after appearing at the Musee
d'Orsay in Paris. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-MANS-TIME (Undated) _ The thing of it is not so much that
thanks to my neighbor, Howard Tedoff, we ended up flying to Bar
Harbor, Maine, just to eat some lobster rolls on a recent Saturday,
but that we got to experience what I think of as rich man's time.
By Michael T. Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   BERSTEIN-MUSICIAN (New York) _ Whenever Leonard Bernstein had to
list his profession on some official form, like his income tax
returns, he did not write composer, conductor, pianist or any other
limiting term. He called himself a musician. He liked the word's
embracing quality and venerable history. In earlier eras, all
professional musicians were composers as well as performers, not to
mention teachers, proselytizers, organizers and whatever else it
took to keep the tradition going. Yet in evaluating Bernstein,
people still look at his accomplishments separately. By Anthony
Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TURANDOT (Beijing) _ A $15 million international
production of the opera ``Turandot'' will be mounted in September
in Beijing's Forbidden City. By Erick Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
