<HEADLINE>
LAWYER HAS TOUGH JOB IN FINDING JURY FOR SENSATIONAL MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROGER CROTEAU  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS _ The lawyer for a former Air Force Academy cadet
accused of murdering a teen-age girl to appease his ex-fiancee says
he faces no easy task in finding an unbiased jury.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Dan Cogdell said ``every newspaper has convicted my
client on Page One,'' a reference to the intense publicity the case
has had in Texas and around the nation since the 1995 slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, state District Judge Don Leonard questioned
potential jurors at the Comal County Courthouse about what they
have seen and heard regarding the murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection continued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, now 20, is accused of killing a 16-year-old Mansfield,
Texas, girl in 1995 at the request of his then-fiancee. The
ex-fiancee, Diane Zamora, also 20, was convicted of murder in
February and is serving a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in his black suit, Graham took notes Wednesday as
Leonard questioned the potential jurors, listening to the answers
and talking in low tones with lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The love story involving clean-cut high school sweethearts that
prosecutors claim led to a rival's murder reads like a play and has
attracted a crush of national media coverage. Finding jurors who
haven't already made up their minds is difficult, even though the
trial was moved to New Braunfels from Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Most members of the jury pool have at least a little knowledge
about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said he would not automatically rule out anyone who
thought his client was guilty; the question is whether potential
jurors can keep an open mind.
</P>
<P>
   Determining that can be difficult. ``I'm afraid of the ones who
say `I saw the TV movie and read the book ... but I don't have an
opinion,''' he said. ``Those are the ones who scare me.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he looks for strength of character in jurors and the
ability to stand up and make an unpopular decision.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Mike Parrish said he wanted jurors who are
intelligent and fair.
</P>
<P>
   While finding a truly unbiased jury is difficult in high-profile
cases, it can be done, said University of Texas law Professor Lucas
Powe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of Texas is capable of finding 12 people in the
county who have not heard of him,'' he said. ``They found 12 people
in Miami who had never heard of Daniel Noriega. They found 12
people in Washington, D.C., who had never heard of Oliver North and
I believe they even found 12 people in Los Angeles who had never
heard of O.J. Simpson.''
</P>
<P>
   But is a juror who pays so little attention to the world around
him a good juror?
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct is no, but in fact we've gone toward a theory in
this country that we want ignorant jurors and the best way to do
that is to find ignorant people,'' Powe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
