<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7534 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BERRY-NAT     07-09 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BERRY-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      COLLINS MAKES CASE FOR TIGHTER BERRY INSPECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Kyra Leasure  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 9 -- Following the outbreaks of food poisoning
in 1996 and 1997 from Guatemalan raspberries, including five
reported cases in Maine, Sen. Susan M. Collins Thursday called for
the federal government to adopt stricter inspection controls of
imported food.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, R-Maine, led the second out of four hearings that are
scheduled to address the safety of food imports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The escalation in the number of foodborne illnesses at a time
when food imports are soaring prompted the Subcommittee to focus
its investigation on the safety of imported fruit and vegetables,''
said Collins, who chairs the Permanent Subcommittee on
Investigations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, at least 1,465 people nationally suffered
Cyclosporiasis, a form of food poisoning that causes nausea,
diarrhea, fatigue and weight loss. Another outbreak occurred in
1997, when another 1,000 people suffered from the poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration and the Center for Disease
Control and Prevention then worked with the Guatemalan Berry
Commission to improve the practices for growing and handling
raspberries in Guatemala. The Commission voluntarily improved water
quality, what is believed to be the source of contamination, and
sanitary conditions and established a system in which only the
safest farms are permitted to export their berries to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Collins and other lawmakers complained that the U.S.
government does not do enough of its own inspections of imported
foods -- which a recent General Accounting Office report noted that
Americans are increasing their consumption of, especially produce.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, 24 percent of fruit consumed by Americans was imported;
in 1995 that number had increased to 33 percent. Of all this fruit,
however, less than 2 percent was inspected by the FDA before it
made its way to supermarkets, according to Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're headed in the wrong direction,'' said Levin.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, as part of his food safety initiative, has
proposed providing the FDA with authority to force other nations to
impose U.S. health standards on their farmers before food can be
exported to the United States. He has also proposed increasing
funding to enhance inspections by FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the new steps for Guatemalan berry production, there was
another outbreak of Cyclospora in Canada just three weeks ago,
which some inspectors believe was caused by raspberries imported
from Central America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that another outbreak occurred despite the
implementation of various control measures suggests either that the
control measures may not have been fully implemented or that the
measures may not have addressed the true source of contamination,''
Dr. Stephen Ostroff, associate director for Epidemiologic Science
at CDC's National Center for Infectious Diseases, told the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country's food safety net must be improved so that
consumers are protected from the risk of unsafe foods, particularly
when contamination is not detectable by the average consumer,''
said Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Once her committee concludes the food safety hearings, Collins
plans to introduce legislation with stricter inspection
regulations, stronger controls over food imports and increased
funding for the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming hearings are scheduled to cover specific fraud and
deceptive techniques used to get food products illegally into the
United States and may present possible remedies for the weaknesses
previously identified.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
