<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH RESERVE CHALLENGED BY FRENCH TEAM AS IT PREPARES FOR
BRAZIL  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAIREFONTAINE, France _ Approximately 300,000 people converged
on the Champs-Elysees in the early hours on Thursday to celebrate
the fact that France was at last in the final of the World Cup.
There were hundreds of thousands more ``supporteurs'' in the
squares of Nantes, Montpellier, Bordeaux and even traditionally
restrained Lyon.
</P>
<P>
   But the team, whose victory over Croatia in the semifinals had
generated all this exuberance, quietly boarded its bus and drove
south for 45 minutes to its country home away from home _ the
national technical center for soccer _ to begin preparing to face
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The French team has trained here in the woods of Clairefontaine
for years and been based here since June 8: two days before the
World Cup began. It is a bucolic, attractive spot, but to hear the
players tell it late Thursday morning, they have just about had
their fill of tranquility, both inside and outside the confines of
their rural retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit disappointing to be here,'' said defender
Marcel Desailly. ``We'd like to be out in the cafes and on the
Champs-Elysees ourselves. It's there where you can really get a
sense of the impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Desailly and his teammates made it clear that their run to the
final is the highlight of their careers. They also made it clear
that they are not getting enough support during their games, and
they were not referring to the record television audience of
approximately 20.5 million in a nation of 58 million that watched
them beat the Croatians. They were referring to the atmosphere
inside the striking, new 80,000-seat Stade de France. Les Bleus
have yet to lose there since it was inaugurated in January, but
they also have yet to sense the passion they see on their
television screens and on the street corners they pass in their bus
en route to and from games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our real fans are outside the stadium,'' said Didier
Deschamps, the French captain. ``It's easy for someone to do the
wave when we score, but we need that support all the time. We need
the same enthusiasm and joy that we can see outside the stadium.
Inside the stadium, there are too many uptight people in suits and
ties. This is not the theater ... If these people are invited by
the sponsors, I have no problem with that. That's part of soccer
these days, but I hope they wake up for the final. I don't want to
hear the samba for 90 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Defender Frank Leboeuf, who will start against Brazil because of
the red card Laurent Blanc received against Croatia, suggested
putting up a sign outside the Stade de France. ``It should read,
`No suits allowed','' Leboeuf said. ``It's an offense to soccer,
which is a sport of the masses. Put on a T-shirt. Paint your face
and start shouting.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reserve goalkeeper Lionel Charbonnier became frustrated enough
in the final minutes of the match to get off the bench and run
behind one of the goals, where he exhorted the crowd to cheer more
loudly. ``It bothered me to see this public so calm,'' he said.
``After Blanc's suspension we were playing with 10 men against 11,
and I could hear the flies fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Charbonnier was not the only French reserve lobbying for less
reserve. Before the semifinal, midfielder Robert Pires had asked
French president Jacques Chirac to shed his business suit in favor
of a French team jersey with the number 23 (there are 22 players on
the French team). But Chirac, even under pressure, declined to defy
decorum and instead kept the uniform in question by his side during
the match, although he brought it with him when he visited the team
in their exuberant locker room afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, fans were already in the streets of Paris
celebrating France's victory and the two goals scored by right
fullback Lilian Thuram. Unlike the English, Dutch or even the
Croatians, French fans don't have traditional soccer hymns with
which to bond. On Wednesday night, they settled for chanting ''On
est en finale!'' (We are in the final) and, perhaps of greater
interest to Chirac, ``Thuram President.''
</P>
<P>
   That was heady stuff for a player who never had scored with the
national team in 37 previous appearances and has scored only once
in his two seasons with Parma in the Italian first division.
``Desailly came up to me after my second goal and said, `What's the
matter with you?''' Thuram said. ``He told me all I usually do is
kick the ball into the stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Although French coach Aime Jacquet said his team would protest
Blanc's expulsion, which came with 16 minutes remaining, a
spokesman for soccer's international governing body FIFA said the
decision by Spanish referee Jose Garcia Aranda would not be
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Blanc, one of the few links between the team that failed to
qualify for the 1994 World Cup finals and the team that has
qualified for THE final, will now have to watch his nation's most
important match from the bench. In his customary spot next to
Desailly will be Leboeuf, a lesser presence and lesser player with
a greater sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare himself with Ronaldo, the Brazilian striker he
should see plenty of on Sunday night, Leboeuf responded, ``I played
striker once, too, and that's why I became a central defender.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
