<HEADER>
A7552 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARDBOARD-CITY-TOKYO-     07-09 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDBOARD-CITY-TOKYO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN AND OUT IN SUMIDA: DRIFTERS REVEAL DEPTH OF JAPAN'S SLUMP  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,100-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Sumida-gawa, which divides Tokyo's east and west, is
among the ugliest of the world's rivers, but also one of the most
immaculate.
</P>
<P>
   A jumble of colorless buildings are reflected in the grey-brown
waters; cars hum constantly along the concrete expressway suspended
above them. But the wide pathways, with their thoughtfully provided
picnic tables, are free of litter.
</P>
<P>
   The flotsam _ human and inanimate _ which usually accumulates
along urban river banks is nowhere to be seen. In fact you could
walk straight past without ever suspecting that this is the saddest
place in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   You might be puzzled by the neat cubes, the size and shape of
shipping containers, which line the walkway. They are made of
cardboard and carefully wrapped with string in waterproof blue
tarpaulins, like giant Christmas presents.
</P>
<P>
   Step inside one _ after removing your shoes _ and you would
discover that each contains a tiny home, with mattress and quilt,
and a makeshift shelf containing comics and newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   One occupant even has even rigged up a portable electric
generator. Pots and pans, salvaged from the garbage left for
collection on the street, hang from nails in the plywood wall.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere is closer to that of a camp site than the
cardboard cities of London or Manhattan. But that is what this is:
the most extreme and pathetic manifestation of Japan's economic
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how many homeless people there are in Japan, but
since the early 1990s, when the bursting of the ``bubble economy''
first began to set off redundancies and bankruptcies, their number
has been growing.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, there were no cardboard houses along the
Sumida; now there are an estimated 500, and the pattern is repeated
in parks, stations, and covered arcades around Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   To a European or American eye, the homeless of Japan are unique:
clean, neat and resourceful, and clinging to self-respect. But in a
society of insiders, their exclusion also brings unique sufferings.
</P>
<P>
   The career of Masami Kobayashi is typical of those who end up
living in the blue boxes by the Sumida River. In 1960, as a
30-year-old steeplejack, he came to Tokyo from his home in Kyushu,
Japan's southernmost island.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three decades, Japan boomed, and no sector
benefited more than the building industry. Even without skills or
an education, an able-bodied man could always find casual work on
the construction sites _ a last resort for the unskilled or
unattached, many of them escaping divorces or business failure or a
spell in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The center of the job market in day laborers was a few hundred
yards from the river, in the area known as Sanya. It was there,
after jobs in various parts of Japan, that Kobayashi arrived. Ten
years ago, there was enough work to go around, even for men of
Kobayashi's age, but all that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government announced that male unemployment had
risen to a record postwar high of 4.3 percent and, since the
collapse of the property market in the early 1990s, construction
has been especially hard hit.
</P>
<P>
   The recruiters now pick only the youngest and fittest men.
``There are too many looking for work,'' says Kobayashi, ``and if
you're over 60 it's almost impossible. I haven't worked for three
years.''
</P>
<P>
   This explains the most striking characteristic of Japan's
homeless _ overwhelmingly they are older men.
</P>
<P>
   One survey, of Tokyo's Shinjuku district, found that more than
90 percent were over 40. The streets around Sanya are full of them,
sitting on the pavement, staring into space, and sipping cups of
cheap sake dispensed from vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that I have a place to live,'' says Hiroshi, a
62-year old, who lives in four square yards of tatami mat in a
cheap hotel paid for by the government. ``But I have no one to talk
to here, and I am a lonely person.''
</P>
<P>
   He lived on the street until three years ago, when he was struck
by a car while drunkenly crossing the road. The permanent injuries
to his legs and arms guaranteed him a place to live, but put paid
to any hope that he will ever work again.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese social security is hedged around with conditions and
exclusions and many of the neediest people, like Kobayashi, fall
through the net. The blue boxes by the river are tolerated by the
authorities, but their occupants are acutely vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Yakuza gangs often employ the homeless as drug pushers or
messengers. Homeless women are a minority, but they are at the
greatest risk, from sexual assault and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest killer, however, is probably the cheap sake. ``Sanya
has always been a place for alcohol, but it's really getting
serious,'' says Megumu Mizuta, a voluntary worker. ``There's a big
difference between drinking after work, and drinking all day when
you have nothing else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the physical threats. Tokyo freezes in the
winter; now, and until September, it is baking hot. Apart from
common ailments, there have been cases of tuberculosis and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Fights and violence are common _ three weeks ago two homeless
men were stabbed to death by a third who was pursued across the
river by police helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to that,'' says Kobayashi. ``Fireworks. The schoolkids
come out in the evenings and throw them into the homes where people
are sleeping.'' Several men have been burned as a result.
</P>
<P>
   It is the mental suffering of alienation _ in a society based
upon groups, rather than individuals _ that is hardest to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these men have no families of their own,'' says
Professor Masami Iwata of Japan Women's University, who has studied
homelessness in the country. ``Their personal identity comes from
their role as workers, and now they have no work. They don't think
of themselves as victims, but as failures, and many of them are
very ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, compared to the population as a whole, the homeless are
few. Apart from a few isolated areas, like Sumida-gawa, they are
not a social problem, certainly not one that politicians or local
government officials are worrying about _ although that may change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently, we noticed a few men wearing ties and business
suits,'' says another voluntary worker. ``We were very surprised,
but they didn't want to talk. They're a minority now, but in a few
years who knows how many of them there will be?'' &QL; 
