<HEADLINE>
IN FUNDS WE TRUST?: WILL ECONOMY SUPPORT OUR RETIREMENT PLANS?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Personal-Finance Editors)   (This insightful 975-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance story
is from ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By PETER L. BERNSTEIN  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When an argument misses the whole point, the result is likely to
be irrelevant, confusing, or just plain wrong. Much of the debate
about the future of Social Security misses the whole point.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not whether Social Security is fundamentally sound
or fundamentally bankrupt, or whether privatizing Social Security
with some kind of giant 401(k) plan would provide us with a more
comfortable old age. At its core, the risk we face has nothing at
all to do with what we now call financial planning.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement has become a central issue of national concern
because the number of retirees is going to grow more rapidly than
the number of people of working age, and that problem intensifies
with the passage of time.
</P>
<P>
   The great uncertainty, then, is whether the economy will be able
to produce sufficient goods and services to support the retired
baby boomers in the style to which they have been accustomed, while
still leaving enough for the younger working members of society to
live in the style to which they would like to become accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the real risk is in the productivity of our economy.
</P>
<P>
   All the money in the world piled up in retirement funds will be
worthless unless the economy can provide the stuff we will want to
buy.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing accomplished by money flowing in and out of
retirement funds is the determination of who gets what, not how
much is available. Money is the ticket to the show but does not
determine what the show will be.
</P>
<P>
   The important point is that more people can enjoy the show if we
can increase the number of available seats. That is why I emphasize
that the standard of living the aging baby boomers can enjoy will
ultimately depend far more on the productivity of the nation than
on the financial arrangements we concoct to fund their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Then how do the financial arrangements enter the picture?
Consider the process by which we finance our everyday spending or
pay off our creditors.
</P>
<P>
   If we are regularly writing checks to pay our bills, or drawing
cash by check or from the ATM, we must be sure to have some way of
replenishing our bank accounts. Money has to come in from
somewhere, or we will go belly-up.
</P>
<P>
   People with jobs bank the wages and salaries they receive from
their employers. People who do not work must look elsewhere to
raise cash _ welfare, monthly pension-fund receipts, a friendly
relative, interest and dividends on investments, or the proceeds
from liquidating assets that have been accumulated over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Note that every one of those sources depends in turn on payments
from somewhere else. For example, the government will not mail
welfare benefits or pay the interest on its bonds unless citizens
pay their taxes or buy the bonds issued to cover budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Dividend payments on equities won't be forthcoming unless
corporations can find a market for their output. The accumulated
assets cannot be liquidated if there are no buyers for those
assets.
</P>
<P>
   This illuminates the true function of retirement funds. A
retirement fund owns stocks and bonds and other investments but
cannot itself finance the spending of the retirees unless the fund
has money in the bank first.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, no matter how much shares of stock and no matter
how many bonds the fund owns, no pensions can be paid unless the
bonds and stocks are paying an income or unless the market is
receptive to buying the investments the fund chooses to liquidate.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, then, retirement benefits are financed from outside
the fund rather than by the fund itself. Retirement funds are
merely conduits; they determine who gets what, not how much is
available _ which means that the true function of the assets in
these funds is to serve as collateral to secure the claims of
future retirees on future production.
</P>
<P>
   But no restructuring of Social Security, no privatization or
other type of reform, will do the trick unless the economy is
prosperous _ unless taxpayers have jobs, corporations can pay
dividends, borrowers can meet their interest payments when due, and
the capital markets are buoyant.
</P>
<P>
   The people who miss the whole point worry that the Social
Security trust fund will be depleted before most of the baby
boomers can claim their rightful share. Yes, if that dread moment
were ever to arrive, the collateral held to secure the promise of
Social Security would no longer exist.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean society would necessarily let its senior
citizens starve; it means only that their needs could not be met by
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Even if reform assured the existence of some form of collateral
for retirement benefits in the years ahead, the existence of that
collateral is still no guarantee that society will be able to
provide senior citizens with the wherewithal to pay for their
groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, for the sake of argument, that we did reform Social
Security. Suppose, too, that the economy of 2010 cannot produce
enough to satisfy the needs of both those who are employed and the
larger number who are retired.
</P>
<P>
   If the collateral of the retirees _ the value of the securities
they own _ is large, the retiree claim will be excessive and the
working people will see their living standards decline.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting social tension will push the working group to
insist upon their rightful share. Wages will escalate, either
causing inflation or disrupting the reliable flow of interest and
dividends and the vibrant market on which asset liquidation
depends. Then the purchasing power of the retirees' collateral will
be much less than today's expectations seem to promise.
</P>
<P>
   The financial arrangements are not the solution. They are part
of the problem. The solution is in economic prosperity over the
long run. &QL; 
