<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IRS-OVERHAUL (Washington) _ The Senate overwhelmingly approves a
compromise plan designed to make sweeping changes at the Internal
Revenue Service. The Senate voted 96-2 to adopt an IRS
restructuring plan that lawmakers hope will provide taxpayers with
greater protections while reining in potential abuses. By DAVID
IVANOVICH
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ Linda Tripp testifies for a
fourth day before the grand jury investigating the Monica Lewinsky
matter. Meanwhile, a state grand jury in Maryland considers
indicting Tripp on wiretap charges in an inquiry that her lawyers
say is political. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FLORIDA (Daytona Beach, Fla.) _ President Clinton meets
with residents and Florida firefighters battling wild fires and
vows to help pay for the clean-up. Earlier, in Atlanta, he and
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., announced five-year, $1 billion
anti-drug campaign aimed at youths. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   PROSECUTORS-DEALS (Washington) _ The Justice Department seek to
reverse an appellate court decision that invalidates the
long-standing practice of U.S. prosecutors who are lenient on
convicts and suspects who cooperate in criminal investigations. The
appeals court says such deals violate a law that bars prosecutors
from promising anything of value to people in return for their
testimony. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DISNEY (Austin, Texas) _ As a state Board of Education
committee voted on whether to dump the board's stock in the Walt
Disney Co. because of its adult-oriented movies, a liberal interest
group released a list of other holdings that might not score well
on a morality test. The companies cited involve alcohol and adult
movies. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   AGENTS-KILLED (Harlingen, Texas) _ Relatives bury Ernie Moore,
who killed four people, including two U.S. Border Patrol agents,
and seriously wounded two others before lawmen fatally shot him.
Meanwhile, authorities say Moore may have been high on cocaine,
marijuana and alcohol at the time of the killings. By JAMES
PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Congressional Republicans,
frustrated by the success of President Clinton's China trip, have
finally found something to complain about: his statements on
Taiwan. Foreign policy wonks know the island is important, but in
the post-Cold War era when we no longer call the mainland ``Red
China,'' do voters care all that much about our Taiwan policy? By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Paris) _ President Clinton and his officials
have learned a lesson in Kosovo, the latest flashpoint in the
Balkans: that threatening military intervention is useless. By
BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLD-CUP (Paris) _ Brazil coach Mario Zagallo has endured
the criticism from fans and media, mediated the internal squabbling
among his talented but ego-driven superstars, and guided his team
to the lip of its fifth World Cup championship. Yet Zagallo still
hears little but second-guessing from Brazil's ardent fans. By JOHN
P. LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (St. Louis) _ Pitcher Shane Reynolds goes after his
11th victory of the season as the Houston Astros open the second
half of the season with the opener of a four-game weekend series
against the division rival St. Louis Cardinals. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With BBN-MICKEY
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ For Americans, President
Clinton's trip to China was little more than a blip on the radar
screen of history. But for millions of Chinese, especially the
young, his message that democracy and freedom are an inevitable
part of their country's future will resonate for generations. By
ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
