<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIH-$ADV11-COX     07-09 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIH-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS POURING MONEY INTO HEALTH RESEARCH
 &HT;    1230&AMP;insert.
 &HT;    With NIH-DATA. For release Saturday, July 11.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., likes to tell a story about
the day retired Army Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf appeared at a Senate
committee hearing and took no prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of these days the American people are going to wake up and
realize how little you guys have invested in basic medical
research,'' Mack recalls the straight-talking Schwarzkopf telling
senators on the committee. ``And when they do, they're going to be
mad as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack, a longtime Senate champion of increased federal support
for medical research, was happy to find a supporter in ``Stormin'
Norman,'' commander of Allied forces in the Persian Gulf war and a
survivor of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two years later, Mack finds himself surrounded by
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   A growing impression that scientists are on the brink of
fundamental breakthroughs in the treatment of cancer, heart
disease, Alzheimer's, AIDS and other modern plagues has pushed
medical research to the status of a political sure bet.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Senate
Republican leaders all are on record as supporting dramatic
increases in the budget of the National Institutes of Health (NIH).
</P>
<P>
   With a budget that already exceeds $13 billion, NIH is the
dominant supporter of America's search for the basic biological
knowledge that underpins the development of new treatments for
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The country's largest private medical philanthropy, the Howard
Hughes Medical Institute, awards about $400 million a year in
research grants, less than 4 percent of the $10.4 billion in
contracts and extramural research grants NIH awarded last year to
scientists at universities, medical schools, private start-up
biomedical enterprises and other research centers. (The remainder
of the NIH budget pays the agency's expenses and funds its own team
of intramural scientists.)
</P>
<P>
   While Congress this year apparently will fall somewhat short
doubling NIH's research funds in five years _ as both Clinton and
Gingrich have advocated _ it's clear to Mack and others that the
country is about to dramatically increase its investment in medical
research.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee is tentatively scheduled to
take up a bill Tuesday that would increase NIH's budget by slightly
more than 9 percent next year. At that rate, the agency's budget
would double in eight years, rather than five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take what we can get,'' Mack said. ``I think we could
end up with an increase this year of a billion to a billion-five.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of an additional $1 billion or more has
researchers, about 80 percent of whom now find their proposals for
NIH support rejected because of limited funds, marveling at their
improved prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to grab a piece of the upcoming government largesse,
scientists are churning out grant proposals at places like Emory
University in Atlanta; the North Carolina research empire in
Durham, Chapel Hill and Raleigh; the University of Alabama at
Birmingham; St. Louis's Washington University; dozens of
universities and science institutes in California and Texas; Johns
Hopkins University in Baltimore; Harvard University, and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is basically no other source of funds for the kind of
research I do,'' said Makkuni Jayaram, a molecular biologist at the
University of Texas at Austin. Jayaram's work is aimed at
understanding how obscure proteins round up isolated pieces of DNA
and assemble them into working genes at just the moment those genes
are needed to carry out a specific activity inside the cell.
</P>
<P>
   When a gene's work is done, the proteins disassemble it and stow
the pieces back on the cell's genomic shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Jayaram, who received $350,000 in research support from NIH last
year, noted that there's no way at this point to predict how
understanding the biochemical processes he is exploring could
someday lead to better ways to treat AIDS, cancer or some other
disease. That's why only NIH can afford to support it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Georgia, leaders of a government-industry-academic
alliance that helps universities in the state attract the
top-flight scientists whose work excites NIH grant makers, also are
pleased at the prospects of new government support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago, Atlanta lost a lost a competition to
Austin, Texas, as the site of the Micro-electronic Computer
Consortium,'' said Bill Todd, president of the Georgia Research
Alliance. ``Since then, that area has became one of the top centers
in the semiconductor industry.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the experience caused Atlanta business leaders to think
in terms of getting the city in shape for the next competition and
led to creation of the consortium of businesses, state agencies and
six universities dedicated to bringing top scientific researchers
to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Biomedical technology is one of the group's principal focal
points, Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many smart people believe we're on the cusp of a biological
revolution that at least replicates, and maybe dwarfs, the
information revolution'' of the past 20 years, Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   Research grants from NIH will be the main force driving the
development of the new industry, Todd believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``To double NIH would be in the national interest because you
can do well by doing good,'' he said. ``The opportunities are there
to subdue disease like Alzheimer's, cancer and heart disease. We
would be using some very advanced technologies that not only serve
the national interest by taking care of people but will fuel the
economy also.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd said the research alliance has raised nearly $200 million
in state appropriations and private support in the past seven years
to endow 27 research chairs at universities, provide modern
laboratory equipment, and support efforts to recruit leading
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to Emory's successful effort three years ago to lure
vaccine researcher Rafi Ahmed away from the University of
California at Los Angeles as an example of the area's focused
campaign to build a biomedical brain trust.
</P>
<P>
   NIH records show Ahmed received four grants totaling more than
$800,000 last year for his studies of the interaction of the body's
immune system with such viruses as HIV and ebola.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional insert.)
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Emory's NIH grants and contracts totaled around $91
million last year, a 26 percent increase since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The records place Georgia 20th in the nation in total NIH
support, between Alabama and Florida. California, which received
more than $1.5 billion from the federal agency, also was home to
some of the fastest-growing grant recipients, with a statewide
increase of 33.5 percent over 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Alabama at Birmingham, with a medical school
that is only 25 years old, received $118 million from the national
institute in 1997, an increase of more than 43 percent since 1993.
Other leading biomedical research centers in the South include Duke
University, which got $152 million last year, and the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill, which got $142 million.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Florida received about $50 million and the
University of Miami, $51 million.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, medical schools in Galveston, Dallas, Houston and San
Antonio shared $280 million in NIH funds, and the University of
Texas at Austin, which does not have a medical school, received
nearly $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   The institution with the most support was Johns Hopkins
University in Baltimore, with $292 million, although several
hundred million dollars granted to various Boston-area hospitals
and other institutions appeared primarily to underwrite Harvard
University research.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional insert.)
</P>
<P>
   While there are several theories about the sudden political
popularity of doubling the NIH budget _ including the fact that the
politically powerful ``Baby Boomer'' generation is reaching the age
where people worry more about their health _ Mack is convinced that
a national awareness of coming breakthroughs is the driving force.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to tell the story of another witness who testified at
the same Senate hearing where Schwarzkopf appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Roy, a student who was injured in the first few seconds
of his first game on the Boston University hockey team and was left
a paraplegic, told senators his dream for years had been to play
hockey for Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now my dream is to be able someday to hug my mom again,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that story had been told 15 or 20 years ago, the emotion we
all felt would have been the same, but we would have said there is
nothing we could do about it,'' Mack said. ``Now, more and more,
people are becoming convinced that there are things, and there will
be things, that we can do about some of these once-hopeless
diseases and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is a growing sense out there that we are getting
very, very close.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
