<HEADER>
A7600 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-     07-09 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORTING OUT FACTS, FICTION ON OUR HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vast majority of us are doing little to promote our own
health.
</P>
<P>
   We know the value of exercise and a healthful diet, yet only 20
percent of us actually consume the recommended seven fruits and
vegetables each day, and only 10 percent exercise on a regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   We are poor models for our children, 20 percent of whom are
already decisively overweight and sedentary by the age of 12 _ and
we are dooming ourselves to an unhealthy old age _ if we live long
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than helping the problem, I sometimes think we in the
media compound it with our explosions of often conflicting
information.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   To clarify what we know about how diet, dietary supplements,
exercise and other interventions contribute to better health and
longer life, 14 national experts in gerontology, exercise and
nutrition got together recently to write a ``Prescription for
Longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   They separated out some of the fads, folklore and false
information, and published their conclusions last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so much hype for products promising the eternal fountain
of youth and many contradictory research findings, people are
confused about what they can do to ensure good health,'' says Dr.
Robert Butler, president of the International Longevity Center and
professor of geriatrics at Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Center and Canyon Ranch health resort in Tucson, Ariz.,
co-sponsored the discussion. The group particularly addressed the
question of which of the much-hyped dietary supplements and other
interventions are truly effective and safe.
</P>
<P>
   For optimum health benefits, participants recommend strength
conditioning with light weights and walking four miles a day, five
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   However, Butler says the experts don't want anyone to be
discouraged by the amount or type of exercise prescribed, noting
that the recommendations ``should be viewed as a goal that has many
graduations in between because any amount of exercise is better
than none.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The experts agree that supplementing the recommended daily
allowance (RDA) of nutrients can reduce the risk of age-related
diseases. For example, high levels of folate and vitamin B-6 have
been shown to reduce the risk of heart disease in women; vitamin C
has been shown to reduce smoking-induced oxidative damage; and
vitamin E supplementation is known to reduce the risk of cancer and
cardiovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
   They prescribe:
</P>
<P>
   _ At least two to four helpings of fruit and three to five
helpings of vegetables per day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Calcium supplements, if necessary, to ensure a daily intake of
1,200 milligrams for men and 1,500 for women (1 cup skim milk has
301 milligrams, 3 ounces of sardines, 324 milligrams).
</P>
<P>
   _ One multivitamin tablet per day to ensure adequate intake of
vitamins B-6, B-12, C, D, E and folic acid (with no or low amounts
of iron for the elderly).
</P>
<P>
   _ Dietary fat reduction to 30 percent or less of total caloric
intake.
</P>
<P>
   _ Regular sun exposure to maintain adequate vitamin D levels and
the sleep/wake cycle. Excessive exposure should be avoided to
reduce the risk of skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Obesity should be avoided at any age but especially to prevent
excessive weight gain with increasing age.
</P>
<P>
   _ One children's aspirin (81 milligrams) per day to reduce the
risk of heart attack and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stress reduction/relaxation activities including exercise,
yoga and tai chi.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Call her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
