r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRUESOME-PARK-TOKYO-I     07-09 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRUESOME-PARK-TOKYO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PARK WITH A HORRIBLE SECRET  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This compelling 725-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ From the surface of the earth at least, nowhere could
appear less sinister than Toyama Park.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in Shinjuku Ward, in the heart of central Tokyo, it is
an unremarkable little place of trees and gravel, a spot where
salarymen take their lunchtime sandwiches and old ladies walk their
poodles. A famous university is next door; a number of hospitals
stand close by.
</P>
<P>
   But the ground beneath Toyama Park contains a secret _ a truly
horrible secret, one of the most dreadful of 20th-century Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months, bureaucrats, politicians and local
people have been passing it around from one to the other, a
historical hot potato which nobody wants to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins more than 60 years ago during the seemingly
unstoppable advance of the invading Japanese Imperial Army through
Manchuria.
</P>
<P>
   In the city of Harbin, a special division was established
officially called the Prevention of Epidemics and Water Supply
Section, but better and more notoriously known as Unit 731.
</P>
<P>
   Its true function was controversial in itself _ the development
and testing of biological and chemical weapons, including anthrax
and bubonic plague.
</P>
<P>
   But the fearful thing about Unit 731 was the means which its
doctors used to carry out their research: experiments on live
prisoners who were deliberately infected in the name of science and
dissected while they were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the human experiments took place in Harbin but,
according to the accounts of former Unit 731 members, experiments
were also carried out in the Imperial Army's medical college and
research headquarters _ now the site of Toyama Park.
</P>
<P>
   The park is about to be dug up for the construction of a brand
new public sports ground. The project will involve excavating the
site where human experiments are believed to have taken place,
threatening to bring the horrible episode literally up to the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   For _ apart from its present-day role as a place of recreation _
Toyama Park is a mass grave. Nine years ago, 200 bodies of several
Asian races were dug up from a nearby construction site.
</P>
<P>
   Former employees claim that on the site of the park, in the
brief period after the Japanese surrender and before the American
Occupation, the bodies of murdered human guinea pigs were buried.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the numbers killed by Unit 731 in Manchuria range
from 3,000 to 30,000; most were Chinese, but they included Koreans,
Russians, American, French and Britons, and the youngest of them
were babies.
</P>
<P>
   The ``logs,'' as they were referred to by their captors, were
cut open while conscious and their organs removed. For decades the
Japanese government refused to acknowledge the existence of Unit
731, until the 1980s when increasing numbers of elderly former
members began speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``My colleagues said they dug a hole ten meters deep and for a
month after the surrender they threw bodies into it,'' said one
former nurse quoted in the Asahi newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bodies included those used in germ experiments and after
the grave was filled in, they built on top of it. One of the staff,
who knew the facts, lived in the building to keep guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans to proceed with the sports center have been on hold since
February when a local citizens' group filed a petition demanding
that a full excavation be carried out before any construction goes
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many local people want this sports center,'' says Noboru
Watanabe, the group's leader. ``We're not against the plan, but we
want to prevent historical facts from being concealed.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation has degenerated into a bureaucratic farce, with
everyone agreeing that something must be done, but nobody prepared
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The council of Shinjuku Ward says that it is up to the Ministry
of Health and Welfare. The Ministry of Health and Welfare says its
the responsibility of the Tokyo Metropolitan Government.
</P>
<P>
   The TMG has referred the matter on to Shinjuku Ward. Members of
the Shinjuku council are divided and no decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
   In Toyama Park life goes uneventfully on, although a walk
through the trees or a nap on the grass will never feel quite the
same again. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 725-word article, it must be purchased _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
