A7611 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX     07-09 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL FOLLOWED TWISTING ROAD TO SUCCESS IN CYBERSPACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. may dominate the world of computer software, but
a smaller company may be developing its own stranglehold on
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, long considered a dark horse in the race to
control the online world, has emerged as the single most dominating
provider of Internet access worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's twisting, turning road from floundering start-up to
undisputed industry leader is chronicled in a new book from Wall
Street Journal reporter Kara Swisher, ``aol.com _ How Steve Case
Beat Bill Gates, Nailed the Netheads and Made Millions in the War
for the Web'' (Times Business, $25, 333 pages). It is the most
detailed profiles yet written about the company behind one of the
Internet's best-known brands.
</P>
<P>
   Now with 12 million subscribers, AOL has more than four times as
many paying customers as its nearest rival. And this year, it
cemented its hold on the industry's top spot by acquiring its
closest competitor and longtime rival CompuServe Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Swisher, who started compiling information for a book on the
Virginia-based AOL more than two years ago while covering the
company as a reporter for The Washington Post, provides a
relatively comprehensive review of AOL milestones and misfires.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly insightful is her recounting of Microsoft efforts
to buy AOL in the early 1990s before the software company launched
its own rival Microsoft Network online service that many had
predicted would wipe out emerging companies such as AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Swisher also provides detailed accounts of some of the darker
days in AOL's history, including the company's infamous 19-hour
outage in August 1996 and its decision later that year to change a
controversial accounting procedure that produced one-time
write-offs running into the hundreds of millions of dollars that
literally wiped out all the profits the company had ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Swisher also provides the best, most balanced profile of AOL's
chief executive, Case, the quiet but effective entrepreneur most
responsible for AOL's rise.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to detailing Case's strategies for guiding AOL to
the top, the author also writes about his affair with one of his
top marketing executives that led to his own divorce and, for a
time, may have threatened his ability to continue running the
company.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Swisher is guilty of some hero worship and corporate
cheerleading in the pages of ``aol.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly everything that goes right with AOL, in this book at
least, is credited to the wisdom and foresight of AOL's founding
fathers. In cases where AOL is the center of controversy or
flat-out mistakes in market judgment, the blame game often
overlooks or soft-pedals the trouble that AOL executives caused for
the company.
</P>
<P>
   In passages that detail negotiations that AOL held in selecting
the Web browser software used on the service, for example, Swisher
describes the formation of a series of deals with software
developers Microsoft and Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Microsoft won the rights to have its Internet
browser integrated into AOL, a turn of events that seemed to leave
Netscape as a jilted partner. Swisher conveys the anger of Netscape
executives at the end result of the negotiations but never really
tells the reader whether AOL misled Netscape in its dealing on
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Even with that one fault, Swisher's book provides a thorough
review of the evolution of AOL. And even if the prose is viewed
through AOL-tinted glasses, it provides keen insight on how
cyberspace has developed to this point and a better understanding
of the people likely to shape much of the Internet's future.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
