A7613 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SMALLSOLDIERS-TE     07-09 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SMALLSOLDIERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SMALL SOLDERS' DIRECTOR HAS FOUGHT THIS BATTLE BEFORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though it took 15 years, we finally got a remake of
``Gremlins.'' At least its original director, Joe Dante, did it,
although he probably thought he'd be making other kinds of movies
by now. This time around, instead of ``don't ever get them wet,''
the lesson becomes, ``don't ever put munitions computer chips in
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens here. Irwin (David Cross) and Larry (Jay
Mohr) are a pair of hapless leftovers at Heartland Play Systems
when it's swallowed whole by the Globotech conglomerate. Whenever
Globotech head honcho Gil Mars (Denis Leary) strides into the
action, you know there's trouble. He's always wearing the official
uniform of heartless capitalist scum everywhere _ the
double-breasted suit.
</P>
<P>
   Spitting out his lines as if he doesn't want to miss his ride,
Mars combines two ideas _ Irwin's pacifist but monstrous-looking
Gorgonites, and Larry's buffed he-man dolls, the Commando Elite _
into a single set of toys. Bored by toys that can't do the stuff
you see in commercials, Mars demands more, so Larry installs
secret-weapon computer chips into the toys. When asked if the toys
won't be too violent for kids, Mars cracks, ``It's not violence.
It's action. Kids love action.'' If the rest of ``Small Soldiers''
were that good, we'd be going somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of stuff that Dante has done so much it's hard
to see how he keeps awake. He makes David Lynch-type entertainment
for kids, set in sun-splashed idyllic small towns where not much
happens, but where something creepy festers beneath the surface. In
``Small Soldiers,'' the small town is Winslow Corners, Ohio, where
Alan (Gregory Smith) has just moved with his parents after he's
been kicked out of a couple of schools.
</P>
<P>
   Alan is a sweet kid who wants to start over, and he helps run
his dad's yuppie-fantasy plaything store, called The Inner Child,
where there are no military toys. When Alan sneaks the Commando
Elite and Gorgonites into the store, they come to life and start
fighting. At least, the Commando Elite do; they seem to run on
sheer testosterone, not the built-in, lifetime batteries. The war
between the toys consumes Alan's life, and gets in the way of his
getting next to Christy (Kirsten Dunst). Except when they battle
the Commando Elite together.
</P>
<P>
   If kids want to see one talking-creature movie this summer,
``Small Soldiers'' may not be it; the animals in ``Dr. Dolittle''
have far more personality. The toys in ``Small Soldiers'' have
limited appeal, since they have the inflexible facial expressions
of, well, toys. The funniest thing about them is that Commando
leader Chip Hazard is voiced by Tommy Lee Jones, who often seems
like a wind-up toy anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Dante always packs his casts with able comic actors _ Cross,
Mohr, Leary, Dunn, Ann Magnuson, the late Phil Hartman _ and mixes
in his repertory company (Dick Miller, Robert Picardo, Wendy
Schaal). ``Small Soldiers'' is glib and fast-moving, but it's
merely a competent, uninspired reprise of what Dante has done
before, Id versus Superego, that dates all the way back to ``The
Howling,'' the vivacious werewolf movie parody that first got him
attention. ``Small Soldiers'' is so cramped that you may start to
feel bad for Dante. That's when the real horror sets in.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Small Soldiers''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 stars on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Joe Dante
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Gregory Smith, Kirsten Dunst, Tommy Lee Jones
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ Mild violence and profanity. There's plenty of
destruction _ mostly to the toys.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
