<HEADER>
A7614 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MADELINE-TEX     07-09 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MADELINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREEN ADAPTATION OF `MADELINE' IS SWEET BUT NEVER CLOYING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mercifully, it's not strung together with a series of rhyming
couplets like the Ludwig Bemelmans books upon which it's based, but
the film adaptation of ``Madeline'' sets its tone early.
``Madeline'' opens with a wonderful piece of animation _ a
shimmering, vibrant piece that has a comforting, primitive look
similar to the old Colorforms appliques.
</P>
<P>
   The animation fades to the real, homey manor house where
Madeline, the original Miss Can Do, and her classmates attend
school; it's a large and friendly private girls-only edifice that's
slightly run down. It makes sense that Daisy von Scherler Mayer
would direct the screen adaptation of ``Madeline.'' Her first film,
``Party Girl,'' in which Parker Posey played an up-to-the-minute
version of a self-absorbed screwball comedy heroine, was basically
the hippest Afterschool Special of all time. Mayer has a talent for
giving women center stage without either condescending or
proselytizing her Girl Power sensibility lends itself to children's
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Frances McDormand, as the girls' teacher, Miss Clavel, has
extra-sensitive antennae. Her eyes pop open like a silent movie
star's whenever something's going on. She's spiritually connected
to her charges, especially to the orphaned Madeline, whose eyes
sparkle with practicality. However, Madeline's brand of
practicality is unique; when she decides to become a vegetarian
after riding in a car with the chicken that was transformed into
dinner, her noisy, fowl-less stance attracts all of the other
girls. (But when it suits her, she reverses herself.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie is dependent on the appeal of its star, little Hatty
Jones, whose old-lady name fits her serious voice and ringing
British accent. In her film debut, Jones' utter conviction in
everything she says and does _ which is what Madeline is all about
_ registers, and it isn't adult or mature at all. (Jones'
willfulness is all performance; with David Letterman recently, she
fell quiet with awe after learning that the Spice Girls were
around.) Mayer has found a group of girls who are distinctive
enough to register as individuals immediately. When they band
around the little star, it feels as if she's won them over by sheer
force of personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madeline'' is full of energy and personality. The movie may
feel a little episodic, if only because elements from several of
the Madeline books are used to bring the little heroine to the
movie screen. The bitter presence of Lord Covington (Nigel
Hawthorne, who seems to have burned away into a spiteful snarl)
hovers over the girls' school. Covington wants to get rid of the
house, and the memories of his late wife that it represents.
</P>
<P>
   But if the house is sold, the orphaned Madeline will have
nowhere else to go. As Covington tries selling it to a series of
buyers, his ambitions are thwarted by Madeline, her newfound dog _
who saved Madeline after a fall into the Seine _ and Pepito
(Kristian De La Osa), the boy next door. Pepito is also the son of
the Spanish ambassador, and the girls all take note of his
charisma. Madeline and Pepito form a special bond when they're
kidnapped by Leopold, Pepito's inept con-man of a teacher (Ben
Daniels, who's audacious and funny _ his lecherous conversations
with Miss Clavel almost rate their own movie).
</P>
<P>
   ``Madeline'' is a likable lollipop of a movie; the audience of
mostly girls I saw it with gave it their full and rapt attention.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Madeline''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Daisy von Scherler Mayer
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Frances McDormand, Nigel Hawthorne
</P>
<P>
   Rating: PG _ Mild violence and action, and a kidnapping
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
