<SLUG> BC-HOME-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOME BEFORE DARK': UNEVEN AND HEAVY HANDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe on a rainy day after school or late at night on the Family
Channel there is a slot on television for ``Home Before Dark.'' But
no compelling reason exists for running out to see this listless,
tiresome movie in a theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Before Dark'' may smack of truth, but it does not ring
with art. The acting is uneven and often heavy-handed. Attempts at
humor fall flat. And crayons couldn't underline the action more
obviously than the music. But ``Home Before Dark,'' written and
directed by Maureen Foley, tells a sad story that seems rooted in
reality, and its central figures _ a family shattered by a fatal
accident _ evoke sympathy and the hope that their burdens might
ease even if they never vanish completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Before Dark,'' set in rural Massachusetts in 1963, tells
the story of Nora James (Stephanie Castellarin). Nora is a
pubescent 11-year-old with literary ambitions and a mother, Dolores
(Patricia Kalember), who has retreated into depression and despair
because of an automobile accident five years earlier that killed
three of her children.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Nora, who attends parochial school, has more than
an ordinary share of responsibilities in a household that includes
two mischievous preschool children and a decent but harried father,
Martin (Brian Delate), who is struggling to make a living as a
carpenter and deal with his misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the assassination of President John F.
Kennedy, whom Dolores once met, prompts her to attempt suicide. She
is institutionalized in Boston; the younger children are dispatched
there to live with an aunt and uncle, and Martin also moves to
Boston, where he can find more work. But Nora, because of her
schooling, is left behind to live with another aunt, the unhappily
married Rose (Katharine Ross of ``The Graduate'' and ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'').
</P>
<P>
   Nora is unwilling to adapt to the childless Rose's mold, and
when Rose tries to suppress the family fiction Nora is writing in
her hope of winning a Seventeen magazine literary contest, their
relationship worsens. Eventually Nora threatens to expose Rose's
infidelity unless she can count on her to help reunite the family
and bring everyone home.
</P>
<P>
   Will Dolores overcome her fear of further loss and return to her
family? Will Nora survive the machinations of her jealous
classmates and win the contest? Nothing about ``Home Before Dark''
is surprising.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HOME BEFORE DARK'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Maureen Foley; directors of photography,
Brian Heller and Mark Petersson; edited by James Rutenbeck; music
by Jeanine Cowen; production designer, Kathleen Rosen; produced by
Michael Williams, Dorothy Aufiero and David Collins; released by
Scout Productions and Hazelwood Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Stephanie Castellarin (Nora), Katharine Ross (Rose),
Patricia Kalember (Dolores), Brian Delate (Martin) and Helen Lloyd
Breed (Sister Concilia). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 110 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
