A7647 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SMOKESIGNALS-TEX     07-09 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SMOKESIGNALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIO HYPE KINDLES MIXED SIGNALS ABOUT `SMOKE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miramax is happily hyping ``Smoke Signals'' as the first
(nationally distributed) film written, produced and directed by
Native Americans, and as such, it contains the expected amount of
stereotype-busting. But all the hype makes the movie seem more
special than it is.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's well-made, funny and poignant, it's hardly
Earth-shattering; it comes down to a story of father-and-son
conflict, with some elements of road movies and buddy movies thrown
in.
</P>
<P>
   One of the buddies is Victor Joseph (Adam Beach), a young Coeur
D'Alene Indian who has had a chip on his shoulder ever since his
father abandoned his family when he was 12. Victor is strong,
handsome with traditional flowing locks and an anti-social attitude
that keeps everyone at arm's length. Everyone, that is, except for
Thomas Build-the-Fire (Evan Adams), who has been inexorably linked
to Victor since they were rescued from a Bicentennial July Fourth
fire when they were babies.
</P>
<P>
   With his glasses, braids, oversized teeth and omnipresent nerdy
suit, Thomas looks like an Indian Urkel. His one physical virtue is
his lilting voice, which he uses to continue the Indian tradition
of oral storytelling _ except that he can never quite keep his
tales straight, and he's constantly telling them to Victor, who
doesn't really care.
</P>
<P>
   When word comes that Victor's father has died in Arizona, the
two young men travel together by bus to retrieve the body. Or
rather, the ashes _ the movie's title is the first sign that it's
big on fire metaphors, and it never misses a trick (Victor's father
even dies near Phoenix, a town named for a firebird). There, they
meet a young woman (Irene Bedard, the voice of ``Pocahontas'') who
befriended Victor's father and tries to help Victor come to terms
with their estrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Director Chris Eyre and screenwriter Sherman Alexie, who based
his script on several of his own short stories, are intent on
making this a mainstream entertainment; the buzz about Native
American filmmaking seems to distract from their purpose. Because
we all have fathers, some of whom have remained close, some of whom
have abandoned us, the father-son theme is far more universal than
all the ads and articles would have us believe.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie does take some amusing shots at movie representations of
Indians, ribbing Victor's stoicism, which he seems to have borrowed
from John Ford movies, and Thomas' attempts at ``Dances With
Wolves''-style mysticism. And there's a great running gag with
Leonard George as a ``traffic'' reporter on the Indians' desolate
Idaho reservation. But when Adams' beautiful voice is put to good
use reading Dick Lourie's poem ``Forgiving Our Fathers,'' you don't
have to be an Indian to relate. It's another example of how ``Smoke
Signals'' may be fine in execution, but isn't the revelation that
its studio wants you to expect.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Smoke Signals''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Chris Eyre
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Adam Beach, Evan Adams
</P>
<P>
   Length: 89 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ violence and language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
