<SLUG> BC-MEGAN'S-LAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME EXPS QUESTION EFFECTIVENESS OF MEGAN'S LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMELYN CRUZ LAT  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Megan's Law, the measure requiring the police to
make information about convicted sex offenders public, remains
politically popular despite reports of vigilantism, noncompliance
and, most recently, a parolee who committed suicide after his
neighbors were notified of his criminal past.
</P>
<P>
   Even as critics say the law is causing problems, some
politicians are maneuvering for even tougher legislation in
California. More than 29 bills related to increased penalties for
sex offenders are working their way through the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very popular law,'' said Elizabeth Schroeder,
associate director of the American Civil Liberties Union of
Southern California. ``These types of laws are easy to pass and
don't cost a whole lot of money, whereas true solutions to problems
require an incredible amount of resolve and public resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Megan's Law, named after a New Jersey girl murdered in
1994 by a paroled sex offender who lived in her neighborhood, the
police are allowed to notify neighbors about convicted sex
offenders living nearby if they believe the offenders pose a danger
to the community.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Michael Allen Patton, the parolee who committed
suicide, the Santa Rosa police said they were following the law in
identifying him as a high-risk sex offender in a notice distributed
to neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Patton, apparently depressed about the flier, hanged himself
Sunday in a redwood grove on Santa Rosa Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said it was inevitable that someday, some child
molester would kill himself after his name and picture was
distributed in a neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will become something common,'' she said.
``However, it ought to give pause to other police departments
considering public notification.''
</P>
<P>
   California has required freed sex offenders to register with law
enforcement agencies since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, state lawmakers authorized the police to notify
residents when high-risk sex offenders moved into a community, and
a hot line was set up to allow criminal records checks of suspected
offenders. A high-risk offender is defined as someone with a record
of multiple, violent sexual offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts on the law and crime said that since increasingly
aggressive measures to notify the public have been used, reports of
vigilantism and parolees refusing to register or moving around have
increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law enforcement officers in California have reported that
prior to Megan's Law, they knew pretty much where all the sex
offenders in their community lived,'' Schroeder said. ``Now, people
are starting to go underground.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem of ``Megan's flight'' has gotten worse since the law
went into effect in the fall of 1996, according to a state
Department of Justice task force that keeps tabs on sex offenders
who fail to register.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,600 parolees in California are considered high-risk sex
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   However, as many as 40 percent of convicted sex offenders have
failed to register. And many who appear on registration lists have
since moved to unknown addresses, have died or have gone back to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   One legal expert said Megan's Law might give the public peace of
mind, but it did not necessarily prevent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really have any hard data to either support Megan's
Law or to disprove it,'' said Louis Yablonsky, emeritus professor
of criminology at California State University at Northridge.
``There's no question that for the general populace, the law gives
people a feeling that something positive and constructive is being
done about the dreadful problem of sex offenders and child abuse.
But this does not necessarily mean that it is controlling and
diminishing the sex offender problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Policies should focus on prevention and treatment, said Wendy
Kaminer, attorney and public policy fellow at Radcliffe Public
Policy Institute in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect that (Megan's Law) will be terribly effective
in protecting children,'' she said. ``A lot of people simply won't
register. They will go underground and will not get the treatment
that they need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
