A7685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATIENCE-OPERA-REVIEW     07-09 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENCE-OPERA-REVIEW-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PATIENCE AND SARAH': A FLAWED CHAMBER OPERA THAT STILL WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Composer Paula M. Kimper and librettist Wende
Persons, whose three-act chamber opera ``Patience and Sarah''
received its world premiere on Tuesday night as part of Lincoln
Center Festival '98, believe that the opera is the first to portray
an openly romantic relationship between two self-affirming women.
</P>
<P>
   They may be right. Not that opera isn't filled with countless
instances of bonded, loving women singing gloriously in duet. But
these relationships are seldom explicitly romantic unless one of
the women plays a boy, as in ``Der Rosenkavalier.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the female voice is the glory of opera. So even though, say,
Bellini's ``Norma'' turns on the rivalry between a Druid priestess
and her confidante over a handsome Roman consul, the soaring duets
for the women reveal the subtext of the story _ that theirs is the
real loving relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to portray lesbian love openly is new to opera, which has
not exactly been in the vanguard of social change. This must
account for the pre-premiere response to ``Patience and Sarah,''
which was commissioned and developed by American Opera Projects
Inc. and played to a sold-out opening night house at the John Jay
College Theater. Though the opera has flaws, it was impossible not
to be moved by the sight of so many excited, eager women in the
audience, many of them in couples.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the proudly lesbian creators had a sure bet in the
story, taken from a novel of the same name by the late Isabel
Miller that has gained cultish popularity. The novel was in turn
inspired by the lives of two early 19th-century women from Puritan
families in Connecticut who settled together on a small farm in New
York's Greene County, Mary Ann Willson, a painter with some
inherited money, and her companion, known as Miss Brundage.
</P>
<P>
   The opera is strongest at depicting the dangerous yet ecstatic
courtship between these bold women. When the tomboyish Sarah (the
Miss Brundage character), dressed in breeches, boots and a rawhide
coat and affectingly portrayed by the mezzo-soprano Elaine Valby,
shows up to deliver firewood to the fine house where Patience lives
with her stern brother, Edward, and his obedient wife, the
well-educated Patience, sung by the formidable soprano Lori
Phillips, is completely smitten.
</P>
<P>
   The opera effectively depicts the perils of their relationship:
Sarah's naivete in talking about her powerful love too openly to
her possessive younger sister; the beating she sustains from her
brutish father when he finds out; the weakness Patience gives in to
when her brother forbids her to see Sarah again.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Persons' libretto is mostly effective, appropriately simple
in prose and even spiked with moments of wry humor. When Edward
tells his sister that he thought she was going to pray hard to
overcome her sinful desires, Patience answers, ``I meant to pray
last summer; I got as far as my knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kimper's score is earnest, but often misconceived. She calls
the work a ``folk opera,'' and its strongest musical moments were
when it sounded like onY+Q!MQA% !e59M9M &QC; 9M UQ5M-%5AIIUQ &QC; Q!MQ59M
! &QC;  &QC; 1 &QC; 5UM% QI%MQ &QC;  &QC; 5 &QC; I%9!IAIY% &QC; UM] &QC; I-M!5 &QC; MQ1eAI &QC; Y%%9 %9Q15UM%
</P>
<P>
   &QC; IQ!Q!QI9M  &QC; IM &QC; I &QC;  U59QI%M%Y9!I1 - &QC; aAI%9 ]%Q! &QC; AIQ!AI &QC; MA
