<HEADER>
A7703 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-LETHALWEAPON-TEX     07-09 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LETHALWEAPON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOURTH OUTING IN THE SERIES SERVES UP MORE OF THE SAME _ WHICH
ISN'T SO BAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it seems strange to think that ``Lethal Weapon 4'' is part of
a franchise that's now more than a decade old, it's even stranger
to realize how safe these ``Weapons'' have become. Once a mean
series with some funny moments, it has become a comedy series with
some mean moments.
</P>
<P>
   When Mel Gibson first played wildman cop Martin ``Lethal
Weapon'' Riggs, Riggs was a near-suicidal psychotic, sticking guns
in his mouth and keeping folks from killing themselves by jumping
off buildings with them. Now he's the class clown, doing everything
but sticking ``kick me'' signs on his partner's back.
</P>
<P>
   And he's growing a sensitive side _ he's gonna be a daddy,
although his companion Lorna Cole (Rene Russo from ``Lethal Weapon
3'') looks less like she's weeks from delivery and more like she
just decided to stuff that embarrassing load of dirty underwear
under her sweater. And partner Roger Murtaugh (Danny Glover) is
gonna be a granddad. This may be the noisiest movie to ever have
people cooing ``how sweet'' before the final credits.
</P>
<P>
   And boy, is it noisy, which isn't to say it's boring. It's about
as much stupid fun as you'd expect, maybe more after the
forgettable ``Lethal 3.'' Once again, Richard Donner directs with a
kick-out-the-jams attitude that simply says, if you keep things
moving fast enough, there won't be time for anyone to notice how
dumb they are. And, yes, when the movie hits the brakes, especially
in scenes in a dentist's office and the inevitable maternity ward,
it looks pretty dumb.
</P>
<P>
   If by now you're impatient to read some plot details, this
probably isn't the movie for you. More and more, the plots in this
series are beside the point; suffice to say that this one involves
some Chinese immigrant smugglers, a slave ring, some counterfeiting
and some very important gangsters. But really, the plot's just an
excuse to get from place to place _ or rather, chase to chase.
</P>
<P>
   Donner makes sparing use of Asian action star Jet Li, who plays
a formidable villain in his first English-language (and first
bad-guy) role. It may seem that Li is being underused, but his
whipcrack-fast speed may simply be too much for a Hollywood camera
at this point _ even in slow motion, this guy looks like he's going
faster than the speed of light, and he's really too much for the
aging Gibson to handle. To the script's credit, it acknowledges
this, but as we've seen before, no ``Lethal Weapon'' villain is
indestructible.
</P>
<P>
   If we don't see enough of Li, it's partly because of the
top-heaviness of the script, which is typical of the series _ every
new entry has added new characters, such as Joe Pesci's annoying
twerp Leo Getz and Russo's Lorna, and now Chris Rock is on board as
Lee Butters, a young detective who seems unusually fond of
Murtaugh. Put that many people into the mix, and someone's gonna
get cheated _ and that's just about everyone except Gibson and
Glover, whose chemistry remains the best thing about the series.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that and the action, which is often preposterous but never
yawn-inducing. The litmus test here comes when Gibson (OK, his
stunt double) is skiing down the freeway on the bottom side of a
dining-room table with Glover and a bad guy in hot pursuit. If that
makes you roll your eyes, you'd better skip Part 4. The rest of us
will be sitting there munching popcorn, adrenalin rushing and
brains happily turned off.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Lethal Weapon 4''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Richard Donner
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Mel Gibson, Danny Glover, Jet Li
</P>
<P>
   Length: 125 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong violence and language.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
