<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-MANS-TIME-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYING TO MAINE FOR A LUNCH OF LOBSTER ROLLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: optional sidebar at end of article) 
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The thing of it is not so much that thanks to my
neighbor, Howard Tedoff, we ended up flying to Bar Harbor, Maine,
just to eat some lobster rolls on a recent Saturday, but that we
got to experience rich man's time.
</P>
<P>
   A very long time ago, when I had an old third-hand Chevy with
cat's-eye brake lights that meant more to me than any car I have
since owned, my friends and I would leave Manhattan for what we
would think of as a day in the country and go up to Yonkers, N.Y.,
to have hot-fudge sundaes at the Adventurer's Inn and then play
miniature golf.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I was relatively poor back then, I think of those
outings as examples of rich man's time, when you can make things up
as you go along and squander time in the pursuit of whims.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that is what I thought wHen Howard, who lives three
floors below me, asked me if I wanted to go flying with him in his
plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where to?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere you want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pittsburgh?'' I asked, not really knowing why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pittsburgh is a nice flight,'' he said and suggested I might
also want to think about Tangier Island in Chesapeake Bay. ``They
serve soft-shell crabs there by the bushel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   We agreed I would come up with a destination by the time we left
on the following Saturday, weather permitting.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the soft-shell crabs he had mentioned, or maybe it
was the newspaper article I read about lobsters being at their most
delicious for having just molted that led me to think of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   I like Maine, and it lay far enough away to make for a
sufficiently extravagant one-day ramble. I recalled how last year,
a friend who lives in Boston had raved on quite a bit about finding
the greatest lobster roll in the world somewhere in Penobscot Bay.
</P>
<P>
   I called her, and she said absolutely I should fly to Bar Harbor
and then take a ferry to Frenchboro and look for Lunt's deli, the
home of the magnificent lobster roll. She said I should wash it
down with Moxie, the regional soft drink that traces its ancestry
back to 1840. Realizing that every journey needs a quest, it seemed
that lobster roll and Moxie would do fine.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the weather permitted, and at 8:15 on the
appointed Saturday morning we drove from Manhattan's West Side to
the Essex County Airport in Fairfield, N.J. Howard showed polite
enthusiasm for the brunch that lay ahead, but it was quite clear
that for him the real thrill was in the flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait until you see Penobscot Bay from a small plane.'' he
said. ``It is unbelievable. It is amazing.'' He has been flying for
20 years, and not only does he love the experience and sensations,
he wants other people to love them, too. He can talk about clouds
as gardeners talk about flowers, commenting on their size and
texture, and on the shade they cast on grasslands or water or wheat
or towns.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 o'clock, we were up, heading northeast, crossing the Hudson
near the Tappan Zee Bridge. The plane, a Cessna Skylane, was a
single-engine four seater. I sat next to Howard, and we talked
through the microphones on our helmets. Occasionally, our plane
would be called by the air traffic controllers who monitored our
flight to its destination, passing us along as we entered different
areas of radar.
</P>
<P>
   All the communications were wonderfully polite. We were
addressed by the registration letters on the fuselage, 7304T, only
the ``T'' was prounced ``tango,'' just as Smilin' Jack, the
comic-strip flyboy, would have said it. The voices from the ground
would occasionally break in and say, ``Seven three oh four Tango,
there's an aircraft approaching at 2,500 feet at 11 o'clock.''
Howard would say ``Thank you'' or ``Much obliged,'' and sure
enough, pretty soon we would see the plane 3,000 feet below us.
</P>
<P>
   Among the instruments in the cockpit was one that used a little
electronic screen to show us exactly where we were, with the
nearest airports marked. That was comforting, and so was another
device that scanned the region for storms. There was nothing of the
sort around. Indeed, there was not a cloud to be seen, which made
me feel a little bad for Howard. ``Maybe we'll have some clouds
when we reach the shore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The voice on the radio said that there was some turbulence at
5,000 feet, but that the air was smoother at 6,000. Howard asked me
my preference. I tried to read his mind, and guessed that he would
like to fly bumpy. ``Turbulence,'' I said, and from his smile I saw
I had guessed right.
</P>
<P>
   We were buffeted for a while, and it enhanced the sensation of
flying. From the controls, I could tell that we were flying at
groundspeeds that fluctuated with the winds from 140 to 165 miles
an hour. With no clouds whooshing by, you could not feel when the
plane was going faster or slower.
</P>
<P>
   The gizmos and the helmets and the radio were fun, but the best
thing was the view of the land spreading out, which looks very
different from 5,000 feet than it does from commercial planes that
fly much higher. It struck me that there was an awful lot of
forest, more than I would have expected, and that there seemed to
be more golf courses than baseball fields.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there were many more airports around than you notice when
you ride on the ground. Another thing was the Connecticut River,
whose meandering modest width struck me as very English.
</P>
<P>
   From our altitude, you could easily see cars, and sometimes you
could even see people, though you could not tell if they were happy
or not.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FINDING PRIVATE PLANES IN PUBLIC PLACES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A number of flight schools in the New York metropolitan area
will rent planes of varying sizes to licensed pilots. Hourly rates
for time spent in the air can range from $50 to $170, depending on
the size of the aircraft. Charter flights cost considerably more
(from $1,500 to more than $4,000, depending on factors like
distance and waiting time for pilots) because of federal
regulations about insurance and plane size for such trips. Here is
a selection of companies that offer airplane rentals.
</P>
<P>
   CALDWELL FLIGHT ACADEMY, Essex County Airport, off Route 80,
Fairfield, N.J., (973) 227-1707.
</P>
<P>
   MAC DAN AVIATION, Essex County Airport, off Route 80, Fairfield,
N.J., (973) 227-3625.
</P>
<P>
   MILLION AIR, Teterboro Airport, 485 Industrial Ave., Teterboro,
N.J., (201) 288-5040.
</P>
<P>
   NASSAU FLYERS, Republic Airport, off Route 110, East
Farmingdale, N.Y., (516) 454-0627.
</P>
<P>
   PROFESSIONAL FLIGHT TRAINING, Sikorsky Airport, South Main
Street, Stratford, Conn., (203) 386-1152.
</P>
<P>
   WESTAIR FLYING SCHOOL, Westchester Airport, Exit 2 off Route
684, White Plains, N.Y., (914) 946-0100.
</P>
</TEXT>
