<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNER PRIZE NOMINATIONS: NO OUTRAGE THIS TIME  
 VICTORIA AND ALBERT RENOVATION  
 TATE SEEKS A VAN DYCK PORTRAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Tate Gallery's announcement of the four finalists
for its Turner Prize, awarded annually to an outstanding British
artist under 50, has in recent years provoked outrage in the
contemporary art world.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, many people were upset that the nominees were all
women; in other years, experts were infuriated because painters
were not represented. Three years ago, the nomination and victory
of Damien Hirst was criticized because he had created installations
with dead animals.
</P>
<P>
   But when this year's names were released last week, there was no
outcry. The finalists included one man (a painter) and three women,
and there was little to get upset about in their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't try for such a well-rounded list,'' said Nicholas
Serota, director of the Tate. ``It just turned out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The four finalists for the $32,000 prize are Chris Ofili, a
painter; Sam Taylor-Wood, who works in film, video and photography;
Cathy de Monchaux, a conceptual artist, and Tacita Dean, who works
mostly in 16-millimeter film. All have had their work shown in
high-profile places, including the much-talked-about ``Sensation''
show at the Royal Academy here and at last year's Venice Biennale.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest is Ofili, 29, whose work was shown in the
``Sensation'' show. Ofili, whose parents came to England from
Nigeria, examines issues of black culture and sexual stereotyping.
Recently, he has been incorporating lumps of elephant excrement in
his canvases, inspired, he has said, by a visit to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taylor-Wood, 31, is perhaps the best known of the group. Her
work focuses mainly on human relationships. At the Venice Biennale,
she showed ``Atlantic,'' made up of video images in three monitors:
a woman's face, the woman sitting with a man in a restaurant, and a
close-up of the man's fidgeting hands.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Monchaux, 37, is known for her wall-mounted sculptures
exploring themes relating to the human body.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dean, 32, is fascinated by the sea, which is a central theme
in much of her work. One of her recent films, ``Disappearance at
Sea,'' was inspired by the story of Donald Crow-hust, an amateur
yachtsman who vanished whilg sailing in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of works by the finalists will be shown at the
Tate from Oct. 28 through Jan. 10, 1999. The winner will be
announced Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The V and A's Ticket
</P>
<P>
   The Victoria and Albert Museum is hoping to receive $36.8
million from the Heritage Lottery Fund to help pay for renovations
of its much-loved British Galleries. The galleries, which are 10
percent of the museum's exhibition space, include its famous period
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   They have not been altered since 1945, when Sir Leigh Ashton, a
former director, arranged them chronologically. The renovation
project is expected to cost about $50 million; $12.8 million has
already been raised from private sources. An announcement of the
Lottery Fund award is expected on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still the only major London museum that has not had a
major lottery grant,'' said Dr. Alan Borg, director of the Victoria
and Albert.
</P>
<P>
   The galleries explore the history of art and design from the
reigns of Henry VII through Victoria, and include 3,000 objects by
every important name in British design from Christopher Dresser to
Charles Rennie Mackintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are objects produced by influential workshops and
factories, including Dwight's Fulham Pottery, the Mortlake tapestry
workshops, Bow Porcelain, Spitalfields Silk Workshops and
Wedgewood, as well as items associated with monarchs. On view is
Henry VIII's writing cabinet and James II's wedding suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These galleries are worn out,'' Borg said. ``We've acquired a
lot of new objects over the last 50 years that haven't been
properly shown. We've also acquired a lot of knowledge about how
spaces can best be designed to suit different audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the lottery money doesn't come through, Borg said, the
renovation will go ahead, with a team already in place to do the
work. Alistair Gourlay, a London firm, will be the architect, and
two London designers will execute the designs of the spaces: David
Mlinaric, known for his renovation of Spencer House, and Dinah
Casson, an experienced museum designer.
</P>
<P>
   The plans include the installation of audio and video equipment
as well as new ways to show delicate textiles and costumes that the
museum has not been able to exhibit because of poor climate
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The period rooms will be arranged so you can actually be able
to walk through them,'' Dr. Borg said. ``Visitors will be able to
take a route so they can hit 50 of our greatest masterpieces.''
</P>
<P>
   The galleries are expected to close for renovations by the end
of the month, and the work is expected to be complete in the fall
of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Tate's Fair Lady
</P>
<P>
   A full-length portrait of Lady Lucy Percy, Countess of Carlisle,
painted by van Dyck around 1636, was withdrawn by Christie's just
days before an auction Wednesday because the Tate Gallery wants to
acquire the work.
</P>
<P>
   The auction was of art and objects from Wentworth Woodhouse in
Yorkshire, which were being sold by the Trustees of Olive, Countess
Fitzwilliam, sellers and heirs to the contents of Wentworth
Woodhouse. The government-owned Tate approached the trustees,
offering to accept the painting in lieu of taxes the estate owes.
Christie's estimates that the portrait is worth about $4.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in the nation's interest that the painting should come
into the public domain,'' said Serota, the Tate's director.
</P>
<P>
   The Tate has only one van Dyck portrait, of the Countess of
Spencer. But the one of the Countess of Carlisle is considered much
better, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the museum and the trustees can agree on a price for the
painting, the final decision is up to Chris Smith, the British
Culture Secretary, who oversees museum commissions.
</P>
</TEXT>
