<HEADLINE>
BYTE-SIZED NUGGETS FROM THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUTOMOBILE ART: People do strange things, and the Internet is
their platform.
</P>
<P>
   Take Don Hermes of Novota, Calif., and his Army Man Car. Hermes
has glued hundreds of plastic soldiers and figures to his Honda
automobile.
</P>
<P>
   Making it more bizarre: He has created a page
(www.crl.com./\Phermes/car) detailing his project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had wanted to make a statement with my car,'' Hermes said.
``It's just a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermes, a computer programmer, is pondering a title for the
project. His choices include ``Battle for the soul of a piece of
Japanese steel'' and ``When you write code for 15 hours straight,
you've just got to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter choice makes the most sense of this project.
</P>
<P>
   ADDRESSES OF THE RICH AND FAMOUS: Is it really good to have an
online database of personal and e-mail addresses of more than
12,000 entertainers, athletes, artists and politicians?
</P>
<P>
   ``We got hate mail saying we were members of the paparazzi,
which we're not,'' said Jordan McAuley, president of Los
Angeles-based J&AMP;M Publications, which produces Celebrity Addresses
Online (celebrity-addresses.com) for free or for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand how people are concerned, but our address
collection has helped many people'' reach celebrities for charities
or worthy causes, McAuley said.
</P>
<P>
   J&AMP;M Publications has published celebrity address lists since
1993, providing addresses to trade magazines and publishing houses.
Moving to the Web will allow more real-time updates, McAuley said.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what this world needs: Cyber-''paparazzi.''
</P>
<P>
   SO LONG, SINGING COWBOY: The best tribute to the late Roy Rogers
is at Alan Davis' Happy Trails Web site
(home.earthlink.net/\Padavis1).
</P>
<P>
   Davis' site has a ``Happy Trails'' sound file and lyrics to
Rogers and Dale Evans' signature song. It also links to several
other Rogers sites, including the King of the Cowboys' official
museum site (www.royrogers.com).
</P>
<P>
   On his site, where Davis is posting condolences he receives,
Davis writes: ``It may be a cliche, but Roy was truly an American
original. The world is a better place because of the messages he
taught children and adults.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Tell the kids that you need help in the garden this summer.
</P>
<P>
   No response? Tell them you want to make tussie-mussies or
hollyhock dolls.
</P>
<P>
   Some response? Mention bugs and pond creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Let them know that these topics are a few of the kid-friendly,
hands-on gardening subjects available for children at Garden.com
(www.garden.com).
</P>
<P>
   The Austin-based site has a series of projects that appear as a
regular feature called Kids' Gardening Camp. The projects focus on
the education beyond gardening, from vocabulary to reading
comprehension to measurement and math.
</P>
<P>
   This week's project is growing a vine tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes on computers for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
