<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      07-09 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MY OWN COUNTRY': FAILS TO RISE ABOVE DISEASE-OF-THE-WEEK FORMULA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mira Nair, the director from India, seems a bold choice to make
a disease-of-the-week television film. With ``My Own Country,'' on
Showtime's Sunday night schedule, she puts her own imaginative and
exotic stamp on the lumpen form, conjuring moments that satisfy the
eye and the heart. Ultimately, though, that form's limitations
defeat Ms. Nair (whose movies include ``Mississippi Masala'' and
``Salaam Bombay!'') and her familiar cast.
</P>
<P>
   This film is inspired by the true story (naturally) of a
dedicated doctor named Abraham Verghese, who confronts AIDS just as
it appears in Johnson City, Tenn., in the mid-1980s. AIDS, in this
version of reality, turns nearly everyone in its path into a noble
and eloquent martyr. The simplistic notion that the disease wraps
people in a cloak of polyester holiness, dispatching them to death
with self-satisfied smiles, trivializes the suffering it recounts.
</P>
<P>
   A quick prologue introduces Verghese _ born in Ethiopia to
Indian parents, trained in India and the United States _ who was an
intern in Johnson City. As the story actually begins, he has
returned to Tennessee with his Indian-born wife, hoping to find a
real home at last (hence the film's title, taken from Verghese's
1994 book about his experience). He has become the local hospital's
single AIDS expert: ``It's my only chance to play hero.''
</P>
<P>
   The good doctor is played by Naveen Andrews, who was the
romantic Sikh in ``The English Patient'' and the pleasure-seeking
prince in Ms. Nair's ``Kama Sutra.'' He looks appropriately dashing
and sincere as he eases the burden of his patients, who include
Glenne Headly, Hal Holbrook and Swoosie Kurtz, all of whom portray
heterosexuals whose contraction of the disease is plausibly
explained. Most of the film's gay characters remain even more
sketchily drawn than the straight ones, although Sean Hewitt and
William Webster _ as a middle-aged couple, deeply decent and deeply
in love _ manage to convey genuine emotion and courage.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning Ellora Patnaik turns the doctor's wife, Rajani,
into the film's one fully realized character. On paper, Rajani is
another stock figure: the lonely woman left at home with the
children while her husband marches forth to his great works. But
her eyes speak of soul-searing pain with an eloquence that the
script, by Jim Leonard Jr. and Sooni Taraporevala, never even hints
at.
</P>
<P>
   What really sets ``My Own Country'' apart is its visual
richness. As shot by Dion Beebe and designed by Phillip Barker, the
film thrills the eye with vivid colors in unexpected places. The
reds and greens of Rajani's traditional Indian clothing reappear in
furniture, on walls, on leaves and flowers, and even in the
intensified skies over Johnson City (portrayed, with cinematic
magic, by Toronto).
</P>
<P>
   Despite her palette, though, Ms. Nair can't create art on a
paint-by-numbers canvas. Like her hero, she doesn't make this alien
territory her own.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTH IN ADVERSITY: For his first film as a director, Dennis
Quaid has decided to stick with a reliable formula, a tale of a
salt-of-the-earth family that finds strength in the face of
dreadful adversity. Not only does ``Everything That Rises,'' airing
8 p.m. ET Sunday on TNT, aim unashamedly for the heartstrings, but
it also finds them and plunks out a pretty fair rendition of ``Home
on the Range.''
</P>
<P>
   The range is in Montana, and a piece of it has been owned by the
Clay family for generations. But someone has said a discouraging
word: debt. Jim Clay (Quaid) is in it up to his Stetson. He stands
to lose his vast acreage and his vaster pride when his son
(14-year-old Ryan Merriman) is severely injured in an accident.
Thanks to Jim's loving wife (Mare Winningham) and his devoted ranch
hand (Harve Presnell), the Clays prevail.
</P>
<P>
   There are no surprising twists in this script, by Mark Spragg,
but the ride is scenic, and the actors, especially Presnell, find
the souls of their characters (although Quaid may have been too
distracted as director and star to modulate his own performance).
The climatic sequence takes place at a rodeo. Will the Clay team
beat the odds? You'll guess. But didn't you guess the outcome of
the competition at the end of ``Babe'' and cry anyhow? Keep your
hanky handy.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MY OWN COUNTRY'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Sunday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Written by Jim Leonard Jr. and Sooni Taraporevala and based on a
book by Dr. Abraham Verghese. Mira Nair, director; Dion Beebe,
director of photography; music by Jeff Danna; edited by Kristina
Boden. Barbara Title, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   With: Naveen Andrews (Dr. Abraham Verghese), Glenne Headly
(Vickie Tally), Hal Holbrook (Lloyd Flanders), Swoosie Kurtz (Hope
Flanders), Marisa Tomei (Mattie Vines), Adam Tomei (Gordon Vines)
and Ellora Patnaik (Rajani Verghese).
</P>
<P>
   `EVERYTHING THAT RISES'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Sunday on TNT
</P>
</TEXT>
