<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MESSAGE WILL CONTINUE TO RESONATE THROUGHOUT CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 12)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7785 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     07-09 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MESSAGE WILL CONTINUE TO RESONATE THROUGHOUT CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 12)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Americans, who are accustomed to their
presidents traversing the globe and making solemn pronouncements
about U.S. relations with other nations, Bill Clinton's journey
through China probably was little more than a blip on the radar
screen of history.
</P>
<P>
   It could be seen as just another stop on the busy schedule of a
peripatetic president who attended an economic summit in England in
the late spring and who will visit with Boris YeltsIn in Russia in
early autumn.
</P>
<P>
   But for millions of Chinese, especially the young, Clinton's
trip was of greater significance. His message that democracy and
freedom are an inevitable part of China's future will resonate
through that vast country for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Long after Clinton's presidency has faded, there will be Chinese
who recall the excitement of hearing his televised policy
discussion with President Jiang Zemin and his address to students
at Beijing University. They will continue to be inspired by the
ideas set forth in their country by the leader of the world's most
powerful democracy.
</P>
<P>
   That should be especially true for those Chinese who have feared
that hope for a better way of life was destroyed in Tiananmen
Square in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Jiang directly on national television, Clinton noted
that he and the Chinese leader continue to disagree about the
``meaning'' of what happened in that tragic confrontation between
young dissidents and government military units.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe and the American people believe,'' said Clinton,
``that the use of force and the tragic loss of life was wrong. I
believe and the American people believe that freedom of speech,
association and religion are, as recognized by the U.N. charter,
the right of people everywhere and should be protected by their
governments.''
</P>
<P>
   For people who have lived under dictatorship rather than
participatory democracy, it can be an intoxicating experience to
think of a day in the future when they will be able to vote and
freely express their political views without fear of reprisal. If
Clinton's forecast proves accurate, the young Chinese who heard his
message will eventually fulfill the dream of those idealistic
martyrs who died in Tiananmen Square nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As if to demonstrate that such monumental change can occur,
Clinton next will visit Russia, where individuals retain vivid
memories of the long, bleak era in which their society was totally
dominated by Soviet totalitarianism.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, American leaders in various fields, including
nine presidents, encouraged people in the Soviet Union and in its
Eastern European satellites to cast off communist dictatorship and
seek freedom.
</P>
<P>
   It finally happened in the Soviet era of Mikhail Gorbachev and
Boris Yeltsin and the American era of Ronald Reagan and George
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In China, it might happen in the era of Jiang Zemin, who appears
to be a more enlightened and progressive leader than his
predecessors and who gave permission for Clinton's message to be
broadcast nationally to the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was chastised by some American politicians and
columnists for refusing to be more critical of Jiang and for
failing to inject himself and the United States into the
50-year-old dispute over Taiwan's claim to be an independent
country. In addition, he was accused of putting the economic
interests of America's great exporting industries ahead of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   He may, indeed, have done that because he is convinced that
trade and economic development are the keys to success in the 21st
century and that they will help produce more humane living
conditions in countries like China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is an accommodator. He is not a master of
confrontational politics. It would have been easy for him to
grandstand by attacking China's leaders and casting his lot with
Taiwan, but he decided it was more important to build a cordial
relationship between America and the most populous nation on earth.
</P>
<P>
   History must decide whether he was right or wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Since Theodore Roosevelt sailed to Panama in 1906 to witness the
construction of his majestic masterpiece, the canal between the
Atlantic and Pacific Oceans, presidents have found it profitable,
from the standpoint of international diplomacy and domestic
politics, to journey abroad and promote democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the trips have simply constituted gestures of goodwill.
Others have resulted in substantive agreements that improved the
climate for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the many words he uttered during his nine-day journey,
Clinton did not leave behind a single defining phrase that
distilled the symbolic significance of his journey and his message.
</P>
<P>
   In his rhetoric, there was nothing comparable to memorable
phrases spoken by two former presidents in divided Berlin during
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy electrified the citizens of that beleaguered
city in 1963 when he declared: ``All free men, wherever they may
live, are citizens of Berlin and, therefore, as a free man, I take
pride in the words, `Ich bin ein Berliner (I am a Berliner).'''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years later, Ronald Reagan achieved a similar impact
when, standing beside the wall erected by communists to divide the
city, he demanded, ``Mr. Gorbachev, tear down this wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Phrases that linger in the human consciousness are those that
cut dramatically through hyperbole and, in simple, direct language,
summarize the magic of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to know what, if any, words or phrases the
Chinese might recall from Clinton's visit. But his message should
be clear because it created a vivid vision of what could happen in
China's future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     07-09 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN
</HEADLINE>
   (ko) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TRACKING `ARMAGEDDON' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The most jittery place in town this week is at Walt
Disney Co. whose most expensive film ever, ``Armageddon,'' opened
to a disappointing box office and faces an uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   Although box office receipts for ``Armageddon,'' which opened
for the Fourth of July weekend, reached a respectable figure, $54.2
million over the holiday, it was below Disney's expectations. The
last two Fourth of July blockbusters were ``Men in Black,'' which
last year took in $79 million in its first five days, and
``Independence Day,'' which grossed $85 million over the same
period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A strong opening was crucial to the momentum of ``Armageddon''
because of the film's huge cost _ at least $150 million, and
possibly far more, with $75 million spent in worldwide marketing.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Disney executives even more nervous are two films
opening this weekend, ``Lethal Weapon 4'' and ``Small Soldiers.''
Both seek the same audience ``Armageddon'' does _ boys and young
men _ and the executives fear that these movies may shift its
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very competitive,'' said Jerry Bruckheimer, producer of
``Armageddon.'' ``Our picture has to have real staying power.
That's what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon,'' directed by Michael Bay and starring Bruce
Willis as a deep-core oil driller who leads a roughneck crew
seeking to destroy an asteroid on a collision course with Earth,
was hurt by several factors. Most important, a similar film, ``Deep
Impact,'' about a comet on a collision course with Earth, opened
two months ago and has emerged as a success, with $137 million
grossed so far. Also, the reviews for ``Armageddon'' were scathing,
although most teen-age boys don't follow the recommendations of
film critics.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Roth, chairman of Walt Disney Studios, acknowledged, ``If I
read some of those reviews, I probably wouldn't go.'' He insisted,
though, that ``Armageddon'' would earn a profit, largely because of
the overseas audience, which is expected to be substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer, one of Hollywood's most successful producers, made
it clear that the critics' reaction upset him. ``I made a different
picture than the one they saw _ I made a real entertaining popcorn
movie, and they didn't get that,'' he said. ``The same critic who
likes `My Dinner With Andre' is not going to have the same response
to `Armageddon.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I make popular entertainment,'' added Bruckheimer, whose other
recent films include ``The Rock'' and ``Con Air.'' ``If critics
don't like popular entertainment, they shouldn't be reviewing it.
Critics who review classical music and opera don't review popular
music, do they?''
</P>
<P>
   But the head of a rival studio, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the disappointing early tally for ``Armageddon''
was not the fault of the critics or even the film itself. He said
the blame should be placed on ``Deep Impact,'' which was made by
Dreamworks/Paramount.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what the lesson is of `Armageddon,''' he said.
``Don't be second.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCREAMING AGAIN  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Jamie Lee Curtis, then 19, made her acting
debut as the scream queen Laurie Strode, who was stalked by a
masked, knife-wielding maniac in ``Halloween.'' The film, directed
by John Carpenter, with in-joke references to other horror films
and plenty of scares, was an unexpected hit.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Halloween' is the movie of my career,'' said Ms. Curtis, who
added that when she walked down the street or went to the market,
someone inevitably asked: What happened to Laurie?
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, Ms. Curtis proposed a 20th-anniversary
``Halloween'' sequel to Bob Weinstein, co-chairman of Miramax with
his brother, Harvey, and head of Dimension Films, the company's
genre unit, which made ``Scream,'' ``Scream 2'' and ``The Crow.''
Bob Weinstein, who saw the original ``Halloween'' at the Eighth
Street Playhouse in Greenwich Village, when he was 23, quickly
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theater was packed, and it was the scariest movie
experience I've ever had,'' he said. ``I said, `Yes, the time has
come to do this 20 years later.'''
</P>
<P>
   The original movie left Laurie shaken but intact. In the new
film, ``Halloween H20,'' which opens on Aug. 5 and was directed by
Steve Miner (``Forever Young''), Laurie is the headmistress of a
private school, trying to put her life together after all that
mayhem 20 years ago. She is helped by her maternal secretary,
played by Ms. Curtis' mother, Janet Leigh, who screamed her way
through the great Hitchcock film ``Psycho.'' To no one's surprise,
the ``Halloween'' lunatic returns.
</P>
<P>
   There have been numerous sequels of ``Halloween,'' including
``Halloween 2'' (1981) with Ms. Curtis. She attributed the success
of the first film, and the strong audience reaction at previews to
the new one, partly to the believability of the characters in an
unbelievable situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laurie was a girl that everyone knew _ slightly repressed,
vulnerable, living in a little bit of a fantasy world, a real
teen-ager,'' Ms. Curtis said. ``In the new film I wanted this to be
a realistic portrayal of someone haunted by demons for 20 years. I
wanted to protect the integrity of that character.''
</P>
<P>
   Horror films don't often open in the summer, which is usually
reserved for action and family movies. But Weinstein is challenging
tradition by opening the movie in August, and the decision made
three studios shift dates: Universal Pictures moved its action film
``Virus'' from August into early next year; an MGM thriller,
``Disturbing Behavior,'' was brought forward by two weeks, to July
22, and Warner Brothers moved the Leslie Nielsen comedy
``Wrongfully Accused'' from Aug. 7 to Aug. 21. The studios didn't
want to collide with ``Halloween H20.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very scary,'' Weinstein said. ``Jamie Lee did not
come back for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ACTRESS AS PRODUCER  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Close, who has had a successful career in films, theater
and television, has just completed a Robert Altman film, ``Cookie's
Fortune,'' and is set to start making ``Mary Stuart'' in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn Close the actress is almost overshadowed by Glenn
Close the producer. Her company, Trillium Productions, has four
films in development, mostly at Walt Disney, as well as a
television movie-of-the-week and a sitcom. She's also set to appear
as Nellie Forbush in the Rodgers and Hammerstein classic ``South
Pacific'' on ABC next year. Ms. Close said that even though the
music would remain intact, the adapters of the television version
would return to the original source material, James Michener's
``Tales of the South Pacific,'' and place it in a more realistic
context, meaning that Nellie will be a more mature woman.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Close, 51, has been nominated for five Academy Awards as
either best actress or best supporting actress. She turned to
producing because while reading and developing scripts, she
realized she had a talent for developing material that may have
been suitable not for her but for other actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to create projects that are gifts to other
actors,'' she said. ``Sometimes I might be part of it, sometimes
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Close is one of only a few movie actresses who seem to move
effortlessly into television and theater. On Broadway, she has won
three Tony Awards, including one for her portrayal of Norma Desmond
in Andrew Lloyd Webber's ``Sunset Boulevard.'' On television, Ms.
Close most recently was an executive producer and starred as Col.
Margarethe Cammermeyer in the critically praised NBC film ``Serving
in Silence,'' for which she won an Emmy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I choose television projects very carefully, and I don't want
to be overexposed,'' she said. ``But my feeling is, good material
is good material. And on television, if something is well-written
and effective, it can have a huge impact, more than any other
medium. I did `Something About Amelia' on television, a
groundbreaker about incest. It opened a national debate. That's
what television can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Close said the ideal age for women in Hollywood is 24 to 35,
``and it's getting younger.'' Roles for women, she said, fall into
various categories. ``They're either other women or the wronged
wife, pretty much a cliche,'' Ms. Close said. ``There are a lot of
mothers, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Close, who has a 10-year-old daughter, said: ``Because of
seeing movies with my daughter, I've analyzed the more classic
cartoons, most of which are Disney. Generally, there are either
wicked stepmothers or no mothers at all. You have to remove the
mother in order to have a story because there's nowhere for the
story to go if you have a protective mother. In that way strong
women are problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Close seemed resigned, if not especially sanguine, about the
plight of women over 40 in Hollywood. There are options other than
Hollywood, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cut my teeth in theater,'' she said. ``As long as I can walk
and talk, I'll still do theater. That's the way I look at it. I
think of my profession as a craft. I choose to give it that kind of
respect. And wouldn't it be great if a big chunk of actors went to
New York to learn their craft before going into movies? It would
not only make them better actors but also inform their choices of
material.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
