A7824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LETHAL-FILM-REVIEW-NY     07-09 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETHAL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LETHAL WEAPON 4': BONES CRUNCH? JOKES FLY? MUST BE GIBSON AND
GLOVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coming attractions for ``Lethal Weapon 4'' boasted a chase
sequence in which Mel Gibson is dragged behind a trailer truck on a
crowded freeway. Brakes screech, drivers veer and vehicles go bang
while Gibson endures this nightmare until Danny Glover manages to
hoist him off the pavement at high speed. After this, the two stars
crash straight through an office building in their runaway car.
Pardon me for having groaned in anticipation of what, in the full
perspective-warping heat of the summer movie season, turns out to
be one of the nicer blow-'em-ups around.
</P>
<P>
   The characters remain funny and likable, and they all live on
Earth. The formula still has some zip. Scenes unfold with that
antediluvian, pre-MTV storytelling logic that some of us still find
helpful, and the story actually has a few substantial ideas in
mind. (It's pro-friends and family; it's anti-slavery.) These are
real virtues even if only relative ones. After all, ``Lethal Weapon
4'' is still a film whose idea of high drama is watching a car get
pushed in front of an oncoming train.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a flamboyant, tongue-in-cheek adventure fueled by
jokey camaraderie and constant forward motion. The fireworks start
so early that the Warner Brothers logo is the first thing to
explode. This is just a way of saying hello in the language of
violent escapist movies, but it's also a nod to the ``Lethal
Weapon'' gambit of scaling preposterous new heights of danger
whenever possible. So the film's opening sequence finds Gibson and
Glover in the midst of a fiery battle against a faceless enemy
who's straight out of a video game. Buddyhood demands that these
two discuss family matters and share a practical joke while dodging
the flames.
</P>
<P>
   If Martin Riggs (Gibson) and Roger Murtaugh (Glover) behave like
longtime pals, the audience has reason to regard them as old
friends too. This 11-year-old series has aged better than most,
sustaining its mix of crazy pyrotechnics, engaging characters and
easygoing rapport. Though it first emerged as one of the more
recklessly violent of action franchises, the ``Lethal Weapon''
formula has come to seem substantial, even venerable, beside newer
and dopier action-adventures. The characters have aged well and the
storytelling wisely made room for new blood.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Chris Rock and his nimble wisecracks have literally
married into the ``Lethal Weapon'' family. (Though the fourth
installment ends on a sweetly valedictory note, Rock helps to make
the prospect of further spinoffs look worthwhile.) Rock plays an
eager-to-please junior detective named Lee Butters who is secretly
Murtaugh's new son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   All Murtaugh knows is that his daughter is pregnant and that he
would hate to have her marry a cop. But Riggs knows the whole
story, which paves the way for the sadistic teasing that is one of
his minor specialties. While Butters tries to curry favor with his
father-in-law, Riggs convinces Murtaugh that the younger man is
making homosexual overtures. Hey, nobody said that these guys had
mellowed past the point of benighted jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Since Riggs' companion, Lorna Cole (Rene Russo), is also
pregnant, and a ruefully funny member of the series' regular cast
(she calls ``Here, boy!'' whether tossing a snack to Riggs or his
dog), the film spends some time on matters of impending fatherhood.
But it also has a murky smuggling plot in which to embroil the
detectives and their ever-pesty sidekick, Leo Getz (Joe Pesci), who
now fancies himself a private eye. Discovering a scheme to smuggle
illegal aliens from China to work as virtual slaves in the United
States, the detectives happen onto a web of trouble involving rival
groups of Chinese gangsters. The main point of this is to introduce
several hair-raising fight sequences and to find a way for Jet Li,
another handsome Chinese action star poised to impress
international audiences, to show off his footwork.
</P>
<P>
   As an equal-opportunity slugfest, ``Lethal Weapon 4'' allows
even the pregnant Lorna to engage in martial arts. And these scenes
are staged by Richard Donner, the series' one and only director,
with his familiar mix of nonchalance and lunacy. One of the better
sequences here has the detectives cornering a Chinese gangster at
his dentist's office and trying to interrogate him while everyone
in the room samples the laughing gas. (``I'm sleeping with my
wife's two sisters!'' the gangster acknowledges amid all the
hilarity.) And for sheer madness, a furious long fight between
Gibson and Jet Li extends the boundaries of bone-crunching for
aging movie heroes everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The series long ago took its name from Riggs' suicidal daring,
and that's still a strong reason why Gibson fits into this role so
well. He seems supremely comfortable with this mixture of charm,
kidding, bullying, boyishness and a tenderness so well concealed
that it's easy to miss.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LETHAL WEAPON 4'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Richard Donner; written by Channing Gibson, based on
a story by Jonathan Lemkin, Alfred Gough and Miles Millar; director
of photography, Andrzej Bartkowiak; edited by Frank J. Urioste and
Dallas Puett; music by Michael Kamen, Eric Clapton and David
Sanborn; production designer, J. Michael Riva; produced by Joel
Silver and Donner; released by Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Mel Gibson (Martin Riggs), Danny Glover (Roger Murtaugh),
Joe Pesci (Leo Getz), Rene Russo (Lorna Cole), Chris Rock (Lee
Butters) and Jet Li (Wah Sing Ku). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 125 minutes. This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon 4'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes blasts of cartoonishly
heightened violence at regular intervals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
