<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: COLLECTORS GO HUNTING FOR TAPAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before there was cloth, there was tapa, or bark
cloth, a primitive kind of paperlike fabric made by tribes in South
America, Africa, Asia and Polynesia. Now, centuries later,
collectors are drawn to these graphically patterned pieces and are
buying them as works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Examples of decorated tapa aren't easy to find; there are a
handful of dealers across the United States. But tapa is still
affordable and attracts both history buffs and collectors of
contemporary and ethnographic art.
</P>
<P>
   In Christie's ``Important Tribal Art'' sale in Manhattan in
November, for example, the first lot was a book titled ``Captain
James Cook,'' printed by Alexander Shaw in 1787. Its text was
attached to a collection of tapa specimens collected in Hawaii,
Polynesia and Tahiti during Cook's voyages. One piece looked like
calico, its beige bark punctuated by charming, flowerlike motifs in
earthy brown. Another had brown polka dots painted randomly between
parallel horizontal lines, intersected by red vertical lines to
form a grid. The book, with an estimate of $10,000 to $15,000, sold
for $43,700.
</P>
<P>
   Tapa is made usually from the inner bark of the paper mulberry
tree but can also be made from the breadfruit tree, the banyan and
the ficus. It is found in the Amazon Basin, Africa, Asia, Hawaii,
Polynesia, Indonesia, New Guinea and Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   It is made from bast, the fibrous skin between the sap and the
bark of the tree. When moistened and beaten repeatedly over a
smooth log, it becomes paper thin and soft. It is then decorated
with vegetal or mineral pigments.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony J.P. Meyer, the owner of Galerie Meyer in Paris,
organized a show of oceanic tapa at his gallery earlier this month,
selling a third of it. As he wrote in the illustrated catalog
(available at the OAN Bookstore, 15 W. 39th St., Manhattan):
</P>
<P>
   ``Tapa was the main type of cloth for most early Neolithic
civilizations. Its use among Oceanic cultures dotting the South
Pacific was not just functional and mundane; as a material it was
in its own right a sacred substance. Magic and religious beliefs
are of the utmost importance in its fabrication.''
</P>
<P>
   The Meyer show featured many tapa styles: a ceremonial apron and
spirit mask from Papua New Guinea; a fringed sash and an elaborate
red, black and white ornamental panel from Fiji; a coat of arms of
the Tonga kingdom, and a long white lioncloth from Samoa. Prices
ranged from $2,500 to $33,000.
</P>
<P>
   What makes tapa so attractive to Western eyes? ``It hits you in
the gut,'' Meyer said. ``Partly because it is NOT woven; it has
another dimension.'' Joseph Gerena, a Manhattan tribal-art dealer
at 12 E. 86th St., agreed. ``The attraction is primordial,'' he
said. ``Tapa is very tactile and a great medium for paint. It also
lets us see the imagination of peoples with limited technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Alpert, a tribal-art dealer in Dallas who lived in
Indonesia in the 1970s, said that while it was impossible to
decipher an individual tapa's meaning unless one knew the maker,
meaning was irrelevant. ``I look at tapa as art,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people learned weaving, cloth superseded bark,'' Alpert
said, explaining why tapa was so precious. ``It was all the rage in
Paris in the 1930s. Max Ernst, Jacob Epstein and Pierre Matisse all
collected it.'' Joel Cooner, of the Cooner Gallery in Dallas, added
that Henri Matisse ``had tapa cloth on the walls of his studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Alpert suggested that anyone interested in buying tapa should
first read ``Traditional Tapa Textiles of the Pacific'' by Roger
Neich and Mick Pendergraft (Thames &AMP; Hudson, $22), ``Patterns of
Paradise: The Styles and Significance of Bark Cloth Around the
World'' by Anne Leonard and John Terrell (Field Museum of Natural
History, 1980, $40) and The World of Tribal Arts magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Cooner warned: ``There's a lot of trash being sold. Use dealers
who guarantee what they sell.'' He said he had found his tapa in
London, not Nepal or Indonesia. ``The good material is already in
collections,'' he explained. ``It was brought back as curios by
military people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Martin, a by-appointment textiles dealer at 310 Riverside
Drive, has sold several tapa panels to the H.M. de Young Memorial
Museum, part of the Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco. The panels,
from Congo (formerly Zaire), were made by Mbuti Pygmies from the
Ituri forest. She likes Mbuti design because ``it isn't
symmetrical, but it's balanced,'' she said. ``The Pygmies are
wanderers, and the things they draw are related to their
wanderings.'' Her Mbuti panels, about 30 inches square, are $1,500
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Hurst, of the Hurst Gallery in Cambridge, Mass., recently
sold a very rare Tahitian tapa printed with impressions of ferns to
the Minneapolis Institute of Art. He said the ferns were soaked in
reddish-brown dye, then applied to the tapa. ``Only certain people
were entitled to receive tapas like this,'' he said. ``Tapas were
presented to important visitors, like Captain Cook.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Zarember, the owner of the Tambaran Gallery at 5 E. 82nd
St., Manhattan, grew up in Australia surrounded by bark paintings
in her family's home. Later she went to Papua New Guinea and saw
how people lined the ceilings of ceremonial houses with bark cloth.
She studied tribal art and now sells old tapas from Fiji, Tonga,
Papua New Guinea, Australia and Zaire.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Throckmorton, at 153 E. 61st St., Manhattan, currently
has two tapas from Samoa, one 68 by 47 inches, the other 58 by 47
inches. Each is covered with tightly interlocking patterns in dark
brown pigment and could be mistaken for a contemporary painting.
One is $1,000, the other $1,500. ``I found them in California,'' he
said. ``You can tell these are 19th century because of the thinness
of the cloth and the tightness of the designs.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Steele, owner of Fine Tribal Art at 87 E. Houston St.,
Soho, is one of the few dealers who also show Amazonia tapa. He is
selling an early-20th-century tunic he said was worn by shamans
from the Jivaro tribe. It is highly ornamented with polychrome
designs rich in imagery. Though there are fewer collectors for
Amazonian works, Steele's tapa prices range from $3,500 to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the building of Brasilia in the 1950s, no one ventured
into the Amazon interior,'' Steele said. ``Now the Brazilians are
turning their backs on their own culture. The cultures are dying
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Mott, a textile curator at the de Young museum, pointed
out that different tribes have different styles: ``The Ituri
designs are tightly composed and less static. The lines are finer
and the spaces are more interrupted by twists and turns. They are
exuberant and mazelike. Samoan tapas are looser and coarser.''
Speaking of the museum's Ituri tapas, she said: ``They appeal to us
because of our 20th-century esthetic. Some look like Paul Klee or
Kandinsky. The sense of life and movement in these tapas draws
people in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
