<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-PATROL-FUNERAL     07-09 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO TO ATTEND SERVICES FOR SLAIN BORDER AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno is scheduled to attend
funeral services Friday for two U.S. Border Patrol agents killed by
a murder suspect who was being sought by authorities in South
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Meissner, commissioner of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, will accompany Reno to the funeral masses
for Ricardo Guillermo Salinas, 24, of San Antonio, and Susan Lynn
Rodriguez, 28, of Harlingen. INS oversees the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave the ultimate sacrifice for their country. They have
our deepest gratitude,'' said Meissner, who was in El Paso on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Moore, 25, who ambushed the agents and was wanted for
killing two other people in an early morning shooting spree
Tuesday, was buried in San Benito Thursday. The town is about seven
miles north of the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is reviewing the policy that allowed the
Border Patrol agents to assist local officers pursuing Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``After tragic incidents like the one that happened in Texas, I
think one always reviews operational policies,'' Eric Holder Jr.,
deputy attorney general, told a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Holder said Justice officials were ``trying to figure out ways
in which you might better protect people who are doing those Border
Patrol functions.''
</P>
<P>
   While admitting that the Border Patrol's role has ``changed over
the years,'' Holder said: ``We will not back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to do the job that the American people
expect us to do on the border with regard to illegal immigration
and also the flow of drugs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting spree began before dawn Tuesday when, investigators
said, Moore walked into a Rio Hondo home searching for an
ex-girlfriend. The owner of the home, Margarita Flores, 53, and her
daughter, Dalia Morin, 31, were shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Morin, 22, Flores' son, was critically wounded. The
ex-girlfriend hid during the shooting and was not harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron County sheriff's deputies responding to the shooting
searched for Moore, last seen driving a white pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas and Rodriguez responded to a call for assistance and
drove their Border Patrol vehicle to the San Benito home of the
suspect's father and questioned him.
</P>
<P>
   When they were walking back to their vehicle, Moore popped up in
a nearby corn field and fired bursts gunfire from a semi-automatic
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas died at the scene. Rodriguez was airlifted to a
Harlingen hospital where she died from her wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron County Deputy Raul Rodriguez, no relation, was wounded
in an exchange of gunfire with Moore, who was mortally wounded when
other officers returned fire.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's father and brother were police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was the first female Border Patrol agent to be killed
in the line of duty. Salinas was a rookie and was still taking
exams to become an agent in the federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Meissner are scheduled to attend morning services for
Salinas in San Antonio, and afternoon services for Rodriguez in
Harlingen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
