A7841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PI-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-09 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PI-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NUMBER-FILLED `PI' IS SMART BUT HARD TO WATCH  (ko) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to be a math whiz to appreciate the heady notions
Darren Aronofsky tosses around in his homemade debut film ``Pi.''
The movie, made for just $20,000, offers a brash horror-comic
variation on a familiar type, the paranoid wild-eyed genius who is
so obsessed with proving a theory that he goes mad. Before he's
finished experimenting on his home computer, Maximilian Cohen (Sean
Gullette), the film's central character, has shaved his head in
order to plug his computer into a specific area of his brain.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Pi'' suggests a zany spoof of the Frankenstein myth, the
movie poses age-old questions about the relationships between
genius and insanity, mathematics and numerology, mysticism and
scientific truth. Such questions may have no clear-cut answers, but
considering them forces you to contemplate what exactly is meant by
the word intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   But as smart as it is, ``Pi'' is awfully hard to watch. Filmed
with hand-held cameras in splotchy black-and-white and crudely
edited, it has the style and attitude of a no-budget midnight
movie. Its ink-stained cinematography and jarring electronic score
by Clint Manswell can be extremely grating.
</P>
<P>
   Maximilian is the furthest thing from an advertisement for the
superiority of the intellect. Plagued by migraine headaches that he
treats by popping fistfuls of painkillers, he lives in a squalid
apartment in Chinatown and spends every moment frantically trying
to prove that the gyrations of the stock market are mathematically
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he has a breakthrough, he is besieged by representatives
from two different groups. A greedy Wall Street brokerage house
that has somehow got wind of his experiments offers to give him a
high-powered computer chip if he will go into business with them.
At the same time, he is approached by a Hasidic rabbi who is
convinced that the same set of numbers that can unlock the patterns
of Wall Street is also a code for uncovering the secrets of the
universe and learning the name of God.
</P>
<P>
   The thoughts tossed around in ``Pi'' couldn't be more opposed to
the movie's chaotic style, but that might be the point. We live in
a world where an obsessive irrationality may be a necessary
prerequisite to penetrating the cool logic of numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
