   &UR; TREATMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STROKE-DRUG-BOS _ Despite the enormous potential for reducing
the toll of death and disability, however, only an estimated 5
percent of stroke patients who might benefit are being treated with
the drug, a genetically-engineered clot-buster called TPA that must
be administered within three hours in order to work. One major
reason is the inability of many Americans to recognize the symptoms
of stroke _ dizziness, numbness, headaches, slurred speech, vision
problems or shortness of breath. Another is that many hospitals and
physicians have been slow to offer the treatment, which can cause
devastating harm if given to the wrong type of stroke patient. By
Thomas Farragher.
</P>
