A7872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-FARE-NYT &LR;      07-09 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-FARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY FARE IN NEW YORK: FROGS IN THE BRONX; SPIELBERG FOR KIDS;
WILDLIFE IN QUEENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAUREL GRAEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The frogs at Wave Hill, the public garden in
Riverdale, look as if they've hopped out of a fairy tale: the kind
in which a frog is really a prince. That's because they're several
feet tall and have thoughtful expressions not often seen on the
residents of lily pads.
</P>
<P>
   The only wizardry they've endured, however, is that of Charles
Smith, who created the frogs by heating and welding, rather than
casting, brass and copper. The frogs owe their green skins to a
chemical process and their smiling attitudes to Smith's
imagination. On view throughout the month, they have inspired two
family art projects.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Wave Hill will present ``El Coqui y Sus Amigos''
(``The Frog and His Friends''), a salute to the frogs of Latin
America. Not surprisingly, Puerto Rican frogs have their own
language and do not utter anything as indelicate as ``ribet.''
According to Jorge Crespo, the artist and author who will lead the
workshop, the frogs say ``coqui.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like birds singing,'' Crespo said. ``A legend has it
that the coqui song appeases the spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Crespo will tell frog stories _ two from Puerto Rico, one from
Mexico and one from Peru _ dramatizing them with shadow puppets.
Then families will make shadow puppets and perform their own plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll encourage them to do frogs,'' he said, but other
creatures will be welcome, too.
</P>
<P>
   On July 25 and 26, Jennifer Monson, a dancer, will lead ``Frog
Free-for-All.'' Visitors will make a frog mask or costume and take
part in a frog frolic, using Smith's sculptures as inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Coqui y Sus Amigos,'' Saturday and Sunday from 1 to 4 p.m.
at the L Learning Center, Wave Hill, West 249th Street and
Independence Avenue, Riverdale, the Bronx, (718) 549-3200. Free
with admission: adults, $4; the elderly and students, $2; children
under 6, free.
</P>
<P>
   A Spielberg Encounter
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Steven Spielberg films that appeal to children were
made before today's children were even born. For contemporary
youngsters, that has meant seeing big-screen adventures only on the
small screen, courtesy of a video store.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, however, they can watch Spielberg's gentle aliens
and enterprising explorers the way they were meant to be seen. ``A
Spielberg Summer,'' at the American Museum of the Moving Image, is
featuring every film he has directed as well as many he has
produced.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, for instance, there will be three showings of
``Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' a film in which the
outer-space creatures are so benevolent and intriguing that you can
only hope to blast off with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're showing is the special 1982 edition,'' said David
Schwartz, the chief curator of film and video. ``There are more
scenes in it with the aliens on the spaceship, and it's the edition
Spielberg prefers.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend also includes ``Back to the Future,'' a 1985 comedy
about a teen-ager (Michael J. Fox) who travels to the 1950s and
accidentally endangers his parents' romance (Spielberg was the
executive producer; Robert Zemeckis directed). Then there is ``The
Sugarland Express,'' an early Spielberg feature (1974) starring
Goldie Hawn as a desperate mother who helps her husband break out
of prison. ``It's one of my favorites,'' Schwartz said, ``and I
think one of the underrated Spielberg films.''
</P>
<P>
   All three films are rated PG. The museum's permanent exhibition
``Behind the Screen'' also allows you to play Spielberg: It
includes a segment in which you can add your own sound effects to a
scene from ``Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Spielberg Summer,'' weekends through Sept. 6 in the Riklis
Theater at the American Museum of the Moving Image, 35th Avenue at
36th Street, Astoria, Queens, (718) 784-0077. ``Close Encounters of
the Third Kind,'' Saturday at 2 and 7 p.m. and Sunday at 2 p.m.;
``The Sugarland Express,'' Saturday at 4:30 p.m.; ``Back to the
Future,'' Sunday at 5 p.m. Free with admission: adults, $8.50; the
elderly and students, $5.50; ages 5 to 18, $4.50; 4 and under,
free.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating a River
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers expect to meet almost anything on the shores of the
East River, but on Saturday the creatures there will surprise even
jaded residents: a boa constrictor, a black-footed ferret, lions
and a mermaid.
</P>
<P>
   They will all be part of the East River Festival, a celebration
in Astoria Park in Queens. And although they aren't native to New
York (the lions and mermaid are courtesy of Disney), the festival
will feature several animals that are. A peregrine falcon and a
Harris hawk, for instance, will be shown by the staff of the
Theodore Roosevelt Sanctuary in Oyster Bay, N.Y., which is also
bringing the ferret and the snake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to introduce people to the idea that New York
City has almost 29,000 acres of parkland,'' said Bram Gunther,
director of the Urban Park Rangers, the founders of the festival.
The exhibits ``help people focus on the fact that animals actually
live in these parks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights will include historical tours of Astoria,
music, dance, sports and ample food. For children, there will be
face painting, crafts and, at 6:15 p.m., a theatrical revue of
numbers from the Disney films ``Pocohontas,'' ``The Little
Mermaid'' and ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you missed the fireworks last weekend, the festival will
go out with a bang at 9.
</P>
<P>
   East River Festival, Saturday from 2 to 9 p.m. at Astoria Park
(enter at 19th Street and 22nd Drive), Astoria, Queens, (888)
697-2757. Free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
