<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Breezes from the north will import cool air with low humidity
into the Great Lakes States and interior Northeast on Friday.
Clouds and showers will accompany the arrival of cool air over
northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Northeast will have a mixture of clouds and
sunshine. Coastal areas will be seasonably warm until Friday night
when the cooler will arrive from the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Very warm and humid conditions will linger over the Southeast. A
front separating the sultry air from the cooler air to the north
will be the focus for afternoon thunderstorms in the Tennessee
Valley and southern Appalachians. Florida will be hot and humid
with scattered thunderstorms especially near the west coast.
</P>
<P>
   The heat will be unrelenting over the southern Plains, where
afternoon temperatures between 95 and 105 degrees will be common.
Clusters of strong thunderstorms will form at the northern edge of
the torrid air.
</P>
<P>
   Morning showers and thunderstorms over eastern Kansas and
Missouri will weaken as they drift southeastward. During the
afternoon, thunderstorms will develop again from western Kansas to
the central Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The interior West will be unusually warm, especially in northern
sections where sunshine will be most abundant. Farther south,
afternoon thunderstorms will form along many mountain peaks from
Wyoming to New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A few potent thunderstorms will erupt ahead of a cold front in
the interior Northwest. In the wake of the front, coastal areas
will turn cooler with gusty northwest breezes and a few showers.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SUN DOGS
</P>
<P>
   For a time on Wednesday evening, it appeared as though there
were three suns in the sky over northwestern Oregon. In ancient
times, the appearance of mock suns was seen as an omen. Today, it
is known that the brightly colored spots are caused when light from
the sun passes through the ice that comprises wispy cirrus clouds.
When sunlight passes through very small ice crystals, a halo
appears around the sun. However, when larger plates of ice act as
the prism, the complete halo is not formed. Rather, two spots of
light, sometimes called sun dogs, appear on either side of the
sun. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
