<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE MUST DECIDE ON DOMESTIC PARTNERS POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Time is running out for United Airlines to
decide whether to comply with San Francisco's pioneering domestic
partners law or to fight the ordinance in court.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, United has shied away from putting its high-profile
corporate identity on the lawsuit that is challenging the
13-month-old equal benefits law. Instead, United has left the legal
fight to the Air Transport Association, an industry organization.
</P>
<P>
   But the city's position is that if United wants to be exempt
from the statute, it will have to go to court in a separate action
to make its point.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed ordinance requires companies doing business with
the city to provide the same benefits to workers with domestic
partners as the companies give to married employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``By entering the lawsuit, United Airlines will prove it's
selected discrimination,'' Supervisor Leslie Katz, a co-sponsor of
the law, said Wednesday. ``They've spent a lot of time and money
recently marketing to the gay and lesbian community, yet they are
denying us benefits and failing to take true steps to recognize our
community.''
</P>
<P>
   United representatives have argued that the dispute isn't over
gay rights, but whether a city can tell a private company how to
manage its business. They say they want to avoid a court showdown
with San Francisco, but may be compelled to follow that course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly hoping that we don't have to do that,'' said
Sue Thurman, a spokeswoman for United.
</P>
<P>
   United's temporary lease for a kitchen and maintenance facility
at San Francisco International Airport is scheduled to expire Aug.
30. The city and United struck a deal in February 1997. If the
airline complies with the domestic partners law, the city will
extend the $25 million lease for another 23 years. If United
doesn't meet the requirements, the lease could be canceled, forcing
the airline to find another site off city property.
</P>
<P>
   United is the largest tenant at the airport and is responsible
for more than 50 percent of the passenger traffic there.
</P>
<P>
   United employs 20,000 people in the San Francisco Bay Area and
71,000 elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The company could provide no specific figure for the number of
employees who would be affected by the city's domestic partners
law.
</P>
<P>
   The airline wants the city to drop its demands until the courts
rule on the legality of the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman described the city's position as unfair. She said
Federal Express, another airport tenant with a new lease, wouldn't
have to adhere to the law's provisions pending outcome of the court
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should United be treated any differently?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dennis Aftergut, San Francisco's chief assistant city
attorney, said the cases are separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want United to keep their word. Federal Express didn't sign
a legal agreement saying it would comply on Aug. 30 or any other
date,'' Aftergut said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
