<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMD-QUARTERLYLOSS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMD has bigger-than-expected quarterly loss
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ AMD Inc. reported a larger-than-expected loss in the
second quarter, hurt by weak sales of specialized memory chips and
specialty semiconductors even as its shipments of microprocessors
outstripped expectations.
</P>
<P>
   AMD has counted on its K6 and K6-2 products, chips that act as
the brains in personal computers, to lead the company to
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   But as the company has improved its manufacturing operations to
crank out more chips, the prices of those chips have fallen in
intense competition from Intel Corp. and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made a major improvement on their yields and
productivity,'' John Lazlo, a PaineWebber analyst, said. ``Whereas
last year, you could chastise (AMD Chairman and Chief Executive
Jerry Sanders) for his execution, that hasn't been the case in the
last quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, AMD lost $64.6 million, or 45 cents a diluted
share. Analysts had expected the company to post losses of 20 cents
a share. AMD had a profit of $9.97 million, or 7 cents a diluted
share, in the 1997 second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sales fell $68 million, or 11 percent, to $526 million from $594
million from the year before.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter, AMD shipped 2.7 million K6 and K6-2
microprocessors, more than expected and 1 million more than AMD
shipped in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   K6 sales are rising because more PC makers are using its chips _
which cost about 25 percent less than Intel's _ in their sub-$1,000
PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AMD rose 12 1/2 cents to $18.12 1/2 in New York Stock
Exchange trading. The financial results were released after the
market closed.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's losses are part of an industrywide slowdown in the
semiconductor industry. On Tuesday, Motorola Inc. posted a $1.3
billion loss, citing weakening demand in Asia and a charge for
restructuring. Intel Corp., another bellwether stock for the chip
industry, will announce its earnings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said in a conference call Wednesday that the company's
results were dragged down by slipping sales and weak demand for its
non-K6 products. Those include chips the company makes for
communications and networking applications as well as its flash
memory business.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said that across the board, sales have been ``pretty
lackluster except for our microprocessor business.'' Sanders said
the company expects weak to flat sales on non-K6 products and will
only see a profit in the third quarter if the company can make $650
to $750 million, primarily in K6 sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Kumar, an analyst at Piper Jaffray, called that claim
``unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going now from a supply constraint to a demand
constraint,'' Kumar said. ``They may be able to increase production
by a million and a half in the third quarter, but then they hit a
brick wall. Intel's not going to let them pick up a million and a
half units a quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Kumar said he expects Intel to continue pushing its low-cost
Pentium II processor, Celeron, to undercut AMD's K6 lines. Intel is
also expected to counteract AMD's next-generation K7, to be
produced in Dresden, Germany, for release next year.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said AMD expects to ship 20 million units of K6 and K7
processors next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out of the reality system we're in,'' Kumar said.
``There's not a chance in the world Intel will let them get away
with 20 million units.''
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the year, AMD plans to produce about 3.5 million
microprocessors in the third quarter and about 4.5 million in the
fourth quarter for a total of 12 million K6 units for the year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Sanders said, sales of Windows 98 in late June have
begun increasing demand for PCs, which were ``dead in the water,''
for April and May.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
