<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEND-NETHAWAY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLAG BURNERS MAKE ODIOUS, PROTECTED SPEECH
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When my annual membership renewal notice from the
American Legion arrives, I always write a check and slip it into
the return envelope without giving the matter a second thought.
</P>
<P>
   I've always been happy to support the American Legion even
though I don't participate in the activities.
</P>
<P>
   When my 1999 renewal notice arrived the other day, it invited me
to look on the back to see what programs my dues were supporting. I
did. I wish my dues did not support one of the programs listed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of you and millions of past and present Legionnaires
there is . . . courage to fight for a constitutional amendment
against flag
</P>
<P>
   desecration.''
</P>
<P>
   I respectfully disagree with my fellow Legionnaires who support
making an exception to the First Amendment in the Bill of Rights
that says, ``Congress shall make no law . . . abridging the freedom
of speech. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The Flag Protection Act, already passed by the House of
Representatives and now in the Senate, would add a 28th Amendment
to the Bill of Rights
</P>
<P>
   that would declare: ``Congress shall have the power to prohibit
the desecration of the flag of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   I prefer ``no law'' limiting freedom of speech to an asterisk
directing readers to check the exceptions listed below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Glory'' is a symbol of America's liberty. People who
desecrate the American flag are making a statement about this
nation that properly outrages all citizens who love and support
this nation and respect the struggles made to preserve the
principles of liberty and freedom laid down by the Founding Fathers
in the Declaration of Independence and Constitution's Bill of
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the First Amendment's free-speech provision is
that it empowers the people to speak out in opposition to the
government and
</P>
<P>
   its symbols without fear of government restraints or limitations
on those expressions.
</P>
<P>
   Flag burning has twice been held to be speech by U.S. Supreme
Court decisions. The justices reasoned that flag burners were
making a statement that expressed a point of view about this nation
and what it stands for.
</P>
<P>
   I join my fellow Legionnaires and Americans everywhere in
disgust with such a repugnant and odious point of view. But what
outrages Americans
</P>
<P>
   about flag burning is the point of view the statement, the
expression, the speech not the act itself. After all, burning is
the
</P>
<P>
   proper way to dispose of the American flag. The difference is
the point of view of the person doing the burning.
</P>
<P>
   Desecration of the flag then means that government must
determine what the flag-burner was thinking and communicating when
he struck the
</P>
<P>
   match. In most cases that wouldn't be difficult to determine,
but it still is a form of political speech.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that proponents of the flag-burning amendment want to
change the Constitution to give Congress the ability to make an
exception to the First Amendment's free-speech provision is an
admission that flag desecration is speech. Otherwise, Congress
could simply pass another flag-desecration law and give the
conservative majority on this Supreme Court a third chance to
review the law's constitutionality. But lawmakers and
constitutional scholars know it would be a waste of time _ flag
desecration is speech.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean that two-thirds of both houses of Congress
and three-fourths all the states couldn't pass a constitutional
amendment giving government the authority to criminalize a form of
political speech most Americans find offensive. The government then
could use
</P>
<P>
   force to protect a symbol of America's liberty at the expense of
liberty itself.
</P>
<P>
   My fellow Legionnaires may disagree, but I think that's a
terrible tradeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
