r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKOLNICK-COLUMN10-COX     07-09 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOLNICK-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bodybuilder has to rebuild life
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The tear has a long way to fall,
slipping out Neal Keselica's right eye, over orbits and cheekbones
that were shattered, past the nose that was severed, the tongue
that was sliced down the middle and choking him, the jaw that was
split, the gums that lost four teeth.
</P>
<P>
   It falls to the floor of Delray Beach's World Gym, where
Keselica came Tuesday to try to feel like himself again, even if he
may never again look like himself.
</P>
<P>
   Not since May 2, the night the personal trainer was driving
south on I-95 in his Camaro. He had just passed the Southern
Boulevard on-ramp when a tractor-trailer truck cut him off.
Keselica swerved into the sandy median. His car fishtailed,
collided with the rear wheels of the truck, careened back to the
median and flipped over several times, landing on the remains of
its roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to get out of the car,'' says Keselica, 31. ``I
thought it might explode. I knew things were hanging off my face,
eyes hanging out of my skull. I grabbed hold of whatever was
hanging. I looked down at my nose in my hand, staring me in the
face.''
</P>
<P>
   A face not recognizable to a friend who was following in another
car, nor the paramedics who treated him at the Trauma Center at
St.Mary's Medical Center in West Palm Beach. Keselica's wallet was
left on the highway, with his shoes and socks. His parents found
them all intact.
</P>
<P>
   Neal had used hand signals to relay their phone number to
doctors, and Mike and Pat flew in from New Jersey, to see their
youngest of three sons disfigured, unable to see or speak, facing
hundreds of thousands in doctor bills, probably still alive because
his muscles cushioned his bones.
</P>
<P>
   Their handsome son, who worked to be that way. Narcissism? Sure.
A life devoted to the beautification of others, and himself.
Keselica trained, napped, lay at the pool. Not much else, other
than learning the latest in nutrition. ``A walking doctor,'' says
former roommate David LaMarca.
</P>
<P>
   The captain of his tennis and soccer teams in high school, a
graduate from the Florida Institute of Technology, a defensive end
for the Edmonton Eskimos of the Canadian Football League, the
author of Eat Right-Get Fit Made Easy, a former bodybuilding
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-3, 270-pound guy Bill Schiebl, general manager of
Gold's Gym in Boca Raton, thought might intimidate clients. ``A
giant physically, but an angel,'' Schiebl found after Neal rented
the right to work. He saw the most clients _ men, women, lawyers,
doctors, thin, fat, young, old. Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   A man so strong that his clients sought his counsel, on
everything. ``I knew them, they knew me,'' he says. ``I was their
pillar. Now I'm so vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   His size belied his sensitivity. He kept a calendar of family
and client birthdays, he always sent Pat flowers on Mother's Day,
he stopped charging some clients, particularly those with weight
problems. He wrote a letter three weeks after the crash, warning
clients, ``You're not off the hook!'' His ``spies'' would be
watching.
</P>
<P>
   He was referred so much business that he bought a condominium.
And yet, he had no health insurance. Just a list of names and
prices on his desk. Too late.
</P>
<P>
   That's why friends will hold a benefit auction tonight at 7:30
at the Surf Cafe in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   Keselica will undergo major facial reconstruction, which
includes rebuilding his nose with a bone from his skull. But that
won't be for at least a month. First he'll see dentists, and
ophthalmologists, and orthodontists, and pain management
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the doctors treat him for free, part of a mass
outpouring of community support. ``It's been amazing,'' Keselica
says. ``I was becoming a cynic, but I've become a true lover of
humanity. If this is what it took, this is what it took.''
</P>
<P>
   Clients, family and friends have referred doctors, driven him
around, opened a donation account, stuffed money in water bottles,
and organized the benefit that will be missing one special guest.
</P>
<P>
   One who sleeps in short shifts, who must avoid the sun, who
fears his nose will come off if he sneezes, who wakes up to cry for
an hour, then spends his day seeing doctors and cleaning his condo.
</P>
<P>
   At least he can see. And talk, though it hurts. He just can't
face seeing everyone. That hurts, too.
</P>
<P>
   With this face.
</P>
<P>
   ``People stare, out of compassion,'' Pat says, ``but they
stare.''
</P>
<P>
   They always stared. But in envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would break down,'' Neal says of his decision not to attend
the auction. ``I have enough sympathy for myself when I look in the
mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching tears fall.
</P>
<P>
   A donations account has been opened at Nationsbank in Neal
Keselica's name. For more information call Nationsbank at (954)
776-8000. For more information on tonight's banquet, call David
LaMarca at (561) 995-6674 or Mina Leyhan at (561) 997-2575.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
