r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-DEALERSHIPS10-COX     07-09 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-DEALERSHIPS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM dealers feel inventory squeeze from strike
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ A steady supply of 800 new cars once filled the lots at
Red McCombs Chevrolet-Geo, but these days the asphalt is mostly
barren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down to 165 new vehicles now,'' said John Depperschmidt,
the new-vehicle department manager at Red McCombs. ``Without a
doubt, we're in bad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The dealership on Research Boulevard in Austin is just one of
many General Motors Corp. franchises across the nation struggling
with dwindling inventory and parts shortages _ a ripple effect of
the two-month labor dispute between GM and the United Auto Workers.
Without a quick settlement to the strike, Red McCombs' supply of
new GM cars could be exhausted in 30 days, Depperschmidt said.
Likewise, Capitol Chevrolet, located on Fifth Street and Lamar
Boulevard, is down to just 22 new units on its lot, said general
sales manager David Howard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably live through July, but it's gonna be real ugly
in August,'' Howard said. ``We're looking at a 20 percent decrease
in sales, at least.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between UAW and GM representatives continued
Wednesday in Michigan. On Tuesday, one of the longest bargaining
sessions yet raised hopes that a settlement might be closer. The
strikes at two Flint, Mich., parts plants have shut down 26 GM
assembly plants throughout North America, including a truck and
sport utility vehicle plant in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Stephen Girsky of the Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
brokerage said he saw some reason for optimism in the tone of a
recorded statement made Tuesday by Donald C. Hackworth, vice
president of GM's North American car group. He noted that for the
first time the executive didn't attack the UAW's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a noticeable change in tone,'' Girsky said.
``It's different from what it has been.''
</P>
<P>
   But a rapid settlement still wouldn't spell instant relief for
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Local GM dealers estimated that 1999 model cars won't hit the
showrooms until six to 10 weeks after the strike is resolved, which
will almost undoubtedly postpone the debut of Chevy's new Silverado
half-ton truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking at early September, but now we're looking at
the end of October or early November, even if they settle today,''
said Howard, of Capitol Chevrolet. ``They've spent a lot of money
preparing this launch, but now we probably won't order as many as
we would have.''
</P>
<P>
   That stands to benefit the No. 1 automaker's chief rivals,
Chrysler Corp. and Ford Motor Co. On Tuesday, Ford cancelled its
owner-loyalty rebate program, designed to lure away GM owners by
promising rebates on certain Ford models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there's no reason for Ford to give up that money, so they
cancelled the rebates,'' said Tommy Perez, a sales manager at
Covert Ford on Research Boulevard. ``Our sales have been up the
past month, and I don't think we've really even felt the force of
(the GM strike) yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, GM dealers are tapping all resources to find
cars that fill the void. Howard said he has been stocking and
selling late-model used cars to try and make up for lost new car
sales. Other dealers said they have scoured locations across the
country in search of anything that diversifies the inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Still, customers are noticing the shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Ryan Hawken perused Red McCombs' lot for a
Camaro that met his criteria, but came up empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing out there,'' Hawken said. ``They don't have
what I want in the right color, (and) I'd like to buy soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales won't be the only casualty if customers like Hawken are
deterred by the small selection.
</P>
<P>
   With customers only trickling into showrooms, a full slate of
dealership employees are left sitting idle _ feeling the financial
pinch on their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Both Howard and Depperschmidt said their dealerships won't
change hours of operation and plan no layoffs. At Red McCombs,
however, a hiring freeze is in effect, though some respite may come
from transferring salespeople to other dealerships in the Red
McCombs chain, Depperschmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to lose employees, but there's a limit to how
far a dealership can go with paying people to sit around and do
nothing,'' he said. ``So it's likely that some might go to one of
our other stores that sells something other than a GM product, and
a few people are using this chance to take vacation time.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of GM parts affects even those consumers who
already own GM vehicles. Dealership service departments are
battling a backlog of orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been feeling (the strike's effects) for the past 30 days
on the service end,'' Howard said. ``We even have a couple used
cars in the lot that need parts that we just can't get right now.''
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
