<HEADER>
A7900 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUHN-COLUMN10-COX     07-09 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Master of Masters
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My first major golf tournament was the 1975 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jack Nicklaus' 79th in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Both newspapers in town had rookies on the golf beat _ Mark
Purdy of the old Journal Herald, and me here at The Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   We drove to Augusta, Ga., together, pulled down Magnolia Lane,
took a right turn into the old parking lot and went on to witness
something we still marvel about to this day.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Masters in which Johnny Miller and Tom Weiskopf
were at their peaks and there was Nicklaus, by then 35, and
everyone wondering if he was ready to cede his spot at the top of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   So came Sunday and there were Nicklaus and the two challengers
painting the scoreboard red, and now Nicklaus was on 16 with
Weiskopf and Miller over on 15 green, a couple hundred yards away,
watching. And Nicklaus spanked this 45-foot putt up and over the
hill to a back-right pin and the ball somehow went down, and here
came Nicklaus _ The Golden Bear _ running off the 16th green,
putter high in the air, leaving, as Weiskopf would say later,
``Bear tracks'' on the green.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour later, with Nicklaus finished at 12-under-par,
both Miller and Weiskopf had 10-foot birdie putts at 18 to force a
playoff. It was the highest of golf drama. And both barely missed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as we drove home, Purdy and I talked about what we'd just
seen and wondered if, as we thought, we might have just seen the
greatest golf tournament in history.
</P>
<P>
   But what did we know? We were a couple of rookies. We had
nothing to measure it against.
</P>
<P>
   We still laugh about it when we see each other because that 1975
Masters is indeed considered one of the greatest tournaments ever
by the historians of the game.
</P>
<P>
   That was my introduction to big-time golf and to Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   And that memory and a dozen others came flooding back Wednesday
when I heard Nicklaus was withdrawing from the British Open,
breaking his 154-consecutive major tournament streak.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered our golf writer, Bucky Albers, and I walking with
him for 72 holes at Baltusrol in 1980 when he won the last of his
four U.S. Open titles. I remembered that last grasp of glory in
1986 when at age 46 he shot a 30 on the back-nine on Sunday to win
his sixth Masters and mesmerize a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus has been, along with Babe Ruth, Jim Brown, Michael
Jordan and Wayne Gretzky, the defining athlete in his sport _ the
athlete against whom others will forever be measured.
</P>
<P>
   Including two U.S. amateur championships, he won 20 majors _ an
outrageous figure _ and finished second in 19 others.
</P>
<P>
   But you know, for all those wins, there is more to the man. Golf
is a game that lends itself to graciousness, but Nicklaus raised it
to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   Of all my memories of the man in combat, the one at the 1977
British Open at Turnberry, Scotland, stands tallest. He and Tom
Watson raced away from the field on the last two days, Watson
finishing 65-65; Nicklaus, 65-66. As they walked up the 18th that
last day, Watson's one-shot victory assured, Nicklaus wrapped his
arm around Watson's shoulder and told him how proud he was of the
way Watson had played.
</P>
<P>
   I keep a picture of that moment on the wall of my office at home
as a reminder of the essence of sport. The picture, clipped from a
magazine, is curled at the corners and faded, a fate Nicklaus'
accomplishments nor his legend will ever face. -----
</P>
<P>
   CONTACT Gary Nuhn by calling 225-2414 or by e-mail at
gary_nuhncoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
