<SLUG> BC-SELIG10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will ownership ties hinder Selig?
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Bud Selig is named baseball's ninth commissioner today, two
questions will rise like a Roger Clemens fastball:
</P>
<P>
   How much power will Selig wield and will he be looking out for
the best interests of the game or of the owners?
</P>
<P>
   Selig, who owns the Milwaukee Brewers, has been the ``acting''
commissioner since he was part of a group that helped force Fay
Vincent to resign in 1992. Vincent didn't always side with the
owners, who are expected to give Selig near-unanimous approval
today.
</P>
<P>
   Power is something Selig neither craves nor wants. His view of
the commissioner's role is in line with baseball's move from the
iron-fisted days of Mountain Landis and even the firm grips of
Peter Ueberroth and Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A commissioner is not czar sitting above the law,'' Selig has
said. ``Yes, a commissioner has a lot of power, but it must be
confined to certain areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig's daughter, Wendy Selig-Prieb, has been running the
Brewers since Selig became acting commissioner in September of
1992, and the plan now is to put the team in trust so Selig is not
in a position that could be construed as a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean there won't be skeptics, even among
owners. Chicago White Sox owner Jerry Reinsdorf has suggested
voting against Selig and bringing in someone with no obvious ties
to ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's office was created in 1920, when owners
decided they needed a strong leader to rebuild the game's image
following the 1919 ``Black Sox'' scandal, in which eight members of
the Chicago White Sox were banned from baseball for conspiring to
throw the World Series. The owners hired Judge Kenesaw Mountain
Landis, who ruled the game until his death in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Landis created a position of strength, but Ueberroth and Vincent
likely were the last commissioners to control the game _ and it
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people realize how the office of the
commissioner has changed since 1921,'' Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   Or 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Rockies owner Jerry McMorris said the commissioner
search committee turned up other candidates, but no other names
have surfaced and there is no proof that anyone besides Selig was
seriously considered.
</P>
<P>
   So Selig, 63, will have a five-year term, but he'll continue to
rule by consensus. It's a role in which he's comfortable, having
governed the game longer than the terms of the previous three
full-time commissioners (Ueberroth, Bart Giamatti and Vincent).
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back on the last five years, it's easy to make the
case that it's been the most active five years in baseball
history,'' Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   Those years include the game's lowest point since the Black Sox
Scandal _ a 230-day players strike that canceled the 1994 World
Series and led to a 20 percent drop in attendance in 1995 and $850
million in operating losses from 1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   But Selig has overseen healthy changes, including the wild-card
playoff format, interleague play and increased revenue sharing
between the large- and small-market clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Bud has done an incredibly good job navigating
baseball through tough times,'' Ueberroth said. ``He'll be
recognized one day by the Hall of Fame for his efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig faces three immediate issues:
</P>
<P>
   _ Marge Schott. The Cincinnati Reds owner was forced out of
day-to-day control of the team because of racist remarks in 1996.
The sanctions end after the season, but baseball officials are
considering a continued limit on her control of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Minnesota Twins. They're threatening to move because
Minnesota's government won't fund a new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pete Rose. Baseball's career hits leader, banned for life in
1989 following a gambling investigation by Giamatti, has applied
for reinstatement, which would make him eligible for the Hall of
Fame. ``I think Bart did the right thing,'' Selig has said.
``There's no reason to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the issues, Selig is ready for the challenge. This
after spending much of the last five years insisting he didn't want
the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meant that, I really did,'' he said. ``But as time went on,
many people came to me and said they felt this would be best for
baseball. And that, ultimately, is what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Boston Red Sox CEO John Harrington: ``He wants to show the
world he can be one of the best commissioners ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell, but as San Diego Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn
says, at least baseball has an official leader again.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, it's nice to know somebody's going to be there to
answer these questions, to give the fans peace of mind,'' Gwynn
said. ``The fans want to know that one guy is in charge of the game
and looking out for the game.'' The Associated Press contributed to
this
</P>
<P>
   story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
