</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phillips had better watch his soiled step
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ This sordid story of he said/she said will end
when Dolphins head coach Jimmy Johnson says it ends.
</P>
<P>
   And, at least for now, Johnson says it has.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonists in the soap opera are Dolphins running back
Lawrence Phillips and a West Palm Beach woman by the name of
Michelle Black. In briefest review of the situation:
</P>
<P>
   Black says Phillips punched her in the face when she refused his
invitation to dance at a Plantation nightclub; Phillips says Black
is lying. The Dolphins, after conducting their own investigation,
are satisfied with Phillips' side of the story (big surprise,
huh?). A police investigation is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   There, you're caught up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the notion that Phillips is a bad guy is hardly bubbling to
the surface for the first time. While at the University of
Nebraska, for example, Phillips was sentenced to a year of
probation and ordered to pay restitution for assaulting Cornhuskers
basketball player Kate McEwen, who happened to be his
ex-girlfriend. And that episode is only the ugliest of a long list
of incidents in which Phillips has been involved.
</P>
<P>
   But is it possible Black, who has a police record of her own,
has exaggerated what transpired during her alleged contact with
Phillips?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, absolutely ye$$$$$.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, desperate to establish a running game, decided
big-back/big-trouble Phillips was worth the behavioral risk when he
signed him late last season after St. Louis released him. Even the
hapless Rams and head coach Dick Vermeil, who coddled Phillips,
eventually tired of the constant baby-sitting chores.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, upon bringing Phillips into the fold, said: ``There's
one rule _ do what's right _ and that encompasses a lot. And I
determine what's right and what's wrong ... and it's not public
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's our J.J., ol' Judge and Jury.
</P>
<P>
   And here's what Johnson said Wednesday afternoon in the wake of
the latest occurrence suggesting a link between Phillips and
trouble: ``He related the incident and what happened and, with all
the information we collected, I believe him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing more than a coach trusting a player, however
prejudicially. That's nothing more than a coach protecting an
investment, however stubbornly.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the police investigation turns up information
contradictory to findings made by the Dolphins?
</P>
<P>
   ``If something comes up that I'm not aware of, then I'll deal
with it,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is Johnson will wait on due process, which is
right and good.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he'll continue to experiment at Phillips'
tailback position in an attempt to squeeze consistent production
from a group. Johnson is talking up the talents of one Ray Nealy, a
scout-team player last year, and says incumbent Karim Abdul-Jabbar,
too, ``stood out'' during summer camps. This year's first-round
pick, John Avery, is also present.
</P>
<P>
   Of Phillips, Johnson was less than effusive between Wednesday
afternoon's practice and evening's scrimmage. He said only that
Phillips ``has looked good'' and ``done a nice job.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that Johnson's method of sheltering Phillips? Or is it
Johnson sharpening a knife?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson took no one else's word on Phillips, who may yet win or
lose a roster spot based strictly on his performance.
</P>
<P>
   But if he has lied to Johnson, Phillips should know something.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be gone faster than he can say, ``Wanna dance?''
</P>
<P>
   (endit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-08-98 2301E
</P>
