<P>
   APPLE _ NEW YORK _ Apple opens its hardware to the universal
serial bus, making it possible to hook up many more peripherals to
the Macintosh, even a floppy disk drive for the iMac. Already
Imation, a spinoff company from 3M, is developing a floppy drive
for the iMac. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman) ETA: 7 p.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
   ATT _ AT&AMP;T confirmed Tuesday that it will offer Texas customers
of its One Rate and One Rate Plus plans credits for billings
through Aug. 31 who received virtually no notice for a 5-cent per
minute increase in their in-state long distance calls. However, as
of Sept. 1, One Rate Plus customers will begin paying 15 cents a
minute for in-state long distance calls instead of the 10 cents a
minute ``one rate'' plan the company advertises. (Hight, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS-SUNTRUST _ SunTrust Banks said second-quarter earnings
rose 11.9 percent fueled by trust, mortgage banking and investment
service fees. The results topped expectations by 1 cent per share.
(Chambers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA _ Delta expands its Florida discount division, Delta
Express, and ends Atlanta-Toldeo service. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GM-DEALERSHIPS _ AUSTIN _ A dealership on Research Boulevard in
Austin is just one of many General Motors Corp. franchises across
the nation struggling with dwindling inventory and parts shortages
_ a ripple effect of the two-month labor dispute between GM and the
United Auto Workers. (Cocks, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AMD-QUARTERLYLOSS _ AUSTIN _ AMD Inc. reported a
larger-than-expected loss in the second quarter, hurt by weak sales
of specialized memory chips and specialty semiconductors even as
its shipments of microprocessors outstripped expectations.
(Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
