<P>
   SOCCER
</P>
<P>
   CUP_ When it comes to dancing a samba or singing the
Marseillaise for Sunday's World Cup soccer championship between
Brazil and France, it's a no-brainer for Delray Beach's Haitian
community. ``We need Brazil. We're waiting for Brazil,'' said Venus
Pierre, 43, owner of Maxo Supermarket, where Haitian radio is
booming with excited talk of the big match -- the Superbowl of
soccer. Forget about France, Haiti's former colonial ruler
overthrown during the only successful slave revolt in the New
World. (Pickel, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE-TRAINER _ BETWEEN, Ga.--Jan Weisman doesn't whisper. But
listen to her commanding voice, with its sorghum-thick Southern
accent, carry across the stables at Wellspring Farm and it quickly
becomes clear that it ain't about murmuring into the animal's ear.
(Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/8. EMBARGOED UNTIL
7/12.
</P>
<P>
   SKOLNICK-COLUMN _ The tear has a long way to fall, slipping out
Neal Keselica's right eye, over orbits and cheekbones that were
shattered, past the nose that was severed, the tongue that was
sliced down the middle and choking him, the jaw that was split, the
gums that lost four teeth.
</P>
<P>
   It falls to the floor of Delray Beach's World Gym, where
Keselica came Tuesday to try to feel like himself again, even if he
may never again look like himself. (Skolnick, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NUHN-COLUMN _ My first major golf tournament was the 1975
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jack Nicklaus' 79th in a row. I thought it was the
greatest tournament of all time. But what did I know? I was a
rookie. I had nothing to measure it against. I still laugh about it
because that 1975 Masters is indeed considered one of the greatest
tournaments ever by the historians of the game. (Nuhn, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STODA-COLUMN _ DAVIE, Fla. _ This sordid story of he said/she
said will end when Dolphins head coach Jimmy Johnson says it ends.
And, at least for now, Johnson says it has. (Stoda, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SELIG _ When Bud Selig is named baseball's ninth commissioner
today, two questions will rise like a Roger Clemens fastball: How
much power will Selig wield and will he be looking out for the best
interests of the game or of the owners? (Graziano, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
