<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TEENDRUGS _ ATLANTA _ President Clinton launched a $2
billion, five-year media campaign against teen drug use at the
Georgia World Congress Center in Atlanta this morning. (JScott,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLITICS _ ATLANTA _ President Clinton also attended a
luncheon fundraiser for Democratic U.S. Senate candidate Michael
Coles. A look at who attended besided Coles and Georgia Gov. Zell
Miller, who didn't and how much money raised. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FIRES _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ President Clinton planned
to get a first-hand account of the fires today when he met with
homeowners and firefighters in Daytona Beach, Fla. Clinton wias to
speak at Daytona Speedway about 3:45 p.m. EDT. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT _ Clinton visits with firefighters and victims of
Florida's raging fires, sympathizes, doles out federal money, then
flies out to Miami Beach for a party fundraiser with plates going
for between $5,000 and $50,000. (Mac, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FIRES_ For 30 days and nights, a band of 200 _mostly volunteer _
firefighters battled blazes in Flagler County. They fought on the
front lines, they slept on the front lines, they ate on the front
lines, heck they were injured and treated on the front lines.
Tuesday, the tiny county's Emergency Management Director was hauled
off to the hospital suffering from either heat stress or
exhaustion. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BOMBS-RUDOLPH _ Members of the Southeast Bomb Task Force still
believe Eric Rudolph, wanted in the Jan. 29 bombing of a Birmingham
abortion clinic, is in western North Carolina. That conviction is
based in part, they say, on reports that Rudolph told people that
if trouble ever came, he would hide among the familiar shadows,
crags and cliffs of the Great Smokey Mountains where he grew up.
Information leading to his capture is worth $1 million in federal
reward. (Scruggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-HISTORY _ ATLANTA _ The NAACP prepares to hold its
national convention in Atlanta, we put into perspective how race
relations have changed since the last time the convention was here
36 years ago and what the hot topics and who the big names were
when the convention met here in past years. (Hill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20-25.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Convention opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   DNC _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton native Charles Bowling is leading
the Young Democrats of America at a time term limits make it more
imperative the Democrats groom young leaders. (Joyce, Dayton Daily
News).
</P>
<P>
   PAROLE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The Ohio Supreme Court rules that
authorities can do warrantless searches on people on parole. The
case stems from a 1995 Montgomery County case in which Lemuel S.
Benton, who was on parole, had his house searched after parole
officers saw him give ``something'' to a friend. (Chorpening,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-SCHOOL _ WASHINGTON _ A popular education program has been
scratched from the October space shuttle flight of Sen. John Glenn
because the astronauts are booked solid with a vast array of
science experiments. (Montgomery, Cox Washington Bureau) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WWATER-CHLORINE _ ATLANTA -- At least one pool at White Water
park failed chlorine tests during 16 of about 75 county inspections
performed since the park opened in 1983, according to public health
officials and inspection records obtained by The Atlanta Journal
Constitution. The inspection record prompted mixed reactions from
public health officials and experts. (Schneider, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PEACE _ WASHINGTON _ Israel's U.N. ambassador Dore Gold
reaffirmed Thursday that Israel views this week's U.N. General
Assembly vote to grant the Palestinians' U.N. delegation nearly the
same rights as those given independent states as ``largely
symbolic.'' Speaking to a Democratic group here on a wide range of
Israeli issues, Gold said the U.N. vote -- which passed ov
overwhelmingly -- represents ``no effective change'' in the PLO
status at the United Nations. Gold's remarks came a day before
Palestinian negotiators were set to arrive in Washington on Friday
for talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
(Abulhassan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-KUWAIT_ Army Lt. Gen. Tommy Franks, commander of the Third
Army at Fort McPherson in Atlanta and in charge of all U.S. Army
troops in the Middle East, recently returned from Kuwait and
assesses the protracted U.S. mission there and whether it's serving
its purpose to keep the unpredictable Saddam Hussein at bay.
(Martz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   USCHINA _ WASHINGTON _ The congressional investigation of
satellite exports to China is likely to expand outside Loral Space
and Communications and Hughes Electronics. At the urging of folks
like Henry Sokolski, head of monitoring nuclear proliferation at
the Pentagon during the Bush Administration, the select committee
that House Speaker Newt Gingrich appointed will look at defense and
makers of other high-tech equipment such as Lockheed Martin and
Motorola to see if national security was put at risk. (Carr, Cox
News Service)
</P>
