A7944 &Cx1f; gen-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BUDGETTHISISTH     07-09 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR JULY
9, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT 202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALASKA -- CHENA. The Army Corps of Engineers expects a project
to dredge the Chena River -- which was line-itemed out of this
year's budget by President Clinton -- to be restored. (Working.)
Gorman
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO -- CITIES. Cities straddling the Front Range were among
the majority of municipalities enjoying prosperity generated by a
strong local economy, according to a report by a Washington-based
advocacy group. Brown
</P>
<P>
   -- ANTHRAX. Already demoted and fined, and possibly facing a
discharge and court-martial for refusing to be vaccinated against
the biological agent anthrax, a Denver-area sailor serving in the
Persian Gulf recently reversed course and accepted the vaccination
series. But the battle over the vaccine may be far from over. The
sailor's mother joined a Washington-based veteran's group in filing
a lawsuit last week demanding that the Navy, the Army, the Air
Force and the Food and Drug Administration provide information
about whether the vaccine is safe and effective. The group also
wants to know whether the military illegally punishes personnel who
refuse the vaccine. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- LOANS. The Senate is expected to pass a bill
reauthorizing the Higher Education Act, lowering the interest rates
college students pay for their loans. In Connecticut, Sen.
Christopher J. Dodd estimates that the new rates will save the
average student $664. (Contingent on a vote today.) Maggi
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS -- BRIEFS. Column for Sunday. (Working.) Wallison
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA -- OIL. Oil company executives and Clinton
administration officials emerged from a closed door meeting on
Capitol Hill to with no agreement in sight on their dispute over
the federal government's share of oil revenues. Egbert
</P>
<P>
   MAINE -- BERRY. Following the outbreaks of food poisoning in
1996 and 1997 from Guatemalan raspberries, including five reported
cases in Maine, Sen. Susan M. Collins Thursday called for the
federal government to adopt stricter inspection controls of
imported food. Collins, R-Maine, led the second of four hearings
that are scheduled to address the safety of food imports. Leasure
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN -- CORRECTION. A month after President Clinton signed a
$200 billion transportation bill, Port Huron will finally see $1.8
million it was promised by the federal government to repave 10th
street, the city's second busiest street. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA -- IRS. Silver State lawmakers hailed passage of the IRS
reform bill Thursday, especially a provision in the bill to keep
hotel and casino workers lunches from being taxed. NOTE: STORY
MOVED AT 11:30 A.M. THURSDAY MORNING. Preston
</P>
<P>
   -- BIO WARFARE. A Russian scientist told a group of conservative
policy makers today that U.S. cities, including Las Vegas, are
vulnerable to an biological weapons attack. (Possible.) Preston
</P>
<P>
   -- REID. Democratic Sen. Harry Reid, who is in the race for his
life this year to stave off a challenge by Republican Rep. John
Ensign, seems to be looking past the upcoming race. Reid has
established a political action committee to raise money for other
Democratic Senate candidates in hopes to gather their support in
his bid to become the next Senate Democratic Whip. Preston
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- DEWINE-TELECOMM. (This will come THURSDAY.) What does it
mean for consumers when telecommunication companies and
entertainment companies merge? Will these information empires lead
to lower cable rates? Or higher phone bills? Or more corporate
evening news casts? The Senate Subcommittee on Antitrust, Business
Rights and Competition, chaired by Ohio Republican Mike DeWine,
held a hearing Tuesday to examine the convergence and consolidation
of telecommunications, entertainment and information industries.
Spoke to OSU and OU professors. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- DEWINE-IRS. An initiative introduced by Senator Mike
DeWine intended to provide tax relief for higher education
institutions passed the Senate, 96-2, as part of the IRS Reform Act
of 1998 Thursday morning. Baker
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- PRISONS. Inmate abuse and the competency of private
prison systems will be the major issues that Texas legislature will
have to face in reforming the prison system later this year,
according to a recent study. Herard
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
