<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-PEACE-0710-COX     07-09 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PEACE-0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI DIPLOMAT: ``SYMBOLIC' UN PLO VOTE COULD HURT STALLED
PEACE PROCESS
 &HT;    By Samar Abulhassan 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Israeli Ambassador to the United Nations on
Thursday reaffirmed that this week's General Assembly decision to
expand Palestinians' rights in the U.N. delegation was largely
``symbolic'' and does not change the PLO status.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a group here on a wide range of Israeli issues, Dore
Gold labeled the move as a violation of the 1993 Oslo peace accords
which could hurt efforts to restart the 16-month impasse in
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in May, 1999, the Palestinians declare a state instead of
negotiating a permanent status agreement,'' Gold said, ``they've
fundamentally abrogated the Oslo agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   His speech to the Washington-based Democratic Leadership Council
comes just a day before Palestinian negotiators are expected to
arrive here to meet with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. The negotiators, Nabil Shaath and Saeb Erekat, will
discuss the U.S. proposal for an Israeli troop pullback from the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Gold, a top advisor to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, said the Tuesday vote that gave the Palestinian observer
mission a nonvoting seat in the 185-member U.N. General Assembly
merely enhanced the Palestinian position as observer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symbolism is what created the great effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinians and others view the 124-4 vote, which granted
them a voice in the assembly, as a large step toward statehood.
They will not have the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer period, Gold said that a controversial
Israeli plan to expand Jerusalem's municipal authority was a
``local'' problem and not an international issue. The ``umbrella''
plan approved last month by the Israeli Cabinet would draw several
settlements and suburbs around Jerusalem under the city's
jurisdiction in such matters as planning and development.
</P>
<P>
   But Gold maintained that the plan, which is opposed by
Palestinians, attempts to strengthen Jerusalem as a city and does
not infringe on any borders.
</P>
<P>
   Gold also touched on relations between the U.S. and Israel,
which he said despite recent disagreements, ``are making a very
serious effort to bridge their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the difficulties, the state of Israel is determined to
make this peace process work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of terrorism, a theme which Gold said continues to
handicap the peace process, he said Israel would reciprocate once
Palestinians ``dismissed Hamas and the Islamic jihad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do our end of the bargain,'' he said. ``We're not going
turn land over for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
