<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7951 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPASMODIC-TWO-AZR &LR;      07-09 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPASMODIC-TWO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE CONDITION ROBS VICTIMS OF VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - When Norma Barer began having trouble speaking 40
years ago, she was told it was stress, it was nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors blamed her gender. Psychologists said it was all in
her head.
</P>
<P>
   Speech therapists attempted to retrain her voice. She tried
tranquilizers. She tried resting her voice. She was given
electroshock therapy. She was ordered to sniff noxious vapors.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing worked, and bouts of depression plagued her over the
next decades as her condition worsened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a horror story,'' Barer says.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the late 1980s that she finally received a
definitive diagnosis. Her problem was not nerves or being born a
woman. But it (begin ital) was (endital) all in her head _ in her
brain, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Barer is one of the estimated 30,000 to 50,000 Americans who
suffer from a vocal disorder called spasmodic dysphonia, in which
nerve signals from the basal ganglia area of the brain send
improper signals to the vocal cords, causing them to either squeeze
tightly shut or remain wide open, interfering with speech.
</P>
<P>
   Although spasmodic dysphonia can be rapidly diagnosed today and
is easily treated with injections of a medicine that temporarily
paralyzes the vocal cords, Barer believes that many people in the
past suffered horror stories like hers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 1950s. Barer was a young wife and mother of two when
she first noticed intermittent periods of voice failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, my voice would catch,'' she says. ``Sometimes
it was perfect. Other times, it was just awful.''
</P>
<P>
   She consulted a psychologist at Phoenix College in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all attributed to nerves, being a woman,'' she says.
When she was referred to a psychiatrist who concurred, ``I sat in
that chair and cried.''
</P>
<P>
   Barer herself began to doubt her sanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how desperate you get,'' she says. ``You'll
do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   She even agreed to five sessions of electroshock therapy,
performed by a psychiatrist who assured her that the procedure was
harmless. Though the therapy has left no serious impairment, Barer
believes that she suffered some memory problems. And the therapy
did nothing to improve her voice.
</P>
<P>
   Another doctor had her inhale some sort of gas _ she's not sure
what it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a nightmare,'' she says. ``I felt like I was
dying, like I was sinking into a deep, black pit.''
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre treatment also proved ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Barer feared that her voice problems would ruin her career as a
dance instructor. On bad days, she had trouble barking out commands
in the classroom. Students often had to strain to hear. For Barer,
the effort to speak was fatiguing.
</P>
<P>
   When she got a job teaching dance at Scottsdale High School, the
children learned that Mrs. Barer was a special teacher who taught
in whispers. They were sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to find help, Barer resigned herself to her condition.
Like others with spasmodic dysphonia, she learned tricks that help
facilitate speech. She avoided difficult words _ words with many
vowels. One man with spasmodic dysphonia, she has heard, even
changed his vowel-laden name.
</P>
<P>
   Some sufferers find that their voice improves when they sing. Or
when they scream _ which forces open the vocal cords. Barer says
she discovered that her voice sounded clearer at a higher pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you raise your voice high, it gets better. But you can't go
around talking like Mickey Mouse,'' she says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to find a career to fall back on if she had to quit
teaching, Barer returned to Arizona State University in Tempe,
Ariz., and earned a master's degree in counseling. That proved to
be an unwise choice. Speaking to clients for long periods was
taxing: ``I was a mess,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Again, she sought a diagnosis. Again, she was told that her
problem was psychosomatic, which she fiercely denied. In
desperation, she consulted a speech therapist in Beverly Hills, a
so-called therapist to the stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't take me long to see what a fraud he was,'' Barer
says.
</P>
<P>
   Saddened, she finally took early retirement from Scottsdale High
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty bad,'' she says. ``I was in bad shape, and I was
really depressed. I was on the verge of a nervous breakdown. I
retreated. I didn't want to see people.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband became ill.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1989, hope.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, who lived in Los Angeles, saw an article in the
``Los'' ``Angeles Times'' about a study being done in Dallas on a
vocal disorder whose symptoms sounded like Barer's. Doctors were
recruiting volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Flown to Dallas, Barer was accepted into the study and diagnosed
with spasmodic dysphonia. Doctors there were not treating the
disorder, but she heard of a program at the Mayo Clinic in
Rochester, Minn., where a new therapy was being used: injections of
botulinum toxin, or botox.
</P>
<P>
   In large doses, botulinum is one of the deadliest known poisons.
In small, controlled doses, it can be a safe, effective remedy for
sufferers of spasmodic dysphonia.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, the doctor heading those studies was her
son-in-law's cousin, Dr. Arnold Aronson.
</P>
<P>
   Barer traveled to Rochester and received her first injection of
botox _ a shot into each vocal cord.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of weeks, her voice was reduced to a breathy
whisper. She loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sounded like Marilyn Monroe,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a strong voice, but even its puny volume was an
improvement over a voice that was strained and cracked. During the
next month, her voice became stronger and soon sounded normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most wonderful thing,'' Barer says, her face
beaming. ``It was the biggest relief in the whole world. It just
lifted my spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Barer now receives botox injections every three to four months
at the Mayo Clinic Scottsdale, where Dr. Stephen Bansberg, an
otolaryngologist, has a client base of about 200 spasmodic
dysphonia patients.
</P>
<P>
   She received her 30th injection June 25. Bansberg injected the
botox _ 1.25 units into each vocal cord under topical anesthetic _
while Dr. Charles Adler, a Mayo neurologist, directed placement of
the needle using an electromyography monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure took less than five minutes, and Barer experienced
no discomfort. She calls the shots ``no big deal.'' During the next
few days, she expected her voice to weaken somewhat and then
gradually become stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Barer, who heads a Valley spasmodic dysphonia support group and
has served on the board of the National Spasmodic Dysphonia
Association, used to celebrate every recovery period. Now, she says
with a shrug, it's old hat.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean it's any less miraculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a thrill,'' she says. ``I'll never get over how
great this is. It's as if this big weight has been lifted. I just
love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barer is even teaching dance again. As a faculty associate at
ASU, she conducts a course called Learning Through Movement,
designed for elementary-school teachers. She also leads exercise
classes for mature women at the Unitarian Universalist Church in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``To have this treatment available,'' she says, ``has changed
my life.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
For more information on spasmodic dysphonia, call 800-795-6732 or
visit the Web site at www.dystonia-foundation.org/spasdysp. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
