<HEADLINE>
`WHATEVER': CLEAR SLICE OF TEEN-AGE LIFE BUT AN OLD PLOT
</HEADLINE>
   ( ko ) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lank-haired and sullen, and with a horsy face that can suddenly
bloom into an expression of secret, dreamy-eyed rapture, Anna
Stockard (Liza Weil), the central character of Susan Skoog's high
school drama ``Whatever,'' is a slightly older, more unsettled,
downscale version of Claire Danes' character in the television
series ``My So-Calle
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DICHTER-ANNIVERSARY-A     07-09 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICHTER-ANNIVERSARY-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISHA DICHTER AND CARAMOOR CELEBRATE 25 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Misha Dichter is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anniversaries are a peculiar commodity in the classical music
world. Concert programmers and record company executives believe _
and the anecdotal evidence suggests they may be right _ that when
composers reach even-numbered anniversaries, listeners become eager
to hear their music again, even if they've been hearing it all
along. Institutions and performers use their own benchmarks as a
reason to party, and that being the case, an anniversary of some
sort can almost always be found.
</P>
<P>
   The Caramoor International Music Festival in Katonah, N.Y., and
pianist Misha Dichter have found an anniversary to celebrate
together: the 25th anniversary of Dichter's debut at Caramoor, and
of an association that has included recitals, concerto
performances, chamber music and master classes every year since
then. For the occasion, the festival is building its programs
around Dichter this weekend, and has established the Misha Dichter
Piano Performance Endowment Fund in his honor. The endowment is now
at $50,000, but Caramoor's executive director, Howard Herring, said
he hoped to raise $1 million; it is meant to pay pianists' fees for
recitals, concerto appearances and special projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart now is very much in Caramoor,'' Dichter said. He
noted that he and his wife, Cipa Dichter, who is also a pianist,
have a house in North Salem, about 10 minutes from the estate where
Caramoor presents its 31 concerts every summer, about a third with
the Orchestra of St. Luke's and the rest chamber music, recitals
and jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, its direction is serious, and its scale is just
right,'' Dichter continued. ``As A &AMP;estival, it doesn't try to be
Tanglewood. And although we've ventured into master classes, it
doesn't aspire to be Aspen, in the sense of having several hundred
string players filling out the ranks of various orchestras.''
</P>
<P>
   Caramoor's celebration of, or with, Dichter includes his
performance Saturday evening of the Rachmaninoff Piano Concerto No.
2, and a chamber concert with works by Saint-Saens, Schumann and
Ravel on Sunday afternoon. His confederates in the chamber
performance will include his wife, with whom he has been playing
duo piano recitals since they were students in the mid-1960s; they
married in 1968 and have two sons. The other performers will be
Robert McDuffie and Nicholas Mann, violinists; Lawrence Dutton,
violist, and Carter Brey, cellist. Blythe Danner will join the
company to read Ogden Nash's descriptive poems for Saint-Saens'
``Carnival of the Animals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rachmaninoff Second is the first piece I played in public,
when I was a teen-ager and I knew nothing, and I still associate it
with feelings of being 15 and bright-eyed,'' said Dichter, 52.
``But that's not why I'm playing it at Caramoor. I suggested it
because it bothers me that everyone thinks it's a cliche, a war
horse. I don't understand that attitude, because for the performer,
the pieces don't get easier, and the discoveries remain fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a piece I've played hundreds of times,'' he added,
``but I'm still learning new things about it. A couple of years
ago, I was playing the Rachmaninoff Cello Sonata with Ralph
Kirshbaum. It's from the same period as the concerto, and it gave
me new insights, so that when I went back to the concerto I felt as
though I hadn't known anything about the piece until now. It just
cleared it up for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dichter was born in Shanghai in 1945 _ his parents were Jewish
refugees from Poland _ and grew up in Los Angeles, where he studied
with Aube Tzerko, who was a student of Artur Schnabel. Later he
studied at the Juilliard School with Rosina Lhevinne.
</P>
<P>
   His career began after he won the Silver Medal at the
Tchaikovsky Competition in Moscow in 1966, but that victory, along
with his fondness for Liszt, whom he has recorded plentifully,
typecast him as a virtuoso technician rather than a player
concerned with works that had deeper intellectual underpinnings. A
few years ago, he sought to redress that view by programming more
Schubert, Beethoven and Brahms in his recitals. His programs at
Caramoor this weekend touch on both the dazzling and the more
thoughtful sides of the repertory.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These days, Dichter said, he plays about 90 concerts a year and
confines his teaching to summer master classes, like those he gives
at Caramoor. The summer is also a time for freshening up his
repertory for the coming season, although he said that lately his
approach to this has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started performing professionally, 32 years ago,'' he
explained, ``I would make a point of learning two new concerti and
a new recital program every summer.'' He added: ``The repertory
really grows that way. But it's also exhausting. This is the first
period when I've mostly gone back to old, friendly pieces. I'll add
new works here and there _ I haven't played all the Mozart concerti
in public, or all of the Beethoven sonatas _ but learning so many
new works every year is not an obsession any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've also realized that there's life outside practicing. Cipa
and I went to Paris in May, for the first time unrelated to any
musical event. We dropped our bags, walked, had meals, rested and
went to museums for four days. And I thought, `Wow! That's what
people do!' It was amazing. It was a revelation to me, to not have
to ask: `Where's the rehearsal? Where do I practice?' I didn't see
a piano for four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then,'' he added, ``after four days away, it took me a
good two, two and a half weeks to feel myself again at the
keyboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is information on performances this weekend by Misha
Dichter at the Caramoor International Music Festival, Girdle Ridge
Road, Katonah, N.Y., (914) 232-1252.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM: The Rachmaninoff Piano Concerto No. 2 in C Minor (Op.
18), with the Orchestra of St. Luke's, Peter Oundjian, conducting,
at 8:30 p.m. The program also includes Dvorak's ``New World''
Symphony and Vaughan Williams' ``Fantasia on a Theme by Thomas
Tallis.'' Tickets: $20 to $55; benefit tickets, which include
dinner, the concert and a post-concert reception, to benefit the
Caramoor Annual Fund: $150 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM: Saint-Saens' ``Variations on a Theme of Beethoven'' and
``Carnival of the Animals,'' Ravel's ``Valse'' and Schumann's Piano
Quintet in E flat (Op. 44). Tickets: $25 to $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
