A7963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT &LR;      07-09 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUCTION OF RARE VIDEOS  
 INDEPENDENTS PREPARE NEW RELEASES  
 NEW VIDEO RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Going Once, Going Twice
</P>
<P>
   It just could be an original concept: the video auction. Later
this summer, Norman Scherer, a rare-tape dealer in New York, plans
to put scores of films and other titles under the electronic gavel
at www.videooyster.com, the Web site named for his company, Video
Oyster. For those movies no store ever seems to carry, the site
might become a good place to look.
</P>
<P>
   A video bounty hunter of sorts, Scherer has tracked the
hardest-to-find material, from out-of-circulation Disney films to
obscure cult items, for nine years. Now he's about to broaden that
approach by posting entire store inventories at his site and
selling them to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes will come from stores that are going out of business.
Proprietors will share in the proceeds and presumably get more than
they would by dumping their stock with tape brokers, Scherer said.
Dealers will submit lists of titles they want to get rid of and
these will be added to a master list at the site, which is updated
monthly.
</P>
<P>
   For $10 a month, anybody can bid on whatever they want. Bidders
might be individuals looking for special titles or retailers
looking for films to fill out their own inventories. Bids will go
up at the rate of only $1 at a time, which should give most
interested parties, private or commercial, ample leeway to compete.
At the end of the month, the highest bidder gets the tape.
</P>
<P>
   During the month one can look in on the progress of the bidding
and respond accordingly. Final prices are hard to predict, but
bargain rates could prevail for particular movies that relatively
few might want.
</P>
<P>
   Scherer said he suspected there would be more bargains than
bidding wars. ``No one can tell what's in demand and what isn't,''
he said. ``Everybody has their own top 100 films.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparing Releases
</P>
<P>
   This week, while most of the video industry is off at its annual
convention in Las Vegas, some of its best small operators are
staying at home and getting ready for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Few independent distributors prepare the ground more carefully
than Milestone Film and Video, a New York company. On Sept. 29,
Milestone plans to issue Orson Welles' ``Trial,'' based on Franz
Kafka's novel and starring Anthony Perkins, Jeanne Moreau and
Welles. The film, looking remarkably sharp and refurbished after
being transferred from a print made from original elements
recovered in Manhattan, is already in its slipcover with blurbs in
place (``Say what you like but it's the best film I ever made,''
Welles says in one.)
</P>
<P>
   Yoichi Higashi's fascinating ``Village of Dreams'' (1997), about
one long ago summer in the lives of rambunctious 8-year-old
Japanese twins, will be released by Milestone on Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the year the lineup includes ``Antonio Gaudi,''
a study of the Catalan architect (October); Hiroshi Teshigahara's
``Woman in the Dunes'' (October); Curtis Harrington's ``Night
Tide,'' with Dennis Hopper in his first leading role (October), and
``Sweetheart: The Films of Mary Pickford'' (November). Information:
(800) 603-1104.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   The Winter Guest
</P>
<P>
   Even the sea has frozen solid on the icy winter day that Elspeth
(Phyllida Law) drops in unannounced and unwanted on her recently
widowed daughter, Frances (Emma Thompson, who is actually Ms. Law's
daughter). Having resumed life in northern Scotland with her
teen-age son (Gary Hollywood), Frances is unreceptive to her
mother's emotional support. As a sort of counterpoint, Alan
Rickman's solemnly talky film weaves in the stories of three pairs
of villagers and ends on a warmly mushy note in, Stephen Holden
wrote in The New York Times, ``a fussy, sentimental exercise in
theatrical counterpoint.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997. New Line. $101.76. Laser disk, $39.99. 106 minutes. Closed
captioned. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sphere
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's Sharon Stone as the starchy biochemist Beth Halperin
down there in the submersible with the brilliant mathematician
(Samuel L. Jackson), the brash astrophysicist (Liev Schreiber) and
the reasonable team psychologist (Dustin Hoffman). On the sea
bottom is a strange round object that sucks in unsuspecting
scientists for some quick mind bending and sends e-mail bulletins
about its mood swings. Sounds extraterrestrial, maybe ``bigger than
Copernicus,'' as the story hype puts it. Anyway, it all gets
checked out in Barry Levinson's ``solid thriller with many showy
scientific overtones'' (Janet Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $107.37. Laser disk, $39.98. 133 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Illtown
</P>
<P>
   If it has no new twist on the old drug-deal-double-cross
formula, Nick Gomez's film does present a cool, dreamy gangster's
world with intimations of purgatory at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Dante (Michael Rapaport) and his lover, Micky (Lili Taylor), are
routinely peddling the stuff when their former partner, Gabriel
(Adam Trese), gets out of jail and, as the characters' names
suggest, rakes up memories of past betrayals. With no plot trails
to break, Gomez turns ``Illtown'' into ``a sleek metaphysical
experiment in visual style'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1996. Live. $83.33. Laser disk, $39.99. 103 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Swept From the Sea
</P>
<P>
   Xenophobic Cornish villagers mistake the babbling young man to
be a crazy person, but he's really the dashing Ukrainian adventurer
Yanko Gooral (Vincent Perez), who's washed ashore after his ship
goes down on its way to America. In Beeban Kidron's heavy-handed
adaptation of Joseph Conrad's story ``Amy Foster,'' Gooral is
nursed to health by a beautiful but strange servant girl (Rachel
Weisz). Despite a loud, determinedly romantic symphonic score,
Perez and Ms. Weisz strike sparks like a wet book of matches. Also
blame the film's soggy thud on ``too much rain, too many shots of
the churning sea and far too much music'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1997. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. Laser disk, $34.95. 115
minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   GREASE. It's summertime in the '50s and the romance is back
between the greaser Danny (John Travolta) and the wholesome Sandy
(Olivia Newton-John) in a 20th-anniversary reissue of Randall
Kleiser's adaptation of the Broadway musical. 1978. Paramount.
$14.99 in wide-screen and regular television format. $19.99 for an
edition with a CD and a booklet about the production. 110 minutes.
PG.
</P>
<P>
   THE FLY. During a matter transference a housefly gets mixed up
with a scientist in the teleportation machine, producing a man with
a fly's head and a fly with a man's head. It all makes ideal
material for Vincent Price, who stars with Herbert Marshall in Kurt
Neumann's cult film, with a screenplay by James Clavell. 1958. Fox.
$14.99. 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   THE FACE OF RUSSIA. In return for its icons, prose and music,
Russia borrowed political and economic ideas from the West. James
Billington narrates the three-part series shown recently on PBS,
which traces the Russians through a thousand years of spiritual
development, literature, art and architecture, music and, finally,
the films of Sergei Eisenstein and modern media. 1998. Home Vision.
Three cassettes, $79.95. 60 minutes each.
</P>
<P>
   A NIGHT IN CASABLANCA. Rick is finished in town and now it's the
Marx Brothers' turn as Groucho, Harpo and Chico tangle with
war-surplus Nazis. 1946. Warner. $14.99. 85 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
