<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WOMAN ACCUSED OF SETTING HUSBAND ON FIRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ An east Texas man was in critical condition at a
Houston hospital Thursday after his wife allegedly drenched him in
gasoline as he slept and set him afire.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at Hermann Hospital said the victim, William
Brocco, 35, of Bellville, suffered second- and third-degree burns
over 60 percent of his body.
</P>
<P>
   The man's wife, Carletta Brocco, 38, was held in lieu of
$250,000 bond in the Austin County Jail in Bellville, about 55
miles west of downtown Houston. She is charged with attempted
murder.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's sisters said the 1:30 a.m. Wednesday attack was the
second time Brocco's life has been touched tragically by fire.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Jody, now 9 and living with Brocco's ex-wife, was
severely burned six years ago as she and another child played with
a butane torch. The torch ignited the child's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel W. Leedy, an Austin County assistant district attorney,
said the latest attack occurred at the couple's mobile home. A
five-gallon gasoline container was found discarded outside the
residence, but authorities have not determined how much fuel was
poured on the man.
</P>
<P>
   After being ignited, Leedy said, Brocco ran to a neighbor's home
for assistance. He was driven to a Bellville hospital by private
vehicle, then taken by helicopter to Hermann.
</P>
<P>
   Leedy said Brocco, heavily sedated and breathing with the aid of
a respirator, has not been extensively interviewed by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Leedy said Brocco and his wife had filed simple assault charges
against each other within the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted murder charge may be taken to the grand jury as
early as July 22, Leedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know she was a strange character,'' Brocco's sister, Bonnie
Schrader, said of her sister-in-law. ``He said he either had to
beat her up or marry her. We kept telling him to leave her, but he
said he loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrader said her brother's marriage was characterized by
violent quarrels.
</P>
<P>
   A second sister, Doris Hampton, said the couple had been married
about 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had known her about four years,'' she said. ``He was kind
of outcasted from the family because of her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
