<HEADER>
A8002 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARNETT-NEWS-COX     07-09 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARNETT-NEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arnett claims to be nothing more than a puppet
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When is a TV reporter not a TV reporter but a mouthpiece?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question facing viewers in the wake of the brouhaha
over Peter Arnett's role in the creation of CNN's retracted story
on Operation Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett has said theTailwind story, which had alleged U.S. use of
nerve gas in Laos, was ``a producer driven show,'' that he was
basically ``the presentation correspondent,'' and that his role was
limited to reading scripts and conducting three on-camera
interviews with questions prepared by others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to lend my byline to the story,'' Arnett said.
That idea of Arnett as mere persona is in sharp contrast to how
many CNN viewers remember him: as the gutsy, independent reporter
smack in the middle of Baghdad _ alone _ on television screens
during the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett, a Pulitzer Prize winning reporter, pointed out that he
has ``always taken responsibilty for my field-action reporting''
and that the situation will not happen again. ``This is a lesson
I've learned the hard way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Peter Arnett wishes he had done the job he normally
has done as journalist,'' says Robert Lichter, director of the
Center for Media and Public Affairs in Washington. ``But it's
getting harder and harder to do that on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   With the increase in the number of shows, ``the real journalist
is being reduced to being a talking head. The old school really
does reporting as opposed to lip synching.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual in TV newsmagazines for off-camera producers to
do much of the reporting, or for on-camera reporters to ``parachute
in'' when the story is virtually done.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reveals the dirty little secret of newsmagazines,'' says
Lichter. ``The producers do work and the correspondents take the
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was business as usual,`` he added. ``There are so many
newmagazine shows trying to fill so much airtime that there is a
distribution of labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsmagazines are profit centers, he said. ``They've expanded
beyond the capacity of staff to do serious reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion of reporter as marketing tool prompted different
responses from those in the industry in wake of Arnett's reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   In a New York Times interview, Christiane Amanpour, CNN's chief
international correspondent, vehemently denied that she narrates
reports developed by others when reporting for a newsmagazine
program like ``Impact.'' ``I believe ... that a network
correspondent should be reponsible for what he or she says on the
air,'' she said. ``We have our face, our name, our voices and our
credibility, and threfore we should be responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Wald, senior vice president for editorial quality at ABC
News, echoed that belief. In ABC's system, ``if it's your face on
the story, you're responsible for it,'' he told the Associated
Press. ``The idea that a correspondent who sits there and tells you
something (but) in fact didn't know that before, doesn't really
know it and is just reading something is not a happy idea for
people in the news business and people who watch.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, however, that while most ABC correspondents are
deeply involved in the stories, there are cases where reporters
read scripts written by others.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hewitt, executive producer of CBS's ``60 Minutes,'' told the
AP that each on-air correspondent is assigned a team of four
producers and they all work together to develop stories. ``No story
goes on the air unless it has been signed off by a correspondent
who is satisfied that this is the story that he or she wants to
tell,'' Hewitt says.
</P>
<P>
   The old school of journalism dictates a more hands-on approach,
even in an era when competition from other media increases deadline
pressures. Marvin Kalb, a Harvard University professor who was a TV
correspondent for 30 years, remembers working with Edward R. Murrow
at CBS in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I went to Murrow, for example, with a story that was not
sufficiently checked out, sourced and clearly written, he would
just give it back to me,'' Kalb told the Milwaukee Journal
Sentinel. ``And I would be humiliated.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, he asks, where are the Murrows? ``It's easy to find
people very, very well paid. Celebrities, people who get sets in
restaurants and on airplanes. But that doesn't mean they're great
journalists; it just means they're very well-known journalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
