<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Lose yourself in a good book (such as war stories)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A former neighbor, seeking to enliven my convalescence from a
recent hospital trip, called to ask if I read romance fiction. I
hated to tell her, but love stories usually embarrass me. It's not
that I'm opposed to love. I value it in people and in dogs _ but
seldom in books. I prefer war and murder and suspense. How do you
tell a kind, romantic-minded lady that?
</P>
<P>
   We chatted about recent novels and autobiographies where, I
admitted, a modicum of love is acceptable. But I don't think she
saw any reason for my turning down 28 love stories she has. I
finally said I would accept them for the firehouse library we have
at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, while I was visiting my son, I lucked into a copy of a
1964 Reader's Digest collection called ``Secrets and Spies'' of
World War II. My son and I were attracted to this book (we each
found a copy at the Habitat for Humanity thrift store in Marianna,
Fla.) because it has a short piece about a German sea raider with a
connection with our family. A German sea captain we knew named
Robert Rogge painted the ship picture my son has over his mantel.
My parents knew him.
</P>
<P>
   He had an American wife, an old friend of my mother's from
Florala, Ala., and everybody was puzzled when he disappeared at the
beginning of World War II. There were rumors he had rejoined the
German Navy, and even reports from people who claimed to have seen
him with a group from a submarine which allegedly made a stop in
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Bernhard Rogge in ``Secrets and Spies'' may or may not have been
our friend, but we liked reading about his strange deceptions and
exploits on the high seas during the war. He could make his heavily
armed ship look like a Norwegian or Chinese merchantman, and he was
famous for rescuing the officers and crews of the ships he sank.
There are a lot of good World War II stories in this book, some old
and rereadable, like Cornelius Ryan's ``The Longest Day,'' some
personal tales by people who were in the war.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorites is about the effort of the Germans to train
civilian German sympathizers to infiltrate the Allies armies,
wearing the uniforms from dead or captured American soldiers and
peppering their talk with expressions like, ``Okay, butch!'' The
would-be spies were not particularly competent, it turned out, and
they were surprisingly easy to detect. One of the tests they
flunked had these questions: ``Who is the brown bomber? What is the
Windy City? Who is `The Voice?' Who are `dem bums'?''
</P>
<P>
   I tried these questions on my children, and they passed, but I
was in doubt about the Windy City, and I wonder if today's
teenagers could answer the questions at all.
</P>
<P>
   There are many stories in the book that might be new to them. Do
they know who Rudolph Hess was? The strange death of the Germans'
field marshal Erwin Rommel engrossed me far more than any love
story. I guess I had long known he was a suspect in the plot to
assassinate Hitler, but I didn't remember that he was actually
murdered. And such a hero to the Germans, admired for his military
genius by even his enemies, and at home during the Normandy
invasion because it happened to be his wife's birthday. Now you
know that's a good story.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old book. My son says it often shows up in secondhand
stores. But if I'm ever again stranded somewhere with nothing to
read, I hope it's at hand instead of 28 romances.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
