r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SMOKE-COX     07-09 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SMOKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low-budget `Smoke Signals' is flying high
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's said that John Wayne once walked up to an Indian extra on
the set of one of his westerns and asked, ``Say, didn't I kill you
12 movies ago?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals,'' winner of two awards at this year's Sundance
Film Festival, gets the Duke back with its own barrage of ``Injun''
jokes. This time, though, the Indians are telling them.
</P>
<P>
   Based on ``The Lone Ranger and Tonto Fistfight in Heaven,'' a
1993 best seller by Sherman Alexie, and directed by Chris Eyre, a
28-year-old Cheyenne-Arapaho Indian, ``Smoke Signals'' is a road
movie with an acid sense of humor and a heritage-ridden theme
that's as universal as it is specific.
</P>
<P>
   Low-budget and low-key, ``Smoke Signals'' offers a short
prologue. In 1976, a Fourth of July celebration on the dilapidated
Coeur d'Alene Reservation in the Northwest turns tragic when a
house burns, killing the adults inside. But their baby, Thomas, is
tossed out a window and lands in the arms of Arnold Joseph (Gary
Farmer).
</P>
<P>
   Skip to the present. Arnold, a philosophical, eccentric
alcoholic, has long since skipped town, abandoning his family. Now
word comes that he died in Arizona. His son, Victor (Adam Beach),
sets out to fetch the body. His unwanted but persistent traveling
companion is the now-grown Thomas (Evan Adams), who, thanks to his
miraculous rescue, regards Arnold as a spiritual father.
</P>
<P>
   The pair make Jack Lemmon and Walter Matthau look like the Even
Couple. Victor is handsome, self-sufficient and reserved, with a
chip on his shoulder about his ethnicity and a smoldering
resentment toward the father who deserted him. Thomas is a
talkative nerd who worships Victor and ``entertains'' him with
nonstop tall tales.
</P>
<P>
   The trip provides a coming of age for both young men, who, in
their very different ways, make journeys of acceptance,
self-awareness and forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar from such movies as ``Dead Man'' and ``Pow-Wow
Highway,'' Farmer has a small role but a solid, anchoring presence
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the film, though, is carried by the relatively
inexperienced Beach and Adams. Like their fledgling director, they
manage just fine.
</P>
<P>
   The picture has a honed casualness that's reminiscent of many
early-1970s flicks, with a fluidity bordering on sloppiness and a
rough-around-the-edges narrative that surrounds pointed insights.
It even invokes a catch phrase from 1970's ``Little Big Man,'' in
which Chief Dan George, an Oscar nominee, kept telling adopted son
Dustin Hoffman, ``It's a good day to die.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Smoke Signals,'' the phrase has a '90s spin: ``It's a good
day to be indigenous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Adam Beach, Evan Adams and Gary Farmer. Directed by
Chris Eyre. Rated PG-13 for vulgar language and alcohol abuse. 1
hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Rambling and rough around the edges, but definitely
worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
