r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBAF-FILM-COX     07-09 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-FILM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thoughtful programming offers entertainment and information
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--You can just sit and watch the movie ... but if you do,
you'll be missing out on the full experience of the National Black
Arts Festival's film and video programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to give people experiences that are entertaining but
also interactive in some sense,'' says Cheryl Chisholm, who
co-curated the film/video portion of the NBAF with documentary
filmmaker Louis Massiah.
</P>
<P>
   So sure, you may be most interested in checking out ``Homage''
to see what four noted African-American filmmakers (including
Charles Burnett) came up with in short films commissioned
specifically by the NBAF. ``This is the first time we could
commission something,'' says Chisholm of films so new even she
hasn't seen them yet. ``It will be very exciting to see what these
filmmakers have come up with, shooting only one reel.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers will also get the chance to see Vibe magazine critic
Harry Allen and Village Voice critic Greg Tate present separate
programs on the aesthetics of music video.
</P>
<P>
   Another new feature of the festival are three workshops about
the business of film, facilitated by three guys who know what
they're talking about. Paris Qualles (``Tuskegee Airmen'' and ``Law
&AMP; Order'') explores the art of writing for the screen. Actor
Charles S. Dutton will talk about making the switch from acting to
directing. And producer Monty Ross, who worked with Spike Lee on
Lee's first six movies, will deal with his area of the business.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a rare screening of Elois Gist's silent film
``Hellbound Train,'' shown with live accompaniment. Chisholm
explains, ``I wanted to bring some audience awareness to the
festival, in terms of the importance of black film preservation.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if you don't find something interesting in the
NBAF's film and video offerings, you're not paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field is so huge when you talk about black film and
video,'' she adds. ``Lou and I wanted to give audiences a sense of
the full scope of what's going on. We may not have succeeded, but
almost.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
