A8006 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBAF-JAM-COX     07-09 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-JAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National Black Arts Festival: At the stroke of midnight, a
cultural spark will ignite a very different after-hours party
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--As much a social event as an aesthetic exercise, the
midnight jam sessions that begin tonight as part of the National
Black Arts Festival mark some rare opportunities. The loosely
structured, $10 programs, staged in the main ballroom of the
Renaissance Atlanta Hotel, are like big after-hours parties where
everyone unwinds _ or rewinds _ after a marathon day of readings,
performances and concerts. (For more information, call
404-817-8700.)
</P>
<P>
   The jams are more than a chance to rub shoulders with visiting
culturati, likely to be hoisting cocktails and catching up with
friends and colleagues they last saw in Berlin or San Francisco or
at the last NBAF gathering. The jams are the festival's informal
forum for the kind of free-flowing cross talk that really defines a
culture and a cultural moment.
</P>
<P>
   That cultural moment might take awhile to announce itself.
Though a diverse mix of musicians are scheduled to perform on each
of eight themed evenings, previous festivals have seen complete
ensembles spontaneously materialize well after 2 a.m. It happened
the last time tenor saxophonist David Murray played the fest,
fronting a ragged yet spirited set that was unexpectedly bum-rushed
by Amiri Baraka. The poet (last seen, in an urban noir nod to
Shakespeare, as a homeless ghost in ``Bulworth'') took on the band
with a verbal barrage that mimicked and one-upped Murray's
blustery, low-down horn lines.
</P>
<P>
   It was an extravagant display of personality, the right move to
snatch the attention of a dwindling, last-call crowd that could
head into the next day's festivities with a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   But even in a city as starved for such scenes as Atlanta, not
everyone wants to lose a night's sleep in their pursuit. So
curators Alexa Birdsong and Joe Jennings have packaged the jam
sessions as themed events. Tonight's launching is billed as a New
Orleans Brass Band Blowout, with performances by the Pinstripe
Brass Band and the Furious Five Social Aid and Pleasure Club, two
Crescent City outfits that honor and extend the century-long parade
band tradition. The rest of the series touches on various aspects
of black music, from blues to hip-hop, with such featured
performers as Atlanta guitarists Theodis Ealey (Blues Monday Jam)
and Jacques Lesure (Jazz Jam, Thursday).
</P>
<P>
   Other sessions will be devoted to vintage rhythm and blues
(Rhythm Review Party Jam, Saturday) and the vocal tradition
(Singers Unlimited Jam, July 17), while a Tuesday Hip-Hop Jam will
deal with new directions in urban sounds. Both a Late Nite Jam
(July 18) and a Mixed Bag Jam (Wednesday) imply anything-goes
concepts: potluck listening for those with energy to burn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an environment within the festival which is more
varied,'' says Jennings, a jazz and R&AMP;B saxophonist who has long
been part of the Atlanta music scene. ``You might have some
drummers there, people from all over the diaspora. You might have
anything happening at any given moment.''
</P>
<P>
   And, despite the heavy talent likely to be crowding the room,
Jennings adds that musicians are welcome to sit in at the
appropriate moments: ``We try to make it clear that it is a jam
session.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
