<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8007 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBAF-THEATER-COX     07-09 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-THEATER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's a wide world of women, gays and politics
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--Theater and performance art have been among the
strongest disciplines at the National Black Arts Festival over the
past decade. This year, a lineup of fascinating variety _ from the
distinguished drama of August Wilson to the fiery musical work of
the Freddie Hendricks Youth Ensemble of Atlanta _ promises to carry
on the tradition. Following are highlights for the first few days
of the fest.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's ``Jitney'' (opening Sunday at the Alliance Theatre),
produced by Crossroads Theatre of New Brunswick, N.J., is his
affectionate profile of self-employed gypsy or jitney cabdrivers in
his native Pittsburgh. He wrote it in 1979, five years before he
gained Broadway fame with ``Ma Rainey's Black Bottom'' and began
the prolific streak of playwriting that has yielded two Pulitzer
Prizes and several of the Alliance Theatre's most powerful
productions. ``Jitney'' remains the least-known of Wilson's works,
but the current version, recently revised, is on a tour of regional
theaters, headed _ Wilson hopes _ for Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Writing it, he says, was a labor of love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was inspired by the way these guys made something out of
nothing, built a cab service out of an empty storefront and a pay
phone and their own resources, created their own joy,'' the
playwright, 52, says from his Seattle office. ``White cabbies
wouldn't pick up blacks in those days, so this service changed
people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Black Woman Speaks'' (4 p.m. Saturday and 8 p.m. Monday at
the 14th Street Playhouse) is a one-woman show by distinguished
thespian Beah Richards _ nominated for an Oscar opposite Sidney
Poitier in ``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner?'' and for a Tony Award
in James Baldwin's ``The Amen Corner.'' In the patented, irreverent
style she calls motherwit, Richards will offer provocative views on
race and womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   Another opinionated take on contemporary life will come from
Adodi Muse: A Black Gay Ensemble (8 and 10 p.m. Saturday and
Sunday, 14th Street Playhouse). It's not every troupe that can
perform one year under the auspices of the Atlanta Gay and Lesbian
Arts Festival and return the next year for the NBAF. Described by
fest organizers as ``intensely honest,'' Adodi explores black gay
men's changing place and struggle for a toehold in American
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Contract'' (2 p.m. Sunday, 8 p.m. Wednesday), written by
Nathan Ross Freeman and featuring actress-comedian Phyllis Yvonne
Stickney, is an in-your-face work of performance art about the
relationship between the human and the divine.
</P>
<P>
   The pride of inner-city Atlanta, the Freddie Hendricks Youth
Ensemble, will bring back its most popular piece, 1991's ``Soweto!
Soweto! Soweto! A Township Is Calling,'' for a one-night reprise (8
p.m. Monday at the 14th Street Playhouse). It's an open-hearted
response to South Africa's suffering in the ensemble's inimitable
style: raw, tender, honest, electrifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend asked me to write a piece about apartheid, and my
first reaction was, `That's across the water, not my problem,'''
said Hendricks, 42, who formed the ensemble from urban
actor-singer-dancers in their teens and early 20s and is preparing
a new work about teenage pregnancy, suggested by Jane Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I found out, the more I realized how wrong I was,''
Hendricks says. ``In the Soweto student uprising of 1976, there
were incredible stories: children dying, mothers crying. It's
history that our young people absolutely need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
