<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The world watches and wonders what is next at CNN
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm watching you, CNN,'' says director Quentin Tarantino.
Jazzman Wynton Marsalis says the same thing, as does actress
Kirsten Dunst.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's promotional mini-spots, in which celebrities and regular
viewers simply say that they're watching CNN, resonate with an
unintended double meaning these days. People are watching CNN more
closely, the institution if not the cable signal itself (ratings
haven't budged much one way or the other), as it tries to pull out
of the darkest two weeks in its 18-year history.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Operation Tailwind fiasco _ the story
alleging U.S. use of nerve gas, the independent investigation that
shredded the report's journalism, the on-air retraction and
apology, the wounded pride of workers inside CNN Center _ the
network now faces a future in which it must overcome its immediate
past.
</P>
<P>
   As upset as some viewers and outside critics are, many who work
at CNN are outraged. In meetings at CNN Center this week, they have
publicly questioned their leaders' handling of Tailwind with
comments that, in a different context, might have gotten them
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Questions have been raised _ and continue to be _ over whether
correspondent Peter Arnett should have been fired for his on-camera
reporting of the Tailwind story, and whether senior management
should have been more skeptical about a report that, in retrospect,
had serious flaws.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a growing number within CNN, burned out on day
after day of doubts, finger-pointing and self-criticism, who wish
for nothing more than a whopping big news story (preferably with no
loss of life, they qualify), the kind that not only gives CNN one
of its periodic ratings spikes but makes people realize that on
certain types of stories, nobody can touch CNN.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody could have outdone CNN on the extent of its own mea
culpa. In addition to on-air retractions and apologies, CNN posted
on its website the entire 54-page independent report outlining its
own corner-cutting. CNN chairman Tom Johnson personally called the
military personnel involved to apologize, and CNN-US president
Richard Kaplan went on CNN's ``Reliable Sources'' to face a
grilling from critics over why he didn't apply the brakes before
Tailwind aired.
</P>
<P>
   Still, CNN let its own standards down, and let viewers down.
Does that mean it can no longer be believed?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. Before it embarrassed itself with Tailwind, CNN
was one of the most respected news organizations in the world. It
may not be right at this moment, but in the long run, that won't
change. ``Dateline NBC'' admitted it rigged pickup trucks to
explode, and has expanded its audience; CNN certainly deserves more
chances than ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, CNN will now be more careful than ever when
producers say they're working on a story that will re-write
history, insisting that every fact and interview be triple-riveted.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen just how Rick Davis, the CNN lifer who's
been named the new executive vice president of editorial standards
and practices, will prevent any more Tailwinds, which is
essentially what he's been charged with doing. Davis could be a
superhero and what would still really matter is whether the
hundreds of people who put on the news can do it right, every time.
</P>
<P>
   Their track record, Tailwind notwithstanding, is encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, we're watching you, CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
