r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-HIGHART-COX     07-09 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HIGHART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `High Art' helps reshape Sheedy
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What comes to mind when you hear the name Ally Sheedy? The Brat
Pack? ``The Breakfast Club''? Judd Nelson?
</P>
<P>
   Well, think again. Those teen-queen roles in the 1980s didn't
let Sheedy use one-tenth of her talent. But ``High Art,'' a
Sundance Film Festival hit, lets her loose, and her work is a
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Whippet lean and as angular as a Picasso sketch, Sheedy plays
Lucy Berliner, a gifted photographer who, a decade ago, went from
``hot young thing'' to ``whatever happened to ... '' at the height
of her career. She simply dropped out. By choice, true, but also
out of some instinctive sense of self-preservatIon.
</P>
<P>
   However, all that's ancient history by the time she meets Syd
(Radha Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   An ambitious, baby-faced editorial assistant at a chichi
Manhattan magazine, Syd lives with her nice-guy boyfriend (Gabriel
Mann) in the apartment below the one Lucy shares with her longtime
lover, Greta (Patricia Clarkson), a heroin addict.
</P>
<P>
   When Syd sees Lucy's work, she's too young to know she's in the
presence of a famous has-been.
</P>
<P>
   But she knows the work is excellent and launches into a
breathless litany of praise before breaking off, embarrassed by her
own loquaciousness. ``That's OK,'' Lucy says with languid humor.
``It's a long time since I've been deconstructed.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Lisa Cholodenko deconstructs the New York art
world with a deft touch. She shows us seductions of all sorts _
sexual, careerist, simply being part of The Scene.
</P>
<P>
   Where the filmmaker and her characters run into trouble is in
the collision between the inherently toxic art establishment and
the self-destructive artist, which leads to a somewhat predictable
denouement.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's Sheedy, all wired irony and wary intensity in
the film's pivotal role. Her growing attraction for Syd is
presented both credibly and with a canny balance between power trip
and genuine desire.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, best known for the Aussie hit ``Love and Other
Catastrophes,'' is also very good. She's a natural-born but
unwitting user, whose naivete is almost a weapon. And Clarkson is
as hilarious as she is pathetic, wandering around in her heroin
haze, making pronouncements in a guttural Dietrich-like drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, ``High Art'' is about the seduction of the innocent.
The question we're left to ponder by this challenging film is, who
is the innocent?
</P>
<P>
   ``High Art''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ally Sheedy and Radha Mitchell. Directed by Lisa
Cholodenko. Rated R for language,
</P>
<P>
   drug use, nudity and passionate kissing.
</P>
<P>
   At Tara. 1 hour, 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Former Brat Packer Ally Sheedy gives us some
lessons in the high art of acting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
