<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-LETHAL-COX     07-09 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-LETHAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Danny and Mel back on the mean streets
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend of mine worried about watching ``Lethal Weapon 4,''
because he hadn't seen the first three flicks.
</P>
<P>
   That's a laugh. Director Richard Donner's cheerfully chaotic
blow-em-up movies aren't exactly the ``Star Wars'' trilogy. The
franchise is closer in spirit to the Bob Hope and Bing Crosby
rambles on the ``Road to'' wherever ... only with exploding tanker
trucks instead of musical interludes. And instead of Dorothy Lamour
in a sarong, we get Rene Russo with a pregnant belly and runty Joe
Pesci ranting with his toxic vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   The main event is the re-pairing of Mel Gibson's hothead cop
Riggs and Danny Glover's long-suffering partner Murtaugh. No. 4
sets up their dynamic nicely as they quibble in their car like an
old couple, facing an armored lunatic wielding a flame thrower. And
wondering why he's there. (Riggs' guess: ``Spokesman for the NRA,
maybe?'')
</P>
<P>
   Shaggy and amiable, ``Lethal Weapon 4'' hardly bothers to get
its real plot going for its first hour. That's just as well. What
we get is a tired, borderline offensive tale of a Los Angeles-based
Chinese mafia, importing illegal immigrants to work as slaves in
payment for their passage to America.
</P>
<P>
   The movie tries to balance the bad Chinese dudes with a nice
immigrant family Murtaugh takes under his wing. But that doesn't
keep some of Riggs' ``flied lice'' taunts from having a racist
reek.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Weapon'' rattles along so entertainingly, you won't mind
its plot holes and messy construction. More than ever, the film is
just an excuse to give its crack supporting cast a series of comic
riffs. Each successive movie has brought a new actor on board. This
time it's Chris Rock, playing a cop whose cheery compliments make
Murtaugh nervous. Rock turns out to be a stiff actor, but makes up
for it with his patented comic outrage. Recalling what it was like
having to stay close to the floor, growing up in a trigger-happy
'hood, he says, ``I didn't learn how to walk till I was 10 years
old.''
</P>
<P>
   Pesci returns in full sputtering fury. Russo, as the Internal
Affairs officer carrying Riggs' child, gets relegated to the back
seat, but still gets to kick some butt. And Hong Kong action star
Jet Li makes a strong Hollywood debut as the meanest of the Chinese
guys. He's mesmerizing in his feline stillness, and even more
impressive in martial-arts action, a switchblade whirl of spinning
legs and deadly accurate fists.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the hyped-up, incoherently staged ``Armageddon,''
``Lethal Weapon 4'' serves up action scenes that are cheerfully
outrageous, yet filmed with a logistical clarity that lets you
suspend your disbelief. And unlike that asteroid movie, it has a
huge saving grace: It's completely free of self-importance. It
knows it's just a dumb movie. But a dumb movie made with this sort
of skill and humor can be one of the best treats of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon 4''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mel Gibson, Danny Glover. Directed by Richard Donner.
Rated R for violence and full-blown profanity. 2 hours, 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A worthy, funny continuation of the
guns-and-guffaws formula.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
