<HEADER>
A8014 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MADELINE-COX     07-09 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MADELINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Madeline' one lovable orphan
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madeline can do anything.
</P>
<P>
   So she is reminded by her beloved teacher-guardian just before
an emergency appendectomy. So she tells herself just before foiling
a band of kidnappers. So she ... well, you get the idea. Anything
can and usually does happen to Madeline, namesake star of this
charming film about a pint-sized, precocious orphan living quite
happily (if a bit precariously) in Paris in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   That she eventually ends up with just about everything a child
could want _ close friends, a loving home, even a loyal, scruffy
dog _ is hardly accidental. ``Madeline'' demonstrates in its own
heartwarming, whimsical way that good things can happen if only
you're willing to work hard and believe in them enough.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``Madeline'' is a kids' movie _ and what, exactly, is wrong
with that? In a cine-summer crammed full of rampaging reptiles and
out-of-control asteroids, ``Madeline'' stands out mostly for the
way it makes sleeping 12 to a room and marching and dressing in
lock step seem like so much fun. (Indeed, I haven't so wanted to be
an orphan since I was 6 and my brothers all discovered that I was
afraid of worms.)
</P>
<P>
   As such, the filmmakers were only being faithful to
writer-illustrator Ludwig Bemelmans' beloved creation. Introduced
in 1939's ``Madeline,'' the plucky redhead was ``the smallest'' of
12 little girls living ``in an old house in Paris that was covered
with vines,'' under the watchful eye of Miss Clavel (Frances
McDormand in this version), a kindly nun.
</P>
<P>
   Several generations of little girls have fallen in love with
Madeline, whose misadventures span six books. ``Madeline'' the
movie brings together incidents and characters from four of them.
Then it's all superimposed on a
we're-never-really-very-worried-about-it-happening subplot
concerning an old meanie (Nigel Hawthorne) who's trying to turn the
girls out of their home.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is fast-paced enough to please today's vid-kids, yet
remarkably faithful to the look and feel of the books. Very small
children might need their hands held during several of the movie's
scarier moments. But because everything always ends very happily
and amusingly (find me a recent ``grown-up'' film with a better, or
better setup, line than a kidnapper's frantically uttered ``Forget
the nun, don't kill the idiots!''), it's doubtful that any
long-term damage will result.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Madeline'' makes refreshingly few concessions to the
in-your-face '90s. No drinking, no swearing and only veiled
allusions to what a foul wheel of cheese really smells like.
</P>
<P>
   The acting, meanwhile, smells just right. Oscar winner McDormand
avoids all the overly saintly or silly stereotypes and comes off as
a nice, competent person who also happens to be a nun. Madeline's
housemates seem like real little girls, not a bunch of would-be
dinner-theater Annies.
</P>
<P>
   But the real star _ with the exception of Paris itself, where
the entire movie was gloriously filmed _ is 9-year-old Hatty Jones
as the indomitable Madeline. At first, and even second, glance, the
ginger-haired Londoner appears to be all round cheeks and button
nose. But get a look at the way she sticks out her little chin
whenever the going gets tough, and you quickly come to understand
what she can do.
</P>
<P>
   Anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madeline''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Frances McDormand, Nigel Hawthorne. Directed by Daisy
von Scherler Mayer.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 29 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: To paraphrase Miss Clavel, something is just right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8015 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SOLIDERS-COX     07-09 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SOLIDERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Soldiers' falls short except in violence
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Action figures come alive, start warring with each other (and
any human who gets in their way) and destroy an idyllic small-town
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The setup of ``Small Soldiers'' borrows liberally from other
movies: ``Toy Story,'' ``Indian in the Cupboard,'' even that old
Karen Black TV flick ``Trilogy of Terror,'' the one with the little
devil doll and the big butcher knife. But what the new movie most
resembles, nearly to the point of being a remake, is ``Gremlins.''
That 1984 flick was also directed by Joe Dante, but I guess he
can't sue himself.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy on computer-generated effects and mayhem, but woefully
light on plot twists or interesting characters (either
flesh-and-blood or plastic), the movie's high concept is this: What
if top-secret military weaponry chips were implanted in a new line
of plastic action figures? And an early shipment got loose and
followed their circuits' imperative, to launch war games?
</P>
<P>
   The toys are divided into two groups. There's the Commando
Elite, resembling G.I. Joes on steroids, led by Chip Hazard
(wittily voiced by Tommy Lee Jones). Their enemy: the Gorgonites,
mutant creatures programmed either to submit or to hide. Frank
Langella lends his voice to their mournful leader, Archer. His
passivity is meant to be noble but winds up being annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Getting caught in the two groups' crossfire is young Alan
(Gregory Smith), one of Hollywood's standard-issue, misunderstood
teenagers, who secretly loves his neighbor Christy (Kirsten Dunst)
and believes that his parents don't have any faith in him. As you
might guess, these problems get sorted out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you can guess most of what the movie has in store, due
to a predictable script. The emphasis here is on the design and
computer animation of the toys. They're impressive, but they're not
interesting. Each soldier is designed with distinct physical (and
vocal) differences, but the movie never takes time to individualize
them.
</P>
<P>
   In scenes that rip off the mutant-toy bits from ``Toy Story,''
we also get a band of Barbie-style ``Gwendy'' dolls (voices:
Christina Ricci, Sarah Michelle Gellar). They've been reprogrammed
by the Commando Elite to be a swarming troop of war babes. Besides
being even more implausible than the main premise, this
transformation seems to be there mainly to let Dante pay homage to
``Frankenstein.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the problems with ``Small Soldiers.'' It can wear
you out with its game of name-that-movie, as it parodies everything
from ``Patton'' and ``Apocalypse Now'' to ``The Hunchback of Notre
Dame'' and even ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the violence. Or, as Denis Leary says in the movie,
playing the head of the toy company responsible for the carnage,
``Don't call it violence, call it action.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe parents can tell that to themselves if they're surprised
by the film's high assault level. Toys wield flamethrowers, knives,
nail guns, chain saws and any sort of workshop-meets-kitchen device
they can turn into a weapon. (The PG-13 rating is mainly for the
violence; people do get attacked by the toys, though there's no
human bloodshed or gore.)
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the flick, surveying the impressive damage the
toys have caused, Leary says, ``This could've made a hell of a
commercial.'' Too true. ``Small Soldiers'' feels like a very long
trailer for the movie it might have been. It doesn't have the
inspiration, magic or wit to be memorable (except for one decent
joke about the Spice Girls). Like the dolls that populate it, it's
just the latest product.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Soldiers''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Gregory Smith, Kirsten Dunst, Denis Leary and Phil
Hartman. Directed by Joe Dante. Rated PG-13 for mini war game
violence, household destruction, mild profanity. At metro theaters.
1 hour, 49 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: So many toys, so little fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
