<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8016 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIVAL-JAKES-COX     07-09 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIVAL-JAKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bishop Jakes in Atlanta for religion conference
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get ready with T.D. Jakes.
</P>
<P>
   That's the title of Bishop Jakes' television show, but it could
also serve as his personal anthem _ a message that is expected to
draw 40,000 people to Atlanta today.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes, head of The Potter's House in Dallas, one of the
fastest-growing megachurches in the country, is in Atlanta today
and Saturday to lead a conference focusing on God, women and
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have church,'' Jakes said of this weekend's
event. ``We're going to have an exuberant, joyful service, but we
want to take on tough issues.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, it wasn't issues the Texas pastor was dealing with
however. It was his growing popularity, the media, celebritties and
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of his popularity have been popping up everywhere in
recent years _ nine best-selling books, two cable television shows,
speaking tours across the nation _ and he now appears ready to
become America's next preaching superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes is just finishing up a 10-city book tour to promote his
latest book,The Lady, Her Lover and Her Lord'' (G.P. Putnam's Sons,
$19.95). Wednesday night, about 400 fans jammed into a Barnes &AMP;
Noble Bookseller's store in Marietta to greet him. Tuesday, Jakes
signed books on Wall Street and preached at a Harlem churchy.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 700 Club, CBS News, and a host of radio and television
station are asking for his time.
</P>
<P>
   I felt funny going to sleep this morning,'' he tells his
advisors. ``I woke up three to four times thinking, ``I don't have
to be anywhere. .''
</P>
<P>
   One of his aides places a schedule in front of Jakes to remind
him that that feeling would not last to long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now who do I have to talk to,?'' Jakes said before sitting on
his hotel bed to do an interview with a radio show.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the celebrities and politicians to deal with,
among them Texas Gov. Georgia Bush and Dallas Cowboy star Deion
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord brought the Bishop in my life,'' Sanders said
Thursday. ``To use a basketball analogy, some basketball players
can shoot but they can't play defense. But the bishop has a
complete game. He's a leader. He's a daddy. He's a theologian . . .
He's complete.''
</P>
<P>
   To be with Jakes Thursday, was to see a man in control, smiling
and working the crowd, knowing his time has come.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, Jakes hustled over to The Industry, a Buckhead
restaurant, to meet with city dignitaries. The Rev. Bernice King,
the daughter of Martin Luther King Jr., delivered an electrifying
prayer, calling Jakes a ``spiritual giant.'' Atlanta City
Councilman Michael Bond told the lunchone guests that they were in
the presence of ``God's messenger.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes took pictures with dignitaries and then paused when he saw
his wife, Serita.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get my girlfriend in here,'' he said, pulling her over and
draping his long arms around her.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was back to business. Jakes told the crowd that he
will talk about sensitive subjects at this weekend's conference:
sexual abuse, HIV rates in the black community, hurting single
women.
</P>
<P>
   We are going to have church,'' Jakes said. ``We're going to have
an exuberant, joyful service, but we want to take on tough
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes gazed at the well-heeled crowd and said he was so excited
about the reception to the conference that he was ``about to pop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around long enough to know that you keep your
remarks at a luncheon brief,'' he said. ``All of you are smiling,
but I know you're looking at your salad and saying, 'Lord, how
long?' ``
</P>
<P>
   But most importantly, are the crowds. They demonstrate Jakes'
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   It's a message people are ready to here, at least if it's T.D.
Jakes who's doing the talking.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, seven hours before the doors would open for the first
night of the conference, lines of women _ white and black _ were
assembling outside the Georgia Dome. According to organizers, women
had traveled from Japan and Hawaii to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not in the closet. He doesn't have a hidden agenda. He
says, 'I went though this, too.' `` said Lisa Simmons , 35, who
traveled from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ain't no joke. It's real,'' said her friend, Anita Gore,
38. `` He helped me deal with rejection. People flock to him
because they're hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
