   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, July 10. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   IRS-OVERHAUL (Washington) _ The Senate gives final approval to
legislation overhauling the IRS, voting 96-2 to impose the most
sweeping shakeup in decades on the tax-collection agency's
management and culture. By Richard W. Stevenson. With graphic;
sidebar, IRS-TAXPAYERS.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN-U.S. (Washington) _ The Senate votes to exempt
agriculture credit programs from sanctions imposed on India and
Pakistan after the two countries conducted nuclear tests in May. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHRATE-DECLINE (Stockholm, Sweden) _ Driven largely by
prosperity and freedom, millions of women _ here and throughout the
developed world _ are having fewer children than ever before. As a
result, birth rates in many countries are now in a rapid, sustained
decline. Never before _ except in times of plague, war and deep
economic depression _ have birth rates fallen so low, for so long.
What was once regarded universally as a cherished goal _ incredibly
low birth rates _ have in the industrial world at least suddenly
become a cause for alarm. With life expectancy rising at the same
time that fertility drops, most developed countries may soon find
themselves with lopsided societies that will be nearly impossible
to sustain: a large number of elderly and not enough young people
working to support them. By Michael Specter. Special Report, 3,000
words. With 3 graphics and photo.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-LIABILITY (Washington) _ Supporters of a measure to set
the first-ever nationwide standards for court-awarded damages for
injuries caused by faulty products fail to win a crucial vote,
leaving the issue consigned once again to the legislative
wilderness, perhaps for years. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   BABY-DEATH (Wilmington, Del.) _ A Delaware judge denounces Amy
Grossberg as an egocentric indifferent to the ``intrinsic value of
the life'' of her newborn son and sentences her to 30 months in
prison for contributing to the baby's death in November 1996.
Minutes later, the judge, Henry duPont Ridgely, issues a far
gentler scolding to Ms. Grossberg's co-defendant and former high
school sweetheart, Brian Peterson, and gave him a two year
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   SHIPYARD-LABOR (New Orleans) _ Five years ago, the workers at
Avondale shipyard voted to join a union, with hundreds of them
cheering wildly outside the company's headquarters along the
Mississippi when the vote count was announced. Today, there is
still no union at the shipyard. The 50,000 pages of documents
stacked in the offices of the National Labor Relations Board are
evidence of what happened instead, producing one of the longest,
most heavily litigated unionization fights in the board's history.
At a time when labor unions nationwide are stepping up efforts to
organize millions of workers, labor leaders and even some
government officials point to the Avondale battle as proof that the
nation's labor laws are cumbersome and replete with loopholes. By
Steven Greenhouse. 1,700 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
