<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-09 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE OVER TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican congressional leaders are gleeful about
a hot new issue with which to badger President Clinton _ his
declaration during his China trip that the United States does not
support and will not recognize a sovereign Taiwan independent of
the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Good grief. Are these folks desperate for political fodder or
what? As a domestic campaign issue, Taiwan's future is not
something that many people under the age of 50 are likely to give a
fig about.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives still reliving the Cold War era, when Taiwan was
the good guy and ``Red'' China a terrifying enemy, are outraged at
what they see as the president's betrayal of an old friend and
trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   But getting voters for whom Mao Zedong is but a dim, distant
historical figure all exercised about standing up for Taiwan?
Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, all Clinton did was clarify a politically realistic
U.S. policy that had previously been deliberately ambiguous. Since
normalizing diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of
China in 1979, we have not questioned China's insistence on
claiming Taiwan as its own.
</P>
<P>
   We recognize the mainland as the only China that exists. Our
position is that Taiwan's future should be determined in peaceful
bilateral negotiations aimed at leading to unification between
Taipei and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's timing was awkward, and Taiwan is miffed. So
Taiwan's backers on Capitol Hill are rushing to reassure the island
that we will still provide a protective shield of some kind against
any Chinese military aggression and will continue to be helpful in
bolstering its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans frustrated by the overall success of the president's
China visit are delighted to single out the Taiwan issue as an
exception. Turning this into a political hot potato for campaign
purposes, however, is quite a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Taiwan has maintained a vast lobbying operation in
the nation's capital that exerts considerable influence on
Congress. But the island means nothing to most American voters.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than 50 years since the pro-American
Nationalist Chinese government led by Chiang Kai-shek fled to
Taiwan to escape the Communist takeover led by Mao Zedong. In the
emotional aftermath of the revolution, the western world rallied
around the Nationalists as the sole legitimate government of China,
in theory merely waiting until the Communists collapsed and they
could return to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived in the nation's capital during the Eisenhower
administration, a powerful ``China lobby'' dictated U.S. policy
toward Asia behind the scenes. Because the mainland's shelling of
its off-shore islands of Quemoy and Matsu was seen as a threat to
Taiwan, the subject dominated the second presidential debate in
1960 between Sen. John F. Kennedy and Vice President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   After Kennedy's election, however, quiet diplomacy and the
limited dispatch of U.S. arms calmed the crisis. No voter has been
known to think about Quemoy and Matsu since.
</P>
<P>
   The myth that the government in Taiwan would some day return to
Beijing died in 1972, when President Nixon decided it was time to
deal with the Chinese again.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese and the Soviets were no longer allies and capable of
sweeping all of Southeast Asia into the Communist net. And while
trading with Taiwan has been lucrative, its market of more than 21
million consumers for U.S. goods paled beside the more than 1
billion potential buyers in the crowded mainland.
</P>
<P>
   To open that China door Nixon, a Republican, agreed to
officially drop the notion that Taiwan was a sovereign state and
the one true China. During the Carter administration, Congress
followed through by repudiating an outdated mutual-defense treaty
with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Taiwan has been increasingly a historical appendix,
still existing but not of much practical use beyond its strategic
location in the South China Sea. Taiwan is touted as a democracy
compared with China's dictatorial ways, but in fact it was long
dominated by Chiang's heirs and held its first direct election for
a head of state only two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When congressional leaders talk about defending Taiwan's
integrity, it is important to know what vital American interests
they think need protecting, and how. Are they talking about going
into battle against China and shedding American blood? Did we not
learn our lesson in Vietnam about the perils of ground wars in
Asia?
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich came close to promising military
action in 1996. He vowed on a visit to Taiwan that the United
States would use ``all necessary means'' to prevent Beijing from
pressuring Taiwan to capitulate ``by force or intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   We have in fact ordered military maneuvers as a warning when
China has seemed to threaten Taiwan, although no shots have ever
been fired. Clinton, for instance, dispatched Navy ships to Taiwan
in 1996 as a signal that we were displeased with China's war games
near the island at that time.
</P>
<P>
   But what if China calls our bluff? Just how far are we really
prepared to go to carry out the GOP's tough talk about protecting
Taiwan?
</P>
<P>
   Congress is reluctant to authorize the use of military power
without some overwhelming necessity. On Jan. 12, 1991, the Senate
agreed to President George Bush's plan to attack Iraq after its
invasion of Kuwait only by a margin of 5 votes. The House went
along with a 67-vote margin. The debate was heated despite the fact
that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein was a certifiable devil and
everyone knew the vital interest involved: oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
