<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ students throughout Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Artley couldn't escape the legacy of Dick and Jane. In
later years, as he continued his work on the lecture circuit,
Artley composed a little response to the frequent question,
``Whatever happened to Dick, Jane and Sally?''
</P>
<P>
   Artley would tell audiences that Dick became a politician. His
slogan? ``Run, Dick, run.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane married and became an ardent advocate for women's rights:
``Help Jane win equal rights for women.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally became a primary teacher with a room full of admiring
children. She frequently said to them, ``Jump, children, jump. Jump
high in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Artley considered his work with Dick and Jane secondary to his
calling as a professor, but he became attached to the characters he
spent so much time with, Toalson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These little characters just took on a life of their own,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
