A8078 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-VISIT-2NDTAK     07-09 0193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-VISIT-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ a GOP revolt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being honest with people helps,'' he said about the book.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich ended his Kansas City visit the same way he began it _
by raising money. At a breakfast at a hotel, Gingrich generated
bucks for the Monday Morning political action committee, which aids
Republican candidates across the country.
</P>
<P>
   At day's end, he was at a hotel in Overland Park, Kan., helping
Rep. Vince Snowbarger of Kansas in his re-election effort against
Democrat Dennis Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Before a crowd estimated at 200, Gingrich urged his listeners to
send a Republican team back to Washington next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Returning Vince will mean a more conservative, smaller
government with lower taxes,'' Gingrich said. ``This is the right
direction and the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Gingrich raised $30,000 at a Snowbarger
fund-raiser before the Republican won his first term. Heading into
Wednesday's event, the Snowbarger campaign already had more than
$100,000 in sponsorships for the event at $1,000 and $500 a person.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8081 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLEA-BARGAINS-2NDTAKE     07-09 0286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLEA-BARGAINS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: to their testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachtel said when he first read the opinion, he thought, ``What
have I done? How are things ever going to be as usual?'' But he and
other lawyers said plea bargains now must focus on cooperation
before a trial rather than testimony at trial.
</P>
<P>
   John P. O'Connor, a defense attorney and former Jackson County,
Mo., assistant prosecutor, said the ruling could be ``worse for
defendants. Now the plea agreement will say, `You're getting
nothing for your testimony,' which'll make (cooperating witnesses)
better witnesses in front of the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, courts have instructed prosecutors to disclose
their promises to defense attorneys. When a witness with a plea
bargain takes the stand, defense lawyers are free to cross-examine
the witness about the deal, trying to attack the witness's
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   For lawyers who represent defendants seeking to cooperate, life
just got more complicated. ``I don't know what to do right now,''
said Carl Cornwell, a Kansas defense lawyer. He said deals with
prosecutors will now involve ``the wink of an eye, `You take care
of me, I'll take care of you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connor said he'll tell his clients, ``the people who
testify will get the better deals. As a practical matter, that's
the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean Paul Bradshaw, a defense lawyer and former U.S. attorney
for western Missouri, said the ruling, though based on logical
reasoning, ``seems to be so contrary to the plea-bargaining process
that has been used for hundreds of years. It seems to me to be one
of those things that can't end up standing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
