<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8086 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-09 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRESS IS ON A RAMPAGE IN AMERICA'S WORKPLACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: I am fascinated by our fascination with stress.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not doubting its existence or its deleterious physical and
emotional effects. But I'm intrigued by the apparent stress
epiphany among so many workers.
</P>
<P>
   Ferocious stress always has visited the workplace, whether it
was a drought-ravaged farm field, an orchestra in performance, a
military command center or a scientific research laboratory. Now,
though, virtually everyone cites stress on the job as a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians approach me at parties to tell me to write about all
the cases of stress-related illnesses they're seeing, particularly
among white-collar professionals at Fortune 500-type companies.
</P>
<P>
   Books regularly land on my desk, replete with suggestions on how
to reduce stress at work.
</P>
<P>
   A survey shows that more than two-thirds of employees say their
heavy workloads are their leading cause of stress.
</P>
<P>
   This finding came from a poll commissioned by the Kensington
Technology Group, which also found that six out of 10 American
workers say they have eye, back, neck, shoulder or wrist pain
associated with their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   These two stresses _ the existence of stress and the physical
pains that may be associated with it _ are closely followed by the
stress of trying to balance work and private lives, the same survey
reveals.
</P>
<P>
   Have we all become a bunch of delicate whiners? Or are our work
lives really that awful?
</P>
<P>
   I understand the adrenalin rush (call it stress, if you will) of
racing to meet deadlines. I understand the stress of dealing with
disparate personalities and temperaments in close quarters. I
understand the stress of between-a-rock-and-a-hard-place management
positions.
</P>
<P>
   I also understand that some people thrive on such strains while
others collapse. These collapsed workers are inundating the offices
of physicians and mental health counselors. They are hurting.
</P>
<P>
   When the Kensington poll asked workers to define the cause of
their stress, about two-thirds said they were being asked to do too
much work within assigned deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   What can the typical American worker do about that? Obviously,
not much.
</P>
<P>
   Staffing levels are set by complex interactions and expectations
of investors, owners and top management. The average worker isn't
going to get a position added to his or her department because he
or she feels overworked.
</P>
<P>
   If, indeed, overwork is causing this stress explosion, then the
typical worker has limited tools to fight it. There's always the
possibility of changing jobs _ ``downscaling'' in the popular
vernacular _ to reduce hours and responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Downscaling, of course, usually means accepting less income.
There is a growing willingness to do that, but certainly not a
wholesale rush.
</P>
<P>
   What's left for the typical worker to fight stress are such
things as getting professional counseling, joining support groups,
meditating, exercising regularly, maintaining good nutrition,
getting enough sleep, using ergonomically correct equipment on the
job and taking breaks when the tension gets too tight to continue
to function.
</P>
<P>
   Any or all of these may not be enough. Maybe today's work world
really is too ferocious for many workers to cope. If so, where does
the responsibility lie for fixing it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
