<HEADER>
A8092 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-09 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHFUL IMAGINATION IS WORTH NURTURING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: A figure of immense power and promise came hurtling
down the sidewalk of our block a moment ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was a boy of about 3 or 4 years, riding a tricycle and
wearing a cape made from, I would guess, a part of a bedsheet. He
leaned a bit forward, pedaling furiously, hair blowing in the wind,
that magnificent cape billowing out behind.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever mythic character he imagined himself to be, he had
become that personage completely _ at least for as long as the
tricycle remained upright and the cape stayed fastened at his
throat.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered, then, a dream of my own at that age. It was the
dream of flight.
</P>
<P>
   I built my plane from the saved parts of wooden vegetable crates
_ a boxlike compartment to sit in, two flimsy boards for wings, two
more for a tail, the whole contraption mounted on a pair of roller
skates.
</P>
<P>
   Our house perched on a steep terrace above the street. If
launched from the brow of that, it seemed I might attain a velocity
that would let me break gravity's shackles and soar free.
</P>
<P>
   So I positioned my plane at the edge, climbed in the box, and
commanded a little friend, a neighbor boy, to shove me over.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was not a happy one. I walked away from the crash
with only a skinned elbow and chipped tooth, but my plane and my
hope of flying were wrecked beyond saving. It's how childish
enterprises often end up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in spite of such risks, I have wondered why so much of
education's effort is devoted to training the young in various
specific skills, and so little simply to nurturing their capacity
for dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   It was much the same in my own school years, though the tendency
seems more pronounced today.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is because the journey of a life has gotten more
rigorous, more fiercely competitive, with less margin for the
heresies and troubling notions that dreamers are apt to bring to
the table.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it is those very ones _ able to set themselves apart by
the power of their imagining _ who shape humanity's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   I saw in the paper the other day where computer whiz Bill Gates
had added a few billions more to his stash, consolidating his
position as the wealthiest human being on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Gates has played a major role in the evolution and popular
acceptance of computer technology. And that's really big money
we're talking about _ certainly nothing to be sniffed at. When
all's said, though, he really is nothing more than a
well-compensated technician, engaged in building a better
mousetrap.
</P>
<P>
   Mohandas Gandhi, by contrast, was among the poorest of men in
material things. But his dream not only propelled India to
independence; it helped light a fire of freedom that would sweep
the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the dreamers govern, the technicians serve.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it was so wonderful just now to see that little boy
speeding down the block with his cape aflutter, unencumbered a bit
longer by practicality.
</P>
<P>
   Time and the world may have their way with him, as with us all.
But it hasn't happened yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
