<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTLEY-OBIT-2TAKES-KA     07-09 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTLEY-OBIT-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST AUTHOR OF DICK AND JANE BOOKS DIES AT 91 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Like millions of other American children,
Judy Toalson and Jan Goldman grew up with Dick and Jane.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters remember they liked the stories about the children
and their younger sister, Sally. And at the beginning of each
school year, when they opened their reading primers, the girls saw
a familiar name on the title page: A. Sterl Artley, their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd say, `Oh, my goodness. There he is again,' '' Goldman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Artley, a professor of education at the University of
Missouri-Columbia for 30 years, died Tuesday at an Overland Park
nursing home, where he had lived since 1996. He was 91. His health
had been failing for two years, said Toalson, of Mission Hills,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Artley was the last remaining author of the popular Dick and
Jane reading primers, which were used in schools from the 1930s to
the 1970s. Nationally recognized as a leader in reading
methodology, Artley was hired by Scott, Foresman and Co. in the
late 1940s to revise the ``Fun with Dick and Jane'' reading series.
</P>
<P>
   Along with William S. Grey of the University of Chicago and May
Hill Arbuthnot of Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland,
Artley crafted the curriculum used by most schools to teach
children to read. He wrote the teaching manuals that accompanied
the series, which focused on three children who lived in a typical
house in a typical neighborhood in post-war America.
</P>
<P>
   During the height of the series' popularity, about 80 percent of
American schoolchildren read about Dick, Jane and Sally, said
Robert Ravis, manager of copyright and permissions for Scott
Foresman Addison Wesley publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen words were used in the first primer. In the second
book, those words were repeated and 21 others added. No page
introduced more than one word, and no story introduced more than
three words. The first five uses of the word were ``bunched'' _
``go, go, go'' _ to make sure children got the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The simple stories revolved around home, neighborhood and
school. Father had an office job; Mother was a homemaker. They had
a cat and a dog, and the short stories had beginnings, middles and
ends.
</P>
<P>
   The stories enchanted children because they could relate to the
characters, said Marjorie Kaplan, superintendent of the Shawnee
Mission School District in Kansas and a former elementary
schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children always love to read about other children,'' Kaplan
said. ``I can just see myself, sitting there in the reading circle,
reading those books. Those of us who learned to read that way have
an affection for those characters.''
</P>
<P>
   That affection was apparent last summer, when the Johnson County
Museum of History presented ``Dick and Jane: Illustrations of an
American Education,'' a two-month exhibit featuring original art
from the books. Record crowds flocked to the museum during the
exhibit, said Kathy Stump, curator of history.
</P>
<P>
   Retired teachers came to gaze upon the memorabilia. So did baby
boomers who remembered learning to read about Spot, the family dog.
Many visitors recorded their memories in a book at the exhibit's
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also grew up with Dick and Jane and have very fond
memories,'' one visitor from Kansas City, Mo., wrote. ``I was so
excited that I could read `See Dick...See Dick Run.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In another entry, a teacher who learned to read using the series
longed for a similar series to use with her first-grade students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories brought much joy to me as a youngster,'' she
wrote. ``I still love to read.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrific nostalgia trip for people,'' Stump said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, the Dick and Jane series came under fire for
reinforcing sexist stereotypes and presenting a lifestyle that was
too ``white'' for much of America. The writers introduced three
black children _ Mike and twins Penny and Pam _ who became Dick and
Jane's playmates.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dick and Jane series really went out of vogue because
other methods of teaching reading achieved success with a greater
number of students, Kaplan said. The strict, controlled vocabulary
of the Scott, Foresman series was replaced in the 1970s with the
whole-language method, which advocates immersing children in
language in all forms _ reading, writing, speaking and listening.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, whole language has come under fire. Proponents
of phonics _ the method of breaking down words into sounds and
teaching children to recognize what symbol goes with what sound _
claim whole language has haphazard results.
</P>
<P>
   In his later years, Artley endorsed whole language, although he
continued to favor the structured method of the Dick and Jane
series, said Richard Robinson, a professor of curriculum and
instruction at the University of Missouri-Columbia School of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who described Artley as a ``major figure'' in the
field of reading, came to MU in the early 1970s for the chance to
work with Artley, who at one time was president of the
International Reading Association.
</P>
<P>
   After he retired in the 1970s, Artley periodically dropped by
the MU education school. But in recent years, fewer faculty members
recognized the man who helped write the books that taught them to
read.
</P>
<P>
   And that was all right with Artley, Robinson said. He shirked
the limelight, preferring to be known as a pre-eminent teacher of
teachers, a man who personally directed the studies of 46 doctoral
students and 289 master's students.
</P>
<P>
   Toalson and Goldman, of Durango, Colo., agreed with that
assessment. Their father also was proud of the work accomplished
through the MU Child Study Clinic, which he founded. For more than
30 years, the clinic gave graduate students the chance to diagnose
learning disabilities and provided testing services for hundreds of
students throughout Missouri. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-BANKS-U.S.-ART-     07-09 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-U.S.-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE BANKS ARE PULLING OUT OF U.S. MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Calif., N.Y., Ill., Mass., Ohio, Ga.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Overcome by bad loans in their home country,
Japanese banks and other financial institutions are in a broad
retreat from the U.S. market, closing offices and cutting back on
their lending to U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   The situation represents a sharp reversal from the late 1980s
and the early 1990s, when Japanese banks were expanding rapidly in
California and elsewhere in the United States, gaining market share
by aggressive lending at low rates and even raising some concern
that the Japanese would dominate banking as they did consumer
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Japanese banks are wary about making new loans or renewing
old ones. ``Basically they're gone, on the sidelines,'' said an
executive at an American bank in charge of making syndicated loans
to corporations who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks accounted for less than 10 percent of the
syndicated loans provided to U.S. companies with investment-grade
credit ratings in the first quarter of 1998, down from 26 percent
in the comparable quarter a year earlier, according to Loan Pricing
Corp., a market research firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks either are pulling out of the United States
altogether or are consolidating operations in New York. The number
of Japanese banks with offices in New York has fallen to 55 from 70
in the last few years, according to a compilation made in February
by Yomiuri Shimbun, a Japanese newspaper. The number with offices
in Los Angeles has dropped to 17 from 25, and in Chicago to 16 from
21.
</P>
<P>
   Some Japanese banks are also selling part of their U.S.
operations. Fuji Bank raised about $1 billion by selling a minority
stake in Heller Financial Inc., a finance company in Chicago, in an
initial public offering at the end of April. In March, Sumitomo
Bank sold Sumitomo Bank of California to Zions Bancorp of Utah for
$546 million. It also sold off pieces and shut down the rest of its
operation that made loans to small and medium-sized businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese banking crisis is also accelerating the sale of
Japanese-owned hotels, office buildings and golf courses in the
United States, many of which were bought at exorbitant prices in
the late 1980s. Nikko Securities, for instance, just agreed to sell
the Watergate Hotel in Washington to the Blackstone Group for $39
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a fire sale,'' said Shuhei Okuda, president of
Mitsui Fudosan USA, the U.S. arm of a Japanese real estate company.
``They have to sell, especially when the bank presses the borrowers
who own the property to sell and repay the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The sharp retreat from lending by Japanese banks has contributed
to a modest increase in interest rates paid by U.S. corporate
borrowers, bankers and analysts said. Some big financings have
taken longer to arrange. Starwood Hotels and Resorts Trust took
longer than expected to arrange more than $7 billion in loans to
finance its acquisition of ITT Corp., in part because Japanese
banks, which in the past would have provided a big chunk of that
money, declined to participate. The delay in financing even
prompted speculation that the takeover might fall through.
</P>
<P>
   But by and large, the retreat from the U.S. market by the
Japanese banks has had little effect on the U.S. economy because
there are many other sources of credit for companies. This
contrasts sharply to the situation in Japan and in other parts of
Asia, where cutbacks in lending by Japanese banks have contributed
to a credit crunch that has driven some companies into bankruptcy
and worsened economic downturns.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the pullback from lending by Japanese
banks has been counterbalanced by financial deregulation in Japan,
which has made it easier for Japanese to invest overseas. With the
dollar strong and interest rates higher in the United States than
in Japan, Japanese money has moved into U.S. stocks, bonds and
banks, helping keep interests rates low and stocks high.
</P>
<P>
   One big fear has not materialized: that the crisis would force
Japanese government and financial institutions to sell off their
U.S. Treasury bonds, causing U.S. interest rates to rise and
slowing the economy. A hint of such a sale by Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto caused the U.S. stock markets to plunge
one day last year. But Treasury bonds are proving attractive to
Japanese and other foreign investors because they pay higher
interest rates compared with similar securities in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The most important effect of the Japanese banking crisis on the
United States is likely to come not from cutbacks by Japanese banks
in the United States but more indirectly. The banking crisis is
plunging Japan into recession, which hurts U.S. exports and also is
making it difficult for the rest of ailing Asia to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the most obvious effect in the United States is less
lending by Japanese banks. Beset by at least $600 billion in
problem loans, mainly on Japanese real estate, Japanese banks are
struggling to maintain capital levels equal to 8 percent of assets,
a requirement for international banks. With their capital eroding
from loan losses and the weak Japanese stock market, the banks are
having to reduce assets, which generally means loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their capital base is so eroded they have to reduce assets any
way they can,'' said Richard Koo, chief economist for Nomura
Research Institute in Tokyo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, assets held by Japanese-owned bank
branches dropped to $347 billion at the end of 1997 from $404
billion at the end of 1994, according to the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Without a big base of dollar-denominated deposits, Japanese
banks and other finance companies generally borrow from other banks
to obtain the money they then lend out in the United States. But
because of fears about the health of the Japanese banking system,
Japanese banks have had to pay higher rates for this borrowed money
than U.S. or European banks do. The banks can no longer profitably
pursue their old strategy of lending at low interest rates to gain
market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're priced out of the market for U.S. companies,'' said
Edward W. Bjelke, executive vice president of Sanwa Bank in New
York. The bank's outstanding loans in the United States have fallen
to about $40 billion from $72 billion a few years ago, he said.
This week, Sanwa said it would liquidate Sanwa Securities (USA)
Co., which has been a dealer of U.S. Treasury securities, and
refocus its investment banking activities on the more profitable
derivatives business.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsui Leasing Capital Corp., a leasing and finance company in
New York that is part of Mitsui Group, recently laid off four of
its six American professionals and is sending four Japanese staff
members back home as it reduces its loans and leases and sells real
estate in Hawaii and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been booking new business,'' said Jeff Fishman, a
vice president who was laid off nine days ago. ``We're in a holding
pattern right now.'' Masato Utsumi, the president, said Mitsui
Leasing was shifting to higher-risk loans and leasings with
potentially better returns because its borrowing costs are now
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Japanese leasing companies, Ryoshin Leasing, which is
part of the Mitsubishi Group, and Crown Leasing, owned by the
troubled Nippon Credit Bank, have shut their U.S. offices entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese banks pulling out of the U.S. market so far have
been mainly smaller, regional banks. The giant nationwide
commercial banks are retrenching as well, though they generally are
not leaving the United States entirely. Dai-ichi Kangyo Bank
recently closed its San Francisco office. Sanwa Bank is shutting
offices in Boston, Cleveland and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Los Angeles office of a big Japanese bank said
that with fewer loans being made, decision-making was being
concentrated in New York. ``In the past, I enjoyed the freedom to
develop the business on my own in the 14 Western states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The beachhead of Japanese banking in the United States has been
California, where the Japanese opened retail banking branch
networks, not just corporate banking offices like those in New
York. By the late 1980s, Japanese banks owned four of the 10
largest banks in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the Japanese banks by and large have performed more poorly
than competitors, and fears of Japanese dominance have subsided.
The merger of two of the Japanese-owned California banks and the
sale of Sumitomo Bank of California leave only two big
Japanese-owned banks in the state, both of which are now the focus
of speculation that they might be sold.
</P>
<P>
   One is Unionbancal Corp., which has about $30 billion in assets
and is the third-largest commercial bank in the state, behind
BankAmerica and Wells Fargo. With both of those big banks having
recently agreed to mergers, Union, which is controlled by Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi, has become the biggest potential takeover
candidate for an out-of-state bank looking to expand in California.
The other bank is Sanwa Bank California, the state's fourth-largest
commercial bank, with assets of $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks deny they are for sale, and both have been performing
better than Sumitomo. Tamio Takakura, president of Sanwa Bank
California, said that with the deregulation of financial markets in
Japan, the expertise his unit had from operating in the ferociously
competitive U.S. market was more valuable than ever to the parent.
The California unit, for instance, is helping to manage mutual
funds offered to Japanese consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are increasingly becoming a strategic unit for them,'' said
Takakura, whose 50th-floor office atop one of the fanciest
skyscrapers in Los Angeles symbolizes the ambitions Japanese banks
once had in the United States. ``They're expecting a lot from us,
not just earnings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
