<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-VISIT-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH FEEDS ELEPHANTS AT ZOO, SIGNS BOOKS, RAISES MONEY FOR
GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Newt Gingrich threw apples to the elephants
at the Kansas City Zoo. He tossed brickbats at President Clinton
for his trip to China.
</P>
<P>
   He raised money for Republicans at the first meal of the day and
at the last. And between it all, he tried raising money for himself
by signing copies of his new book Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the speaker's frantic day in the Kansas City
area?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like selling books, but the zoo is a big deal,'' Gingrich
said.
</P>
<P>
   So there he was, the speaker of the House, the man third in line
of succession to the presidency, standing on a rocky ledge _ in
near 90-degree heat _ happily lobbing apples at six female African
elephants at the zoo's Okauango Elephant Sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker has had a lifelong passion for zoos. At age 10, he
fought in vain to persuade city leaders in his hometown of
Harrisburg, Pa., to build one.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich had visited the Kansas City Zoo before, but not since
its $71 million renovation was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Republican, I'm perfectly happy to be posed in front of
elephants,'' Gingrich said to a throng of television cameras,
before going off on a private tour.
</P>
<P>
   The elephants seemed perfectly happy, too.
</P>
<P>
   He was more serious but equally relaxed earlier at a meeting
with The Kansas City Star's editorial board. In a wide-ranging
session, the speaker whipped out answers with practiced efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, 55, saved his harshest rhetoric for Clinton's recent
visit to China and specifically the president's comments about
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott's criticism Tuesday,
Gingrich lambasted the president for what he said were harmful
remarks that suggested the United States' commitment to Taiwan and
its healthy democracy was waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very dangerous mistake and very typical of this
administration,'' Gingrich said. ``I can't for the life of me
imagine why he would say it in China.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has said the president's comments represented no
change in U.S.-Taiwanese relations.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich was undeterred, saying Clinton had sent a signal to
other countries that the United States was unreliable. The
president should have been clear, Gingrich said, by saying that the
United States would not tolerate any military activity by the
Chinese against Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's creating an ambiguity that is very dangerous,'' Gingrich
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also complained that China gained everything and the United
States nothing from the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time (the leader of) a democracy visits a dictatorship,
it's the dictatorship that gains,'' the speaker said. ``If you
haven't gotten a concession in advance, why would you go?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked at the editorial board meeting about the legacy of the
so-called 1994 Revolution, when the Republicans captured Congress,
Gingrich didn't blink.
</P>
<P>
   ``It succeeded,'' he said. ``We reformed welfare, balanced the
budget, cut taxes, saved Medicare without a tax increase and just
passed reform of the IRS (Internal Revenue Service). By any
reasonable standard of the summer of 1994, that's a pretty amazing
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP will increase its 11-seat edge in the House by 10 to 40
in November, Gingrich predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the historical tendency for the party controlling the
White House to lose seats in midterm elections, Gingrich said, the
GOP's pledge of lowering taxes will resonate with working
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mathematical odds against Democrats gaining seats are
enormous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On other matters, Gingrich:
</P>
<P>
   - Suggested the country should begin paying off the national
debt by $10 billion to $20 billion a year, eventually resulting in
lower interest rates by as much as 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   - Pledged again that the House would vote on a campaign reform
bill this year, adding that he supported unlimited individual
contributions, as long as they were reported immediately on the
Internet, but also a ban on corporate and union ``soft money''
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   - Insisted that he didn't know whether he would run for
president in 2000 and wouldn't decide until Labor Day 1999.
</P>
<P>
   - Said Clinton, as the nation's chief law enforcement officer,
should make sure the White House staff cooperates with independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude is, we ought to relax and let Judge Starr get
done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Clinton continued to rank high in popularity polls
while the speaker floundered, Gingrich admitted that he was ``too
professorial, too direct'' to be a national leader. He also
suggested the media were biased against him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meantime, succeeds because he steals GOP ideas, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's noontime stop for a book-signing event may have been
another reminder of public disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   About 125 persons stood waiting for autographs. Other
luminaries, such as Jimmy Carter and Walter Cronkite, drew hundreds
more in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dismal,'' said Roger Doeren of Rainy Day Books in
Fairway, Kan., which sponsored the event.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the heat and the lack of street parking for the poor
turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich completed most of his work in 20 minutes, far quicker
than the hour allotted for the task. The book, ``Lessons Learned
the Hard Way: A Personal Report,'' recently was discounted 50
percent by its publisher in an effort to sell more copies. The
account is full of mea culpas for Gingrich's first years as
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old Georgian recounts in sometimes painful detail
his handling of the government shutdown in 1995 and his allegations
of shoddy treatment aboard Air Force One. He writes about his own
ethics violation and about how he almost was dumped from the
speakership in a GOP revolt. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
