<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLEA-BARGAINS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-BRIBERY LAW QUASHES FEDERAL PLEA BARGAINS, JUDGES RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM JACKMAN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Federal prosecutors cannot cut deals with witnesses in
exchange for testimony, a federal appeals court in Denver has ruled
in a case that could dramatically affect how the government
prosecutes criminals nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   A drug-conspiracy case in Wichita, Kan., provided the basis for
the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruling. A co-defendant
testified against Sonya E. Singleton in exchange for a lighter
sentence, using a plea agreement that lawyers described as
boilerplate language for virtually all federal prosecutions around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Singleton's lawyer, John V. Wachtel of Wichita, argued that
a federal law prohibiting bribery of witnesses should apply to
prosecutors as well as defendants. A three-judge panel, featuring
two judges who also will hear the appeal of Oklahoma City bomber
Timothy McVeigh, unanimously agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If justice is perverted when a criminal defendant seeks to buy
testimony from a witness,'' Circuit Judge Paul J. Kelly wrote, ``it
is no less perverted when the government does so.'' Offering a
reduced prison sentence is the same as paying money to a witness,
the court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The panel ruled that the co-defendant's testimony should be
disallowed because of the government's illegal promises. The
appeals court ordered Singleton to be retried without the tainted
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the most revolutionary case since Gideon, if it
stands,'' said defense lawyer James Wyrsch, referring to the 1963
Supreme Court ruling that every criminal defendant was entitled to
a lawyer. ``It could affect state court prosecutions as well as
federal prosecutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some defense attorneys worried that the ruling will make
negotiating plea bargains more difficult, because prosecutors can't
explicitly promise leniency in exchange for testimony. And
witnesses who have struck deals without such explicit promises will
be tougher to attack on the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie N. Williams, the U.S. attorney for Kansas, declined to
comment on the ruling or on what his office's next step would be.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, lawyers would ask the entire 10th Circuit to review a
three-judge panel's ruling. If they fail with the circuit, lawyers
may then appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Brandenburg, a spokesman for the Justice Department in
Washington, said, ``We obviously disagreed with it (the ruling).
The question is what to do now.'' He said Justice Department
lawyers were meeting to determine how to handle the case.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the ruling strictly applies only to the 10th
Circuit, which encompasses Kansas, Colorado, Oklahoma, Utah, New
Mexico and Wyoming, though judges in other circuits could adopt the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see a flood of motions to suppress or motions
to strike'' witnesses who have cut deals with the government, said
Daniel E. Monnat, a Wichita lawyer who's also a director of the
National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Monnat also predicted that lawyers involved in cases already on
appeal will file supplemental briefs citing the Singleton case. He
did not know whether the ruling would affect such cases as
McVeigh's, in which key witness Michael Fortier received a reduced
sentence in exchange for his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals on new issues are rarely accepted if the issue wasn't
originally raised during the trial, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with the Singleton case noted that it is
practically identical to thousands of criminal cases prosecuted
across the country each year. After Singleton and six others were
indicted in 1996, one of the defendants decided to plead guilty and
testify against the others.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for Napoleon Douglas' cooperation, prosecutors in
Wichita promised to ask the judge to reduce Douglas' sentence, not
charge Douglas with any other crimes related to the case, and to
inform both the judge and Douglas' parole board of his cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Singleton's trial in January 1997, her lawyer,
Wachtel, read an article in a criminal-justice journal entitled:
``Paying the Witness _ Why Is It OK for the Prosecution, but Not
the Defense?''
</P>
<P>
   The article was written by an Oakland, Calif., lawyer named J.
Richard Johnston who was familiar with the federal bribery statute,
which reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever directly or indirectly gives, offers, or promises
anything of value to any person, for or because of the testimony
under oath...to be given by such person as a witness (at)
trial...shall be fined...or imprisoned for not more than two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's article concluded by suggesting to defense lawyers
that when prosecutors have promised anything of value in return for
testimony, ``the defense might at least ask the court to inform the
jury that this is an apparent violation of (the bribery statute).''
</P>
<P>
   Wachtel said he called Johnston and discussed it. Inside his
firm, Wachtel said, ``Everyone said, `You can't win.' '' He asked
U.S. District Judge Frank G. Theis to suppress Douglas' testimony,
and Theis refused.
</P>
<P>
   But in arguments before the 10th Circuit in Denver in January,
Wachtel said, the judges ``were very concerned that the federal
government might be violating the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the 25-page ruling was issued July 1. It concluded that
the government is as subject to the law as anyone else. ``We can
find no policy by which prosecutors may be excused from statutes
regulating testimony presented to the federal courts,'' Kelly
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Promising something of value to secure truthful testimony is
as much prohibited as buying perjured testimony,'' the opinion
continued. ``The government may still make deals with accomplices
for their assistance other than testimony, and it may still put
accomplices on the stand; it simply may not attach any promise,
offer, or gift to their testimony.'' MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
