<HEADLINE>
ART THAT STANDS ON ITS OWN 2 WHEELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in `a' and `e' category.) 
(mk) 
 By JIM McCRAW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While the art community may look upon ``The Art of
the Motorcycle'' at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum as 114 pieces
of 19th- and 20th-century kinetic sculpture from around the world,
the hordes of motorcyclists who will see the show this summer are
likely to view it as a long-overdue celebration of the sport, the
machines and the pioneers they love.
</P>
<P>
   And the exhibition is altogether timely, since 1998 marks the
50th anniversary of Honda motorcycles, the 75th anniversary of BMW
motorcycles (the show's sponsor) and the 95th anniversary of
Harley-Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Some 54 museums and private collections around the world
contributed machinery for display on the Guggenheim's spiral
walkways, clad for the summer in stainless steel by the architect
Frank Gehry, who was responsible for the installation.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition starts on the main floor with the world's first
motorcycle, the steam-powered Micheaux-Perreaux of 1868, and a 1998
MV Agusta F4, a 175-mile-an-hour superbike from Italy (on loan from
King Juan Carlos of Spain) raised on a platform, the alpha and
omega of motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry has put the earliest machinery in a single room, including
the first gasoline motorcycle, the 1886 Daimler that marked the
beginning of Daimler-Benz, and several gorgeous three-wheelers.
This way, observers can see the humble beginnings of a worldwide
industry. Upstairs, on the fifth and seventh levels, motorcycles of
the '50s and '90s stand in dimly lit side rooms, wavy ribbons of
highway under their tires.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside that gallery is the first series-produced
motorcycle, the 1894 Hildebrand &AMP; Wolfmuller from Germany, with its
monster 1,500-cubic-centimeter engine and 30-mile-an-hour top
speed. It provided the first hint that these early, utilitarian
machines _ replacements for the horse _ could be beautiful,
exciting and very fast.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few feet from the Hildebrand &AMP; Wolfmuller is one of the
more audacious machines in the show, the 1907 Curtiss, built by
Glenn Curtiss, an aviation pioneer and all-around daredevil.
Powered by an air-cooled V8 engine, this one-of-a-kind machine went
136.36 miles an hour at Ormond Beach, Fla., in 1907, setting a land
speed record that would stand for four years, and a motorcycle
speed record that would not be broken for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   Between the record-breaking Curtiss on the Guggenheim's first
level and a delicious silver, Italian-built 1997 Morbidelli V8 _
the world's only production V8 motorcycle _ on the seventh, there
are more than 100 bikes that enthusiasts will find historically
significant, beautiful and interesting.
</P>
<P>
   All the great bikes of the 20th century are represented. There
are several Harley-Davidson street bikes and racing bikes. Among
these is a 1957 Sportster, the machine that pulled Americans back
from their fling with British motorcycles, and that is still
produced 41 years later. Defunct American brands like Indian,
Henderson and Crocker are here, too.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sterling Triumph Bonneville, the bike of choice in
the 1950s for its combination of style, speed and sound; it was a
later version of the Triumph that Marlon Brando rode in ``The Wild
One.'' There is a Vincent Black Shadow, the fastest bike of its
time, with the biggest engine of its day (1,000cc) and a design
that used the engine itself as part of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   A personal favorite is the Ariel Square Four, with an engine
unlike any before or since. Whereas the Triumph is a ``vertical
twin,'' with one piston going up while the other goes down, the
Ariel Square Four has two vertical twins in one engine block, with
two crankshafts joined together. It was an idea that did not
endure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A gleaming Matchless G50 stands here, a single-cylinder 500cc
machine that raced successfully for years, unlike today's
one-season wonders. There is a Norton Manx, a monster that made its
name in races on the Isle of Man. Several BMWs are included _ from
the R32 of 1923, a wonderful melding of Art Deco and Bauhaus
design, to the 1998 R1200C cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Italy is well represented by a handful of Moto Guzzis, with
distinctive sideways V-twin engines and shaft drive. Exotic racing
and street Ducatis, the epitome of Italian industrial design, are
here in force, as are MV Agustas, significant for their world
championships and gorgeous aluminum castings.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the Honda Super Cub of 1958, every Japanese brand
is accounted for. Honda, Yamaha, Suzuki and Kawasaki are each
significant for their mechanical one-upmanship, their quality and
their broad appeal. It is no accident that Japanese companies are
the world's most successful motorcycle makers.
</P>
<P>
   There are bikes that gave a kick-start to car companies, that
grew up from scooters and bicycles, that came from arms makers,
aircraft manufacturers and international conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Are some bikes missing? Sure. There is, for instance, no Suzuki
RE5, the first bike with a Wankel rotary engine, which was followed
later by a Norton rotary. Both succumbed to anti-smog regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there a Honda CBX, an in-line six-cylinder that far
outsold the Benelli Sei six-cylinder from Italy that is
represented. There are no late-model turbo-charged bikes from
Japan. No Yamaha R1, the quickest bike in the world, zooming a
quarter-mile in less than 10 seconds. No Honda CBR1100XX, which is
the world's fastest street bike, capable of reaching 180 mph.
</P>
<P>
   And there is not a single police cycle on display. That is
astonishing, considering police bikes' importance to law
enforcement, their continual use in movies and their continued
production in the thousands every year. There are a couple of very
nice World War II military bikes, a German Zundapp and a U.S. Navy
Harley.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is light on sidecars, too, but the Bohmerland
that is here is red, yellow and wonderful. The Bohmerland
motorcycle and wood-trimmed sidecar could haul up to six people and
had a special low-range transmission for traversing mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation is simple, straightforward and uncluttered.
There are no rails, cables or cordons between the viewer and the
motorcycles. Each bike is held up on its tires, not by its
kickstand or center stand, but by tiny nonintrusive cables and
wedges of clear plastic, to give the impression that each bike
stands on its own. The information about each is printed directly
on the floor. The walls are stark white, and bare, with the
exception of a historic-placement blurb at the start of each
section, and there is plenty of light on the subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry and his colleagues could have slathered the walls with
film stills, advertising and poster art, but they didn't, and the
exhibition is better for it. These are elsewhere, mounted in
display cases along the rails of the walkways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of The Motorcycle'' is impressive in its depth,
breadth and purpose, worth several visits for avid motorcyclists.
No major museum will show this many motorcycles again for a long
time, and no other museum may ever do it this well.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES: ``The Art of the Motorcycle'' remains at the
Guggenheim Museum, Fifth Avenue at 89th Street, through Sept. 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
