<SLUG> BC-SPASMODIC-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPASMODIC DYSPHONIA TREATMENTS MORE THAN JUST TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - The Mayo Clinic in Scottsdale, Ariz., is one of
about half a dozen medical centers in the country conducting
research on the vocal disorder spasmodic dysphonia.
</P>
<P>
   Spasmodic dysphonia is a rare condition often mistaken for voice
strain or emotional illness. Although stress may exacerbate the
condition, it is a neurological disorder caused by faulty nerve
signals traveling from the basal ganglia area of the brain _ where
muscle movement is controlled _ to the vocal cords.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of spasmodic dysphonia. In the adductor
type, the vocal cords are squeezed shut, producing strangled,
strained speech. In the less common abductor type, the cords remain
open, producing intermittent breathiness.
</P>
<P>
   No cause is known, but in some patients there appears to be a
genetic component.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment for the ailment includes surgery in which a portion of
the laryngeal nerve is removed. For some patients, this proves to
be an effective long-term remedy. For others, it may provide only
temporary relief or none at all.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1980s, injections of botulinum toxin, or botox,
have proved a safe, effective, non-surgical treatment. The botox
temporarily weakens the vocal cords, leaving the voice soft or
breathy, depending on the amount of toxin given. As the toxin wears
off, the voice becomes stronger, producing a normal voice that can
last from three to six months or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Injections then must be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment of patients with the adductor type of spasmodic
dysphonia is more successful than for those who suffer the abductor
type.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors are still unfamiliar with the condition, and
patients may flounder before finding a proper diagnosis. But word
is spreading in the medical community, says Dr. Stephen Bansberg,
an otolaryngologist who treats about 200 spasmodic dysphonia
patients at Mayo Clinic Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more now that know it and recognize it so they
can get them (patients) to us faster, so we can treat it,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosis takes a practiced ear. No blood test exists to detect
the disorder; no scanning device can find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diagnosis is basically listening to the voice,'' Bansberg
says.
</P>
<P>
   Most patients come for treatment every three to four months.
Thursday is botox day at Mayo.
</P>
<P>
   Bansberg has seen dramatic recoveries in his patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a personal standpoint, it has become a significant part
of my practice,'' he says. Thursday ``has been one of my most
enjoyable days, my most fun thing to do. It's professionally
gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime sufferers are most grateful for the treatment. After
struggling for years to improve their speech, they revel in the
botox therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Younger patients who have yet to experience the worst of the
disorder are dismayed at the prospect of life-long treatment.
</P>
<P>
   They may have to wait some time for a cure, Mayo neurologist Dr.
Charles Adler says.
</P>
<P>
   Adler, who works in the field of movement disorders, says cures
for such neurological illnesses as Parkinson's disease and Lou
Gehrig's disease are more imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Until a cure is found, surgery and botox injections are the
patient's best hope. But that's pretty good, Bansberg says.
</P>
<P>
   Though spasmodic dysphonia is a rare condition, it is a
significant impairment. Some patients have voices so weak and so
strained ``it brings you to tears,'' Bansberg says.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that without treatment, they would fear losing their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone, the power of speech is an essential part of human
existence, Bansberg says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice is part of their being. It defines them as a
person.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
