<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-APPALACHIAN-HIKING-     07-09 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-APPALACHIAN-HIKING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE TRAIL WITH BILL BRYSON: UPHILL, DOWNHILL AND OUT OF SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add art note)  (Duplication warning: Also moving in `t' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic locator
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(bl) 
 By HUBERT B. HERRING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A book about hiking the Appalachian Trail? Spare me.
</P>
<P>
   I could imagine it: We walked. We saw trees. We went up. We went
down.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me while I watch some paint dry, or curl up with a good
phone directory.
</P>
<P>
   So why, on a sunny, crisp day, did I drive three hours to walk a
few miles of that trail with the book's author?
</P>
<P>
   Simple. Because the author is Bill Bryson, whose ``Notes From a
Small Island'' is a decidedly untouristy, nonlinear trek around
England, where he lived for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   And ``A Walk in the Woods,'' published by Broadway Books and on
The New York Times best-seller list for the fifth week July 12,
turned out to be far more than a walk on the Appalachian Trail. His
comically out-of-shape hiking partner, Stephen Katz (``he brought
to mind Orson Welles after a very bad night''), announces at the
outset that he cannot go an hour without a doughnut. And trail
banter is not the high-minded soul-searching of, say, Meriwether
Lewis, but: ``These college kids are willing to trade Pop Tarts for
Snickers. What do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   And why did he tackle the trail? No furrowed-brow, Everest-size
rationale _ no ``because it's THERE'' _ for Bryson. No, it was so
that the sight of the ``guys in camouflage pants and hunting hats''
at the local diner wouldn't make him ``feel like such a cupcake.''
</P>
<P>
   Splitting the difference between New York City and his home in
Hanover, N.H., we met in Williamstown, Mass.; the Appalachian
Trail, bouncing along the Berkshires, passes near here.
Appropriately, considering the junk-food theme that meanders so
defiantly through the book, we met at a Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   What was I in for? Bryson, on the page, seems like a cross
between boisterous stand-up comic and jovial misanthrope, skewering
practically everyone in his, well, path. Was I turning myself into
comic fodder?
</P>
<P>
   Probably. But when Bryson stepped out of his minivan, trademark
pipe in mouth, I didn't see a boisterous comic. I encountered a
gentle man, with a reddish beard, a National Geographic cap and
probably a bit more bulk than he had when he was in hiking trim.
</P>
<P>
   He and I headed off on our quest, which, befitting the book's
loony tone, nearly evolved into ``Searching for the Appalachian
Trail With Bill Bryson.'' He'd said in his book that often the
hardest part was getting onto the trail, and, sure enough, back and
forth we drove: ``Right past here.'' ``No, couldn't be this far.''
``I remember after coming out of the woods, sitting and having a
smoke just there.'' Even though he is an Iowa native, he has
acquired a hint of a British accent.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after asking a couple of neighbors, we tracked it down:
a skinny parting of the woods, a single white blaze painted on a
tree set back from the road.
</P>
<P>
   And it was through this inauspicious gateway that we stepped
onto the great trail. When one hears of the Appalachian Trail
marching grandly from Georgia to Maine, the Holy Grail of thousands
of hikers, it is easy to imagine some glittering promenade,
something out of ``The Wizard of Oz'' perhaps. Or, at the very
least, a wide, formidable path.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality is often more like what we encountered: dense,
rocky woods, sometimes with something resembling a path, sometimes
just a scramble. The hiker is essentially alone in the vast forest
that covers much of the Eastern United States, following, like
Hansel or Gretel with backpack, the white rectangles of paint that
the kindly trail-blazers have sprinkled in their wake. These
blazes, depending on the terrain, might appear on trees, standing
or fallen, or on a rock outcropping.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 100 yards into the woods, whose leaves were just gearing
up for their coming-out party, the shy Appalachian Trail finally
announced itself, with a sign assuring us that, ahead, lay Mount
Greylock and points south. Perhaps in understatement, perhaps not
to dispirit ``through hikers,'' it did not give the distance to
Georgia, which is perhaps 1,500-plus miles.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson walked ahead of me, clearly in his element out on this
trail, but seemingly exerting himself more than a seasoned hiker
would be expected to, even though he was not burdened by a hefty
backpacker's pack. In fact, to my surprise, he had no pack at all,
and turned down several offers of water from my daypack.
</P>
<P>
   We crossed a swampy area, where logs split lengthwise had been
inserted as a bridge, then headed up Mount Greylock, a solitary
peak that dominates the landscape here. As we did, the comic in
Bryson poked softly through as he related the unusual way he was
catapulted into full-time writing, something he had long pined to
do.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, while he was an editor at The Times of London, he and
his family were vacationing in Yorkshire. He ``was moaning more
than usual'' about escaping to some such place and focusing on his
writing. A few days after returning to work, his wife, Cynthia,
called and said: ``I've put the house on the market. If you're
going to do it, do it.'' (He recounted this with a laugh, but when
I asked his wife about it later, she said, ``He was furious.'')
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the house was sold, they moved to the country
and the rest is history, or at least Bryson's particular brand of
travel writing.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, he'd written with reverence that the trail ``is
said to be the largest volunteer-run undertaking on the planet.''
On his walk, he'd seen various volunteers doing trail maintenance,
and his reverence was intact now. ``Look,'' he said, pointing to a
fallen sawn-off log. ``Someone came up here with a chain saw _ FOR
US.'' A pause, then a childlike, heartfelt, ``Bless them.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whoops. We suddenly realized that the trail, and the white
blazes, had vanished. There is always a danger in the woods,
especially if you get lost in conversation or in reverie, that the
trail can zig when the instinct of your feet tells you to zag. We
retraced our steps, found the missed turn _ sure enough, it had
been marked by a log laid across the trail-not-to-be-taken, but we
had stepped right over it _ and headed steeply uphill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get lost on the trail,'' Bryson said as we huffed
upward, ``but once you do, it's easy to compound it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book, he tells of being accidentally separated overnight
from Katz deep in the Maine woods. It ended well, on a typically
comic note (``Lost, no water _ and you with the chocolate chip
cookies,'' Katz whined), but Bryson said now with true emotion,
``I've never been so happy to see another person.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz is a butt of so many jokes _ he balked at leaving a motel
to return to the trail because ``The X-Files'' was on and he'd just
stocked up on cream soda _ that I'd marveled that he didn't mind
the ridicule. ``It's a pseudonym,'' Bryson said. ``Katz was the
name of a Des Moines drugstore.'' Was ``Katz'' exaggerated?
``Plenty!'' he shot back with a grin. ``But is that what the trip
was like? Exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   On their 1996 trip, Bryson and ``Katz'' did not finish the
trail; they did a long stretch here, little bits there, for a total
of 870 miles out of more than 2,100. ``I plan to do the whole
thing,'' Bryson insisted now. But his writing is so giddy, so
loopy, that completeness would somehow seem a sacrilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only part I feel guilty about,'' he said, ``is not
finishing the 100-mile wilderness in Maine,'' a weeklong trek that
completes the trail with a triumphant ascent of Mount Katahdin.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson, who is 46 (``but I have a body that's much older''), had
lamented how quickly he had gotten out of shape. And at one
particularly rugged spot, with the trail rising dramatically
through a stand of evergreens, the views starting to open up
through the trees, he said, ``If this gets much steeper, this'll
have to be a memorial article: the end of Bill Bryson.''
</P>
<P>
   He does walk most places: ``I have to because I've written about
it so much.'' In the book, he comes up with the startling statistic
that an average American walks just 350 yards a day, a state of
affairs he calls ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   We hiked an hour or so to a windy clearing that delivered a
stunning vista of Williamstown and the Vermont hills beyond. After
coming north through New York, Connecticut and Massachusetts, the
trail from here skims the spine of Vermont's Green Mountains, then
crosses into New Hampshire at Hanover, where, since 1995, Bryson
has lived with his wife and four children, aged 7 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   From a spot like this, I could easily imagine the lure of the
Appalachian Trail, the lure of being pulled along over those
mountains. The trail, from here, seemed like an idyllic stroll over
modest mountains, though in fact it ranges from the literally
pedestrian _ walking along roads or across the Bear Mountain Bridge
in New York _ to the grueling, like the steep, rocky, wind-blasted
ascent of Mount Washington in New Hampshire's White Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Even knowing that, the pull was strong, but reality intruded.
Time was scarce. We would have to turn around here.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, the New York-New Jersey Trail Conference is
celebrating the 75th anniversary of the Appalachian Trail this
year, dating to the 1923 completion of a section in Harriman State
Park. Bryson, in giving the history of the trail, notes that work
began in earnest in 1930 and the trail was completed in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   I offered some trail mix, but he turned it down. ``I can't eat
things like that anymore,'' he said. ``I ate so much of it.'' But
he eyed my particular mix with scientific interest, clearly having
become a connoisseur. Then, with a cold wind blowing and the
sweeping vista as a backdrop, he huddled under his jacket to light
his pipe. On his hike, he said, he got bored at his campsite at
night, so he picked up a pipe when he first dropped in on
civilization. But ``I plan to quit on the book tour,'' he vowed.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson glanced longingly at the sign that said three miles or so
to the top of Greylock, pointing to another inauspicious parting of
the woods, and said, ``I wish we had time to go the whole way.''
</P>
<P>
   He was about to take a break for a trip to England, ``to get
away from my publicist,'' he said with a laugh. ``No, it's to plan
a TV series _ a sort of `Notes From a Small Island' on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   And his next book? ``It will be about Australia,'' he said.
``I'd always thought of Australia as `Baywatch' with cricket, but
after going there I know there's a lot more to it.''
</P>
<P>
   This hike, he said as we reluctantly headed down, ``was one of
my favorite days on the trail.'' Then he paused and added with a
slight sigh: ``I could DO this. If someone said, `I'd give you a
living wage to go out and walk every day,' I'd do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
