<HEADER>
A8134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-IRS-BOS &LR;      07-09 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-IRS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE WILL SIGN IRS OVERHAUL MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Acting on an election-year crowd-pleaser, the
Senate Thursday adopted and sent to President Clinton legislation
that will change the rules of the game for the nation's most hated
government bureaucrat _ the tax collector.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Thursday that he will sign into law the most
comprehensive overhaul of the Internal Revenue Service in 46 years.
The bill will extend rights and protections to taxpayers subjected
to audits every year, as well as shorten the time needed to take
advantage of a cut in the capital-gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of politically explosive congressional hearings
featuring taxpayers' tales of abuse by the IRS, Congress designed
the legislation to accelerate the transformation of the IRS from a
feared and aggressive tax collector to a customer-friendly agency
focused on the 98 percent of taxpayers whose returns are never
audited.
</P>
<P>
   The tax break provision, which critics contend primarily
benefits wealthy stock speculators, will reduce the time
investments must be held to qualify for lower 20 percent capital
gains tax to 12 months from 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 96-2 to adopt the bill, while the House two
weeks earlier approved it 402-8. Senators opposing the measure were
Democrats Paul Wellstone of Minnesota and John D. Rockefeller IV of
West Virginia. GOP Senators Jon Kyl of Arizona and Kay Bailey
Hutchison of Texas did not vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that the Senate has finally passed bipartisan
legislation to reform the IRS and strengthen taxpayer rights,''
Clinton said in a statement. ``This reform will help my effort to
create an IRS that respects American taxpayers and respects their
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate majority leader Trent Lott congratulated Clinton for
``finally coming around to our side on IRS reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year the White House said we didn't need significant IRS
reform,'' said Lott. ``They supported weak reforms and opposed
creating an oversight board.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration acknowledged that IRS abuses took
place, but insisted they were uncommon and not experienced by the
vast majority of taxpayers. A compromise in the measure will allow
a new oversight board to provide strategic direction for the IRS,
but leave day-to-day operational decisions in the hands of
government workers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will cost an estimated $12.9 billion over 10
years as a result of less-aggressive tax collections. To offset
part of that cost, the law will allow some wealthy, elderly
taxpayers to convert their individual retirement accounts into Roth
IRAs, which should raise an estimated $8 billion in the next 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   IRS spokesman Steve Pyrek said the legislation will help Tax
Commissioner Charles O. Rossotti reorganize and modernize the
agency that collects $1.6 trillion in taxes every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to provide us with the kind of tools we need to
provide the kind of services we want to offer,'' said Pyrek.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will shift the burden of proof in many cases
from the taxpayer to the IRS, a change that brings tax prosecution
more in line with other criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``For far too long, the Internal Revenue Service has been
allowed to consolidate power without the counterbalance of
accountability,'' said Senator William V. Roth Jr. of Delaware,
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee. ``This is the bipartisan
conference agreement on a plan that will effectively change the way
the Internal Revenue Service does business.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will create a nine-member oversight board, which
will include six members from the private sector, to help develop a
strategic plan for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, a former Virginia high-technology executive appointed
by Clinton to take over the beleaguered agency last November, will
get new powers over personnel intended to speed up the
reorganization into a more businesslike operation.
</P>
<P>
   The new law will require the IRS to fire an employee who lies,
falsifies, or detroys documents to hide mistakes or deliberately
fas to obtain approval signatures on documents authorizing the
seizure of a taxpayers' home, personal belongings or business
assets. The bill will create a new Treasury Department inspector
general for tax administration to oversee wrongdoing by IRS
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also will protect innocent spouses from tax bills
incurred by their divorced or separated partners and make it more
difficult for the IRS to seize residences to satisfy unpaid tax
bills. It also will restrict the agency's ability to charge
interest and levy penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The new law will prohibit the IRS from seizing a home to cover
the cost of tax bills amounting to less than $5,000 and will
require the agency to first obtain a court order.
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping measure was a priority for Republican lawmakers who
view it as part of their tax-cut philosophy. The reorganization
attracted Democratic and White House support after a series of
congressional hearings featured wronged taxpayers last fall and
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders consider the IRS bill as the first step
toward eliminating the entire tax code. The House earlier this year
voted narrowly to abolish the tax code, but that bill is not
expected to pass the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision of the legislation, requested by Las Vegas
gambling interests who provide free meals to their workers, will
allow the meals to be tax free for the employees and be a tax
deduction for the companies.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will also replace the trade law term ``most
favored nation'' with ``normal trade relations.'' Granting ``most
favored nation'' status to a country, such as China, has become a
contentious issue in recent years, and many lawmakers were
uncomfortable with the term because it suggested a preferential
status.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
