ATTN: Managing editors, entertainment editors, weekend editors:
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following celebrity profiles and features.
</P>
<P>
   The articles, which moved within the last week, are from The New
York Times (NYT), The Boston Globe (BOS), Los Angeles Daily News
(LADN), Hearst Newspapers (HNS), Fort Worth Star-Telegram (TEX) and
The Arizona Republic (AZR).
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmissions of these stories, please call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LUCINDAWILLIAMS-COX (Nashville) _ With the great reception her
songs are getting at packed shows, the road is bliss for
singer-writer Lucinda Williams. By Eileen M. Drennen.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SPICE-BOS (Undated) _ A Spice Girls Q&AMP;A, with Baby Spice,
instead of Ginger Spice. By Jim Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROCK-BOS (Undated) _ ``I used to work in a retail record
store,'' says KC (ne: Harry Wayne Casey), the brains, voice, and
hook-meister of KC and the Sunshine Band, a man who knows the joy
of repetition. By Jim Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-OZZY-BOS (Undated) _ Ozzy Osbourne is the godfather of
heavy metal, the now-sober icon to whom all young metal-ites turn
for inspiration and insight. By Jim Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CARPENTER-BOS (Undated) _ Mary Chapin Carpenter has
nothing to promote right now. She's on the road merely for the fun
of it, because she wanted to play. By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-VANMORRISON-BOS (Undated) _ Unreleased Van Morrison
emerges from the twilight zone. By Thomas C. Palmer Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LOVETT-TEX (Undated) _ Two Texans are having breakfast with
screenwriter-director Don Roos when Roos asks them to explain the
difference between Dallas and Fort Worth. One of the Texans is Lyle
Lovett, so it seems best to defer to him. Lovett, having just
polished off a plate of ``huevos rancheros,'' gives the standard
line: Fort Worth is old cattle culture, Dallas is new money. But
then, Lovett waxes nostalgic. By Robert Philpot.
</P>
<P>
   CELEBS-BULLOCK-COX _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Actress Sandra Bullock may
be best known for her roles as an Internet whiz and a damsel in
distress, but in Austin, she's building a reputation as a real
estate investor.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ALEXIE-PROFILE-HNS (Undated) _ Screenwriter Sherman Alexie,
whose novels have the bite of a mad dog but rely on the beauty of
the human spirit, talks about his latest project: ``Smoke
Signals.'' The movie garnered the Audience Award and the Filmmakers
Trophy at the most recent Sundance Film Festival. By Andy Summa.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-ALEXIE-BOS (Miami Beach) _ Director Sherman Alexie
suggests that ``Smoke Signals'' flows counter to the current
Hollywood trend not because it is so new, but because it is like so
many other movies. By Michael Saunders. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KEROUAC-ESTATE-NYT (New York) _ The battle over Jack Kerouac's
estate grows heated. By Robert Smith.
</P>
<P>
   WAR-POET-KAN (Undated) _ George Hamby went off to World War I,
serving in the same division as a first lieutenant named Harry
Truman. Fought at Verdun and in the Argonne, returned home, found
that his fiancee was dead of the flu. He became a steelworker and
outlived two wives. An unremarkable life, except for this: When he
died two years ago, this uneducated man left behind poetry written
from the trenches. Some of it sad. Some of it funny. By Barbara
Hollingsworth.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-WHITE-PROFILE-HNS (Undated) _ Author and commentator Bailey
White's personal style may keep her uneasy in the spotlight, but it
endears her to her fans as well. White wrote ``Quite a Year for
Plums.'' By Carol Rust.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-SONDHEIM-REVIEW-HNS (Undated) _ Following well-received
biographies of several key 20th-century artists (painter Salvador
Dali, architect Frank Lloyd Wright, composer Leonard Bernstein),
Meryle Secrest has turned her attention to Stephen Sondheim,
indisputably the most important composer and lyricist in
contemporary musical theater. By Everett Evans.
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-ALEXIE-SPI (Undated) An in-depth profile of Sherman
Alexie, the nationally known Indian writer and Seattle resident who
turns to film now with the indie production of ``Smoke Signals,'' a
film festival hit which opens nationally and in Seattle on July 3.
Just what makes this 32-year-old phenom run? And is he is danger of
spreading himself too thin, what with his poems, short stories,
novels and films, plus a relentless schedule of public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENERAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROY-ROGERS-APPRECIATION-HNS (Undated) _ Roy Rogers was really a
guy named Leonard Slye who was born in Cincinnati but grew up in
Marietta, Ohio. The fact that he was a fellow Ohioan was not lost
on me. Even as a 6-year-old member-in-good-standing of the Roy
Rogers Club, Columbus chapter, I felt we had a special bond. By
Cynthia Robins.
</P>
<P>
   MOXLEY-MURDER-BOS (Greenwich, Conn.) _ Twenty-three years after
the bloody murder of Martha Moxley, investigators are reopening the
case, probably hoping DNA typing can finally identify the killers.
By Ellen O'Brien. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   ALLENDE-COOKING-NYT (Undated) _ The morning sun that flooded
Isabel Allende's kitchen was as innocent and unblemished as a
perfect egg yolk. It slid across the hand-painted ceramic tile
counter, warmed her back and made her dangling silver earrings
sparkle. But the 56-year-old Chilean novelist was, for the moment,
immune to the poetry and the pleasure of the spring sun. Bent in
her own shadow, calibrating the flame under the omelet pan on her
stove, Ms. Allende, had surrendered to an atavistic ritual of the
kind that might have made a scene in one of her novels. By Molly
O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   HANNAH-HOME (Oxford, Miss.) _ It's not easy to imagine what sort
of house Barry Hannah might live in. His characters, who saunter
and stumble and soliloquize through his heavily autobiographical
fiction seem to have no home: they are drunk at the controls of a
jet or bargaining with God atop a horse or roaring down the road in
a Lincoln with beer cans rattling around the floorboard. So it is
strange to step out of Hannah's Jeep Cherokee, with a basket of
bright new tennis balls in the back seat, and onto the driveway of
his modest, Eisenhower-era house in this pretty, antebellum town.
By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
