<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8152 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-BRAZIL-HNS &LR;      07-09 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BRAZIL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Brazil's coach stands alone
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ Brazil coach Mario Zagallo stood there alone,
pandemonium breaking out around him, an ear-splitting din spreading
across the Stade Velodrome and Brazil celebrating a berth in the
World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
   Players and assistant coaches sprinted onto the field to
celebrate the stirring penalty-kick shootout win over the
Netherlands on Tuesday. Drum beats and blinding colors filled the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo tried to rejoice, but after a few steps onto the field,
he stopped, slumped his shoulders and burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   He walked in a small circle and looked around the stadium, as if
searching for someone to hug. He took off his glasses and lowered
his head, as his chest trembled from the emotion and tears streamed
down his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have known the yellow jerseys a long time,'' Zagallo said.
``I was happy.''
</P>
<P>
   It might have been the most appropriate picture of them all
Tuesday night, as Brazil moved toward Sunday's World Cup showdown
with France.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo, 66, the ``Gray Wolf,'' a man whose every move has been
scrutinized and often criticized for most of the past four years,
celebrated the moment by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Always, Zagallo has by himself had to withstand the pressure of
coaching the world's greatest soccer team under the world's
greatest collective microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are involved in Brazilian football, you are expected
to be a dominating team,'' Zagallo said. ``I know this.''
</P>
<P>
   And when even the slightest imperfection shows itself, of which
there were several in the months before Tuesday night's victory,
Brazilians traditionally skewer the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the coach is Zagallo, who has been involved with the
Brazilian monster practically since birth and in most countries
would be a legend, it does not seem to matter.
</P>
<P>
   Even moments before Tuesday's wild celebration, when Zagallo
made the bold move of picking Emerson as one of his five choices in
the penalty shootout, gasps of surprise could be heard inside the
stadium as Emerson walked toward the penalty spot.
</P>
<P>
   Before that critical moment, Emerson had appeared in only two
games throughout the tournament and had just five national-team
appearances total. But Zagallo went with a hunch.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Brazilian media _ you think American journalists
are critical? _ literally were yelling at Zagallo from the media
stands, calling him an old fool.
</P>
<P>
   But Emerson easily whipped in the shot. Brazil won.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I saw in training I knew he was a penalty-taker,''
Zagallo said of Emerson. ``He has good nerve. And he took his
penalty just as he did in training.''
</P>
<P>
   By himself, Zagallo took the chance on the young Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   Barely more than a week earlier, when Brazil lost a meaningless
first-round game to Norway after clinching first place in Group A,
Zagallo again was in the middle of the fire, with calls for him to
be fired even as the team moved on.
</P>
<P>
   He was called ``a second-rate coach'' by legendary Brazilian
star Carlos Alberto. It was pointed out over and over again in the
media that only one team ever had lost a first-round game and went
on to win the World Cup (Germany, in 1990).
</P>
<P>
   Others criticized Zagallo for sticking to a game style that was
40 years old, as Brazilian newspaper Estado de Sao Paulo called it.
</P>
<P>
   Even the incomparable Pel, a longtime friend of Zagallo's, said
the Brazilian team looked slow and badly prepared in first-round
games.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo's response: ``The World Cup doesn't begin until after
group play. Without a shadow of a doubt, we will respond. The
players know what went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil responded with a 4-1 thrashing of highly regarded Chile
in the round of 16 and has not stopped steaming toward a fifth
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just one match to go,'' Zagallo said. ``We will get
there. We will get the fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo has been a part of all four of Brazil's titles.
</P>
<P>
   He was a teammate of a teen-age Pel in 1958, when Brazil blasted
Sweden 5-2 in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later in Chile, he was the veteran captain and
acknowledged heart of a Brazilian team that topped Czechoslovakia
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, he was head coach and helped assemble perhaps the
greatest soccer team in history, with the likes of Pel, Jairzinho
and Carlos Alberto cruising through the tournament and overwhelming
Italy 4-1 for the championship at Estadio Azteca in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   And four years ago the Brazilian federation named Zagallo team
supervisor, a sort of coach behind the coach, as Carlos Alberto
Parreira took Brazil to a shootout victory over Italy.
</P>
<P>
   No one in soccer can match Zagallo's run of success.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there he was Tuesday night, weeping all alone as if it was
his first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people do not realize how difficult it is to win in
the World Cup,'' Zagallo said. ``That was a very difficult game we
had. We easily could have been the losers. I appreciate every game
we win.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo's players support him. Dunga, 35, the veteran and
captain whom many believe will succeed Zagallo as head coach in
four years, bristles when asked about the criticism Zagallo has
received.
</P>
<P>
   ``His job is tougher than anyone's,'' Dunga said.
</P>
<P>
   In a game where it takes a lot of ego to be among the best _ and
Brazilian players admit they might lead the world in egos, too _
some have criticized Zagallo's cautious style and selection of
starters.
</P>
<P>
   When he named Bebeto to replace the injured Romario before the
World Cup and Bebeto proceeded to look tired and old in early
games, Denilson, 21, begged for playing time and the nation seemed
to agree.
</P>
<P>
   But Zagallo stayed with his choice and in victories over Denmark
and the Netherlands, Bebeto had his best games. In both games,
Denilson came in late and offered a boost of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo says he will stay with Bebeto for Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot bear the thought of not winning, just like everyone
else in Brazil cannot,'' Zagallo said. ``I have to do the things
that I believe will help us win. If people say we are playing an
ugly game, I'd rather play an ugly game and win than pretty
football and lose.''
</P>
<P>
   As Brazil barrels toward another crown, he stands alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one game left,'' Zagallo said. ``Our mission is
almost complete. It hasn't been very easy, but now we have no
doubt. We are saving our best game for the last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine how it will be when everyone plays their best game. It
will be beautiful. We will win, I have no doubt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
