<HEADLINE>
THE TRIBUTES KEEP ON COMING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is talk at the University of California at Riverside of
establishing a  &UR; Sonny Bono &LR;  School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a statue of the late rock star/politician is being
built in downtown Palm Springs, reports the Los Angeles Times. But
that's not enough; a triangle of land in Dupont Circle in
Washington is being designated Sonny Bono Park, a place that will
be marked with a plaque and a vault containing a pair of
congressional cufflinks and the sheet music for ``The Beat Goes
On.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING THERE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. astronaut  &UR; Andrew Thomas  &LR; said Wednesday, in a press
conference upon returning to Earth after 130 days aboard the space
station Mir, that he thought the ``dull'' blue and gray interiors
should be painted light blue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not one eentsy little time, in 18 driving scenes shown in
``Nash Bridges'' and examined by the American Coalition for Traffic
Safety, does Nash Bridges, his sidekick or any good or bad guy on
the show ever buckle his or her seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Elliott Mintz &LR; , publicist for  &UR; Don Johnson &LR; , told the Wall
Street Journal that he would discuss the matter with his client.
The coalition raises ``an important point,'' he said, ``and one
that shouldn't be summarily dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Israeli airline El Al is offering flights to nowhere,
whereon passengers pay $85 for a gourmet dinner, all the wine they
can drink and their choice of four movies. The plane never leaves
the skies over Jerusalem. ``I think it's going to be a great
success,'' an El Al spokesman told Moment magazine., &LR;  ``(It's) very
decadent.''
</P>
<P>
   _ British Airways flight attendants have been instructed to be
``less British'' and ``more informal,'' says a report in the Daily
Telegraph of London. The staff has been told to look passengers in
the eye and be more outgoing and friendly. ``Forty million people a
year fly with us,'' said an Airways spokesman explaining the need
for a new attitude, ``and very many of them are not British.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pennsylvania Legislature is considering laws to ban
discrimination against motorcyclists or people dressed like
motorcyclists in employment, public accommodation and housing, says
Independent Biker magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Driving along the Oregon coast last week,  &UR; Thomas Burchfield &LR;
</P>
<P>
   saw a sign that read ``Nehalem'' (the name of the town),
``Public Dump and Cemetery.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ninety members of that rollicking and boisterous Kennedy clan
went to Hyannis Port over the weekend to have some good, clean
family fun and to work on their image. The Boston Herald reported
that the event was family-only but for a crew from People magazine
(well, somebody has to report how wholesome they've become).
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``People's Court'' ruling in that Florida case where a man
claimed injuries from being hit with the wares of a topless dancer:
He was hit, said  &UR; Ed Koch &LR; , but he wasn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rocky Mountain News reported that the airplanes pulling
``Got Milk?'' and ``Nantucket Nectars'' banners over the All-Star
game in Denver were sanitized versions of the banners for strip
joints usually flown over games.
</P>
<P>
   _ More spy food, from  &UR; Matt Buka &LR; : Cloak au Vin, Peep Tarts,
007-Up, Goldfingers and Chicken Pot Spy.  &UR; Dave Edmonds &LR;  suggests
Mata Hari-cots verts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Invitation to Saturday's Rockin' Rainforest Gala at the
California Academy of Sciences specified the attire: black tie or
frog suits.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Times of London's list of possible  &UR; Tina Brown &LR;  successors
at the New Yorker include in-house possibilities:
 &UR; Hendrik Hertzberg &LR; , senior editor;  &UR; Kurt Andersen &LR; , columnist;
 &UR; David Remnick &LR; , staff writer;  &UR; Bill Buford &LR; , literary editor.
</P>
<P>
   Outside possibilities: Slate editor  &UR; Michael Kinsley &LR; ; Time
magazine's  &UR; Walter Isaacson &LR; ; Vanity Fair editor  &UR; Graydon Carter &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to jump into my bucket of fear and go out and audition
for stronger roles. Now's the time for me to take the time to
polish the rough edges and learn to say a line instead of making
faces.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jenny McCarthy relaunching herself as a serious actress _ she
promised to stop sticking out her tongue _ in Movieline magazine.
She said she was so offended when Steven Seagal asked her to take
off her dress to audition for a role in ``Under Siege 2,'' that she
told him to rent her Playboy video if that's what he wanted.
</P>
</TEXT>
