<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8159 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      07-09 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Friday, July 10. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
ARPAIO-ATTACK (Phoenix) - A 27-year-old Glendale, Ariz.,
hairstylist apologized to Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio
Thursday and said he doesn't remember attacking him the night
before near a Scottsdale strip mall. The sheriff is taking it
personally: ``When he saw me, something went crazy.'' Sean
Huskisson was arrested on suspicion of aggravated assualted after
he allegedly hit Arpaio in the throat and wrestled with two other
law officers. By CHRISTINA LEONARD. Story will move in the ``A''
category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUNS' PLANE - The Phoenix Suns basketball team says recent news
reports about the FAA weighing maintenance sanctions against
America West Airlines have ``heightened our sense of urgency to
change planes for the remaining term of our charter agreement.''
The Suns fly on the oldest plane in the America West fleet, a 1969
737-100. It's had its share of problems, including an incident last
spring when a pilot walked off the plane with Suns players aboard,
concerned that it wasn't safe to fly. After being reassured that
the plane was flight worthy even though it was missing its yaw
damper, he returned and flew without incident. Checking with
America Westt to see if they've repaired the part, which is subject
to a recall by Boeing. The plane, which also flies commercially
during the Suns' off season, just returned late last month from a
major maintenence check. With AVIATION. By
</P>
<P>
   MARY JO PITZL. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AVIATION-MCCAIN (Washington) - Arizona Sen. John McCain won
committee passage of a bill designed to restore quiet at national
parks by establishing a system to limit flights overhead. But the
senator was also attacked by citizens' groups for pushing through
an unrelated provision that would allow more daily flights to take
off and land at large airports. Some groups said McCain was
buddying up to America West Airlines, which would become eligible
for direct flights between Phoenix and Washington's Reagan
National. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SMOKE-FILM
</P>
<P>
   (Undated) -  &UR; First-time director Chris Eyre and the gifted
writer Sherman Alexie wove their intimate experiences as Native
Americans into ``Smoke Signals,'' an honest, funny and moving film
that sends up Hollywood stereotypes of American Indians. It is the
first major commercial movie written, directed and co-produced by
Native Americans and starring Native Americans. Wtih SMOKE-REID. By
BOB FENSTER. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SMOKE-REID (Undated) - ``Arizona Republic'' reporter Betty Reid saw
an early screening of ``Smoke Signals,'' loved the thoughtfulness
and the humor, and compares it to life on the reservation. By BETTY
REID. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MADELINE-FILM (Undated) - Ludwig Bemelmans delighted families for
generations with his sing-song stories and charming drawings of the
12 little girls of Paris who lived in two straight lines and their
Dear Miss Clavel, who cherished and protected them. How can you
turn such a delicate treasure into a movie? With delicate attention
to detail and whimsy, it turns out in ``Madeline.`` By BOB FENSTER.
Story will move in the ``E`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LETHAL-FILM (Undated) - It's ``Lethal Weapon 4,'' which means more
humor, more things blowing up, more Mel Gibson-Danny Glover-Joe
Pesci, now with Rene Russo and Chris Rock to fill things out. Does
it hold up in sequel land? Is it worth its $140 million pricetag?
By BOB FENSTER. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RETRO (Phoenix) - For Amy Bowling, there's nothing interesting in
the '90s. Flashback three decades and Bowling is right at home,
basking in the comfort of a Charles Eames lounge chair and ottoman.
In her time-warp world, she wears vintage clothes, decorates her
apartment in '60s modern furniture and frequents the kind of
lounges that never bothered to update the furnishings. Bowling is
part of an ever-growing subculture that collects and craves all
things vintage. These people spend most of their waking hours
living in yester-decade. With sidebar RETROMUSIC and photo. By JAYE
BEELER. Stories moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOFU (Undated) - Ponce de Leon needed a better map. Forget the
Fountain of Youth. He should have been looking for the (beginital
field (endital) _ that is a field filled with soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to praise a bean, but this is one mighty bean.
</P>
<P>
   Research shows that not only can it lower fat and cholesterol in
diets by pinch-hitting for numerous items heavy in animal fats, but
soy can play a preventive role in the fight against several
cancers, including breast, colon and prostate. Soy also has been
found to help soften the unpleasant symptoms of menopause. With
sidebar TOFU LIST. By STEFANIE L. PEARSON. Stories moved in the
``D'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SPASMODIC (Undated) - When Norma Barer began having trouble
speaking 40 years ago, she was told it was stress, it was nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors blamed her gender. Psychologists said it was all in
her head. It was not until the late 1980s that she finally received
a definitive diagnosis. It (begin ital) was (endital) all in her
head _ in her brain, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Barer is one of the estimated 30,000 to 50,000 Americans who
suffer from a vocal disorder called spasmodic dysphonia. With
SPASMODICSIDE. By BARBARA YOST. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
