<HEADLINE>
60,000 SUBSCRIBERS TO SHARE $8 MILLION IN BC-BS SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts has agreed
to pay $8 million in refunds to about 60,000 &UR;  &LR; subscribers to settle
a lawsuit alleging that it had failed to pass along hospital
discounts to policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which awaits approval from federal and state
courts, concludes a lawsuit filed in 1995 by Health Care For All, a
Boston consumer group. Blue Cross, the state's largest health
insurer, denied wrongdoing as part of the settlement reached May 26
but disclosed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit covers consumers who purchased traditional indemnity
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tremendous victory for consumers,'' said Robert
Restuccia of Health Care For All. ``We applaud the management of
Blue Cross for recognizing a problem and working with us to solve
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross officials could not be reached for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement calls for Blue Cross to pay $8 million to 60,000
subscribers, plus about $1.25 million in lawyers fees, $175,000 to
the Caring for Children Foundation, and $50,000 to Health Care For
All, the lead plaintiff in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The case is one of about a dozen similar lawsuits filed against
Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans across the country, including
those in New Hampshire, Vermont, Virginia, Ohio, North Carolina and
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the lawsuits allege that the health plans deceived
their subscribers, who can wind up paying more than their fair
share of the bill. The practice works this way: A Blue Cross member
undergoes surgery at a hospital. The charge is $10,000. Under a
contract that requires patients to be responsible for 20 percent of
the charge, the subscriber pays $2,000. But insurers frequently get
discounts from hospitals. If the discount is 50 percent, the actual
bill is just $5,000. The subscriber's $2,000 payment then amounts
to 40 percent of the actual bill. Meanwhile the insurer pays
$3,000, or 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Blue Cross of Massachusetts in the past argued that it passed
along the savings to its policyholders in the form of lower
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, a Superior Court judge last week allowed a
lawsuit against Blue Cross to obtain class-action status. The
lawsuit, filed by Thomas Prive of Merrimack, N.H., alleges that
Blue Cross of New Hampshire failed to share hospital discounts with
its policyholders. The insurer has denied those charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts lawsuit alleged that Blue Cross engaged in the
practice between Jan. 1, 1990, to Dec. 31, 1995. Only subscribers
of traditional indemnity policies who paid coinsurance for hospital
care during that period would be eligible for a refund, according
to Stephen Rosenfeld, the lead attorney in the case. Rosenfeld said
he expects subscribers to be notified ``within several months.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross discontinued the practice on Jan. 1, 1996. At the
time, the insurer said the move was unrelated to the lawsuit filed
by Health Care For All or the furor raised by consumer groups in
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   If judges in Suffolk Superior Court and US District Court in
Boston grant their preliminary approval, the insurer will send out
notices to subscribers eligible for refunds, which would range from
$25 to thousands of dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the settlment is significant for Blue Cross, which
made just $12.7 million in 1997, after a $97 million loss in
1996. &UR;  &LR; Insurance companies, however, typically set aside money in
their budgets to cover lawsuit settlements or adverse legal
judgments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
