<HEADER>
A8171 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKE-REID-AZR &LR;      07-09 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-REID-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN SENSE OF HUMOR DELIGHTFULLY SHOWCASED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BETTY REID  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - The stoic Indian, silent and proud, has long been a
stereotype of American film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals,'' a new movie written and directed by and
starring Native Americans, demonstrates that humor is very much a
part of reservation life.
</P>
<P>
   While the movie is often hilarious, it also deals with serious
issues common in Indian life _ alcoholism and fatherless families
struggling through cultural and economic crises.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins on the Coeur d'Alene Reservation in Idaho.
Victor (Adam Beach) sets off on a journey to Phoenix to recover the
ashes of his father, who has died years after abandoning his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Victor is accompanied by chatterbox Thomas (Evan Adams), who
lost his own father as a baby. Thomas is kind of a lovable nerd,
who talks endlessly as he tries to work out the meaning of being
Indian in 1990s America.
</P>
<P>
   Some Phoenix area Indians were treated to advance screenings in
April and June.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Curley, who grew up on the Navajo Reservation, was
delighted by the movie's portrayal of the funny side of Indian
life. He especially enjoyed the scene that showed Thomas'
transformation into an Indian Superman at a roadside cafe during
the trip to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   In the scene, Thomas, sporting two braids and a pinstripe suit,
walks into the bathroom. But when he comes out, his jet-black hair
is flying in the breeze and he's wearing a Superman T-shirt
emblazoned with ``Frybread Power.'' At first, he glares like a
fierce Indian warrior, the image that he thinks the world expects.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as Victor sizes him up, he puts on a silly grin that shows
he's aware of the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas could not hold it in,'' Curley said. ``I think he
grinned because that wasn't him. After that scene, he reverts back
to himself toward the end of the movie because the braids return.''
</P>
<P>
   But even these Indian movie buffs find Indian humor hard to
define. Many struggled to describe it, then simply said, ``You
know, it's what happens on the `rez' or among a group of Indian
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean Harmon, a Hunkpati Lakota Sioux who lives in Tempe, Ariz.,
with her two sons, said simple rez expressions such as the teasing
``aaayy'' can unleash laughter among the Sioux. On the Navajo Rez,
``chish'' can produce the same result.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to understand Indian humor, and ``Smoke Signals''
did a real good job,'' Harmon said. ``Indian humor is like when a
tribal member gets a new hairdo or dresses up. To the mainstream
audience, someone will say, `You look nice.' To Indians, its,
`Aaayy, what a nice haircut' or, `Who are you? Going to a funeral?'
''
</P>
<P>
   To Harmon, Thomas' transformation scene at the cafe is all about
Indian men and their egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian guys are as vain as Indian women because they like the
long-hair look, it gives them that warrior look,'' Harmon said. ``A
non-Indian woman might say, `Look at that manly Indian.' Indian
women will say, `Aaayy, get over yourself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with local Native Americans show that Indian humor
draws heavily on teasing, puns in both English and Indian
languages, efforts to take the sting out of serious events, and
enjoying the foibles of non-Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals'' tackles stereotypes about buffaloes, warriors
and the reserved Indian through satire. Images of fry bread,
``Indian cars,'' vast rolling landscapes and extended relatives do
not escape Indian humor.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Knox, a teenage Hopi-Pima and Maricopa, enjoyed references
to that delectable fry bread. In one of Thomas' stories, Victor's
mother is caught in a fry-bread-shortage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   There are only so many round fry breads available to feed a
large army of relatives. The solution, as told by Thomas, is to cut
the yummy bread in half so more people are fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make a lot of food when there are Hopi ceremonies,'' Knox
said. ``We make enough, but sometimes there is a shortfall. We just
cut it in half.''
</P>
<P>
   The teenager, a resident of Maryvale, Ariz., said her only
disappointment was that the movie lacked urban Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals'' carried the attitude and fashion of
reservation guys, Knox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to see Indians in sports clothes, Adidas or
Nikes in the movies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dodie Manuel, a Phoenix area resident who is Shuswap from
British Columbia, said the movie captures glimpses of Indian life
that could exist just about anywhere on the reservation. She
particularly loved the way Thomas chattered and launched into
stories about fry bread, relatives and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel said she laughed each time Thomas, portrayed at times as
a pain in the neck to Victor, pronounced ``Victor'' in a sing-song
manner. That meant a story was forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Real reservation men sometimes come across as reserved. Thomas
bucks that trend by being a friendly deep thinker and a nerdy kind
of Indian gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked Thomas. What could have been a real serious movie, he
lightened it up by chattering and making up stories,'' Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
   Deenise Becenti, a Navajo journalist based in Window Rock,
Ariz., said the movie offers a glimpse of Indian life rarely
captured on movie screens.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, viewers are treated to a scene of young Indian
women driving an old car in reverse. To a non-Indian person, it
doesn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian cars come in different shapes and sizes,'' Becenti
said. ``That car only runs in reverse. Whereas the rest of America
would say, `Why would you drive a car like that?' To the Indian, it
runs and it will get them somewhere.'' &QL; 
Betty Reid can be reached at betty.reid(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
