<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FIRE TOP COACHES AT FARM TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the Bruins assembled the roster of their top farm
club in Providence, R.I. last season, management believed it had a
talented, competitive contender in the American Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   However, for reasons no one can quite understand, the Providence
Bruins finished with a last-place 19-54-7 recond. Thursday
Providence owner Ed Anderson and Boston management announced that
head coach Tom McVie and assistant coach Rod Langway were relieved
of their duties. No successors were named, though word out of
Providence was that the positions could be filled quickly.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in four years the Bruins have fired
McVie. The first was when he was an assistant under Brian Sutter
and both were let go after the 1994-95 season.
</P>
<P>
   McVie, who has two years remaining on his contract, and Langway,
who has one year left, could be retained in other positions.
Assistant general manager Mike O'Connell said he talked to McVie
about a scouting position where he would assess prospects or
perhaps track the progress of players the Bruins were interested
in. Another option would be working with some of the Bruins'
younger players in a developmental role. O'Connell said he would
get back to McVie in the next couple of days but McVie said he's
definitely interested in something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think negative thoughts anymore,'' said McVie, reached
by telephone at his home in Washington. ``I'm a positive thinker.
As a player, I was traded five times and as a coach I have been
fired seven times. The amazing thing wasn't that I was fired seven
times, it was that I kept getting hired.''
</P>
<P>
   McVie, who has a joke for every occasion, said it was difficult
to keep his sense of humor last season as the losing continued to
feed off itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried everything I could,'' he said. ``It wasn't fun. It's
like when Holyfield keeps knocking you down. You want to go sit in
the corner for a while. I think some veteran guys had the I-95
disease. They were (upset) by the time they got to the Foxborough
exit. There were some young players who felt overwhelmed by the
league. What went wrong? A lot of things. I feel bad not being able
to go back there. But I'm not going to shoot myself or anything. I
think I can do a good job developing players. There's not much I
haven't done in 43 years.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said he talked to Anderson, who felt a change was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed brought it to our attention two or three weeks ago,'' said
O'Connell. ``I talked to Tom over the weekend and informed him of
the decision we made. We're going to have a lot of the same players
back in Providence next year who were there last year and we felt
(the same coaching staff) probably wouldn't be the best thing. If
you've coached, you understand how difficult it is. It's a
24-hour-a-day job during the season. When you're losing, those 24
hours seem like 36.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has been close friends with McVie for years, said
it was an agonizing decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he was the perfect fit for the team we had,'' said
Anderson. ``For the first six weeks, it looked like we all knew
what we were talking about. Then it all disintegrated. There were
17 games when we were either leading or tied going into the third
period and we won one. We made the decision as a result of not
wanting to expose ourselves to the potential for another season
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said things are starting to heat up on the free agent
front with regard to increasing the team's depth but nothing was
imminent ... The Bruins have opened preliminary discussions with
goalie Rob Tallas, a restricted free agent. O'Connell said he is
awaiting a proposal from Tallas's agent, Jay Fee.
</P>
</TEXT>
