<HEADER>
A8176 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRS-OVERHAUL-625&AMP;ADD-     07-09 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-OVERHAUL-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES IRS OVERHAUL ON 96-2 VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., W.Va., Minn., Del.)  (th) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate gave final approval Thursday to
legislation overhauling the Internal Revenue Service, voting 96-2
to impose the most sweeping shakeup in decades on the
tax-collection agency's management and culture.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed the House 402-8 late last month, now
goes to President Clinton, who said he would sign it quickly into
law.
</P>
<P>
   The bill gives new rights and protections to the relatively
small numbers of taxpayers who get into serious disputes with the
IRS. Instead of forcing taxpayers to prove their innocence in civil
tax-court cases, as under current law, the new law shifts the
burden of proof in many cases to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The tax agency will face new limits in imposing interest charges
and penalties, and will be restricted in its ability to seize a
home during collection proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's more ambitious if less easily legislated goal is
to reshape the culture of an agency that critics contend is too
focused on striking fear in the hearts of taxpayers and not enough
on helping citizens comply with a tax code of ever-increasing
complexity.
</P>
<P>
   It establishes an outside board with broad authority to oversee
the IRS' management and policies, and strengthens the role of the
taxpayer advocate, an internal ombudsman who can take up complaints
from individuals.
</P>
<P>
   It provides the IRS with more flexibility to hire managers from
private industry to help sort out problems like its outdated
computer system. And it calls for the agency to scrap an
organizational structure that divided it into geographical units
and replace it with one based on serving three main constituencies:
individual filers, small businesses and big corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also contains a tax cut of sorts, a capital gains
provision inserted during House-Senate negotiations last month that
affects those who sell stocks. It reduces to 12 months from 18
months the period that investors must hold stocks or other assets
to qualify for the lowest capital gains tax rate of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is ``intended to cause the IRS to function more like a
financial services organization and less like a law enforcement
agency _ one that emphasizes customer service and efficiency, in
addition to the prevention of waste, fraud and abuse,'' said Phil
Brand, the director of IRS policies and procedures for KPMG Peat
Marwick, the accounting and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Although the administration had opposed the bill in its early
stages last year, the measure built up unstoppable momentum after a
series of hearings in the Senate Finance Committee laid out horror
stories from taxpayers who had been harassed, intimidated or
otherwise mistreated by the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate opened debate Wednesday on the bill's final
version, some Democrats objected to the inclusion of the capital
gains tax provision. Democrats were also concerned that Republicans
were bashing the IRS to build a case for abolition of the entire
progressive income tax system and its replacement with a
single-rate flat tax or a national sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   But with an eye toward the mid-term congressional elections in
November, most members of both parties and administration officials
were eager to support the bill and claim some credit for it. In the
end, the only two no votes on final passage Thursday came from Sen.
Jay Rockefeller of West Virginia and Sen. Paul Wellstone of
Minnesota, both Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del., who is chairman of the Finance
Committee, said the legislation ``is not only good for the American
taxpayer, but for the agency as well.'' Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.,
said that the IRS ``will now work for the American taxpayers and
not the other way around.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and
Charles Rossotti, the IRS commissioner, said passage of the bill
``represents one more step in our continuing efforts to insure that
each and every taxpayer is treated fairly and that the IRS collects
our nation's revenue efficiently and effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, a former computer-industry executive who took over at
the IRS last year, has won high marks from Republicans in Congress
for working with them to change the way the agency operates.
</P>
<P>
   And former IRS officials said the establishment of an outside
board will create ongoing pressure for the agency's leadership to
root out problems, punish employees who mistreat taxpayers and
become more responsive to public concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But some tax experts said the new taxpayer protections will open
the door to more tax cheating, a growing problem in a system that
relies largely on voluntary compliance.
</P>
<P>
   They said there will always be tension between the desire of
members of Congress to help constituents who have tax problems and
the need of the IRS to enforce a tax code that Congress complicates
with constant tinkering. And it remains unclear how
enthusiastically the IRS' workforce of 102,000 will embrace the new
approach, especially after serving as a political punching bag for
the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll definitely see an improvement in the IRS, and we firmly
believe taxpayers will face fewer problems in coming years,'' said
John Berthoud, president of the National Taxpayers Union, a
grassroots organization that is pushing for an overhaul of the
entire tax system.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not going to be possible with the current tax system
to get a non-intrusive IRS,'' he said. ``You're still going to have
people frustrated by complexity. And you're still going to have
people lodging complaints that the IRS is not friendly or is
focused too much on bringing in the money or is not respectful of
their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most important changes brought about by the bill is
the creation of a nine-member oversight board, made up of six
private citizens, the Treasury secretary, the IRS commissioner and
a representative of IRS employees.
</P>
<P>
   The board would have no role in setting tax policy, but would
have broad authority to develop the agency's basic strategy and to
review operational and management performance.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that some of the IRS' problems stem from the
complexity of the tax laws passed by Congress, the bill would
require Congress to do a complexity analysis of any proposed
changes to the tax code, and give the IRS an opportunity to assess
the costs of collecting projected new revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Among other changes included in the bill are new protections for
divorced or separated people who face tax liabilities run up
unknown to them by their former spouses, and an extension to tax
accountants of the same kind of confidentiality privilege enjoyed
by lawyers and their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Given the sweeping nature of the changes the bill will impose on
the IRS _ and the potential for internal confusion and upheaval in
the tax agency along the way _ the full payoff in terms of better
service and higher voluntary compliance rates may not come for six
years or so, said Kerrey, who served on a congressional commission
that came up with many of the provisions in the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost have to count on the benefits occurring beyond your
political life,'' Kerrey said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
