<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-FILM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEREOTYPES GO UP IN `SMOKE SIGNALS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Few movies that deal with Native Americans rise
above Hollywood stereotypes. Perhaps that's because none of them
was made by Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Until ``Smoke Signals.''
</P>
<P>
   This drama about two young Indian men coming to terms with their
past is written by, directed by, produced by and stars Native
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The result of all that focused talent is a movie that's strong
on authenticity and identity, but not as strong on drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals'' has fine moments, while potential peeks out of
all the cracks in its rough surface.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins on the Coeur d'Alene Reservation, where the
traffic reports run this way: ``Yep, a truck went by, about an hour
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor (Adam Beach) leaves the ``rez'' on a journey to Phoenix
when his father dies, years after leaving his family. Victor
harbors much rage against his father, who was guilty of both abuse
and abandonment, yet loved his son.
</P>
<P>
   Victor is accompanied by the bothersome Thomas (Evan Adams), who
lost his own father as a baby. Thomas is the kind of pest who won't
stop talking and usually says just the wrong thing.
</P>
<P>
   Along the journey, the two young men struggle to come to terms
with each other and with their memories of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals'' has several strong points, including touches
of ironic humor, strong feelings for the ties that bind fathers and
sons, and some lively irreverence, including a funny song about
John Wayne's teeth and a discussion of the relationship between
Jesus and fry bread.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``Smoke Signals'' doesn't have a strong story or a
vital sense of being about something important.
</P>
<P>
   Victor and Thomas encounter racial bigotry, but nothing comes
from the confrontation. This may be realistic, but it's not
particularly dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the humorous commentary about Indian problems seems
forced, or perhaps the delivery by the stars is just too stilted.
</P>
<P>
   Their self-awareness of being Native Americans assumes a
self-consciousness that stalls the story. They constantly remind
themselves _ and us _ that they're Indians. Point taken early, now
move on and do something with it.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also suggests that Native American problems with
poverty and alcoholism might all be solved if European descendents
would simply return to London, Rome and Moscow. True enough, and
the Valley's traffic problems would be solved if everyone simply
would move back to LA.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Smoke Signals'' is one of those small films that fits
into the category of: may not be a great one, but it's great that
we got one at all.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13, ``Smoke Signals'' contains minor profanity and
violence, but no sex or nudity. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
