<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES GAIN IN LIGHT TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury prices made modest gains Thursday, bolstered
by a strong dollar. But trading was light, with many investors
waiting for new economic data before making any significant
committments.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's plan for tax cuts has disappointed currency traders with
its lack of details, and the dollar rose Thursday against the yen
and other leading currencies. Also helping the dollar has been
concerns that China may devalue its currency. A strong dollar makes
dollar-denominated investments like Treasury securities an
attractive investment to foreign investors because of the potential
gains from currency translation.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 9/32, to 107 15/32.
The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the
price, fell to 5.60 percent, from 5.62 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices were held down by competing debt from new
corporate and agency issues. Fannie Mae priced for sale $2 billion
of 10-year notes yielding 37.5 basis points more than a Treasury
security with a similar maturity. (A basis point is one-hundredth
of a percentage point.)
</P>
<P>
   With rates now at historic lows, companies and municipalities
are taking advantage to raise cash or refinance existing debt to
reduce debt service payments. The added supply of debt to the
market can often pressure yields to move higher until the glut is
absorbed by investors.
</P>
<P>
   In the municipal market, the state of New York priced $563.2
million of general obligation refunding bonds Thursday through
underwriters led by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. The bonds were initially
priced to yield a maximum 5.23 percent for bonds maturing in 2021,
with shorter maturities priced to yield from 4 percent in 2000 to
5.20 percent in 2018.
</P>
<P>
   While trading was considered quiet, the talk was that Friday's
report on June producer prices might break the market's inertia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow's PPI release is projected to show that goods
inflation remained quite benign in June, aided in a large measure
by depressed energy prices and the turmoil in Asia,'' said Donald
Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management, referring to
the Producer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   Fine expects next week's consumer price report to be subdued and
nonthreatening. And that the General Motors strike may be clouding
near-term consumption patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``All things considered, economic statistics seem to be
suggesting that the economy slowed substantially during the second
quarter,'' he said. ``And while sustainability of this slackening
is still uncertain, there is little hint of any sharp rebound in
the third quarter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
