<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW BIMMER FOR THE SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
( JT ) 
 By JAMES G. COBB    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of convertibles shake, rattle and roll. They leak and
squeak, and, without the integral bracing of solid tops, they flex
like sponges when you wring them out on bouncy roads. Outside the
Sun Belt, they require six to 10 months of compromise for two to
six months of wind-blown freedom.
</P>
<P>
   This accepted wisdom is fast becoming out of date. The Chrysler
Sebring, for instance, is solid and comfortable for year-round
service. The Volvo C70 has a durable top that looks as if it would
hold up to winters in Lapland. And both cars, by convertible
standards, have generous back seats.
</P>
<P>
   But few cars shatter ragtop myths quite as thoroughly as the
3-Series BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The rigid structure that makes solid-top Bimmers so riveting
serves the convertibles well, too. The soft-top 323 is stable and
responsive, comparing favorably with the coupe. It does weigh 200
pounds more, and it feels even heavier. It moves a little slower
and skips a bit on rippled pavement. But the body stubbornly
refuses to shudder.
</P>
<P>
   The test car was free of squeaks and rattles, and the slight
rear wind noise was unobjectionable. Because I drove it during a
weekend of continuous rain, the roof never came down. While that
made it impossible to experience the 323's summertime pleasures, it
was easy to judge the car as it is more often used, as a top-up,
year-round transportation device.
</P>
<P>
   In hours of high-speed late-night Interstate driving, through
wind-driven rain and thundering tractor-trailer traffic, the car
felt completely stable, safe and in control. While the ride was
firm and a little bouncy, it was not unpleasant. The seats were
comfortable and the driver-oriented controls, functional and
minimal, felt just right.
</P>
<P>
   While the 323 coupe is a nice addition, with the smaller, less
expensive six-cylinder engine, the convertible is a masterstroke.
Previously, someone shopping for a four-seat BMW soft-top had to
choose between the anemic four-cylinder 318i, which has been
discontinued, or the lovely but expensive 328i. At $35,270, the 323
isn't cheap, but it is within reach of more people than its $42,070
sibling, and it performs nearly as well.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people have already calculated that the 323 is a good
deal, and supplies of the convertible are tight. After visiting
several dealerships, a friend, who had hoped to present a
convertible as a birthday gift to his mother, despaired of finding
a car equipped as he wanted. Mom ended up with a more practical
328i sedan instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
