<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILWAUKEE-STEELTECH-A     07-09 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILWAUKEE-STEELTECH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
START-UP METALWORKING FIRM STRUGGLES TO BE INNER-CITY SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic on mnufacturing employment in 4 cities is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
 (bl)  
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ When President George Bush dropped in on Steeltech
Manufacturing Inc. here in 1992, he told reporters following him on
the campaign trail that the newly minted, minority-owned
metal-processing company was proof that ``the American dream can
still come true.''
</P>
<P>
   There is impressive evidence today that his faith was justified.
Steeltech has moved into a cavernous new manufacturing plant in one
of this city's poorest, toughest neighborhoods. Customers praise
the quality of its welding and its painting equipment, which can
electrically coat larger pieces of steel than any other independent
plant in the country. Steeltech has grown to more than 200
employees, many of whom are thrilled to have left behind dead-end
minimum-wage jobs or the welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has given people around here hope,'' said Kim Jordan, 42,
a single mother of three who has done everything from welding to
helping out in research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the privately held Steeltech is no dream come true
for its investors or for customers who had to provide cash and
other concessions to keep it afloat. Even though it has finally
begun to generate some operating profits, Steeltech has not made
payments on more than $30 million in federal, state, local and
private loans since 1996. Milwaukee taxpayers are shelling out
$50,000 a month to bondholders to forestall foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Still worse, two contracts that have accounted for more than 80
percent of Steeltech's revenue are about to end. Rumors of imminent
bankruptcy were swirling until the company recently won a contract
to work on the steel roof of Miller Park, the Milwaukee Brewers'
new baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been constant firefighting,'' said Charles Wallace, 52,
the company's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson? So far, Steeltech is stark proof that the goal of
returning skilled, industrial jobs to blighted inner cities remains
a daunting one, even when the economy is booming and many companies
are frantically scavenging the nation for skilled _ or simply
trainable _ labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could never sustain an economy on this basis,'' conceded
James Scherer, the administrator following Steeltech's struggles
for Milwaukee's Economic Development Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The city is not giving up, though. The shuttering of urban
factories over the last two or three decades has been cited by
sociologists like William Julius Wilson as the single largest
factor in worsening the poverty, crime and drug use that grip many
inner-city neighborhoods and strangle once-thriving retail
districts. While no one expects these jobs to return on a broad
scale, smaller manufacturing companies like Steeltech are seen as
important adjuncts to rebuilding a more service-oriented urban
economy that can profit from a central location and the labor
available in inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   Although Steeltech's wages are at the low end of the industrial
scale here, they still offer a better prospect of upward mobility
than most entry-level service jobs, such as those at the Walgreen's
drugstore that recently opened across the street where clerks start
at $6 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The debate about Steeltech's value might be clearer if it were
simple to measure its costs and benefits, but that can't be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good for Milwaukee and it's met its social goals,''
maintained Paul Hollowell, executive vice president of Oshkosh
Truck Corp., which ended up as both Steeltech's major customer and
a source of working cash. Did Oshkosh benefit? ``It's like W.C.
Fields said about being tarred and feathered,'' Hollowell said,
pointing out that Oshkosh wrote off $3.2 million in loans extended
to Steeltech. ``But for the honor, we'd probably rather not have
done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dempsey, director of the Campaign for a Sustainable
Milwaukee, a coalition of community and labor groups, argues that
Oshkosh clearly benefited because Steeltech helped it maintain its
standing as a leading truck supplier to the military. Other
Milwaukee businesses made money selling Steeltech goods and
services. ``The jury is still out,'' he said, ``on whether the
Steeltech jobs justify the heavy public investment to create
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steeltech's story has unfolded in a era when the number of
minority-owned businesses nationwide has been growing. The most
recent U.S. census figures showed a 60 percent increase in such
businesses, to 2.15 million, from 1987 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   And Harriet Michel, executive director of the National Minority
Supplier Development Council, a New York City-based nonprofit group
dedicated to linking major corporations and government purchasing
groups with minority-owned companies, says the growth is
continuing. ``But most of them are professional service
companies,'' she said, ``because the start-up costs are cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to setting up new businesses in the poorest urban
areas, most of the action is in the commercial and service sectors,
said Elisabeth Reynolds, vice president of the Initiative for a
Competitive Inner City, a Boston-based group working to identify
urban business opportunities. Where manufacturing does succeed, it
tends to be small and closely integrated with existing activities.
Auto company suppliers in Detroit and garment makers in New York
are frequently cited examples.
</P>
<P>
   ``To create a business out of thin air,'' she said, ``is more
risky than building on something that's there.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Steeltech's singular journey began with a broad public-private
partnership and a torrent of publicity. The prime mover was Super
Steel Products Corp. chairman Fred Luber, who saw a chance to help
Oshkosh, one of his major customers, fulfill the Pentagon
requirement to set aside a certain amount of business for minority
subcontractors to qualify for a $1.4 billion contract to build
cargo transport vehicles for the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Steeltech's job, Luber figured, would be to paint and assemble a
newly designed cargo platform to go with the trucks, known as the
flat-rack. Although the first order was for just 8,000 flatracks,
the Army was expected to need 100,000 eventually.
</P>
<P>
   The well-connected Luber won the backing of figures like the
popular Milwaukee Mayor John Norquist,and cajoled numerous public
and private groups into going along because of the project's
potential social benefits. He and his lawyer were able to recruit
black and Hispanic investors to hold a majority of Steeltech's
stock by arranging for the company to lend them the money to
acquire their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   But Steeltech was nearly strangled at birth by its Pentagon
contract, which was based on a wildly optimistic guess about the
company's overhead. The profit outlook did not begin to improve
until 1995, when Steeltech landed a second flatrack contract and a
contract to paint Dodge Ram truck frames for the nearby auto
components subsidiary of A.O. Smith Corp. (Smith sold the business
last year to Tower Automotive Inc., based in Minneapolis).
</P>
<P>
   Each step forward has been clouded with developments that have
made the company a local business soap opera. Relations with Luber
became strained over how costs and equipment were allocated during
the first two years that Steeltech operated out of the Super Steel
factory. Management turnover _ Wallace is the fourth chief
executive _ and labor tensions became routine. The labor unrest
gave the United Electrical Workers the opening it needed to
organize the plant after a contentious struggle that hurt
Steeltech's local reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Steeltech also lost money in ill-fated efforts to diversify into
making jail cells and modules for fast-food restaurants. Part of
the problem was that the Oshkosh and Tower contracts occupied too
much of its capacity for it to pursue other businesses that might
have been more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Steeltech has also paid a price for pursuing its social mission.
</P>
<P>
   Its founders envisioned stories like that of Shafi Roemel
Brooks, who was 40 when he was hired and trained as a painter in
1995, a month after returning home to Milwaukee from five years in
a federal prison in Texas on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold drugs from the time I was 14, and if it hadn't been for
Steeltech I would probably have gone back to the streets,'' said
Brooks, who earns $11 an hour and is now married. He says Steeltech
made it possible for him to acquire both his first home and a 1997
Chevy Blazer.
</P>
<P>
   Often, though, the results have been disappointing. Absenteeism
rates were astronomical in the early years, as workers unused to
the discipline of factory life were given multiple chances to shape
up. Background checks were perfunctory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people were attracted thinking they'd get cut slack
because it was minority-owned,'' Ms. Jordan said. Union officials
cite one case in which the company allowed an employee who was late
17 times during the 30-day probationary period to become a
full-time employee.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace has tightened standards for reviewing the 2,000 job
applicants coming through Steeltech's doors annually. But he still
faces high turnover. Many workers tire of the factory's rigors, and
others leverage their training into higher-paying jobs at Tower and
other local employers. Two-thirds of the hourly work force has been
at Steeltech less than two years.
</P>
<P>
   This year, skilled workers have been leaving out of fear about
Steeltech's prospects. Steeltech lost the flatrack contract to a
San Diego-based subsidiary of Korea's Hyundai, which will build its
version of the cargo carrier with Mexican labor in Tijuana, and to
Summa Technology Inc. of Huntsville, Ala., which is owned by E.C.
Lee, an Asian-American. Summa, which won the part of the contract
set aside for minority-owned businesses, plans to make its units
with just 85 workers in a new automated factory in Coleman, Ala.
Steeltech will make the last of its 16,000 flatracks in the next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, Tower is installing its own
high-technology paint line. It has given Steeltech notice that it
will quit sending Dodge truck frames by early next year. Tower said
Chrysler Corp. had required it to install the new paint line to be
eligible to make frames for the new Dodge Ram scheduled for 2002.
Tower figures that making the inevitable switch now could save $1.5
million that is currently eaten up trucking frames to Steeltech and
repairing the nicks and dents that come with such transfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're protecting 700 jobs at our plant,'' said James Lozelle,
who oversees Tower's Milwaukee operations.
</P>
<P>
   Steeltech got a crucial lift, though, when it won a $2 million
subcontract from Mitsubishi Heavy Industries America to build the
roof of the new baseball park. Now, Wallace said, Steeltech has
more than a year's breathing room and a good shot at further work
on other contracts with Mitsubishi. Several other irons are in the
fire as well, including a potential deal with Caterpillar.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of more new contracts could seal the one thing
Steeltech really needs: some kind of agreement from its many
creditors to refinance or forgive more than $30 million in debt.
Wallace, who owns the biggest chunk of the 60 percent stake held by
minority investors, hopes to complete a package that forgives $3
million in debt and refinances the rest.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot come too soon for Hubert Nelson, his head of
marketing. ``This can be a profitable $100 million company in five
years, but the thing that comes up over and over again with
potential clients is, `Your financial condition scares me,''' said
Nelson, whose marketing resume ranges from Exxon to Miller Brewing.
``It's a tough nut to crack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
