<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8194 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADELINE-FILM-AZR &LR;      07-09 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADELINE-FILM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADELINE' A NOSTALGIC DELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Ludwig Bemelmans, the eccentric writer and artist
who created Madeline, has delighted families for generations with
his sing-song stories and charming drawings of the 12 little girls
of Paris who live in two straight lines and their Dear Miss Clavel,
who cherishes and protects them.
</P>
<P>
   How can you turn such a delicate treasure into a movie? With
delicate attention to detail and whimsy, it turns out, in
``Madeline,'' a family treat for young children and nostalgic
parents.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite obvious that director Daisy von Scherler Mayer and
her writing crew loved Bemelmans' books as much as parents who have
read them over and over again to their children through the years.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer (``Party Girl``) captures the whimsical look and mood of
Bemelmans' Paris of the 1930s and even develops many of the books'
wispy story lines:
</P>
<P>
   - The finely tuned ability of Miss Clavel (Frances McDormand) to
tell when something is not right with her girls.
</P>
<P>
   - The spunky, mischievous and forthright attitude of Madeline
(Hatty Jones), the smallest of the girls at the boarding school,
who, as an orphan and a ward of the church, depends on the
redoubtable Miss Clavel while pushing her to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   The movie develops three plots:
</P>
<P>
   - Madeline's various emergencies, including a trip to the
hospital, then her rescue by a brave dog.
</P>
<P>
   - The efforts by the girls to save their school from closure by
the stuffy Lord Covington (or Lord Cucuface, as the girls dub him),
who has a distinct distaste for brats.
</P>
<P>
   - Madeline's running battles with the boy next door, who
torments the girls and ultimately must depend on them for rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie will reward and please children and parents
who love the books, it may not win many new converts. The humor is
muted and subtle, in competition with the '90s approach toward
crude slapstick as evidenced by most of children's TV, in which
bathroom humor predominates.
</P>
<P>
   It's to the director's credit that she maintains the books'
lighter touch toward humor. However, she comes up short trying to
infuse the movie with energy.
</P>
<P>
   Bemelmans' breezy, brief approach worked so well in the books,
when parents could turn the pages any time their children started
to drift during readings. The movie's pages turn more slowly, and
kids may get restless
</P>
<P>
   Still, the books remain the books, and the movie is a noble
effort to offer families entertainment that does not rely on the
incessant dog-butt humor of the standard-issue ``Dr. Dolittles'' of
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   McDormand (``Fargo'') makes an endearing Miss Clavel; kids will
wish they had her for a teacher. Newcomer Jones assumes the
Madeline persona without any fuss, and the other girls are neatly
cast to take us back to a more pleasant time.
</P>
<P>
   On a note of personal synchronicity, I had just finished reading
one of Bemelmans' adult books, ``The Hotel Splendide,'' and
recommend it highly to anyone who can find it.
</P>
<P>
   For parents of children under age 10, I'd recommend ``Mulan''
first, then ``Madeline,'' then ``Dr. Dolittle,'' if the kids insist
on seeing it.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG, ``Madeline'' contains a couple of references to
personal hygiene that the strictest of parents might find
objectionable. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
