<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENT OF VICTORY, BRAZIL COACH ALSO ADMITS NERVOUSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SOC-WORLDCUP-VECSEY, SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE) 
(JT) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OZOIR-LA-FERRIERE, France _ Never has he been more confident of
victory, Mario Zagallo, the much-criticized Brazil coach, said
Thursday as Sunday's World Cup final against France approached. And
never has he been more nervous. The dependability of Ronaldo's
scoring and Taffarel's goalkeeping have not been enough to calm
him, he said. So he has resorted to tranquilizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been the most emotional moments ever since the Denmark
game,'' Zagallo said, referring to the tense 3-2 victory last
Friday in the quarterfinals. ``But I've never been so sure I'm
going to win a title, given the way the team has grown and the
toughness they've shown.''
</P>
<P>
   At 66, he is known as the Little Ant for his emphasis on hard
work. He favors sweatsuits over coats and ties and wears a cap over
his graying hair. He seems to be the Walter Brennan of the soccer
set, but he gives as much as he takes with the frenzied Brazilian
news media. And he has made all the right moves to get his team
into Sunday's championship game where Brazil will be seeking an
unprecedented fifth World Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo is the cornerstone of Brazilian football. Pele is more
famous than his former teammate, but Zagallo is the one person who
has been around for all four of Brazil's triumphs in the World Cup.
He was a left wing on the teams in 1958 and 1962; he even scored in
the 1958 final. It was Zagallo who coached the 1970 team, which is
considered the greatest of all time, and he was an assistant to
Carlos Alberto Parreira as Brazil prevailed again in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he has not fully convinced all of Brazil that he knows what
he is doing. There are 160 million citizens and 160 million coaches
in Brazil. Zagallo was loudly booed in May when Brazil suffered an
unacceptable loss to Argentina in Rio's Maracana Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But because he has already made his career, he can ignore the
media criticism and the phone calls from Pele telling him to play
three forwards instead of two. And he can tolerate the placing of
Zico, another former star, on the team to look over his shoulder as
an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo has done things his way and has produced an unfailingly
entertaining team, one that makes mistakes but one that accepts
these misdemeanors in the taking of great, mesmerizing risks.
</P>
<P>
   Before the penalty-kick victory over the Netherlands in the
semifinals, someone suggested to Zagallo that he had abandoned the
``beautiful game'' that Brazil demands for a hybrid of European and
South American football.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't imitate anybody,'' he snarled. ``We are our own men
with our own footballing culture, which has allowed us to lift four
World Cups.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Zagallo scared the purists when he said: ``I would
rather win playing ugly football than lose playing attractive
football. Efficiency in football is based on victories. Everyone
wants to win, and I'm no different.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was Zagallo who also coached the one Brazilian
team that lost in the semifinals, the 1974 team that finished
fourth with a style that was uncomfortably defensive and European
for many followers of `jogo bonito,' the beautiful game. That team
tied both Scotland and Yugoslavia, 0-0, and many were concerned
that the 1998 team was too old and slow and would also crawl into a
defensive shell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they criticize me; I understand that,'' Zagallo said.
``Football is passion. I've lived this way for 50 years as an
athlete and coach. This is my happiest moment.''
</P>
<P>
   It was bad enough that the fans and media were finding fault
with Zagallo. But another coach, Egil Olsen of Norway, said that he
could do much better with Brazil's talent than Zagallo could. That
stung, and what hurt even worse was that Norway defeated Brazil,
2-1, in a first-round matchup after Brazil had already won its
group and its placing in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of slowing his team under a caution flag, though,
Zagallo kept the green light lit. With Rivaldo, this Brazil team is
more talented in midfield than the 1994 team, and it has continued
to attack from all directions, with the great Ronaldo churning like
a fullback toward the goal, with the defenders Cafu and Roberto
Carlos storming down the wings, with a balance that forces defenses
to play with scattered concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has surrendered seven goals in this World Cup, compared
with three in 1994, but for Zagallo that seems an acceptable
exchange for allowing his players great freedom and creativity. He
has said that he did not mind winning ugly, but those were only
words. This team is as attractive as it is talented. It leads the
tournament with 14 goals scored. Zagallo was so overcome by
Wednesday's penalty-kick victory over the Netherlands that he wept
on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the favorites and we will win,'' Zagallo promised. ``On
Sunday, 80,000 will be cheering for France, but that is not a
problem. Because, in the hearts of Brazilians, the players will
have 160 million people cheering for them. Brazil has always won
abroad. We are used to beating the home team. And we will do it
again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
