<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S RULING PARTY MEETS TO PICK NEW LEADER, MAKE REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The ruling Golkar Party opened a special
congress Thursday to choose a new leader and refashion the
organization so that it can respond to calls for political and
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golkar is not only facing competition from the already
established parties, but also from the new parties that continue to
multiply,'' President B.J. Habibie told an audience of nearly 1,000
delegates in his opening remarks of the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Although nearly 30 new parties have been created since the
resignation of President Suharto in May, Golkar officials say the
real challenge comes from within the party, which has dominated
Indonesian politics for more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now Golkar has depended on Suharto as a groove of
unity,'' said Bambang Suharto, one of those who is expected to
compete for the party leadership. ``But after Suharto stepped down,
there is no more groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Bambang is not related to the former President.
</P>
<P>
   Growing social protests and a deepening economic crisis may have
helped force Suharto, 77, to resign, but his shadow looms over the
party. Two of his children are on the powerful advisory board of
the party, and the former president remains chairman of the party
board of patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate believed to have Suharto's backing for the
leadership, Edi Sudrajat, also has the support of the party's
remaining Suharto loyalists and the military, a critical core of
support, because 21 of the 27 provincial leaders are from the armed
forces, known as ABRI.
</P>
<P>
   Those leaders plus one from the party executive board and
another from the board of patrons are to choose the next chairman
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Edi's leading rival, State Secretary Akbar Tandjung, warned
that Suharto's influence and his organization of the party would
have to be eliminated if the party were to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to separate ourselves from the bureaucratic influence,
whether it is civilian or ABRI,'' said Akbar, who is believed to
have Habibie's support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are finished with him,'' he said of Suharto. ``We have to
look to the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
