A8203 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LETHAL-FILM-AZR &LR;      07-09 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETHAL-FILM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO JOKE: `LETHAL WEAPON' REHASH TOO VIOLENT TO BE FUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Take a few dozen shootings, a couple of garrotings,
a little eye gouging. Mix them up with a guy punching out a
pregnant woman, the odd larynx crushing, a bloody impalement and
enough sonic explosions to shake the people in the theater next
door _ and what do you have? A comedy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Lethal Weapon 4,'' the name of the game is how many lame
comic routines can our heroes lurch through while they dispatch the
bad guys in several grotesque ways? The effect is to make the
slayings as funny as the gags _ which isn't that tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lethal Weapon 4'' reels around the same rut as the first three
installments, distinguishing itself only by jacking up the violence
and the soundtrack. Hollywood remains convinced that if the
explosions are loud enough, people won't notice that they're
watching a lot more of the same old thing.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth movie in the series seems like the 40th.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Gibson and Danny Glover return as Riggs and Murtaugh, LA's
craziest cops, who break more laws than the people they arrest.
Actually, they never arrest anyone. They either lose 'em or kill
'em.
</P>
<P>
   The story this time around is even more unimportant than the
story last time around. It has something to do with Chinese
gangsters, although not much.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Riggs and Murtaugh stumble around from chase to beating
to shooting to explosion while they chatter endlessly about cell
phones, aging and fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs and Lorna (Rene Russo) are about to have a baby, if they
can find the time between her having to kick-box bad guys and his
having to wreck half of LA while trying to ask a guy a simple
question.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Pesci returns as Leo, the professional butt of short-guy
jokes. To pump up the humor, there's Chris Rock as a cop who wants
to be just like his heroes. To juice up the action, toss in Chinese
kung fu star Jet Li.
</P>
<P>
   Li, making his Hollywood debut after a long Hong Kong career,
actually adds vitality to the nonsensical fight scenes. He could
become a crossover action star, given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson and Glover wheeze through the action and mutter through
the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson can still deliver a wacky gag or two, and that's about
all the scriptwriters could come up with.
</P>
<P>
   Glover should have retired from the series after No. 3, if not
No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Russo, who enlivened the last one with her comic pizazz, is a
cipher here.
</P>
<P>
   Rock, who has great comic potential that Hollywood has yet to
tap, is funnier in the previews than he is in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Rock has the unfortunate tendency to deliver the straight lines
in exactly the same hyper fashion as the punch lines, so you can't
tell which is which.
</P>
<P>
   Director Richard Donner, who directed the first three ``Lethal
Weapons,'' seems as weary of the whole thing as everyone else
connected with the project.
</P>
<P>
   Must tire them out, hauling all that money to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a way for them to make even more money off ``Lethal
Weapon 5'' without risking millionaire's fatigue syndrome: Don't
shoot a new film. Just cobble one together from outtakes of the
first four. No one would know the difference.
</P>
<P>
   If you were thinking of sending the kids, ``Lethal Weapon 4'' is
rated R for heavy profanity and graphic violence. 2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
