</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN SAYS HE EXPECTS `FAIR MARKET' OFFER FROM SOME TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Mo Vaughn, who may be down to his last three months
as a member of the Red Sox, said Thursday he is confident that some
team will sign him to a contract that will give him ``fair market
value.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Red Sox' latest proposal _ a guaranteed four-year deal
for $37 million _ doesn't come close to what Vaughn believes will
be the market for a free agent of his stature this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we're going to get a market deal in 1998,
what fair market value is,'' Vaughn said Thursday before taking the
field for the first time since June 26, when he pulled his right
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn would not hazard an opinion on what he believes that
number is, but a fair guess would be $12 million a year for four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't personal, this is big business. I'm going to get
market value in 1998, period. There are a lot of things that
(factor) into that, but there will be no hometown discount.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that he had once pledged to take less money if
convinced the Red Sox were making a commitment to winning, Vaughn
said, ``I said that a year and a half ago, the middle of last year.
A lot of other things have happened since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market changes every day. The stock market changes every
day. People's attitude change every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Pedro Martinez's six-year, $75 million deal, which pays
the Sox pitcher an average of $12.5 million a year, had helped to
set the market for this winter's batch of free agents, Vaughn shook
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro's deal was last year,'' he said. ``This is a new year.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn pledged that he would not talk about his contract
situation again until after the season, and repeated that his first
preference is to play in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But it was equally apparent that Vaughn is certain, and has
received private assurances, that he would be able to land the deal
he is seeking from another club. Among the teams expected to be in
the market for a first baseman next season are Baltimore, Toronto
and Texas. The Rangers have a new deep-pockets owner, Tom Hicks, a
Dallas-based media mogul who also owns hockey's Dallas Stars and
took that team from the third-lowest payroll to third-highest
payroll in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark, the Rangers' current first baseman, is a free agent
and unlikely to be re-signed. With Texas, Vaughn would be able to
bat third, which remains his preference, with RBI king Juan
Gonzalez batting behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's feelings for the Red Sox almost certainly have waned
because of his battles with the front office over the years. Those
battles came to a head last spring, when the team offered him only
a two-year deal when he refused to enter the team's employee
assistance program in the wake of his arrest on drunk driving
charges. He was subsequently acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn implied that he still has doubts whether the Red Sox
really want to sign him. It's equally apparent that he is stung
that the club does not treat him the same way it does Martinez and
Nomar Garciaparra, both of whom received precedent-setting deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said we could get a deal done in a telephone
booth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about recent television reports that the club has had him
tailed by private investigators, Vaughn smiled and said he had no
knowledge whether that's the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know,'' he said. ``If anybody wants to know
anything about me, just ask me, If they want to take a probe, dig
through my house, just come and ask me. I'll open my door. I got
nothing to hide. If that's the case, there will be nothing to be
found.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he will not allow his contract status to be a
distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only control what happens out here,'' he said. ``I'm
ready to play. The most important thing is to go out and do
whatever I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we said no to an offer at the All-Star break
doesn't mean the situation is impossible. I'm not angry, I'm not
upset ... Really, I'll let my bat talk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
