</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OIL-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF RUSSIA'S STATE OIL COMPANY POSTPONED AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's faltering economy and plunging world oil
prices prompted the government of President Boris Yeltsin Thursday
to postpone the sale of its state oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said Thursday night that the auction of the
company, Rosneft, would be delayed until September or October. It
is the second time that the government has put off the sale because
of a lack of bids.
</P>
<P>
   The Rosneft auction is important to Russia as a source of
desperately needed revenue. The government hopes to sell a
controlling interest in the company for at least $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It has also become a very visible symbol of the nation's
economic distress.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to head off another embarrassing failure, Sergei
Generalov, the Russian minister of fuel and energy, said Thursday
night that the government planned to extend the deadline for the
auction for several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that moment oil prices will reach an acceptable level,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His calculation is that export limits by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries will strengthen oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said several Russian companies had asked that
the deadline be extended. But it is not clear if they will be in a
position to bid in several months' time.
</P>
<P>
   When the government announced the terms of the Rosneft auction
earlier this year, it seemed like a golden opportunity to snatch up
a piece of the Russian oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   The government took measures to encourage a high bid. It spurred
competition by removing restrictions against bids from foreign
companies.
</P>
<P>
   It announced it was auctioning 75 percent of the company plus
one share. This meant that the winner of the auction would win
solid control of the company and would have the right to
restructure it.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting its confidence in the sale, the government demanded a
starting price of $2.1 billion. It also insisted that the buyer
invest at least $400 million in the company.
</P>
<P>
   At first it seemed as if the strategy was working. The auction
attracted interest from major Western companies, including the
Royal Dutch/Shell Group, which formed a bidding coalition with
Gazprom, Russia's natural-gas monopoly, and Lukoil Holding, the
Russian oil company. Meanwhile, British Petroleum teamed up with
Russia's Uneximbank.
</P>
<P>
   But the fall of world oil prices took a heavy toll, as did the
growing anxiety over emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   When the auction was held in May, no one bid. Seeking to salvage
the auction, the government lowered the sales price by $500 million
and reduced the requirement to invest in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Even that did not work, however. In recent weeks, Royal
Dutch/Shell and British Petroleum made clear they would not
participate in the auction, which was due to expire on July 16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gazprom developed its own cash-flow problems when the
Yeltsin government demanded that it pay billions of rubles in back
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to put off the Rosneft auction again adds to the
enormous pressure to come up with revenue from other sources.
Tonight, a senior Russian official said the government would sell
up to 5 percent of Gazprom this year as well as government shares
in the government telecommunications company, Svyazinvest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Rosneft decision also adds to the nation's dark mood.
Russian stocks and bonds rose slightly Thursday, reflecting
expectations that the International Monetary Fund and the World
Bank will soon complete their negotiations with Russia for a
multibillion-dollar loan.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has said it needs $10 billion to $15 billion in
assistance. The IMF has signaled that it is willing to provide some
funds but maybe as little as $5.6 in additional financing, forcing
the Russians to turn to other sources, including commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Odling-Smee, a senior IMF official, is coming to Moscow
to try to wrap up the talks.
</P>
<P>
   But the slight upturn in the market was overshadowed by the
drumbeat of dissatisfaction here.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Russian Coal Miners Union demanded that Yeltsin
resign. The Central Bank reported that its reserves to prop up the
ruble had fallen from $16 billion two weeks ago to $15 billion as
of last week.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin insisted that his government would defend the ruble and
that devaluation could be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the capability,'' he said. ``We have a plan of
action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
