<HEADER>
A8207 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-BMW-ART-$A     07-09 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-BMW-ART-$ADV12-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW 323 IS LAST HURRAH FOR A STAR PERFORMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (JT)  
 By JAMES G. COBB    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tempus fugit, technology advances. My laptop computer, obsolete
soon after I first booted it up two and a half years ago, is a
virtual antique. Auto cassette decks have given way to CD changers,
CD-ROM navigation devices and mini-disk audio. Every four years,
like clockwork, Honda trots out an all-new Accord.
</P>
<P>
   So in car years, the current BMW 3-Series, which arrived in 1991
as a '92 model, is positively geriatric _ indeed, three generations
of Accords have been sold in that period. But retirement looms; the
current 3-Series sedans get their gold watches and fond farewells
next month with the arrival of four-door models that are slightly
larger, roomier and plusher. New coupes and convertibles come next
year. Until then, BMW is trying to maintain interest in the current
design with a new engine and a new name.
</P>
<P>
   A feisty terrier in a dog-eat-dog business, BMW knows something
about survival of the fittest. Its ever-mutating 3-Series, which
accounts for 44 percent of overall sales, has become a genus with
31 species sold around the world. In the United States, choices
range from the $22,000 318ti hatchback, which is what that magna
cum laude student was really hoping to get for graduation (not that
the fountain pen wasn't appreciated) to the $55,000 fully loaded M3
convertible, the latest iteration of the ``M'' line of racing-tuned
cars.
</P>
<P>
   At the low end, the 318ti and the 318i sedan share a 16-valve
four-cylinder engine (it actually displaces 1.9 liters, despite the
name). Higher up the ladder are the 328 coupe, sedan and
convertible. These used to be known as 325s _ in the '80s, they
were the Ultimate Striving Machines of the archtypical yuppie _ and
they share a smooth and powerful 2.8-liter in-line six.
</P>
<P>
   The new 323s fall in between, replacing the old 318 coupe and
convertible and offering two more cylinders. But the 323 name is
misleading, too, since the engine actually displaces 2.5 liters.
BMW says it uses the 323 name to avoid confusion (ha!) with its
previous 325s, which had an engine more closely related to the
328s.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? No matter, the upshot is that soon, the only
four-cylinder BMWs sold here will be the hatchback and the plainest
Z3 two-seater. The next-generation 3-Series sedan will have the
same engines as the coupe and convertible: in-line sixes of 2.5,
2.8 or (in the M3) 3.2 liters.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Americans who want a six-cylinder BMW can have
one for less than $30,000, for the first time in five years. The
$29,270 323is coupe is not quite as fast as the $33,770 328is _
going from a stop to 60 miles per hour in 7.1 seconds, compared
with 6.6 _ but it handles with the gusto of its more powerful
sibling, whipping tight corners into submission at speeds that may
astonish drivers accustomed to Camrys and Luminas. And unless your
friends spot the badge on the trunk lid, they'll never suspect you
saved $4,400.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the smaller engine, the differences are few: the 323
has fewer standard features and less in the way of options.
</P>
<P>
   Since most 323s and 328s fall in the $30,000 to $40,000 range,
they are often compared with cars like the Lexus ES 300, the
Infiniti I30 and the Cadillac Catera. While those are quite
competent cars decked out like junior limousines, the 3-Series is
smaller and sportier, with less _ for now _ in the way of frills.
Compared with the wood trim, gathered leather and electronic gizmos
of $30,000 Japanese cars, the basic appointments of the 323
underscore the age of the design. It comes with manual seats (power
adjustments are offered on the 328) in plain leatherette (real
leather is a $1,450 option, or part of a $2,125 ``premium'' package
that includes a front armrest, power sunroof and remote locking).
Fog lights, standard on the 328, are $260 extra. The steering wheel
cannot be adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   A sport package, with 16-inch alloy wheels, high-performance
tires, fog lights and sport suspension, is a bargain at $990. All
323s have an automatic traction/stability control and some of the
best anti-lock brakes around.
</P>
<P>
   The car underwhelms at first. There is a lot of hard plastic.
Some of the switches and levers _ the map light toggles, the seat
levers _ feel as if they were fabricated in Detroit instead of
Munich, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But even a spin around the block is likely to win you over, for
like its rich relatives the 323 is a joy to drive. Each time you
fire up the engine, or downshift cleanly into second gear, or take
a familiar curve faster than you dared before, you appreciate the
engineering a little more. Cut a tight corner, and the fat tires
grip like Velcro. Crunch the brake pedal, and the car stops right
now. Punch the accelerator and the 323 scats without the usual
rear-drive twitch or front-drive monkey business. No matter the
maneuver, there is no muss, no fuss _ just a direct, immediate
response.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While the engine is not the world-beater of the 328, it is a
serious power plant in its own right, with twin overhead cams, four
valves per cylinder and variable valve timing. The five-speed
manual gearbox _ if you choose an automatic, you'll miss half the
fun _ brings out the engine's best. Horsepower is 168 (compared
with 138 for the 318 and 190 for the 328) and peak torque is 181
foot-pounds (versus 133 for the 318, 206 for the 328). Because the
torque, or pulling power, is strongest around 4,000 rpm, a driver
who wants extra oomph may need to downshift, revving the engine,
but with this slick gearbox, playing the gears adds to the fun.
</P>
<P>
   Worthy as it is, the engine is only part of the equation, for
the car's greatness begins with its exquisite balance. The weight
is distributed nearly perfectly, half over the front wheels and
half over the rear, thanks to a rear-drive layout and tricks like
sticking the battery under the trunk floor. The body structure
feels as solid as a skyscraper I-beam. Matched with a supple
suspension, it pays benefits: The handling doesn't come unglued
unless the car is pushed awfully hard, and the ride stays firm but
absorbent. The noise level is tolerable if not hushed, and the
exhaust rumble is pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see even now, seven years after the current
3-Series landed on these shores, what a benchmark it has been. Even
as the coupe nears its final year of production, it feels fresh.
</P>
<P>
   The car shows its age mainly on the inside. Only when seated in
the cozy cabin do you fully grasp the 323s compactness _ it is 20
inches shorter than a Catera. There is adequate space for four
people, though the cabin is narrow and rear headroom is tight for
6-footers.
</P>
<P>
   If the interior seems spare, remember that it has changed little
since 1992, a period when sybaritic luxuries became common in the
competition. And while the test car's lovely ``Avus blue'' paint
($475 extra) was lustrous and the body panels matched perfectly,
interior pieces fitted together less well. Gaps around the glove
box and center instruments were not uniform. Interior colors seemed
mismatched, and the side air bags wore vinyl tags that looked like
the labels on bargain-basement luggage. Modular inserts between the
front seats allow one to customize the placement of the cup
holders, ashtray and coin holder, but the plastic bits look cheap
and feel wobbly.
</P>
<P>
   Criticisms of the 3-Series have included high insurance and
service costs. Computer-coded keys have cut the high theft rate _
though 1995-97 models remain on the Highway Loss Data Institute's
list of 10-most-stolen cars _ and premiums have begun to decline.
To hold down service expenses, BMW is providing free oil changes
and maintenance for three years or 36,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Even with old bones, this new Bimmer runs circles around most
$30,000 cars. It handily makes my short list of drivers' machines
that don't require a trust fund, with the likes of the delightful
Honda Prelude, the no-nonsense Ford SVT Contour and the all-smiles
Mazda Miata. And even though the 323s replacement is around the
corner, a year is a long time to put off having fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
