u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FLORIDA-HNS &LR;      07-09 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FLORIDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRAISES HEROIC FIREFIGHTERS, CONSOLES RESIDENTS IN FLORIDA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ With the fires along the Florida coast
finally waning, President Clinton on Thursday dropped by this
beachfront city to congratulate fatigued firefighters and console
residents whose homes had gone up in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiching the sympathy visit between an anti-drug event in
Atlanta and a Democratic fund-raiser at the home of actor Sylvester
Stallone in Miami, Clinton used the occasion to announce more
federal emergency aid to the region.
</P>
<P>
   The state will receive a $1 million grant to create 200
temporary jobs to assist in cleanup and restoration in areas
affected by the fires. Also, 29 counties will be eligible for more
direct federal disaster assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The site of the presidential visit was the Daytona Speedway, the
popular race car track, where the parking lot had been converted
into a staging area for emergency workers and headquarters for
media covering the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The speedway made national news recently when it had to cancel
its popular Pepsi 400 race because of poor visibility attributed to
the raging fires.
</P>
<P>
   However, the skies were relatively clear when Clinton made his
grand entrance with his extended motorcade, which did a slow
half-lap around the banked race track usually reserved for cars
that exceed speeds of 75 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a crowd of firefighters and volunteers in an
air-conditioned tent outside the track, Clinton said, ``I'm here
because I think it's important that every American knows that this
summer, notwithstanding the great movies, the real American heroes
are not up in space fighting asteroids, they're in Florida fighting
fires.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier the president met with 10 families who had lost almost
everything they owned to the fires. Most were living in hotels and
many were renters and had no insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton listened sympathetically as Todd and Robin Banks talked
about looking for a new residence after finding out Monday that
their home in Palm Coast had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all ash,'' said Robin Todd. ``There was nothing you
could distinguish.'' The Todds, who have two young children, said
they had no renters' insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Several firefighters came to hear Clinton speak about their
ordeal of waging war against the wildfires in sweltering heat
without proper equipment and without much sleep or food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen anything like it. The fire wasn't doing what
it was supposed to do,'' said Jim Novakowksi, a 47-year old Florida
Ranger from Stuart, who spent 14 days on the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Novakowski said he didn't mind the duty. ``I'm a
firefighter. I enjoy fire.''
</P>
<P>
   While Novakowski said Clinton's visit was a ``morale booster,''
another firefighter wondered why the president showed up after the
worst was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have been here a week and a half ago when the whole
community was going up in a ball of flames,'' said Don Mullen, a
39-year old firefighter from Boca Raton, Fla. Clinton was in China
when the fires were at their peak and dispatched Vice President Al
Gore to Florida in his place.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen said that the ``only reason he (Clinton) is here today is
this is a stopover on the way to a fund-raiser This is a kind of
dog and pony show.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Mullen pulled out his camera and snapped a picture of the
president as he addressed the crowd. Afterward, Mullen said he
liked the president's comments, particularly his warnings that
local communities have to better prepare for fires as the Earth's
climate becomes warmer.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 25, at least 2,126 wildfires have charred more than
484,623 acres in 67 counties along a 120-mile stretch of the coast.
At least 355 homes and other structures have been damaged or
destroyed, and 8,300 people have spent some time at shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have estimated that the fires caused more than 100
injuries. Three elderly people died when they were being evacuated
from their nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of fighting the fires has been estimated at $104
million and the damage has been estimated at $276 million.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day in Atlanta, Clinton announced the launching
of a nationwide anti-drug media campaign, an advertising effort
that has already been tested in a dozen cities. The $1 billion ad
campaign over five years _ the largest ever _ will target youths
between the ages of 9 and 18, particularly middle-school children.
It includes spots on television, radio, magazines, billboards,
newspapers and web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a crowd of students, Clinton urged them and their
parents to watch the ads, which were to be aired simultaneously on
the major networks Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing in the world to do is to get people to
change their habits, especially if what you're doing feels good in
the moment,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., joined the president
in announcing the new program, Republicans have been extremely
critical of the administration's drug efforts. They claim that the
president has not put nearly as much energy into targeting teen
drug use as it has teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also attended two fund-raisers on the daylong trip. In
Atlanta, he attended a lunch for Senate candidate and cookie
magnate Michael Coles who is opposing GOP incumbent Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, he flew to Miami for a Democratic congressional
fund-raiser at the home of Stallone, the star of a number of action
movies.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami fund-raiser was projected to raise $800,000 while the
Georgia event was expected to net $ 1 million. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
