<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETAIL-SALES-ART-NYT &LR;      07-09 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUNE RETAIL SALES ARE INCONSISTENT AND POLARIZED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American retailers reported their June sales Thursday, and the
results were reliably perplexing. Following two months of stellar
sales for the entire industry, companies were all over the map in
June, demonstrating that when shoppers tighten their purse strings
even slightly, retail wheat and chaff quickly become separated.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap Inc., for example, continued its hot run, reporting that
sales in stores open at least one year rose 15 percent, while the
Limited Inc. said sales gained only 1 percent after two months of
better-than-usual sales. Wal-Mart Stores Inc. boomed ahead with a 9
percent sales gain, while Kmart Corp. said sales rose only 1.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a month unlike other months,'' said Richard Baum, an
analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``Usually things like luxury or
discounters are all good, but in June, you had a lot of
polarization. Among department stores, there were some good
performances, but then there were disappointments with J.C. Penney
and Sears.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goldman, Sachs retail composite index rose 4.4 percent in
June from June 1997, a slightly stronger gain than the 4 percent
increase reported for the comparable period a year earlier. But the
gain was not as strong as the 7.1 percent rise in May of this year,
or the 10.2 percent gain in April, the industry's biggest increase
in nearly a decade. Sales in stores open at least one year, or
same-store sales, are considered to be the best measure of a
retailer's health.
</P>
<P>
   Sales by general merchandise retailers have lagged behind the
rest of the strong economic indicators in recent years as shoppers
have held off on purchases of clothes in favor of cars, services
and other goods. But the spring gave new life to retailers, pushing
up retail stocks, which have outperformed the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index this year. The S&AMP;P retail index is up 54.8 percent
so far this year, compared with a 19.39 percent gain in the S&AMP;P
500.
</P>
<P>
   But a lack of consistency tends to vex investors and analysts
alike. How do you choose which luxury name to play, for example,
when you see Investcorp's Saks Fifth Avenue chain report sales
gains of 8 percent, while its rival, Neiman Marcus, a Harcourt
General Inc. unit that serves almost an identical customer,
reported a gain of only 1.9 percent _ especially when those two
retailers were in the exact reverse position in May?
</P>
<P>
   And how big a bet do you place on the specialty retailers when
Ann Taylor Stores Corp. suddenly reports a gain of 9 percent for
June after losses in many recent months, and when the same can be
said of the rest of the specialty retailing group?
</P>
<P>
   ``You live and die with these things,'' lamented Jeffrey Feiner,
an analyst at Lehman Brothers Inc. ``You have to look at it in a
company-specific way. To make a group call with retailers has
always been very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that surprised on the downside, and were punished for
it, were those catering to the middle- to lower-middle-income
shoppers. J.C. Penney &AMP; Co., for example, announced that its sales
fell 2.1 percent and that its second-quarter earnings would be
lower than expected as a result. Wall Street sent the stock
tumbling $5.8125, or 8.1 percent, to close at $65.625.
</P>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. also reported a weak month. Sales at the
retailing giant rose a mere three-tenths of 1 percent, and its
stock also took a hit, closing at $59.3125, down $2.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Department stores, which have posted inconsistent results all
year, were again all over the map in June. Dayton Hudson Corp.
reported a 7.1 percent sales jump, largely bolstered by its Target
division, where sales rose 4.9 percent. Sales at Dillard's Inc.
department stores were flat, and Federated Department Stores Inc.
reported a 3.4 percent gain. May Department Stores Co. said sales
rose 4.5 percent, and Kohls Corp. reported gains of 4.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Retail analysts expect that second-quarter earnings should still
be strong among retailers, because of the solid sales in the
spring, which left little inventory to mark down. ``We think the
bottom line is that second-quarter earnings will be very good,''
Baum said. ``But July sales may not be so great, because there may
be nothing left in the stores to sell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
