<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COX     07-09 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Affidavit: Anderson admits to trafficking
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILOXI, Miss. _ Greg ``Cadillac'' Anderson, who played backup
center for the Atlanta Hawks last season, has confessed to his
involvement in a four-person cocaine transportation and
distribution operation, according to an FBI affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson ``knowingly and willfully'' possessed as much as a
kilogram of cocaine, conspired with at least three others in making
deals for the controlled substance and carried the drugs across
state lines, from Houston to Biloxi, Miss., according to a federal
indictment filed June 25 in U.S. District Court in Biloxi.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was detained, but not arrested, on May 20 at the Grand
Casino Bayview Hotel during an FBI sting operation, according to
the FBI affidavit attached to the indictment. An informant was
present when Anderson was paid $26,000 for the drug, according to
the affidavit. Howard Hill, who was working with Anderson, then
sold approximately three ounces of cocaine to the FBI informant,
according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was charged with one count of conspiracy to possess
with intent to distribute a controlled substance, two counts of
possession with intent to distribute a controlled substance and
three counts of interstate travel in aid of unlawful activity.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson confessed to his involvement and cooperated with the
FBI during their investigation, according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Federal drug charges bring strict sentences without the
possibility of parole, but defendants who cooperate with
authorities often get more lenient treatment when they are
sentenced. FBI Special Agent Matthew Campbell _ who headed the
investigation of Anderson and co-defendants Kenneth ``K.B.''
Blackmon of Houston, Howard ``Nikki'' Hill of Jackson, Miss., and
Kevin Porter of Biloxi, Miss. _ said Thursday that Anderson's
arrest should come ``soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we catch somebody doing something wrong, it
doesn't mean we'll arrest them right away when there is no risk of
flight,'' Campbell said. ``When he makes his appearance to answer
the indictment, then he'll be arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackmon was arrested on May 29 and is free on $100,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 34, is a 10-year NBA veteran who played for six teams.
He earned the NBA minimum salary with the Hawks last season,
approximately $242,000. However, Anderson made $6 million for two
seasons in the Italian League, 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was contacted by The Journal and Constitution on
Wednesday and Thursday, but he refused to comment or to reveal the
name of his attorney.
</P>
<P>
   But last week in Houston, Anderson said, ``I just got my name
caught up in something. . . . I'll get through it.'' He carried on
with his daily summer activities -- playing ball during the day at
a Houston high school, participating in a pro-am summer league and
lounging with old friends.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Anderson's friends expressed shock at the news of the
indictment. Yet the indictment states that Anderson was involved in
drug business from early 1998, during the Atlanta Hawks season,
until late May.
</P>
<P>
   The quartet, according to the document, performed ``the unlawful
activity being a business enterprise involving the distribution of
. . . cocaine, and thereafter did perform acts to promote, manage,
establish, carry on and facilitate . . . unlawful activity.''
</P>
<P>
   In his affidavit, Special Agent Campbell described this series
of events:
</P>
<P>
   On May 16, Hill and Porter were stopped in Biloxi by FBI agents.
A search of Porter's vehicle uncovered ``approximately one kilogram
of powdered cocaine,'' stashed in the engine compartment of the
truck.
</P>
<P>
   Porter and Hill said the cocaine had been picked up at
Blackmon's home in Houston. Hill said Blackmon ``fronted'' him the
cocaine but that Hill left a 1996 Impala at Anderson's residence as
collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said Anderson brokered the deal between him and Blackmon
for a $1,000 fee. The cocaine was transported from Blackmon's home
to Anderson's, where it was placed in the engine compartment of
Porter's truck. Porter drove the drugs to Hill, who had flown into
Gulfport, Miss., from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Also on that day, Hill cooperated with the FBI by making several
monitored calls to Anderson. Hill was paged by Anderson, who
instructed Hill to return on that same date. ``Come back and do the
same thing,'' Anderson said. He also told Hill to split the
remaining cocaine, about one quarter of a kilo.
</P>
<P>
   On May 18, Hill told Anderson in a telephone conversation that
he'd sold $26,000 worth of cocaine and that Anderson should come to
Biloxi to retrieve the money and forward it to Blackmon. Two days
later, Anderson flew to the Gulfport/Biloxi Regional Airport and
was driven by Hill to the Grand Casino Bayview Hotel. There, Hill
gave Anderson $26,000 in cash and showed Anderson about three
ounces of unsold cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Hill then sold the remaining cocaine to an FBI undercover agent,
with Anderson present. As the undercover agent left Room 870, FBI
agents entered the room and detained Anderson. During questioning,
Anderson admitted to being involved in the cocaine deal, saying
that Blackmon secured the kilo of drugs that Hill and Porter had
when they were stopped on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, trying to cooperate with the FBI on May 22, made
monitored phone calls to Blackmon, who wondered why Hill had not
returned to Houston with cash. ``(Hill) has it sewn up down
there,'' Anderson told Blackmon. Anderson also told Blackmon that
Hill wanted two more ``shoes,'' as in two kilograms of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Blackmon answered, ``OK,'' and gave his pager number. Hill then
called Blackmon, who said, ``You have me worried down here, man.''
Hill assured him everything was fine by saying he'd already sold
one kilo and had broken down another to sell.
</P>
<P>
   A premature announcement in Washington, D.C., by an FBI
official, Tom Kneir, that ``a Hawks player'' was indicted
apparently triggered the unsealing of the indictment. As a courtesy
to the Hawks, U.S. Attorney Brad Pigott in Mississippi successfully
asked a judge to unseal the indictment on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   In cases of cooperation by indicted parties, and with a minimal
risk of flight, the indictments often are sealed until an arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
