<SLUG> BC-SPIVEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spivey says he decided to transfer
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Georgia Tech basketball player Travis Spivey plans to
transfer, but the point guard said Thursday that it is his own
decision and coach Bobby Cremins did not force him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine,'' Spivey said, sounding surprised that his
departure had attracted so much attention. ``I don't have a problem
with coach Cremins.''
</P>
<P>
   Spivey's high school coach, Joel Hopkins of Mount Zion Christian
Academy in Durham, N.C., has denounced Cremins and his program,
saying he would never send another player to Tech.Spivey is the
fifth player to leave the basketball program in three years, and a
sixth, Pablo Machado, is considering a transfer. ``It was my
decision (to leave),'' Spivey said. ``Coach Cremins called me in
and we talked. He told me I could come back or I could transfer. He
said he wanted me to do whatever I felt was best. I felt it was in
my best interest if I transferred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spivey said he ``was never comfortable'' at Tech. ``I came to
Tech for basketball reasons and because of (the city of) Atlanta,''
he said. ``I wasn't that comfortable (in the classroom). Deep down,
Georgia Tech was never the right situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Spivey was thought to be in academic trouble, he never
was given probation or an official warning. However, he was two
hours short of the required number needed to be eligible to play
next season without attending summer school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, (Cremins) did bring in another point guard,'' Spivey
said. ``I'm not saying (Tony Akins of Berkmar High) would've come
in and taken my place, but I felt we would have split playing
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Spivey is enrolled in summer school at North Carolina Central
University and will decide in the next few weeks where to play next
season. He would have to sit out a year and will be eligible forthe
1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm visiting Minnesota Monday and then probably Nebraska,'' he
said. ``There are a couple more I may talk to, but I won't decide
until after this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Jones, an assistant at Minnesota, confirmed that the
Gophers have an interest in Spivey. ``We've requested a
transcript,'' Jones said, ``and we want to talk to him and find out
exactly why he decided to leave. We're interested, but we want to
be sure why he's not returning.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
