<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A. Jones' flight lands in Cox's doghouse
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI -- Andruw Jones is in the doghouse again.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves center fielder, as well as rookie first baseman
Randall Simon, were late reporting back to the club after travel
delays from their native Curacao Thursday. Jones was scratched from
the lineup early in the afternoon, leaving manager Bobby Cox in
personnel bind and not happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't rely on planes and weather,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the pair faced disciplinary measures, the manager
replied, ``Oh, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, traveling with his father, and Simon had a 9 a.m. flight
out of Curacao that would have arrived in Miami at noon. But Jones
called to say the flight had been cancelled and, while they were
able to book an afternoon flight, it would not put them into Miami
International Airport until 5:30 p.m. They then faced U.S. Customs
and a long ride up the coast through rush-hour traffic.
</P>
<P>
   What irked Cox most was the Braves are already playing a man
short, with left fielder Ryan Klesko out at least until Saturday
while he recovers from his appendectomy. That left Cox with a
22-man roster and he started a Danny Bautista-Gerald
Williams-Michael Tucker outfield for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Simon expected to arrive at Pro Player Stadium just
before gametime and were available for pinch-hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You live and learn,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Klesko attempted taking batting practice for the
first time since his June 29th emergency surgery and, depending on
how things go in the batting cage tonight, could be back in action
Saturday after missing just eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did some light jogging (Wednesday) and there's still a lot
of pain in there, just running,'' Klesko said. `` The doctor said
the pain from the scar tissue is going to be there for up to four
to six weeks. Swinging right now, opening up my hips and putting a
lot of pressure down there, it's just not doing it. I tried it a
couple times (Wednesday) and basically fell over.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss rests
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was a good opportunity to start Ozzie Guillen, who had
gone 12 days without seeing action. But the move was actually a
chance for Walt Weiss to catch his breath after what seemed an
endless All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a free moment,'' said Weiss. ``As crazy as it
was, it was still a highlight for me and my family. But it's not
something you'd want to do more than once.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers itinerary
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wohlers was scheduled to pitch Thursday night in Class AAA
Richmond's game in Columbus, accompany the R-Braves to their next
series in Toledo this weekend and then ponder the next move. A
chance exists he could return to Atlanta, but Cox was noncommittal
until management could evaluate the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Lonely fifth starter
</P>
<P>
   With an off-day falling Monday, Kevin Millwood will miss his
turn in the rotation again, meaning the Braves 10-4 fifth starter
will be making just three starts in a 29-day period. Millwood, who
shut out the New York Mets for eight innings his last time out July
4, will next work July 18 against Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're skipping him, unless someone wants an extra
day,'' Cox said. ``That puts (Tom) Glavine and (Greg) Maddux on
seven days rest. Everyone is rooting for Kevin but you can't (push
the rotation back).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
