<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons have cash to spend under cap
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Atlanta remains about $1.6 million under the salary
cap after signing its nine-member draft class of 1998. That puts
them in slightly better-than-average shape relative to the league.
</P>
<P>
   The number could increase, depending on the situation with
backup quarterback Mark Rypien. Rypien, who probably won't
participate in training camp while his son and wife battle serious
illnesses, could retire. He could be waived. He could join the team
once the season has begun.
</P>
<P>
   If Rypien does not play, the team could end up with $2 million
or so left under the cap. It is conceivable the extra money will
afford the opportunity to pick up a quality player if one is
released from another training camp.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Harold Richardson and head coach Dan Reeves
aren't ready to commit the money in any one direction. They say
they want to extend the contract of quarterback Chris Chandler
(which won't occur sooner than a couple weeks before the regular
season, when the final roster is taking shape).
</P>
<P>
   Two-minute drill
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' minicamp ended Thursday, but a voluntary passing
camp will be held today. It is the last formal gathering of the
entire team before training camp begins July 23. ... Injury update:
WR Kevin Thornal (quad bruise) and LB Cornelius Bennett (Achilles)
were dinged, neither seriously. Fullback Bob Christian's knee
continues to bother him. The only other fullback on the roster is
rookie free agent Darren Fisk of Colorado. ... Chandler, who would
have been the favorite in the Dan Reeves Golf Tournament on
Thursday afternoon at Chateau Elan, didn't play. Reeves said
Chandler committed months ago to play in the Isuzu Celebrity Golf
Challenge in Lake Tahoe, before dates were set for minicamp. He
therefore was excused. ... With Chandler gone, Steve DeBerg got
more reps. The highlight: a 55-yard pass down the right sideline,
that Keith Crawford caught for a touchdown. The ball was just over
the fingertips of the defender. ... Veterans were measured and
weighed Tuesday, and 28-year-old defensive end Chuck Smith hit
6-foot-2 1/2. Last year, he was 6-2. ``I want to pick up another
half by the time I retire,'' he said. ... Smith and left tackle Bob
Whitfield each have hosted the ``Sports Unlimited'' show on Media
One. Whitfield has less experience at this kind of thing, but said,
``At least I'm better than Magic,'' a reference to Magic Johnson's
much-maligned new show on Fox/Channel 5.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
