</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mining for prospects passed over in draft
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- There aren't many Jessie Tuggles out there, but the
Atlanta Falcons _ like every NFL team _ are looking for them.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle made the team as an undrafted free agent from Valdosta
State in 1987, when there were 12 rounds in the draft rather than
the current seven. He started four games at middle linebacker as a
rookie, has led the team in tackles nine straight years and has
been to four Pro Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   After the draft every spring, NFL teams continue mining for
talent, signing college players who slipped through the cracks.
Atlanta signed 12, waiving three since.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to handicap the prospects of these players since
they won't play in pads until July 23. But some arrived with bigger
reputations, and wallets, than others. The Falcons gave five
signing bonuses of $10,000 or more to undrafted rookies. By
contrast, the Chiefs gave one bonus that big, and none more than
$6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle Jose Portilla (6 feet 6, 320 pounds) of Arizona and
left tackle Michael Edwards (6-6, 290) of Nevada got two of the
large bonuses. Both said coaches haven't given them any special
insight about their chances to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't said what their plans are,'' Portilla said. ``I'm
just working on adjusting to all the humidity, and getting used to
the playbook.''
</P>
<P>
   The other rookie free agents are Darren Fisk, a 6-1, 230-pound
fullback from Colorado; defensive end Ben Huff (6-4, 275) of
Michigan; wide receivers Corey Allen (6-1, 199) of Georgia and
Octavus Barnes (6-2, 200) of North Carolina; quarterback Brian
Brennan (6-5, 225) of Idaho, linebacker Schad Freeman (6-3, 235) of
Valdosta State and safety Brad Trout (6-2, 209) of Valdosta State.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle's path was unusual. It's more likely a few rookie free
agents will make the five-man practice squad. Robbie Tobeck made
the practice squad in 1993 and played sparingly in '94 before
starting all 47 of 48 games since. He has moved from left guard to
center this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, receiver Kevin Thornal of SMU, defensive end Barry
Mitchell of Idaho and tackle Jeremy Akers of Notre Dame made the
practice squad despite not being drafted. Each will be in training
camp this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
