<SLUG> BC-SELIG-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's official and unanimous: Selig voted commissioner
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Bud Selig had the word ``acting'' dropped from his
commissioner's title Thursday and pledged to ``ensure that baseball
remains as important and as attractive to every child as it was to
me when I was growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has doubts about Selig's heart being in the right place
for baseball. And the owners on Thursday gave the 63-year-old a
unanimous vote of approval by naming him the ninth commissioner of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Selig has served as interim commissioner since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people recognized the job that was being done,'' Mets
owner Fred Wilpon said. ``There was a great turnaround in baseball,
and Bud should get the credit. It happened on his watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners praised Selig for reinvigorating the game with
interleague play and wild-card playoff races.
</P>
<P>
   Selig will continue to rule by consensus. ``A commissioner is
not a czar sitting above the law,'' he said. ``Yes, a commissioner
has a lot of power, but it must be confined to certain areas.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he does not expect sweeping changes, although the
major-league office probably will be overhauled _ except for Paul
Beeston, the chief operating officer, who will continue to deal
mostly with the players union. One of Selig's biggest challenges
will be to try to correct the huge disparity between the
small-market and big-market teams. Right now, almost every division
and wild-card race is led by a team with a big payroll. But first
and foremost, Selig said he will make sure there are no more work
stoppages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the average fan is unhappy about,'' he said. ``He
or she doesn't want to hear anymore about what I said, (about) what
Don Fehr said. The more we focus on the field, the better off we'll
all be.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig has resigned from his positions as president and CEO of
the Milwaukee Brewers, the team he owns.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Wendy Selig-Prieb, will take over those duties
officially. She has been handling the day-to-day business
operations of the club. Her recent focus has been on the club's new
park.
</P>
<P>
   Selig owns about 35 percent of the club, and his share will be
put into a blind trust. Bob Dupuy, Selig's personal lawyer, is
drafting the terms of a trust, in which the Brewers will be placed
into to remove any potential conflicts. Selig will have to name a
trustee who will vote on his ownerships interest when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Selig-Prieb insists she will not compromise her job and ask her
father for advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (will) have no involvement,'' she said. ``Like everyone
else, he'll have to read it in the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig said: ``I hear most people say, 'He's an owner, and he's
one of them.' First and foremost, for those who know me, I am a
fan. There is no one who could love this game more than I do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
