</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOSEVELT-SECURITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOSEVELT TO JOIN SOCIAL SECURITY ADMINISTRATION STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than 50 years after his grandfather created
Social Security as part of the New Deal, James Roosevelt is joining
the Social Security Administration to help prepare the retirement
program for the demands of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth S. Apfel, the Social Security Administration
commissioner, announced Thursday that Roosevelt, a longtime
Democratic activist and Cambridge, Mass. lawyer, has been named an
associate commissioner for retirement policy. Roosevelt will begin
work later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased Jim is joining us as a member of our
executive team,'' said Apfel. ``He will bring a wealth of knowledge
and expertise on retirement policy to Social Security as we discuss
and debate the challenges facing Social Security in the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt is a member of the Democratic National Committee and
legal counsel to the Massachusetts Democratic Party. He made an
unsuccessful run for the Democratic nomination for Congress in
Massachusetts' 8th district in 1986, the year that Representative
Joseph P. Kennedy II won the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt joins the Social Security Administration at a critical
point in the debate over the future of Social Security. Congress
has been reluctant to make changes because of fear of political
repercussions. But the popular retirement program faces a major
challenge in the next century when the enormous Baby Boom
generation reaches retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has urged Congress to hold back on spending
the projected budget surplus until the Social Security issue has
been resolved. Agency officials said Roosevelt will be based in
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
