<HEADER>
A8224 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-RAHAL-HNS &LR;      07-09 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RAHAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cleveland's where it all began for Rahal
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CLEVELAND _ In 1982 as a 29-year-old rookie, Bobby Rahal won his
first Indy-car race just a few miles away from where he grew up in
northern Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years later, with three CART championships and 24
victories behind him, Rahal returns to the Burke Lakeshore Airport
runway course for the final time in the Medic Drug Grand Prix of
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   It has been six years since Rahal won a race, and he would love
to get his last victory at the place where it all began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland is a place that holds special significance for me,''
Rahal said. ``I have a lot of local backing here, and that's keeps
me up for this race. Everybody is cheering for me. I have great
memories here, and it would be great to finish my career here the
same way I started it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahal grew up in Medina, Ohio, only 35 miles south of downtown
Cleveland. He now lives in New Albany, Ohio, with his wife Debi and
their four children. Rahal decided before the year began that the
1998 season would be his last as a driver.
</P>
<P>
   Being a driver is only part of Rahal's job these days. When his
Indy-car career began, Rahal just wanted to prove he could be a
competitive driver. Now he is the co-owner (with David Letterman)
of a two-driver team, along with being on the board of directors
for CART.
</P>
<P>
   Team Rahal consists of Rahal's Miller Lite Reynard Ford and
Bryan Herta's Shell Reynard Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday will be Rahal's 255th start in the Indy-car series. He is
the only driver who has competed in all 16 previous events at
Cleveland, a place that brought him plenty of success over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rahal has nine top-five finishes on the airport course,
including three seconds and two thirds during a five-year stretch
from 1987-91.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland is one of the best road circuits we have,'' Rahal
said. ``I really enjoy driving this course, and it has always been
very kind to me. I've had a fair amount of success here and the
fans always have warmly welcomed me here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artistically speaking, it's not the most beautiful track in
the world, but every driver I know loves racing here because it's
so wide. It's very racy, and it produces a lot of action.''
</P>
<P>
   The course also has a hairpin-type curve on the first turn past
the start-finish line, where the cars may be three- and four-wide
as the drivers try to squeeze into the same spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hairiest starting corner in motor sports,'' Rahal
said. ``It looks like the Oklahoma Land Rush going in there for the
first lap.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahal said a lot of things will be running through his mind when
he hops into his car to make his final start in a city close to his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to spend my summers up here with my grandparents,''
Rahal said. ``But it was different then, and it was different when
CART first came here. The downtown area was called `The Mistake By
The Lake.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But you compare that to the way it is today, with The Flats,
the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame, Jacobs Field and Gund Arena, and
it's a much different atmosphere. All the drivers want to come here
now.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of young drivers have been coming to Rahal lately to make
their pitch as the next driver of the Miller Lite Ford. Rahal has
interviewed several potential replacements to take over his seat,
but he isn't close to making a selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to some guys from Formula One and some other CART
drivers,'' Rahal said. ``But we've also talked to Formula 3000 guys
and Indy Lights drivers. No one from the IRL has contacted me about
the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the talk about people not getting opportunities, 99
percent of my calls come from drivers in Europe and South America.
A lot of guys from Brazil are dying to get a ride. The person we
choose doesn't have to be an American. We want someone who is
capable of running up front, but for me, it's going to come down to
desire and the guy that really wants it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how Rahal approached his career when he finally got his
chance on the CART circuit and won at Cleveland in only his fourth
race, defeating Indy-car legends like A.J. Foyt, Mario Andretti,
Rick Mears and Al Unser.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of 1998, Rahal will try to keep running up front
and maybe get one more victory before he hangs up his helmet. He
ranks 12th in the FedEx points standings, but he would like to
finish in the top 10. He is only two points behind Al Unser Jr.,
who holds down the 10th spot.
</P>
<P>
   A victory at his home track would be a great way to move up in
the points chase, but more importantly, it would a magical way for
Rahal to close out an outstanding career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't enter my last year to coast around the tracks and get
accolades from the fans,'' Rahal said. ``I still want to win races,
and I have a few more chances before I have to move over for the
kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
