<HEADLINE>
NEW WELFARE RULES WOULD RAISE ELIGIBILITY STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With nearly 10,000 families slated to have their
welfare cash benefits cut off Dec. 1 under Massachusetts' new
two-year time limit, Acting Governor Paul Cellucci's administration
will propose narrow circumstances Friday under which they might be
granted a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed regulations developed by welfare officials,
the welfare commissioner could grant an extension to a family in
which a parent works full time but earns less than what the family
gets in cash aid.
</P>
<P>
   That sets a high bar, which most families would not be able to
clear. For example, a person who works full time at minimum wage
would earn $854 a month, the amount a family of eight receives in
welfare benefits. The average welfare family has three members _ a
mother and two children _ and obtains $565 a month.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are other extenuating circumstances under which
families could qualify for an extension. The commissioner, for
instance, could also consider whether a parent has been offered a
job but couldn't accept it because she was unable to obtain child
care; whether a parent has made a sincere effort to find a job but
could not get one; and whether the family has been complying with a
host of state welfare rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the poor denounced the proposal for making it too
difficult for truly needy families to stay on welfare. They also
criticized the plan for giving the commissioner too much power to
decide on extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates contend the state should create standards under which
waivers would be automatically granted and take into consideration
other factors such as whether there are obstacles standing in the
way of a person's ability to get and hold a full-time job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other states say that if you play by the rules, we will give
you an extension,'' said Deborah Harris, an attorney specializing
in welfare issues at the Massachusetts Law Reform Institute. ``This
state says that if you play by the rules, we will consider giving
you an extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple fairness requires that people should know what the
rules are and know whether they will be able to feed and house
their children if they follow the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   But in what some advocates consider a promising development, if
the commissioner denies a waiver request, the case could be
appealed through an administrative process and ultimately to the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Ross, coordinator of the Women's Alliance, a
Framingham-based grass-roots advocacy group for low-income women,
noted that one-third of the cases closed under Massachusetts' new
welfare system have been due to procedural problems. ``If the
implementation of the time limit is fraught with as many
problems,'' she said, ``it is going to be really crucial that we
have the ability to appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the aim is to nudge as many people into work and off the
welfare rolls as possible, administration officials acknowledge
they were trying to create as few circumstances as possible in
which waivers would be granted .
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation all along is two years should be time enough
for the vast bulk of individuals on welfare to be able to
transition off,'' said one high-ranking administration official who
asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of the 10,000 families subject to the Dec. 1
cutoff do not currently have to work because they have preschool
children. But administration sources said a new intensive program
will be started this summer through the Department of Employment
and Training and state-contracted career centers to help these
families get jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The time limit applies to families with able-bodied parents and
children at least 2 years of age who have been on the welfare rolls
for 24 months in a five-year cycle. The commissioner would be able
to grant extensions for up to six months an unlimited number of
times.
</P>
<P>
   Administration sources said discussions are currently underway
to have a state agency monitor the well-being of families who are
not granted waivers to the time limits and to make sure they are
aware they would remain eligible for other programs such as food
stamps and Medicaid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
