<HEADER>
A8230 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-LADN     07-09 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE TV MOMENTS TRULY RANK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We've hit a speed bump in our overzealous,
here-comes-the-millennium need to ``rank 'n' roll,'' the fallout
which could cause a great many of us to simply stop, drop and roll.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is no one has figured out how to define a defining
moment.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the current issue of TV Guide attempts to construct
TV's 50 greatest sports moments. It appears the editors did so by
throwing suggestions into a hat and pulling them out with greased
salad tongs. The great moments seem to be there, but their
illogical order leaves the reader to wonder what, if any, criteria
was considered.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning, anytime the Miracle On Ice is confused with Torville
and Dean's perfect 6.0 at the '84 Olympics, the filters in coffee
machines at TV Guide need to be scanned.
</P>
<P>
   TV Guide, of course, admits it wants this list to ignite debate.
The only debate is whether to simply incinerate or roll into a
giant torch and burn TV Guide's building to the ground with it.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to some insight into the socio-cultural
ramifications with these kinds of exercises? TV Guide, in all its
triviality, manages to do neither.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to this: The bottom line is, everyone's a sucker for
lists. And if you're going to determine, and not undermind, the
most important sports moments in TV history (we know, TV Guide's
guideline was just ``the greatest,'' but we suggest taking it a
step further), a starting point could look something closer to
this:
</P>
<P>
   1972: ABC's coverage of the hostages at the Munich Olympics. For
reminding the world that sports isn't just fun and games and that a
so-called sportscaster (Jim McKay) can cover a news event if
properly trained.
</P>
<P>
   1939: NBC beams the Princeton-Columbia baseball game to a
handful of homes in the New York. For the birth of televised sport.
</P>
<P>
   And so on.
</P>
<P>
   By our definition _ and here's the distinction _ TV can't be
taken that seriously. It lost that right long ago. It's definitely
an entertainment medium with journalism-by-mistake mentality, and
only if it creates ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, when we were inspired to feed this ``list-monster,''
we've decided a ranking of the defining moments in sports TV should
look more like this (with a slant toward how it impacted Los
Angeles):
</P>
<P>
   1. Vin Scully's attempt at entertainment television. From spring
1969 to summer of 1970, Scully hosted a game show for NBC called
``It Takes Two.'' From January to March 1973, he tried hosting a
weekday afternoon talk show for CBS called ``The Vin Scully Show.''
The former was replaced by ``Dinah's Place,'' the latter by ``The
Secret Storm.'' And sports fans in L.A. didn't have to fret about
Scully pulling a Dick Enberg and leaving us for the network riches.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``The Munsters,'' first season, episode 29 called ``Herman
the Rookie,'' airdate April 8, 1965. Leo Durocher appears as
himself _ as the Dodgers manager. For a kid growing up in L.A., it
left a scarring effect. Was Walter Alston the Dodgers' skipper, or
was it really Durocher?
</P>
<P>
   TV was wrong. So TV was bad.
</P>
<P>
   Durocher also delivered maybe the best line in sports TV history
for that decade. After watching Herman Munster during a tryout,
Durocher exclaims: ``I don't know whether to sign him with the
Dodgers or send him to Vietnam!''
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Leave It To Beaver'' episode called ``Long-Distance Call,''
airdate June 16, 1962. Beaver Cleaver, on a dare from pal Whitey,
calls the Dodgers locker room and asks for Don Drysdale. When
Drysdale comes to the phone, they have a conversation that any kid
would love to have with a big-leaguer. A local newspaperman hears
about it, writes a story, Beav gets in trouble ... but that's
another story.
</P>
<P>
   This episode inspired kids everywhere to reach out and bond with
their heroes.
</P>
<P>
   (Writer's note: Don't try this with Bill Grabarkewitz,
especially after an 0-for-5 day).
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Who's The Boss'' episode from 1990 called ``Take Me Back to
the Ballgame.'' Tommy Lasorda appears as himself. It explains this
warped relationship with Tony Danza.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``The Bold and the Beautiful,'' episode from 1993. Mike
Piazza appears as himself. He also appears to take the ``bold'' and
``beautiful'' parts to heart. Leaves L.A. five years later.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``The Brady Bunch,'' fifth season, second episode called
``Mail Order Hero,'' airdate Sept. 21, 1973. Joe Namath appears as
himself. This marks the end of Namath's NFL career (see L.A. Rams,
benchwarmer), and the beginning of the end of his acting career
(see ``The Waverly Wonders'').
</P>
<P>
   7. ``The Brady Bunch,'' first season, episode 18 called ``The
Undergraduate,'' airdate Jan. 16, 1970. Wes Parker appears as
himself. Greg Brady has a crush on his teacher, Miss O'Hara, whose
boyfriend happens to be the Dodgers first baseman, who promises
Brady Dodger tickets if his grades improve.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Parker's acting career stalled, but surprisingly, Fes Parker
started getting more TV work.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Gilligan's Island,'' episodes called ``Topsy-Turvy''
(airdate Nov. 14, 1966) and ``High Man on the Totem Pole'' (airdate
Feb. 27, 1967). Roman Gabriel, Al Ferrara and Jim Lefebvre appear
not as themselves, but as natives. It helped set a bad precedent.
Ten years later, Jim Bouton starred in ``Ball Four,'' based on his
controversial tell-all book. The sitcom lasted one month before
Bouton was left on TV's deserted island.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``The Simpsons,'' episode 8F13 called ``Homer at the Bat,''
airdate Feb. 20, 1992. Darryl Strawberry appears as himself, in
cartoon form. The then-Dodgers controversial outfielder shows his
vulnerable side, crying when Bart and Lisa taunt him with
``Darr-yyylll.'' Turned out to foreshadow Strawberry's cry for
help.
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Bowling For Dollars,'' hosted by Chick Hearn, circa 1970.
Chick interviewing the common folk. Simply put, it's the reason why
there are no bowling game shows on TV today. Ask anyone who saw it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
