<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUACKS-MUSEUM-425&AMP;ADD     07-09 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKS-MUSEUM-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM IS TESTAMENT TO ATTEMPTS TO CURE ETERNAL ILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ It is odd to find the Museum of Questionable
Medical Devices here in the capital of Midwestern niceness.
</P>
<P>
   But just across the river from all the skyscrapers, in the
historic St. Anthony Main complex, is an array of bogus medical
devices spanning two centuries, a stunning testament to the myriad
ways people have tried to make money off the eternal ills of
humankind.
</P>
<P>
   Baldness, impotence and obesity seem to inspire the most
creations, including slimming soaps, ``sanitized tapeworms'' and a
remarkable hair-loss device _ the Crosly Xervac _ that creates a
vacuum to pull blood to the scalp and no doubt caused more hickeys
than hair growth.
</P>
<P>
   For more general health benefits, there were contraptions like
the MacGregor Rejuvenator, dating from 1932, a magenta
iron-lung-like machine in which a patient would lie, to be blasted
with magnetism, radio waves and infrared and ultraviolet light, in
hopes of reversing the aging process.
</P>
<P>
   The museum of quackery is tiny, out of the way, open mostly in
the evenings and is free. After 14 years, it is taking off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing 750 people a week now,'' said Robert W. McCoy,
the 71-year-old retired salesman who founded it, ``and with the
books we sell and contributions, it's finally self-supporting.
Until this year, I was subsidizing it from Social Security, my
pension and my wife's salary.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy's wife, Margaret, a pediatrician who overcame an initial
fear of being spotted by a patient, helps out on busy weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's good at explaining things,'' McCoy said. ``But she won't
do phrenology readings.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrenology machines, the first devices he acquired, back in
1984, are McCoy's specialty, featuring a metal helmet that looks
like a torture device. The contraption spits out a personality
reading based on the shape of the user's head. After a series of
loud clanks, this visitor's $2 reading produced mixed results: very
superior in friendship, combativeness, veneration and amativeness;
average on agreeability, sympathy and suavity, but, alas, deficient
in faith, ideality, time and tune.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy's collection now includes 200-odd items, thanks to loans
from the Food and Drug Administration and the American Medical
Association, purchases, and donations from the growing ranks of
medical experts who have found the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a medical historian in the other day who was just agog
at what we have,'' McCoy said. ``People fall for things that are
really preposterous. Especially about sex.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pre-Viagra, attempts to restore ``sexual vitality'' involved
items like a 1918 prostate gland warmer, which was plugged into a
socket, then inserted into the rectum, or the Manhood Belt of the
same era, which created a burning sensation when activated by body
sweat because it was soaked in red pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s, those seeking an aphrodisiac might have turned to
Radithor, a concoction of distilled water laced with radium.
Radioactivity became the miracle cure for all kinds of things,
offered in suppository form for women, or in a jock strap for men.
``Weak Discouraged Men!'' trumpets one circular. ``Now Bubble Over
with Joyous Vitality Through the Use of GLANDS and RADIUM.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum also has an old fluoroscope, an X-ray machine used in
the 1950s to fit shoes: children would stick their feet in, then
look through the machine to see their green toe bones wriggling
around inside the shoe. McCoy's relic turned up in a West Virginia
department store in 1981, long after its use was generally banned.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the museum's displays were late-night television fodder,
like the foot-operated bosom enlarger, a pump with pink cups to be
placed over the breast. Or the dieters' glasses, tinted blue on one
lens, brown on the other, on the theory that tinted food would be
so unappetizing that the wearer would eat less.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy has blood-letting instruments, vision enhancers and one of
Wilhelm Reich's original orgone energy accumulator boxes,
metal-lined containers the doctor said would capture free-floating
orgone, or libidinal energy. After a fight with the Food and Drug
Administration, which in 1957 ordered him to stop shipping the
boxes, Reich was sentenced to two years in prison, where he died.
</P>
<P>
   Among this year's additions are green Kangle Magnetic Balls from
Beijing, purporting to work wonders on, among other things,
headache, finger cramp, sore throats, fever, problems with
urination, and, with repeated use, to help the elderly maintain
``strong brains.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum highlights not only arcana of the past, but
contemporary products marketed for health purposes, from blue-green
algae to bogus cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   And for all the goofiness of the collection, the message adds up
to a salutary Midwestern sermon against snake oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just recently, there was a lady who said, `How dare you have
magnetic insoles in here, when they really work,' and got really
testy,'' McCoy said. ``It turns out she sells them. Most of the
time, when people come in and say how wonderful their copper
bracelets are, or whatever, I give them a copy of an old pamphlet,
`Of the Imagination as a Cause and Cure of Disorders in the Body.'
People don't seem to know that the scientific method is. It seems
to slip past them. We try to ask, in a gentle way, `How do you know
this thing works?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
