<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8234 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIRUG-ADS-BOS &LR;      07-09 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIRUG-ADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO BEGIN TOUGH NEW ANTI-DRUG AD CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House is trading the frying egg that is
``your brain on drugs'' for the frying pan, with a set of new TV
ads that include a teenager smashing her kitchen with a skillet _ a
visual metaphor for the destruction caused by heroin.
</P>
<P>
   The $2 billion advertising blitz, billed as the largest and most
ambitious effort ever to teach teenagers about drugs, is part of a
five-year, anti-drug media campaign announced Thursday in Atlanta
by President Clinton and House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the most expensive. The campaign marks the first time
the federal government is paying directly for media exposure. The
ads are bolder, brasher, and more hip, but will they work? The
president believes the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ads were designed to knock America upside the head and
get America's attention and empower all of you who are trying to do
the right thing,'' Clinton told an Atlanta audience of mostly
children.
</P>
<P>
   Whether surfing the Internet, reading the newspaper or listening
to the radio, Americans will be bombarded with the ads, which began
running last night and reached an estimated 40 million people. The
campaign is targeted at both children and parents, and the ads are
tailored to the particular market in which they appear.
</P>
<P>
   Private donations, including donated media time, are expected to
cover half the cost of the campaign. So far, Congress has
appropriated $195 million to the first year, and Gringrich promised
he would fight to get the remaining funding from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all trying to reach out to every young American and say,
`Don't do it,' '' said Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Drug surveys consistently have shown that drug use has risen
among 8th, 10th and 12th graders, at the same time the perception
that drugs were dangerous or harmful has dropped. Drug use among
youths, especially among middle-schoolers, has been rising steadily
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The White House-sponsored ads are intended to restore both the
stigma and the perception of harmfulness to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   However, sociologists and drug researchers have questioned the
efficacy of such campaigns in the past. They say it takes more than
a media blitz to addresss a social problem as large and complex as
drug abuse. Others raise the prospect that the government may be
throwing money at a serious problem without solid research to back
up the spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest problem is that there have been no evaluations of
the Partnership for a Drug-Free America ad campaigns in the past,''
said Scott Ehlers, a spokesperson for the Drug Policy Foundation,
which is dedicated to promoting drug-policy reforms and is partly
funded by George Soros, who supports the use of medical marijuana.
``We're embarking on this $1 billion campaign with taxpayers
dollars and we don't know the effectiveness of these ads.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said the White House already has seen positive
results from a 12-city pilot project of the media campaign that
began earlier this year. Calls to local and national drug hot lines
increased dramatically, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One television add that will air features a teenage girl sitting
on her bed hugging a stuffed rabbit. Suddenly her room is deluged
with water pouring through the door. Swept up in the flood, she
fights to breathe as a voice says, ``There's this thing going
around called sniffing. You think you're getting high, but the
dizzy, fuzzy feeling is just what happens when your brain doesn't
get oxygen.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ad features a teenager smashing an egg _ and then
destroying her kitchen _ with a frying pan. ``This is what happens
to your brain after snorting heroin,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ads are different from commercials,'' explained a
staffer of the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy.
``Ad agencies get instant feedback. They see Nikes moving off the
shelf, or not. We're trying to change attitudes, and the first step
is awareness, seeing the ads.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
