</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGENTS-KILLED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN WHO KILLED BORDER AGENTS, 2 OTHERS BURIED IN QUIET CEREMONY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BENITO, Texas _ Beneath spreading ebony trees, Ernest L.
Moore was buried Thursday morning in a quiet country cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   A hymn was sung and a prayer recited as family members and about
100 mourners gathered around Moore's steel casket. But when the
brief graveside service was over, there were still few answers for
why a young man from a well-respected law enforcement family would
resort to violence after his girlfriend left him. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``They are good people,'' Bill Elliot, a spokesman for Valley
Baptist Hospital in nearby Harlingen, said of Moore's family. ``You
just never can tell what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. George Morrison asked mourners, who included many
police officers, to show compassion to the Moore family, saying,
``Even when we don't understand it, even when we ask why, Jesus
says, `My peace I give you. Let not your heart be troubled.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, 25, the son of a veteran Harlingen police detective and
brother of a San Benito police officer, had raced past the same
graveyard early Tuesday. He had just fled a home in nearby Rio
Hondo where he had killed two and left his romantic rival for dead,
after a botched attempt to abduct his former girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   He fell in a hail of bullets outside his parent's home a short
time later, but not before killing two U.S. Border Patrol agents
and wounding a deputy sheriff trying to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron County Sheriff Omar Lucio said he could not confirm
published reports indicating Moore had cocaine and marijuana in his
system at the time of the killings. But the sheriff did say Moore's
friends told him they had been drinking with Moore within hours of
his early-morning rampage. A toxicology report had not yet been
received by his office, Lucio said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and Doris Meissner,
commissioner of the Immigration and Naturalization Service, will
attend services Friday morning in San Antonio for Border Patrol
agent trainee Ricardo Guillermo Salinas, 24, and then fly to
Harlingen for the funeral of Susan Lynn Rodriguez, 28, the first
female Border Patrol agent to be killed in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, funeral services for Margarita Flores, 53, and her
daughter, Delia Morin, 31, will be held in San Benito.
</P>
<P>
   The two women were killed when Moore entered their home shortly
after 5 a.m. Tuesday, looking for Julie Cox, his former girlfriend.
He also seriously wounded Dan Morin, 22, who had been dating Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who was staying at the Morin home at the time, was not
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Morin, who was shot twice in the back during the incident,
remained in critical condition Thursday at Valley Baptist.
Sheriff's deputy Raul Rodriguez, who also was wounded, was awake
and talking Thursday, the hospital spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
