   For retransmissions of these stories, please call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLACES AND DESTINATIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-TOURISTS-HNS (Shiraz, Iran.) _ For two weeks this spring, I
joined a group of Bay Area residents on a journey that few
Americans have experienced in the last two decades of difficult
U.S.-Iran relations. By the end of the trip, we agreed that we have
rarely, if ever, been made to feel so welcome as Americans anywhere
in the world. By Gail Bensinger.
</P>
<P>
   NAPLES-HNS (Naples, Italy) _ The only Napoleans we encountered
were friendly. No one tried to pick our pockets, hold a knife to
our throats or otherwise live up to Naples' frightful reputation. I
began to wonder whether all those stories were circulated by locals
who didn't want tourists monopolizing the restaurants. By John
Flinn.
</P>
<P>
   OUTER-BANKS-SURF-HNS (Cape Hatteras, N.C.) _ As a transplanted
California surfer, I needed to find some East Coast waves. Like,
right here on the Outer Banks of North Carolina. By Rex Babin.
</P>
<P>
   OUTER-BANKS-TOURISM-HNS (Cape Hatteras, N.C.) _ Things to do on
Cape Hatteras when you're not surfing: Shipwrecks and pirates: The
Outer Banks, also known as ``The Graveyard of the Atlantic,'' like
a cemetery, with hundreds of ships that have been buried over
several hundred years along the Banks. By Rex Babin.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MOUNTIE-BOS (Ottawa) _ The 125th anniversary of the RCMP
_ a police force with a special cachet, is being celebrated this
year. By Linda Matchan.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AUDUBON-BOS (New Bedford, Mass.) -- The Audubon legacy
takes flight at a New Bedford Art Museum. By M.R. Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS (Blackall, Queensland, Australia) _ Way
beyond the blue horizon might be one definition of the Australian
Outback. Beyond imagination and reason yet another. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   GLACIER-PARK-BOS (Glacier National Park) If you do the math,
Glacier National Park played host to 1.7 visitors per acre last
year. And few of those visitors to the million-acre park in
northwestern Montana likely came away disappointed. Created in
1910, Glacier is an American treasure. The $10-per-vehicle entry
charge, good for seven days, has to be one of the best
entertainment tickets in the country. By Jeff Larsen.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ST.NICHOLAS-NYT (Demre, Turkey) _ The slogan of this
pretty town on Turkey's magnificent Mediterranean coast might be:
``Catering to Cults and Religions for More Than 2,000 Years.'' By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BLACK-REGIMENT-NYT (Washington) _ A memorial to a black
Civil War regiment. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-NYT (Amsterdam) _ Windows on the canals: The
scenic hotels of Amsterdam. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSUMER NEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPER-NYT (Livingston, Texas) _ For years, whenever vacation
time rolled around, LaVere and Ginny Keller would roll out of Salt
Lake City in their camper truck and explore the West. ``It was
pretty tight quarters, especially when our three daughters were
with us,'' he recalled. ``But we loved it. We'd get home, and we'd
say, `Wouldn't it be great if we could just keep going?''' In 1994
they did just that. The Kellers retired, sold their house, bought a
trailer and a truck to tow it, and took to the road full time. At
Rainbow's End, a camp for up to 400 recreational vehicles here in
the piney woods of East Texas, they joyously described the changes
in their lives _ the 17 states they have toured, the new friends
they have made at RV camps along the way and most of all, the new
freedom.
</P>
