<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CHILD-CARE-$ADV12-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINDING THE CHILDREN WHILE ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ill., Minn., Iowa)   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
 (JT)  
 By JULIA LAWLOR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time Rebecca Teiken left town on a four-day business
trip, her 5-year-old son, Spencer, was cared for by a sitter. Ms.
Teiken made sure Spencer had his favorite blanket and stuffed
animals, called him every night to chat and counted the hours until
she would see him again.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing that didn't trouble her was the cost of Spencer's
overnight care. Her employer, Amoco, reimburses workers for
dependent care _ to a maximum of $1,500 a year _ when they travel
overnight on business and there is no other family member at home
to care for a child or, in some cases, an elderly relative. As a
single parent who travels often, Ms. Teiken says the policy allows
her to pursue a career she loves without sacrificing peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I travel, this is one less thing I have to worry about,''
said Ms. Teiken, 40, a project manager for Amoco in Des Moines,
Iowa. In her area of the country, Ms. Teiken pays about $50 a day
for overnight care. ``I know I can pay the caregiver well,'' she
said, ``and that reduces the stress on me, so I can focus on the
work.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amoco is one of a relatively small number of companies offering
such benefits to employees who must travel as part of their jobs.
The Families and Work Institute, a research firm in New York, has
found that 6 percent of companies with 100 or more employees
reimburse child-care expenses when workers travel on business.
</P>
<P>
   In a global economy, travel has become a fact of life for more
and more workers. In 1996, the most recent data show, 42.9 million
Americans traveled on business, a 21 percent increase from 1991,
according to the Travel Industry Association of America. One in
five employees regularly takes overnight business trips, according
to a 1997 study by the Families and Work Institute. What's more,
the workplace is increasingly populated by single parents _ almost
one of every five employed parents is single, the study indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many companies that offer such a child-care benefit say
that relatively few workers take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't use it that often,'' said Bonnie Anderson, vice
president of employee relations for American Express Financial
Advisors in Minneapolis. Ms. Anderson, 49, a single mother who
travels once or twice a month for her job, usually arranges for her
parents or close friends to care for her daughter, Sashi, 10, when
she cannot be there.
</P>
<P>
   But occasionally a backup plan can fall through, and she must
pay for overnight care. About a year and a half ago, just before a
trip to California, Ms. Anderson wound up hiring her daughter's
regular day-care provider to care for her for two nights, and the
$50 extra cost was reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a huge economic benefit for me, but what I like
about it is that the company wants to do the right thing,'' said
Ms. Anderson, who lives in Robbinsdale, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Amoco, based in Chicago, began its program in 1993 as it started
to see an increase in employee travel. Roughly 160 people used the
benefit last year, out of a total of 28,000 employees in the United
States, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to help employees meet the balance between work and
their personal lives,'' said Patricia Massucci, Amoco's director of
corporate policies and work-life strategies. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some employees, however, may question whether such a policy
helps employees lead a more satisfying personal life, or simply
keeps them on the job and away from home longer.
</P>
<P>
   Employers should consider ways to structure their work so that
travel is not always necessary, said Karol L. Rose, leader of the
work-life effectiveness practice for PwC HR Solutions, a benefits
consulting unit of Pricewaterhouse Coopers LLC, the accounting
giant. A sales call might be made just as easily through a video
conference, for instance, as through a face-to-face meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This benefit is fine as far as it goes,'' Ms. Rose said. ``But
there should be lots of options. Having the company pay for your
dependent care when you're traveling is not the solution, but it
may come in handy.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One business that is rethinking its expectations for employee
travel is HR Solutions' parent. ``In general, we're looking at ways
of doing for travel what has been done for child care,'' said Iris
Goldfein, vice chairman of human resources at Pricewaterhouse
Coopers. ``We can't take travel out of our business, but we can
make it easier for people.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm is testing a program in its Philadelphia office to
reimburse workers for dependent-care costs incurred while
traveling. For the last year, a new policy in its management
consulting division dictates that employees do not travel on
Sundays. The firm is also considering whether to limit travel on
Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plain and simple, we are trying to get people more time with
their families,'' Ms. Goldfein said. Reimbursing workers for
child-care costs, she said, is one way of recognizing ``that travel
is an additional burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, like John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance in
Boston and HBO, the premium cable division of Time Warner,
reimburse child-care expenses when employees are out of town only
if their jobs do not normally require travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not appropriate for a salesperson whose job is to
travel three days a week,'' said Shelley Fischel, vice president of
human resources and administration at HBO. ``If you have to go to a
conference once a year, you'd qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employers also reimburse child-care costs if a worker's
business travel necessitates additional child care during evenings
or on weekends. Mark Majors, 34, a Chevron engineer in Pascagoula,
Miss., was reimbursed a total of $500 last year for evening child
care when he had to travel overnight and his wife, Kim, a
pharmacist, worked late hours.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Carter, 35, a lawyer for Dorsey &AMP; Whitney in Minneapolis,
is reimbursed between $500 and $700 a year when he travels to cover
the times he and his wife must hire a baby sitter, at $9 an hour,
to watch their four children, all under age 7. Though Carter's
wife, Dede, is a stay-at-home mom, she has volunteer commitments
that keep her away from home on nights and weekends; her husband is
often called out of town at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   In two of her last three jobs, Cynthia Ahart, 41, now a
marketing executive for a computer trade publication, has been
reimbursed for all or part of the child-care expenses incurred
because of her travel. A single mother of a 13-year-old daughter,
Alexandra, Ms. Ahart says she travels 30 percent of the time and
has spent as much as $150 a night for child care. One week-long
trip to a conference cost her $1,200, with less than half of it
reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to travel and being visible is critical,'' said Ms.
Ahart, a resident of Newton, Mass., who will soon be transferring
to her hometown of San Francisco. ``I hate leaving her alone, but
I've been able to triple my income in five years. Much of what I do
is sales-related. You have to be face-to-face with people.
Management has to have the impression you're willing to go the
extra mile for the client.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before accepting one job, Ms. Ahart negotiated partial payment
of her child-care bills while on the road despite the fact that the
company did not have such a policy. Still, the strain of traveling
has made her want to cut back. After she moves to San Francisco,
Ms. Ahart plans to leave her daughter with her parents or
ex-husband when she has to travel _ and to be at home more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that she's a teen-ager, it's important for me to be
there,'' Ms. Ahart said. ``My next demand, instead of asking for
more money, will be to ask for less travel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
