<SLUG> BC-IRS-OVERHAUL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES COMPROMISE BILL TO OVERHAUL IRS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Thursday overwhelmingly approved a
compromise bill designed to implement sweeping changes at the
Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now moves to President Clinton, who is expected to sign
it into law.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 96-2 Thursday to adopt an IRS restructuring
plan that lawmakers hope will provide taxpayers with greater
protections while reining in potential abuses at the nation's
tax-gathering agency.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, hailed passage of the bill, saying ``it's not only good
for the American taxpayer, but it's good for the agency itself and
it's good for the employees who work there.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth chaired two rounds of dramatic Senate hearings on alleged
IRS abuses, events that helped create a groundswell of support for
the IRS overhaul bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., who has been working for the last three
years on an effort to restructure the much-despised agency, said
the legislation will ensure ``that every American taxpayer will be
able to file their taxes easier, will receive better service from
the IRS and will have legal recourse if they are mistreated or
wrongly confronted by the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate vote came less than two weeks after the House
approved the compromise plan by a vote of 402-8.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, whose administration initially resisted
lawmakers' efforts to revamp the agency, said Thursday: ``I am
pleased that the Senate has finally passed bipartisan legislation
to reform the IRS and strengthen taxpayer rights. ... I look
forward to signing it into law.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton characterized the bill as a tool he will use in his own
program to improve the agency. ``This reform will help my effort to
create an IRS that respects American taxpayers and respects their
values,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Among a host of provisions aimed at arming taxpayers with
broader rights when in a dispute with the IRS, the bill would shift
the burden of proof from the individual to the government when an
individual's case lands in tax court. For his part, the taxpayer
would still have to demonstrate a willingness to provide the
necessary tax records to decide the case.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring plan, hammered out by House and Senate
negotiators during a conference committee last month, would create
a nine-member, independent oversight board to keep an eye on the
agency's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would provide new protections for an ``innocent
spouse,'' typically a divorced woman who finds herself the target
of an IRS action because of tax cheating by a now-missing, former
spouse.
</P>
<P>
   It would bar the IRS from assessing penalties and interest if
the agency failed to contact the taxpayer within 18 months after
filing a return. And it would extend a guarantee of confidentiality
similar to the attorney-client privilege to certified public
accountants and other tax preparers involved in non-criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democratic senators who voted against the compromise
plan, Sen. John D. Rockefeller IV of West Virginia and Sen. Paul
Wellstone of Minnesota, both cited a provision that shaves benefits
for veterans _ not the IRS issues _ as the main reason for their
objections to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee and a leader of the IRS restructuring effort in the
House, said the overhaul bill is ``about our values and our
priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about right and wrong,'' Archer said in a written
statement Thursday. ``It's about putting the taxpayer first and the
IRS second. It's about fundamental fairness and justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides instituting changes at the IRS, the bill also includes a
$2 billion capital gains provision inserted by Archer, the House's
chief tax writer.
</P>
<P>
   That item would roll back from 18 months to a year the amount of
time an investor must hold onto a stock or other investment in
order to receive more favorable tax treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which had insisted on increasing the capital
gains holding time during negotiations on last year's tax cut plan,
has said it will not oppose the IRS bill because of that one issue.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS bill also includes a highly controversial provision that
grants a $200,000 tax credit to individuals inheriting estates
worth $17.2 million or more. Wealthy heirs received that hefty tax
break because of what numerous administration and congressional
sources described as a technical error in last year's tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Archer opposed administration efforts to revise that
provision, arguing that such a change now would amount to a tax
increase.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the bill, which is expected to cost the government
$13 billion over 10 years, lawmakers have decided to change the
rules governing who can convert an individual retirement account
into the new, more flexible Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes will raise money to pay for the bill in the first
few years, since IRA holders must pay taxes when transferring their
funds to a Roth IRA. But critics complain that provision will end
up costing the government billions of dollars in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
