<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-DEADLY-ATTACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY KILLED, SISTER INJURED IN HOME INVASION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KIEHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 7-year-old boy was killed and his 3-year-old sister injured
early Thursday by masked men who broke into their Windsor, Conn.,
home and held their mother hostage, according to the children's
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Police called to the home at 2:30 a.m. found Jarrell and Lindsey
Cuyler with their throats slashed.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was pronounced dead at the scene. The girl was listed in
stable condition at Hartford Hospital Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the attack did not appear to be random, but they
had no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor Police Captain Peter McDermott said the children's
mother, Tammi Cuyler, 30, spent about seven hours at the poilice
station Thursday and had been ``very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott said the house and neighborhood were still being
searched for evidence late Thursday, but so far ``we really haven't
uncovered anything significant that leads us anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody at this point is a suspect,'' said McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they did not anticipate making any arrests last
night.
</P>
<P>
   The children's mother told her mother, Karen Armstrong of
Bloomfield, that she heard a noise at one of the doors in the house
and investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Two masked men then entered the home and, while one held Cuyler
down, the other went into the children's bedroom, said Armstrong,
the children's grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyler heard her son Jarrell say, ``What are you doing?'' and
then she heard Lindsey scream, Armstrong said Cuyler told her.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyler said she then began to scream and stuggle with the man
holding her and the men left at that time, the grandmother said.
She also said her daughter told her she had ripped away a glove and
a watch from one of the attackers as he fled.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyler's 18-month-old nephew was also in the house, but he was
not injured.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyler is a supervisor at the state Department of Children and
Families. Her husband and the father of Jarrell and Lindsey, Arnold
Cuyler of Bristol, is a banker. They are seperated.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuylers had lived at their Lovell Avenue home about a year,
said Jeannette Canuel, who lives next door to the Cuylers. Canuel
said she woke up to go to the bathroom about 2 a.m. Thursday, but
did not hear anything unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Although Canuel, 83, said she did not talk to Cuyler often, she
thought she was a good mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell she loved those kids,'' said Canuel. ``I would
never think anything wrong of her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
