<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8251 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHIPYARDS-LABOR-2TAKE     07-09 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIPYARDS-LABOR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION ORGANIZATION DRIVE EXPOSES FLAWS IN NATION'S LABOR LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.) (sw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Five years ago, the workers at Avondale shipyard
voted to join a union, with hundreds of them cheering wildly
outside the company's headquarters along the Mississippi when the
vote count was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is still no union at the shipyard. The 50,000 pages
of documents _ furious charges and countercharges _ stacked in the
offices of the National Labor Relations Board are evidence of what
took place instead: one of the longest, most heavily litigated
unionization fights in the board's history. At a time when labor
unions nationwide are stepping up efforts to organize millions of
workers, labor leaders and even some government officials point to
the Avondale battle as proof that the nation's labor laws are
cumbersome and replete with loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   National union leaders assert that the laws encourage Avondale
and other companies to dismiss union supporters and use other
illegal tactics to beat back organizing drives because it can take
five years or more before the courts order an employer to accept a
union. By that time, some organizing efforts have died.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials, acknowledging the problem, say scores of
cases are caught up in this legal limbo, as companies file appeal
after appeal. These include Overnite Trucking, which is fighting a
Teamsters' organizing drive at its terminals nationwide, and the
Santa Fe Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas, which has litigated for
five years against a hotel workers' election victory.
</P>
<P>
   Many Avondale workers say they desperately need a union to raise
wages at the lowest-paying major shipyard in the nation and to end
Avondale's unusually high rate of fatal accidents. According to the
union, at least 29 workers have died in accidents since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   These unhappy factors, the workers say, explain why they voted
1,954 to 1,632 in June 1993 to join the New Orleans Metal Trades
Council, notwithstanding Avondale's intense anti-union campaign.
The labor board officially certified the Metal Trades Council as
the union for the Avondale workers, which would normally bring
negotiations for a labor contract. Instead, Avondale refused to
recognize the union or bargain with it and began its appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process to put a union in takes too long,'' said Harry Lee
Thompson, a pipefitter who began working at Avondale in 1969, after
returning from Vietnam. ``Five years is too much. It's a slap in
the face of the working man.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Feinstein, the labor board's general counsel, said the
Avondale case had exposed many weak links in the system. He
acknowledged that the mountain of papers and months of hearings had
taxed the board's staff to the hilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to take issue with the notion that it's frustrating
that an election that took place five years ago still hasn't come
to conclusion,'' Feinstein said. ``It's something we're looking at
as an example of the process not being what it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Avondale case, a judge with the National Labor Relations
Board found that in the company's zeal to keep the union out, it
had violated the law more than 70 times, dismissing, for example,
28 workers because they supported the union. Even though those
workers were dismissed four or more years ago, none of them have
been reinstated because Avondale is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Defending its lengthy legal maneuvering, Avondale Industries,
the nation's largest nonunion shipbulder, asserts that the vote for
the union was tainted by fraud. Avondale, which beat back
organizing drives in decades past, insists that unionization would
hurt it by pushing up production costs and causing it to lose
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a new campaign to show that stubborn employers can
make a mockery out of the right to organize, the AFL-CIO is
pointing to Avondale as the nation's leading corporate outlaw for
the way it has kept unionization efforts at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Avondale struggle is important because it's a group of
workers who have tried so hard for so long to form a union, and
they've had everything thrown in their way,'' said John Sweeney,
president of the AFL-CIO. ``We're seeing the rule of labor law
becoming the rule of hypocrisy _ corporations that pretend to be
upstanding citizens and live off taxpayer money violate fundamental
laws that are supposed to protect workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Avondale workers point to what they view as an unfortunate
contradiction. Officials from one federal agency _ the labor board
_ found Avondale guilty of ``egregious misconduct'' and ``an
outrageous and pervasive number'' of labor law violations. Yet
those at another federal department _ the Navy _ recently awarded
Avondale a $685 million contract to build amphibious assault craft,
with the possibility of $5 billion more.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Avondale workers often say they need a union to get fair wages
and fair treatment at the shipyard, which looks like a giant
erector set in the shadow of the Huey P. Long Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Wages range from $8 an hour for the least-skilled workers
($16,600 a year) to $13.50 an hour ($28,000 a year) for welders and
pipefitters, including those with 25 years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   At the Ingalls shipyard in neighboring Mississippi, the top pay
rate is $2 an hour higher, while at the Bath Iron Works
shipbuilding concern in Maine, top pay is $3.50 more, or 26 percent
higher. Both are unionized.
</P>
<P>
   Avondale's pensions are also low. Retirees with 30 years'
experience often receive $300 a month. And many workers complain
that they cannot afford Avondale's family health insurance, which
costs them almost $2,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Another big worry is safety. According to the most recent
federal statistics, 12 Avondale workers died in accidents from 1982
to 1994, often from falls or having large pieces of metal crash
down on them. That's twice the number at the shipyards with the
second largest number of deaths, Tampa Bay Ship Building, in
Florida, and National Steel and Shipbuilding, in San Diego. And
Avondale's death toll is more e than double the number at its
larger competitors, Ingalls and Newport News.
</P>
<P>
   Avondale officials say they have improved their record, noting
that there have been no deaths since 1994. In a statement,
Avondale, the largest private employer in the New Orleans region,
said it has ``an excellent safety record relative to the rest of
the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Pyburn Jr., an Avondale lawyer, maintained that the labor
board's tortoise-like pace, and not the shipbuilder, had caused the
years of delay. Repeated appeals are justified, he said, because
the company believes that the labor board failed to properly
oversee the election and that the unionization vote was fraudulent
for numerous reasons, including that some voters failed to show
identification.
</P>
<P>
   Many union supporters argue that the labor board needs to act
faster and that unions should be installed quickly after winning an
election, just as political candidates are. If the labor board or
courts overturn the election, national union officials say, then
the union should be removed.
</P>
<P>
   For many workers, the dispute is not about abstruse legal
issues, but bread-and-butter ones. Avondale, the home of the
shipyard, and other communities around the port are hardly
prosperous, with the area replete with dilapidated one-story houses
and aging pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Pyburn defended Avondale's wage levels, saying they are the
highest of any shipyard in the area. But many Avondale workers say
they have relatives at nearby shipyards who earn more than
Avondale's top rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sweatshop, with such low wages,'' said Mike Boudreaux,
a mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a labor board judge found that Avondale intimidated
employees so systematically that he ordered an unusual remedy. In
addition to reinstating illegally dismissed workers, the judge,
David Evans, ordered Avondale's chairman, Albert L. Bossier Jr., to
read a statement _ or stand alongside a board official who read a
statement _ to the shipyard's 5,300 workers, cataloguing its labor
law violations and pledging to end such practices.
</P>
<P>
   Evans ruled that Avondale had sought to suppress the union by
punishing dozens of workers because they supported the union.
Federal labor law bars managers from retaliating against union
supporters. Evans found that Avondale had acted illegally in
discharging the 28 pro-union workers, suspending 5 others, issuing
18 warning notices, denying benefits to 8 employees and assigning
``onerous'' work to 8 others.
</P>
<P>
   Pyburn said the workers were disciplined for valid reasons, like
leaving work stations without permission.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal labor law, administrative law judges make the
initial decisions in labor dispute, and those decisions can then be
appealed to the full labor board and after that to a U.S. Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   If the labor board rules against Avondale on its appeal
regarding the dismissals and discipline, the shipyard could appeal
to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, where it has already
appealed the ruling upholding the election. The company can also
appeal to the Supreme Court. These appeals could take at least
another year, meaning that workers dismissed in 1993 might not have
a chance at reinstatement until 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, union supporters nationwide say it is fruitless to
look to the labor board and courts for redress. Instead, many
Avondale workers are rallying behind a campaign that aims to
pressure Avondale to recognize the union. They are demonstrating
outside the shipyard, getting dozens of clergymen to denounce
Avondale and urging the Navy to take a tougher stance toward
Avondale.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, the Vietnam War veteran, said: ``A foreman once said
to me, `Why are you passing out handbills for the union? You're one
of the top-paid people and you're going to retire soon.' I said,
`Maybe one day my son or relative will want to come out here. I
want them to get a fair shake on wages and benefits. I want them to
be treated better than I'm treated.' If someone doesn't stand up
for something, then where will we be?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
