<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ATHLETICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURKETT, RANGERS DOWN ATHLETICS, 4-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Warren Spahn and Johnny Sain do not pitch for
the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spahn and Sain and pray for rain'' might have been a snappy
slogan for the 1948 pennant-winning Boston Braves. But 50 years
later, the Rangers found out in the first half they won't win
anything with only Rick Helling and Aaron Sele pitching well.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers need more. They need what John Burkett gave them
yesterday and they need to win games like they did yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett stopped the Oakland Athletics on one run through eight
innings before the Rangers broke through with three in the ninth
for a 4-1 victory yesterday at Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to win a low-scoring ballgame,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``We've won a lot of games when we scored a lot
of runs, but we haven't won too many where our pitcher pitched well
and the other pitcher pitched well. We need to win games like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, who was 4-9 with a 5.95 earned-run average in the first
half, out-dueled Oakland starter Kenny Rogers, who also allowed
only one run _ a homer by Mike Simms _ through eight innings. The
Rangers scored three in the ninth against Oakland reliever Billy
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``John and Darren Oliver are a big part of our season,'' Oates
said. ``You hope Aaron Sele and Rick Helling keep pitching the way
they have, but they're going to need some help. John Burkett could
be one of those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would prefer it be Burkett and Oliver, rather than
have general manager Doug Melvin give up valuable minor-league
prospects for Reds pitcher Pete Harnisch or somebody else. But
Burkett was 0-4 with a 5.14 ERA in his past five start before
yesterday's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My location was really good today,'' Burkett said. ``I've had
a couple of good games lately, but today I was able to piece
together the best parts of my game. I used my fastball a lot, which
is a pretty good sign. When I'm able to establish my fastball and
get it low, that usually means I'm going to have a pretty good
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett got one break in the first inning after Rickey Henderson
led off with a single. Bip Roberts followed with a blistering line
drive, but right at first baseman Will Clark, who caught it and
stepped on the bag to double off Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett got another break in the sixth when Henderson, after a
run-scoring single, tried to steal third base with two outs and was
thrown out by catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to steal third with two outs usually goes against
baseball common sense, especially with an All-Star like Ben Grieve
at the plate. But Henderson said he believed he had the Rangers'
signs. He expected Burkett to throw a changeup, instead the Rangers
had changed the signs and Burkett threw a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready,'' Rodriguez said. ``You've got to pay attention
to the runners all of the time, and he's a good runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Burkett: ``With Pudge behind the plate, most of the time
I'm hoping they run. Rickey Henderson is no exception.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Burkett was in control, holding the Athletics
to four hits. He did not walk a batter and struck out five. But the
effort was almost wasted until the ninth, when Tom Goodwin's
pinch-hit single led the way to a three-run rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely the way to start the second half,'' Clark
said. ``Get a well-pitched ballgame and find a way to win late in
the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
