A8260 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-DEATH-370&AMP;ADD-NY     07-09 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-DEATH-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG PARENTS SENTENCED IN DEATH OF NEWBORN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., N.J.)   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Denouncing Amy Grossberg as an egocentric
indifferent to the value of the life of her newborn son, a Delaware
judge sentenced her Thursday to 30 months in prison for
contributing to the baby's death in November 1996. Minutes later,
Judge Henry duPont Ridgely issued a far gentler scolding to Miss
Grossberg's co-defendant and former high school sweetheart, Brian
Peterson, and gave him a two-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to receiving the longer sentence, Miss Grossberg was
depicted by two Delaware prosecutors as the principal culprit in
the death and portrayed in a far harsher light than Peterson during
an emotional three-hour court session in Delaware Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Grossberg sobbed as she pleaded for leniency, telling the
judge she accepted full blame for the death: ``I'll never be able
to forgive myself for what has happened. It's something I'll never
be able to forget.'' She cried again as guards led her away to
prison, a day before her 20th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson listened to Miss Grossberg's appeal in tears, but later
regained his composure in a 10-second statement to the judge. ``All
I can say is I'm sorry for what happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Grossberg's lawyer, Robert Tanenbaum, renewed old arguments
that the baby was still-born and the fractures in his head did not
contribute to the death. The infant was found in a Dumpster behind
a motel in Newark, Del. Prosecutors argued insisted that the
fractures were a cause of death. But they conceded they could not
prove that the fractures had been deliberately inflicted, or who
had caused them.
</P>
<P>
   This helped explain why they retreated from their
headline-grabbing talk of late 1996 about seeking the death penalty
against the Wyckoff, N.J., couple and allowed them to plead guilty
to manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the denunciations of Miss Grossberg for hiding her
pregnancy, the hearing included new disclosures about futile
appeals by Peterson to convince Miss Grossberg to get either
medical help or an abortion in the weeks before their fateful trip
to the motel near Miss Grossberg's dormitory on Nov. 12, 1996. In
addition, he urged her to go to a hospital instead of the motel,
his lawyer said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Peter Letang called Miss Grossberg
cavalier and self-absorbed in her refusal to tell her parents or
friends about the pregnancy and her threats to commit suicide if
Peterson violated her secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy Grossberg sacrificed that baby to hide the truth,'' Letang
told Ridgely. ``Her secret was more important to her than the life
of that child. Grossberg did not want this baby.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore his argument, Letang quoted in open court from
four letters Miss Grossberg wrote Peterson at the start of their
freshman years in college nearly two years ago. In one, the
prosecutor said, she wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want is for it to go away.'' The ``it,'' Letang said,
referred to the fetus. Some of the letters carried what Letang
described as the salutation, ``Baby Dumps.''
</P>
<P>
   The other prosecutor, Deputy Attorney General Paul Wallace,
called her cold-hearted and cruel and said she feared disclosure of
the pregnancy would lead to loss of both her parents' respect and
her years of college at the University of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the threat she saw in her own son,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the prosecutors depicted Peterson, now 20
years old, as enraptured with his girlfriend and loyal to her and
her demand for silence. Letang characterized Peterson's attitude as
both chivalrous and stupid.
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal to the judge to give Peterson a more lenient
sentence, partly for cooperating with investigators after pleading
guilty last March, Letang noted that Peterson had urged Miss
Grossberg to seek prenatal care or an abortion, and to go to a
hospital instead of the motel.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, Letang said, Peterson acquiesced in Miss
Grossberg's insistence on keeping the pregnancy secret. Letang told
Ridgely he once asked Peterson why he did not tell her parents
about the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   He said Peterson told him he did not want to violate Miss
Grossberg's trust. He quoted the youth as saying, ``It's not my
body, it's her body.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanenbaum argued in court that Miss Grossberg suffered a seizure
during childbirth and thought the baby was born dead. He denounced
the prosecutors for ``unfairly attempting to demonize and
dehumanize her.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanenbaum said his client had planned to inform her parents of
the pregnancy during the Thanksgiving recess. He insisted she did
not know she was pregnant until August 1996. Prosecutors said,
however, that Peterson knew in April or May. Tanenbaum did not
explain what Miss Grossberg planned to do after informing her
parents.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference after sentencing, Tanenbaum called the
case tragic and insisted again that his client had no intention of
ever harming the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she rejected Peterson's appeals to go to a hospital,
Tanenbaum said: ``The kids panicked. They made a mistake and that's
why she pleaded. She should have gone to a hospital. Isn't it nice
to have hindsight? Keep in mind, she was an 18-year-old and made a
mistake and she's paying the price for the rest of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of Miss Grossberg's lawyers, John Malik, pointed out
that both teens were involved. ``They each had opportunities at
different times to stop this. They didn't exercise good judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Malik said she should have told her parents, a rabbi, a friend,
or a counselor about the pregnancy. Asked why she chose not to, he
said, ``She put a premium on being the perfect daughter and she
thought this would be a disappointment to her family.''
</P>
<P>
   In their defense of Peterson, his lawyers, Jack Litman and
Russell Gioiella said he broke the law by not seeking medical help
for the baby after the birth or getting independent verification of
his belief the child was born dead. They also said he exercised bad
judgment by not driving to a hospital instead of the motel before
the birth.
</P>
<P>
   Gioiella said his client ``succumbed to her desire to control,''
adding, ``His feeling for Amy overwhelmed his judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridgely was succinct in his sentencing rulings. He said both
came from exemplary families and had excellent backgrounds prior to
the birth.
</P>
<P>
   Of Miss Grossberg, the judge said, ``If there's a disturbing
aspect to your character, an unsettling trait as the time of
childbirth neared, it was an egocentricity that blinded you to the
need to seek help and to the intrinsic value of the life of the
child.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he told Peterson he considered his remorse sincere and
praised him for urging Miss Grossberg to seek prenatal counseling.
But, he criticized Peterson for not revealing Miss Grossberg's
pregnancy. In addition, the judge said, ``As this child's father,
you should have protected him from an unassisted birth.''
</P>
<P>
   The two faced a maximum of 10 years each on their manslaughter
pleas.
</P>
<P>
   After sentencing Miss Grossberg to 30 months and Peterson to 24,
he gave her credit for 64 days already served in jail and him 61
days. He also imposed 5 years of probation on Miss Grossberg and 2
on Peterson. Both must also perform 300 hours of community service
after prison, including working in clinics for pregnant teen-agers
and counseling teens on parenthood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
