<SLUG> BC-WORLD-COURT-U.S.-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CALLS FOR SHARP LIMITS ON WORLD CRIMINAL COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain, Canada, Germany)  (mk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The United States set out new conditions Thursday for
taking part in an international criminal court, calling for sharp
limits on its scope and authority.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has long made clear its opposition to an independent
tribunal with broad powers to investigate war crimes suspects
across the globe. But for the first time since the 161-nation
conference began here on June 15, the United States specified where
it stood on the limits of the court's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   The United States said it could agree to the court only if its
automatic jurisdiction were limited to genocide, which it views as
the worst outrage. And the American delegation insisted that the
court should have automatic jurisdiction only if the suspect's
country signed the treaty setting up the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Washington opposed automatic jurisdiction for crimes against
humanity or such war crimes as rape and torture. For these, under
the American proposal, the court could bring charges only in those
countries that grant jurisdiction, by opting to be included.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's statement underscored how strongly the United States
opposes the kind of court sought by human rights groups and many
democratic allies, and points out how the battle lines will be
drawn as the U.N. conference moves into its final and most
contentious week.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's primary objection is that American soldiers might
be vulnerable to politically motivated charges. The Pentagon
worries that American soldiers who unwittingly kill civilians
during a peacekeeping operation could find themselves facing
charges of crimes against humanity before a court packed with Iraqi
judges.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's statement made many delegates conclude that they may
end up designing a court that would be rejected by the world's
largest superpower. In explaining Washington's position, David
Scheffer, head of the American delegation, said: ``Automatic
jurisdiction over all of the core crimes might satisfy the most
optimistic requirements of theory. But it is a recipe for limited
participation in the court, and in the result, an ineffective
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We constantly have troops serving abroad on humanitarian
missions, rescue operations or missions to destroy weapons of mass
destruction. Someone out there isn't going to like it, but we are
the ones who do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups argue that by seeking 100 percent protection
of its citizens, the United States is granting immunity to some of
the world's most loathsome dictators and war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the American concern, but the loopholes it is
creating to protect American citizens are the same ones that would
allow rogue countries to shield themselves,'' said Jelena Pejic,
head of a delegation from the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights'
here.
</P>
<P>
   The American effort to limit the court's jurisdiction has
support from key partners in the U.N. Security Council, like France
and Russia, but it was deeply discouraging to many Western allies
who have been battling for a powerful and independent court.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 countries, including Britain, Canada and Germany,
oppose the U.S. position and insist that the court should have
broad powers to prosecute crimes against humanity and war crimes,
even against suspects whose countries have not signed the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much political prestige has been invested in creating a
truly independent court,'' a Western European delegate said. ``It
will be slim and weak without the United States, but I see no
further room for negotiation whatsoever.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States, however, is gambling that as the conference
reaches its end on July 17, many countries will bend rather than
draft a treaty that the United States and other powerful nations
refuse to sign. ``They have a court within their grasp,'' Scheffer
said. ``But they must be reasonable about the limitations of this
court.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If they seek to extend the court's jurisdiction over
states that have not signed the treaty, they will generate an
enormous amount of conflict in international relations.''
</P>
<P>
   There already is an enormous amount of conflict at the
conference. The United States entered the negotiations arguing that
the U.N. Security Council should have primary responsibility for
initiating any investigation by the court's prosecutors. That would
be a permanent version of the Security Council-sponsored ad hoc
tribunals that are now trying accused war criminals from the
Balkans and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of nations vehemently oppose that position, arguing that
the prosecutor should have authority to bring cases without the
Security Council's consent. Many Third World countries, which see a
neocolonial bent at the Security Council, also oppose giving it so
prominent a role.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations lost that battle. In a discussion paper
earlier this week, the conference's organizing committee omitted
the American option of assigning the Security Council primary
responsibility for initiating cases. Instead, the document offered
a watered-down version preferred by a majority at the conference,
allowing the Security Council to intervene and postpone a trial for
12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The United States accepted that defeat, but moved to tighten the
conditions in which the court can operate. In most crimes, the
United States would require the court to secure the consent of a
suspected war criminal's country. Human rights groups argue that
state-consent provisions are tantamount to giving President Saddam
Hussein of Iraq a veto over his own trial, but the United States
says it is the only way to win widespread cooperation for such a
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   In the American proposal, if the court wanted to try a suspect
for genocide, and the suspect's state refused to cooperate, further
action would require that the Security Council override that
country's objections. But any permanent member could veto the
Security Council's intervention.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also recommended that countries that sign the
treaty be allowed to choose whether they permit the court to
prosecute war crimes or crimes against humanity against one of
their citizens; this is known as an opt-in choice. Many Arab and
nonaligned states support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is more desirable in the early years of the
court to bring in as many states into its jurisdiction as
possible,'' Scheffer argued. ``Far too many countries would not
sign up unless there was such a provision.'' Others countries are
dismissive. ``The treaty is not a Chinese banquet,'' said Elizabeth
Wilmshurst, deputy leader of the British delegation. ``If you
become a party, then you must accept the court's jurisdiction in
all core crimes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
