<HEADLINE>
DIVER'S BODY RECOVERED FROM ANDREA DORIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Mich.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A veteran diver was found dead Thursday, floating face down 200
feet below the surface in the first-class bar lounge of the rotting
Andrea Doria, a luxury liner that continues to lure people to death
42 years after she sank off the coast of Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Roost, 46, of Ann Arbor, Mich., a sheriff's department
diver who has been searching the depths of the ocean for more than
20 years, is the latest victim to die searching the 697-foot
Italian luxury liner.
</P>
<P>
   On June 28, Craig Sicola of New Jersey died shortly after
resurfacing from a dive. The cause of death: too much nitrogen in
his system. In July 1993, Robert Santulli of Long Island died
searching the wreckage. In July, 1992, a Florida diver, Mathew
Jared Lawrence, died inside the Andrea Doria.
</P>
<P>
   ``This incident is another tragic example of the dangers
associated with recreational deep water diving,'' said Rear Admiral
Richard M. Larrabee of the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Roost had chartered The Seeker, a commerical diving boat out of
Montauk, Long Island. From the boat, Roost dove into the shimmering
waters just before noon Wednesday _ a challenging dive Roost wanted
to conquer.
</P>
<P>
   At about 200 feet the water is darker than night. When Roost
failed to return to decompress from being under heavy water
pressure, about two hours later, the crew of the Seeker became
worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only stay in the water, at that depth, about 20
minutes,'' said Lt. Junior Grade Craig Jaramillo, assistant
operations officer of the Coast Guard Group at Woods Hole. Swimming
to the surface of the water would take Andrea Doria explorers about
an hour, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard searched the area with Jayhawk helicopters
Wednesday night and Thursday morning, hoping he was alive, floating
on the choppy waters. When they didn't find him, it became clear
that Roost had died.
</P>
<P>
   Seeker diving crews found Roost on their seventh dive search at
about 1:30 p.m. Thursday, and headed to Montauk, to bring his body
to a Long Island medical examiner for an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo said the cause of death is unclear. Roost had not
gotten tangled or trapped inside the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Roost had wanted for some time to conquer the shipwreck, said
Mike Graczyk, general manager of the Divers Inc. store in Novi,
Mich. Roost had owned that store and another, Divers Inc. in Ann
Arbor, for the last 16 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of his goal dives. That's the dive that he wanted
to do,'' Graczyk said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
