<HEADLINE>
FORMER AU PAIR DEFAULTS ON WRONGFUL DEATH DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Former British au pair Louise Woodward has allowed the
deadline to pass for contesting the wrongful death suit filed
against her by the parents of eight-month-old Matthew Eappen, the
infant fatallly injured while in her care.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's failure to challenge the suit within 20 days of its
filing means that, under court rules, she has waived her right to a
trial.
</P>
<P>
   If Woodward does not seek a special dispensation for more time
to file a response, Judge William G. Young will declare her
responsible for the child's death and determine how much she should
pay the Eappens in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Legal specialists speculated Thursday that Woodward is not
contesting the suit either because she lacks funds for a lawyer,
believes a defense would be fruitless, or is confident that any
judgment against her would be uncollectable in England.
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens' lawyer, Fredric L. Ellis, said Woodward's lack of a
defense is tantamount to admitting responsibility for Matthew's
death. He said he is unsure how much money he will request in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Collins, a close friend of the Woodward family in England,
said Thursday that the 20-year-old former au pair continues to
disclaim any responsibility for the child's death, and views the
default as ``a purely legal technicality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just going to ride it out because she hasn't got enough
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins also said Woodward would not respond to the Eappens's
contention that her default is an admission of guilt, saying it was
merely a ``sensational'' statement on their lawyer's part.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward returned home to England last month after the Supreme
Judicial Court upheld her manslaughter conviction and 279-day
sentence in the Newton, Mass. boy's death.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's English solicitor, Paul Barrow of Liverpool, also
said Woodward is abandoning her civil defense for lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got no money,'' Barrow said. ``It's as simple as that.
There's no hidden agenda. There's no other reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Woodward would represent herself in future legal
proceedings, Barrow said: ``I can't discuss a client's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather that fight the case in the United States, Woodward may
decide to concentrate on opposing efforts to collect a judgment
from a US court in England, legal observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, the Eappens's attorney, Thursday insisted that ``there
was no clear answer'' to whether any award would be collectable in
England.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrew Miller, a member of Parliment from Woodward's
hometown of Elton, said, ``A judgment may be made against her but
it's unenforceable. She's not in the US and she's not under their
jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ellis is hopeful. He asked Young to schedule a hearing Oct.
5 to assess damages against Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Ellis said, he will seek to determine the
extent of Woodward's assets, including whether she has signed any
book or movie deals.
</P>
<P>
   He said the purpose of the suit is to prevent Woodward from
profiting from Matthew's death. The Eappens have said that any
award that is recovered will be donated to a foundation they set up
to fight child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But getting information from Woodward in England may be
difficult. To do so, Ellis would have to seek her deposition
through a complicated procedure set out under The Hague convention
dealing with international law.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward and her parents have long insisted that her story was
not for sale. She said she has turned down six-figure offers, and
proclaimed, ``I have no intention of profiting from this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   But last month the Daily Mail, a British tabloid, admitted it
had paid Woodward's parents $60,000 for an interview last November.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning to England, Woodward's most highly publicized
interview was with the BBC, for which she was not paid.
</P>
<P>
   Young has already frozen Woodward's assets in the United States
so that any money would be available to pay an award. He issued an
injunciton last month that prohibits her from spending any money
she gets for her story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
