<SLUG> BC-PROSECUTOR-DEALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT TO APPEAL LENIENCY RULING IN CRIMINAL CASES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department will appeal a federal court
decision that outlaws in six states the long-standing practice of
U.S. prosecutors going easy on suspects who cooperate in criminal
investigations, Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr. said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled July 1 that federal
prosecutors violate U.S. law when they promise criminals and
suspects leniency if they assist in the prosecution of a case. A
unanimous three-judge panel said a federal law barring prosecutors
from giving, offering or promising ``anything of value'' in return
for testimony includes pledges of lighter prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The department maintains the decision, which applies to the
Rocky Mountains region, runs counter to both what Congress intended
and what justice requires. A prosecutor, who must often turn to
convicts and suspects for their first-hand knowledge of criminal
activity, would have difficulty getting necessary testimony if
leniency could not be offered, the agency argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are obviously concerned about the opinion,'' Holder said.
``It goes to the way in which prosecutors at the federal, state and
local levels have conducted themselves for a good number of years.
... If the decision is read very, very broadly, it could have a
very wide-ranging impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said the department will ask all 12 judges on the 10th
Circuit to review the panel's decision. The Denver-based 10th
Circuit covers Colorado, Kansas, New Mexico, Oklahoma, Utah and
Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the court threw out the drug conspiracy and
money laundering convictions of Sonya Singleton, saying federal
prosecutors illegally offered leniency to conspirator Napoleon
Douglas in return for his testimony against Singleton. The
government promised Douglas it would not prosecute him for any
other violations of federal drug law and would urge the sentencing
judge and parole board to take his cooperation into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious purpose of the government's promised actions was
to reduce his jail time, and it is difficult to imagine anything
more valuable than personal physical freedom,'' Judge Paul J. Kelly
Jr. wrote for the three-member panel. ``The government may still
make deals with accomplices for their assistance other than
testimony, and it may still put accomplices on the stand; it simply
may not attach any promise, offer or gift to their testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   The two other judges on the panel were David M. Ebel and
Stephanie K. Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   The court's controversial decision brings into question the
convictions of Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh and his fellow
conspirator Terry Nichols, verdicts that were reached in large part
due to the testimony of Michael Fortier.
</P>
<P>
   Fortier, who knew of the plan to bomb the Alfred P. Murrah
Federal Building but failed to tell authorities, testified only
after receiving promises of leniency from federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Fortier faced a maximum penalty of 17 years in prison for
failing to tell the police, lying to the Federal Bureau of
Investigation, hiding evidence and trafficking in guns, but he was
sentenced to only 12 years due to his cooperation with prosecutors.
McVeigh was sentenced to death for the April 19, 1995, bombing,
which killed 168 people. Nichols was sentenced to life in prison
for conspiracy and manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th Circuit will hear the appeals of McVeigh and Nichols,
who were convicted in the U.S. District Court in Denver. Holder
said it is difficult to predict how the decision, if upheld on
appeal, would affect the bombing verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you look at the opinion and you can see some
problems that might crop up'' for prosecutors, he said. ``But any
opinion has to be looked at in light of the specific facts of the
case that you are considering. So it's hard to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said the Justice Department will monitor any court
motions defense attorneys might bring on behalf of their clients in
light of the 10th Circuit's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kent Schaffer of Houston, president of the Texas
Criminal Defense Lawyers Association, hailed the 10th Circuit's
decision for bringing equity to criminal trials. The appeals court
said it is no more legal for prosecutors to reward witnesses with a
lighter prison sentence than it is for defense counsel to pay
people cash for their testimony, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one commodity more precious than money is liberty,''
Schaffer added. ``Liberty is a much stronger motivating force than
money for somebody in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
