<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-LADN     07-09 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAMPEDE OF PROSPECTS FOR '98 TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Starting the second half of the year, racing wears
an uncommonly rosy, healthy glow. We're talking not about the
industry but about the horses.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of keeping star horses sound, active and
marketable has been chronicled ad nauseum, so when the best-known
runners in the country stick around for more than a few months, the
phenomenon deserves to be mentioned. That, knock on wood, is what's
happening, giving fans a familiar cast of characters to argue about
as the race for Horse of the Year and division championships hits
the far turn.
</P>
<P>
   Not only new faces such as Real Quiet, Victory Gallop and Fiji
are training for big summer races, but so are the stars of 1997,
the winners of the Kentucky Derby and Preakness (Silver Charm), the
Belmont Stakes (Touch Gold), the Breeders' Cup Classic (Skip Away)
and the Horse of the Year title (Favorite Trick).
</P>
<P>
   It's only the second time in the Breeders' Cup era that the
winners of all those races have been active this late in the
following year. The other time was 10 years ago, when Alysheba
(Derby and Preakness), Bet Twice (Belmont) and Ferdinand (Classic
and Horse of the Year) were still going, although Ferdinand was on
his way to a 0-for-6 season.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the '98 Horse of the Year contenders, with
estimated odds and a campaign strategy for each:
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away (6-5): Exhausted after the Hollywood Gold Cup victory
that solidified his No. 1 ranking, he'll pass up the Aug. 15
Pacific Classic at Del Mar to concentrate on the eastern races,
beginning with the Aug. 8 Whitney at Saratoga or the Aug. 30 Iselin
at Monmouth Park. If he holds form, he'll keep winning through the
Sept. 19 Woodward and Oct. 10 Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park,
and not even a loss in the Nov. 7 Breeders' Cup Classic at
Churchill Downs will dissuade the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm (3-1): He beat the world in Dubai, but he must
prove his connections aren't dodging Skip Away here at home. If
he'd run in the Gold Cup, he would have been the consensus third
choice and might well have finished fourth. He'll use the July 25
San Diego at Del Mar to prep for a Pacific Classic showdown with
Gentlemen for West Coast preeminence.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet (6-1): By the width of this column, he missed the
Triple Crown, which would have guaranteed him Horse of the Year.
Because of an unspecified training setback, he'll miss the July 19
Swaps at Hollywood Park to face Victory Gallop again in the Aug. 9
Haskell at Monmouth. But forget those 3-year-old races; he'll have
to step up and beat older horses to have a shot at the big prize.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop (8-1): Handicapper Jerry Brown, founder of the
Thoro-Graph sheets, notes that the Belmont winner shows the same
speed-figures progression that Skip Away had as a 3-year-old. Brown
has a lot of company in thinking Victory Gallop will accomplish
more than Real Quiet in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Touch Gold (15-1): A late start to the season could be a curse
or a blessing. His allowance comebacker at Churchill set him up for
the Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji (20-1): The 4-year-old is the only distaffer in our top 10,
and she could pick up the electoral pieces if the boys beat up on
each other. But the turf filly has nowhere to run in the Breeders'
Cup, so she'll have to keep dominating races the way she did at
Santa Anita. Trainer Neil Drysdale is aiming for the Aug. 1 Ramona
at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   Any 2-year-old (40-1): Favorite Trick set a high standard: A
2-year-old has to go undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Bearhart (50-1): The reigning turf champion looked great
winning the Manhattan on the Belmont undercard. He'll run in the
Bowling Green at Belmont on Saturday and shoot for a repeat in the
1{-mile Breeders' Cup Turf. A rarity: Six of the seven '97
Breeders' Cup winners are still active.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen (75-1): Californians' Horse of the Year pick last
year, third in the Gold Cup won by Skip Away, needs to win a
rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick (100-1): A 3-year-old who can't go 1\ miles races
a rocky road to Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: The return of Free House, in the Bel Air Handicap
at Hollywood Park on Saturday, adds to the list of familiar faces.
The '97 Santa Anita Derby winner, an in-the-money finisher in all
three Triple Crown races, hasn't raced since the Super Derby at
Louisiana Downs in September.
</P>
<P>
   He looked sensational in a paddock schooling session Thursday
and will be favored over Wild Wonder and four others in the 1
1/16-mile Bel Air. He'll carry 124 pounds, including Chris
McCarron.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a lot more kind (since resuming training),'' trainer Paco
Gonzalez said. ``He used to be very tough to gallop.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Hollywood Oaks will test Manistique, who is 2 for 2
after earning a huge 110 Beyer speed figure in her debut. Gary
Stevens will ride the 3-year-old daughter of Unbridled against
Princess winner Sweet and Ready and third-place Visible Slew.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead: The last major race of the Hollywood Park meet,
the Swaps Stakes a week from Sunday, won't have Real Quiet but will
have Grand Slam, D. Wayne Lukas' barn announced.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Slam, one of the top 2-year-olds of '97, came back from a
tendon injury to win the Peter Pan and will ship west next week.
Old Trieste, Old Topper, Shot of Gold and Lord Smith are the other
Swaps probables.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion box: Hollywood Park ought to drop the hoofbeats sound
effect from its replay shows in the interest of, oh, I don't know,
not looking like complete amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   The background noise adds nothing in the way of realism, since
hoofbeats can't ordinarily be heard from the grandstand, and
certainly not when the horses are a quarter-mile away on the
backstretch. Are viewers supposed to think there are little
microphones under the rail all the way around the track?
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago some wires got crossed and the hoofbeats
went out over the track's PA system _ before the race started.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
