A8275 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     07-09 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPP ATTORNEY CLAIMS DEMOCRATIC LEGISLATORS IN MARYLAND URGED TAPE
INQUIRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of Linda Tripp's attorneys claimed Thursday a
Maryland prosecutor yielded to political pressure in launching an
inquiry into the tapes Tripp secretly made of conversations with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Anthony Zaccagnini said Maryland prosecutor Stephen
Montanarelli told Tripp's legal team that Democratic members of the
state Legislature had ``directly contacted'' him asking ``that
Linda be investigated and prosecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with NBC-TV, Zaccagnini said Montanarelli's
admission ``speaks of political motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Montanarelli's office denied the claim by
Zaccagnini. ``That's absolutely untrue,'' said Gavin Patashnick.
``This office is apolitical.''
</P>
<P>
   Patashnick said the prosecutor received ``no telephone calls or
letters urging us to investigate'' whether Tripp, a resident of
Columbia, Md., violated state law when she taped 20 hours of
Lewinsky's telephone conversations without her knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes _ in which Lewinsky reportedly discusses an 18-month
sexual affair with President Clinton and his urging her to lie
under oath about the relationship _ triggered a federal grand jury
investigation that began in January under the direction of
independent counsel Kenneth Starr. Tripp testified for a fourth day
before that grand jury Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Lewinsky have said under oath they did not
engage in sex. Clinton has publicly denied that his relationship
with Lewinsky was sexual and said he never urged her to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Montanarelli announced early this week that a Maryland grand
jury was investigating whether Tripp violated a state law making it
a felony to tape record a person's conversation without that
person's knowledge. Before Tripp could be convicted, Montanarelli
would have to prove Tripp knew the taping was illegal. If found
guilty of the anti-wiretapping law, Tripp would face five years in
prison and a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Tripp's spokesman Philip Coughter said she would
return to the federal grand jury in Washington next week. ``Despite
the events which have recently unfolded in Maryland, I continue to
focus on my testimony before the federal grand jury,'' Tripp said
in a statement read by Coughter.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating Montanarelli's inquiry in Maryland are two grants
of immunity given Tripp in return for her cooperation before
Starr's grand jury, which is investigating whether Clinton or any
of his associates obstructed justice by trying to cover-up his
alleged sexual misbehavior with Lewinsky or Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   One of Tripp's immunity deals was worked out with Starr. The
other was signed by a federal judge who relied on a law saying no
testimony or evidence received from a witness can be used against
that witness except in cases of lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever she says at the grand jury cannot be used against
her,'' said Robert Bloom, a law professor at Boston College of Law.
At the same time, Maryland prosecutors might be able to produce
other evidence through Tripp's conversations with her book agent,
longtime Clinton-hater Lucianne Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the hard piece of proof is whether Linda Tripp knew what
she was doing was illegal,'' Bloom said. ``And that's something the
agent might have discussed with her (Tripp), whether taping the
calls was illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg told The Associated Press on Thursday that she made her
own tapes of conversations with Tripp and notified her that she was
recording their calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come and get me, coppers!'' Goldberg said from her office in
New York. ``They don't want my tapes because if they get my tapes,
they have no case.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said she told Tripp in one tape that she ``checked it
out and you're OK in Maryland'' to engage in taping phone calls.
Goldberg said that Tripp's response on the tape is ``silence'' and
that Tripp then went on to a different subject of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a federal judge in Little Rock, Ark., granted a
request from Clinton's lawyers to not release documents in Paula
Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit against the president. The sworn
statements by Clinton and Lewinsky denying an affair were made as
part of the Jones case and put under seal by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which was dismissed April 1, alleges that Clinton,
while he was governor of Arkansas, summoned Jones, a state
employee, to a Little Rock hotel room in 1991 and asked her for
oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright ruled that
the Jones' case file would be made public. Clinton's lawyers
objected and Wright on Thursday said the files would remain closed
until she decided otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was made in a lawsuit brought by various news
organizations and journalism groups to open the case files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
