u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED-ARMY-MISSILE     07-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-ARMY-MISSILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON MAY LOOK BEYOND LOCKHEED FOR ANTI-MISSILE CONTRACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Defense Department said Thursday that it would
consider finding a competitor to Lockheed Martin Corp. as the prime
contractor on the Army's trouble-plagued $15 billion anti-missile
system, a project that had been seen as the forerunner of a much
larger program to shield the entire nation from missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said it decided to consider a second contractor _
and possibly, an entirely new design _ after five consecutive test
failures, the most recent in May, when an anti-missile missile
failed to hit its target over the New Mexico desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are obviously considering this as one of our potential
alternatives _ restructuring the program,'' said Lt. Gen. Lester
Lyles of the Air Force, the director of the Pentagon's Ballistic
Missile Defense Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``A second source, depending on when you do it on a program, is
not necessarily a panacea,'' he said at a news conference,
referring to an alternate contractor. ``We're examining very
closely the costs for bringing on a second source, the time it
takes to bring on a second source, whether or not you ask the
second source to do a Chinese copy _ that is, build the same
missile to print _ or to have a competing design.''
</P>
<P>
   A decision to seek an alternate contractor or another design
could delay the anti-missile system for years and would raise new
doubts about the feasibility of so-called Star Wars technology to
protect the United States from missile attack through the use of
satellites, radar and anti-missile missiles. The Pentagon is now
committed to developing such a national missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   Virnell Bruce, a spokeswoman for Lockheed, the Bethesda,
Md.-based defense contractor, said that the company understood the
Pentagon's need to ``answer all the questions that are put upon
them, to have a thorough look at the alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said that ``we've put every possible corporate
resource'' at the disposal of the Defense Department ``to insure
that this is a successful program _ we're really adamant about
that. We believe in the program, and we believe it will be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army program now under scrutiny is known as Theater
High-Altitude Area Defense, or THAAD, and it is being developed to
protect troops in the field from attack by short- and medium-range
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   It is supposed to be an improvement on the Patriot missile
system, which gained fame when it was used in the Persian Gulf War
in 1991 as a defense against Scud missiles fired by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has already spent more than $3.2 billion on the
THAAD program. The project is about four years behind schedule, and
there is little hope in the Defense Department that it will meet
its deadline to have the weapons ready for use by the Army in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the string of test failures, the program has been
harshly criticized in Congress, with prominent lawmakers calling on
the Defense Department to consider an alternative to Lockheed.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Lyles said that the Pentagon was
negotiating with Lockheed to require the company to pay for future
test failures.
</P>
<P>
   While he said there has been no decision on the exact fine that
might be imposed on the company for each failure, Lyles said that
``if we have subsequent failures, we want them to pay a significant
amount.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired, if you will, Lockheed Martin as our prime contractor
to pull these things together and to help us address all these
types of things,'' Lyles said. ``So there is culpability on the
part of the contractor.'' He continued: ``They have volunteered
willingness to support some aspects of the costs associated with
the THAAD missile tests, if we continue to have more failures.''
</P>
<P>
   In the failure in May, Defense Department officials said, the
anti-missile missile spun out of control because of a defect in a
booster rocket and crashed two miles from the launch pad at the
White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico. The test was supposed to
determine if the missile could knock down another missile while
both traveled at speeds of 11,000 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Lyles suggested the level of frustration in the Defense
Department with the program when he noted that in each of the five
tests, a different component had failed _ proof that no one repair
or redesign would end the problems.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Pentagon had abandoned plans to stage another test
next month. ``After looking at where we are in the failure analysis
and looking at some of the questions that still need to be
answered, I don't think we're going to be able to make this
summer,'' he said. ``We are looking at the fall time frame.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
