<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apple's new widens range of peripherals
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The iMac, Apple Computer Inc.'s ballyhooed economy
computer, represents a big step toward the mainstream of personal
computing for the company that prides itself on making computers
for an elite minority, industry experts said Thursday at the
Macworld Expo.
</P>
<P>
   That step is the connection for devices such as printers,
scanners and joysticks, which are known as peripherals. In using
just the Universal Serial Bus, the iMac will be able to connect to
a much wider range of peripherals than previous Macintosh models.
</P>
<P>
   By abandoning proprietary connections such as its Apple Desktop
Bus and Macintosh modem and printer ports, and switching to the USB
technology, Apple essentially allows iMac owners to buy
off-the-shelf peripherals that are made for machines from IBM, Dell
Computer Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp. The USB, technology is one
of three commonly used connections throughout the much larger
IBM-compatible industry. The others are parallel ports and serial
bus ports. USB also replaces Apple's proprietary connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``USB is an emerging industry standard,'' Apple's interim chief
executive Steve Jobs told an audience of about 3,000 Mac users
Wednesday at Macworld Expo in the Jacob Javits Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of peripherals will be available for the Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said that in the future all Macs will accommodate
only the USB technology.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of software titles available for those PCs, the
peripherals do not readily work on the Macintosh operating system.
The system incompatability and Apple's tiny 4 percent share of the
computer market have drastically limited the choices of software
and hardware available to Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   Now, because of the switch to USB connections, that hardware
incompatibility vanishes with a relatively simple software change
that allows the equipment and the Mac operating system to talk to
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that accommodates a non-specific Mac interconnect is
an improvement for Mac users,'' said Steve Dube of Wasserstein &AMP;
Pirella in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Dube also disagreed with a manager from one of Apple's key
peripheral suppliers, who said Thursday that Jobs' has taken a
major gamble by limiting iMac to only one type of connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think USB is not a wild bet for Apple,'' he said. ``That's
probably going to be a standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Apple depends on hardware companies to invest the money
on programming that will let their products work with Macintosh
machines. Mindful of that, Apple brought a dozen or so of them
together Thursday in the Jacob Javits Convention Center to talk
about their products.
</P>
<P>
   With only a few months warning about Apple's plans for USB,
Hewlett-Packard Co. rushed into production a chip-carrying adapter
so iMac customers can use any of five HP 670C- or 690C-series
Deskjet printers when the computer is shipped in the middle of
August.
</P>
<P>
   Those printers cost $199 to $249. The $79 adapter is a cable
connection between the iMac USB port and the printers' serial port,
but HP will put USB connections directly on future printers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a transition product,'' said Hugh Amick of HP. ``We plan
to come up with a printer that provides out-of-the-box
connectivity.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more talked about peripheral products at the
semi-annual Macintosh show is the SuperDisk from Imation.
</P>
<P>
   Built for the iMac and selling for $179, SuperDisk is a
floppy-disk drive with a USB connection. Imation, an Oakdale,
Minn., company that was spun off from 3M a few years ago, has high
hopes for the product because Apple's iMac has no floppy disk
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding it cut costs on the iMac, which at $1,299 already is
priced well above sub-$1,000 entry-level products from Compaq, HP
and others. Apple also justified the decision by noting that floppy
discs traditionally have been used to back up files and to transfer
work between computers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
