</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton thanks firefighters during visit
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Weary firefighters got a hearty thanks
Thursday from President Clinton, and another day of decent weather
further eased the drought-stricken state's wildfire crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important that every American knows with the
summer movies out that the real American heroes aren't up in space
fighting asteroids but are here in Florida fighting fires,''
Clinton said, drawing roaring applause from about 700 firefighters
from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spent the morning in Atlanta promoting a new
anti-drug campaign, was scheduled to attend a fund-raiser Thursday
night at the home of actor Sylvester Stallone in Miami before
returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Even as fire officials heard the praise from Clinton, they
warned that the crisis hasn't ended. Although predicted brisk west
winds did not materialize Thursday to fan the flames and most of
the blazes in the hardest-hit counties are under control, only
sustained rains will end the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is still too dry,'' Gov. Lawton Chiles told the
gathering, which took place in a tent at Daytona International
Speedway, where the fires caused the July Fourth Pepsi 400 stock
car race to be postponed. ``Florida is better off than we were four
days ago, but we need to keep praying for rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Memorial Day, fires in all 67 Florida counties have burned
nearly 500,000 acres, destroying 350 homes and other structures and
doing $276 million in damage. Firefighting and other emergency
relief efforts have cost $104 million so far, according to Florida
Division of Emergency Management officials.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in Volusia County one week after the crisis
peaked. Last Thursday, three major fires threatened to encircle
homes and businesses in most of Flagler County, prompting worried
officials to order an unprecedented evacuation of the entire county
_ some 45,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Residents were not allowed back into their homes until Monday,
with hundreds of people packing shelters at high schools and
churches in surrounding counties while thousands stayed with
family, friends or at motels.
</P>
<P>
   The fires extinguished most fireworks across the state for July
4, with Chiles banning all personal use of the devices and most
cities and counties canceling their shows out of respect for the
beleaguered firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 firefighters have battled the blazes, many from other
states _ including the Atlanta metro area.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was introduced by Palm Coast firefighter Randy Holmes,
who helped save the home of Karen Terry, who also spoke at the
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very fast-moving fire,'' Holmes said. ``It created
very intense heat and very thick smoke. We went from house to
house, fighting each time like it was our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry's home survived, although flames charred her grass up to
the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to thank you,'' she said. ``Our fence is down, our
shed is down, but our house is still standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who met with some people who lost homes before making
his speech, said he got daily briefings on the blazes during his
recent trip to China, and was even asked by Chinese officials about
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every report I got, someone told me that the greatest
concern was for the firefighters, who wouldn't eat and wouldn't
sleep because they were so obsessed with saving every home,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Chiles passed on a message that Daytona Beach
officials begged them to express: Much of the state, including
Volusia County, is now free of smoke and any other serious
immediate effects from the blazes.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona hoteliers and tourist businesses have lost millions due
to the postponement of the stock car race, which kept an estimated
250,000 free-spending tourists away during what would've been the
beach town's biggest summer weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are calling the White House and asking what they can
do,'' Clinton said. ``If you haven't taken your vacation yet, one
thing you can do is come down here and give these people an
economic boost. They've gotten the fires under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
