<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEENDRUGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton launches anti-drug campaign
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton spent a busy half-day stop Thursday in
Atlanta, first kicking off a national anti-drug campaign and later
helping raise money for a Democratic Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke about drugs to a crowd of about 700, most of them
children from the metro area, at the Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   After the drug speech, Clinton appeared at a fund-raising
luncheon for Michael Coles, a Democrat who is challenging incumbent
U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   At the anti-drug event, Clinton related a story about how his
brother, Roger, ``nearly died from a cocaine habit.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said, ``There's somebody like my brother back at your
school. He's a good kid, just a little lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The $195 million ad campaign, which has been tested in Atlanta
and 11 other markets, debuted nationally Thursday night on the four
major television networks. Unlike previous anti-drug campaigns,
this one will have a budget for paid broadcast time and print
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ads are designed to knock Americans in the head and get
their attention and empower you to do the right thing,'' the
president told the children in the audience. ``America's mounting a
new and sweeping effort to change the attitude of an entire
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The debut ads ``will reach 40 million Americans, including
millions and millions of children,'' Clinton said. ``They get the
message across that drugs are wrong, illegal and can kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with Clinton at the World Congress Center were Health
and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala; Attorney General Janet
Reno; House Speaker Newt Gingrich; Gov. Zell Miller; and Atlanta
Mayor Bill Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before President Clinton, Gingrich related a story
about a 19-year-old acquaintance who had a ``synthetic drug''
slipped into her drink at a party. She was rushed to a hospital
where she lapsed into a coma.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just celebrated her 21st birthday,'' said Gingrich, ``and
she's still in a coma.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was introduced by Kim Willis, a 13-year-old from Erie,
Pa., who's involved in drug-prevention at her school. She said, ``I
don't want to see my classmates ruin their lives through drugs.''
After leaving Atlanta, Clinton flew to Daytona Beach, Fla.,
Thursday where he thanked firefighters for saving homes from
wildfires burning across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
