<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta unit adds flights in Orlando
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Delta Air Lines is expanding its Florida-based
low-fare unit for the second time this year by adding new routes
between Orlando and four cities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Delta's discount rival, AirTran, released sharply
improved ridership figures for June and said it expects
second-quarter earnings to exceed analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Atlanta-based Delta said the expansion of Delta
Express reflects the continued success of the unit, which was
launched in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While Delta Express does not serve Atlanta, it is becoming an
important element in its strategy. Delta derives more than 20
percent of its revenue in Florida, and it created the Express unit
to offset low-fare competitors including AirTran, Southwest
Airlines and Metrojet, a similar unit begun by US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The new flights will connect Orlando with Albany, Buffalo,
Rochester and Syracuse, starting Oct. 1. Three of those routes are
being abandoned by AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   The latest additions will boost Delta Express' route system to
22 cities, up from 10 when the operation began.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Delta is ending service from Toledo, Ohio, and Fort
Wayne, Ind., this fall, continuing a withdrawal from smaller
markets that can be served by commuter affiliates so that large
jets can be used on longer routes. Other cities being cut from
Delta's route map include Idaho Falls, Idaho; Fresno, Calif.; and
Jackson Hole, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran's parent, Orlando-based AirTran Holdings, said June
traffic rose 43 percent from a year earlier, while capacity was up
32 percent. The company said its two airline units, Orlando-based
AirTran Airways and AirTran Airlines, which flies mainly from
Atlanta, filled 62.9 percent of their seats in the month, adding
that the Atlanta operation's load factor increased more than nine
points.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Holdings also said it expects second-quarter earnings to
exceed analysts' expectations of 10 cents per share. The results
would mark AirTran's first profitable quarter since its
predecessor, ValuJet, was temporarily grounded in 1996 after the
crash of Flight 592.
</P>
<P>
