<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARNINGS-SUNTRUST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SunTrust Banks beats earnings expectations
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- SunTrust Banks, one of the first major Southeastern
institutions to report earnings, set the hurdle high, tallying a 12
percent gain in second-quarter net income. The earnings per share
gain was higher _ 14.3 percent _ because stock buybacks reduced the
number of shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was another solid SunTrust quarter,'' said R. Harold
Schroeder of Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``SunTrust is a model of consistency,'' said Jefferson Harralson
of Robinson-Humphrey. The Atlanta banking company's earnings of 88
cents per share vs. 77 cents in the quarter ending June 30, 1997,
was a penny ahead of 19 analysts' consensus expectations, according
to the First Call service. Net income was $185 million, compared
with $165.4 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The latest results were attributable to a $94.3 million, 13.3
percent, surge in revenue. The bulk of that stemmed from a $68.8
million increase _ or 30.2 percent _ in non-interest income.
</P>
<P>
   Net charge-offs in the quarter were $29.4 million, while the
provision for possible loan losses was $33.5 million. Schroeder
said slight increases in charge-offs and the loan loss provision
were in line with loan growth.
</P>
<P>
   Measures of profitability remain high, with return on assets
coming in at 1.32 percent and return on common equity at 21.88
percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, it cost SunTrust Banks about 60.2 cents to bring in a
dollar's worth of revenue, a relatively high figure compared with
its peers, which have costs close to 55 cents per dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Also, non-interense increased 16.8 percent in the quarter
to $482.8 million. Much of the increase came from personnel
expenses, which rose from $235.3 million in last year's second
quarter to $279.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   SunTrust Banks spokesman James C. Armstrong ascribed the
increased non-interest expenses to ``commissions based on fee
income,'' but he added that ``we're replacing everyone's PC and
preparing for the year 2000.'' For the six months, net income was
$365.9 million, or $1.73 a share, vs. $326.5 million, or $1.51 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Total assets were $61.4 billion at quarter's end, up from $55.5
billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bank stocks generally were down, and SunTrust was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
