<HEADER>
A8283 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-HISTORY-COX     07-09 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-HISTORY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta has been increasingly hospitable to NAACP
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The last time the NAACP came to Atlanta, blacks were
not allowed in most of the city's hotels. Black patrons were turned
away from downtown restaurants. The Ku Klux Klan picketed against
the convention delegates. A different Atlanta awaits the NAACP as
it prepares to meet in the city beginning Saturday, said R.L.
White, president of the Atlanta NAACP branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as (segregation is) concerned, there's been a total
change,'' White said. ``We emphasize now that prejudice is more
subtle. You find it in corporations and boardrooms. Equal
opportunity is the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Jordan, lawyer and former NAACP Georgia field director,
recalled that his major task in 1962 was finding housing for the
delegation because most hotels were not open to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 2,000 delegates stayed at the Atlanta University
Center, and the Freedom Fund Dinner was held in the Morehouse
College gymnasium, he said. Nobel Prize-winner Ralph Bunche had to
stay at the home of Morehouse President Benjamin Mays because he
could not get a room in the city's hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was still an exciting time,'' Jordan said. ``It was
negative that the downtown hotels were not open to us but that
didn't make it a negative experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said the convention was ``spirited'' and that delegates
believed attitudes across the nation were changing. ``The civil
rights movement was in full swing and the smell of victory was in
the air,'' he said. ``The sense was that achievement was possible
and within reach. ``
</P>
<P>
   The city was more desegregated in 1962 than it had been when the
NAACP last met in Atlanta in 1951, when 1,700 delegates attended.
Hotels were segregated in 1951 and entertainer Josephine Baker
cancelled a benefit performance after she was refused
accommodations in three major hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates were encouraged by keynote speaker Roy Wilkins, former
NAACP assistant executive secretary, to use their voting power to
eliminate segregation. Other speakers included Bunche, educator
Mary McLeod Bethune and Phillip Wilkie, an Indiana legislator. By
1962, most theaters, restaurants, high schools and parks had been
desegregated and Vernon Jordan said it was important to the NAACP
to host the convention in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was in the South, it was only logical that it be in
Atlanta,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Casper Jordan, no relation to Vernon, is a now-retired Clark
Atlanta University librarian. But as a student in 1962, he said, he
didn't feel the ``full brunt'' of the discrimination delegates
faced during the convention, but he appreciated the hospitality the
city's leaders showed the NAACP. Then Mayor Ivan Allen officially
welcomed the group, and the NAACP was able to use city facilities
during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were used to bad treatment, so any good treatment at all
made it nicer,'' said Casper Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Voter registration, employment discrimination, school
desegregation, housing and urban renewal and the role of direct
action through boycotts, sit-ins and picketing in the civil rights
movement were among the issues discussed at the 1962 convention. In
a speech to the group, the Rev.. Martin Luther King Jr., encouraged
the use of nonviolent direct action as a ``logical sister'' to
legal action.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of direct action as a topic of discussion
represented a significant change in the NAACP's strategy for
fighting discrimination, said Professor Charles E. Jones, chairman
of the Afro-American Studies program at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made the NAACP so dominant was that they decided to fight
racist institutions not through direct action, but through the
courts,'' Jones said, calling the 1954 Brown v. Board of Education
decision outlawing school segregation the organization's ``crowning
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the organization has been trying in recent years to
``redefine and recreate'' the influence it had at the height of the
civil rights movement. In the absence of blanket segregation, he
said the organization lacks a rallying cause. However, Jones said
he is encouraged by the NAACP's present direction and leadership.
</P>
<P>
   `` It is good that the organization is dealing with such '90s
issues as the plight of black farmers and tapping into the youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
