<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEEDLES-COX     07-09 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEEDLES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's worth a shot
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Christina Contreras has always hated shots. But since
she was diagnosed with diabetes in 1996, she's had to check her
insulin level with needles at least four times a day.
</P>
<P>
   It was a routine with which the 26-year-old Alpharetta resident
stoically lived until she got to participate in clinical studies of
a new technique, called ``micro-poration,'' that uses a laser to
pierce the top level of skin.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the process was painless. And Contreras became an avid
supporter of researchers' quest to develop ways to inject medicine
through the skin without the use of traditional needles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' she said. ``I didn't mind doing the checks any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   From the development of ``micro-needles'' to a laser punch used
by Contreras, several techniques _ some pioneered in Georgia _ are
showing promise in making it easier for patients to get the drugs
they need with a lower risk of pain and infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a bit of interest in this right now,'' said Dr.
John Ansel, a dermatology professor at the Emory University School
of Medicine and chief of dermatology at the Atlanta Veterans
Administration Medical Center. ``A lot of drugs can't be given
orally, and this (the new developments) might be a way to
administer medication without patients writhing in pain.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, doctors have used distractions and numbing creams to
ease the pain of shots. At Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center,
child life specialists are often called in to do play therapy with
children to turn their attention away from shots. And both Scottish
Rite and Egleston Children's Hospital use a cream called Emla to
numb children's skin.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, researchers are approaching the issue of pain from
a radical new perspective. Perhaps the needle could be discarded in
even more cases, replaced with lasers, ultrasound or electrical
currents.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the Georgia Institute of Technology, for
example, presented a prototype last month at a national symposium
that they say could accomplish the goals. The product, which looks
like a nicotine patch, is comprised of a strip of hundreds of
cone-shaped needles too small to see with the naked eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like putting a piece of tape on your skin,'' said
Ansel, who recently tried the device at another presentation. ``It
didn't hurt at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating an effective, pain-free way to administer drugs would
be a boon to many patients _ especially those with chronic
diseases. Those suffering from diabetes, like Contreras, would no
longer have to take insulin shots, but instead could rely on a
strip to control their blood sugar levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be very user-friendly,'' said Dr. Mark Prausnitz,
assistant professor in Georgia Tech's School of Chemical
Engineering. ``Instead of constantly having to inject themselves,
they could depend on something that's about the size of a square
inch.''
</P>
<P>
   The product could use a microprocessor to control a pump that
would allow the device to be programmed to deliver drugs at optimal
levels. The pump could be controlled by a doctor or a patient, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Prausnitz is the only researcher who has presented the
microneedles for review, he said he's aware that a handful of other
organizations are experimenting with similar needles.
</P>
<P>
   The field is also exploring a host of other techniques to
administer medication or draw fluids needed for standard tests.
Some companies, for example, are using electrical currents to drive
the drugs into the skin.
</P>
<P>
   And SpectRx, a Norcross company, specializes in the use of laser
technology to develop non-invasive tests. Already, it has marketed
a light test for infant jaundice overseas _ eliminating the painful
heel stick now used in hospitals. And it is conducting clinical
trials for a screening device for diabetics that involves shining a
blue light into the lens of the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It also is experimenting with microporation, which involves
shooting or ``punching'' a laser the diameter of a human hair into
the skin. Contreras was part of the group that participated in its
early research and development studies.
</P>
<P>
   The laser is powerful enough to extract fluids to gauge levels
of blood sugar and other substances, according to Bill Wells,
SpectRx's director of communications. And that means there's no
need for blood to be drawn in the traditional fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found a way to break the barrier without causing
pain,'' he said. ``We believe this might be a very good discovery
that not only allows non-invasive testing, but potentially could
enhance drug delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to why these new devices don't cause pain is because
they cross the outer layer of skin _ called the stratum corneum _
but don't strike nerve endings. In the case of the microneedles,
they act like little tunnels that go through the stratum corneum
and then release the drugs where they can be easily absorbed by
capillaries and carried into the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   But the stratum corneum is designed to keep out outside
elements, such as bacteria, and is resistent to such invasions. In
response, it could develop allergies or inflammation to deter
transdermal patches or other devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skin is designed to keep things out,'' Ansel said. ``And
the challenge researchers face is to get around this wonderful,
evolved wrapper we have.''
</P>
<P>
   There are technical and business issues as well.
</P>
<P>
   With the microneedles, researchers are still studying how to
design them so they don't break. Currently, they're being made out
of silicon _ the same material used for computer chips _ but
Prausnitz said he believes a different material should be used.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the university would not be marketing the device. Instead,
Prausnitz said, a drug company would have to become intrigued
enough with the product to run it through its regulatory paces and
market it. That could take a while or could stall the entire
project.
</P>
<P>
   And at SpectRx, microporation probably will not be available
until 2000, Wells said, because of the rigorous clinical trials
required for U.S. Food and Drug Administration approval.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, no matter what systems eventually make it to
doctors' offices in the new millineum, big, bad needles will
probably never disappear entirely. Sometimes, researchers say,
they're the only and best way to get the right drug to the right
part of the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, the conventional way is still the easiest and
safest way,'' said Prausnitz. ``But for us, the focus is (to) come
up with several good alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
