<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8287 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUECROSS/SHIELD-COX     07-09 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUECROSS/SHIELD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WellPoint Health Networks acquires Georgia insurer, creating a
windfall
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- For four years, Leonard Schaeffer of WellPoint Health
Networks has longed for a major stake in Georgia's health insurance
market. On Thursday, Schaeffer got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia and WellPoint announced a
deal under which WellPoint would acquire Georgia's largest health
insurer for about $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic opportunity to become part of what's the
best, largest and fastest-growing HMO in the state,'' said
Schaeffer, WellPoint chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was attractive, he said, because of its booming economy,
good regulatory environment and growing appetite for managed care.
</P>
<P>
   And WellPoint, with a Blue Cross connection, was a perfect fit,
said Richard Shirk, Blue Cross of Georgia chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Shirk said the deal would provide capital to expand the
insurer's investment in information technology, increasing its
capacity to analyze medical data.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also would create big individual financial winners,
from some policyholders to a group of private investors. A number
of executives and employees will share a $28 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint already covers 100,000 Georgians through its preferred
provider organization, under the UniCare label. Solidly profitable
and fast growing, WellPoint is known for its innovative insurance
offerings, especially for individuals and small employers. It has
6.7 million managed-care members overall, most of them in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer also said WellPoint emphasizes consumer choice of
managed care plans. ``We don't believe that every American is going
to wind up in an HMO,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Announcement of the deal came one day after Blue Cross announced
a settlement of a lawsuit by consumer groups, which challenged the
company's 1996 conversion to a for-profit company. The settlement
clearly paved the way for the merger, which requires the approval
of regulators, Blue Cross shareholders and Georgia Insurance
Commissioner John Oxendine. The deal is expected to close in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Under the transaction, the companies said, Blue Cross will
continue to be headquartered in Atlanta and will keep marketing its
insurance products in Georgia under its current name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the second most-recognized brand (name) in Georgia,
behind Coca-Cola,'' Schaeffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Winners in the deal include the 70,000 Blue Cross policyholders
who received _ at no cost _ five shares of stock in Cerulean, Blue
Cross' parent company, at the time of the conversion. These
policyholders, who had bought Blue Cross insurance as individuals
or as part of groups that aren't self-insured, will get stock or
cash valued at about $4,000 per shareholder. They will get a
choice, subject to an aggregate limit, once the deal closes.
</P>
<P>
   The charitable foundation Blue Cross created under the lawsuit
settlement would have an initial worth of about $80 million, the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, several consumer groups filed suit in Fulton
County Superior Court over what they called an unconstitutional
transfer of Blue Cross' assets in the for-profit conversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer groups have gotten something _ that's to their
credit,'' said Judith Bell of Consumers Union in California, who
tracks Blue Cross conversions nationally. Nevertheless, she said
the entire value of Blue Cross should have been transferred to the
public trust when the company switched to a for-profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislators and regulators had the responsibility and
power, and didn't exercise either,'' Bell said. ``The Georgia
public is still out $420 million. And that's not chump change.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the merger rewards the private investors who sunk
almost $50 million into Cerulean during the conversion. The
investors would get stock in WellPoint, a return that Shirk said
would amount to about 34 percent on annualized basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly an incredible deal for the (private) investors,''
Bell said. ``Anyone would take that return.''
</P>
<P>
   And 260 Blue Cross management and non-management employees will
share a total cash bonus of $28 million. The average payout is
$97,000. The highest, $3.8 million, goes to Shirk.
</P>
<P>
   The WellPoint-Blue Cross deal continued the sweeping
consolidation among health insurers, sparked by the growth of
managed care and its pressure to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``WellPoint and Blue Cross now will have more negotiating
ability with employers,'' said Brent Layton of Atlanta consulting
firm Layton &AMP; Associates. The merger, he said, ``probably
restructures health care from state line to state line.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross has 1.7 million policyholders in its medical plans.
It earned $4.4 million on revenues of $1.5 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Under the transaction, Blue Cross will become an operating
company under WellPoint. Possible management changes, if any, would
come when the integration of the companies is complete.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint has spread out from California in the last two years,
having recently picked up the health care business of John Hancock
and Massachusetts Mutual. ``They have been very aggressively
expanding, trying to make themselves into a true national player,''
said Dave Norton of consulting firm Towers Perrin.
</P>
<P>
   But its Blue Cross roots stem from California, where its managed
care business is operated as Blue Cross of California. In 1996,
WellPoint and Blue Cross of California merged into a
stockholder-owned company. As a result, charitable foundations
worth $3.2 billion were created.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came before the stock market opened Thursday.
WellPoint shares closed at $71.06 1/4, up $1.43 3/4 in New York
Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
