<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FOOD-ANTIBIOTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL CITES RISKS OF INFECTIONS FROM FOOD ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Humans can contract antibiotic-resistant infections
from animals used for food, a National Academy of Science panel
said Thursday, but the public health risks of these transmissions
through eating meat or poultry or by being in contact with the
animals has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was charged with investigating the safety of a wide
variety of drugs in livestock. It returned with a report that both
presented possible problems with the use of drugs, but also
pointing out that many drugs help insure the safety of the food
supply.
</P>
<P>
   The number of documented cases of human illnesses traced to
antibiotic-resistant disease organisms from animals is very low,
the experts said, but the true risk is difficult to assess because
critical data are lacking on sources of human diseases and the
extent that food animals harbor resistant germs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Coffman, provost at Kansas State University in
Manhattan and chairman of the panel, said antibiotics used to
control and treat diseases in animals help provide healthier meat,
eggs and dairy products for consumers. ``But there have been a few
cases in which resistant bacteria have been passed to people,''
Coffman said. ``Extra vigilance is needed to prevent the spread of
bacteria that cannot be destroyed with currently available drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member panel _ which included health specialists, food
industry scientists, disease experts and consumer representatives _
reviewed the role of drugs in the food supply, the majority of
which are antibiotics. The committee included members of two units
of the National Academy of Sciences _ the National Research Council
and the Institute of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, in a 200-page report, recommended that the
federal government establish a permanent oversight panel to monitor
drug resistance and suggest the best ways for antibiotics to be
used in humans and animals. This panel should include members from
regulatory agencies, medical and veterinary groups, the food
industry and consumer groups, said the report, whose sponsors
included the departments of Agriculture and Health and Human
Services and the American Feed Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   The report also recommended establishing a national database on
antibiotic use and resistance trends in humans and animals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it called for more research to develop new classes
of antibiotics because bacteria that develop resistance to one
antibiotic tend to become immune to others in the same class.
Current monitoring systems to detect the levels of drugs in meat,
milk and other food products from animals are adequate, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said 60 percent to 80 percent of all cattle, swine,
sheep, and poultry in the United States receive antibiotics at some
point. While some of these drugs are used to treat specific
diseases, it said, much of the estimated 19 million pounds of
antibiotics used annually in agriculture is added to food or water
to promote the growth of animals and to prevent disease
transmission among animals held in close quarters. This
``subtherapeutic'' use of antibiotics allows more animals to be
raised at lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumer groups have called for regulators to ban
antibiotic use in food animals for purposes other than to treat
specific diseases posing an immediate threat. The Center for
Science in the Public Interest, a Washington-based consumer group
that has campaigned for restricted antibiotic use among both
animals and people to preserve the effectiveness of the drugs, said
the new report bolstered its call for banning subtherapeutic uses
in the food system.
</P>
<P>
   However, the new report estimated that such a ban in agriculture
would cost consumers between $1.2 billion and $2.5 billion a year
in higher prices for poultry, beef, pork, fish and other foodstuff.
In addition, the report said, animal diseases might become more
widespread, increasing public health risks, and lead to higher
demand for antibiotics for treating sick animals.
</P>
<P>
   The Animal Health Institute, representing makers of vaccines,
drugs, food additives and other animal health products, said
conclusions of the report were consistent with other studies
calling for prudent use of antibiotics in farm animals, better
monitoring and science-based regulations governing approval and use
of antibiotics. It praised the report for recognizing the benefits
of antibiotic use in improving the food supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
