<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BK-WORLDCHAMPIONSHIP-     07-09 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BK-WORLD </SLUG>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
America tarnishes basketball image
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ NBA players have proved their point by electing not to
compete for the United States in the World Championship of
Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   As NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik watched 28 fringe players
try to show they have what it takes to represent America, he
admitted as much _ the NBA, as well as basketball in the country in
which it was invented, will suffer because the NBA's stars will not
shine in Athens, Greece, when the World Championship begins this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of American basketball is taking a hit in this
thing,'' Granik said. ``USA Basketball takes a hit around the
world. But it's even bigger than that (for America's basketball
reputation).
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the world, they just can't understand it. People in our
(NBA) office have spoken to people in Greece and Italy and France _
places where we're going to play exhibitions _ and they're saying:
`We can't understand why Americans don't want to play for their
team. What does that have to do with the NBA?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think in that sense, it has hurt the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what NBA players wanted when they decided not to commit
to the U.S. national team. Originally, a dozen NBA players _ 11 of
them All-Stars at some point in their careers _ were on the U.S.
team. Those are the players fans and big-money sponsors expected to
see when the U.S. team arrived in Athens, as well as in four
exhibition games across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   One of those exhibitions, in Detroit, was canceled. The other
three _ two in Monte Carlo and one in Rome _ will have
substantially less marquee value than they would have if the United
States showed up with Gary Payton, Tim Duncan and Grant Hill
instead of players such as Jason Sasser, Acie Earl and Larry
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Those are good players, probably good enough to compete for a
medal in Athens. But they are borderline NBA talents, and none has
come close to being an NBA All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   NBA players technically are not boycotting the World
Championship. They merely refused to commit to play. That left USA
Basketball, the governing body for America's international play in
the sport, with no choice but to replace the original 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's disappointing that the NBA players aren't here,''
said Granik, who doubles as the president of USA Basketball. ``But
for USA Basketball, this is going to be perhaps a more interesting
adventure. I think we do have enough players to be competitive. And
certainly, the outcome is going to be a lot more in doubt than it
has been in the competitions when the NBA has participated. So it
makes it a little bit more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's the positive spin. But there is no denying the
NBA has been left dumbfounded by its players' actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I have not gotten a reasonable explanation for
why they aren't playing,'' Granik said. ``I told them that if they
wanted me to resign (as USAB president), I would. We wanted to do
whatever it took to field the best team we could. The NBA's not
losing any money in this deal, but USA Basketball is. And I think
that's another thing that NBA players don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   But money is not the issue, at least not in regard to the NBA
players' absence from the U.S. team. What NBA players did was make
sure the image of the United States as basketball royalty would be
tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing the 28 players trying out for the U.S. team can
do about that. But coach Rudy Tomjanovich, who prefers to
concentrate on the positive aspects of leading Team USA rather than
the negatives caused by NBA players, believes the team that
represents the country will have a less stressful experience in the
World Championship than NBA counterparts would have had.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life as a coach is always filled with pressure,''
Tomjanovich said. ``That's what it's all about. The way I deal with
it is just to go out and try to do your best. You prepare your team
and then let the cards come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you're right about that (having less pressure now). There
is a pressure not to lose if you have the NBA guys. And it's no fun
playing not to lose. If you're out there and you win by 15,
everybody's saying you should have won by 30.''
</P>
<P>
   If NBA players were involved, just showing up would be enough.
Enough to win games. And enough to satisfy fans and overseas
corporate tie-ins who wanted to see NBA stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
