<HEADER>
A8290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-KING-TRIAL-825&AMP;AD     07-09 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-TRIAL-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY ACQUITS DON KING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal jury acquitted Don King of nine counts of
wire fraud Thursday, the second time he was tried on a charge of
attempting to defraud a Lloyd's of London insurance syndicate out
of $350,000 after a Julio Cesar Chavez bout was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Although one juror caused a heated deadlock regarding the guilt
of Don King Productions, a defendant along with King, the
government has chosen not to retry the promoter's company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for all America _ not black America or white
America,'' said King, who said he read from a Bible as he listened
to the verdict, then received the embraces of his lawyers and shook
most of the jurors' hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you all very much,'' he said, leaning over the jury box.
</P>
<P>
   The post-verdict scene was reminiscent of one of King's
circus-like news conferences. The promoter laughed boisterously, he
soliloquized his jubilation in religious and hyperbolic terms,
quoting Lord Acton, Martin Luther King Jr, the Bible, Thomas
Jefferson and Rudyard Kipling, and he signed autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to say goodbye,'' one juror said to King, gently
kissing him.
</P>
<P>
   As King ventured from the 15th floor courtroom to talk to
reporters outside the U.S. Courthouse in Lower Manhattan, he
greeted three court security officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm free again!'' he said, embracing one. ``I'm free,
brotherman!''
</P>
<P>
   When two rabbis who displayed their support during the
three-month trial approached King, he gleefully shouted, ``My
rabbis! These are my rabbis!''
</P>
<P>
   In his jubilation, King did not directly scorn the government's
case against him, but referred to those who abuse power. ``When my
lawyer said, `We the people,' my liver quivered and my heart
palpitated,'' said King.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, King, 66, looked like a man unworried
about his legal fate. Although his trademark flamboyance was muted
by the trial's formality, he frequently flashed his broad smile,
garrulously greeted visitors, some bearing gifts, and joked with
the courtroom artist. ``I tried desperately to feel down, but
couldn't,'' he said. ``I'd say, `Your head is in the lion's
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's verdict meant King has won acquittals from two
federal juries in Manhattan, the first one in 1985 on charges of
tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's aftermath, Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney for
the Southern District, said she would not prosecute Don King
Productions again on the wire fraud charges because it would not be
``in the public interest.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That contrasted with her decision to retry King after a hung
jury in 1995 forced U.S. District Judge Lawrence McKenna to declare
a mistrial in the government's first case against King.
</P>
<P>
   This time, White's office added King's company to its indictment
of King.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum prison term King could have faced if he had been
convicted on all nine counts was was 45 years, but sentencing
guidelines would have pared those years down.
</P>
<P>
   He could have been fined up to $250,000 for each count; fines of
$1 million for each of the seven counts could have been levied
against his company.
</P>
<P>
   A company conviction could have barred him from promoting fights
in Nevada, but the state attorney general had reserved a decision
on that until the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment had prevented King from promoting fight cards in
New Jersey; a call to the state Athletic Control Board seeking
comment was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors presented the case against King and his company
with more clarity than the government did in 1995 but jurors
evidently were not fully persuaded that King or his company
submitted a fake contract to Lloyd's after the cancellation of
Chavez's 1991 fight against Harold Brazier that stipulated King was
due repayment of $350,000 in ``maintenance nonrefundable training
expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense argued that Chavez got $80,000 in training expenses
and owed $270,000 more from a $736,000 loan King made to Chavez
against a future purse, money that was characterized as a
``maintenance'' payment.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fiscus, one of the jurors, said he was persuaded by a
faxed insurance binder that Lloyd's covered what the defense said
it did.
</P>
<P>
   Between Tuesday afternoon and early Thursday, the case had
plunged into chaos. One juror, Dean Yager, pushed to convict King
and his company.
</P>
<P>
   Yager was also said to have related to the remaining jurors a
newspaper report that King's maximum sentence could be 45 years.
The jury forewoman reported to McKenna that they were deadlocked,
causing McKenna to interview each juror Wednesday to see if they
could continue to deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna urged them to deliberate again at 12:15 p.m. Thursday
without discharging Yager, which was an option. After 100 minutes,
the jury told McKenna it had a verdict on King but continued
deadlock on the company.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna refused a government request to compel the jury to
deliberate further on the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got unanimous on King this morning,'' said Marianne Mileno,
the jury forewoman, on Thursday. Regarding friction over Yager's
stand on convicting the company, she said, ``It was very emotional.
It was difficult personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Yager said little as he rushed from the courtroom. Asked if the
3 1/2 months of jury service had embittered him, he said:
``Precisely.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Fleming Jr., a lawyer for King, said the defense was
unhappy with Yager at jury selection but could not dismiss him for
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although he wouldn't have been our first choice, we were
surprised that he was as unyielding and unreasonable as we heard he
was,'' Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   King's legal fights are not over. Now, he must fend off a
federal lawsuit filed against him by Mike Tyson, his former money
train.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll deal with it,'' King said, pausing to expound upon
life's various forms of love. ``I love him. He's my beloved
brother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2047EDT &QL; 
