u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHEAT-SANCTIONS-SPI &LR;      07-09 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-SANCTIONS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE EXEMPTS WHEAT FROM SANCTIONS AGAINST PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Pakistan poised to make a major wheat
purchase, the Senate Thursday voted 98-0 to exempt Northwest wheat
farmers from the effects of sanctions imposed against Pakistan for
testing nuclear weapons six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains unclear whether the House and President Clinton
can act quickly enough to make the U.S. eligible to bid for next
Wednesday's Pakistani purchase of 350,000 metric tons of wheat,
which is expected to be worth at least $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   There are only three major competitors for the Pakistani soft
white wheat market _ Australia, Canada, and the United States. The
bulk of the U.S. soft white wheat is grown in the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wheat farmers of the Pacific Northwest are six days away
from a disaster,'' said Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore. ``Farmers across
this country are staring an economic train wreck in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan in recent years has emerged as a major market for
wheat, Washington state's largest agricultural export. Last year,
Pakistan purchased more than one-third of Washington state's wheat
crop, with a value of as much as $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, led by Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., Sen. Slade Gorton,
R-Wash., and Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash., has been vowing for
weeks to help Northwest wheat farmers retain the Pakistani market.
But a House-passed measure to do that has stalled in the Senate
after becoming entangled in the debate over tobacco policy.
</P>
<P>
   Senators hope the unencumbered measure they approved Thursday
can be approved in the House on Tuesday _ the first day the House
returns to work after a lengthy recess and the last day for action
before Pakistan wants the wheat bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have high hopes that the House will act on the 14th,'' said
Thomas Mick, executive director of the Washington Wheat Commission.
``We're very pleased (by the Senate vote), and just hope it isn't
too late.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he is prepared to sign the measure, which
was partly brokered by his national security adviser, Sandy Berger,
at Murray's behest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that the Senate has passed legislation today that
is consistent with my view that U.S. food exports should not become
an unintended victim of an important non-proliferation law,''
Clinton said. ``Food should not be used as a weapon, and I will
resist any action that would lead to a de facto grain embargo.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's vote reflected not only widespread concern over the
plight of American farm families, but also increasing unhappiness
in the Senate with the breadth of U.S.-imposed sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other country on Earth imposes sanctions as often as the
United States,'' said Sen. Tim Johnson, D-S.D. ``It is often an
emotional, short-term calculation which drives these sanctions, and
it is America, all too often, rather than the target nations, which
becomes isolated, victims of our own sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing figures claiming that the United States is imposing 115
sanctions against countries that are home to 75 percent of the
world's population, Senate leaders Thursday had hoped to pass a
broader bill that would have exempted Boeing airplanes and other
products. The bill also would have allowed Clinton some flexibility
in the imposition of sanctions against India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   But the broad bill was highly controversial among Democrats, and
ultimately, the only issue on which the Senate could agree was to
help the wheat farmers. Nonetheless, many senators clearly saw
their action as the first step toward chipping away at the
country's use of sanctions as an instrument of foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating the shift of the debate from agriculture to foreign
policy, Thursday's discussion was led not by Murray, the prime
sponsor of the original effort to rescue wheat farmers, but by
Sens. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., and Joseph Biden, D-Del., who have
taken charge of an effort to re-evaluate overall U.S. sanctions
policy.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions against countries that test nuclear weapons,
sponsored by Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, and approved unanimously by
the Senate in 1994, were supposed to function as a deterrent, and
have never before been imposed. Although Glenn said the threat of
sanctions has helped slow nuclear proliferation in countries
including Argentina, Brazil, South Africa and South Korea, they
failed in India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not kept the nuclear genie in the bottle in the
subcontinent, and now we see the bizarre spectacle of the American
government poised to wrestle American farmers to the ground,'' said
Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's 3,500 wheat farmers have become accidental victims
of the Glenn amendment, which requires the president to impose
sanctions against countries that test nuclear weapons. The
sanctions law exempts food, but includes credits, and therefore
covers the U.S. government-issued credit guarantees Pakistan needs
to borrow money from private banks to buy U.S. wheat.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, Pakistan has used the credit program
to buy about $1 billion worth of wheat from the United States, most
of which has been grown in the Northwest, according to Chris
Goldthwait, general sales manager of the U.S. Department of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Without the U.S. credits, Pakistan will not buy U.S. wheat,
according to a Pakistani official.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wheat which is produced in the Northwest is more suited to
our eating and cooking habits back home, and last year we bought
almost 40 shiploads from the United States, worth more than $350
million,'' said Farrakh Qayyum, minister for trade at the Pakistani
Embassy in Washington. ``But without those credits, a wheat
purchase from the United States is not possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
