<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8300 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-U.S.-8     07-09 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-U.S.-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES UNANIMOUSLY TO WEAKEN SANCTIONS AGAINST INDIA AND
PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bowing to pressure from farmers, the Senate on
Thursday unanimously agreed to exempt food exports from sanctions
that the United States imposed on India and Pakistan after those
two countries conducted nuclear tests in May. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's action, by a 98 to 0 vote, lifts the largest and
most painful economic penalty that Washington inflicted, and leaves
almost no meaningful sanctions in place to punish India and
Pakistan for the nuclear detonations that drew international
condemnation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Restrictions on military aid remain, but there was never much to
begin with. The World Bank has resumed aid to India, with the
administration's support. And foreign grain dealers were eagerly
lining up to take Pakistani orders after American farmers were
sidelined by the sanctions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senators said they were still deeply troubled by the nuclear
explosions and the threat of a new arms race in southern Asia. But
looking ahead to the November elections, senators said they also
had important farming constituents to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether the Pakistanis buy U.S. wheat, Canadian wheat or some
other country's wheat isn't going to make a difference on a dinner
table in Islamabad, but it sure will in Topeka,'' said Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky., who helped write the bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, rushed the
bipartisan bill to the floor Thursday on short notice, bypassing
the usual committee that reviews legislation.
</P>
<P>
   There was reason to hurry. Pakistan is going into the world
grain market next Wednesday to buy 350,000 metric tons of wheat. If
the sanctions law is not changed by then, American wheat farmers
could not bid on the sale, which agricultural experts value at $37
million.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A parade of farm-state senators took to the floor on Thursday to
urge approval. Wheat prices have plunged to a seven-year low
because of excess supply, causing many farmers from the Dakotas to
the Pacific Northwest to give up their land. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington state wheat growers need this bill,'' said Sen.
Patty Murray, D-Wash. Her state sends 37 percent of its wheat to
Pakistan, which pays Washington farmers about $500 million a year.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., voiced even more distress: ``We in the
Pacific Northwest are six days away from disaster.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders have promised to whisk the Senate bill
through the House when it returns from recess early next week.
Clinton indicated in a statement issued on Thursday saying he
supported the legislation.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The whole deal nearly fell apart earlier on Thursday when Sen.
John Glenn, D-Ohio, who wrote the sanctions legislation, balked at
an early draft that gave Clinton the authority to exempt other
sectors besides agriculture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the provision said it would give Clinton a
diplomatic carrot to entice India and Pakistan to sign treaties to
restrict their nuclear testing.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have dumped out everything on sanctions, and given
the president complete carte blanche without Congress being
involved at all,'' Glenn said in an interview after voting for the
bill that exempted only food products.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Arms Export Control Act of 1994 punishes countries that test
nuclear tests by cutting off trade credits, private bank loans,
loans from international institutions and loan guarantees to
American companies doing business there.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last several weeks, the World Bank has resumed aid to
India with Washington's agreement, even though the sanctions that
were automatically triggered by the nuclear tests call on the
United Statesto oppose such lending. Administration officials cited
an exemption in the law for humanitarian aid, a category that the
White House is apparently defining to include most of the
activities undertaken by the World Bank in India.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   World Bank loans were aimed at projects to assure that more
children complete primary school, to train health workers and to
pay for immunization and nutrition services for pre-school
children, and pregnant and nursing women. There were also loans for
irrigation systems and maintaining rural roads.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The remaining sanctions include a longstanding provision that
cut off all arms sales and military aid to Pakistan after the
United States determined in 1990 that Pakistan possessed nuclear
devices. Among other things, it scuttled the sale of 28 United
States F-16 fighter jets for which Pakistan had already paid $600
million.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The legislation approved on Thursday, the Farm Export Relief
Bill, exempts from the sanctions financing and credits for food
products and fertilizer that are guaranteed by the government and
extended to American farmers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Food should not be a weapon of foreign policy,'' said Sen.
Richard Lugar, R-Ind. ``When sanctions are unduly rigid and
automatic, they become a roadblock to diplomacy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Congress has been having second thoughts lately about the merit
of sanctions, one of lawmakers' favorite foreign-policy cudgels.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McConnell is heading a bipartisan, 18-member task force to
review the effectiveness of scores of sanctions the United States
has imposed over the years. The task forces' report is due in
September.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many free-trade advocates in the Senate, like Chuck Hagel,
R-Neb., argue that unilateral sanctions inflict no pain on their
targets, who buy their wares elsewhere, and hurt American
businesses in an increasingly global marketplace.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., summed up the reservations of many
lawmakers: ``We need to keep in mind that while we're bashing
sanctions, we've not made a distinction between countries who pose
a threat to us and those who do not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
