<HEADER>
A8308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGS-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      07-09 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGS-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW WELL TO MOVIES AND MAGAZINES MIX? 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NEWYORKER-SUCCESSION) 
 (lh) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Tina Brown's announcement on Wednesday that she was
quitting as editor of The New Yorker to develop a magazine,
television shows and movies with a unit of Walt Disney Co., puts
her in the middle of one of the hottest fashions in the media
industry: the melding of journalism and Hollywood. Peter Bart, the
editor of Daily Variety, called magazine articles ``the source du
jour for movies.''
</P>
<P>
   But though it is still unclear how the arrangement, with the
Miramax Films division, will work, it is the kind of situation that
has heightened concerns about how the need to generate movie ideas
has the potential to warp journalistic principles and to create
conflicts of interest within media conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, there have been allegations, usually denied,
that entertainment companies like Disney and Time Warner have used
publications they own to promote films or other projects produced
by their studios.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, various shows on ABC, now owned by Disney, have
devoted a great deal of time to several movies produced by Disney,
although the network has maintained in each instance that there was
justified journalistic interest in the films.
</P>
<P>
   The trend plays into more general criticism that the news media
have become oriented toward entertainment rather than hard
journalistic truth. ``The journalist is focused on the economic
demands, not on the demands of the information he or she is working
with,'' said Bill Kovach, the director of Harvard University's
Nieman Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   William Broyles Jr. an Oscar-winning screenwriter and a former
managing editor of Newsweek, said that ever since so-called new
journalism _ a school in which writers are given more license to
re-create scenes _ became popular many publications have become
more oriented toward spinning compelling yarns rather than dry
expositions of fact, and that that is what attracts the studios.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood loves magazine stories, he said, because ``they have a
whiff of authenticity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It legitimizes the story ideas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Susan Lyne, who worked for Disney for several
years scouring magazines for movie ideas, and whose job involved
speaking with journalists even as they were shaping their articles,
insisted that the studio never sought to skew the facts or twist
ideas. ``I just don't know good journalists who would do that,''
said Ms. Lyne, who now is an executive vice president at ABC.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most difficult aspect of Hollywood's fascination
with magazines, and journalists' infatuation with Hollywood, is
that very few articles receive Hollywood interest actually get
turned into movies. Kovach said that after he quit The Atlanta
Constitution years ago because of a dispute over his journalistic
independence, he signed a deal to turn the tale into movie. A
decade later, he said, he still gets occasional calls about a
project that seems to go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   Broyles said that another reason many of the projects languish
is that the studios never really intend to make movies. ``Some
stories are optioned by people who just don't want anybody else to
have them,'' said Broyles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8314 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALTERNATIVE-TRADE-$AD     07-09 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-TRADE-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD TIMES FOR RETAILERS WITH A CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Md., Pa.)   (For release Sunday, July 12)  
 (JT)  
 By SARA SILVER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pueblo to People had a clever name and a noble mission _ selling
clothes and crafts made in Latin America to people in the United
States, and giving the Indian artisans and farmers a chance to earn
a decent living by traditional means instead of leaving their
villages to search for work in the cities.
</P>
<P>
   But neither words nor deeds were enough to pay the bills. After
two decades, Pueblo to People announced its demise last Christmas
in a letter to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company was known as an alternative, or ``fair trade,''
organization _ one that acts as a good-hearted middleman by selling
handicrafts made by cooperatives, so that their members can work
their way out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pueblo to People had bright, committed people, but it's hard
to run both a business and a nonprofit, to balance your head and
your heart,'' said Brian Backe, marketing director of Serrv
International, another fair-trade concern.
</P>
<P>
   At their peak in the mid-1980s, dozens of nonprofit
organizations tried to sell through catalogs, generating an
estimated $15 million to $20 million in annual revenues. But many
soon faced harder times.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, the retail market dipped, paper and mailing
costs soared, and all catalog companies faced unprecedented
competition in the mailbox. Many of these groups had little cash in
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were a small, undercapitalized company, it hit you like
a punch in the stomach,'' said William Dean, a consultant in San
Francisco whose firm advises companies that sell through catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   The market forces that felled Pueblo to People also brought down
at least three smaller fair-trade organizations last year. Still,
those companies that survived the shakeout have increased their
sales, by some estimates taking in as much as $25 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Littrell, a professor at Iowa State University who
researches alternative traders, says there are just four such
groups in the United States with more than $1 million in annual
sales. ``The majority of consumers want good products, and if it's
made decently then that's a plus,'' she said. ``The era of the
message carrying the product is over. The product must carry the
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Pueblo to People, which was based in Houston, boomed in the
1980s and early 1990s. During Central America's civil wars, the
group sold to sympathetic Americans in part by describing the
effect the war had on the artisans. The tactic worked. Sales grew
to about $3.5 million in 1997, from $1 million in 1986, enabling
the group to pump more than $10 million into impoverished villages
in the region. Problems arose, however, in inventory management,
quality control and the fierce loyalty given to certain suppliers,
even when their items were not selling.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which year after year offered many of the same
brightly colored Guatemalan jumpers and bags, cashew brittles and
$350 alpaca throw blankets, began to splinter. ``The fact that we
survived so long is pretty miraculous considering the level of
sophistication with which we approached the problem of running a
business,'' said Sandy Calhoun, the catalog coordinator for Pueblo
to People.
</P>
<P>
   Groups that have survived _ Ten Thousand Villages, Serrv, Equal
Exchange and Marketplace: Handwork of India _ all say they put
sound finances before noble missions. All say they run frugal
businesses despite sales that have grown as much as 20 percent a
year. They pay executives $40,000 to $50,000, for example, far less
than what their counterparts receive at larger retailers. Finally,
they say, they put consumers' needs first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't work with suppliers as charities and sell
poor-quality products,'' said Paul Myers, director of Ten Thousand
Villages, which is based in Akron, Pa., and sold $6.8 million of
merchandise last year through Mennonite churches and a network of
125 stores. The organization avoids catalogs, steers clear of the
clothing market, which is often fickle, and holds $5 million in
equity to weather downturns.
</P>
<P>
   Serrv, based in New Windsor, Md., and an arm of the Church of
the Brethren, started in the 1940s by selling place mats and cuckoo
clocks made by World War II refugees. Last year, it sold $5 million
in products like beeswax candles made by former welfare recipients
in North Carolina, candlesticks by Salvadoran widows, and thumb
pianos by South African slum dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more important to its continued success was the
hiring of a designer two years ago to update and coordinate product
lines, assuring that tablecloths from India matched glassware from
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   To prove that alternative businesses can be viable, Equal
Exchange, a coffee retailer based in Canton, Mass., set itself up
in 1986 as a for-profit corporation to show it could survive
without tax breaks or contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The company, with $4.7 million in revenues last year, buys
mostly organic coffee from Latin American, Indonesian and Tanzanian
cooperatives. It gives farmers money up front to eliminate their
dependence on expensive credit to buy seed and material, and pays
20 cents a pound above market rates to raise living standards and
encourage environment-friendly agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Though it once hoped to branch into other products, Equal
Exchange is now content with staying alive in the gourmet coffee
market _ and the $200,000 pretax profit it produced last year.
``Accomplishing change within the system is so difficult,'' said
Jonathan Rosenthal, the executive director. ``If we survive and
grow, that's success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
