<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 BofA Deal Walloped At Public Hearings   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In the first and perhaps only public hearings on the biggest bank
merger in U.S. history, Bank of America and NationsBank came under
heavy attack yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Packing the first of two days of hearings at the Federal Reserve
Bank of San Francisco, community groups and politicians expressed
grave concerns that the plan to create the first coast-to-coast
bank could cut competition, lead to higher fees and reduce
community reinvestment and charitable giving.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank CEO Hugh McColl, who will run the combined bank from
Charlotte, N.C., reiterated the two banks' unprecedented 10-year,
$350 billion community development pledge, calling it ``a floor and
not a ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   The pledge includes $180 billion for small-business lending and
$115 billion for affordable housing. He also noted that combined
charitable giving will top $100 million this year, making the new
BankAmerica the most generous financial institution in the country
``by a long shot.''
</P>
<P>
   His BofA counterpart, David Coulter, pointed out that BofA
helped build California by financing everything from the Golden
Gate Bridge to Silicon Valley to Hollywood, including the film,
``It's a Wonderful Life.'' He said the bank intends to continue its
``unparalleled commitment to the communities we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of the 200 speakers presenting their views yesterday
and today are worried about the merger. ``Life is not so wonderful
in Oakland, Bay View-Hunters Point and other areas that still
suffer from redlining,'' said David Glover, executive director of
Oakland Citizens Committee for Urban Renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Although supporters of the merger testified, its critics were
more outspoken. One of the taped banners on the walls read,
``NationsBank Go Home,'' while another said, ``Don't Redline
California.''
</P>
<P>
   John Gamboa, executive director of the Greenlining Institute in
San Francisco, called the banks' $350 billion pledge ``a hollow
commitment'' because it does not spell out how the loans would be
distributed by geographic market and by product, such as loans to
minority- and women-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have the banks made specific pledges on charitable giving or
minority representation among upper management and the board of
directors, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Other banks that have recently merged, such as Wells Fargo,
Washington Mutual and Union Bank of California, have made
more-specific pledges, said Alan Fisher, executive director of the
California Reinvestment Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Californians are afraid that this mega-merger will
accelerate movement away from meeting the distinct needs of
California communities and toward cookie-cutter loans and predatory
banking,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union attorney Earl Liu urged the Federal Reserve
Board to hold up approval of the merger until the new BankAmerica
pledges not to increase fees and minimum-balance requirements,
passes cost savings on to consumers, reaches specific community
reinvestment goals with community groups, and guarantees affordable
checking and savings accounts for low-income consumers .
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Supervisor Mark Leno said the $350 billion
community reinvestment pledge should be made binding by including
it in the banks' merger application.
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing merger applications, the Federal Reserve Board is
required to examine the banks' compliance with the Community
Reinvestment Act of 1977, which requires banks to meet the
``convenience and needs'' of all the communities they serve.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers have never been blocked after such a review, though a
few have been delayed. Many of the speakers at yesterday's hearing
called for additional hearings in Los Angeles and 21 other states
where the combined bank has branches. But they and several bank
analysts believe that even the two-day San Francisco review of the
NationsBank/BofA merger is mainly a formality.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks have received ``outstanding'' marks from regulators
for their community reinvestment programs. Moreover, about half the
speakers yesterday applauded the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $350 billion commitment is unprecedented,'' said Bruce
Marks, executive director of Boston-based Neighborhood Assistance
Corporation of America. ``It makes BankAmerica/NationsBank the
largest provider of affordable mortgages and developer of
affordable housing in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Marks was accompanied by five African Americans who testified as
to how well they have been served by NationsBank. Genie McNab, 67,
who relies on Social Security payments &UR; ,  &LR; said that earlier this
year she traded a 12.5 percent mortgage loan on her Atlanta home
from another company for a 6.5 percent fixed-rate, 30-year loan
from NationsBank with no down payment and no closing costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now also
praised NationsBank as a leader in community reinvestment. Houston
Mayor Lee Brown called NationsBank ``an excellent corporate
citizen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
