<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Washington Mutual Debuts   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Seattle-bas k?~ Washington Mutual will soon be the second biggest
lender in California. But the giant thrift has a tough hurdle to
overcome as it looks for new business _ few Californians have ever
heard of it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When it comes to name recognition in California ... we have
none,'' said Gini Lawson, first vice president of advertising.
Washington Mutual has 365 branches in the state, but until recently
they all operated under the names Great Western and American
Savings, companies Washington Mutual acquired over the last year
and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual has spent the past three months changing the
name plates on its California branches. On Monday it launches a
humorous television advertising campaign to start building name
recognition and a reputation for good customer service.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has a difficult job ahead as it battles such
gargantuan names as Bank of America and Wells Fargo _ on their
native turf. The stakes will rise October 1 when Washington Mutual
is scheduled to complete its acquisition of another huge thrift,
H.F. Ahmanson, parent company of Home Savings of America.
</P>
<P>
   At that point Washington Mutual will operate about 600
California branches and jump ahead of Wells Fargo to become the
second largest lender in the state. It will manage 17 percent of
all California deposits, compared to 21 percent for Bank of America
and 14 percent for Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   Barring any unannounced banking mergers before October,
Washington Mutual will be the seventh largest lending institution
in the United States with $156 billion in assets under management.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual executives believe the key to future growth is
to address consumers' two biggest frustrations with banking.
``People don't want to be treated like a number and they are tired
of being nickeled and dimed to death with fees,'' said Brad Davis,
senior vice president of corporate marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The company's products and advertising are both geared to
address these pet peeves. Its flagship product, a no-fee checking
account, goes further than most other banks by offering overdraft
protection, no minimum balance, no fee for using a teller and no
direct deposit requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Although checking accounts cost banks an average of $150 per
year to maintain, Davis said Washington Mutual makes a profit on
its free accounts after 12 to 18 months. That's the point at which
most account holders have between two and three other
``relationships'' with the bank, such as a mortgage or a
certificate of deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Some 175,000 free checking accounts, which are particularly
attractive to the under-30 crowd, were opened at Washington Mutual
in the first five months of this year. ``We build the relationship
so when they get older and they need a car loan and a mortgage,
they will come to us,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep staffers tuned to the needs of customers, Washington
Mutual sends ``secret shoppers'' to each branch four times a year
to rate customer service. Branch managers' salaries are tied to the
previous year's ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual is also making an effort to reach low-income
and minority customers and small businesses with a promise to lend
$120 billion to these groups over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its public relations value, the pledge makes good
business sense, because 80 percent of new homeowners in California
are ethnic minorities, said Robert Gnaizda, public policy director
of the Greenlining Institute, a San Francisco advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   A series of TV spots, which premiere Monday, feature Washington
Mutual customers going to extreme measures to express their
satisfaction with the thrift. In one ad, account holders take a bus
tour of tellers' homes and are thrilled to find a favorite teller
mowing the lawn in front of his house.
</P>
<P>
   In the second spot, enthusiastic but graceless Washington Mutual
clients form a cheerleading squad. In the third, two young boys
visit what looks like a baseball card shop to check out the latest
Washington Mutual ``teller cards''.
</P>
<P>
   The company's award-winning TV ads for the Pacific Northwest
market have gained a lot of notoriety, particularly spots featuring
the ``Rodeo Grandmas'' in cowboy hats and chaps. Since appearing in
the ads, the four grandmas have appeared as guests on TV programs
like the Rosie O'Donnell Show.
</P>
<P>
   All the spots were created by McCann-Erickson/Seattle ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   Banking industry analyst Jim Bradshaw, a former California
banking regulator, said he believes the Washington Mutual formula
will work well here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk in, it feels awfully different than the
traditional bank branch you go to,'' said Bradshaw, of Portland,
Ore.-based Pacific Crest Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual branches generally have customer service desks
positioned near the front door, ``so you're greeted quickly after
you enter, they make you feel at home instantly, and they direct
you to where you need to do your business,'' Bradshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said a company survey shows that 90 percent of Washington
Mutual account holders say they would recommend the bank to a
friend, compared to 46 percent of Wells Fargo customers and 42
percent of Bank of America customers.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Marymee, a Wells Fargo spokesman, said of Washington
Mutual, ``Smart competition is good for the marketplace. We're
doing what we've always done, which is concentrating on delivering
fast, convenient service for our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bank of America spokesman Harvey Radin: ``The strength we
bring to the market is our range of services and the convenience of
... large branch and ATM networks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
