<SLUG> BC-ARMY-KUWAIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. deployment in Kuwait remains substantial
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Rarely has a year gone by since the end of the Gulf
War in 1991 without American military forces scrambling back to the
region for a few months to counter another threat from Saddam
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   This year's crisis came in February, when the Iraqi dictator
refused to grant U.N. weapons inspection teams access to certain
areas and threatened to shoot down U-2 spy planes.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike past deployments that were quickly scaled back as
soon as the crisis ended, this one has lingered long after Saddam
backed down.
</P>
<P>
   From a high of 12,000-13,000 troops on the ground in Kuwait in
February, the numbers have been reduced to 3,500-4,000, said Army
Lt. Gen. Tommy Franks, who is responsible for all U.S. ground
forces in the Middle East as commander of the 3rd U.S. Army at Fort
McPherson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have drawn the force level down in accordance with our view
that Saddam Hussein is not now pressing a crisis,'' Franks said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But that is still three times more foreign troops, most of them
American, than are usually in post-war Kuwait when no Iraqi threat
is looming.
</P>
<P>
   Franks said a decision was made after the agreement between U.N.
and Iraqi officials averted another war ``that we should watch this
for a period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to do that, Marine Gen. Anthony Zinni, commander of
Central Command, which oversees the region, created a Combined
Joint Task Force that provides an infrastructure and a small
deterrent force. That force can be bolstered by at least 5,000
combat ground troops from the U.S. within 96 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted to be able to do was match Saddam's cycles of
arrogance and recalcitrance,'' said Franks.
</P>
<P>
   There is no timetable for reducing forces in Kuwait to what they
were before February. Saddam is too unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
