<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-COX     07-09 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton joins Democratic bash for Coles
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- President Bill Clinton praised Michael Coles as ``a
doer'' and a man of courage who would have impressed America's
founding fathers Thursday, but he acknowledged that the Democratic
candidate for U.S. Senate might not always see eye to eye with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not expect this man, if he is elected to the Senate, to
vote with me on every issue,'' Clinton said at a fundraiser for
Coles in Atlanta. ``I want him to only do so when it is consistent
with his conscience. But I believe he thinks enough to know that we
will be building a future based on progress, not partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles, who expects to face incumbent Republican Sen. Paul
Coverdell in November, raised as estimated $500,000 at the event
hosted by Gov. Zell Miller and Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 guests paid from $500 to $10,000 to attend the
luncheon at the Marriott Marquis downtown, with the more generous
givers receiving brief photo sessions with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's campaign manager Marty Ryall said Clinton's
participation in the fundraiser shows that Coles has aligned
himself with ``the liberal wing of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, Coles praised the Clinton administration for
the nation's low unemployment and balanced budget. But at a press
conference after Clinton left, he cited specific differences he had
with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Coles said he strongly disagreed with the administration's
decision to use a $15 billion cut in medical benefits for veterans
with smoking-related illnesses to help fund a highway bill. Coles
added that he never supported Clinton's abortive attempt to create
a national health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when he was running against House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, Coles declined to say whether he planned to vote for
Clinton in his bid for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to let Newt drag me into sideshow issues,''
Coles said. ``I voted for Clinton in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's approval rating in Georgia this month was 53 percent,
down slightly since fall 1996 but still higher than it has been
throughout much of his six years in office.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton and Coles were somewhat reserved toward each other,
they let their emotions flow in praising Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Coles choked back tears after Miller, his close friend,
introduced him. He said Miller was the person most responsible for
his presence in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Democrats must convince moderate Republicans and
independents that the prosperity Americans and Georgians now enjoy
_ the lowest crime, unemployment and inflation rates in a
generation and a balanced budget _ are connected to the policies of
their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just that Zell Miller is a good man with a lot of
energy and a lot of courage and he was great in the Marine Corps
and he gives a good speech,'' Clinton said. ``The HOPE scholarship
was in fact the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta attorney Emmet J. Bondurant, who attended the luncheon,
said Clinton' spoke well and should help energize Democrats to work
for Coles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
