<SLUG> BC-POWER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Big Glitch in Electricity Market   By Kenneth Howe  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In the biggest glitch to hit the state's electricity market since
it was deregulated three months ago, prices for backup power shot
up 1,000 percent on Wednesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wholesale price for ``replacement reserve power'' in
California skyrocketed as high as $5,000 per megawatt from a normal
$5 to $10 per megawatt.
</P>
<P>
   The Independent System Operator, which runs the the state's
electricity system, buys reserve power as a kind of insurance in
case a heat spell or emergency causes a surge in energy usage.
</P>
<P>
   This week's price spike cost the ISO more than $9 million. The
ISO passes the cost to power companies, which pass it along, albeit
indirectly, to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities can't directly pass on the higher costs because
rates have been capped at current levels for four years. However,
rates actually were expected to decline before those four years
were over. But if the utilities are forced to absorb higher costs
for reserve power, rates may continue at their high level for the
full period.
</P>
<P>
   The price jump is an embarrassment because electricity
deregulation, which began March 31 after a three-month delay, was
supposed to lower energy costs, not raise them.
</P>
<P>
   Although this spike applied only to power for several hours,
such expensive price swings are apt to occur again unless federal
regulators agree to change energy-trading rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about this,'' said Jeffrey Tranen, chief
executive of the ISO, which is based in Folsom. He said that ISO
officials were already discussing the problem with the Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission, which governs energy matters.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of this week's price spike lies in the interplay
between supply, demand and federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, companies that generate electricity compete to sell
electric power into the state's power grid.
</P>
<P>
   The company with the lowest price gets the contract to provide
power for certain parts of the state for a set amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   The market for normal power needs is highly competitive,
insuring a low price.
</P>
<P>
   However, fewer suppliers are interested in the smaller market
for back-up power, so the price tends to be higher. To prevent
prices from going too high, the federal regulatory agency limits
how much companies can charge for emergency power.
</P>
<P>
   However, a handful of companies that are based out of state but
have generating plants in California recently applied to the agency
to have their price caps lifted. The agency complied.
</P>
<P>
   Once the cap was lifted, the power companies could charge
whatever they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like giving someone the keys to the bank,'' said Mike
Florio, a senior attorney with the Utility Reform Network and a
member of the ISO board.
</P>
<P>
   Tranen of the ISO said he could not disclose which companies
jacked up the price of emergency power.
</P>
<P>
   However, the power companies asking that their price caps be
lifted include: AES Corp., based in Arlington, Vir.; Houston
Industries Inc.; Dynegy Inc., also based in Houston; and Duke
Energy Corp., based in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The ISO needs 500 megawatts of replacement reserve power _
enough to power a half-million homes _ each hour.
</P>
<P>
   Such power generally goes for about $5 to $10 a megawatt. But on
Wednesday, the lowest price for backup power that would be
available between 1 p.m. and 2 p.m. yesterday shot up to $2,500 a
megawatt.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three 60-minute periods, the price went to $5,000 a
megawatt, before dropping down to $750 a megawatt for the hour
ending at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tranen said the ISO had little choice but to buy the backup
power. However, the ISO did not buy any replacement reserve power
for today. &UR;  &LR; Instead, the agency relied on other back-up power
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Tranen said he believed the price spike was only temporary. ``I
believe this is a blip and we will solve it with the regulators and
then we can move on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tranen wants the FERC to bring back the price caps until more
competitors enter the reserve market. Or they could be removed for
all competitors, which would bring more companies into the market.
</P>
<P>
   Tranen said the market could also become more competitive if
out-of-state generating companies are able to participate in the
reserve market. They can't now due to technical computer
limitations at the ISO.
</P>
<P>
   With the hot summer coming up, the ISO will need to buy even
more reserve power.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-July, the ISO expects to be able to bring out-of-state
companies into the reserve market. That will help prevent the
likelihood of another price hike. But the future really depends on
what FERC decides to do.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
