<SLUG> BC-BBO-COMMISSIONER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELIG'S THE ONE ... OFFICIALLY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ On his 2,130th day as acting commissioner, Major
League Baseball club owners looked at Bud Selig and liked what they
saw. So Thursday they elected him quickly and unanimously as the
sport's ninth commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Although Selig will shed the ``acting'' from his title Aug. 1,
he is not expected to alter the way in which he has performed his
role since Sept. 9, 1992, two days after the last commissioner, Fay
Vincent, resigned under pressure. The owners don't want him to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud knows how to get things done,'' said Drayton McLane of
Houston, who, with Carl Pohlad of Minnesota, led the effort that
persuaded Selig to accept the job. ``He is the most effective
political leader I have ever met. Every owner trusts him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Reinsdorf of the Chicago White Sox had been portrayed by
other owners and officials as opposing the idea of an owner being
commissioner, but he voted for Selig and said afterward: ``I don't
think there's anybody in America who could do the job that he can
do. The only alternative was bringing in an outsider. That just
didn't make any sense at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig, who will turn 64 years old July 30, was elected as
quickly as it took the owners to take a roll-call vote, having
previously voted to dispense with the requirement that election be
done by written ballot. He was elected for a five-year term with
his salary to be set by the executive council.
</P>
<P>
   Selig currently earns $2.5 million as council chairman and is
expected to begin his full-time job with a salary of at least $3
million a year. As the man in charge for the past 70 months, Selig
has already served longer than four of the previous eight
commissioners: Peter Ueberroth (1,643 days), Gen. William Eckert
(1,129), Vincent (1,091) and A. Bartlett Giamatti (154).
</P>
<P>
   As the first owner to become commissioner, Selig will be
replaced as the trustee of his approximately one-third share of the
Milwaukee Brewers, before he officially takes office. The club's
board of directors is expected to elect Wendy Selig-Prieb, his
daughter and current vice president, as president.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said he will move out of his office at County Stadium and
open a new office in downtown Milwaukee, dividing his time between
there and the commissioner's office on Park Avenue in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was sensitive to possible conflicts arising from his
position as an owner, Selig told a news conference that after 28
years as club president, ``It's time for me to go now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I really believed in my heart and mind that I couldn't do
this, if I'm not capable of making that very emotional and very
sensitive shift, then I should have had the decency to say I just
can't do that,'' he added. ``But I know that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig's election surprised absolutely no one, not on
management's side, not on the players' side.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time it has been clear that eventually the owners
would formally name Bud to be the commissioner,'' said Donald Fehr,
the union chief, whose relationship with Selig has improved since
it reached its nadir during the labor dispute in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sue Selig, the commissioner's wife, said Thursday she
``knew in my heart'' probably since the labor dispute was resolved
that he would accept the job. Selig, however, steadfastly said he
did not want the job, though never ruling out that he would take
it.
</P>
<P>
   A search committee, meanwhile, considered hundreds of
candidates, and Jerry McMorris of Colorado, the chairman, had
whittled the list to four names, including Leonard Coleman, the
National League president. But an increasing number of owners told
Selig he was the only man for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working on him as long as I can remember,'' Pohlad
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud has stiff-armed us for over a year,'' McLane added.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said Thursday he was driving in his car one day and said
to himself, ``You're going to do this.'' He did not say when he had
that conversation, but another owner said Selig disclosed his
decision in late May or early June.
</P>
<P>
   A critical factor in his decision, Selig said, was the presence
of Paul Beeston as Major League Baseball's chief operating officer
for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul will do much more of the day-to-day, operational
things,'' he said. ``I'll do more global things.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the global area is the problem of resolving the
economic disparity between large and small revenue clubs. That
issue and lasting labor peace are the two most important matters
facing Selig.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to reduce the acrimony from this equation once and for
all,'' said Selig, who was in charge of the owners' labor committee
in the sport's last three work stoppages. ``We've never been able
to do that. We've had eight work stoppages. We have to make sure
that the next generation doesn't have to endure any work
stoppages.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners have responded positively to Selig's
consensus-building style and seem to feel he will be a ``safe''
commissioner because he never acts in a precipitous or
controversial manner.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Colangelo, managing partner of the Arizona Diamondbacks
and the National Basketball Association Phoenix Suns, compared
Selig favorably with David Stern, who has been considered the most
successful commissioner of a professional league.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're two different individuals with different personalities
and different methodologies,'' Colangelo said. ``Each in his own
way has been very effective.''
</P>
<P>
   During Selig's tenure as acting commissioner, the owners have
adopted interleague play, three-division leagues and wild-card
teams for the playoffs, greatly increased their revenue sharing and
approved a limited form of realignment, shifting Selig's Brewers
into the National League.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
