<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND OFFICIALS DEFEND THEIR INQUIRY OF TRIPP 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Maryland investigators on Thursday defended their
new inquiry of Linda Tripp as she made her fourth appearance before
a federal grand jury here that is investigating the Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp has emerged as a central witness in the inquiry by
the Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, into whether
anyone committed perjury, witness tampering or obstruction of
justice in connection with the president's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday a Maryland prosecutor, Stephen Montanarelli,
convened a local grand jury to investigate whether Mrs. Tripp broke
a state law when she secretly recorded telephone conversations with
Ms. Lewinsky. The law in Maryland, where Mrs. Tripp lives, requires
that both parties to a telephone conversation consent to its
recording.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland authorities on Thursday disputed the claims of Mrs.
Tripp's lawyers that the inquiry was a politically motivated effort
to intimidate Mrs. Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no political agenda at all,'' said Gavin Patashnick,
Montanarelli's spokesman in the Special Prosecutor's office.
``We're an apolitical office.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp's lawyers have complained that the Maryland inquiry
had been sought by more than 40 Democratic state lawmakers and was
begun as she was appearing before the Washington grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Montanarelli, who heads an office of the state Attorney General
that handles white collar and public corruption cases, was given
the inquiry at the request of Marna McLendon, the prosecutor in
Howard County, where Mrs. Tripp lives. Ms. McLendon, a Republican
up for re-election, decided she could not proceed without being
accused of a conflict shortly after she received a letter from the
state Democratic lawmakers urging an investigation of Mrs. Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp on Thursday issued another statement that the
Maryland inquiry would have no effect on her testimony in the
Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the events which have recently unfolded in Maryland, I
continue to focus on my testimony before the federal grand jury,''
she said in a statement read by a spokesman, Philip Caughter.
</P>
<P>
   Montanarelli faces significant obstacles in any potential
prosecution of Mrs. Tripp. An immunity letter issued by Starr and a
sealed immunity order from a federal judge prevent the Maryland
prosecutor from using any evidence or information that Mrs. Tripp
provides to the independent counsel against her. As a result,
prosecutors in Maryland will be unable to use the tapes that she
turned over to the independent counsel's office and Mrs. Tripp's
testimony about why she made them.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, investigators will have to look elsewhere to try to
make a case against her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immunity she gets precludes the state from using anything
she turns over,'' said Professor Sarah Sun Beale, a criminal law
authority who teaches at the Duke University School of Law. ``What
the prosecutors use must be independent and pre-existing
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Beale said the Maryland authorities could try to make
a case from other evidence. For example, Lucianne Goldberg, a book
agent and friend of Mrs. Tripp, has said she instructed Mrs. Tripp
to make the tapes in the mistaken belief that Ms. Lewinsky's
consent was not required. Ms. Goldberg also had copies of some of
the tapes, but has apparently turned them over to the independent
counsel. The Maryland authorities could seek those tapes from
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp is expected to return to the grand jury in Washington
next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
