<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-AD-COLUMN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS AGGRESSIVELY COURT HISPANIC CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bilingual education may be under attack in the public schools,
but American businesses do speak Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers spent $1.4 billion last year trying to reach
Spanish-speaking and bilingual Hispanic consumers, according to
Hispanic Business magazine in Santa Barbara, Calif. That was more
than double the $628.2 million spent in 1990 and four times the
$333.5 million of 1985, based on the magazine's numbers.
</P>
<P>
   While still less than 1 percent of the $186.8 billion spent on
all advertising here in 1997, according to McCann-Erickson
Worldwide, a unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos., experts say the
Hispanic number will keep growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are beginning to recognize that the Hispanic population
is very large,'' said Dolores Kunda, director of Hispanic marketing
at Leo Burnett USA, part of Leo Burnett Co. and a board member of
the Association of Hispanic Advertising Agencies. ``The Hispanic
population is as large as the population of Canada,'' she said,
referring to the perhaps 30 million people of Hispanic descent now
living in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent census estimates for 1995 show the Hispanic
population at 26.9 million, or just under 10 percent of the total
population. The Census Bureau predicts that will rise to more than
11 percent in 2000 and to 13.8 percent in 2010, with the Hispanic
population nudging out blacks to become the largest minority.
</P>
<P>
   In response, mainstream publications like Newsweek and People
have come out with Spanish editions, Ms. Kunda said, and bilingual
magazines like Latina are cropping up.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Hispanic radio stations has grown to more than
400, according to SRDS Hispanic Media and Market Source.
</P>
<P>
   And, while mainstream networks struggle to hold onto viewers in
a world full of cable channels, Univision Communications Inc., the
largest of two Hispanic networks, has grown to 2.8 million
prime-time viewers today from 1.3 million in 1993, according to
Anne Corley, vice president for public relations. It added more
viewers in the coveted 18-49-year-old segment than any other
network, including NBC, between 1993 and 1997, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to deliver a block of viewers has made Hispanic
television so popular in places like Miami and Los Angeles that
Spanish-language programming now leads in some time slots, said
Ernest Bromley, chief executive of Bromley, Aguilar &AMP; Associates, a
Hispanic advertising agency in San Antonio that is part of the
D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles unit of the MacManus Group.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Bromley said, most advertisers were attracted to
the Hispanic market for political reasons. ``Now, it's for
marketing reasons,'' he said. ``They can see sales from the work
that they do.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hispanic Business tracks only those ads designed for the
Hispanic, mostly Spanish-speaking media, Maria Zate, senior editor
there, said a new breed of Hispanic ad has been cropping up over
the last two or three years. These ads are in English and appear in
mainstream media, she said, but are clearly aimed at Hispanic
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   She cites two examples, both for McDonald's Corp., one of the 10
largest advertisers to Hispanic consumers. One, she said, features
a father and daughter in a McDonald's restaurant, discussing the
girl's coming 15th-birthday gala.
</P>
<P>
   The other shows a toddler looking at McDonald's french fries, as
his eager father tries to prod him to speak. When the child utters
his first word, ``Papa,'' English-speaking viewers understand but
only Spanish speakers get the joke that the word also means potato,
Ms. Zate said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Just how much is being spent on such crossover advertising is
tough to measure, she said, because determining whether the ad is
aimed at Hispanic consumers can be subjective.
</P>
<P>
   Ads in English for Hispanic people might become more common
because they now tend to be bilingual, she said. Figures from the
1990 census show that 9 million of the 17.3 million Americans who
spoke Spanish at home reported they also spoke English ``very
well.'' Another 3.8 million reported speaking it ``well.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``There's a lot of controversy there,'' because
making Hispanic ads in English could undercut agencies that deal in
Spanish-language ads.
</P>
<P>
   Bromley, Aguilar makes 85-90 percent of its ads in Spanish,
Bromley said. The percentage of the Hispanic population who speak
Spanish most of the time is going up, not down, he maintained.
``We're seeing people who are English-dominant who are becoming
more Hispanic,'' he said. ``They're reclaiming their language,
renewed pride.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are people going to increase their knowledge of English? Of
course they are,'' Ms. Kunda said. ``Are they going to give up what
makes them Hispanic, what is important to them? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising tries to reach consumers on an emotional level, she
said, and for the Hispanic population, ``Spanish is the language of
the soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic agencies will be needed for English ads as well, she
added, because of the cultural nuances.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Nogales, chairman of the National Hispanic Media Coalition,
agrees that the Hispanic population will continue to have a
distinctive culture best appealed to with the aid of Hispanic
agencies. But he said the day when English ads for them outnumber
those in Spanish could be only 20 years away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The move is going from Spanish to English very fast,'' he
said. Of advertisers, he said, ``The population is moving from one
to another much faster than they perceive so they're getting left
behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
