<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DISNEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS EDUCATION PANEL VOTES TO UNLOAD $43 MILLION IN DISNEY STOCK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Name of Harryette Ehrhardt is cq) 
(see optional trim, optional ending) 
 
By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ &UR;  &LR; A State Board of Education committee voted
Thursday to dump $43 million in Walt Disney Co. stock, despite
concerns the move makes bad sense financially and could push the
board down ``a slippery slope'' toward becoming the moral barometer
for Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-five percent of the entire S&AMP;P 500 fail some litmus
test or another,'' protested state Rep. Harryette Ehrhardt,
D-Dallas, who appeared with the liberal interest group Texas
Freedom Network at a press conference to denounce the move.
</P>
<P>
   The group said the decision was prompted by ``an influential
radical right organization'' whose primary concern is not the
welfare of Texas schoolchildren but the Disney company's practice
of extending health benefits to domestic partners of gay and
lesbian employees.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said if the board were truly concerned about children,
it would sell off major holdings in a host of other companies,
including a casino company, breweries, defense contractors and
those with human rights and labor relations problems _ all issues
that could fail some group's morality test.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal passed committee by a 2-0 vote, with two Democrats
abstaining in an effort to delay a final board vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done some rather foolish things with some of their
subsidiary investments,'' allowed member Will Davis of Austin, one
of the Democrats who tried to stall the vote. But, he added, ``It
is a slippery slope. Somebody's going to have something they don't
like about some of these big multifaceted corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   A final vote on the controversial proposal is expected Friday
before the full 15-member board, putting Texas in the position of
becoming the first state to tell the company _ which built its
reputation around wholesome family entertainment _ that it is not
going to put its money into companies that produce violent and
sexually explicit material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has taken a bold, firm stand that there's enough
violence exposed to the children, and explicitness _ just too
much,'' said Board Chairman Jack Christie, a Houston Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Although Christie has thwarted previous efforts by social
conservatives on the board to unload Disney holdings, he said he
changed his mind after the American Family Association sent him a
video with excerpts from several movies, including ``Pulp
Fiction,'' ``Trainspotting'' and ``Chasing Amy,'' depicting
violence, sex and profanity. The movies were produced by Miramax
Films, a Disney subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do divest, I hope it sends a message to Miramax that the
public in general has had enough enough of exposing children to the
violence and explicitness in these movies,'' he said. ``How many
more school shootings do you want before we have to do something to
reverse that trend?''
</P>
<P>
   Abstaining with Davis on Thursday was Rene Nunez of El Paso, who
said he resented the pressure the vote would put on him by his
political opponent, Donna Ballard, an outspoken Republican and
social conservative from east Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Voting to sell the 406,000 shares of Disney held by the
Permanent School Fund were David Bradley of Beaumont and Richard
Neill of Fort Worth, both Republicans and social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Christie also said he hopes the AFA did not target Disney over
its tolerant policies toward gay and lesbian employees but rather
the violent and sexually explicit nature of some movies and
recordings produced by Disney subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any evidence of that but that wouldn't influence
my decision at all,'' Christie said. ``My main objection are the
excerpts from the films I saw from Miramax, that it would be a bad
future business investment.''
</P>
<P>
   In protesting the Disney decision, Ehrhardt noted that some
funds people may find objectionable are Harrah's Entertainment
Inc., a casino operator in which the schools own 170,000 shares of
stock valued at more than $3.9 million, and Wal-Mart, which sells
Miramax movies on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Other holdings include Anheuser-Busch Companies Inc., Asahi
Breweries Ltd., LVMH Moet Hennesey ADR, Atlantic Richfield Co.,
Avon Products Inc. and GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``To activists on the left you will have to justify holding the
stock of corporations tied to pollution, animal testing, red-lining
and armament sales to developing nations,'' Ehrhardt said. ``From
the right you will be assaulted for holding the stock of companies
that provide domestic partner benefits and cover the health care of
women who choose to terminate pregnancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie said Ehrhardt and other representatives of the Texas
Freedom Network raised ``a very legitimate question'' about whether
the board has headed into a dangerous area of examining the
morality of all its investments. And he said he does not not know
the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be the moral compass of this state, and
shouldn't be,'' he said. ``We're standing on the edge of that
slippery slope. ... How long we can stand there, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said it was a good question whether the Permanent School
Fund ought to divest itself of stock in companies like Harrah's and
those that produce alcohol and beer, but that he is not ready to
re-examine all of the holdings in the $17.6 billion Permanent
School Fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
State Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, in a statement opposing
divestiture, said, ``I think most Texas parents consider alcohol
and gambling to be a greater danger to the moral fiber of their
children than `Mulan.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One brokerage analyst who follows Disney stock said it would be
a mistake to sell an investment in the entertainment giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very bullish on Disney,'' said Linda Bannister, analyst at
Edward Jones in St. Louis, enthusiastically noting that Disney is
planning to enter the cruise line business at a time when aging
baby boomers and other demographic factors are ``really playing
into the cruise lines' hands.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Disney stock chalked up an investment return of 45
percent in the last year, easily surpassing the 29.7 percent return
of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index of large companies, a key
investment benchmark. The total return includes dividends and stock
price appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Disney stock closed Thursday at 111 1/4, up 2 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But an official with the Social Investment forum in Washington,
D.C., praised the committee vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for investors to take a stand on important
social and environmental concerns,'' said Alisa Gravitz of the
Forum, a nonprofit association of people in the investment
industry. It has about 500 members nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Gravitz said good portfolio managers can find other, morally
acceptable investments that will match or exceed the return that
Disney stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas school fund began purchasing Disney stock in 1996, and
since then has seen a total return of 108 percent, or 48 percent
annualized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is over the long term will Disney management
start changing their practices,'' Gravitz said. ``Our experience
has been that when a group of shareholders make a commitment and
work with the company over time that you see change down the line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
