<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S TOUGHEST SHERIFF TUSSLES WITH HAIRDRESSER 
 F 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINA LEONARD AND RACHEL OCHOA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ America's Toughest Sheriff went toe-to-toe with a
drunken hairdresser Wednesday night and came out a winner, though
not without help.
</P>
<P>
   And not without receiving a blow to the throat and a reminder
that good deeds sometimes reap bad results.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Sean Huskisson of Giggles Hair Salon apologized
from jail for punching Sheriff Joe Arpaio and two other officers as
they tried to prevent him from driving away from a Scottsdale
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Huskisson, 27, said he doesn't even remember tussling with
Arpaio, aide Dave Hendershott and a Scottsdale police officer in
the parking lot of When in Naples restaurant about 9 p.m.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   `'All I remember is waking up in a holding cell this morning,''
said Huskisson, who was arrested on suspicion of aggravated
assault, resisting arrest and disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what caused the situation to arise ... I don't
have a clue as to what happened.'' Later, he added: ``I meant no
harm. I apologize.``
</P>
<P>
   But Arpaio, who said Huskisson had ``super-strength,'' described
the incident differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was personal, because nothing (occurred) until he
saw me and started screaming and swearing,'' the sheriff said.
Huskisson first started fighting with Hendershott, Arpaio said, but
``when he saw me, something went crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio, his wife, Ava, and Hendershott, the department's
Director of Development and Operations, were leaving the restaurant
in the 7000 block of E. Shea Boulevard when they noticed Huskisson,
who was with three friends, stumbling toward his car, police said.
</P>
<P>
   When Hendershott attempted to stop the man from driving, a
struggle ensued, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It worsened after Huskisson noticed the sheriff, Arpaio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started swinging at me - I won't say what he said - but
evidently he knew who the sheriff was,'' Arpaio said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hendershott and Arpaio suffered minor injuries - sore
muscles, a few bruises.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a swing in on my Adam's apple right here,'' Arpaio
said, pointing to his throat. ``He got in a good shot.``
</P>
<P>
   Stan Levine, who witnessed the attack, said Arpaio and
Hendershott were just trying to prevent a drunk from causing
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sheriff Arpaio) really saved these people's lives and other
people's lives too. If that fellow got behind the wheel, it could
have very well been a fatality,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   Huskisson was so intoxicated he could hardly walk, Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   Huskisson, whose blood-alcohol level was 0.186, said he started
drinking with friends about 6 p.m. He had a couple martinis, but
doesn't remember anything else.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Scottsdale police report, the friends were
leaving Such is Life Bar when Huskisson and his wife began arguing
over the car keys.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing this, Hendershott, who stands 5 feet 11 and weighs well
over 200 pounds, stepped in to help. While he was trying to subdue
Huskisson, who is 5 feet 9 inches, 170 pounds, the suspect saw
Arpaio and tried to approach him. The sheriff is 5 feet 9 inches
and 195 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to fight through me and his two friends to get
to the sheriff,`` Hendershott said.
</P>
<P>
   It finally took Hendershott, Arpaio, Huskisson's two friends and
a Scottsdale police officer to control Huskisson, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Hendershott said he was hit in the head and choked with his
necktie. Huskisson woke up at the Scottsdale police department
Thursday morning with scrapes and bruises, but no memory of the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   `'That doesn't surprise me,'' Hendershott said. ``Last night, he
sure remembered the sheriff. He went after the sheriff three
times.``
</P>
<P>
   Of Arpaio, Huskisson said his opinion is ``neither here nor
there.``
</P>
<P>
   A stylist at Giggles said Huskisson is ``one of the best
hairstylists in Scottsdale'' and doesn't believe he would attack
the sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who asked to remain anonymous, said Huskisson just had
a baby girl and is a very nice person.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The press) is already tearing him up and he doesn't deserve
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's deputies said they see no connection between
Wednesday's fight and past death threats against Arpaio, including
a May 11 threat that was broadcast on the Sheriff's Office radio
frequencies.
</P>
<P>
   In that incident, a male voice or voices said, among other
things, ``Joe Arpaio. . .I'm goin' to kill him,'' and ``I'm going
to put a bullet in your brain.''
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast included details about how an attack was to be
carried out. Deputies say they're especially worried that whoever
made the threat had enough inside knowledge of the Sheriff's Office
communications to get into the system.
</P>
<P>
   Of the latest incident, Arpaio said he's glad Huskisson didn't
drive, but comes away with a sobering realization: ``I'm beginning
to learn there are people out there that do not like me.'' &QL; 
Christina Leonard can be reached at 444-8995 or at
christina.leonard(at)pni.com via e-mail. Chuck Kelly contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
