<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8343 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-HMO-BILL-BOS &LR;      07-09 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-HMO-BILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS TURN UP HEAT ON HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For two years, opinion polls have signaled that
voters are dissatisfied with their health maintenance organizations
and want greater freedom in choosing doctors and seeking
treatments. Now, with the November elections approaching,
politicians are turning HMO reform into a major campaign issue, one
that could soon swamp the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   From California to Georgia, House and Senate candidates are
bashing HMOs in television ads. And in Congress, Republican leaders
who once balked at new HMO rules are rushing to write their own
bill, fearful that Democrats have beaten them to a winning campaign
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is incredibly potent,'' said Mark Mellman, a
Democratic pollster. ``I don't think there will be a Senate race, a
congressional race or a gubernatorial race this year where this
issue is not debated in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have long favored new rules on HMOs, in some measure
as a reaction to media accounts of insurers denying patients needed
medical care and limiting their ability to pick their own doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Support for new HMO regulations marks a change of heart for
Republicans leaders in Congress. Last November, Senate GOP leader
Trent Lott warned insurance and employer groups to prepare for
``war'' against new HMO rules, and his office reportedly told
lobbyists to ``get off your butts, get off your wallets'' to
prepare for the battle. Now Republcians feel they must put forth
some kind of HMO legisiation to counter the Democratic initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60 percent of all Americans get health coverage through
managed care programs. Under the most prominent Democratic plan,
HMOs would have to allow patients to see a doctor out of the HMO
network, at no extra charge, if there is no appropriate doctor in
the network. Patients would have the right to appeal HMO treatment
decisions to an outside panel. HMOs would have to pay emergency
room bills if ``a prudent layperson'' thought the hospital visit
was necessary. The most controverisal provision allows patients to
sue HMOs that deny them needed care, a right most patients do not
have today.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic proposal is tougher on HMOs than are most state
laws, and it is more far-reaching than a proposal now before the
Massachusetts legislature.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans are proposing a narrower bill that does not
include the right to sue an HMO for withholding treatment. Senate
Republicans have not yet unveiled their bill, but it is expected to
look similar to the House GOP proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the insurance industry is running TV and print
advertisements opposing any new federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   One HMO group, the American Association of Health Plans, says it
has spent about $2 million on a public relations campaign opposing
new federal rules. ``We're going to be investing a lot more as we
go through the year. It will be significant,'' said Mark Merritt,
the group's chief of strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers say that most people are satisfied with their health
plans, and that the new federal rules will drive up costs and force
some employers to cut health benefits. ``Nearly two million
Americans could lose health coverage,'' claims one AAHP television
ad, which accuses politicians of bashing HMOs merely to win votes.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers alone may not match the $40 million that tobacco
companies reportedly spent to help kill this year's tobacco bill.
But the pricetag of the HMO debate is sure to rise as candidates
seize on it as an issue for this year's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the candidates are going to spend a fortune on this,''
said Ron Pollack of Families USA, a consumer group that supports
new HMO regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates have already started. ``If you can choose who
changes the oil in your car, you should be able to choose who
delivers your baby,'' says Roy Barnes, a Democratic candidate for
Georgia governor, in a TV ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have led a successful fight to let doctors, not insurance
companies, decide how long women stay in the hospital after a
mastectomy,'' says Jan Schakowsky, a Democratic congressional
candidate in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   While the rhetoric may sound familiar, some analysts warn that
parallels to the fight over President Clinton's 1993 health reform
plan are limited.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, more people belong to HMOs than in 1993, and some
pollsters say many of them are anxious about their health care. And
this time, their anger is focused on one villain: the HMO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, doctors are not seen as the greedy ones,'' said Bob
Castro, a Republican pollster, at a health politics forum Thursday.
``There has been a blame-shift to the insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   That stands in contrast to the failed 1993 &UR;  &LR; effort, when
patients, businesses and health providers all felt they would have
to sacrifice something to institute a new health care system, said
Pollack of Families USA. ``This time, no one feels their ox is
being gored, except for the HMOs -- and no one cares about them,''
Pollack said. ``In fact, that makes it better, because the HMOs are
unpopular.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said Mellman, Democrats can cast their proposal as
the government using its policing and regulatory powers to set new
rules for HMOs. By contrast, voters saw the Clinton plan as using
the government's ``bureaucratic and programmatic powers'' to set up
a large new bureacracy, which many opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is percolating not only in this year's congressional
campaigns but in state races as well. On Wednesday, Bob Taft, a
Republican candidate for the governor of Ohio, backed part of a
Democratic rival's health care plan, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky, Representative Jim Bunning faces criticism from his
opponent in a US Senate race for backing away from a bill that
would have imposed tough rules on HMOs. Bunning had signed on as a
co-sponsor of the bill, then withdrew his name.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Senate, Democrats have stalled a variety of
legislation by threatening to attach their managed-care proposal to
nearly every bill that comes to the floor. The threat forced
Republican leaders to set aside an appropriations bill for the
Veterans Administration, and it is partly responsible for forcing
Republicans to delay action on a product liability bill that they
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have said that Lott, the GOP leader, will not allow a
debate or vote on their managed care bill because it is sure to
draw support from Republican senators facing elections this fall.
Tom Daschle, the Senate Democratic leader, Thursday predicted the
measure would win ``60-some'' votes if a simple up-or-down vote was
held.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
