<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTORS-POOR-550&AMP;ADD-     07-09 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-POOR-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS TO BUY A STAKE AND RUN 2 CHICAGO HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)  (mk) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a novel effort to take control of their patients' care, a
group of physicians said Thursday that they had reached agreement
to salvage an eminent teaching and research hospital on Chicago's
South Side that had been especially rocked by the turmoil in the
nation's health care.
</P>
<P>
   The physicians and an Arizona investment firm said they would
buy the 523-bed Michael Reese Hospital and Medical Center and a
smaller hospital. The physicians, who would be minority owners,
would hold a majority of the seats on the board and would control
the hospitals' operations.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. is selling Reese and the 212-bed
Grant Hospital, in Lincoln Park, for $60 million to the physicians
and Doctors Community Healthcare Corp. of Scottsdale, Ariz., and a
company that is buying debt owed the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia, the latest of three owners in a decade, is under
federal investigation for fraudulent billing practices, and the
sale is part of a vast reorganization of the company. Columbia
bought eight hospitals in the Chicago area in a now abandoned
effort to become a major presence in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Health care industry analysts said the transaction was another
approach in physicians' efforts to unite to fight managed
care-organizations and for-profit hospital chains, like Columbia,
which have chipped away at their incomes and patient care
prerogatives.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians have often formed and bought hospitals, but most are
small, suburban and specialized. The Reese venture is unusual for
its size and its focus on the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   ``That arrangement _ a silent corporate partner giving
physicians control over everything but the budgeting aspect _
that's unusual,'' said Richard Wade, senior vice president and
chief spokesman for the American Hospital Association.
</P>
<P>
   But in a climate of cost constraint, Wade asked, ``will they be
able to make the tough decisions to secure the future of the
institution?''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said they expected at least 200 of 1,200 affiliated
physicians to pay $10,000 to $30,000 each to buy 20 percent
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tuft, chairman and principal owner of the investment firm,
said he would have the last word on the annual budget. The
hospitals' chief executive will report to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Reese Hospital, one of Chicago's biggest hospitals,
occupies about 40 acres along Lake Michigan. It was established in
1881 by an immigrant German Jew and California real estate
developer, Michael Reese, to serve the city's growing Jewish
population.
</P>
<P>
   But in time, Jews moved beyond the inner city, to the North
Shore. Financial support stalled and new settlers, blacks and
Mexican-Americans, moved into the South Side. About 10 years ago,
the owners sold the company to a managed care organization, Humana,
which sold the hospital in 1993 to Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors complained that both owners let facilities and services
decline. With the spread of managed care and the expanded use of
outpatient care, Chicago, like most cities, found itself with more
hospital beds than it needed. Reese, the doctors feared, would be
closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there's excess supply,'' said Dr. Claudia Fegan, an
internist and Reese's medical director. ``But this is about access.
This population, on the South Side, is not a population that would
be served if we go away.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   About 25 percent of the hospital's patents are covered by
Medicaid, the state-federal health program for the poor, and 35
percent, many of whom are also poor, by Medicare, the program for
the elderly, Dr. Enrique Beckmann said. Beckmann is a pathologist
and president of Reese-Grant Acquisition Group, which first
approached Tuft about buying the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main focus,'' Beckmann said, ``has been to make sure we
don't lose this community asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Reese physicians questioned whether any for-profit investor
would provide the financing and support they said Reese needs.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Humana and Columbia, Dr. Quentin Young, an internist and
president of the American Public Health Association, said: ``I just
happen to believe that when you add `for-profit' the record is
clear. You get very bad results.'' Tuft, who has made similar
investments in three smaller hospitals in Massachusetts, California
and Washington, D.C., said he hoped to prove otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that health care is very, very, very local,'' he
said. ``We look at ourselves as stewards of health care for the
community, and that means keeping the entity viable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
