<P>
   ATTN: Managing editors, weekend editors, automotive editors,
business editors
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following automotive and features.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmissions of these stories, please call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-BOS (Undated) _ When last we left the intrepid
columnist, he was asleep in a diesel truck somewhere near
Rochester, N.Y., with almost 2,000 miles remaining to his
destination and three days to get there. Part II. By John R. White.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CAR-LEASE-NYT (Undated) _ What to look out for when
returning a car coming off lease. By Andrea Adelson.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-CORVETTE-NYT (Undated) _ No modern car on the American
road is more red-, white- and blue-blooded than the Chevrolet
Corvette. Introduced as a 1953 model, it was Americas first true,
mass-produced sportscar _ the United States' answer to the
pint-size roadsters that were being imported from Europe. And the
Corvette remains the only American sports car to stand the test of
time. A million-plus Corvettes have been built in more than four
decades, more than any other single sports car ever. By Michelle
Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-CADILLAC-NYT (Undated) _ After decades in which
Cadillac represented the epitome of American luxury cars, it will
start selling its first truck this fall, a sport utility vehicle
similar to the Chevrolet Tahoe and GMC Yukon. By Leonard M. Apcar.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ Not everyone can afford a
car like the $67,400 Jaguar XJR sedan. But after a few minutes
behind the wheel of this baby, some of you just might start running
some numbers though your head to see if you could somehow pull it
off. Perhaps you don't really need that bigger house, fancy motor
home, or sleek new sailboat after all _ especially with the XJR
beckoning. By G. Chambers Williams III.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART (Undated) _ A lot of convertibles shake, rattle and
roll. They leak and squeak, and, without the integral bracing of
solid tops, they flex like sponges when you wring them out on
bouncy roads. Outside the Sun Belt, they require 6 to 10 months of
compromise for 2 to 6 months of wind-blown freedom. This accepted
wisdom is fast becoming out of date. By James G. Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-BMW (Undated) _ A feisty terrier in a dog-eat-dog
business, BMW knows something about survival of the fittest. Its
ever-mutating 3-Series, which accounts for 44 percent of overall
sales, has become a genus with 31 species sold around the world. By
James G. Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
