<HEADLINE>
WOODWARD PURSUES `COME AND GET ME' STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nearly broke and an ocean away, Louise Woodward seems
to have decided to hold up her hands and let the Eappen family try
to collect a civil judgment against her, legal analysts said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strategy,'' said Boston attorney Thomas Hoopes. ``This
way she doesn't have to sit down and negiotiate. She just says
`Come and get me, but I don't have anything anyway.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Telling her family's attorney in England that she could not
afford to fund her defense, Woodward removed herself from the first
step in the civil suit pending against her in a U.S. District
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Now a judge will decide how much the life of baby Matthew Eappen
was worth, as his parents, Sunil and Deborah, try to prevent the au
pair convicted of killing their son from benefiting from the sale
of her story.
</P>
<P>
   Once a dollar amount is set in the civil suit, it would be
difficult for the Eappens to prevent Woodward from receiving money
from a media outlet for her story, so long as she is not paid in
the United States, or by a company covered by US law, said Boston
attorney Roderick MacLeish, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are open issues about the international enforcement of a
judgment,'' he said, referring to a treaty currently pending before
the U.S. Senate that would make it easier to collect international
civil judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, cases are examined by British courts on an individual
basis, and, in general, they are not enforced, according to several
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens could choose to file suit in England, MacLeish said,
to help ensure the collection of any funds Woodward might receive.
But it would be more likely that they would choose to sue any media
outlet that might offer money to the former au pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a sizeable verdict, it probably won't be
meaningless, because it will prevent Louise Woodward from doing
business with any enity that is subject to the jurisdiction of the
U.S. courts,'' MacLeish said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may get a little tricky because everyone will be alert to
this,'' he said. ``So money could change hands without everyone
knowing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Joseph Balliro, Jr. said that if Woodward changed her
mind, and decided to fight the case after all, she could argue for
a special dispensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in another country, and it makes it susbsantially
difficult for her to attend to a matter in federal court,'' Balliro
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for defendants in civil suits to default,
specialists say, though it is far less likely to occur in cases of
wrongful death because defendants usually feel their reputation is
at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hoopes: ``What's uncommon about this is that you have
someone who protested her innocence to the whole world, and now the
protestation has collapsed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
