<SLUG> BC-ARBITRATION-MARKETPLACE-ART-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: BIG BOARD BROKERS WIN MORE IN ARBITRATION THAN THEY
LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Stock Exchange may be the market of
choice for investors who want the best execution of their
securities trades.
</P>
<P>
   But Jonathan Kord Lagemann, a securities lawyer in New York,
says those lodging complaints against their brokers appear less
likely to succeed at the Exchange's arbitration department.
</P>
<P>
   He bases his conclusion on the results of customer arbitration
cases filed at nine self-regulatory securities organizations since
1980. Lagemann found that the percentage of arbitration hearings
held by regulators at the Big Board that led to awards for
customers fell to 41.4 percent last year from 51.3 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is the opposite at the nation's biggest
self-regulatory organization, the National Association of
Securities Dealers, which operates the Nasdaq market. Last year,
58.4 percent of the customers who brought complaints against
brokerages there won something. In 1990, 54 percent did.
</P>
<P>
   Lagemann recently pointed out this widening gap between the two
exchanges in a letter to the Securities and Exchange Commission.
Chris Ullman, a spokesman for the commission, said: ``While
statistics can tell different stories, this study has piqued our
interest, and we are going to look into it. We are not going to
wait until the next scheduled review of the New York Stock
Exchange.'' The SEC reviews arbitration procedures at each
self-regulatory organization about every two years.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitration information that Lagemann consulted goes back to
1980 and was compiled by the Securities Industry Conference on
Arbitration, a rule-making body formed at the Securities and
Exchange Commission's behest in 1976. It includes customer cases
that went before the New York Stock Exchange, the American Stock
Exchange, the National Association of Securities Dealers, as well
as the regional exchanges and the Municipal Securities Rulemaking
Board.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 6,665 arbitration cases were filed by customers
against their brokerage firms last year. (Brokerage customers are
generally required to resolve disputes in arbitration rather than
in the courts under the agreement they sign with their brokers upon
opening an account.) The bulk of the cases filed last year _ 90
percent, or 5,997 _ went to regulators at the NASD. A distant
second was the Big Board, which received 546.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of cases received by the NASD in this bull
market have more than doubled in the last decade, they have fallen
by 52 percent at the Big Board. The NASD might be expected to
handle the most arbitration cases, since it oversees 5,573 firms
nationwide. The New York Stock Exchange oversees 441 member firms,
and only 283 of those conduct business with public customers.
</P>
<P>
   Because the number of cases is so much smaller at the Big Board,
its win rates may be more volatile as well. Just a few more
customer victories, for example, can push up its win rate far more
than they could at the NASD.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the trend is clear. In 1996, customers arbitrating at the
Big Board won only 33.6 percent of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Like most securities lawyers contacted for this article,
Lagemann gives the New York Stock Exchange high marks for
efficiency and staff professionalism in its handling of arbitration
cases. ``In all respects other than the win rates, arbitrating at
the New York Stock Exchange is far preferable,'' Lagemann said.
``The arbitration counsel are courteous, they get cases heard in
six or seven months, administratively it is so much better.''
</P>
<P>
   James E. Buck, senior vice president and secretary of the New
York Stock Exchange, said that the question should not be why the
Big Board has lower win rates, but why the NASD has higher victory
rates. ``The New York Stock Exchange has the highest regulatory
standards, so we tend to have the best firms, and the fewest major
mishaps,'' he said. ``All of the recent cases, the debacles that
have spawned large numbers of arbitration cases, Stratton Oakmont,
Hanover Sterling, Bevill Bressler, First Jersey Securities,'' have
been NASD firms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Buck is correct about this. And, for comparison purposes, data
are not available on the win rates for firms that are members of
both the New York Stock Exchange and the NASD, which would
eliminate the effect of more risky penny stock firms in the NASD.
</P>
<P>
   Penny-stock firms, though, are far from new for the NASD. Back
in the late 1980s, when Blinder Robinson, Stuart James and other
notorious penny-stock firms were alive and kicking, the customer
arbitration results between the two organizations were comparable.
</P>
<P>
   When a case is brought to the New York Stock Exchange, the
exchange's arbitration counsel picks a three-person panel to rule.
The plaintiff can reject any of the people selected for cause and
is allowed to reject one, if need be, without supplying a reason.
</P>
<P>
   Are there differences between the panels? Some lawyers think so.
Lewis Lowenfels, a securities lawyer in New York who has brought
many arbitration cases said: ``In my experience, arbitration panels
at the NASD are more customer oriented. They seem to be more of a
populist forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Bentley, an attorney in Newark, N.J., specializing in
arbitration matters was, in the early 1980s, arbitration counsel at
the New York Stock Exchange. What concerns him about the current
gap in win rates is that it may point to too much control by the
Exchange's arbitration counsel in the selection of the panel. ``If
they went to a random selection process, they would take that
potential for prejudice out of the system,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
