<SLUG> BC-AVIATION-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. MCCAIN PRAISED, CRITICIZED FOR BILL TO CUT AIRCRAFT  NOISE
OVER PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain was applauded Thursday for a bill
to reduce aircraft noise over national parks, but then he was
accused of using the same bill to help a Phoenix-based airline and
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republican won approval of the Senate Commerce,
Science and Transportation Committee, which he heads, for a measure
that would allow greater federal control over commercial air-tour
operators.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain was criticized by citizens' groups opposed to another
provision in the bill designed to enhance airline competition by
permitting more takeoffs and landings at such airports as Chicago's
O'Hare and Washington's Reagan National.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would grant Phoenix-based America West Airlines what it
has long sought from Congress: the opportunity to fly nonstop from
Phoenix to Washington's Reagan National Airport, a key business
destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have impugned my motives, suggesting that my secret
purpose is to convenience my own travel between Washington and
Arizona,'' McCain said in a statement prepared when the bill was
introduced. ``I find this charge wearisome and offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even so,'' McCain continued, ``to allay these concerns, I have
pledged not to take a nonstop flight from (Reagan National) to
Arizona should such an opportunity ever result from this
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Not satisfied, members of several groups accused McCain of
ignoring local plans to limit the expansion of Reagan National,
which is just across the Potomac River from the capital, and to
direct more flights to a suburban airport, Dulles International.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is trying to just run roughshod over the local population''
in the District of Columbia area, said Don MacGlashan, spokesman
for Citizens for the Abatement of Aircraft Noise.
</P>
<P>
   MacGlashan said it was ``interesting'' that America West would
benefit from the bill. ``Obviously, it will open up a lot of things
for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain spokeswoman Nancy Ives said that relaxing the
flight-mileage rule that was holding America West back ``is for the
benefit of travelers across the nation, not for any one airline.''
The Transportation Department would still need to certify that
exemptions to the rule are in the consumer interest.
</P>
<P>
   America West flies nonstop to Dulles International but must make
a stop from the West before landing at Reagan National.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's bill would lift that restriction by allowing exemptions
to a rule forbidding carriers from flying into Reagan National from
a distance greater than 1,250 miles. The rule is designed partly to
steer traffic toward the newer Dulles airport.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, McCain aides said that adding more flights _ and,
in the one case, allowing them to fly a longer distance _ is
designed to increase airline-industry competition, resulting in
better service and lower fares. Other members of the Commerce
Committee agreed with McCain's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Bill Franke, chairman and chief executive officer of
America West Holdings Corp., said that flying nonstop to Reagan
National from Arizona ``would be really significant.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said last year that, to mollify critics, he would agree
to a continued ban on nonstop flights from Arizona to Reagan
National. But he decided instead merely to apply the ban to his own
travel so as not to punish others, according to Ives.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won plaudits for the park overflights provision, which
would require companies to apply to the federal government for
authority to conduct air tours over national parks.
</P>
<P>
   However, the bill wouldn't apply to Grand Canyon National Park,
which has its own air-route requirements. Environmental groups have
challenged those requirements in federal court, contending they are
not stringent enough to restore the canyon's natural quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Although approving the bill, the Commerce Committee planned to
return to consider some minor amendments next week.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Barker can be reached at 202-662-7264 or at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com via the Internet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
