<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8362 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATE-TERM-ABORTION-BO     07-09 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATE-TERM-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAR ABORTION INTENSIFIES PARTIAL-BIRTH DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV   AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Partway through the procedure, a doctor realized the
late-term fetus he was aborting was in fact a full-term baby and
delivered the infant instead. The error has angered activists on
both sides of the issue and intensified the fight over abortions
performed well into a woman's pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise birth late last month came after ultrasound testing
at the A-Z Women's Center, which terminates pregnancies through the
24th week, showed the teenage mother was 23.6 weeks pregnant,
Phoenix police said. But the doctor, who has had run-ins with
Arizona medical authorities before, delivered a 37-week-old baby
girl weighing 6 pounds, 2 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's skull was fractured and she had lacerations on her
face, but she showed no signs of brain damage, Phoenix police said.
A Texas couple now plans to adopt her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This highlights the fine line between where you separate life
from death and it will do nothing but help the cause,'' said Robert
Trynham, spokesman for Senator Rick Santorum, the Pennsylvania
Republican who last year sponsored a bill banning so-called
partial-birth abortions, which passed the House and Senate but was
vetoed by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of a woman's right to an abortion, even late in
her pregnancy, said the potentially fatal error in Phoenix had
nothing to do with abortion, everything to do with medical
ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shouldn't have anything to do with partial-birth
abortion,'' said Betsy Cavendish, legal director of the National
Abortion Rights Action League, which supports reproductive rights.
``This was a case of malpractice. ... It appears something went
awry and those who are responsible will be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident is also likely to resound in Washington, where
legislators are preparing to take up the issue of late-term
abortions once again.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two weeks, on July 23, the House is scheduled to
vote whether to override Clinton's veto; the Senate is expected to
take up the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act, which would forbid the
procedure except to save a mother's life, in September. A
two-thirds majority is needed in both chambers to override the
veto, and the Senate vote is expected to be tight.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, employees at the A-Z Women's Center, housed in a
concrete block-and-stucco building beside a medical center, turned
away all questions about the baby's unexpected birth Thursday. Not
a single patient sat in the clinic's waiting room, which is filled
with row after row of pastel-flecked chairs and must be entered
through a thatched steel cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are cooperating 100 percent with police,'' said a woman in
a white medical coat.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Biskind, who delivered the child, could not be reached
for comment at his home in Scottsdale. But the Arizona Board of
Medical Examiners said it has had contact with him before; Biskind,
licensed in Arizona since 1981, was censured by the agency for
``gross neglect'' two years ago because a 26-year-old woman left
the clinic after an abortion and bled to death, records indicate.
</P>
<P>
   A complaint over quality of care is pending against Biskind, and
his file at the medical board contains a ``letter of concern'' over
the inappropriate prescribing of medicine and another for
misdiagnosis or mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police are investigating the baby's birth on June 30,
but are uncertain whether any laws were broken, said Sergeant Mike
Torres. At the same time, Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley
would like a chance to investigate and hopes police refer the case
on to his office, said spokesman Bill Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Under the criminal code, a Phoenix physician may not attempt to
abort a viable fetus unless a second physician is on hand to take
over in case a live birth occurs. Performing an abortion after 26
weeks is illegal in Arizona, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, 17, went to the clinic after a home pregnancy test
result was positive, police said, and an ultrasound was performed.
The mother, whose identity was not disclosed, returned the next day
to undergo a late-term abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question really is what did (Biskind) know and when did he
know it,'' said one local law enforcement official, who requested
anonymity. ``Of course, his answer will be: `It came as a total
shock to me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although no criminal charges have been filed, the fact that the
mother was 17 years old and that the clinic mistook a baby for a
fetus is expected to add to the debate over the controversial but
legal procedure that opponents call partial-birth abortion. During
the procedure, the fetus's skull is collapsed and then the now-dead
fetus is delivered through the birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   The question of wrongly estimating the fetus's age has not been
a focus of past debate; abortion foes did not make it an issue
Thursday. Instead, the debate has centered on the morality of
aborting a late-term fetus whose life doctors would try to save
under other circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``That a doctor made a mistake is not the issue,'' said Douglas
Johnson, legislative director of the National Right to Life
Committee, a group that opposes all forms of abortion. ``It is the
routine practice of killing a baby at 5 months.''
</P>
<P>
   The half-page advertisement for A-Z Women's Center in the Yellow
Pages promotes the clinic as ``the only Abortion Provider in
Arizona up to 24 weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates and opponents, however, said that other clinics and
hospitals in the area perform the procedure but that most decline
to advertise for fear of attracting antiabortion demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason this baby is getting so much attention is that
it lived,'' said Dr. Carolyn Gerster, chairwoman for Arizona Right
to Life, a former member of the state medical board and a sometime
demonstrator outside the A-Z clinic. ``It will certainly focus
attention on the issue and maybe get more people to ask, `What's
the cut-off for performing abortions.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like Gerster, abortion opponents around the country seized on
the baby's birth to draw attention to abortion in general and
partial-birth abortions in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case reminds us of the truth about abortion _ that
innocent lives are taken, in some cases right up until the time of
delivery,'' Representative Charles T. Canady, a Florida Republican
who sponsored the House bill, said in a prepared statement.
``Miraculously, in this instance, a little girl who was sentenced
to die is alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion-rights advocates noted that Biskind halted the abortion
as soon as he realized the fetus was viable outside the womb. The
newborn was then taken to Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center
across the street from the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody in the clinic made a mistake and corrected it,'' said
Louise Melling, associate director of the ACLU Reproductive Freedom
Project. ``They acted exactly as you would want people to act. They
took care of this delivery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
