<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIPOLLINI HAS ONE GOAL: JUST LOOK AT HIS BICYCLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ Mario Cipollini, the biggest hot dog outside
the dreams of Oscar Mayer, has come to Ireland for the start of the
Tour de France with a bicycle as green as a shamrock.
</P>
<P>
   The star Italian sprinter and showman arrived Thursday with his
Saeco teammates and the 20 other teams of nine men each who will
set off Saturday in the three-week race. The riders began showing
up for cursory medical examinations at Dublin Castle on Thursday
afternoon and few are very likely to attract more attention than
Cipollini.
</P>
<P>
   Cipollini knows no Gaelic and less English, so he will be spared
explaining to the natives that his bicycle was not painted in honor
of the Emerald Isle. Like his yellow bicycle, it was painted in
honor of Cipollini.
</P>
<P>
   He flaunted the yellow bicycle last year during the two days
that he wore the yellow jersey of the Tour's leader. This year his
eye is on the green jersey of the points leader, hence the green
bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   A notoriously feeble climber, Cipollini does not have a bicycle
with the red polka dots that denote the king of the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   For all his sartorial bluster, his pet cheetah and Via Veneto
scruffy good looks, the 31-year-old Cipollini is surprisingly
soft-spoken. While he may refer to himself as the Lion King or Il
Magnifico, he does not say he is the sport's best sprinter. He
agrees, however, with anybody who does say so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy being among the best for 10 years,'' he said
during the Giro, where he tied Eddy Merckx's career record of 25
stage victories. ``It's more difficult every year for me to train,
to suffer. My biggest boost is that I win, which makes it
worthwhile. I still feel an indescribable joy when I do.''
</P>
<P>
   And he keeps winning. After his triumphs in the Giro early in
June, he went to Spain and won four stages there in the Tour of
Catalonia, his tuneup for the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   His overall strategy here will be the same as last year: finish
high in the short prologue on Saturday and then try to win the
first road race around Dublin on Sunday or the second stage to Cork
on Monday, gaining enough bonus seconds for victory to don the
yellow jersey again and wear it to France on Tuesday. Until July
18, the Tour's terrain will be flat _ ideal for sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Cipollini will rely on his Saeco teammates to
overtake any breakaways and power him to the front near the mass
finish. Saving energy, he will tuck in behind his leadout man, Gian
Mateo Fagnini _ a good enough sprinter himself to have won two
stages in the last Giro _ and then burst past him and presumably
everybody else with 100 or 150 meters left.
</P>
<P>
   Any sprint finish in the top 25 of the 189-man field will also
give him the points, on a sliding scale of 35 down to 1, that count
toward the green jersey. That is Cipollini's main goal in this
Tour, he says, but to win the jersey, not just keep it for a few
days, he will have to get over the Pyrenees and Alps and make it to
Paris Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   In his four previous Tours, citing the heat, lack of motivation
and general weariness, he has been unable to finish. ``They say I
can't do it,'' he said, ``but I think I can. When I get something
in my head, I go for it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
