<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRONG RETAIL SALES PUSH SHARES OF RETAILERS HIGHER
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales rose 4.4 percent in June, down from the 7.1 percent
increase in May and the 10.2 percent gain in April. And not every
chainparticipated in the sales gains. J.C. Penney, for example,
announced that its sales fell 2.1 percent and second-quarter
earnings would be lower than expected as a result. But shares of
retail companies have jumped, as indicated by the Standard &AMP; Poor's
retail stores index, which is up 54.8 percent so far this year,
compared with a 19.39 percent gain in the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE APPROVES IRS OVERHAUL
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved legislation overhauling the Internal Revenue
Service. The measure, which was approved by the House late last
month, now goes to President Clinton, who has said he will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA DELAYS SALE OF OIL COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has postponed the sale of its state oil
company, Rosneft, for the second time because of a lack of bidders,
which was attributed to the faltering Russian economy and plunging
world oil prices. The Government, which expects to sell a
controlling interest in the company for at least $1.6 billion, will
put it up for sale this fall.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ SETS ANOTHER RECORD HIGH
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 85.19 points, to 9,089.78,
and the Nasdaq composite index posted its second consecutive record
close, rising 4.43 points, to 1,939.82. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
composite index of 500 stocks fell 7.82 points, to 1,158.56. DuPont
and other companies issued warnings on their earnings that sent
investors scrambling to grab some profits.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont announced that its second-quarter earnings would be 10
percent to 15 percent lower than the 99 cents a share it earned in
the comparable period last year, sending shares of the chemical
company down $7. DuPont attributed the lowered earnings
expectations to problems with its crop protection products
business, prompted by the Asian financial crisis and weather and
pricing pressures in North America.
</P>
<P>
   TREASURY PRICES RISE
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices made modest gains Thursday, bolstered by a
strong dollar. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.60
percent from 5.62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DETAILS EMERGE IN ARCHER INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   After more than three years of being shrouded in secrecy,
evidence from the government's investigation of a huge price-fixing
conspiracy involving Archer Daniels Midland is emerging as the
first criminal case stemming from the inquiry heads to trial.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYER SEES ARBITRATION GAP
</P>
<P>
   A securities lawyer who studied customer arbitration cases filed
at nine securities organizations says investors lodging complaints
against their brokers appear less likely to succeed at the New York
Stock Exchange's arbitration department than they have in the past.
The trend is the opposite at the National Association of Securities
Dealers, which operates the Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK MUTUAL FUNDS ATTRACTED CASH
</P>
<P>
   Investors increased their purchases of stock mutual funds by an
estimated $24 billion in June. Investments in bond and so-called
hybrid mutual funds declined to an estimated $6.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   DUNLAP CALLS HIS OUSTER UNFAIR
</P>
<P>
   Albert Dunlap, who was dismissed last month as chairman of
Sunbeam, called his ouster unfair and said he was certain he would
have turned the small-appliance company around next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
