<SLUG> BC-BBO-SELIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL SELIG THE COMMISH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes commissioner history text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ He grew up wanting to be like Joe DiMaggio. Instead,
after six years of indecision, Bud Selig has become Fay Vincent's
replacement as commissioner of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latest twist in a fascinating career for Selig, who
has been majority owner and chief executive officer of the
Milwaukee Brewers for 33 years and interim baseball commissioner
since September 1992. By a 30-0 vote by baseball owners here
Thursday, Selig is now fulltime commissioner. He has agreed to a 5
1/2-year contract, details of which have yet to be worked out, and
he will put his interest in the Brewers in a trust by Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Like Vincent, who was asked to resign six years ago, Selig, 63,
promised harmony among owners. But he says he also will work toward
the end of acrimony among large and small markets as well as with
the players' union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fan,'' said Selig after the vote Thursday. ``There is no
one who can love the game more than I do. It's history and
tradition and above all it's decency. We've had eight work
stoppages. We have to ensure the next generation doesn't have to
endure any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus belongs back on the field. We need to get together
and take the anger out of the system. Yes, we will have our
differences. That's part of the business. But we can work together.
And by the turn of the century you will see the greatest
renaissance in baseball history.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened Thursday was hardly historic. After six years of
service, a longer tenure than the late Bart Giamatti and Fay
Vincent combined, he is merely assuming fulltime the job that has
been his all along. Selig will have two offices, one in New York
and one in Milwaukee. Much of the day-to-day operation will be in
the hands of Paul Beeston, a former Toronto owner, who virtually
has been running baseball's central office for the last 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   Beeston, who plans to have a big role in the national and
international marketing of the game, was among those who for years
had been urging Selig to take the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be a problem,'' he said. ``Bud is a man
of integrity. Until today, it was very difficult. Before today, we
didn't know who would be the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acrimony is a problem, but I think it's realistic that we can
one day eliminate it. Right now, we're working together and we've
got to continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got great leadership,'' said Yankee owner George
Steinbrenner. ``It's leadership that has been there. Leadership
that understands the problems that owners have. I don't recall
before if we've ever had that, and we've had some very good
leadership. I'm not criticizing anybody. Selig has done well for
the small market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we hopefully have a good relationship with Don Fehr
and the union. We have labor peace, and that's good. We have a
sport on the upswing. I can sense it.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado owner Jerry McMorris, who headed baseball's search
committee, said no one interviewed was better qualified to handle
the problems that still plague baseball since the 1994 strike. As
commissioner, Selig becomes chairman of the Executive Council (of
owners), which in the absence of a commissioner had become
baseball's ruling body.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four or five challenges that Bud is very familiar
with,'' said McMorris. ``Differences in the markets and in the
payroll size of the team. International expansion and how we market
our game to keep it affordable for families. Also how to get
additional stadium facilities that are needed in different parts of
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Colangelo, the Arizona owner who also owns an NBA
franchise, sees Selig as the logical choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that history plays a significant role in baseball,''
said Colangelo. ``When you look at Bud and Paul you have two guys
who have been in the trenches. They've run franchises. They
understand the ins and out and what it takes to run a team. That's
invaluable to team operators to know they have that kind of
leadership. What you're about to see is a collective effort for
baseball to continue its rise. But will represent all of baseball _
fans, players, and the owners.''
</P>
<P>
   True to his nature, Selig put an emotional cap to his acceptance
speech. He is a long way from the days when he was called a used
car dealer from Milwaukee. Aside from the money, said to be at
least $3 million a year, he is assuming the role because it feels
it's the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a baseball man,'' said Selig. ``I've been one all my adult
life. I dreamed of being one when I was a kid. I thought I would be
the heir-apparent to Joe DiMaggio. After I saw a curveball, I knew
I had to do something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time. There is a burden to always do the right thing.
It's 33 years later, and it's time to go. It's also time, if I
can't make the shift, I should have the decency to say I just can't
do it. But I believe I can.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from Associated Press was used in this report.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE COMMISSIONERS
</P>
