<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL MARKET VALUE, YOU KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Maybe he has good reasons. Maybe there's so much bad
history between himself and the Red Sox front office that Mo Vaughn
can't see fit to play for Boston anymore. But after listening to
Vaughn explain himself, I'm having a hard time sticking up for the
big guy.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are to blame for letting it get this far, and for
busting the chops of their best player. There is a Duquette
double-standard (pre-Duke people are not to be trusted, post-Duke
people are worthy). But now that Mo has rejected, and refused to
counter-offer, a four-year, $37 million contract extension, we can
come to only one conclusion:
</P>
<P>
   The issue is market value. The issue is about what Mo makes vs.
what Albert Belle makes; about what Mo makes vs. what Gary
Sheffield makes.
</P>
<P>
   And it makes me sick.
</P>
<P>
   I love Mo as a competitor and like him as a person. Few athletes
have done for Boston what Vaughn has done off the field.
</P>
<P>
   But first he told us that this was about playing for a winner.
He said he wanted to see a commitment from the Sox front office.
They did that.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was about the length of commitment the Sox were willing
to make. They offered him only two years in the spring, which was
tantamount to a Dear John letter. A 30-year-old player with
Vaughn's resume is never offered a two-year deal. But now the Sox
are willing to commit to four years. And Vaughn's people failed to
counter, preferring to put it off until the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So now we know it's not about winning and it's not about a
long-term commitment. It's strictly about the Benjamins. And we
don't mean Mike Benjamin and family.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn calls it ``market value.'' That's a euphemism. Market
value is the silly scorekeeping that drives agents and greedy
ballplayers. Never mind where you can win, or where you are loved,
or where you want to make your home. Get the most money you can
get. Don't settle for a penny less than what people of comparable
talents are making. This is why Antoine Walker won't be a Celtic
much longer. And now it's why Mo has made up his mind to go.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he'll explain himself later, and talk about being followed
by Red Sox detectives looking for dirt. Maybe he'll tell stories
about smear campaigns by the Sox front office, wiretaps on his
phone, and Red Sox double agents posing as dancers at the Foxy
Lady. But right now we can only assume it's strictly about money.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn Thursday said, ``The bottom line is this: we are gonna
get a market deal in '98 _ what fair market value is. I'm gonna get
my market value contract in '98. Period. There's a lot of things
that take into that, but I'm going to get that. There will not be a
hometown discount.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a little touchy when asked about old remarks that he'd
stay in Boston for less if the Sox showed a commitment to winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that a year and a half ago. And we're winning. But the
market changes every day. The stock market changes every day and
people's attitudes are gonna change every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Sox have met a couple of his conditions (commitment
to winning and four-year deal), how does he explain rejecting a $37
million offer without even countering? What would he tell angry and
disappointed Red Sox fans?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't tell 'em anything, because when you try to tell 'em
something, they're never going to understand,'' Vaughn said. ``I
just have to go and play and play hard like I always have. The only
way to explain yourself is when things are done. You can't explain
yourself in the middle of a situation. 'Cuz there's no way for
people to understand. If things get done either way there'll be an
opportunity to explain yourself. Hopefully, people will
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he expect to be booed when the Sox come home to play the
Indians Wednesday night?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been booed before. No one wants to get booed. But I've
sat down with my family and I've sat down with my people and this
is the best situation we could come up with for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said we could get this deal done in a telephone
booth if everybody wants to get it done. This is not a posturing
situation. It's a situation where you're gonna do a deal, or you're
not gonna do a deal. We've been talking for two years. There's
nothing else we can say. We know what everybody looks like. We know
what their breath smells like. We've been that close. It will
happen or it won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks like it won't happen. Vaughn's going to give Sox fans
another three months of sweet swings and sweat and then he's off to
Texas, Baltimore, New York or Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   This is a complicated story. There's been a lot of irrational
positioning in both camps. Granted, the Sox waited too long and
treated Vaughn shabbily, but now Mo has to decide if he wants to
play for Boston in exchange for lifetime security or just take the
top dollar. At this hour, he's leaning toward the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Market value, you know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
