<SLUG> BC-STATES-CORRECTS-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SEN. REID STARTS LEADERSHIP PAC AS HE FIGHTS TO SAVE HIS OWN
SEAT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark D. Preston  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORRECTS FIFTH GRAPH AND SIXTH GRAPH
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 9 -- Sen. Harry Reid is openly campaigning for
a top Democratic leadership position next year, bringing many
people -- including his chief opponent -- to speculate that the
Nevada Democrat thinks he has already won this year's Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In a apparent move to win support from his colleagues to replace
retiring Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., as Senate minority whip, Reid
formed a political action committee in May to help Democrats across
the country financially with their Senate campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Reid does not deny he is interested in becoming the next whip
and said the people of Nevada would benefit if he is elected to the
leadership position. Reid points to his seniority in the Senate as
one of the main reasons discussions of an interim nuclear dump site
at Yucca Mountain came to a halt in June. And Reid said his
position on the Senate Appropriations Committee has brought
millions of dollars into the Silver State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the chairman of the Democratic Policy Committee, and I am
in line to be the next whip,'' he said. ``I think the people of the
state of Nevada are very happy I am in a leadership position and
best friends with (Senate Minority Leader) Tom Daschle.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid said there are ``a lot of reasons'' he opened the PAC three
months ago, which he said has raised about $100,000. Reid said his
PAC dubbed the Searchlight Leadership Fund has contributed to about
32 Senate campaigns including former Indiana Gov. Evan Bayh and
California Sen. Barbara Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Ensign, R-Nev., who is leaving his House seat this
year to challenge Reid, said the Democratic senator is making a
mistake if he thinks the Senate race is over five months before the
November election. And Ensign said Reid is following the same
ill-fated path of Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., who was upset by Sen.
Bill Frist, R-Tenn., in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Some political pundits speculate that Sasser was more focused on
succeeding retiring Sen. George Mitchell, D-Maine, as the next
majority leader, instead of focusing on his campaign back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Reid) is in the race for his life out here,'' Ensign said.
``We don't think he is going to be the next whip, because we don't
think he is going to be in the Senate after November.''
</P>
<P>
   Ensign said it is ideologically impossible for Reid to be part
of the ``liberal leaning'' Democratic Senate leadership team and
still represent the needs of Nevadans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevada is a very conservative state,'' Ensign said. ``When you
run for leadership positions in the Senate they normally elect more
liberal members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very typical for (Reid) to be doing one thing in
Washington and saying another (in Nevada).'' Paul Henry, chairman
of the Nevada Democratic Party, refuted Ensign's statement and said
Reid is very active on a number of issues important to Nevadans.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first day of his election, he has paid a great deal of
attention to constituent services,'' Henry said. ``This is a man
that is very much in step with the issues that concern the people
of Nevada.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Burdish, executive director for the Nevada Republican Party,
said he is not surprised Reid formed his own leadership PAC.
Burdish also said Republicans will be watching to make sure Reid
doesn't use the PAC to illegally fund his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern about him starting up a leadership PAC to fund
other campaigns is if he starts to receive campaign contributions
from the campaigns he has already given to,'' Burdish said. ``If he
is doing it to raise money for his campaign to get around FEC
contribution rules I don't think it is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., said he would support Reid if he
runs for the whip position. Bryan also said he thinks Reid will
beat Ensign, but it will be a tough campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this point, Sen. Reid has run a great campaign,''
Bryan said. ``I think Sen. Reid is going to win, but Congressman
Ensign is a formidable opponent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
