</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-MANAGED-CARE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP AT RISK IF HEALTH BILL FAILS TO PASS, POLLSTERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican strategists conceded Thursday that their
party was vulnerable on managed-care legislation and needed to pass
a credible bill before the November elections or risk political
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for Republicans not to come up with some
token effort, because we are perceived as the party that doesn't
care about the issue,'' said Rick Reed, a Republican media
consultant who has worked on the managed-care issue. ``This issue
can only intensify at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks came at a pivotal time in Congress, as Democrats in
the Senate have begun to carry out their threat to attach their
managed-care bill to essential spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, soon after Democrats tried to add the proposal to a
bill to provide money for the Departments of Veterans Affairs and
Housing and Urban Development for the next year, Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi, the majority leader, pulled the bill from the Senate
floor rather than consider the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, led by Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the minority
leader, vowed to repeat the tactic on other spending bills,
threatening to tie up the Senate, which has 45 business days left
to complete legislative business before adjourning for the
elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has said that he has offered Democrats a chance to debate
their bill but that so far the offer, which Daschle maintains has
too many limitations, has been rejected. With the clock ticking, it
is clear that Republicans and Democrats must come to an agreement
on bringing managed-care legislation to the floor soon.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Thursday that Lott's refusal to allow the
managed-care amendment was one reason they refused to end their
filibuster against a product liability bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our Republican colleagues won't agree voluntarily to allow
a full and fair debate on this issue, we will force them to address
it,'' Daschle said at a news conference. ``We will be back, again
and again and again, for as long as we have to, until we get a
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week may be crucial for Republicans in their efforts to
address the managed-care issue. A Senate Republican task force,
headed by Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the assistant majority
leader, is expected to announce a detailed outline of their party's
managed-care bill, and House Republicans are also expected to make
their legislation public.
</P>
<P>
   In what turned into a day of salvos related to managed care, a
group of conservatives, including Randy Tate, the head of the
Christian Coalition, and small-business representatives held a news
conference Thursday morning to promote medical savings accounts as
a remedy to the problems of managed care. The savings accounts,
which are now functioning on a limited basis, are in the House
Republican bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need more Soviet-style regulations,'' said Steve
Forbes, a potential candidate for the Republican presidential
nomination in 2000, referring to Daschle's bill. ``We have too many
restrictions and regulations on health care today.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two hours later, a panel of four prominent Republican and
Democratic strategists and pollsters discussed their strategies and
the issue's impact on congressional campaigns. The discussion was
sponsored by Families USA, which supports Daschle's bill.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster, said his polls showed
Democrats with a 15- to 25-point advantage over Republicans on the
issue. Republicans did not dispute that assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to agree that this is not something that Republicans
have an advantage on,'' Reed, the Republican consultant, said,
adding that Democrats ``are perceived as more capable by the
public, and that's a problem for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Reed and Bob Castro, vice president of the Luntz Research
Cos., which helps Republicans, challenged the notion that the
managed-care issue is as explosive as Democrats say it is. But they
acknowledged the potential for damage to their party.
</P>
<P>
   It does not help matters, Castro said, that Congress has done
little legislatively this year. He counseled Republicans to move
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more time that passes, the less credible that Republicans
look on the issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A centerpiece of the Democratic bill is a provision that gives
all patients the right to sue managed care companies for bad
decisions, something most Republicans oppose, viewing it as a gift
to trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, as well as the insurance industry and
small-business groups, contend that Daschle's bill would increase
costs and rapidly raise the number of uninsured, a position Castro
reiterated.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Shrum, a Democratic media consultant, said the charge
sounds like an ``old song.'' In at least one poll, he said, those
surveyed were given a worst case scenario that involved increased
costs, more regulation and unnecessary lawsuits and 66 percent
still favored the proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
