<SLUG> BC-COPPOLA-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR AWARDED $80 MILLION FOR UNMADE PINOCCHIO MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A Los Angeles jury ordered the Warner Brothers
movie studio Thursday to pay director Francis Ford Coppola and a
partner $60 million in punitive damages for blocking their efforts
to make a movie based on the story of Pinocchio.
</P>
<P>
   The award followed one of $20 million last week by the same jury
in Los Angeles County Superior Court to compensate Coppola and his
partner, Fred Fuchs, for lost income from the movie, which was
never made.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was a resounding triumph for the director of movies
like ``The Godfather'' series and ``Apocalypse Now,'' whose
relations with major Hollywood studios have often been strained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warner Brothers has traditionally not treated its creative
people well,'' Coppola said outside the court. ``Hopefully, this
will teach them to treat creative people as an asset, not as
serfs.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers, a unit of Time Warner, called the $60 million
in damages ``simply ludicrous'' and said it was confident the award
would be reduced or overturned by the judge or on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute goes back to 1991 when Coppola entered negotiations
to make Pinocchio and two other pictures for Warner Brothers. But
the studio and Coppola could not agree on the movie budget.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola later approached another studio, Columbia Pictures, to
make a Pinocchio movie. Columbia, owned by Sony Corp., agreed but
later dropped the project.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers wrote Columbia saying it had the rights to the
project. Coppola said in his lawsuit that Columbia dropped the
project because of Warner's objection. But Coppola said Warner
never had a contract with him.
</P>
<P>
   Warner argued that there was a contract and that Columbia
dropped the picture for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ruled before the trial that there was no contract. The
jury was asked to decide whether Warner Brothers reasonably
believed it had a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Chapman, one of Coppola's lawyers, said Thursday that
Warner Brothers prevented Coppola from making the film because
``they had a vendetta against him.'' Warner Brothers denied any
vendetta, saying it was still working with Coppola on another film.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict might make studios more wary of the common Hollywood
practice of not signing formal long contracts. Coppola never signed
such contracts for the other two films he agreed to make for Warner
either. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
