<SLUG> BC-PAINEWEBBER-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKER SAYS POLITICAL VIEWS DREW PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An organizer of an unsuccessful anti-affirmative
action ballot initiative in Houston last year has accused the
city's former mayor and his former employer, the brokerage firm
Paine Webber, of trying to pressure him to curtail his political
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber officials said Thursday that they had spoken to the
organizer and employee, Edward Blum, about his anti-affirmative
action efforts. The officials said they had sought to prevent Blum
from making speeches and publishing his opinions criticizing
government programs that provided preferences to minorities and
women.
</P>
<P>
   Blum, a Paine Webber stockbroker for 16 years, resigned last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Blum was not fired,'' Paine Webber said in a statement.
``He was asked to refrain from publishing articles with a point of
view that reflected negatively on the firm's reputation and led to
client complaints and a loss of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Blum is president of the Campaign for a Color Blind America, a
private nonprofit organization that opposes affirmative action. He
was also co-chairman of the campaign in favor of the Houston Civil
Rights Initiative, which would have barred the city from hiring and
promoting workers and awarding city contracts based on race and
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Blum also accused Bob Lanier, who was mayor of Houston then and
an opponent of the ballot initiative, of notifying Donald Marron,
chairman and chief executive of Paine Webber Group. Blum said
Lanier had threatened Paine Webber with the loss of contracts to
underwrite bonds for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier conceded Thursday that he had complained about Blum's
tactics promoting the initiative to his employer last October. Both
Lanier and the company denied that he had suggested that Paine
Webber would lose city contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's completely false,'' Lanier said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of Blum's organizations was connected to Paine Webber.
But during the campaign on the ballot initiative, Blum was
identified as a broker at Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   In a written reprimand dated March 31, company officials
criticized Blum for submitting an anti-affirmative action op-ed
article to a number of business journals, stating that his position
could ``negatively affect'' the brokerage house's business.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the letter stated, ``You are advised that the firm
will not clear for publication articles or other press contacts in
which you espouse an anti-affirmative action position such as in
the article submitted to The Wall Street Journal or published in
The Investor's Business Daily.''
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber's employee code of conduct requires articles
written by workers to be cleared by the company's communications
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly they're telling me that I can't express a view that
could be construed as anti-affirmative action,'' Blum said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Blum and his supporters say that Paine Webber's tactics were at
best heavy-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to be having a national conversation on race
and his views fall within the parameter of that discussion,'' said
Abigail Thernstrom, an author and opponent of affirmative action.
``You don't want a society in which people feel intimidated or that
their jobs are on the line because of their political views.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
