<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SCHLOTTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIKES PEAK WAS MOLEHILL FOR THIS RIG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mike Ryan makes his living keeping Hollywood
supplied with hot cars and colossal driving stunts.
</P>
<P>
   But last weekend, the Santa Clarita stunt driver and businessman
was working without a script as he drove to his third straight
victory in the big rig truck class at the Pikes Peak International
Hill Climb in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, 41, hit speeds of over 80 mph as he powered his
Freightliner cab through the 12{-mile, 5,000-foot ascent in 14
minutes, 30.87 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The time was a record for Ryan's class, 10 seconds faster than
he achieved in winning in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said he started competing at Pikes Peak as a way of
promoting his stunt career and his business, Picture Vehicles of
North Hollywood. ``It's just turned into something really neat,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan made his first runs up Pikes Peak on motorcycles, always
finishing near the middle of the pack. Then he saw a guy climb the
hill in a semi truck _ and was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, whose stunt credits include ``Terminator II'' and ``Thelma
and Louise,'' said his truck is a specialized racing machine.
``It's like a sprint car on steroids,'' he said of the
1,200-horsepower machine.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said he plans to defend his title next year at Pikes Peak.
And he hopes to run other events, possibly including the Baja 1000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``I plan to keep doing this for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen ... again:For the fourth time in the past five years, Rod
Millen of Newport Beach was the overall winner of the Pikes Peak
climb.
</P>
<P>
   Millen failed to crack the 10-minute barrier and was more than
three seconds off his record time (10 minutes, 4.06 seconds), set
in 1994. But he was still the fastest guy out there, finishing in
10:07.70.
</P>
<P>
   Cup drivers return to Fontana:NASCAR's Winston Cup series takes
a recess next weekend, allowing several Cup drivers to come to
Fontana's California Speedway for the Craftsman Truck No Fear
Challenge and the Busch Grand National Kenwood Home &AMP; Car 300 on
July 19.
</P>
<P>
   Signed up for the truck race are Cup regulars Bobby Hamilton and
Ernie Irvan. Entered in the Busch race are Dale Jarrett and Dick
Trickle. Michael Waltrip has signed up for both.
</P>
<P>
   Also racing will be former Houston Oilers and Atlanta Falcons
coach Jerry Glanville, who will race in the trucks and in
Saturday's Winston West race.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets remain available for the three races and Friday's
qualifying runs. Prices are $10 for Friday, $30 for Saturday and
$35 for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Go west: Valencia's Sean Woodside trails series leader Kevin
Harvick by five points as the Winston West tour heads to Portland,
Ore., for tonight's TCI Digital Cable 200.
</P>
<P>
   Woodside has been a study in consistency this season, finishing
in the top 10 in all seven races, while winning once. He also has
completed the most laps and led the most laps.
</P>
<P>
   The series makes its second visit to California Speedway in
Fontana on July 18 for the California 200.
</P>
<P>
   Nuts and bolts: Winston Cup driver Mark Martin, in third place
in season points, has a herniated disc but will delay surgery until
after the season.... Ricky Craven will be back in the driver's seat
of the Budweiser No.50 car at Sunday's Winston Cup Jiffy Lube 300
after a four-month recuperation from post-concussion syndrome....
Todd Bodine, who failed to qualify for nine of this season's first
16 Winston Cup races, has lost his job in the No.35 Tabasco
Pontiac. Fellow drivers Ted Musgrave and Mike Skinner are reported
close to losing their rides as well.... Though his old car has
already given him the points lead in the NHRA's top fuel division,
Cory McClenathan will debut a new dragster at next week's Mopar
Parts Mile High Nationals in Colorado.... A new sports car racing
series has been formed, bringing the total to three in the United
States. The American Le Mans Series tour will be based in
Indianapolis and will run as many as 11 events in 1999.... Alex
Zanardi was the last CART driver to win a race from the pole,
taking the Cleveland Grand Prix a year ago. The series bonus for
such a feat has grown by $15,000 per race since and stands at a
record $255,000 for Sunday's race.... Tony Stewart drove his Team
Menard G Force/Aurora to a fast lap of 228.505 mph during testing
at Atlanta Motor Speedway. The time was not official. If it had
been, it would have been a new Indy Racing League record.... Wally
Dallenbach Jr., recently fired from his Winston Cup job with Team
SABCO, will drive for Pennzoil/Panther Racing in the IRL's Lone
Star 500K in Texas in September.... Dallas has joined Indianapolis
and Las Vegas as cities seeking to host a Formula One race in
2000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
