<HEADLINE>
EPIDEMIOLOGIST CHOSEN TO HEAD CENTERS FOR DISEASE CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ga., N.Y.)   (EDS: Subs to give location of Mount Sinai School of Medicine in
graf 6.)  
(lh) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration has selected Dr. Jeffrey
P. Koplan, an epidemiologist, as the next director of the federal
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Koplan spent 22 years
at the agency before leaving four years ago to run the research arm
of Prudential Healthcare, one of the nation's largest health
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human services, is
expected to announce the appointment on Friday morning at the
centers' headquarters in Atlanta, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Koplan will assume the post on Oct. 5, replacing Dr. David
Satcher, who left the agency in February to become surgeon general.
</P>
<P>
   Koplan is ``respected by the left and the right alike,'' said
one official who is familiar with Koplan's selection but who spoke
on condition that he not be identified. ``I have been impressed by
the people who have called on his behalf. Unlike any other senior
post, I haven't heard a bad thing from anyone who has some ax to
grind.''
</P>
<P>
   At the disease control centers, Koplan will oversee a vast and
often unseen bureaucracy with 6,900 employees and a wide-ranging
mission, from curbing the spread of sexually transmitted diseases
to investigating the effects of violence on the public health. He
is also being appointed administrator of the Agency for Toxic
Substances and Disease Registry, which is concerned with preventing
health damage from exposure to hazardous substances. Neither
appointment requires Senate confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Boston, Koplan, 53, is a graduate of Mount Sinai
School of Medicine in New York City and the Harvard University
School of Public Health. He began his career at the Centers for
Disease Control in 1972 as one of the agency's celebrated ``disease
detectives,'' who are dispatched around the world to investigate
outbreaks of infectious diseases. For the next two decades, he
worked on public health matters, including the eradication of
smallpox and the promotion of screening for breast and cervical
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, Koplan was instrumental in formulating the
agency's response to the AIDS epidemic, particularly its efforts to
protect the nation's blood supply, an effort that later became
controversial. In 1984, he led a federal delegation to Bhopal,
India, to investigate an explosion at the Union Carbide chemical
plant. Five years later, he became the first director of the
agency's new Center for Chronic Disease Prevention and Health
Promotion, a job he held until he left the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Koplan is a world-class scientist, but above all, he is a
leader,'' said Dr. Bill Roper, who served as the director of the
centers from 1990 to 1993 and who later recruited Koplan to
Prudential Healthcare, a unit of Prudential Insurance Company of
America. ``He has a deep personal commitment to public health and a
burning zeal for prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   At Prudential, Koplan is president of the Center for Health Care
Research in Atlanta, where he supervises studies intended to make
medical care more efficient and effective.
</P>
<P>
   That experience may be particularly useful for Koplan in his new
job, as the centers tries to persuade managed-care organizations to
pay more attention to public health.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a very strong mix of technical expertise and
management ability, with a vision of where to go with public
health,'' said an agency official, who insisted on anonymity. ``My
sense is that his appointment will be very warmly received.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
