<SLUG> BC-BOEING-PRODUCTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING PRODUCT OF TRANSPORT JETS TO DOUBLE OVER NEXT FEW YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as The Boeing Co. eliminates jobs and slashes production of
commercial jets at the former Douglas aircraft plant at Long Beach,
Calif., it's a much different story for the 8,000 Boeing workers
who assemble the military's giant C-17 transport less than a mile
away.
</P>
<P>
   Production of the cargo jet for the U.S. Air Force will nearly
double over the next several years, and this week Great Britian
gave the strongest signal yet that it may become the first foreign
customer for the C-17.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Defense Secretary George Robertson, after a year-long
review of that country's defense priorities, announced Wednesday
that the government plans to buy four C-17s ``or their
equivalent.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a small order by Great Britian is considered significant
since it could lead to other NATO countries deciding on the C-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good news,'' Rick Fuller, Boeing's C-17 spokesman in
Long Beach, said Thursday. ``We are very encouraged that the U.K.
has publicly identified their air transport needs.''
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that any actual order for the C-17 by Great
Britian is still months away.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing would be able to deliver the first C-17 to Great Britian
less than two years after any contract is signed, Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Boeing submitted an unsolicited proposal to
the U.K. Ministry of Defense to lease several C-17s for up to 12
years to meet its strategic airlift requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The United Kingdom has already ordered 25 of Lockheed Martin's
smaller C-130J transports to replace older model Hercules
transports. The C-17 can carry up to four times as much cargo as
the C-130J, but land on the same length runway.
</P>
<P>
   With a flyaway cost of about $175 million dollars, the C-17 is
more expensive than a Boeing 747, which has a list price of from
$158 million to $176 million.
</P>
<P>
   By improving manufacturing processes, Boeing reportedly believes
it can reduce the unit cost of the C-17 to about $150 million. But
that is still a lot of money for a single airplane, and Great
Britian and other European countries are looking at the possible
development of something called the Future Large Aircraft to meet
their military airlift needs.
</P>
<P>
   Cost of such an aircraft is estimated at $75 million, but many
aviation experts don't believe the plane will ever get off the
ground because of declining defense budgets and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing believes there is a market outside the United States for
as many as 50 of its C-17s.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the only orders have come from the U.S. Air Force,
which will get 120 planes. Forty have been delivered. Nine more
will be delivered to the Air Force this year. Production will peak
at 15 planes a year by 2002, Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the C-17 is assembled at Long Beach, the parts are
manufactured elsewhere. About 2,000 workers in St. Louis build the
nose section.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing inherited the C-17 in its merger last year with McDonnell
Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   The C-17 plant in Long Beach is less than a mile from the
Douglas facility where Boeing now builds the MD-90, MD-80 and
MD-11, as well as its new 100-seat jet, the 717.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing is discontinuing production of all the McDonnel
Douglas planes. That could leave only the 717 commercial line in
Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   However, Boeing executives have been studying the feasibility of
adding a 737 assembly line in Long Beach to ease production
problems of that model in Renton. A decision is expected by Aug. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
