<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY ACQUITS DON KING 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs for clarifications; minor changes throughout)  
(lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal jury acquitted Don King of nine counts of
wire fraud Thursday, the second time he was tried on charges of
attempting to defraud a Lloyd's of London insurance syndicate out
of $350,000 following cancellation of a boxing match involving
Julio Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   The jury could not reach a verdict concerning Don King
Productions, a defendant along with King. It voted 11-1 to acquit
the company, according to one juror. The government has chosen not
to retry the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for all America _ not black America or white
America,'' said King, who said he read from a Bible as he listened
to the verdict, then received the embraces of his lawyers and shook
most of the jurors' hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you all very much,'' he said, leaning over the jury box.
</P>
<P>
   The post-verdict scene was reminiscent of one of King's
circus-like news conferences. The fight promoter laughed
boisterously, soliloquized his jubilation in religious and
hyperbolic terms and signed autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to say goodbye,'' one juror said to King, gently
kissing him.
</P>
<P>
   As King ventured from the 15th floor courtroom to talk to
reporters outside the U.S. Court House in Lower Manhattan, he
greeted three court security officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm free again!'' he said, embracing one. ``I'm free,
brotherman!''
</P>
<P>
   When two rabbis who displayed their support during the
three-month trial approached King, he gleefully shouted, ``My
rabbis! These are my rabbis!''
</P>
<P>
   In his jubilation, King did not directly scorn the government's
case against him, but referred to those who abuse power. ``When my
lawyer said, `We the people,' my liver quivered and my heart
palpitated,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, King, 66, looked like a man unworried
about his legal fate. Although his trademark flamboyance was muted
by the trial's formality, he frequently flashed his broad smile,
garrulously greeted visitors, some bearing gifts, and joked with
the courtroom artist. ``I tried desperately to feel down, but
couldn't,'' he said. ``I'd say, `Your head is in the lion's
mouth.'''
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday's verdict, King has won acquittals from two
federal juries in Manhattan, the first one in 1985 on charges of
tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney for the Southern District of
New York, said she would not prosecute Don King Productions again
on the wire fraud charges because it would not be in the public
interest.
</P>
<P>
   That contrasted with her decision to retry King after a hung
jury in 1995 forced U.S. District Judge Lawrence McKenna to declare
a mistrial in the government's first case against King.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This time, with McKenna presiding again, White's office added
King's company to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   King faced a maximum of 45 years in prison had he been convicted
on all nine counts, but sentencing guidelines would have pared that
down.
</P>
<P>
   He could have been fined up to $250,000 for each count; fines of
$1 million could have been imposed for each of the seven counts his
company had faced.
</P>
<P>
   A conviction against his company could have barred King from
promoting fights in Nevada, but the state attorney general had
reserved a decision on that until after the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment had kept King from promoting fight cards in New
Jersey. A call to the state Athletic Control Board seeking comment
was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors were not convinced that King or his company submitted a
fake contract to Lloyd's after the cancellation of Chavez's 1991
fight against Harold Brazier that stipulated King was due repayment
of $350,000 in ``maintenance nonrefundable training expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense argued that Chavez, who was injured during training,
prompting the bout's cancellation, got $80,000 in training expenses
and owed $270,000 more from a $736,000 loan King made to Chavez
against a future purse, money that was characterized as a
``maintenance'' payment.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fiscus, one of the jurors, said he was persuaded by a
faxed insurance binder that Lloyd's covered what the defense said
it did.
</P>
<P>
   Between Tuesday afternoon and early Thursday, the case had
plunged into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the jury forewoman reported to McKenna that one
juror related to the others a newspaper report that King's maximum
sentence could be 45 years. The forewoman also reported to McKenna
that one juror was causing a deadlock, leading the judge to
interview the jurors Wednesday to see if they could continue to
deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   One juror, Dean Yager, had pushed hard to convict King and his
company, according to lawyers involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna urged the jurors to deliberate again at 12:15 p.m.
Thursday. After 100 minutes, the jury told McKenna it had a verdict
on King but continued to be deadlocked on the company.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna refused a government request to compel the jury to
deliberate further on the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got unanimous on King this morning,'' said Marianne Mileno,
the jury forewoman. Regarding friction over Yager's stand on
convicting the company, she said, ``It was very emotional. It was
difficult personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Yager said little as he rushed from the courtroom. Asked if the
three and a half months of jury service had embittered him, he
said: ``Precisely.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Fleming Jr., a lawyer for King, said the defense was
unhappy with Yager at jury selection, but could not dismiss him for
cause.
</P>
<P>
   King's legal fights are not over. Now, he must fend off a
federal lawsuit filed against him by Mike Tyson. ``We'll deal with
it,'' King said, pausing to expound upon life's various forms of
love. ``I love him. He's my beloved brother.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
