<HEADER>
A8401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FIREFIGHTER-FUNERA     07-09 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FIREFIGHTER-FUNERAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING FUNERAL FOR FIREFIGHTER WHO BATTLED BURNS FOR MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was a tough one for the New York City Fire
Department, maybe tougher than some of the others.
</P>
<P>
   Not just because Capt. Scott LaPiedra, who died on the Fourth of
July, left behind a wife and four young children. Or because he was
twice cited for bravery. Or because he was a member of a family
that counted among its ranks a father who is a retired police
officer and brothers who are now in the police, fire, sanitation
departments.
</P>
<P>
   For some firefighters, LaPiedra's funeral Thursday in Staten
Island was especially difficult because the captain, a veteran
marathoner, had died after running the bravest, and most
spectacular, marathon of his 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite burns to 70 percent of his body, LaPiedra, with big
lungs and a big heart, defied medical logic by surviving for a
month. And in the process, firefighters often found it difficult to
cope with what became an emotionally draining roller coaster, day
after praying day, week after hoping week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he hung on, it kind of made it a sadder situation,''
said Lt. Timothy Murphy of the Glen Falls Fire Department in
upstate New York, who, as a firefighter and a licensed funeral
director, knows a thing or two about emotional duress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in limbo,'' said Murphy, who didn't know LaPiedra but
felt compelled to drive four hours to pay his respects. ``Everyone
is like, `Is he going to make it? If he does, what's the situation
going to be?'''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters are accustomed, of course, to danger on the job;
LaPiedra was the third New York City firefighter to die this year
as a result of job-related injuries and the 767th in the
department's 133-year history. But when a firefighter dies, it
usually occurs so soon after the devastating blaze that people can
grieve and bounce back in relatively quick order.
</P>
<P>
   This, however, did not happen in LaPiedra's case. And it only
gave firefighters more time to appreciate the risks that their
colleagues embrace and to contemplate their own mortality and
vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were praying for Scottie every day, so how can you not
think about it?'' said Capt. Michael DeGennaro of Engine Company 82
in the Bronx. ``It puts everything in perspective because you don't
know who it's going to happen to next.''
</P>
<P>
   LaPiedra, a 19-year veteran who was a ranking officer in Ladder
Company 176 in East New York, Brooklyn, had been injured while
fighting a five-alarm inferno on June 5 that swallowed a row of
small, wood-frame houses in that neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve others were injured that night; one other firefighter,
Lt. James W. Blackmore, 48, died in the blaze, while two others
remain in stable condition at New York Hospital-Cornell Medical
Center with serious burns.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong Staten Island resident, LaPiedra was, by all
accounts, the consummate family man and neighborhood guy, living
with his wife, Addie, and their four children in the same house
that he had grown up in with his seven siblings.
</P>
<P>
   At work, he was revered for quiet leadership and unassuming
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great teacher and 100 percent professional, yet he
did it with a smile,'' said Lt. Cliff Miller, a pallbearer
Thursday, who retired last year after a heart attack. ``We had a
party last year to celebrate my recovery and his promotion to
captain. I'll always remember him and I, arm and arm, with the
pipers playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, more than 12,000 others remembered LaPiedra, too,
descending upon St. Peter's Roman Catholic Church in a pleasant,
residential neighborhood dotted by shingle-style houses and
magnolia trees.
</P>
<P>
   At 11 a.m., the crowd grew hushed as Police Department
motorcycles began purring toward the church, past an army of
firefighters in crisp blue uniforms standing 20 deep and extending
perhaps a half-mile. Other teams followed: two black cars groaning
under the weight of flowers, bagpipers wailing ``Amazing Grace''
and drummers playing drums covered in purple-and-black bunting.
</P>
<P>
   One, two, three, drum roll. One, two, three, drum roll.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a mournful silence, punctured only by chirping birds
and barking dogs in the distance. A fire engine rolled up to the
church carrying LaPiedra's coffin, which was wrapped by the
red-and-white flag of the Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   It was standing room only inside the 850-seat church, with
relatives occupying most of the front pews to the right of the
aisle, and city officials, including Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and
Fire Commissioner Thomas Von Essen, sitting to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was one of several people to eulogize LaPiedra. And to
let LaPiedra's four children _ Scott, 13, Buddy, 12, and twins,
Megan and Shannon, 10 _ know how much their father was revered and
respected, the mayor asked the congregation to stand, salute the
captain and applaud.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Richard LaPiedra, the captain's brother and a fellow
firefighter, who delivered the most heartfelt of the eulogies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott, I would've felt privileged if I had only known you as a
friend,'' he said, his voice quivering with emotion. ``I am honored
for 30 years to have been your brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people lingered after the funeral, talking quietly,
sighing heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ennis Keating, a firefighter with Ladder Company 37 in the
Bronx, reminisced about how he and other firefighters had prepared
french toast, sausages and eggs every morning for the last month
for LaPiedra's family, who had maintained a vigil at Jacobi Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But now, there will be no more breakfasts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
