<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8403 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-CROUSE-MADKINS-LA     07-09 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-CROUSE-MADKINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAST BREAK FOR MADKINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Twenty-nine players are in Chicago, vying for the
right to be slandered and second-guessed and maybe even snubbed by
the very people they aim to please.
</P>
<P>
   Former UCLA guard Gerald Madkins is among the players
auditioning to be stand-ins for an all-NBA team that came up with a
collective case of blue flu six weeks before basketball's turn on
the world's stage.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA lockout has left peripheral players such as Madkins in a
bit of a bind; the summer leagues, long an opportunity for free
agents to assimilate an NBA team's system and showcase their
individual talents, won't have the same emphasis this year. Teams
are unsure of their rosters because no player transactions can
occur during the labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the FIBA World Championship in Athens, Greece, as
the only proving ground around. And yet to play for Team USA is to
risk being perceived as traitors rather than patriots by some NBA
suits, or singlets, as it may be.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the competition itself. With Vlade Divac playing
for his native Yugoslavia and a handful of other NBA players
representing their homelands, the battle for first place among the
16 participating nations is expected to be fierce.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian team has been practicing together for months and
the Greeks always are tough on their home turf. But heaven help the
patchwork patriots from the U.S. if they fail to bring home the
title, and with it, the automatic berth for the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 candidates chosen to accept this assignment are playing
with a stacked deck; if they win, the spin back in the states will
be they simply minded the chips in the absence of Vin Baker, Gary
Payton, Terrell Brandon, Tim Duncan, Kevin Garnett, Tom Gugliotta,
Tim Hardaway, Grant Hill, Allan Houston, Christian Laettner, Glen
Rice and Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   If they lose, they're liable to know how the U.S. soccer team
felt during the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   None of that matters to Madkins, 29, who started the 1997-98
season with the Rockford Lightning of the Continental Basketball
Association, was summoned by the Miami Heat for a 10-day stay
midway through the year and spent the last month under contract
with the Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between a career-threatening moped accident at UCLA
after his freshman year and a career-lurching ride through France,
Spain, the CBA and the NBA, Madkins learned to discern his inner
voice in the din.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife (Julie) and I looked at it like this,'' Madkins said
Thursday from Chicago. ``I've been in the NBA for parts of three
seasons but I've been an American for 29 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The attention to defense that distinguished Madkins' career at
UCLA remains keen, both on and off the court. To cover himself,
Madkins said he contacted the NBA Players' Association before
accepting the invitation to what amounts to a three-day tryout (the
squad will be selected Saturday and the team will leave Wednesday
for Greece by way of Monaco and Rome).
</P>
<P>
   ``The players' association said they wouldn't hold it against me
if I came here,'' said Madkins, who isn't one to bear a grudge if
they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been bounced around so much. I can't really say I'm in
the NBA, even though I finished the season there. I can honestly
say my career is on a downward slide. Who knows if I'll ever play
in the NBA again, with the lockout? So this is a great opportunity
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Madkins, who averaged 12.8 minutes in 19 games with the
Warriors, is the oldest guard and fourth-oldest player in camp.
There will be no need to towel off the basketball when Madkins gets
through handling it. Battling the likes of ballyhooed 5-foot-5
guard Earl Boykins, a recent college graduate, isn't likely to make
the L.A. resident sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another tryout in a long line of them,'' said Madkins,
who has acquiesced to more auditions than a struggling actor since
leaving UCLA in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   His big break came in 1993 when he was signed by the Cleveland
Cavaliers. He spent two seasons there and has bounced back and
forth between the CBA and the NBA since.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball took Madkins far, transporting him to the edge of
Hollywood, quite literally, before dumping him off at the side of
the road to navigate the final mile. It has proven to be a long and
oftentimes lonely journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough grind for me,'' said Madkins, whose fatal
flaw, if you can call it that, is he's too selfless a player to put
up the numbers that command attention.
</P>
<P>
   CBA coaches have told him as much. All Madkins knows is, ``I've
never gone anywhere and stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Madkins is starting to feel the pull to put down some permanent
roots. He and Julie, his college sweetheart, have two boys,
Christopher, 2, and Brandon, six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to leave your children, even though you know
you're doing it for the betterment of their future,'' said Madkins,
who will miss Christopher's birthday if he survives Saturday's cut.
</P>
<P>
   His firstborn turns 3 on Aug. 9, the date of the championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be magical if Madkins was able to give his son a belated
gift of a gold medal. Truth to tell, any souvenir from the trip
would be priceless to Madkins, who has labored long enough to fully
appreciate the opportunity created by the NBA's labor strife.
</P>
<P>
   If Madkins makes the team, you can be sure there will be no
flying elbows or fire extinguishers in Athens. A pampered U.S. star
like Charles Barkley or certain NHL standouts he and the other
prospective players decidedly are not.
</P>
<P>
   That alone should make everyone root all the harder for this
team, whomever ends up on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like myself,'' Madkins said, ``don't need a lot. We
just want to be a part of something that's growing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
