<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8405 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIR     07-09 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY MOTHER AND SON ARE CON ARTISTS LONG ON THE RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., La., Fla., Utah, Calif., Nev., Hawaii)  (Eds.: An expanded version of this story is scheduled to move by
midnight ET.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 This article was reported by JAMES RISEN, CHRISTOPHER DREW and
DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI and was written by Drew.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over the last two years, Sante and Kenneth Kimes, a
mother-and-son team with long criminal records, have traveled
across the United States and beyond, always remaining a step ahead
of criminal investigators seeking to question them about theft,
arson and the disappearance _ or murders _ of at least three
people.
</P>
<P>
   They fled the West earlier this year, avoiding police who were
hunting them in connection with a complex swindle and a murder that
left a house burned to ashes in Las Vegas and the body of a friend
crumpled in a dumpster at Los Angeles International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators zeroed in on them in Louisiana, where the Kimeses
purchased a mobile home under a false name. But police just missed
them there, and they discovered the mobile home abandoned in
Florida. Again the Kimeses were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Police finally tracked them down Sunday in New York, arresting
them at the New York Hilton on a Utah warrant for writing a bogus
check.
</P>
<P>
   But one last time, investigators now fear, they were just hours
too late.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after the mother-and-son team were in jail that
investigators suspected their involvement in the disappearance
earlier that day of a wealthy East Side Manhattan socialite, Irene
Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   And in interviews Thursday, investigators in New York and in
other cities said they believe the Kimeses are classic con artists,
using fake names, fradulent documents and quick getaways. When they
were arrested Sunday, they were carrying Mrs. Silverman's passport
and other papers, an investigators believe they were fraudulently
trying to take possession of her home. In addition, officials said
they had recovered a 9-mm handgun from a car the Kimeses were
driving and that they were analyzing blood found outside her 65th
Street townhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And law-enforcement officials said they have been struck by how
closely the pair's dealings with Mrs. Silverman tracked a series of
possibly fraudulent transactions they had early this year with
David Kazdin, a Los Angeles businessman and longtime friend of the
Kimeses whose body was later found in an airport dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who spent any time with them quickly realized they were
scammers,'' DePasquale said. ``They came across like real
first-class types at the start. But pretty soon, everyone saw they
were just conning people left and right.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the concern is that Mrs. Kimes, 63 and long a wealthy
woman, has a lengthy history of committing petty and bizarre crimes
and hiding behind numerous aliases. But while neither of the
Kimeses has been charged with any crimes in connection with the
disappearances of Mrs. Silverman and a banker in the Bahamas, and
the murder Kazdin, the investigators say they are trying to
determine why her activities have taken on a more serious and
disturbing cast, and how her 23-year-old son came to join her in
these suspicious dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives from New York and Los Angeles met in New York on
Thursday to compare notes on Mrs. Silverman's case and the murder
of Kazdin. Detective Mike DePasquale, a homicide co-ordinator for
the Los Angeles Police Department, confirmed that the Kimseses are
suspects in Kazdin's murder and that efforts to obtain some of his
money is the most likely motive.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said Bahamian officials also would
like to question the Kimeses in connection with the disappearance a
banker, Syed Bilal Ahmed, there in 1996. Doug Hanna, chief of the
criminal investigative unit of the Royal Bahamas Police, said Ahmed
had some dealings with Sante Kimes, who was in the Bahamas at that
time, but that she had left the Bahamas before police could ask her
about them.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna said Ahmed's body has never been found and his
disappearance has never been solved. He added that the Bahamas
never issued an arrest warrant for Sante Kimes because police did
not have enough evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   New York City detectives said they also have not gathered enough
evidence to charge the Kimeses in Mrs. Silverman's disappearance,
and they still have found no sign of her body. The Police
Department and federal agents executed a search warrant on the
Kimeses' green Lincoln Town Car Wednesday, finding two suitcases in
the trunk that contained $10,000 in cash, a loaded 9mm handgun,
some loose ammunition for a .22-caliber gun and a collection of
documents involving Mrs. Silverman's finances. The documents
contained Ms. Silverman's signature, but the authorities were
investigating Thursday night to determine whether they were
authentic or forgeries.
</P>
<P>
   But while police try to determine whether the Kimeses, who are
being held at Rikers Island have committed any violent crimes,
several investigators said there is substantial evidence showing
they have tried to bilked other people out of their money.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews and records show that the first public signs of Mrs.
Kimes' propensity for trouble came in the late 1970s, when she and
her husband, Kenneth K. Kimes Sr., a wealthy owner of motels and
other real-estate, were living in an expensive beachfront home in
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Catterlin, a lawyer who represented Mrs. Kimes then,
recalled that she was accused of stealing a car from an auto
dealer's lot. He also said an insurance company sued her for
passing off a new quilt that she had lost as an antique worth
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Catterlin said Mrs. Kimes also would embellish the truth to
appear more wealthy than she was. For example, he said, she would
tell people that a five-carat glass ring was a diamond given by her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the lawyer said, she often used aliases. When Mrs.
Kimes later failed to pay his legal fees, Catterlin said, he sued
her unsuccessfully, identifying her in court papers by 22 possible
names. ``She was known by every name there ever was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mr. Kimes' motel companies bought a house on a golf
course in Las Vegas in 1980, and the couple also spent time in the
early 1980s in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kimes also was convicted in mid-1985 of stealing a $6,500
mink coat from a piano bar at one of Washington's most fashionable
hotels. And about two weeks after that, she was arrested for
enslaving several Mexican maids at houses the couple owned in San
Diego, Las Vegas and Honolulu. She served a five-year sentence for
refusing to pay the maids or allow them time off, and her husband
pleaded guilty to a lesser offense.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout these years, acquaintances said, the Kimeses often
lived at a house on a golf course in Las Vegas that one of Mr.
Kimes' motel companies bought in 1980, and neighbors say they
rarely socialized. ``She always had lots of hair and wore a
wide-brimmed hat, but I never talked to her,'' said one long-time
neighbor who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Her husband died in 1994, and the most serious questions about
Mrs. Kimes _ and how she seemed to team up with her son _ have
arisen since then.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Ahmed, an official of the Gulf Union Bank,
based in the Cayman Islands, disappeared in September 1996 after
going to Nassau to investigate irregularities at the bank's unit in
the Bahamas. Hanna said Ahmed met with Mrs. Kimes shortly before he
disappeared. And shortly after that, Kenneth Kimes was arrested in
Florida in May 1997 on attempted theft charges.
</P>
<P>
   But law-enforcement officials say the questions about the
Kimeses' activities intensified after they conducted a series of
financial transactions with Kazdin late last year and early this
year. The deals involved the house in Las Vegas that the Kimeses
had bought in 1980, and had later sold to Kazdin, the Los Angeles
man who owned a document-copying business.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas and Los Angeles police say these deals now seem
remarkably similar to parts of the Silverman case.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe that the Kimeses had promised Kazdin that they
would provide him with a steady tenant who would rent the property.
But late last year, the Kimeses arranged for the house to be sold
to the renter, another Las Vegas man named Robert McCarren. The
real estate documents were notarized by a woman named Nanette
Wetkowski, a local notary public who was a business partner of the
Kimeses. Police believe the documents were falsified, and that the
renter was simply a front for the Kimeses.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas police said they believe Ms. Wetkowski should have
known that she was notarizing false documents. The purpose of the
false sale was to obtain a new loan of $280,000 on the property,
police believe, with that money going to the Kimeses.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the check from the loan cleared, police said,
Kazdin's body was found in a dumpster at Los Angeles International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The house in Las Vegas burned on Jan. 31, and local fire
officials determined that the fire had been set. Officials
considered Sante Kimes a suspect in the fire, said Mike Patterson,
the Las Vegas chief of fire investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said that fire officials believe that the fire was
related to the complex real estate transactions that had occurred
just before the fire. He said that Mrs. Kimes may have used
McCarren as a front for the purchase in part to obtain new fire
insurance on the home that she could not have obtained with her
long criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson added that there is an open criminal arson
investigation of Mrs. Kimes, which has remained open because fire
officials did not know where she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our theory is that they used Mr. McCarren to rebuy the house
to get additional insurance, then burned it,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely set by her, you didn't have to go inside to
see that. There had been a fire upstairs, and a fire downstairs,
and they weren't even related.'' But Patterson added that ``I
didn't even have any clue where to find them.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kazdin's murder in March, McCarren was held by the Kimes
in Los Angeles this spring, and police believe he could have become
their next victim, but he escaped and called the Los Angeles police
for help. The Kimeses then fled themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as April, they lived at the Beverly Wilshire Hotel
in Beverly Hills, and it was there that they ordered the green 1997
Lincoln Town car that eventually led to their capture. Scott Burns,
the district attorney in Iron County, Utah, said the dealership
agreed to accept their order by phone because the Kimses had
purchased other cars without problems.
</P>
<P>
   The dealership had an employee and his wife drive the car to the
Wilshire on April 4, 1998, where the Kimeses bought them a $500
dinner at a glitzy restaurant and rewarded them with a $100 tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took the check, it was for $14,900 and headed back
home,'' Burns said. ``It was only later that the dealership learned
the account had been frozen.''
</P>
<P>
   The check was written from a Wells Fargo Bank account of Ms.
Wetkowski, the notary public who worked as the Kimeses' accountant,
authorities said. When Sante Kimes was informed that the check had
bounced, she apologized and called it ``a mistake,'' Burns said.
But before sending a new check, the Kimses moved to Las Vegas and
Sante Kimes began calling the dealership to complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she'd only write them a new check if they gave her
new car, `` Burns said. ``She'd be grumbling, `I want a black one.
I want a 1998. The trunk leaks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After a series of haggling phone calls over the course of the
next several days _ all of which were placed from public
telephones, investigators said _ the car dealer grew worried and
filed a criminal complaint. It was then that Utah officials learned
that the Kimeses were wanted for questioning in the Kazdin murder.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Kimes resumed her calls demanding a new car, Utah
police set up a sting. The dealership agreed to deliver a new car
to Mrs. Kimes at the Las Vegas Hilton. But unbeknownst to the
Kimeses, a detective would accompany the delivery and was prepared
to arrest them.
</P>
<P>
   But when they arrived at the hotel bar, they were paged by the
Kimeses, and Sante asked them to meet her and Kenneth at Landry's
Hotel, a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that the Kimeses were suspects in a murder, and fearing
that their cover had been blown, the detective decided not to.
</P>
<P>
   `He was afraid for their well being,'' Burns said. ``So he and
the transporter just headed back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Police picked up their trail when they purchased a mobile home
in Louisiana, and used Ms. Wetkowski's name to purchase it. Police
tracked the mobile home to Florida, but found it abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The next time they heard about the Kimeses was when the
informant in Las Vegas contacted the police to say they had called
him and asked him to join them in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
