<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DROP DEVIL RAYS 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Yankees' final place in the American
League East standing has become almost a foregone conclusion. After
Joe Girardi supplied the runs with a two-run homer and Andy
Pettitte and Mariano Rivera combined Thursday night to shut out
Tampa Bay, 2-0, in the first game following the three-day All-Star
break, the Yankees forged 11-and-a-half games ahead of the
second-place Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   For the Yankees, the shutout was the second in a row, following
David Cone's effort against Baltimore on Sunday _ the first
back-to-back shutouts since 1989. The Yankees have won seven games
in a row, 11 of their last 12, and their clinching number for a
playoff spot already is down to 62 with 80 games to play.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle for posterity remains heated: With a 62-20
record, they are tied with the 1902 Pittsburgh Pirates for the best
82-game record in history. If the Yankees do manage to pull away
from Honus Wagner and the '02 Pirates, it will be because of their
starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 32 games, the Yankees have had 26 quality starts _
six or more innings, three earned runs or less. The earned run
average of the starting pitchers has dropped from 4.18 to 3.59, and
they have a record of 20-5.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, who yielded only five hits and one walk while striking
out eight in eight innings Thursday night, established immediately
that the Yankees would not be guilty of attention deficit disorder
as the second half of the season began.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre called a mandatory, full-squad workout for
early Thursday afternoon; apparently, Torre understands the mindset
of his boss, George Steinbrenner, how he dwells on preparation and
how he might feel about losing the first game after the All-Star
Game break to an expansion team. Torre also wanted to give his
players a chance to reacquaint themselves with the game, following
three days of rest and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   The three days off changed nothing. Chuck Knoblauch led off the
game and fought Bryan Rekar, the Devil Rays' starter, until
grounding out on the seventh pitch of the at-bat. The Yankees
eventually loaded the bases, forcing Rekar to throw 27 pitches
before Darryl Strawberry flied out to end the scoreless inning.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, however, the Yankees scored the inning after forcing
the opposing starter to throw an unusually high number of pitches.
With one out in the second, Rekar threw a fastball into the back of
Scott Brosius. Girardi worked the count to two balls and one
strike, a natural hit-and-run situation for Girardi, a contact
hitter, and Brosius did indeed break from first base.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than hit the ball through the first-base hole,
Girardi smashed a line drive into the Tampa Bay bullpen in right
field for his third home run of the season _ as many home runs as
Girardi hit in his first two years with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, now 11-5, guarded the two-run lead with dogged
intensity, sometimes throwing his fastball _ clocked as high as 90
mph _ over the outside corner. Then, when the Tampa Bay hitters
leaned over the plate, Pettitte would ram his cut fastball, a ball
that moves inside to right-handed hitters, in on their hands and
they would swing weakly.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Pettitte threw a cutter with so much
movement that Randy Winn swung at it and missed _ before being hit
by the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   When Pettitte wasn't striking somebody out, his infielders were
making plays, turning potential hits into outs. Derek Jeter, the
shortstop, charged a two-bounce grounder in the third and threw
off-balance to get Quinton McCracken and end the inning. Brosius,
the third baseman, speared a line drive to open the fifth inning
and then fielded grounders from the next two hitters, assuming
responsibility for the entire inning himself.
</P>
<P>
   McCracken smacked a one-out single in the sixth and Bobby Smith
laced a grounder into the shortstop hole _ but Jeter grabbed the
ball, flipped it to second to Knoblauch, who avoided McCracken and
completed the double play. Only the Baltimore Orioles have allowed
fewer unearned runs than the Yankees among the 30 major-league
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay loaded the bases in the eighth with the aid of an
error by Brosius. But with two out, Torre stuck with Pettitte. When
Smith grounded to second, Knoblauch fielded the ball and threw
high, drawing Tino Martinez off the base, but Smith went out of the
baseline to avoid Martinez's tag attempt and was called out, ending
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera took over in the ninth, walked the first two batters,
then pitched out of the jam by getting Wade Boggs to ground to
third for the final out with runners on second and third. It was
Rivera's 23 save of this marvelous Yankee season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
