<HEADLINE>
HOT _ VERY HOT _ WELCOME AWAITS COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ Like Gunga Din, I stopped for provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Gatorade. Thermometer. And the latest issue of ``Texas
Monthly'', in which writer and Wichita Falls native Skip
Hollandsworth delightfully expounds on the virtues of the Cowboys'
newest summer home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spend too much time outside,'' penned Hollandsworth,
``the temperature of your blood starts to rise, your vision blurs,
and your legs start quivering like dying fish on hooks. And then
you faint.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it is hot all over Texas these days. El Nino, probably
still angry that Owner Jones fired Jimmy Johnson, won't release his
boilerlike grip.
</P>
<P>
   But even in normal balmy summers, Wichita Falls is hot.
Legendary hot. Like the name on the popular bike race, it is Hotter
n' Hell.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, I headed for ground zero. The Cowboys' soon-to-be
main practice field. The 50-yard line. The epicenter of Hell
itself.
</P>
<P>
   I carefully laid the thermometer on the grass and then stood
there, wondering why I hadn't packed a pith helmet, a camel and
several canteens. I looked at the thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   124!
</P>
<P>
   I turned around to see if, by some chance, a nuclear bomb had
quietly gone off behind me.
</P>
<P>
   Nope. I checked the thermometer again.
</P>
<P>
   Still 124.
</P>
<P>
   My legs started quivering and I thought of Hollandsworth's fish.
</P>
<P>
   The heat notwithstanding, it is easy to see why owner Jerry
Jones thought Midwestern State University would make a fit host for
his famous football team. The campus is a jewel in the sun _ 170
acres of tree-lined sidewalks and trim, brown-bricked buildings
with Spanish-tiled roofs. A ``handsome'' campus, the Chamber of
Commerce would call it.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, the Cowboys are trading up. About a full century
up, compared to the grim Gothic ambiance of their former home, St.
Edward's in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   For eight years, the Cowboys mined the conveniences of preparing
for the football season in the political and social capital of the
state. They didn't mind the heat, they said. But the team, in time,
outgrew its boundaries and its welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jones was ready for a change. And Midwestern State was
ready to carve its place on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Robertson, a mass communications senior, was helping
prepare stock for the soon-to-open Cowboys Pro Shop, a large tent
adjoining the practice fields where fans will be able to purchase
Cowboys T-shirts and sundry souvenirs. The prediction here is that
it will be a raging success _ i.e., the tent is air-conditioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people _ the older generation, I guess _ didn't like the
idea of the Cowboys coming to town,'' Robertson said. ``But in the
long run, it's going to create a lot more money for the local
economy. Not too many people outside of Texas have heard of Wichita
Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   In the parking lot outside of the Pro Shop tent, I checked the
thermometer again.
</P>
<P>
   122.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up,'' Hollandsworth wrote, ``I was told the
reason that there are two state mental hospitals there ... was
because so many people went crazy during the summer, when the heat
is as heavy as wool.''
</P>
<P>
   The neatest and oldest building on campus is the Hardin
Administration Building, erected when the ``new campus'' was opened
in 1937. The main hallway is lined with photographs of campus
scenes, from football games to the student center to,
conspicuously, two shots of the Hardin building taken after a
six-inch winter snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe I was so hot that I just dreamed it.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the school's public information office, director Janus
Buss said, ``This is one of the biggest things to hit not just the
school, but the city. We're excited about the exposure. A lot of
people around the country couldn't tell you what or where
Midwestern State University is.''
</P>
<P>
   For five weeks, Buss knows, dispatches and wire service reports
will go out around the world with the city's name and Midwestern
State's prominently mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a PR dream come true,'' she confesses.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope, of course, none of the Cowboys will succumb to the
Hadeslike heat. Let's hope none of the team's limo radiators will
boil over. Let's hope the players will avoid the kind of headlines
here that plagued them in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   On the front page of the ``Wichita Falls Times Record News'' the
other day, there was a big story about how bloodhounds really can
catch criminals and another story about a local outbreak of head
lice.
</P>
<P>
   I checked the temperature at the newspaper stand.
</P>
<P>
   123.
</P>
<P>
   There is a modern mall near the Midwestern State campus and
enough chain restaurants to salve all but the most discriminating
tastes. For any players who might be reading this, the classiest
strip club in town, Maximus, is way out on Seymour Highway.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cowboys, another chapter is about to begin. The Barry
Switzer era is over. The Hotter n' Hell chapter is about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Bring plenty of water. Wear loose clothing. And whatever you do,
don't bring a thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   The heat is like wool. And here come America's Sheep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980709.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8546 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNS'PLANE-AZR &LR;      07-09 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNS' </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS RAISE SAFETY CONCERNS OVER AMERICA WEST CHARTER PLANE
</HEADLINE>
 PLANE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 yMARY JO PITZL AND BOB YOUNG 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Phoenix Suns want to fly on a different plane because of
reports that the Federal Aviation Adminis tration is concerned
about airplane maintenance at America West Air lines.
</P>
<P>
   But the airline replied Thursday that the 29-year-old plane is
per fectly safe and is flying on regular commercial routes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Federal Aviation Administra tion last month put the airline
on ``Troubled Air Carrier Status,'' cit ing safety concerns raised
by the airline's flight attendants and me chanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have expressed our own concerns to America West regarding
the age and condition of the air craft,'' Bryan Colangelo, the
Suns's executive vice president and general manager, said in a
statement. ``They have repeatedly assured us that all maintenance
and safety issues are sufficiently monitored and addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, recent news has heightened our sense of urgency to
change planes for the remaining term of our charter agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined further comment Thursday, except to say the team has
ongoing discussions with the airline about its charter agreement.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Built in 1969, the Boeing 737-112 that the Suns lease is one of
the oldest in America West's fleet. Suns officials have been
negotiating with airline officials for months, trying to upgrade
equip ment on the aging plane.
</P>
<P>
   America West officials would not comment directly on the Suns'
statement but said the plane poses no problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message to get across is the aircraft is in great shape,''
said airline spokeswoman Patti Nowack.
</P>
<P>
   She dismissed as ``allegations, speculation and rumors'' reports
that the Suns' plane is the subject of FAA scrutiny because airline
offi cials failed to comply with a mandatory maintenance check and
instead continued to fly the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been notified by the FAA that there are any
problems with that aircraft,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was returned to service June 28 after undergoing an
annual maintenance check. It is modified annually for the
basketball team, with more first-class seats installed to
accommodate the players.
</P>
<P>
   During the off season, the plane is fitted with cabin-class
seats and is used to fly commercial routes. Nowak said she did not
know to which cities the plane is flying now. It looks like a
regular America West airplane but with a Phoenix Suns logo next to
the passenger door.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, some Suns players balked at flying on the plane
after its pilot walked off as he was getting ready to take the team
to Houston. The pilot was concerned about how the aircraft would
oper ate because its yaw damper, which helps stabilize the plane in
flight, was inoperable and the weather forecast called for choppy
weather between Phoenix and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After conferring with a senior pilot who was more familiar with
the plane, the pilot returned and flew to Houston without incident.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the March 30 inci dent, combined with the age of
the plane, fanned some players' fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my Lord,'' Suns center John ``Hot Rod'' Williams, a nerv
ous flyer anyway, said at the time. ``Any time the pilot jumps off,
that makes you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the team needs a new plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't like a car,'' he said last spring. ``You can't just
pull over to the side if something goes wrong. They said that part
isn't important. If it's not important, why'd they put it on the
plane?''
</P>
<P>
   A plane is ``completely flyable'' without its yaw damper, and
the part is not on the FAA's ``minimum equipment list,'' which
stipulates which parts must be in good working order before a plane
can leave the ground, said Russ Young, a safety officer with
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   But repeated problems with the 737's yaw damper have made it the
subject of an FAA airworthiness directive. By mid-2000, the part
must be replaced in all 737s. Replacement parts should be avail
able this fall, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, if a yaw damper breaks, the plane's owner
should fix it promptly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what happened, Nowack said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   However, she declined to provide copies of the maintenance
records and could not specify when the repair was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's operational now,'' she said. ``It was fixed when we knew
there was a problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention of the part being reported as causing
``diffi culty,'' according to 12 years' worth of records filed with
the FAA. The records are current through mid-April, the latest date
for which information could be obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Nowack said she didn't know why the yaw damper never appeared on
the service-difficulty reports, but she said she assumed it was
because it never caused a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, however, Colangelo characterized the yaw damper as
an ``ongoing problem.''
</P>
<P>
   And Boeing has said that the part has been a persistent problem.
</P>
<P>
   Although the yaw damper was never mentioned, incidents ranging
from the mundane to the alarming are detailed in the
service-difficulty reports.
</P>
<P>
   The repairs cropped up during routine inspections as well as
during flights, such as a September 1997 incident in which the
plane had to make an unscheduled landing be cause cabin pressure
was not being maintained. A check found that seals on the aircraft
door were not tight. The seals were replaced, and the plane
returned to service, re cords show.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's service-difficulty his tory revealed nothing out of
the ordinary, said Bill Waldock, associ ate director of the Center
for Aerospace Safety Education at Em bry Riddle Aeronautical
University in Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   Waldock reviewed records dating back to 1991 at &UR; The
Republic's &UR; request.
</P>
<P>
   He said some of the repairs might appear frightening to a
layman. But, he noted, problems were fixed as soon as they were
detected.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it, the airplane itself was never in danger,''
Wal dock said.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane's condition is a touchy subject. The Suns and the
airline have a long and mutually beneficial relationship, including
naming rights of America West Arena, where the team plays.
</P>
<P>
   The plane is scheduled to be retired at the end of next year
because it won't meet new noise-abatement guidelines that take
effect in 2000. Modifying the plane to make it run more quietly
would not be cost-efficient, airline officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   Using a newer-model craft could increase charter costs by four
or five times, according to airline officials, and the Suns' plane
actu ally is newer than many planes used to charter professional
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Suns players contin ued to fly on the plane, even
those with doubts about its reliability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been assured that noth ing can go wrong, that there is
no more chance, no more possibility that something could go wrong
(than on any other plane),'' said forward Danny Manning. ``We've
heard that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, when the pilot gets on the plane, then gets off saying
he doesn't want to fly the plane because it's inadequate, or he
doesn't feel comfortable doing it, that puts thoughts in your head.
</P>
<P>
   Others, such as guard Jason Kidd, said they weren't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jerry (Colangelo, the club's president) and Bryan
(Colangelo) were nervous about it, then I would be,'' Kidd said.
``But they've as sured us it's safe. We fly for a living. With a
perfect airplane there's always something that could go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard a few complaints, but I'm not that worried about
it. When we win a championship, maybe that (a new plane) will be
our reward.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
