<SLUG> BC-STREETSMARTS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW OF GRAVITY BOUND TO CATCH UP WITH INTERNET STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK VEVERKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
What will be the pin that pops the Internet bubble?
<TEXT>
<P>
   I hate to break it to you, but some event or series of events
ultimately will let the air out of these insanely valued Web
stocks. Gravity will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Most reasoned investors and even those stock-pickers who trade
like they're free-basing St. John's Wort will tell you that Yahoo
doesn't deserve its current market capitalization of about $8.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   That's bigger than the $7.6 billion-dollar market capitalization
of the New York Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   For heaven's sake, despite a second-quarter loss reported on
Wednesday that included one-time charges associated with the
company's acquisition of Viaweb, a maker of e-commerce software,
Yahoo's stock still rocketed as high as 9 percent to $202 in
after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, while most analysts pounded the table
yesterday for their firms' clients to buy Yahoo, the stock closed
down $2.19 at $184. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   It's wacky. Even Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan couldn't have
envisioned such madness when he made his infamous ``irrational
exuberance'' assessment of the market in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. By most enlightened accounts, Yahoo is a
fine company led by smart managers who have built a well-oiled
brand-building machine. It is the No. 1 Internet search engine and
deserves a stellar stock price.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you intelligently justify an $82 price surge in five
weeks?
</P>
<P>
   Short answer: You can't. Which brings us to this point: What
factors might bring Internet stocks in general, and Yahoo in
particular, back to Earth?
</P>
<P>
   One possible scenario is that weaker Internet stocks eventually
may start to suffer from their laggard positions and begin to miss
their quarterly earnings targets.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, some of the economic models used by analysts to
value Internet stocks may be called into question.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, could cause investors to re-evaluate their
positions in such search engine stocks that are performing like
Yahoo, says fund manager Kevin Landis of Firsthand Funds in San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  ``Like all stocks that miss their numbers, the laggards'
stock prices should head south,'' Landis says. ``That, I think,
will be the wake-up call'' for investors to start selling even
their top-performing Internet holdings, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Beating the consensus earnings estimate of Wall Street analysts
hasn't been terribly difficult for Yahoo, maintains Landis, who
doesn't own any Yahoo shares in either his technology value fund or
technology leaders fund.
</P>
<P>
   Landis, for one, thinks that Internet stock analysts have been
easy on the companies by setting relatively low earnings targets.
(Yahoo beat second-quarter earnings estimates of nine cents a share
_ charges excluded _ by six cents.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; That could change. ``Pretty soon, you're going to see some
analysts break from the ranks and become more bullish, raising
their expectations (of quarterly profits),'' Landis says.
</P>
<P>
   Another pin that could pop the bubble could be a general
downturn in the overall stock market, says analyst Dave Jones of
the California Technology Stock Letter in Half Moon Bay.
</P>
<P>
   A geopolitical event such as a war or energy crisis likely would
awaken investors to the fragility of Internet valuations, Jones
says.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Internet stocks has been difficult to watch for
Jones. In April, the Overpriced Stock Service, the California
Technology Stock Letter's sister publication, recommended that
investors short Yahoo at $114 a share. And although the stock has
defied such wisdom, Jones sticks by his publication's basic
assessment. ``The facts are that (Yahoo's valuation) isn't real,''
Jones says.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the stock analyst believes that a lot of money is
parked in Internet companies because there are few other hot
sectors to turn to.
</P>
<P>
   One last hope to return sanity to Internet stock prices is that
content really will be king. While, for now, portals and the
delivery of eyeballs on the Internet are winning investors' favor,
the companies that will bring entertainment programming and
financial services to the Internet will be the stocks that fetch
high valuations, says the chief executive of a Bay Area Internet
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once investors start to figure out that content companies will
drive relationships with the portals,'' their money will begin to
shift to stocks other than search engine companies, the CEO says.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist analyst Paul Noglows weighed in
yesterday as a voice of reason on Yahoo. He went against the grain
of his analyst counterparts by lowering his rating on the Santa
Clara company to ``hold'' based solely on valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Because the stock is trading around 37 times 1999 revenue
estimates of $265 million, `` I just didn't feel comfortable
telling investors to buy the stock at ($184) a share,'' Noglows
says.
</P>
<P>
   Reason. What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON RAIDERS
</P>
<P>
   The move by big-hitting investment banker Frank Quattrone from
Deutsche Bank Securities to Credit Suisse First Boston is proving
to be a transition of major proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the technology banker and his top lieutenants
joined CS First Boston, more than 100 Deutsche Bank bankers,
analysts and support people are following them to new jobs at CS
First Boston offices in Menlo Park, San Francisco, London and
Boston, according to a Bay Area executive recruiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the largest shifts of talent that I've ever
seen,'' the recruiter says.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Veverka can be reached at 901 Mission St., S.F. 94103,
phone at (415) 777-8444, or e-mail at mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. He also
appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak program on Tuesdays and Thursdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
