<HEADLINE>
HOFFMANS MAKE SIBLING HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the late 1800s, there were rare instances when major-league
managers had brothers on their rosters. But on Thursday, Dodgers
manager Glenn Hoffman and his brother, San Diego reliever Trevor
Hoffman, are believed to have made major-league history when the
manager and player were in opposing dugouts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1898, Fred Clarke managed his brother Josh at Louisville of
the National League. From 1894-95, Cleveland's Patsy Tabeau managed
his brother George. And in 1884, Ed Hengel managed his brother
Moxie during the lone season of existence for the Chicago franchise
of the Union Association.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the 1997 edition of ``Total Baseball _ The
Official Encyclopedia of Major League Baseball,'' the Hoffman
battle is one of a kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know fathers and sons have played against each other. But
brothers?'' said the 40-year-old Glenn. ``There is always a first
for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a neat business to be able to see your brother on the
other side,'' said Trevor, 30.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw unnerved: While with the Cincinnati Reds, Jeff Shaw was
pitching for a club written off for the playoffs. The new Dodgers
closer, who has 23 saves, inherits the pressure of finishing games
for a team fighting to make a major turnaround toward the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be the same situation anywhere else,'' said
Shaw, who was not used Thursday after being traded Saturday for
infielder/outfielder Paul Konerko and pitcher Dennis Reyes. ``The
Dodgers being in a large market is the same as Cincinnati in a
small market or in Pittsburgh. It's a one-, two- or three-run lead
and you go out there and get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino out longer: Dodgers shortstop Jose Vizcaino expects to
be out 3-4 more weeks to recover from his right-ankle sprain.
Vizcaino, who was placed on the 15-day disabled list on June 22,
has missed 14 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino had his cast removed Monday and began working out on a
treadmill Wednesday. Juan Castro, who went 2 for 4 at shortstop
Thursday, Wilton Guerrero and Alex Cora are expected to platoon at
the position.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks Mike: During the All-Star Game, former Dodger Mike Piazza
and Dodgers right fielder Gary Sheffield discussed hitting. The two
were involved in a blockbuster seven-player deal May 15 that sent
now New York Met Piazza to Florida and Sheffield to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield said Piazza suggested they both need to stay on their
back leg longer, which would help their hands come through the
hitting zone quicker. After working on it during batting practice,
Sheffield hit a two-run, first-inning homer off San Diego's Mark
Langston in his first at-bat Thursday. His homer also extended his
streak of reaching base to 21 straight games dating to June 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about our power and what we've been doing
wrong,'' said Sheffield. ``He had some great advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: Right-hander Ramon Martinez began shoulder exercises
Wednesday. Martinez, who had season-ending shoulder surgery June
30, said he will begin weightlifting in August and might return to
his native Dominican Republic for the remainder of the season....
Right-hander Darren Hall, who pitched two innings for Class-A San
Bernardino on Tuesday, said he is ready to return, and the Dodgers
will likely make a decision on him soon. The reliever has been on
the DL since April 8 with a rotator-cuff injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
