<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP GETS BEST POSSIBLE FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ There are other teams that might have made for a
storybook World Cup final: Holland, possibly the most brilliant
side in France the past month; or Croatia, overlooked and
underestimated; or even faltering Nigeria or the dangerous Danes or
maybe even Italy, which makes defense, at least in my eyes, a
beautiful thing.
</P>
<P>
   But it's impossible to ignore the truth, which is that the first
62 games of the 1998 World Cup have led to the perfect championship
game, a fight between the reigning champion, seeking an
unprecedented fifth crown, and the proud host, thrilled to be
taking part in the final for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   That Brazil and France, which will face off Sunday night at the
Stade de France in Saint-Denis, may also be the two finest teams
--- sorry, Holland --- in the tournament makes it all the better.
But that neither of them are all that great says more about the
current state of world soccer than anything else might.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians have stumbled through this tournament, constantly
seeking to find form, a search that has led to moments of brilliant
offensive soccer and little else.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ronaldo is a god; he hasn't been at his best during this
Cup, slowed by a knee injury, and yet there is no other striker
here even remotely near his level. Yes, he's got some superb
support, especially from the brilliant Rivaldo and from Dunga, the
rock at the back of the Carioca midfield.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense, despite Cafu and Junior Baiano and Roberto
Carlos, has been porous, so much so that with a little more luck,
Denmark might be here instead of the Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   Poor defense is part of the price Brazil pays to play beautiful,
flowing soccer, (ital) jogo bonito (end ital), to make art from
sport. If only it were so. Rarely this Cup have the Brazilians been
artists, or poets; when given the perfect opportunity to
demonstrate how stunning this game can be, in the semifinal against
the Netherlands, they sat back on defense and went at the superior
Dutch with a counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   Put this Brazilian side up against the wonderful team that won
the title in 1970, and it would be sad. Maybe 3-0, maybe 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, put this one up against the team that outlasted Italy in
the '94 final at the Rose Bowl. I'll take the '94 bunch, which ---
thanks to Carlos Alberto Parreira's defensive tactics --- was far
more organized than this group.
</P>
<P>
   That said, we can expect the (ital) penta (end ital) from
Brazil. It is too strong for France, especially a France that must
play without suspended Laurent Blanc, the backbone of the finest
defense on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Defense is the core of the French game, which is workmanlike
and, in the hands of playmaker Zinedine Zidane, capable of some
remarkable things. But take away Zidane, and take away defensive
midfielder Didier Deschamps, and take away three-quarters of that
back line --- Blanc and stopper Marcel Desailly and right back
Lilian Thuram, the hero of the semifinal triumph over Croatia ---
and what you've got is a quite ordinary team.
</P>
<P>
   No forward has scored in three games, and the way starters Youri
Djorkaeff and Stephane Guivarc'h thrash around out there, it's
amazing that France ever produces up front. Defenders --- Blanc and
Thuram --- are responsible for all the goals since the first round,
when 20-year-old Thierry Henry, somehow relegated to a reserve
role, found the net three times.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's defense can be scored upon, but can France do it? We'll
see.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of truly strong teams in France is a product of
soccer's globalization. The sport has become, largely, faceless:
Everybody does the same things, everybody knows each other (they
all play, all the world's stars, in the same leagues, in Italy and
Spain and England and France). That's why when someone like a
Ronaldo or a Zidane comes along, he is so celebrated. There are few
Ronaldos and Zidanes in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there is a creed, ``professionalism,'' which dictates
that results matter over content, over style. When you are touched,
you go down and hope the referee awards you a penalty kick. When
someone goes by you, you grab his jersey or kick his ankles,
anything to stop him. It's the way the game is played, and
everybody knows this.
</P>
<P>
   The losers are the fans, who are denied --- except in a few
instances, when the Dutch play or when Ronaldo or Zidane or one of
Laudrups weaves their magic --- what they most want: spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this has led to an amazing amount of parity, so we
get few blowouts anymore. The games are tighter, and that's good;
if only they were more spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, the best teams --- Brazil and France and Holland
--- survive, and so we get the promise of a ``great'' final, a
matchup between two of the ``finest teams in the game.
</P>
<P>
   If only that were enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
