<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CROWNHEIGHTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
21-YEAR TERM FOR INCITING A KILLING IN CROWN HEIGHTS, BROOKLYN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ending the criminal case stemming from the city's
worst racial clashes in years, a man convicted of inciting the
crowd before the killing of a Hasidic scholar in Crown Heights was
sentenced Thursday to 21 years in prison, a term even longer than
that dealt to the killer.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Charles Price, was convicted of violating the civil
rights of the victim, Yankel Rosenbaum, by egging on a crowd during
the first of four nights of violence that tore apart the Brooklyn
neighborhood in August 1991. Although Price was not directly linked
to the stabbing of Rosenbaum, prosecutors said a member of the mob,
Lemrick Nelson Jr., carried out the stabbing afterward. Nelson was
sentenced to 19 and a half years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In imposing a sentence on Price on Thursday, Judge David Trager
of U.S. District Court in Brooklyn said he did not render the
maximum sentence, 24 years, because he did not believe that Price
intended for the mob to kill Rosenbaum. However, Trager said he did
not impose the minimum sentence, slightly more than 19 years, in
part because Price had not expressed any remorse for ``the evil
that his rhetoric set in motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Price is the last of two men charged in the Rosenbaum killing.
Prosecutors said that he received a longer sentence than Nelson in
part because Price had a previous criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   The sentencing ended the criminal phase of one of the most
bitter racial conflicts in the city's recent history. The Crown
Heights violence, which exposed the rifts between the black and
Jewish residents of the neighborhood, had repercussions citywide,
and was seen as a key element in the electoral defeat of Mayor
David Dinkins by Rudolph Giuliani in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this sentence we close the last chapter of a terrible
incident in New York City history,'' Valerie Caproni, the assistant
U.S. attorney who prosecuted the case, told the court Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caproni asked the judge to impose the maximum sentence on
Price, arguing that ``bias crimes strike at the very essence of
what we are as Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, the length of the sentence depended on Trager's
interpretation of the legal significance of Price's actions. If the
judge had found that Price's conduct constituted manslaughter or a
lesser offense, he would have imposed a lighter sentence.
</P>
<P>
   However, in court Thursday, Trager said that Price's conduct in
inciting the crowd was so reckless and depraved that it met the
legal standards of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``By setting off what he did he bears the moral
responsibility,'' Trager said. He later added that ``even though he
did not intend to kill Rosenbaum, the bottom line is he is morally
and legally responsible for the events he set off.''
</P>
<P>
   The violence in Crown Heights erupted after a 7-year-old black
boy, Gavin Cato, was fatally injured in a traffic accident
involving a car driven by a Hasidic Jew. During the trial of Price,
a prosecutor, Alan Vinograd, said that he fired up with mob with
expressions like ``Kill the Jews!'' ``An eye for an eye!'' and
``Let's go!''
</P>
<P>
   Price and his lawyers have continued to maintain his innocence,
and have announced their intention to appeal the verdict. Thursday,
Price demonstrated a powerful speaking voice as he told Trager that
the jury had reached the wrong verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry for his death,'' Price said. ``I had nothing to do
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement, Price denied that he had ever demonstrated
any racial prejudice and said he had not received justice from the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell me I got a fair trial and I don't see it,'' Price
said. ``I can't do anything because I am a small person.''
</P>
<P>
   During her statement to the court, Fay Rosenbaum, Yankel's
mother, assailed Price's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no apology from Charles Price, no remorse,''
she said. ``While his family and friends will always be able to
visit him and be with him irrespective of the sentence passed, my
husband and I, Yankel's family and friends are left only to visit a
grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rosenbaum said her son was the ultimate innocent victim, a
man who harbored hatred for no one and who was killed by a
hate-filled mob.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yankel accepted people for who they were, not what they were
or what they had _ irrespective of race, creed or color,'' she
said, her voice breaking. ``His respect of all people was
demonstrated by his absolute abhorrence of discrimination of any
kind, his unqualified defense of the oppressed and his inflexible
principles of fairness, equality, truth and justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the real Yankel Rosenbaum that Charles Price would
have found had he bothered to seek, had he not vented his putrid,
violent hate, calling for his cold-blooded murder and insuring that
it was carried out with no regard or respect for Yankel, the
person, but with a blind, baseless bigotry aimed at what Yankel was
_ a Jew.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
