<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN10-COX     07-09 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Streak hits 9 behind 3 HRs
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In nine innings Thursday, the Braves reconfirmed much of
what had been learned over the season's first half. No park can
hold them, and their bullpen still can make a henchman's blood run
cold.
</P>
<P>
   In their first visit to Pro Player Stadium since last October's
NLCS debacle, the Braves extended their win streak to nine games _
the longest in two years _ with a 6-4 win over Florida, the game
determined on a Chipper Jones two-run homer in the first and Javy
Lopez's upper-deck job with two men on in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Not as convincing was the relief work of Dennis Martinez, who
was handed a four-run lead in the eighth and promply gave up a pair
of runs after a Todd Zeile double and Derreck Lee's triple. With
the lead down to two, John Rocker and Russ Springer worked out of
the mess with a pair of line-drive outs, before Kerry Ligtenberg
recorded his 10th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to get a scoreless 1-2-3,'' said Rocker. ``That
would have been a shame to lose that one, after being up 6-0. But
that's a good way to start the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz took a shutout into the sixth inning to improve his
record to 6-2. The night marked the seventh time in Smoltz's 12
starts this season he has held opponents to two runs or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chipper set the stage with the bomb in the first and Smoltz
was on the top of his game,'' said manager Bobby Cox. ``Awesome
performance. We're just trying to be careful with John. He threw 95
(mph), 96 all night long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as hard as I've thrown this year,'' Smoltz said.
``Coming off seven days off, I didn't know how I'd come off but my
back cleared up real good.''
</P>
<P>
   With Andruw Jones scratched from the lineup when his (and
Randall Simon's) morning flight to Miami from Curacao was canceled,
the Braves played three men short, with Ryan Klesko still
recovering from an appendectomy. But Lopez filled the power vacuum
with a three-run shot into the upper deck as the Braves had their
fourth multi-homer game in the last seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big relief, coming out of a slump,'' said Lopez, who
neglected to recall he is hitting .362 in his last 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   Slump? ``Well, I was trying to get to the All-Star Game with 20
home runs,'' the catcher confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was better for 20. He merely won a game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
