<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ADD TWO, TALK TO ELLIS' AGENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys got two more rookies to agree to
terms yesterday and began negotiations with the agent of top pick
Greg Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Former Alabama-Birmingham safety Izell Reese, a sixth-round
pick, and former Cincinnati tight end Rod Monroe, a seventh-round
pick, became the fourth and fifth of the Cowboys' nine draft picks
to come to terms. Both players agreed to three-year deals, Cowboys
vice president Stephen Jones said. On Wednesday, Michael Myers,
fourth-round pick from Alabama, and seventh-round picks Antonio
Fleming, from Georgia, and Tarik Smith, from California, agreed to
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys talked to the agents of the remaining unsigned
picks, including Ellis' agent Butch Williams yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams nor Jones, who is handling the Ellis negotiations, was
available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have said they will try to get things done before
training camp opens Wednesday. Williams proved his commitment to
that pledge by flying to Dallas yesterday for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the parameters for Ellis' contract have been set. As the
eighth overall pick, he will likely get a little better deal than
the one signed by ninth pick Fred Taylor, who got $10.7 million
over six years with a $5 million signing bonus from the
Jacksonville Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's eighth pick James Farrior received $8,846,000 over
five years with a $4 million bonus from the Jets.
</P>
</TEXT>
