<P>
   (NYT11) HADERA, Israel -- July 9, 1998 -- AUSCHWITZ-LAND, 7-9 --
An Israeli teacher, Zypora Frank, 63, sits in front of papers that
prove her grandfather's factory in Poland stood on land that became
part of the Auschwitz death camp. Her parents had tried to shield
her from all this. ``It was a horror Q to suddenly be connected to
this place!'' she exclaims. ``My blood pressure soared, I got a
bloody nose, I thought I was going to die.'' Her grandfather, whose
tile factory once stood there, was among those who lost his life
there. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- NY-FIREFIGHTER-FUNERAL, 7-9
-- Scott, 13, left, and his brother Buddy,12, peer out the window
of their limousine at some of the 12,000 firefighters in formation
following the funeral service for their father, Capt. Scott La
Piedra, in Staten Island on Thursday. Despite burns to 70 percent
of his body, LaPiedra, with big lungs and a big heart, defied
medical logic by surviving for a month before finally succumbing on
July 4. He was 40-years-old. (J. Emilio Flores/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ROME -- July 9, 1998 -- BIRTHRATE-DECLINE-2, 7-9 --
Elderly Italian men playing bocce in a park in Rome. With the
lowest birth rate in the world, Italy is increasingly becoming a
nation of older people. There are now more people over the age of
60 in Italy than there are under 20. (James Hill/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) STOCKHOLM, Sweden -- July 9, 1998 -- BIRTHRATE-DECLINE-1,
7-9 -- Mia Hulton, 33, and her friend, Ryszard Szukin, 47, chat at
their home in Stockholm. Like many European women, she does not
intend to start a family soon. ``There are times when I think
perhaps I will be missing something important if I don't have a
child,'' she says. ``But today women finally have so many chances
to have the life they want. I just find it hard to see where the
children would fit in.'' (Michael Specter/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
