Graham Nickson, a quick-witted, soft-spoken British painter who is
the dean of the school, in order to kick-start his students. (Sarah
Boxer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MINNEAPOLIS -- July 9, 1998 -- QUACKS-MUSEUM-2, 7-9 --
Robert McCoy in a phrenology machines, which renders personality
readings based on the shape of the head. After 14 years, McCoy's
Museum of Questionable Medical Devices is finally taking off.
``We're seeing 750 people a week now,'' says Robert McCoy, the
71-year-old retired salesman who founded it. ``Until this year, I
was subsidizing it from Social Security, my pension and my wife's
salary.'' (Steve Woit/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MINNEAPOLIS -- July 9, 1998 -- QUACKS-MUSEUM-1, 7-9 --
The MacGregor Rejuvenator, in the Museum of Questionable Medical
Devices, was advertised in the 1930s as reversing the aging
process. After 14 years, the museum of quackery is finally taking
off. ``We're seeing 750 people a week now,'' says Robert McCoy, the
71-year-old retired salesman who founded it. ``Until this year, I
was subsidizing it from Social Security, my pension and my wife's
salary.'' (Steve Woit/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- NY-CROWNHEIGHTS, 7-9 -- The
family members of Yankel Rosenbaum gather Thursday outside the
courthouse in Brooklyn after the sentencing of Charles Price.
Yankel's brother, Norman, third from left, attended with his
mother, Fay, and his father, Max. Price was convicted of violating
Yankel's civil rights by egging on a crowd during the first of four
nights of violence that tore apart the Brooklyn neighborhood in
August 1991. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 --
SUB-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-B&AMP;W, 7-9 -- Zambelli Silverman in her
Manhattan town house in 1983. Ms. Silverman, an 82-year-old Upper
East Side socialite, disappeared on Sunday; Sante and Kenneth
Kimes, a mother-and-son team with long criminal records, might have
been involved, but have yet to be charged with any crimes in
connection with her disappearance. (Keith Meyers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MILWAUKEE -- July 9, 1998 -- MILWAUKEE-STEELTECH-2, 7-9
-- Despite the lauded quality of Steeltech Manufacturing's work,
Chief Executive Charles Wallace says ``It's been constant
firefighting.'' Even though it has finally begun to generate some
operating profits, Steeltech has not made payments on more than $30
million in federal, state, local and private loans since 1996.
(John Saller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MILWAUKEE -- July 9, 1998 -- MILWAUKEE-STEELTECH-1, 7-9
-- The quality of Steeltech Manufacturing's work, as exemplified by
this welder, draws praise. But the privately held company is no
dream come true for its investors or for customers who had to
provide cash and other concessions to keep it afloat. Even though
it has finally begun to generate some operating profits, Steeltech
has not made payments on more than $30 million in federal, state,
local and private loans since 1996. (John Saller/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HADERA, Israel -- July 9, 1998 -- AUSCHWITZ-LAND, 7-9 --
An Israeli teacher, Zypora Frank, 63, sits in front of papers that
prove her grandfather's factory in Poland stood on land that became
part of the Auschwitz death camp. Her parents had tried to shield
her from all this. ``It was a horror Q to suddenly be connected to
this place!'' she exclaims. ``My blood pressure soared, I got a
bloody nose, I thought I was going to die.'' Her grandfather, whose
tile factory once stood there, was among those who lost his life
there. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- NY-FIREFIGHTER-FUNERAL, 7-9
-- Scott, 13, left, and his brother Buddy,12, peer out the window
of their limousine at some of the 12,000 firefighters in formation
following the funeral service for their father, Capt. Scott La
Piedra, in Staten Island on Thursday. Despite burns to 70 percent
of his body, LaPiedra, with big lungs and a big heart, defied
medical logic by surviving for a month before finally succumbing on
July 4. He was 40-years-old. (J. Emilio Flores/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ROME -- July 9, 1998 -- BIRTHRATE-DECLINE-2, 7-9 --
Elderly Italian men playing bocce in a park in Rome. With the
lowest birth rate in the world, Italy is increasingly becoming a
nation of older people. There are now more people over the age of
60 in Italy than there are under 20. (James Hill/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) STOCKHOLM, Sweden -- July 9, 1998 -- BIRTHRATE-DECLINE-1,
7-9 -- Mia Hulton, 33, and her friend, Ryszard Szukin, 47, chat at
their home in Stockholm. Like many European women, she does not
intend to start a family soon. ``There are times when I think
perhaps I will be missing something important if I don't have a
child,'' she says. ``But today women finally have so many chances
to have the life they want. I just find it hard to see where the
children would fit in.'' (Michael Specter/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BAR HARBOR, Maine -- July 9, 1998 -- RICH-MANS-TIME, 7-9
-- Howard Tedoff beside his Cessna Skylane after a flight from New
Jersey to Maine in pursuit of lunch. ``Wait until you see Penobscot
Bay from a small plane,'' he says. ``It is unbelievable. It is
amazing.'' He has been flying for 20 years, and not only does he
love the experience and sensations, he wants other people to love
them, too. (Michael T. Kaufman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- PATIENCE-OPERA-REVIEW, 7-9 --
Lincoln Center Festival: Lori Phillips, left, and Elaine Valby in
``Patience and Sarah.'' The opera is strongest at depicting the
dangerous yet ecstatic courtship between these bold women. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- ONEGIN-BALLET-REVIEW, 7-9 --
Sue Jin Kang as Tatyana and Roland Vogel as Eugene Onegin. The cast
on view did its visible best to fill in the outlines of clearly
sketched roles. One of the problems after John Cranko's death in
1973 was that his ballets were so meticulously accurate in their
details that they began to look preserved in amber. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. -- July 9, 1998 --
APPALACHIAN-HIKING, 7-9 -- Bill Bryson, intrepid hiker and author
of ``A Walk in the Woods,'' resting outside Williamstown. ``It's
hard to get lost on the trail,'' he says. ``But once you do, it's
easy to compound it.'' (Matt Anderson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) KATONAH, N.Y. -- July 9, 1998 -- DICHTER-ANNIVERSARY, 7-9
-- Pianist Misha Dichter at Caramoor in Katonah. This weekend,
Caramoor will be celebrating the 25th anniversary of Dichter's
debut here, and an association that has included recitals, concerto
performances, chamber music and master classes every year since the
beginning. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- BERNSTEIN-MUSICIAN-2, 7-9 --
Leonard Bernstein conducting the New York Philharmonic in the park
in August 1986. His works will be played Friday night at a free
concert in Central Park. Bernstein's early symphonies are the
efforts of a clearly gifted young musician to fashion American
jazz, Hebraic chant, Mahlerian angst and Stravinskian
propulsiveness into big, sweeping statements. (Barton
Silverman/1986 New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- BERNSTEIN-MUSICIAN-1-B&AMP;W, 7-9
-- Leonard Bernstein conducting the New York Philharmonic in the
park in August 1986. His works will be played Friday night at a
free concert in Central Park. Bernstein's early symphonies are the
efforts of a clearly gifted young musician to fashion American
jazz, Hebraic chant, Mahlerian angst and Stravinskian
propulsiveness into big, sweeping statements. (Barton
Silverman/1986 New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
