<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
CANBY-THEATER-BRAIN-2, 7-9 -- John Goodman and Frances Conroy in
``Skin of Our Teeth.'' The production is showing its age these
days, but there's nothing wrong with that unless, as sometimes
happens in this staging, you have the feeling that the actors are
patronizing their material, patting it on the head. What is more
difficult to accept is Wilder's conviction that man will somehow
muddle through. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
CANBY-THEATER-BRAIN-1, 7-9 -- Malcolm Gets, center foreground, and
other actors in William Finn's chamber opera ``A New Brain.'' The
production is composer-lyricist Finn's attempt to deal with what
was obviously a doomy, seriously traumatic experience: the
preliminary diagnosis of an inoperable brain tumor, which he
received in 1992 just two weeks after winning Tonys for his book
and score for ``Falsettos.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 12 --
DRAWING-SCHOOL-2-B&AMP;W, 7-9 -- Graham Nickson, who invented a
two-week drawing marathon at the New York Studio School of Drawing,
Painting and Sculpture a decade ago. The quick-witted, soft-spoken
British painter, who is the dean of the school, came up with the
idea in order to kick-start his students. ``What is space?'' he
asks his students. ``Think of negative space as yogurt and then
drop a raspberry into it. The berry doesn't sink. It's held in
place by the yogurt.'' (Sarah Boxer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
