<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8574 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KEISSER-LADN     07-09 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES' GWYNN CAN'T BELIEVE WHAT'S HAPPENED TO THE DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES Tony Gwynn walked down the tunnel from the Padres'
clubhouse to the visitor's dugout, gazed at the empty Dodger
Stadium, and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``How,'' said Gwynn to the walls of the stadium, ``could they
fire Mark Cresse?''
</P>
<P>
   That is just one of the dozen or so questions people have about
the Franchise Formerly Known As The Dodgers. The routine now for
everyone, from the players to the fans, is to come to the ballpark,
buy a scorecard and see if you recognize the names.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres' Hall of Famer-to-be grew up in Long Beach as a fan
of the Dodgers, back to the years when the franchise was
transitioning from the Drysdale, Wills and Willie Davis era to
Lopes, Garvey and Cey.
</P>
<P>
   So watching the Dodgers chip away at this foundation of
consistency with Marlin-like abandon left him as dumbfounded as the
next guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all so ... so ... different,'' said Gwynn before
Thursday's game, a 12-2 Dodger win. ``Something like this has never
happened before. That's why there's so much ... Heck, it's so
unusual I don't even know what to call it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers have not only been stable around here (meaning Los
Angeles), but around baseball. They've been as stable a franchise
as you could have. So to make the moves they've made in just one
year has caught a lot of people off guard. Things just weren't done
the usual Dodger way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, like 1997, Gwynn would make his first visit to
Dodger Stadium and spend a few hours touching base with guys he's
known as Dodger landmarks, guys like Cresse, the former bullpen
coach and fellow Long Beacher who was launched at the same time as
Glenn Gregson and Reggie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he spent a few minutes talking to Bobby Bonilla and
finding out how he likes being in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers always were consistent about their personnel. The
manager, the general manager, the players,'' Gwynn said, ``these
are guys who were here 10, 20, 30 years. So turning it around like
they've done is incredibly surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was told that four different hands made the four major
decisions of 1998. The owners (Fox) traded Mike Piazza, Fred Claire
traded Hideo Nomo, Bob Graziano fired Fred Cclaire and Bill
Russell, and Tommy Lasorda made the Jeff Shaw-Paul Konerko deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's response: Welcome to baseball, '90s style.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way things are done now. Corporate people own teams
and make swift and emotionless corporate-style dexisions. Tradition
may be hallowed by some, but it can be an obstacle to the
ever-hungry bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around baseball, just about everyone is talking about what Fox
has done to the Dodgers,'' he said. ``They're not talking about the
Dodgers as much as pointing a finger at Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn has gone through two separate fire sales during his 17
seasons in the Padres organization, in 1987 and 1993, watching the
Padres dispense or lose personnel like the Alomar brothers, Derek
Bell, Joe Carter, Fred McGriff and Gary Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   So there is no time for him to worry about what the Dodgers are
doing. Whatever childhood attachment he had about the team departed
the first time he stepped into the batter's box against them.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the Padres of 1998 bear a resemblence in
several areas to the Dodgers of old. There is the presence of two
Dodgers on the coaching staff, Dave Stewart and Davey Lopes, and
catcher Carlos Hernandez is a former Dodger. But it goes beyond the
literal.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, a club-record 25 games over .500 and leading the
N.L. West by five games, have built their team around a solid corp
of pitchers -- Andy Ashby, Trevor Hoffman, Kevin Brown and Joey
Hamilton. It has stuck by a solid veterans, one homegrown, Gwynn,
and two acquired four years ago in a major trade, Ken Caminiti and
Steve Finley.
</P>
<P>
   When it decided to make a offseason move, it was for a
high-quality talent like Brown, who gives the Padres the kind of
pitching depth to compete with the Atlanta Braves in the
postseason, much less the N.L. West. The Padres have lowered their
team ERA from last year's 4.99 to 3.62.
</P>
<P>
   The roster has also been supplemented by products from the farm
system, guys like outfielder Ruben Rivera and pitcher Matt Clement,
who are slowly being given room to grow into their uniforms and
have been labeled as untouchables -- the way Paul Konerko once was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moves we made were the right moves,'' said Gwynn, who
considers this Padres team to be the best one ever. ``The guys we
have counted on have delivered. Greg Vaughn (30 homers, 74 RBI) has
come through like a champ.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had all of the ingredients you need to have in a good
year. But our offense can be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti started the season slowly, hitting .240 into late June
before a nine-game, .531 sprint to end the first-half. Gwynn, who
has hit .353 or better the last seasons, will tell you that he's
having a horrible season at .329 and 45 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good enough to get us a five-game lead, but we can
do better,'' said Gwynn. ``We'll have to if we want to keep things
going. We have to remind ourselves that we haven't accomplished
anything yet. We've played well, but we still have half a season to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Dodgers. But Dodger fans may not be watching the
standings as much as the transaction wire. The Padres are here
through Sunday, then don't return until September. By then, the
walls may be the only thing Tony Gwynn recognizes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
