<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8575 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-LEWIS-LADN     07-09 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-LEWIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDHAM PASSING TEST AS GM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When there were no opportunities for women basketball players in
the United States, like the playmaker she was at USC, Rhonda
Windham created one.
</P>
<P>
   Founder of the Say No Classic that has provided summer league
basketball for college players since 1991, and many other
tournaments for former players, Windham would not rest until the
job was done. She is the consummate businesswoman with a special
interest in women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Today her job as the general manager of the Los Angeles Sparks
is just as demanding. It's grueling, has many challenges, but it's
everything Windham wanted and more when she sought the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my job,'' Windham said while watching the Sparks work
out at the Forum. ``It's a lot of work, a lot of hours, but this is
what I've wanted to do. I've been working toward being a boss in
women's basketball on a full-time basis for a long time. All I'm
trying to do is do the best job I can possibly do and share with
our team and our staff the insight I may have to this game.''
</P>
<P>
   And that would be plenty.
</P>
<P>
   The rebirth of the new women's pro leagues today probably can be
traced back to the mid-80s at USC, where Cheryl Miller, Pamela and
Paula McGee, Cynthia Cooper and Windham transformed and popularized
the game on the collegiate level, drawing national attention and
paving the way for young girls to follow in their footsteps. Except
for Paula McGee, who is a minister and manager for her twin sister,
Pamela, all are making their mark in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   Windham, a New York native who grew up in the Bronx, left her
mark at USC where she is still the career record-holder in assists
(735). She made her most assists (197) as a freshman in 1983,
dishing off to Miller and the McGeees en route to the Trojans'
first NCAA championship. She redshirted in 1984, another banner
season for USC, after undergoing knee surgery, but returned just as
strong, and as a senior won the 1987 Naismith Award for the
nation's top players under 5-foot-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always providing leadership in getting our team
together and knowing how to keep egos in check and making sure
everybody got the ball on our national championship team,'' Pamela
McGee said. ``I guess she somewhat has the same responsibilty now
as general manager.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BALANCING ACT
</P>
<P>
   For Sparks president Johnny Buss, Windham brought the perfect
balance to the position. Besides the management skills she honed
with the summer league program, she spent seven years as assistant
public-relations director with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how I am and what I need to balance myself,'' Buss
said. ``There were certainly general managers that I talked to ...
but to balance me, I needed someone who had a strong interest in
women's basketball, and a person who would put their heart and soul
into it. I needed someone who was business-minded, that would be
strict and tend to the business at hand. I tend to be a free
spirit. I needed Rhonda to balance me out.''
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIVE DECISION
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most crucial decision Windham has made was firing
her former USC coach, Linda Sharp, after the team produced a 4-7
mark midway through the inaugural season last year.
</P>
<P>
   Windham demands ``effort and passion'' from the players as well
as from the staff, but when she saw that missing and didn't see any
signs of improvement, she fired Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to take my personal feelings put of it,'' said Windham,
who spoke briefly to Sharp at the women's NCAA Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Windham moved another old friend, Julie Rousseau, from assistant
to interim head coach after relieving Sharp. Rousseau salvaged the
season, turning it into a near playoff contender. Windham removed
the interim label and made Rousseau a permanent fixture.
</P>
<P>
   Friendship aside, Rousseau understands the nature of her role as
head coach and Windham's responsibilty as the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I even took this job and Rhonda told me last season
that I was going to be the interim head coach, she said this is not
about friendship, this is business and I know that,'' said
Rousseau, who used to coach in Windham's summer league. ``She put
me in this position because she believed in me. In that same
respect, I know that any decision she would make would be for
business-sake and professional-sake and I respect her enough for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   GROWING PAINS
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, in the second year of the WNBA, the Sparks (3-8) are
in another uncomfortable position, struggling to find consistency
before another playoff passes.
</P>
<P>
   Windham is concerned, but she's not panicking. She sighted the
late arrivals of Lisa Leslie and Haixia Zheng, who played in the
World Championships and joined the team two days before tipoff, and
subsequent injuries to the Sparks' promising top draft pick,
Allison Feaster, and then Zheng, as contributing factors to the
sluggish start. She's not ready to push any buttons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a young coach and she has a bright future in this
league as a head coach,'' she said. ``I have a lot of confidence in
my staff and the players that we have on this team. It's important
not to panic. And if you believe in your personnel, sometimes when
you don't want to be patient you have to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all in a day's work as a general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
