Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- ONEGIN-BALLET-REVIEW, 7-9 --
Sue Jin Kang as Tatyana and Roland Vogel as Eugene Onegin. The cast
on view did its visible best to fill in the outlines of clearly
sketched roles. One of the problems after John Cranko's death in
1973 was that his ballets were so meticulously accurate in their
details that they began to look preserved in amber. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. -- July 9, 1998 --
APPALACHIAN-HIKING, 7-9 -- Bill Bryson, intrepid hiker and author
of ``A Walk in the Woods,'' resting outside Williamstown. ``It's
hard to get lost on the trail,'' he says. ``But once you do, it's
easy to compound it.'' (Matt Anderson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) KATONAH, N.Y. -- July 9, 1998 -- DICHTER-ANNIVERSARY, 7-9
-- Pianist Misha Dichter at Caramoor in Katonah. This weekend,
Caramoor will be celebrating the 25th anniversary of Dichter's
debut here, and an association that has included recitals, concerto
performances, chamber music and master classes every year since the
beginning. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- BERNSTEIN-MUSICIAN-2, 7-9 --
Leonard Bernstein conducting the New York Philharmonic in the park
in August 1986. His works will be played Friday night at a free
concert in Central Park. Bernstein's early symphonies are the
efforts of a clearly gifted young musician to fashion American
jazz, Hebraic chant, Mahlerian angst and Stravinskian
propulsiveness into big, sweeping statements. (Barton
Silverman/1986 New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 9, 1998 -- BERNSTEIN-MUSICIAN-1-B&AMP;W, 7-9
