<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASORDA SWEARS HE DIDN'T BACK-STAB RUSSELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Incredibly, my old pal, Tom Lasorda, still is sizzling at me for
breaking omerta more than two weeks ago and brazenly quoting ousted
Dodger manager Bill Russell about what he thought of Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   Before the start of Thursday afternoon's match between the
Dodgers and San Diego Padres, he angrily berated me in the Dodger
clubhouse in front of Eric Karros' locker, then took me in the
players' television lounge and continued his verbal assault behind
closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you do that to me?'' shrieked Lasorda. ``I thought
you were my friend. Do you realize that you've caused me to have to
defend myself all over the country?
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you quote Bill Russell saying those things about me?
How could Bill Russell say those things about me? I love Bill
Russell. I would never do anything to hurt him. You've caused me a
lot of grief.''
</P>
<P>
   For that, Tommy, I'm very, very sorry.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to solemnly promise right now that the next time Bill
Russell accuses you of undermining him and Fred Claire, I won't
write it. ...
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, Tom Lasorda bristled when I questioned him about
giving up that intriguing young hitting prospect, Paul Konerko,
plus left-handed pitcher Dennis Reyes for reliever Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you give up on Konerko?'' I wondered. ``What if he
turns out to be a great hitter?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, well, what if he doesn't?'' bristled Lasorda. ``We
needed a stopper. And we got a damned good one in Shaw.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but Lasorda just might have gotten rid of a future
star in Paul Konerko.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Konerko's going to be one of those guys who can hit 30
homers, hit .300 and drive in 100 runs,'' a well-known major league
scout told me in the Dodger Stadium pressbox.
</P>
<P>
   The scout pleaded anonymity because he wants to remain Tom
Lasorda's friend. ...
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, I heard Bob Graziano the other day say that Tom
Lasorda will help him locate a general manager. I'm sure he will.
Here's betting that ol' Tommy points to himself. ...
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, Tom Lasorda cocked his fearsome left hand against me
in the pressbox, although he did so in a playful manner. But even
had he popped me, I wouldn't have retaliated. I don't fight
septuagenarians. ...
</P>
<P>
   I'll believe Tom Lasorda that these Gary Sheffield-Juan
Castro-Trenidad Hubbard Dodgers will make a strong second half
impact in the West Division if they can rough up the Padres' Kevin
Brown today as thoroughly as they did Mark Langston Thursday. ...
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the 7th inning and the Dodgers holding a 12-1
lead, Glenn Hoffman did his Red Auerbach-lighting-a-cigar victory
bit when he had Roger Cedeno pinch hit for Gary Sheffield. ..
</P>
<P>
   I know how FIFA can get rid of all the insufferable flopping
that goes on in its sport. Change its absurd, purely subjective red
card rule that has deprived France's fine defender, Laurent Blanc,
from participating in the World Cup final against Brazil. You can't
blame guys giving Oscar performances when such theatrics might
result in rivals being ejected and their teams suddenly having a
one-man advantage. ...
</P>
<P>
   The two best World Cup players this soccer dilettante has seen
is Brazil's Ronaldo and England's Michael Owen. ...
</P>
<P>
   I'll be surprised if Brazil, quicker, slicker and flashier,
doesn't beat France by at least two goals. . .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
