u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SOLDIERS-REVIEW-     07-09 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SOLDIERS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY FAILS TO SAVE PLOT OF `SMALL SOLDIERS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the monster toys against the human soldier toys, with real
people caught in the middle, in the violent live-action,
computer-animation and puppet kid's movie, ``Small Soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   As any kid could predict, it's the monster toys who are the nice
heroes, while the soldier toys are the kill-'em-all bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Soldiers'' is a mix of live action (real actors and
settings) with two forms of trickery. One is actual puppets,
created by the studio of the famous Stan Winston, who has gotten
four Oscars for films such as ``Jurassic Park'' and ``Terminator
2.'' The other is Industrial Light and Magic computer animation
matching the puppets Winston's teams created.
</P>
<P>
   The mix of all three is really pretty amazing, creating an
almost seamless interaction between life, animation and puppets.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the story built around the animation, while
beginning with nice touches of parody to amuse adults in the
audience, soon degenerates into a juvenile script aimed directly at
kids who like to see things smashed up. It comes with enough
violence and dangerous behavior to concern parents.
</P>
<P>
   One scene that may scare some kids has a ``live'' toy soldier
getting his legs chewed off in a garbage disposal while his top
half is still visible. In another scene, a boy climbs a live power
pole with instructions on how to short out the neighborhood. Wonder
if kids will try that after seeing this?
</P>
<P>
   But once word gets around summer camp how cool-destructive these
animated toys are, it's going to be hard to keep kids from going.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is directed by Joe Dante, who brought us ``Gremlins,''
and has much of the feel of that movie. Watch close to see a
Gremlin toy spotted in a trash bin.
</P>
<P>
   When a big, heartless megacompany buys up a small,
child-friendly toy company, the plan is to create toys that will
sell, no matter how bad they are for kids.
</P>
<P>
   The toy designers have already come up with two new, completely
separate toy ideas. One is a race of monster-looking but peaceful
fantasy creatures called Gorgonites who are forever looking for
their lost island of Gorgon.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a squad of toy soldiers modeled after the kind of
cliche Nick Fury-style commando characters you'd find in the kind
of military comics parents don't want their children to read. Each
one's name fits his character. The leader is Chip Hazard. The radio
man is Link Static.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the big company (Denis Leary) decides that the two
lines should be designed as enemies, with the heroic Commando Elite
human soldiers out to track down and kill the monster Gorgonites.
</P>
<P>
   To make the toys sophisticated, futuristic software is combined
with a computer chip designed for military weapons. The resulting
toy soldiers are unexpectedly and frighteningly human and
ultra-aggressive. Unfortunately, in their rush to market the toys,
the company doesn't have time for field testing.
</P>
<P>
   Once out of their boxes and turned on, the toy's new computer
chips give both races the ability to learn. The Gorgonites, trained
to hide and lose when attacked, are at the mercy of the
increasingly real Commando Elite, who only want to destroy the
``Gorgonite scum.''
</P>
<P>
   In a small Ohio town, young Alan (Gregory Smith) and his
would-be girlfriend Christy (Kirsten Dunst) befriend a group of the
goofy-looking Gorgonites when they are mercilessly attacked by the
Commando Elite. The commandos then turn their attack on the kids
and eventually their families. At first, the humans have an
advantage because they are larger and smarter, but the commandos
learn and get lots of reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, there are some pretty funny touches to the film, such
as a commercial in which a company selling its military chips to
the public boasts, ``You'll enjoy the same high-quality technology
the U.S. Defense Department gets.'' Globotech's business is
``turning swords into plowshares for you and your family.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon the film turns into a formulaic child's film with
little to offer adults except admiring the computer animation. That
is quite impressive, but so what? How long can we be interested in
real-looking toys?
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Gorgonites, Archer (voice of Frank Langella),
is an appealing, furry-beast character. The rest of the creatures
are comic: One looks sort of Frankenstein-ish; another is a big eye
on a long neck.
</P>
<P>
   The voices of the Commando Elite may be the best joke in the
movie. They belong to actors who could have played the same role in
war movies 30 years ago: Besides Jones, they are Ernest Borgnine,
Jim Brown, Bruce Dern, George Kennedy and Clint Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The commandos also recruit a collection of Barbie-type dolls
onto their side.
</P>
<P>
   When his troops start ogling the faux-Barbies, Chip Hazard tells
them, ``This is the modern army, those are reinforcements.'' The
dolls are stripped down, and computer brains are placed between
their oversize Barbie-doll breasts. (No, really.)
</P>
<P>
   The film does have a number of humorous lines and moments. When
one of his squad is killed (chopped in half), Hazard says ``Nick
Nitro's battery has run out, but his memory will keep on going and
going and going.''
</P>
<P>
   The occasional one-liners and great animation effects are not
enough to keep adults enthralled through the mundane story of the
humans fighting toys, or the uninspired romance between the
12-year-old kids.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the adult cast includes Jay Mohr, the late Phil
Hartman and Robert Picardo, all in small roles.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, there would seem to be a conflict between the
rating for ``Small Soldiers'' and its intended audience.
</P>
<P>
   The movie gets and deserves a PG-13 rating, which means that
parents are warned to consider carefully before letting their
children age 12 and younger see it.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the movie is aimed at kids 12 and younger.
One must assume either that the filmmakers thought their movie
should get a less-severe rating, or that they know few parents
restrict their younger kids from seeing PG-13 movies, unless the
rating is for sex instead of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The cynical view is that the studios _ in this case DreamWorks
and Universal _ are just banking on parents not caring. It's
possible that in this case the filmmakers thought they would get by
with a PG, since much of the violence is between toys. But because
the toys seem so human, it still seems very violent.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the Motion Picture Association of America's reason
for the rating mentions drug use. This is from the toys putting
prescription pills in the parent's alcoholic drinks, not from
children using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sex _ except one big smooch between the 12-year-olds
_ and only doll nudity. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-98 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
