<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8590 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-LETHAL-REVIEW-HN     07-09 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LETHAL-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIBSON, GLOVER TEAM UP FOR MORE COMEDY, MAYHEM IN ``LW 4'' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Policemen Martin Riggs and Roger Murtaugh are the two stooges of
super-violent action movies. Where they go, mayhem follows,
giggling all the way.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth entry in their ``Lethal Weapon'' series, Murtaugh
(Danny Glover) and Riggs (Mel Gibson) spend their professional time
trying to stop smugglers who are bringing Chinese immigrants into
the country for forced labor. In their private moments they are
each coming to grips with an unexpected pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the plot matters much, but it turns out the smuggling
covers up an even more dangerous plan to get some major Chinese
crime lords into the country.
</P>
<P>
   A subplot, so downplayed you may miss it, is that some of
Murtaugh's associates are beginning to wonder where a lowly street
officer gets the money to pay for his family's lavish lifestyle.
Even Riggs is worried Murtaugh is on the take.
</P>
<P>
   More interesting are the personal stories. Murtaugh's daughter
is pregnant and hasn't named the father. And Riggs' live-in mate,
Lorna Cole (Rene Russo again), is also with child.
</P>
<P>
   Both babies are due any day. Murtaugh is trying to find out who
the dad is (he prays the father is black and not a cop) and widower
Riggs must decide whether to propose to Lorna.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs and Murtaugh have caused so much public destruction in
their police work _ the opening scene in which they cause an oil
tanker to explode has been shown in previews for months _ that they
both have been promoted to captain to keep them off the street and
out of trouble. Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   If the purpose of a movie review is to let readers know if they
will enjoy seeing a picture, then ``Lethal Weapon 4'' requires
asking just one question: Did you like its predecessors? Whatever
you felt about previous ``Lethal Weapon'' movies, you are almost
sure to feel the same about this edition. It is cut very much from
the same cloth, by many of the same tailors.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are Gibson and Glover back, but also so are Joe Pesci
as the irritating, foul-mouthed sleaze-ball Lou Getz (``LW 2 and
3'') and Russo (``LW 3'') as Cole, an officer who matches Riggs in
tough fighting, sex appeal and zany attitude. Steve Kahan returns
to play Capt. Ed Murphy for the fourth time.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Richard Donner returns to direct. Aside from
making all four ``LW'' movies, Donner has guided Gibson through
``Maverick'' and ``Conspiracy Theory.'' He is one of the few
directors who has a sure hand blending comedy and action scenes (he
also did ``Superman: The Movie``).
</P>
<P>
   Most action-movie sequels suffer badly compared to their
originals, relying on bigger (not better) action to cover up a lack
of a reason to exist (aside from making more money from the same
title, that is).
</P>
<P>
   Donner and action producer Joel Silver, who also has been there
all the way, have managed to maintain a high-percentage of the
original film's qualities, such as they are. While adhering closely
to a formula established in 1987, the sequels have felt relatively
fresh, especially ``Lethal Weapon 2.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret has been finding ways of doing the predictable action
scenes in wild and funny ways, and by playing up the strong comic
relationship between the stars. In addition, all the ``LW'' films
keep up such a furious pace you hardly notice how ridiculous they
are.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it helps that this is the first ``LW'' movie in six
years. The plotting is thin, disguised beneath all the bells and
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least five action set pieces, most of them
extremely well staged. There's a gun fight between our heroes on a
fishing boat and smugglers on a ship. There is a car chase _ as if
there wouldn't be _ in which Gibson ends up in a predicament so
outlandish and funny it would be unfair to describe.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention that there is some pretty gross violence?
</P>
<P>
   As superficial as the personal stories are, we have to be
thankful when an action film these days makes any attempt at
character.
</P>
<P>
   In the original ``Lethal Weapon,'' Riggs was near suicidal after
the death of his wife. Eleven years later, he still struggles with
the idea of marrying someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wear the ring anymore,'' he says, ``but I look down,
and it's still there.'' No kidding, that line elicited a sad
``Awww'' from the woman sitting behind me.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the comedy built around the nutty cop (Riggs)/stable
cop (Murtaugh) relationship is a major element. After Riggs
convinces Murtaugh to distract a bad guy by stripping to his shorts
and acting like a bird, he tries to pat the older officer on the
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't touch me when I'm naked,'' snaps Murtaugh.
</P>
<P>
   A running joke involves a young cop, Lee Butters (comedian Chris
Rock), who is being very friendly to Murtaugh. It is Butters who is
the lover of Murtaugh's daughter. Riggs has convinced his pal that
Butters is so nice to him because he's gay.
</P>
<P>
   Rock's character supplies some funny moments, but like Pesci,
whose main comic riff is to cuss like he's back in a Scorsese
movie, he detracts far more than he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson and Glover give a good show; they don't act like they
were playing the same rather thin characters for the fourth time.
They are the core of this series, as much as the wild stunts and
heavy violence.
</P>
<P>
   Russo, who was a major attraction of ``LW 3,'' is under-used
this time. She does have two good scenes and one good fight, even
nine months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, almost forgot. Every action film needs a chief villain,
and here the part is played by Jet Li, a martial arts expert and
Asian star. He's not threatening-looking. He can sure move in
fights though. (These things are so over-edited, they can make
anybody look good.)
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the soundtrack is at times so loud, both from music
and gunfire, that it's often hard to catch key words of dialogue.
You may miss completely the comic explanation, when it finally
comes, of where Glover gets all his money.
</P>
<P>
   After ``LW 3'' Gibson and Glover made noises about not doing any
more sequels. And with a superstar status that lets him pick almost
any role and any salary, Gibson had little reason to change his
mind, especially after winning serious filmmaker status with his
best-director Oscar for ``Braveheart.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Lethal Weapon 3,'' the most profitable of the series, made
$319 million worldwide _ not counting the post-theatrical ancillary
markets. Is it any wonder Warner Bros. was willing to pay Gibson
$20 million to make another one? Even so, he said no for years,
only relenting when _ he said _ the script and the time were
finally right.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, ``LW 4'' is unexceptional story-wise and too long.
Still, it's one of the more entertaining action films of late.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sex or nudity, but there are tons of profanity and
over-the-top gore in the R-rated movie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
